<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-KOHL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: HELMUT KOHL, HUMBLED 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times says in an editorial Thursday, Jan. 20: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Former Chancellor Helmut Kohl's resignation as honorary chairman
of his beloved Christian Democrats was forced on him by his own
embattled proteges. But it will not stop the unraveling of his own
reputation or that of his party. By defiantly flouting his legal
obligation to reveal the names of donors to a secret campaign fund,
Kohl compounds the damage he has already caused.
</P>
<P>
   For 16 years Kohl dominated German politics. He guided the
peaceful reunification of his country, helped fashion the political
framework for a united Europe and led the way to economic
cooperation on the continent and the adoption of a common currency.
But his admission that for years he operated a system of secret
accounts to handle undeclared cash donations to his party has dealt
a heavy blow to his formidable reputation. Now it threatens to
consume his party as well.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors in Bonn last month opened a preliminary criminal
investigation of Kohl, who has acknowledged that he received more
than $1 million in undisclosed political contributions while in
office. The former chancellor had stunned Germans in November when
he admitted, after previous denials, that he had used illegal bank
accounts to channel secret political contributions to local
branches of his party. But he has refused to disclose the names of
the contributors, citing his ``word of honor'' not to do so. Kohl's
image as a statesman is rapidly degenerating into that of a corrupt
and arrogant machine boss.
</P>
<P>
   The Kohl affair is a reminder that the United States is not the
only advanced democracy where the insatiable demands of campaign
finance threaten to undermine democracy. Since the reckless
fund-raising of the 1996 American presidential campaign, France,
Spain, Italy and Britain have all been rocked by fund-raising
scandals. It is troubling that a scandal of this magnitude is
occurring in Germany, which has the most generous system of state
financing of political parties in the world _ a result of similar
scandals in the 1980s in which Kohl was also implicated. Clearly,
public financing of elections has to be linked to vigorous
enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   The current scandal grew out of a public prosecutor's
investigation into cash payments of a half-million dollars to party
officials linked to an arms export deal with Saudi Arabia. Party
officials also allegedly received large sums of money from a French
oil company that took over a chemical plant in eastern Germany in
1992.
</P>
<P>
   The widening investigation has exposed extensive deceit in the
upper reaches of Kohl's party. Last week his protege and successor
as party leader, Wolfgang Schauble, admitted accepting $52,000 in
cash from the same fugitive arms broker who gave secret donations
to Kohl's intermediaries. And on Wednesday the party said that $4.5
million more in apparantly illicit funds had been uncovered. Nobody
has yet alleged that the former chancellor benefited personally
from secret accounts. But he must not be allowed to hide behind his
stature as a statesman. If Kohl is to salvage his diminished
reputation _ and his party's _ he should disclose what he knows and
cooperate fully with efforts to establish the facts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
