r s BC-GLF-HOPE-LADN     01-20 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-HOPE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOMS LEADS AFTER 63
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY MORGAN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERMUDA DUNES -- David Toms had a breakthrough year on the PGA
Tour in 1999 with two victories and earnings of $1,959,672, which
was more than what he had won in his previous nine years on tour
combined.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever he had going in 1998 he had going again Wednesday when
he shot a nine-under 63 and grabbed the first-round lead in the $3
million Bob Hope Chrysler Classic.
</P>
<P>
   Toms was playing Indian Wells Country Club, regarded as the
easiest layout in the four-course rotation, and made the most of
his day with a round that included two eagles, five birdies and not
a single bogey.
</P>
<P>
   ``My irons were real sharp today,'' he said. ``For nine-under,
you usually make a lot of putts. I made a couple of good putts, but
the rest of them were putts that you're supposed to make.''
</P>
<P>
   His longest birdie of the day was a 20-footer on the par-3,
163-yard 15th hole. Three other birdies were inside 15 feet and one
his eagles came from five feet on the 517-yard fifth hole, which he
reached with a five wood on his second shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``The conditions today were ideal,'' Toms said, referring to the
sunny, almost windless day. ``I think it was like playing golf in a
dome. Obviously, we all would like to play in this every day, if we
could, or at least I would.''
</P>
<P>
   Toms wasn't the only one who played well Wednesday in this
annual, five-day birdie binge. Paul Goydos, Bob Tway, Neal
Lancaster and Robert Damron were a shot behind at 64, and last
year's runner-up, Steve Pate, was at 65 along with the likes of
Esteban Toledo and Glen Day.
</P>
<P>
   Davis Love III appeared ready to join the Lancaster group at 64,
but he drove out of bounds on his final hole, took double bogey and
settled for a 66 at Indian Wells. Last year's winner, David Duval,
had a 68 at the Arnold Palmer at PGA West, the same course on which
he shot his stunning, final-round 59 to win a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Tour rookie Casey Martin, playing at Indian Wells, had a solid
68 that included a chip-in for eagle.
</P>
<P>
   `` I had a lot of great looks, but I just didn't putt that
well,'' he said. ``But at the same time, I hit it great.''
</P>
<P>
   Love is playing in his first event of the year and said the Hope
tournament was a good place to start the season. He didn't qualify
for the recent Mercedes Championship at Kapalua because he didn't
win last year -- he hasn't won since the 1998 MCI Classic -- but he
probably wouldn't have enjoyed it anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been working on my swing,'' he said, and I didn't want to
try it out over there. With the winds, that would have been
counterproductive for me.
</P>
<P>
   I've been trying to get everything tuned up, and I felt pretty
good about that. This is a good spot to begin.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocco Mediate played Wednesday at La Quinta Country Club, a
7,060-yard test thought to be the toughest of the Hope courses, and
said it was important to shoot well there and get it out of the
way. His 66 gives him plenty of confidence going into today's round
at Indian Wells, which he considers one of his favorite courses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It always has been,'' he said. ``You don't really have to
prepare. I just know what to expect.''
</P>
<P>
   What was unexpected Wednesday were some surprisingly high
numbers by some golf's well-known figures. Perhaps the biggest of
them all was Arnold Palmer, who was playing on his own course at
PGA West and struggled to a 10-over 82. Former U.S. Open champion
Steve Jones had a 78. Fuzzy Zoeller was at 76. Tour rookie Gary
Nicklaus had a 74 that included a back-nine 39. Tom Kite, who broke
the tour record for a 90-hole event with a 35-under-par 325 in
winning the 1993 Classic, was at 73.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, 114 of the 128 players in the field were at par or
better. Only 14 others failed to break par.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
