<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUELCELL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUEL CELL MAY BEAT BATTERY BLUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY JONATHAN SIDENER  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The cell phone of the future may run without batteries, powered
instead by methanol, the key ingredient in windshield washer fluid.
</P>
<P>
   And it may solve mobile phone users' biggest complaint: not
enough talk time from their batteries.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers from Motorola Labs in Tempe and Los Alamos National
Labs in New Mexico have produced a working version of a
methanol-powered fuel cell small enough to fit inside a cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   Battery technology has improved slowly over the years. Today's
best batteries require recharging after two or three days of
moderate phone use. The new fuel cell offers dramatic improvement
over battery power. It will support moderate use of a phone for
about a month before needing to be refueled, Motorola says.
</P>
<P>
   The new power source is slightly bigger than a postage stamp and
slightly thicker than a penny. Prototypes of the fuel cartridges
are about the size of AA batteries.
</P>
<P>
   Like all fuel cells, this one uses a catalyst to convert energy
stored in fuel directly to electricity.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola, one of the leading makers of cell phones, joined with
Los Alamos because researchers there had developed fuel cells that
run on methanol, also known as wood alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   Methanol is rich with fuel, holding 10 times the energy, ounce
for ounce, as today's best batteries.
</P>
<P>
   The fuel cell is up and running on a laboratory bench, as
Motorola tests its safety, durability and reliability.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers expect the device to be safe. It generates no extra
heat, making electricity at room temperature. The two byproducts of
the chemical reaction are carbon dioxide and water.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be three to five years before you see it in a product,''
said Bill Ooms, director of Motorola Labs' material, device and
energy research division.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers faced hurdles trying to get a working fuel cell in a
small electronic device. Fuel cells traditionally produce too low a
voltage to run a phone.
</P>
<P>
   Putting several cells together increased the voltage but created
another problem, because the cells require oxygen. Stacking the
cells restricts air flow and creates the need for an air pump.
</P>
<P>
   But that made the system too big.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola Labs came up with circuitry to convert the output of a
single cell to the higher voltage.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola says it still faces the technical challenge of making
the fuel cells less expensive than rechargeable batteries.
</P>
<P>
   Ooms said other researchers are looking at fuel cells as a power
source for electronic devices.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're probably in the lead for applying them to small portable
equipment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Jodoin, an analyst with the Cahners In-Stat Group high-tech
market research firm, said it's difficult to assess competition
because fuel cell research is likely being done in secret.
</P>
<P>
   ``Motorola produces the phones and the semiconductors (that
control power use), and now they're addressing the remaining
consumer concern: battery life,'' Jodoin said. ``Within the
industry, that makes them pretty unique.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-00 0009EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
