<HEADLINE>
SLOCUM LEAVES USC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   USC assistant coach Shawn Slocum has resigned to return to Texas
A&AMP;M and work with his father, Aggies head coach R.C. Slocum.
</P>
<P>
   Slocum, 34, coached linebackers and special teams the past two
seasons for USC, after spending the previous seven years at Texas
A&AMP;M. He will coach linebackers for the Aggies.
</P>
<P>
   According to sources, Slocum wanted to return his family to
Texas and had just built a home in College Station.
</P>
<P>
   He is the fourth USC coach to leave the staff since the end of
the season. Offensive line coach Steve Greatwood was fired;
quarterbacks coach Ken O'Brien refused a reassignment to tight ends
and resigned while wide receivers coach Mike Wilson entered private
business.
</P>
<P>
   Slocum's departure means that USC has openings for a tight-ends
coach and linebackers coach.
</P>
<P>
   Although Slocum was USC's only special teams coach, he was
expected to split duties with new wide receivers coach Dan Ferrigno
next year, after the Trojans' special teams performance faltered
during a 6-6 season.
</P>
<P>
   Of a more immediate concern to USC is how Slocum's departure
will affect the recruitment of linebacker Amon Gordon of Mira Mesa
High in San Diego. Gordon has listed USC as his leader but now says
he is unsure, and is scheduled to visit Miami this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   USC coach Paul Hackett will make a home visit this week to
Gordon and his roommate, Mira Mesa quarterback Teyo Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Among those believed to be interested in the job is former USC
linebacker Riki Ellison.
</P>
<P>
   Welch finished: Offensive lineman Matt Welch has ended his
playing career because of recurring shoulder injuries and will take
a medical redshirt, which means his scholarship will not count
against the team's total of 85. Welch, who also played tight end,
had one year of eligibility remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Acosta commits: USC has secured a commitment from offensive
lineman Carlos Acosta of Moorpark Community College. Acosta played
at Thousand Oaks High School and is the Trojans' 16th commitment.
</P>
<P>
   Who's eligible? Cornerback Eric Reese may be declared
academically ineligible this semester, which would result in his
missing spring practice. Reese's status should be determined by the
end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   No track? Wide receiver Kareem Kelly is not working out with the
track team and is unlikely to run for the Trojans this season,
because of time constraints.
</P>
<P>
   The other football players who double as track athletes --
Marcell Allmond, Lucais MacKay, Sultan McCullough, Darrell Rideaux
-- are all working out with the track team.
</P>
<P>
   Sanford commits: Los Alamitos High quarterback Mike Sanford Jr.,
the son of former USC assistant coach Mike Sanford, has orally
committed to Boise State University.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
