<HEADLINE>
SO FAR, QUIET WEEK FOR MARTIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY MORGAN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERMUDA DUNES -- It has been a quiet week, so far at least, for
Casey Martin and his cart at the Bob Hope Chrysler Classic.
</P>
<P>
   Martin said nobody ``has gotten in his face'' about riding a
cart on tour, but that could change. Opinions appear to be mixed
among this week's professionals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't speak for anybody else,'' said last year's Hope
winner, David Duval. ``To me, is it a big deal that he's playing?
No, he earned his way out here.
</P>
<P>
   ``He went to (qualifying) school, finished in the top 15 on the
Nike Tour and earned his spot. As far as the other stuff with the
cart and the court, I have no say in the matter. I haven't thought
about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's out here and it's no different seeing him out here than
anybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis Love III, on the other hand, didn't want to talk about it
at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably better than I don't comment on that subject,''
he told reporter.
</P>
<P>
   (box) Glen Day, who is just two shots behind first-round leader
David Toms, played in last week's Sony Open in Honolulu despite the
fact he doesn't like the course, Waialae Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``The course is just not good for me,'' he said. ``I like to hit
it left to right, and you've got to hit right to left there. It's
just, you know, some courses just aren't for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Then why did he go?
</P>
<P>
   ``Because my wife (Jennifer) said she wanted to go to
Honolulu,'' he said. ``Just like any good husband, I said, `Yes
ma'am.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
