<SLUG> BC-WORKER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELIGION A TABOO TOPIC ON THE JOB? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY KELLY ETTENBOROUGH  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Phoenix city employees can go too far when talking about God at
work.
</P>
<P>
   That's what Richard Behn discovered when he was suspended after
telling co-workers that salvation through Jesus is the only way to
heaven.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the groundskeeping supervisor is suing the city, saying it
violated his rights of free speech and freedom of religion.
</P>
<P>
   The case adds to the national debate over what kind of religious
conversation is appropriate in the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   If the message comes from, or seems to come from, the
government, then it's wrong, said Marci Hamilton, a New York law
professor and expert on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Individuals can talk about personal convictions, she said, until
it becomes harassment.
</P>
<P>
   But that line is blurry.
</P>
<P>
   Workplace religious discrimination charges are rising, according
to the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission. From 1992 to 1998,
complaints jumped about 29 percent, from 1,388 to 1,796.
</P>
<P>
   Federal and state laws require employers to reasonably
accommodate employees' religious beliefs unless that imposes an
undue hardship. A prayer break, for example, is a reasonable
request.
</P>
<P>
   But when faced with religious discrimination claims, courts
often favor the employer, said Richard Foltin, legislative director
for the American Jewish Committee in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is that it's not particularly problematic to
have an employee once say, `I'd like to talk to you about my
faith,' '' Foltin said. But the workplace becomes a ``hostile
environment'' when one person's right to free speech runs into
another's right to be free from harassment.
</P>
<P>
   The city wouldn't comment on Behn's suit, but has a policy
against a hostile work environment.
</P>
<P>
   As an evangelical Christian, Behn says he has a duty to tell
others about his faith, following a higher call from God.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Behn was suspended for one day for discussing his
religion with those he worked with and supervised at Maryvale
Baseball Park.
</P>
<P>
   He was told to stop sharing his faith and giving religious
literature to those who requested it, although he had been doing it
for 15 years, said his attorney, Bryan J. Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Behn's supervisors said his ``preaching on the job'' created an
uncomfortable work environment, court documents say. If he
continued, he could face further discipline, including termination
or reassignment to a less desirable position.
</P>
<P>
   Behn appealed through city administrative channels and lost.
Tuesday, he filed suit in the U.S. District Court in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a right to be religious on the job,'' Brown said. ``He
was talking about his own religious experiences. He was inviting
people to church.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown is a lawyer with the American Family Association Center
for Law &AMP; Policy in Tupelo, Miss., a center that specializes in
cases involving Christians' civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   Marie Chapple Camacho, spokeswoman for the Phoenix Parks,
Recreation and Library Department, said Wednesday that the city had
not seen the lawsuit and had no comment.
</P>
<P>
   The other defendants named in the lawsuit _ David Johnson,
northwest district parks supervisor, and Rob Harman, parks facility
supervisor at Maryvale Baseball Park _ did not comment.
</P>
<P>
   The Parks Department has a policy encouraging employees to
respect each other's beliefs. The city says Behn violated that
code, court documents say.
</P>
<P>
   But Brown said that same code actually supports Behn's views.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are called to respect everyone. Sexual orientation is
included,'' Brown said. ``If I'm talking about my relationship with
another man, Richard Behn must tolerate that. If he is talking to
another employee about his relationship to Jesus Christ, that will
put him out in the desert counting cactuses.'' &QL; 
 &UR; Reach the reporter at Kelly &QL; 
 &UR; .Ettenborough(at)ArizonaRepublic.com or at (602) 444-7728.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-00 0038EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
