<HEADLINE>
A JACKET WITH BUILT-IN MOBILE TELEPHONE?  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This quirky 250-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE
INDEPENDENT newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
  
 By JOHN LICHFIELD  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ France Telecom is working on a jacket with a built-in
mobile telephone, which it hopes to issue experimentally this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Speaker and microphone will probably be hidden in the sleeves;
front and sleeve buttons may double as keyboard push-buttons.
</P>
<P>
   There remains one small, technical problem. How do you wash or
dry-clean such a jacket or suit, without ruining the telephone?
</P>
<P>
   The research agency of France Telecom, the Centre National
d'Etudes des Telecommunications, believes that such clothes will be
all the rage in three to ten years' time. The prototype, to be
produced this summer, will help to overcome other remaining
difficulties, such as cost.
</P>
<P>
   Would the talking suit owner of the future be able to transfer
the equipment from one piece of clothing to another? Or would he or
she have an entire talking wardrobe?
</P>
<P>
   France Telecom is cooperating in the research with a company
called i-wear, which specializes in the development of electronic
and telephonic clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Other projects under consideration include clothes with
transmitters to allow the wearer to be tracked by satellite
(applicable to prisoners on parole or unfaithful husbands?).
</P>
<P>
   Longer-term ideas include: sports clothes which measure speed
and distance; evening wear which changes color when it is subjected
to bright lights or loud music; and overcoats capable of checking
their own pockets to make sure that their owner has left nothing
behind. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this intriguing 250-word article from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London, it must be purchased from the New York Times
Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or
fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
