<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-TEXAS-OSU-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OKLAHOMA STATE RIDES DESMOND MASON TO VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   STILLWATER, Okla. _ Arriving for a frothy showdown of Big 12
leaders last night, Texas' 14th-ranked Longhorns were confronted by
a packed house of screeching Oklahoma State supporters at
Gallagher-Iba Arena, officially numbered at 6,381.
</P>
<P>
   But really, the 12th-ranked Cowboys (14-1, 3-0) needed only one
of them ... Desmond Mason.
</P>
<P>
   Demonstrating anew why his name adorned a variety of preseason
All-America checklists, Mason almost single-handedly shot the
Longhorns (11-5, 3-1) out of a share of the conference lead with a
30-point performance that led to a 73-65 Cowboys victory.
</P>
<P>
   Pretty much the way Cowboys coach Eddie Sutton laid it out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach emphasized that this was a really big game,'' said
Mason, who shot his way out of a slump in which he had scored 20
points and gone 8-for-31 from the field in three games against
Division I foes. ``He said I was probably going to play 40 minutes,
and he needed me to be focused for every one of them.
</P>
<P>
   Mason produced 40 extremely focused minutes, adding six
rebounds, two blocks, an assist and a steal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, one thing is it was Texas, and you have to get pumped up
or they'll run over you,'' he said. ``And being from Texas
\RWaxahachie\S myself, it always means a lot to me and seems to be
one of my better games. For two days in practice, I took about
1,000 shots, and it paid off. I'd like to play them more often.''
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorns, who lost to a ranked team for the third time
(they have also beaten three), would probably pass on that idea.
Their first clue about the course of the evening came after they
went on a 10-0 run to take a 17-10 lead in the first half. Over the
next four minutes, Mason outscored them 11-2.
</P>
<P>
   At halftime, Mason had 17 of the Cowboys' 29 points, although
the Longhorns held a 30-29 lead.
</P>
<P>
   It would be their last. Mason opened the second half with eight
unanswered points, launching the Cowboys to an eventual 54-41 lead
with 6:36 remaining. Texas eventually closed it to four on Darren
Kelly's 3-pointer with a minute remaining but could get no closer.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding Mason's performance, Sutton said, ``That's the best
game I've had from any player since I've been back at Oklahoma
State.''
</P>
<P>
   So good, in fact, that teammate Glendon Alexander, who finished
with 17 points, admitted to being a bit awed.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the first time I've ever become a spectator during a
game,'' he said. ``But he looked, so good I just stood back and
watched.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas got 24 points from Chris Mihm and 13 each from Gabe
Muoneke and Kelly, but coach Rick Barnes noted that it wasn't
enough to offset one hot Cowboy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was terrific,'' Barnes said, ``but the kind of player he
is, you knew he was going to break out pretty soon.''
</P>
<P>
   The game got away from Texas during a 10-point swing in the
second half when the luckless Longhorns watched two layups, two
follow shots and a 3-pointer rim out.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just didn't fall during that stretch, and it hurt,'' said
Mihm, who refused to blame the loss on the pressure of back-to-back
battles with ranked teams. Texas beat Oklahoma on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this time of year,'' he said, ``you're supposed to be ready
for stuff like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Mihm also ducked questions about whether he would return to
Texas next year or opt for the NBA draft after this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I am a member of the University of Texas, and
that's all that matters,'' he said. ``It's unfair to my teammates
to talk about anything else.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
