<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REP. SKELTON SEES NEED TO REVAMP OVERSEAS BASES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MURPHY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Ike Skelton of Missouri returned from a trip
to Asia and the Pacific this week, convinced of the need to retain
and possibly revamp America's military operations there.
</P>
<P>
   Skelton, from Lexington, is the ranking Democrat on the House
Armed Services Committee and he made the 11-day trip to Guam,
Australia and Singapore with three other committee Democrats. It
was paid for with money from the group's budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stability in the region can only be maintained by a continued
U.S. military presence,'' Skelton told reporters Wednesday. ``Both
U.S. and foreign officials emphasized this to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Australia, for example, could not have performed its recent
mission in nearby East Timor without American help in
communications, intelligence and lift operations, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The United States might want to station more troops in Guam and
Australia for training and exercises, Skelton added. Those troops
could be transferred from Japan and Okinawa, where he said such
training is becoming more difficult because of local regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no reason to believe that such a redeployment is
imminent, but we do think it is prudent to think in advance so that
such a move could be made in orderly fashion,'' Skelton said.
</P>
<P>
   The delegation also met with agricultural officials in Australia
and Singapore. The countries import American goods and Skelton
believes the potential exists for an even larger market there.
</P>
<P>
   In Singapore, the Skelton group went to a chamber of commerce
function also attended by Sen. Kit Bond, a Missouri Republican, who
was there on a trade promotion mission.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-00 0104EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000120.0022 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 01:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1139 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-DDAY-KAN &LR;      01-20 0378
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DDAY-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCULPTURES RENDERED BY AREA ARTISTS RECALL DAY OF NORMANDY
INVASION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN BURNES  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two sculptured beach obstacles, recalling the obstructions
placed by the German army along the French shoreline to impede the
1944 Normandy invasion, have just been completed for the National
D-Day Memorial in Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Custom Metal &AMP; Fabrication of Olathe assembled the objects
according to the design of Baldwin City, Kan., sculptor Matt Kirby
and the research of Paul Dorrell, director of Kansas City's Leopold
Gallery.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Custom Metal employees loaded the obstacles for an
initial trip to Baldwin City. There they will remain outdoors for
several weeks, acquiring the appropriate sheen of rust and weather.
</P>
<P>
   Then it will be off to Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   The beach obstacles are the latest objects for the memorial to
be finished by area artists. Sculptor Jim Brothers of Lawrence
already has shipped several bronze statues of soldiers to the
shrine, which is under construction.
</P>
<P>
   The obstacles are roughly 7 feet long in each direction and have
been rendered 25 percent larger than the originals placed by the
Germans. Representatives of the American Normandy Cemetery in
France sent photographs and drawings to guide the artist.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the project still proved complicated.
</P>
<P>
   At first, representatives of the D-Day memorial considered
ordering the beach obstacles in bronze. But those would not have
offered sufficient contrast to the bronze soldiers that already
have been made.
</P>
<P>
   Stainless steel was another option. But while stainless steel
can be darkened with a blow-torch, it is difficult to achieve a
uniform color, Dorrell said.
</P>
<P>
   Kirby and Dorrell then decided on a variety of dark steel that
will rust to a certain point but then stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you think of World War II, you think of black-and-white
photographs and rusting metal,'' Kirby said.
</P>
<P>
   These obstacles, once rusted just so, will evoke that distant
time.
</P>
<P>
   Kirby already has been getting compliments about the obstacles,
especially from those old enough to remember the originals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exciting to be involved in a project like this,'' Kirby
said. ``My dad is impressed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
