r a BC-HATCH-KAN &LR;      01-20 1032
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HATCH-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HATCH FINDS AN ELECTORATE THAT MAY BE LOOKING FOR SOMETHING ELSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK MONTGOMERY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Note: This is the seventh in a series of reports about the
presidential candidates in Iowa, the first major contest in the
2000 primary season. )
</P>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ When you're in last place, as the polls here
put Sen. Orrin Hatch, you can spend an easy hour or two with the
youngsters at Wallace Accelerated School.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're the second president this week!'' a first-grader told
the Utah Republican. Principal Maggie McGill explained that
Democrat Bill Bradley had zipped through three days earlier, and
whoa, you should've seen all the reporters.
</P>
<P>
   When you're in last place, you'll take any question that a
cafeteria full of third-graders can muster. Did you do homework in
school, Mr. Hatch? (``I wish I did more.'') What's the difference
between Republicans and Democrats? And do you really, really want
to be president?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh yes, I do,'' he deadpanned. ``I wouldn't be going through
this misery if I didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   A dozen grown-ups in the room laughed. And Hatch, who has 19
grandchildren, was quick to clarify that talking to kids isn't
misery, of course, but the travel and debates and time away from
family can be ``very, very tough _ as it should be.''
</P>
<P>
   Something about this presidential race is not as it should be,
in the four-term senator's opinion: How can one of Capitol Hill's
most productive conservatives _ who has the most political
experience by far in this GOP field of six _ wind up lost on the
national media's radar?
</P>
<P>
   ``The Eastern liberal media _ they've written me off, basically
because I don't have a lot of money,'' said Hatch, 64, as he left
the school.
</P>
<P>
   ``People out there know that the major media are trying to lead
them by the nose, telling them how to vote _ it's either (George
W.) Bush or (John) McCain. That's nonsense. And when I mention that
to voters, they say, `Doggone it, you're right.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Hatch entered the race late, about seven months ago. He carried
name-recognition and a resume that included sponsorship of scores
of bills, from patent-law reform to protections on the vitamin
industry.
</P>
<P>
   This year, however, Washington credentials may not be what the
Republican electorate is searching for, said Bruce Gronbeck,
professor of communication studies at the University of Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact, for the last 25 years, it's been pretty easy for a
candidate to run against Washington, especially if it's the party
out of office,'' Gronbeck said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Orrin Hatch is running an awfully low-profile campaign, almost
as if he's trying to position himself in a safe corner to pick up
the pieces if George W. destructs,'' he said. ``No catchy phrases.
Staying away from the Jesus issues. He's trying to be an eminently
reasonable, issues-centered politician.''
</P>
<P>
   A tall, blue-suit conservative and bishop in the Church of Jesus
Christ of Latter-day Saints, Hatch said, ``I do believe in helping
people who would help themselves if they could.''
</P>
<P>
   The senator himself rose from a childhood of selling live
chickens door-to-door. He landed a scholarship to Brigham Young
University and now sits as chairman of the Senate's powerful
Judiciary Committee, where in 1991 he staunchly defended U.S.
Supreme Court nominee Clarence Thomas against sexual-harassment
allegations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got experience money can't buy,'' he says. ``Steve Forbes
is a fine man, but before you run for president, don't you think
you should be elected to something?''
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 Hatch surprised both aisles in the Senate when he and
Democrat Edward Kennedy of Massachusetts co-sponsored a $24 billion
program to get states to provide health insurance for children of
low-income working parents. Hatch surprised them again when he and
Sen. Dianne Feinstein, a California Democrat, teamed up to craft
anti-tobacco legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the only candidate who has a proven record of getting both
sides together,'' Hatch said. ``The most famous duo in Washington
right now is the Hatch-Kennedy duo.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatch proposes getting rid of the capital-gains tax and all
federal estate and gift taxes.
</P>
<P>
   He upholds the Second Amendment. Instead of taking action
against firearms makers and legitimate dealers, Hatch vows to crack
down on criminals who use guns: 10 years in prison for a felon
possessing a gun, 20 years if the gun is fired and a life sentence
if somebody gets hurt.
</P>
<P>
   He's probably the most vocal member of the GOP pack when it
comes to addressing Clinton administration scandals. He says, ``I'm
going to bring morals back to the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   As for campaign-finance reform, Hatch claims to be a living
example, asking individuals to chip in at least $36 _ not that he
wouldn't love a lot more. He chose $36 because, on the day he
announced his campaign, Texas Gov. Bush had already raised $36
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a million people each gave me 36 bucks, I'd win this
thing,'' he said. Even Pierre Salinger, the press secretary to
Democratic presidents John Kennedy and Lyndon Johnson, mailed Hatch
$36.
</P>
<P>
   So far, he's raised a total of about $2.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch isn't used to losing elections, or even being involved in
a close race. His toughest Senate re-election fight came in 1982,
when he captured 58 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking from a car phone on Wednesday, Hatch said he'd be
content to finish anywhere but last in Iowa. And if a campaign
funded ``not by fat cats, but by skinny cats'' can catch fire, what
a terrific thing for politics, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, I'm not up here driving through five inches of snow in
northern Iowa for nothing,'' he said. ``But if people examine all
the candidates and decide they don't want me for president, I can
live with that.''
</P>
<P>
   The schoolchildren in Des Moines liked Hatch so much, several
surrounded him and asked for his autograph. ``To Jennifer,'' he
wrote for the girl who escorted him down the halls. ``You're a good
person. Always do what's right. Love, Orrin Hatch.''
</P>
<P>
   Dick Feerick, a campaign volunteer from Minneapolis, said under
his breath, ``Too bad they can't vote.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
