<SLUG> BC-STAFF-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN CENTURY ALLOWS NONTRADITIONAL FAMILY MEMBERS ON HEALTH
PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   American Century Investments took a brave step this month in
providing a new health insurance benefit to its employees _ so
brave that its underwriter declines to be revealed.
</P>
<P>
   The new benefit at the Kansas City-based mutual fund, brokerage
and investment company allows workers to include one nontraditional
household member in their employer-subsidized health-care coverage.
</P>
<P>
   For those who don't have or need to include a spouse in their
coverage, the new Plus One plan lets them include a sibling, an
in-law, a domestic partner or even a live-in nanny in their plan.
</P>
<P>
   Bravo to American Century for recognizing that ``family'' means
different things to different people at different times.
</P>
<P>
   American Century employees cannot include both a spouse and a
``nontraditional'' adult dependent. It's a choice. Therefore, the
company's overall health insurance costs aren't expected to rise
more than 1 to 2 percent, according to actuarial studies.
</P>
<P>
   Plus One may be in the vanguard of health insurance changes, but
it's not unique. Bank of America also allows employees to include a
dependent adult instead of a spouse in their coverage.
</P>
<P>
   One American Century employee has signed up his father-in-law,
who didn't have any health-care coverage. Another worker included
her sister, who is living with her and serving as her children's
nanny.
</P>
<P>
   American Century's benefits manager, Susie Rawlings, said the
company intended to do this for several years but was stymied by an
inability to find an underwriter.
</P>
<P>
   Even underwriters that had been involved in insuring domestic
partners were nervous about this largely untested coverage and
didn't want publicity until there was a financial history.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, the program has eligibility requirements. In the
first month, only 40 of American Century's 3,000 employees signed
up for it. But the company deserves credit for understanding that
employees do not live cookie-cutter lives.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the most pressing ``family'' need _ the one that most
affects a worker's peace of mind and ability to work _ deals with
the medical needs of someone other than a spouse or child.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, in many dual-income families, both husband and wife
have health insurance through their own employers. If a wife
doesn't need to put her husband on her policy, she may want to add
another adult (perhaps an adult child) who lives in the household
but has no group insurance.
</P>
<P>
   American Century, which is on Fortune magazine's ``100 Best
Companies to Work For'' list, eventually found an insurance partner
to underwrite its Plus One plan. I can't tell you who it is.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, trailblazing has uncertain outcomes, and it's easier
to lie low until public opinion and financial results are known.
Staying anonymous is a safe, conservative choice.
</P>
<P>
   But kudos to American Century and Bank of America for providing
and publicizing a benefit that will help attract and keep workers.
That's how companies get on ``best places to work'' lists.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-00 0109EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
