<SLUG> BC-KRACE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS BILL WOULD REQUIRE POLICE TO LOG RACE OF MOTORISTS THEY
STOP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN A. DVORAK  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOPEKA _ The Kansas Legislature is stepping into a simmering
national debate over whether police officers pay closer attention
to minorities when deciding to make traffic stops and other routine
searches.
</P>
<P>
   Under a bill proposed Wednesday, Kansas law enforcement agencies
would have to gather and disclose information about the racial
characteristics of drivers they pull over. The goal is to determine
whether officers treat minority motorists differently than white
motorists _ a practice commonly called racial profiling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am convinced racial profiling exists in Kansas and other
states,'' said Rep. David Haley, a Kansas City, Kan., Democrat who
helped prepare the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Proof, he acknowledged, is elusive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing is to find out if there's a problem,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about racial profiling have been asked for years.
Minority drivers, convinced they're more susceptible to speeding
tickets than non-minorities, may use another term _ DWB, driving
while black.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement agencies often deny they do things that way.
Frequently, however, hard statistics aren't available to show what
really goes on.
</P>
<P>
   The bill before the Legislature would provide some answers.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas Highway Patrol doesn't oppose the bill, said Sgt.
John Eichkorn, a spokesman for the patrol. In fact, he said, he
wants to see data about Highway Patrol traffic stops just as Haley
does.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to have that information,'' he said. ``We don't
believe there is a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill reflects a growing nationwide controversy, as
allegations crop up in state after state about minority drivers
being stopped allegedly because of their race.
</P>
<P>
   The issue drew prominent attention in New Jersey, where
minorities charged that state police practiced racial profiling
along the New Jersey Turnpike.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina and Connecticut have passed laws that require
police to track the racial and ethnic backgrounds of motorists
stopped by officers, and other states are considering such
measures. No similar bill has surfaced in the Missouri General
Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Laws on the issue have been proposed in Congress. And in June,
President Clinton, who called the practice of racial profiling
``morally indefensible,'' ordered federal law enforcement agencies
to compile statistics on the race of those singled out for routine
searches, such as traffic stops and border inspections.
</P>
<P>
   The issue has even crept into the campaign for the Democratic
nomination for president. On Monday, Vice President Al Gore and
former U.S. Sen. Bill Bradley exchanged sharp words about the issue
during a debate in Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Eichkorn of the Kansas Highway Patrol said troopers do not take
race into account when they decide to pull over a driver for
speeding.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the patrol studied people it arrested for drug
offenses in 1997 and 1998. About 14 percent were black, while half
the others were white and half were Hispanic.
</P>
<P>
   Under the bill proposed Wednesday, authorities would have to
record information about the race, color, ethnicity, gender and age
of those stopped for traffic violations.
</P>
<P>
   Also required would be information about the location of the
traffic stop, the nature of the alleged violation and the
disposition of the case.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement agencies such as the Highway Patrol, city police
departments and county sheriff's offices would be affected.
</P>
<P>
   Each year, they would have to send traffic-stop data to the
Kansas attorney general, who would then review the data and report
to the governor and Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   The Highway Patrol already gathers at least some of the
information required by the bill. But the information isn't
computerized and easily accessible.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Mike O'Neal, a Hutchinson Republican who is chairman of the
House Judiciary Committee, said he supports the concept of the
bill.
</P>
<P>
   It's not certain whether racial profiling occurs in Kansas, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't heard it's a problem,'' said O'Neal, who confers
frequently with judges and others in law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   Cost probably will be cited as a reason not to pass the bill.
</P>
<P>
   The Highway Patrol, already operating on a tight budget, would
have to assign staff to computerize traffic-stop data.
</P>
<P>
   Local police departments, depending on what data they collect
about their traffic stops, would also face additional costs,
perhaps substantial.
</P>
<P>
   State officials will study how much the bill would cost. The
expense estimates, O'Neal predicted, ``will choke a horse.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-00 0111EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000120.0028 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 01:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1145 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-CASSERLY-PLANS-HN     01-20 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CASSERLY-PLANS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN McCLAIN  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
The more he listened to NFL owners recommending former Washington
Redskins general manager Charley Casserly, the more impressed Bob
McNair became.
<TEXT>
<P>
   After spending a record $700 million to bring the NFL back to
Houston, McNair knew he couldn't afford to make a mistake when
hiring someone to run the football side of his operation.
</P>
<P>
   Casserly, who spent 22 seasons (1977-98) with the Redskins
before new owner Daniel Snyder fired him last preseason, wowed
McNair with his preparation, organization and dedication during
several telephone conversations and two long interviews in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   When Casserly was introduced as the executive vice
president/general manager of the NFL's latest expansion entry at a
news conference Wednesday, it was easy to see how McNair could be
so impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll start to work tomorrow,'' Casserly said after signing a
five-year contract. ``We want to get this thing up and running as
soon as possible so we can start scouting. Houston will be at the
(Indianapolis scouting) combine (Feb. 24-28).
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to hire a couple of administrative assistants and two
secretaries, plus a couple of interns. We have to get the computers
up and running so we can monitor league activity.''
</P>
<P>
   Casserly, 50, is a workaholic whose passion and enthusiasm for
football are contagious. Although he was involved at every level on
the personnel side of the Redskins operation, including negotiating
contracts and serving on NFL committees, his specialty is scouting.
</P>
<P>
   ``My challenge to Charley is to hire the best scouting staff
possible,'' McNair said. ``I agree with Charley on the importance
of scouting. We're long-term thinkers, and we know it's going to
take some time to get the team where we want it to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Casserly announced Wednesday that the unnamed team will be a
member of the BLESTO scouting combine, rather than National.
</P>
<P>
   The contracts of NFL scouts expire after the draft, which means
Casserly will have to wait until late April at the earliest to
begin hiring his. Depending on who is available, Casserly can fill
every scouting position, or he can keep a couple vacant until after
the 2001 draft.
</P>
<P>
   McNair and Casserly are talking about the size of the scouting
staff and how many directors they will have.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason we want to start scouting right away is that
statistics show that 70 percent of the players drafted each year
are cut within four years,'' Casserly said. ``Ten percent of those
cut continue playing with other teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``That means 80 percent of this year's draft will be cut, and
we're going to have a shot at them, either because they've been cut
or they become unrestricted free agents when their contracts
expire.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to go anywhere and everywhere. People around the
country are going to get sick of seeing scouts from Houston.''
</P>
<P>
   McNair was the main reason Casserly signed with Houston rather
than agree to formal interviews with the Steelers and Saints.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob's committed to running a first-class organization, and he
wants to build a winner,'' Casserly said. ``His philosophy is to
spend a lot of money to get the best possible people. We're not
going to waste money, but we know that you get what you pay for.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are going to be knocking down doors to work here.''
</P>
<P>
   Casserly plans to use the draft and free agency to build the
team. He has a huge advantage with an expansion team because he can
start from scratch with the salary cap at a time when most teams
are limited severely by it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to take advantage of both, but the foundation is
still the draft,'' he said. ``But it would be wrong to ignore the
free-agent market.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Redskins, Casserly experienced success and failure in
the draft and free agency, but he left Washington in such
outstanding shape that it won the NFC East this season and advanced
to the second round of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good about the way I left the Redskins,'' he said. ``I
left them with an outstanding quarterback (Brad Johnson) and three
No. 1 picks (this year). Hey, I'd like to take over a team like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he knew he was going to be looking for a new job once
the Redskins' sale to Daniel Snyder was completed in the offseason,
Casserly's objective to do what was best for the team never
changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew every day I went to work, I was fired,'' he said.
``When Dan Snyder officially took over the team, it was a matter if
I left then or in six months. I wanted to go then, so I could look
for another job.''
</P>
<P>
   Like other NFL personnel people, Casserly cautions fans about
getting so excited that they think Houston's expansion team will
have the early success of Carolina and Jacksonville rather than
stumble out of the gate like Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a fundamental difference in that there won't be as
many quality players available,'' Casserly said. ``When the
Panthers and Jaguars were starting, teams hadn't really figured out
free agency. Now, teams are doing a better job of signing their
best players to long-term deals.''
</P>
<P>
   McNair said Wednesday that the general manager was the most
important hire, followed by the head coach and quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to think seriously about hiring the head coach a
year from now,'' Casserly said, even though the team doesn't start
playing until the 2002 season. ``Bob will hire the head coach with
input from me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob and I have the same philosophy. Our first choice is to
have someone who's been successful as a head coach in the NFL or as
a head coach in college. I don't think there's any such thing as an
offensive head coach or a defensive head coach. The No. 1 thing I
look for is leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as the quarterback, you shouldn't force the issue. If
you have a chance to draft a franchise quarterback, I think the
ideal situation is to also sign a veteran quarterback who'll be
like a coach on the field. If there's not a quarterback worth that
pick, trade the pick or draft another player.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
