<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 01:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1146 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      01-20 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
IT'S about starting from the ground up and having someone at your
side who knows what it's like to get dirt under his fingernails.
</P>
<P>
   Just like you know.
</P>
<P>
   It's about starting with nothing, not even a name, and having
someone nearby who shares your vision of beauty even when others
see only a blank canvas.
</P>
<P>
   It's about taking chances and realizing that for every one
victory there will be two setbacks, but having someone nearby who,
like you, trusts his instincts because that's what has carried him
this far.
</P>
<P>
   As a young man, Bob McNair borrowed $2,000, leased a delivery
truck and opened his first business. Today, he is a billionaire.
</P>
<P>
   As a young man, Charley Casserly, then a schoolteacher, knocked
on legendary Redskins coach George Allen's door until his knuckles
ached. He finally earned a job with the Redskins as an unpaid
intern in 1977 and lived at the YMCA for $8 a night. Today, he owns
three Super Bowl rings.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to see why it didn't take McNair long to make Casserly
the first general manager of Houston's new NFL franchise.
</P>
<P>
   In Casserly, McNair sees something that bears a strong
resemblance to what he sees in the mirror every day. Casserly is
McNair's alter ego of sorts, someone who has done everything in
football that McNair has done in business.
</P>
<P>
   This match should work, but don't call it a match made in
heaven.
</P>
<P>
   It's a match made from so many shared experiences scratching in
the dirt and clawing to the top of their respective fields. McNair
and Casserly share not just the same dream but remarkably similar
backgrounds. And already there seems to be a trust forming between
the two that you'd never find in a resume.
</P>
<P>
   Such relationships are vital within any NFL franchise, but
perhaps more so with one that doesn't yet have so much as a chin
strap to its name, whatever that name might be.
</P>
<P>
   Distrust and incompatibility have splintered so many owner-GM
relationships before, including Casserly's with Redskins owner
Daniel Snyder last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew every day I went to work, I was fired,'' Casserly said
of his final Redskins experience. ``When Dan Snyder officially took
over the team, it was a matter if I left then or in six months.''
</P>
<P>
   To McNair's good fortune, Casserly left then and was available
now. Casserly never clicked with Snyder, the brazen one they call
``Kid Owner'' in D.C.
</P>
<P>
   But such should not be the case with Casserly's new boss. Like
McNair, Casserly is meticulously organized. When Casserly arrived
at McNair's office almost two weeks ago for his first face-to-face
meeting with Houston's NFL owner, he had under his arm detailed
manuals that outlined every aspect of his plan for building
Houston's team.
</P>
<P>
   From draft strategies to future free-agent possibilities,
coaching prospects and philosophies on building the football
organization, Casserly outlined his vision for McNair.
</P>
<P>
   McNair was blown away by Casserly's attention to detail. He then
made some calls to NFL insiders.
</P>
<P>
   Among those singing Casserly's praises were former Redskins
coach Joe Gibbs, former Jets coach Bill Parcells, Giants owner
Wellington Mara and Steelers owner Dan Rooney.
</P>
<P>
   ``The overwhelming response was that Charley demands respect in
the NFL,'' McNair said.
</P>
<P>
   Casserly, like McNair, also is less than flashy but hardly
bland. He answers questions directly and prides himself on
professionalism, preparedness and checking his ego at the door.
</P>
<P>
   He won't wow you with pizazz. But if the McNair-Casserly plan
works, he won't have to.
</P>
<P>
   It is a hard-working, direct style that carried Casserly from
intern to Super Bowl and had the Saints and Jets also courting his
services this month.
</P>
<P>
   It was Casserly who hired Norv Turner for the Redskins in 1994,
then promptly discarded older players as he began overhauling the
franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Casserly certainly made some draft mistakes along the way, most
notably selecting quarterback Heath Shuler out of Tennessee. And
ultimately, he fell out of favor with the new kid owner.
</P>
<P>
   But the Redskins were again in the playoffs this season, and it
was Casserly who acquired quarterback Brad Johnson, running back
Stephen Davis, receiver Michael Westbrook and cornerback Champ
Bailey. Casserly's deals also brought Washington three No. 1 picks
in the upcoming NFL draft.
</P>
<P>
   The man knows what it's like to start with nothing but a dream.
So does McNair.
</P>
<P>
   This could be the start of a beautiful friendship.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
