<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 01:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1153 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-GLF-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     01-20 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FIRST STEP FOR MARTIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIAN WELLS _ To his immense relief, Casey Martin didn't shoot
the temperature on a warm, windless Wednesday at the Bob Hope
Classic. He didn't whiff with his 3-wood at the first tee or push
any shot farther right than Rush Limbaugh.
</P>
<P>
   Martin's first official round as a card-carrying member of the
PGA Tour was a solid, if not scintillating, 4-under-par 68 at
Indian Wells Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   He missed only two fairways, but struggled with greens that were
harder to read than the fine print in a contract. His confidence
over putts deserted him, which is par for any course in the desert.
</P>
<P>
   On the back nine, Olin Browne, who played directly behind
Martin, used the occasion of one of the interminable, inevitable
logjams that dragged out Wednesday's round to ask how his fellow
pro was faring.
</P>
<P>
   Told that Martin had missed a three-foot par putt on his second
hole and too many birdie attempts to mention, Browne nodded
sympathetically. ``Join the club,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Browne, between swigs of water, explained it takes a few days to
adjust to the vagaries of the greens on the different courses and
that rookies such as Martin, who are seeing the tournament layouts
for the first time, are at a marked disadvantage.
</P>
<P>
   Great. That's all Martin needs; another handicap.
</P>
<P>
   Martin's quandary is that time is like golf's more hardened
traditionalists: It is decidedly not on his side.
</P>
<P>
   His right leg has been rendered so brittle as a result of a
congenital circulatory problem that constricts blood flow, his
doctors worry one day he is going to take a step and his leg will
snap like a twig. With Martin, it's not a question of if he's going
to lose his leg but when.
</P>
<P>
   Given how rushed he feels to groove his game, it's a small
wonder Martin didn't drive his cart into the foursome in front of
him on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows he's fighting a time bomb of sorts,'' said Martin's
father King. ``He wants to have positive experiences early because
he knows, realistically, he's not going to be out here a long time
no matter how he plays.''
</P>
<P>
   It'd be bad enough if the only sound Martin heard was his own
physiological clock ticking. But he also has to try to tune out all
the strident voices of people who are quick to nit-pick his
performance, holding every missed putt or imperfect swing against
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are quick to critique Casey,'' King Martin
said.
</P>
<P>
   That isn't just an overprotective father talking. We heard it
ourselves, following Martin around outside the gallery ropes.
</P>
<P>
   When he drove a couple feet left of the fairway on his second
hole, someone said the way he sprays his shots, it's a good thing
he gets to use a cart.
</P>
<P>
   When Martin missed a two-foot birdie putt on his third hole, one
man remarked to another that he doesn't appear to have the putting
stroke to succeed at this level.
</P>
<P>
   On it went for nearly five hours, this eyeing of Martin's game
through some invisible magnifying glass.
</P>
<P>
   All we can say is being rich and retired must mean never having
to consider how your own work would have held up under the same
scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   It's a shame more people _ besides the reporters who made up the
majority of his gallery _ didn't check out Martin's PGA Tour debut.
</P>
<P>
   It was hard not to slip into a sympathy limp, watching Martin
lumber the 92 steps from the 10th green to the 11th tee. The fact
is, between green and tee, golf remains for Martin a good walk
spoiled by his obvious pain.
</P>
<P>
   There were a few holes where Martin could have sat his aching
leg down in his cart after hitting off the tee. He chose instead to
stand and engage in small talk with his playing partners. To a man,
they later would describe Martin, 27, as a gentleman and a joy to
be paired with.
</P>
<P>
   If only it were that easy to win over his fellow touring pros.
</P>
<P>
   The PGA Tour can be as cruel and cliquish a place as high
school. It is an environment where friendships often are forged or
forgotten on the basis of one's ranking on the money list.
</P>
<P>
   There are players who get bent out of shape when someone else
gets a better courtesy car. We shudder to think how they feel about
Martin being a media magnet before he posts a top-10 finish.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, for his part, is doing his best to throw the media off
his scent. He shifted uncomfortably when surrounded by reporters
after his round and said it makes him uneasy getting the amount of
attention ``that only a handful of guys have to deal with and most
of them are exceptional at the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin dearly wants to belong. His father's most fervent hope is
he is given a fair chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know how much it means to him to be accepted in this
setting,'' King Martin said. ``My biggest hope for him is he can
get to the point where he's really not an outcast, even though he's
suing the PGA.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin's 68 was a step in the right direction. A few more rounds
like that and his ball-striking will be what people remember, not
his disability. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-00 0158EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
