<SLUG> BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONICS GETTING SMARTER, BUT SO ARE ABSENT FANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Winning six games in a row, including triumphs over the Spurs
and Lakers, has left the Sonics just a couple of games behind their
1996 pace that took them to the Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Always eccentric and occasionally electric, this group has one
thing going for it that is not often said of most NBA teams: Week
by week, the Sonics seem to be getting a little smarter.
</P>
<P>
   Fewer foolish shots. More defensive awareness. Better use of
talent. They have yet to lose to a team with a sub-.500 record.
</P>
<P>
   The points are mentioned as a public service because eyewitness
accounts of these developments are increasingly rare.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics have the NBA's fourth-worst attendance (15,474
average).
</P>
<P>
   That's just the paid count. KeyArena's empty-seat acreage
indicates a lot of ticketholders can't give their tickets away.
</P>
<P>
   The latest example was Tuesday, when the club claimed 13,326 in
paid attendance, a figure that looked generous by about 2,000.
While Cleveland at 16-21 is hardly a glam outfit, it does have
Shawn Kemp.
</P>
<P>
   The former Seattle hero heard applause and heckles that barely
qualified as a smattering. The event had the zip of an Al Gore
concert.
</P>
<P>
   The decline isn't unique to Seattle. NBA attendance is down
nearly 10 percent. But when a place accustomed to sellouts suddenly
finds itself barely ahead of bottom feeders Vancouver (15,391),
Golden State (15,317) and the L.A. Clippers (15,217), the Sonics
are in serious hurt.
</P>
<P>
   As if that insult weren't enough for the franchise, embarrassing
national injury was added Tuesday when the Supreme Court let stand
a $7.4 million judgment against the Sonics and owner Barry Ackerley
for being a grinch of an employer.
</P>
<P>
   Ackerley refused to pay overtime to a group of Sonics ticket
sellers, who were fired around Christmas 1994 for pursuing their
rights. At the trial in Seattle federal court, the jury said club
management's ``conduct was malicious or in reckless disregard'' of
the former employees' rights, and made Barry, as well as his son,
Bill, personally liable, along with the company.
</P>
<P>
   Legions of ex-Ackerley employees around town undoubtedly cheered
the news that someone finally got a piece of a guy whose
belligerence and litigiousness is his civic legacy. But the massive
hit charged against the Sonics' corporate entity, Full House
Entertainment, cannot bode well.
</P>
<P>
   While it will be claimed that the damages have nothing to do
with the team, the fact is the basketball operation seems destined
to lose money for a second consecutive year, following the lockout
debacle that reduced the 1998-99 season to 25 home games, as well
as no playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Losing money again, for a franchise that has delivered more
consistent sports entertainment than any other in the market, is
the sign of bad management, locally and nationally, as well as a
decaying product.
</P>
<P>
   The management problem is not just employee-rights abuse. The
Sonics and all NBA teams operate under a new collective bargaining
agreement. The downside includes giving long-term, guaranteed
contracts at maximum values to young veterans vulnerable to flops
for non-health reasons.
</P>
<P>
   That was the riskiest aspect of last summer's $87 million deal
for Vin Baker following an abysmal season. Although Baker has
picked up his game considerably, his occasional disappearances
haunt the Sonics because so much is invested in him.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the rules allowed president Wally Walker no real choice.
Each one of Walker's peers would have made the same decision. But
that doesn't reduce a basketball follower's sense of grievously
misplaced reward.
</P>
<P>
   When fans see the Sonics pick up free agents such as Billy
Owens, a mediocre player who can't even stay in shape to earn his
millions, the disaffection is compounded. When a popular,
successful, colorful coach such as George Karl is cashiered for
reasons not obvious to the average customer, alienation takes root,
and doesn't go away with a one-point win over the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   But the capper comes when teams raise ticket prices to witness
this distortion of what was once America's hottest game.
</P>
<P>
   The league's average ticket price increased this season 13.8
percent to $48.37, excluding suites, according to Team Marketing
Report of Chicago. That's American sports' highest, outstripping
the gouge from the NHL ($45.70) and NFL ($45.63).
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics' average price is $64.60, behind only the Knicks and
Lakers. Although the Sonics dispute a part of the calculation, that
doesn't change the jaw-dropping fact that middle-class fans are
being asked to pay $60 to see the current NBA, particularly after
its surreal underbelly was exposed by the lockout.
</P>
<P>
   The lockout gave labor-cost certainty to the owners, and
guaranteed lifetime security to players. The fans received neither
cost certainty nor the security the game would go on as it once
did.
</P>
<P>
   While the Sonics on the KeyArena floor are getting smarter and
better, the franchise and league have gone the other way.
</P>
<P>
   The one perversely redeeming aspect is that fans have finally
registered their feelings the only way available to them _ by
becoming non-fans.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel
</P>
<P>
   can be reached at 206-448-8135
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
