<HEADLINE>
JACKSON WAKES UP KOBE, LAKERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Unstoppable or unwatchable, the Lakers are showing
themselves to be a remarkably versatile bunch.
</P>
<P>
   Their 16-game winning streak is a fading memory. Their latest
significant trend, a pair of losses in a recent three-game span.
</P>
<P>
   And for their signature moment Wednesday night -- coach Phil
Jackson giving a very public verbal whipping to young Kobe Bryant
for a critical fourth-quarter turnover, as the Lakers tripped over
themselves while grap pling with the Cleveland Cavaliers.
</P>
<P>
   But Bryant responded, the Lakers regained their balance, and a
win even tually did follow. There just wasn't much in the 95-86
victory for Jackson, or18,997 fans at Staples Center, to get
excited about.
</P>
<P>
   And on the heels of Monday's home loss to Seattle, there was new
reason to worry about the Lakers' collective health.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're diseased,'' Jackson mused. ``We're not at ease
right now. We've got to figure out how we want to play as a
basketball team and get cohesive again. We had real good cohesion
and it worked great for us . We have to get back to that.''
</P>
<P>
   They had it, at least, for stretches of the fourth quarter, when
the La kers -- who trailed for most of three quarters -- outscored
the Cavaliers 28-13. Even as they pulled away, however, there was
tension.
</P>
<P>
   After finally regaining the lead, 83-79, midway through the
fourth, Bryant got too fancy, losing his dribble to Bobby Sura.
Brevin Knight cashed in the turnover for an 18-foot jumper at the
other end, prompting a Laker timeout and a Jackson lecture.
</P>
<P>
   In one of his most animated moments as Laker coach, Jackson
bellowed at Bryant, who furrowed his own brow as he yelled back.
But the intense exchange was short and to the point, and quickly
forgotten, as Bryant scored four of the Lakers' last 12 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted it to register with him,'' Jackson said of his
tirade. ``That we don't want to have this happen. We've gone
through this a couple times, where situations can get critical in
ballgames, that's something we don't need to have happen. But Kobe
played a fine game tonight. Stat-wise, there's a lot of things out
there to be said about his game.''
</P>
<P>
   The most glaring was the six turnovers, but Bryant also had 25
points (on 6-of-15 shooting) and 13 rebounds, four assists and two
blocked shots .
</P>
<P>
   And one earful of a lecture.
</P>
<P>
   Said Bryant: ``I told him, I said, look, I try to make a play
sometimes , and I know it doesn't come out, it doesn't happen the
right way sometimes, but I'm out there, trying my heart out. And he
said it's cool, just put it behind you, just move on to the next
play, buckle down and win t his game.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant did, but the criticism stung.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took it hard,'' he said. ``I was ticked off. That's your
natural reaction, man. You want to go out there and you want to win
the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson made his point, though. ``He's here to teach, I'm here
to learn ,'' Bryant said.
</P>
<P>
   In the undercard, Shaquille O'Neal took turns abusing undersized
Cavs centers Mark Bryant (6-foot-9), Kornel David (6-9, 230) and
Andrew DeClercq (6-10) and finished with 27 points and 23 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland's calling card is former All-Star forward Shawn Kemp,
but it was the Cavaliers' zippy guards that kept the Lakers
off-balance all night. Rookie Andre Miller dashed and drove for 20
points, Knight got 15 and Sura had nine. Kemp, meanwhile, fouled
out in the fourth with just 14 points.
</P>
<P>
   And the Lakers, who trailed by as many as 15 points in the
second half, proved once again they can win with one good quarter,
even while shooting 34.6 percent for the game.
</P>
<P>
   But they have gone more than a week since their last solid win,
and faces are growing longer as the Lakers try to rediscover their
magic touch. They'll need it soon -- the Portland Trail Blazers
arrive Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to explain,'' said Glen Rice, who finished with 17
points on 3-for-13 shooting. ``We're going to try to find the
answers tomorrow.''
</P>
</TEXT>
