<HEADER>
A1179 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-CLIMATE-PACIFIC-SFCHR     01-20 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLIMATE-PACIFIC-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OCEAN DATA SUGGEST SHIFT IN WEATHER
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CARL T. HALL 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  Fresh hints of a long-term shift in Pacific sea temperatures
that might affect West Coast weather for the next 20 years or more
were reported Wednesday.
<P>
   Studying the latest satellite pictures of the Pacific,
scientists at NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory in Pasadena noted
the outlines of a ``giant horseshoe pattern'' of warm ocean water
beginning to dominate the entire western Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   The pattern, part of a mysterious phenomenon known as the
Pacific Decadal Oscillation, tends to be much longer-lasting but
more subtle than the well-known El Nino and La Nina events, which
can have powerful weather-warping effects.
</P>
<P>
   For the Bay Area, a new phase in the Pacific Decadal Oscillation
would mean a generation of more frequent, longer-lasting La Ninas
and dryer, cooler winters. It would mean more stormy weather
further north and in the Pacific Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   For the Southwest, it would probably mean drier than normal
weather, while the Southeast could have warmer weather and more
hurricanes. Storms and snowpack would increase in the Northwest and
Rocky Mountain states. Northern states would have lower winter
temperatures.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble is, nobody knows what might trigger a shift from one
phase to another, or even how to tell whether a shift has occurred
until years after the fact.
</P>
<P>
   ``This might fade away by summer,'' said Tom Murphree, a climate
scientist at the Naval Postgraduate School in Monterey.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is it easy to gauge just how the long-term pattern plays out
one season to the next.
</P>
<P>
   All agree that we are now in an extended La Nina, an event that
occurs in the equatorial Pacific but affects weather in both
hemispheres. It is indirectly tied to cooler-than-normal water
sitting along the California coast, for example, a factor cited for
this year's lower-than-average rainfall and light snowfall in
California's Sierra Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   The question is how long the current patterns might continue.
</P>
<P>
   Most climate experts expect La Nina to begin breaking up soon.
But if the past year proves to be the start of a new phase in the
Pacific Decadal Oscillation, what had seemed to be a fleeting event
could linger well into the new century.
</P>
<P>
   Experts have less than 100 years of observations to go on, so
the timetable amounts to little more than a guess. Moreover, each
cold or warm phase of the Pacific Decadal Oscillation can have
numerous La Ninas and El Ninos within it, further complicating
predictions.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Bill Patzert, oceanographer at the Jet Propulsion
Laboratory, said the most recent satellite data suggest that
``there is much more than an isolated La Nina occurring in the
Pacific Ocean.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest data were based on satellite readings of the Pacific
made from December 30 through January 8 by the U.S. French
TOPEX/Poseidon satellite.
</P>
<P>
   Water temperatures are inferred from sea surface heights, which
the satellite can determine with astonishing accuracy.
</P>
<P>
   Sea surfaces were found to be in a range three to nine inches
lower than normal, associated with cooler-than-normal water, all
along the Pacific coast of Central and South America.
</P>
<P>
   But the scientists are paying especially close attention to the
so-called ``giant horseshoe'' of warmer water, which appears to
have been expanding for the past year, dominating the northern,
western and southern Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   Taken as a whole, the data appear to be consistent with the
beginnings of what is technically known as a cold or ``negative''
phase in the Pacific Oscillation. But it's far too soon to be
certain.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're talking about something that takes a decade, and you
are looking at a snapshot of data taken over a matter of weeks or
months,'' said David Battisti, atmospheric sciences professor at
the University of Washington. ``You really can't conclude anything
from this snapshot.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the long-term climate variability from Northern
California to Alaska is explained by shifts in the decadal
oscillation, he noted, making the phenomenon a favorite topic of
research.
</P>
<P>
   From the mid-1970s to the mid-'90s, warmer-than-normal water
conditions prevailed off the West Coast, while seas were colder
than normal in the Central and northern Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   That was the warm phase of the Pacific Decadal Oscillation.
``The pattern does look different now,'' Battisti said, although he
emphasized that the ``pattern'' could just as easily be a fluke.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
