<HEADLINE>
DUCKS SURPRISE STARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN   
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- The Mighty Ducks waived a veteran, brought up a pair
of kids and held a players-only meeting Tuesday. One win since the
New Year and a fading shot at the playoffs facilitates changes.
</P>
<P>
   Coming off perhaps their worst performance of the season, the
Ducks played with the urgency and passion needed to win. They
battled for loose pucks, played with toughness, paid attention to
the game plan and for the first time in 17 tries won a game with a
third-period rally. Paul Kariya, who pointed the finger at himself
for not playing well during the doldrums, scored twice in
three-goal third as the Ducks beat the injury-riddled Dallas Stars
3-1 Wednesday in front of 13,723 at the Pond.
</P>
<P>
   Kariya's wrist shot from the slot gave the Ducks a 2-1 lead with
13:19 left in the game, but that's not the goal that embodied the
Ducks' second win in 11 games. Instead, it was his hustle that
created his open net goal with 0.1 seconds remaining that the
tell-tale sign of why the Ducks won.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a night where we needed some strong leadership, and we
certainly got it from Paul,'' Anaheim coach Craig Hartsburg said.
``He was outstanding, especially in the third period when you need
your best players and captain to step up, and he certainly did for
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Kariya left the ice with under a minute to play after getting
hit in the face inadvertently with a stick. He returned, blood
dribbling down his face, to outrace Dallas' Brett Hull and dive to
knock the puck into the open net. It capped the Ducks' first win
when trailing after two periods. They were 0-15-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played our system very well (and) we stayed patient,'' said
Kariya, who has a team-high 22 goals. ``The main thing was just to
be a team ag ain. We had gotten away from that. Things weren't
going well and guys got off the program. It happens. We had to get
back to playing a team game .''
</P>
<P>
   And while the roster moves and meeting may provide nothing but a
short-term fix, it certainly beats the alternatives. ``I think
we've been working hard but had no results so it's been frustr
ating,'' Ducks goalie Guy Hebert said after his 21-save
performance. ``I think we're just sick of losing.''
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim's scoreless drought reached 128 minutes, 56 seconds
before Antti Aalto beat Dallas goalie Manny Fernandez on a
bad-angle backhander 1:08 into the third period to tie it 1-1.
Momentum swung fully toward the Du cks less than a minute later Joe
Nieuwendyk was knocked from the game with a separated right
shoulder thanks to a crunching check by Jeff Nielsen.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: After waiving left wing Jim McKenzie on Tuesday, the
Ducks recall ed left wing Maxim Balmochnykh, 20, and defenseman
Vitaly Vishnevski, 19 , and both made their NHL debuts against the
Stars. ...Ducks winger Stu Grimson is out three to four weeks with
a broken left hand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
