<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 09:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1197 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN21-COX     01-20 0554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Rebel flag represents worst of Southern heritage
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many in South Carolina say the Confederate battle flag that
flies over the state capitol symbolizes racism. Many others say it
symbolizes southern heritage.
</P>
<P>
   And the difference would be...?
</P>
<P>
   This is an argument over a distinction without a difference, for
the only southern heritage the flag represented and represents was
the Civil War. South Carolina led the way in secession, attempting
with other southern states to break up the United States in order
to preserve a regional economy based on slavery, and a slavery
based on race.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to Confederate apologists then and now, without slavery
there never would have been a Civil War. Period.
</P>
<P>
   The flag was struck at the end of that war and was not unfurled
again until it became the informal ensign of a post-Reconstruction
South that was forcing legal segregation on black southerners and
stripping them of their citizenship rights. It since has been taken
up by every clod who mistakes his whiteness for a state of grace.
</P>
<P>
   The battle flag was incorporated into the Mississippi state flag
in the 1890s to fly over the state's enactment of Jim Crow laws. It
was added to the Georgia state flag in 1956 as part of that state's
defiance of Supreme Court rulings outlawing racial segregation.
</P>
<P>
   At least South Carolina is flying the flag more or less by
inadvertence. It was hoisted over the capitol in 1962 as part of a
national centennial observance of the Civil War. It was to have
come down at the end of that four-year period. But raised benignly,
it has been keep aloft perniciously _ a rallying standard for every
dewy-eyed Confederate romantic and racial bully in the state and
for many outside it.
</P>
<P>
   You want southern heritage? Try this: The South was a full
partner in the founding of the nation and the American revolution.
During Reconstruction it led the way in progressive social
legislation, not least by spreading public education. It was a
pillar of the politically venturesome New Deal. Its most decent
people, often at huge personal risk, overcame segregation. It has
produced some of the nation's richest literature. Its sons and
daughters have fought and served honorably in every American war --
including, yes, the Civil War, when they fought foolishly as well.
</P>
<P>
   Why on Earth would some folks _ no, let's be plain here: why
would some white people want to characterize their region by the
worst idea it ever had and the most tragic four years of its long
history? We know why, don't we?
</P>
<P>
   There's another upside to southern heritage, too _ the civility
for which the region has been rightly known. That's fading but
survives in reasonably hardy remnant.
</P>
<P>
   Black southerners have been trying to tell white southerners for
a hundred years that many bad things and no good ones have happened
to them under Confederate colors. They are frightened and
embarrassed and insulted by the battle flag.
</P>
<P>
   Simple politeness alone ought to retire the flag to museums.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
