<DOCNO> NYT20000120.0052 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 09:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1198 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-mintjim20     01-20 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-mintjim20 </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMN ON ROCKER
</P>
<P>
   BY:JIM MINTER
</P>
<P>
   C.2000 COX NEWS SERVICE
</P>
<P>
   Pardon me for venturing a bit deeper than my usual frustrations
with low-fat cooking, blossom end rot, fire ants, Japanese beetles
and being unable to reach a live human being on the telephone.
However, I don't want to be the only newspaper columnist in America
who failed to dive into the John Rocker affair.
</P>
<P>
   Seldom in the history of journalism has so much been said and
written about so little. Who is John Rocker? Is he the secretary of
state or something? A member of Congress? Head of some powerful
organization? A college professor? Of course not.
</P>
<P>
   He is a name that in certain times of the year appears at the
tail end of a baseball box score. Beyond mindless entertainment,
what he has to say, one way or the other, amounts in public issue
to not much more than a spit into the Atlantic Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Of all that I've read in the newspapers and heard on television,
Furman Bisher and Andy Young are the two who haven't gone off the
deep end. Bisher, The Atlanta Journal's ``senior sports
columnist,'' examined precisely what Rocker said to the Sports
Illustrated reporter. What he said wasn't as inflammatory as the
reaction. How many Braves fans, for example, have not entertained a
suspicion that the laid-back, board room demeanor of the team's
overpaid superstars has not contributed to World Series failures?
</P>
<P>
   Writing in The Constitution, Andy Young, who once created his
own controversy with a reference to ``smart ass white boys,''
suggested that ``The 100 Percent Wrong Club, Atlanta's oldest black
sports club, should honor John Rocker for bringing his reactionary
attitudes into the open where they can be addressed in the Atlanta
style - with humor, truth and reconciliation.'' (Humor, truth and
reconciliation should be in bold capital letters).
</P>
<P>
   ``After all,'' Young continued, ``similar insecurities and fears
are just beneath the surface in many of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of us also tend to run off at the mouth without real
meanness or hatred. Count me in. Although I certainly don't hate
teenagers, my granddaughter being one, I'm inclined to mumble
uncomplimentary remarks about ``idiot teenage drivers.'' In
traffic, I've been known to cuss ``old fools,'' of which I am one.
</P>
<P>
   When kids see snowy white heads behind steering wheels they
refer to them as ``Q-tips.'' The label is somewhat derogatory to
elderly drivers, but not without a touch of humor.
</P>
<P>
   Metro Atlanta is adapting to the new experience of Third World
immigration, particularly workers from south of the border. Many
speak, or read, little English, if any at all. They are unfamiliar
with streets and highways. They are here because they are poor, and
being poor, they chug along on expressways in dilapidated cars and
pickup trucks, trying to figure out where they're going.
</P>
<P>
   I suspect that many decent citizens, in the heat of rush hour
traffic, have referred to such drivers in uncomplimentary terms
that while innocuous within the confines of a private automobile,
would not wash in a national magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Having been a sportswriter in another life, I can guess how
Rocker was helped to present himself as the most bigoted Georgian
since the late J.B. Stoner. I know how a large ego new to the
limelight can be encouraged to make outrageous statements to fit a
supposed macho image. I also know that a reporter, within ethical
boundaries of good journalism, can ask: ``Look fellow, do you know
what you are saying? Do You really mean that?'' The answer is part
of the story.
</P>
<P>
   ``During my tenure as ambassador to the United Nations in the
1970s,'' Andrew Young wrote, ``the New York press even goaded me
into a series of headlines that served only to make my work more
difficullt. And there was not the pressure of 60,000 sports fans
shouting at me. I know what it's like to be taunted, and it's not
hard for me to walk a mile in John's shoes.''
</P>
<P>
   I don't know John Rocker, and have no desire to make his
acquaintance. One reason I got out of sportswriting shortly after
major league sports came to town was becaue I didn't like dealing
with smart-ass professional jocks. Over the years my regard for the
species has dwindled.
</P>
<P>
   I do know somebody who knows John Rocker very well. This person,
who is far from being a racist and a bigot, tells me that offstage
he is a nice enough fellow. He may be. Most people are.
</P>
<P>
   Vigilante journalism scares me, even when practiced in what
practitioners think is a good cause. It can do more harm than a
popoff professional athlete who has learned to throw
100-mile-an-hour strikes but not how to keep his mouth shut.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody in his right mind falls for the baseball commissioner's
ploy of shipping Rocker off to be examined by a psychologist in
Baltimore. If the Braves want to cure what ails John Rocker, the
smartest thing they can do is send him to dinner with Andy Young.
If that happened, the Braves would have a better pitcher, Mr. and
Mrs. Rocker would have a better son, and Atlanta would be a better
community. I'd bet on it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-00 0932EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000120.0053 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 10:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1240 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN23-CO     01-20 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Castro flourishes as a victim
 &HT;    For release Jan. 23, 2000.
 &HT;    By HOWARD KLEINBERG
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Every once in a while, I pause to take note that Fidel
Castro has won another round, either with the United States or the
Cuban exiles in this country. He is a remarkable man in his own
tyrannical way. He has managed to position himself as the enduring
victim.
</P>
<P>
   Through the 41 years of U.S. embargo, Castro has used that act
to rally his people. He blames all wrongs on the United States and
his gullible people believed it then and believe it now.
</P>
<P>
   With each crisis that has developed between the cross-straits
countries, Castro has emerged a victor. In the early 1960s, when
exile Cubans were making nominal military forays on the island's
coast, Castro turned out to be the big winner when his Soviet
benefactors insisted, as a price for withdrawing their missiles
from the island, that exile incursions be barred by the U.S.
government. Exiles never have forgiven John Kennedy for giving that
assurance.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariel Boatlift of the early 1980s was another Castro
victory _ of sorts. While it is true that about 100,000 truly
disenchanted people managed to flee the island then, Castro also
used the occasion to dump many of his criminals and criminally
insane onto Florida's shore.
</P>
<P>
   The signs coming from Havana that a capitalist-based economy is
beginning to emerge, compliments of participating countries such as
Canada and Spain, show that our embargo (and prestige) is futile.
</P>
<P>
   It is said that Canadians and Europeans by the thousands go to
Cuba on vacation but only once. Outside the hotel, the environment
is not one tuned to tourists. Nevertheless, millions of dollars
have poured into Havana by foreign companies, while the U.S. sits
on the outside, not just looking in but trying to get compensation
for what was taken away without payment by the Castro revolution.
</P>
<P>
   The latest drama around the six-year-old Elian Gonzalez may be
as big a victory for Castro as any of the others. His emissaries
have gone to the pope and to European capitals to plead that their
little Elian be returned to his father.
</P>
<P>
   He has rallied the Cuban people to march by the hundreds of
thousands demanding the return of Elian. Cuban flags, on both sides
of the Straits of Florida, are as abundant as are mosquitoes in
August.
</P>
<P>
   Again, Fidel tells his people, the United States is a bogey man
who has kidnapped one of his children. Even polls in the United
States show an overwhelming majority in favor of the child's
return. But, I suspect Castro would not like that to happen just
yet.
</P>
<P>
   He's enjoying the moment. Any grumbling in Cuba about human
rights, economics or quality of life is set aside for the moment.
Everyone's out in the streets waving flags or photos of Elian. The
few perennial dissenters who have not yet been jailed feel awfully
alone today.
</P>
<P>
   Castro is the shrewdest and most durable of all dictators. He
successfully purged his country of dissenters -- either by firing
squad, prison, or emigration -- got the U.S. to impede exile
counter-revolutionary activity, brought the pope into Havana as a
stage prop, enticed the Baltimore Orioles to come down, play and
shake hands, all the while showing zero tolerance for human rights.
</P>
<P>
   He has become more than a thorn in our side. As his resilience
continues, and as exile frustration builds, the argument over Elian
tears at the pollsters, editorialists and political activists in
the United States. There were no demonstrations in Havana against
the return of the child; not allowed.
</P>
<P>
   And when the United States eventually, and properly, returns
Elian to his father, Fidel will have won another victory _ not
based on his own policy but on U.S. policy that hasn't known what
to do about Castro for more than four decades.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-00 1033EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
