<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 10:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1248 &Cx1f; sci-z
r l BC-CLOT-THICKENS-ART-NYT     01-20 1405
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLOT-THICKENS-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CLOT THICKENS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from DISCOVER
magazine, contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!----------------------
 &HT;    TWO COLOR SLIDES are available FREE OF CHARGE to purchasers of
this article. The art can be sent ELECTRONICALLY by e-mail. Please
specify that you want the art when you order the article.
 &HT;    ----------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``l'' lifestyle news and ``a'' general news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By KAREN WRIGHT  
 c.2000 Discover magazine  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   For decades, heart disease has been the No. 1 killer in the
United States. But the underlying cause of heart disease has eluded
its pursuers. High cholesterol levels, for example, have never
correlated well with heart disease. Most heart attacks happen to
people with normal levels.
</P>
<P>
   And while medical researchers understand how cholesterol builds
up in a damaged patch of artery, they've never proven that
cholesterol itself does the initial damage.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's because it doesn't. A rogue theory of heart-disease
progression holds that another player is at work. The suspect is
homocysteine, a byproduct of protein breakdown that can damage
blood vessels and provoke the cascade of events that leads to
plaques and clotting.
</P>
<P>
   The homocysteine theory has recently won the grudging acceptance
of the medical establishment, and homocysteine is now recognized by
the American Heart Association as a potential risk factor.
</P>
<P>
   The tale of homocysteine's treachery even has a hero. Kilmer
McCully was a promising young graduate of Harvard Medical School in
the 1960s when he heard about a rare disease called homocystinuria.
Researchers knew little about the disease except that it produced
high levels of homocysteine in a patient's urine.
</P>
<P>
   Victims often died in childhood of vascular complications such
as heart attack and stroke.
</P>
<P>
   McCully wondered if there could be a connection between these
unusual fatalities and high homocysteine levels. When he examined
tissue from two child victims, he noted the characteristic plaques
of arteriosclerosis. Strangely, however, the plaques were not
associated with any fat deposits.
</P>
<P>
   In 1969 he wrote a paper proposing that homocysteine might
influence the development of heart disease in the population at
large.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was published in a good journal by reputable people, and it
was sort of ignored,'' McCully says.
</P>
<P>
   McCully decided to follow his hunch anyway. In his lab at
Massachusetts General Hospital in Boston, he did studies on animals
and tissue cultures to test how homocysteine interacts with other
substances in the body and with the linings of veins and arteries.
</P>
<P>
   Homocysteine comes from the breakdown of an amino acid called
methionine, which is abundant in meat and dairy products. McCully
discovered that the homocysteine molecule is metabolized by enzymes
that act in concert with B vitamins: B12, which comes from meat,
seafood and dairy products, and B6 and folic acid, which are both
abundant in vegetables and whole grains.
</P>
<P>
   He knew that patients with homocystinuria had genetic defects
that disabled these enzymes. But he reasoned that a B-vitamin
deficiency in an otherwise healthy person could shut down the
enzymes as well. In fact, homocysteine could be concentrated in the
blood of anyone who ate a lot of animal protein and didn't get
enough B vitamins to process it completely.
</P>
<P>
   McCully found out that such an accumulation could be bad news
for blood vessels. His experiments and many others since then have
shown that homocysteine can damage cells in the vascular linings,
interfere with the constriction and dilation of blood vessels, and
promote blood clotting. That damage is a first step in the scarring
and hardening of arteries; the deposits of fat and cholesterol that
build up over these scars are often the last step in heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   And to make matters worse, because homocysteine is transported
in low-density, or ``bad,'' cholesterol, it could be playing a
crucial role in the cardiovascular problems associated with high
cholesterol levels.
</P>
<P>
   The more McCully learned about homocysteine, the more convinced
he became of his theory. But he was trained as a biochemist and
pathologist, not as a clinician. Although he could decipher
homocysteine's mechanism of action, he wasn't equipped to undertake
the human trials that might have validated his suspicions.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the establishment,'' he adds, ``felt that until it was
proven in patients, (the theory) probably was wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Wrong'' wasn't the half of it. When McCully first made his key
observations, the cholesterol model of heart disease was wowing
cardiologists. There was no need for an alternative theory. And for
a decade or so, McCully was one of only a handful of scientists who
appreciated the complicated biochemistry of homocysteine
metabolism.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1970s, he couldn't find funding for his medical
research and wound up working as a pathologist at a Veterans
Affairs hospital in Providence, R.I. (where he has remained). But
he persisted in publishing modest studies funded by a
better-established colleague's grant.
</P>
<P>
   Then about a decade ago, results from some of the first major
long-term studies of heart disease began to trickle in. To
McCully's surprise, many included data on homocysteine. To everyone
else's surprise, the data revealed significant correlations between
homocysteine and heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   In a study of almost 15,000 physicians, for example, those whose
homocysteine levels were highest had more than three times the risk
of heart attack as those whose levels were lowest.
</P>
<P>
   In an ongoing 50-year study of the population of Framingham,
Mass., an examination of more than 1,000 seniors found that
homocysteine levels corresponded to clogging of the arteries in the
neck. About 80 trials have suggested that elevated homocysteine is
associated with hardening or blockage of blood vessels.
</P>
<P>
   The homocysteine hypothesis suddenly became respectable.
McCully's colleagues cite several reasons for the theory's belated
acceptance. In addition to the cholesterol prejudice, there's the
fact that, until recently, measuring homocysteine levels was
costly, difficult and time-consuming. But the latest homocysteine
blood tests are fast and affordable.
</P>
<P>
   Most experts agree that there's a desperate need for a long-term
study to evaluate whether lowering homocysteine levels will in fact
help to prevent heart disease. But they say that even if the
connection holds up, homocysteine won't entirely eclipse the other,
more familiar, risk factors such as age, weight, smoking, blood
pressure and cholesterol levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't say, `Well, I'll take folic acid and eat whatever I
want and I'll be protected,''' says Craig Scott, a cardiologist at
the University of Pennsylvania. High homocysteine levels don't
guarantee a heart attack, he says, and low levels won't rule one
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I do recommend folic acid for all my patients,'' Scott
says. ``It's something that everybody who's at risk for coronary
disease should consider doing as an adjunct.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately such recommendations may scuttle efforts to prove
once and for all the merits of the homocysteine hypothesis. Federal
guidelines introduced in 1998 increased the amount of folic acid
that must be added to enriched grain products; that increase,
together with the growing popularity of B vitamins in cardiology
clinics, might eliminate any heart conditions caused by vitamin
deficiency and homocysteine surplus.
</P>
<P>
   The latest results from the Framingham study, for example, show
that the new fortification program has added an average of 100
micrograms of folic acid to subjects' daily diets, resulting in a
sizable lowering of homocysteine levels, Krauss says. ``That's
going to make it difficult to do the studies that need to be
done.''
</P>
<P>
   For McCully, it's perhaps the final irony in a bittersweet
career.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (Karen Wright is a contributing editor to Discover magazine.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
