<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Yet another teen about to hit the road
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ One more child purportedly under my
supervision is about to enter the driving world. The rock 'n' roll
stepson turns 16 in March, and his new ride is sitting in the
driveway.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a new ride, of course. Unless you're a car dealer and
thus privy to discounts that those of us not in the business don't
get, buying a new car for a 16-year-old makes about as much sense
as naming cats. Young drivers, at least the ones who have come out
of my household, tend to run into inanimate objects not long after
getting a license.
</P>
<P>
   It's best that they drive something that won't look much worse
with another dent in it. Let them practice on something cheap and
battered before actually ponying up money for something shiny and
new.
</P>
<P>
   In the stepson's case, the ride is a 1987 Dodge Dakota truck
with about 80,000 miles on it, well-maintained by its owner but
showing the normal cosmetic wear of a 13-year-old vehicle. One
would have thought we had bought the boy a brand-new BMW by the way
he reacted. That's the way nearly all of us feel about the first
vehicle we were able to call our own. I bet if you walk up to 100
people and ask them the year and make of their first car, 99 would
be able to tell you _ even people who can't remember their wedding
anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   My first car was a 1954 Dodge, and I was the third generation of
Borders males to drive it, starting first with my grandfather. I
loved that car, which could hold eight comfortably. It was in great
shape for being 17 years old, and I soon paid to have the
upholstery redone and put in lime-green shag carpet. (This was the
'70s, so I'm forgiven.)
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, after a few years, the automatic transmission died, and I
couldn't find a replacement and stupidly sold the car for scrap. My
brother a few years ago found a magazine advertisement in a
used-book store for the exact same car, down to the color and
hyped-up ``Powerglide transmission.'' If I ever find a version of
this car, I'm buying it.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the stepson has great plans for the truck. New paint
job, all black. Lifters, or whatever you call those things that
jack it up high. Fat tires. A huge stereo system, which certainly
is a necessity since the cab is all of 5 cubic feet. Whatever. Keep
working at Denny's and save your money, I say. We bought the ride;
fixing it up is on his dime, though his grandparents sprung to redo
the interior _ all in vinyl, wisely. Teen-age boys spill soft
drinks, chips and Lord knows what else on the average of once every
three minutes. If I had it to do over again, I would have covered
his entire bedroom in naugahyde and put in a floor drain so you
could just hose it off every week or so.
</P>
<P>
   I had nothing to do with teaching him to drive, leaving it in
the hands of professionals and his mother, who seems to have aged a
bit in the past few months while riding shotgun as he drove around
town. My nerves are shot after teaching one ex-wife and two
daughters, and having an ancillary role in teaching a couple of
other kids. I rode with him the first time the day we bought the
truck. It could have been worse, but I got a charley-horse in my
leg stomping down on a nonexistent brake pedal.
</P>
<P>
   Lest one think we take this driving stuff too cavalierly, let me
hasten to add that I have been lecturing him regularly as I take
him to school on the vagaries of other drivers: How you can't trust
that someone is really turning just because they have on a turn
signal. Why you always look both ways before going through an
intersection, even if the light is green. Wear a seatbelt at all
times. Etc. I hope some of it has sunk in, but you never know. He
passed driver's education so he's state-sanctioned. There is only
so much you can do except worry, of course, which never ends.
</P>
<P>
   He'll be gone like the wind once he gets his real driver's
license, home for meals and sleep. That is the reality of turning
16, the first hard turn into adulthood and independence, though
there are plenty of curves along the way. Let's just hope he stays
on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of The Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel. E-mail: gborders(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
