<SLUG> BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A look at tax rhetoric, from read my lips to so help me God
 &HT;    By Dave McNeely
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Something about a Bush running for president and
talking about economic policy _ particularly taxes _ sends a
nervous tingle down the spine. It's kind of like watching someone
attempt a two-and-a-half backward flip off the high diving
platform. Will he survive?
</P>
<P>
   In a New Hampshire debate, Texas Gov. George W. Bush, after
saying it's important to cut taxes both in good times and bad, was
asked, ``Is this no new taxes, so help me God?''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not only no new taxes _ this is tax cuts, so help me
God,'' Bush replied.
</P>
<P>
   The reference was unmistakable. In 1988, Bush's dad pledged, in
accepting the GOP presidential nomination: ``Read my lips: No new
taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, President Bush acquiesced to a tax increase.
Two years after that, he was beaten for re-election by a Democratic
campaign with this slogan posted on the headquarters wall in
Arkansas: ``It's The Economy, Stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   The elder Bush had learned a painful lesson about the political
appeal of feel-good tax policy during his first run for the
presidency, against former California Gov. Ronald Reagan in 1980.
Reagan had shifted in the late 1970s from calling for spending cuts
_ ``Frankly, I'm afraid this country is going to have to suffer
two, three years of hard times to pay for the binge we've been
on,'' he said as late as 1978 _ to so-called ``supply-side
economics.''
</P>
<P>
   The supply-side theory, derided as ``the economics of joy'' by
the late Herbert Stein, chairman of Richard Nixon's Council of
Economic Advisers, let Reagan say he could increase defense
spending, cut taxes and still balance the budget.
</P>
<P>
   Bush called it ``voodoo economics.''
</P>
<P>
   Reagan won anyway, and the elder Bush quickly forgot the voodoo
tag when asked to be Reagan's running mate. In 1984, as the federal
debt escalated, Bush defended Reagan in a debate with Democratic
vice presidential nominee Geraldine Ferraro.
</P>
<P>
   When Reagan took over in 1981, Bush said, inflation and interest
rates were very high. ``This president turned it around, and I've
been with him every step of the way,'' Bush said. ``And of course I
would continue those kinds of programs because it's brought America
back. America's better off.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, as Reagan was retiring, an increased federal debt and
continuing budget deficits made it seem Bush had been right in 1980
with his ``voodoo economics'' label. Bush won anyway, for what some
have come to call Ronald Reagan's third term.
</P>
<P>
   A recession began in 1991, and in 1992, the contention by
Democrat Bill Clinton and Independent Ross Perot that Bush just
didn't get it about the economy helped knock him out of the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   Fast-forward to 2000 _ a time of budget surplus _ and the
younger Bush's tax-cut proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's carefully packaged to appeal to the traditional
Republican electorate, while letting Bush say he's helping ordinary
people'' by dropping the rate in the lowest tax-bracket from 15
percent to 10 percent, said Bruce Buchanan, a University of Texas
at Austin government professor who specializes in the presidency.
``It's an effort to make real the `compassionate conservative'
tag.'' And that helps its appeal in the general election.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, GOP rival John McCain's attitude toward use of the
projected budget surpluses leans toward that of Democrat Bill
Bradley, who talks about fixing the roof while the sun is shining.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very much in favor of tax cuts for middle-income and
lower-income Americans,'' McCain said during the recent Michigan
debate. ``I believe we must save Social Security, we must pay down
the debt, we have to make an investment in Medicare. For us to put
all of the surplus into tax cuts, I think, is not a conservative
effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Bradley and Vice President Al Gore continue to talk
about shoring up Social Security and spending a considerable amount
of the surplus in expanding health care. Even though Bush says his
proposal leaves money for Social Security, if he beats McCain, he
can expect to hear talk of irresponsible trickle-down economics
that would punish everyone who doesn't drive a luxury car.
</P>
<P>
   ``Either Gore or Bradley is going to be able to hammer him on
that,'' Buchanan said, ``and his claim that this helps the middle
class is going to seem empty.''
</P>
<P>
   Dave McNeely writes about politics for the Austin
American-Statesman. You may contact him at
dmcneely(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
