r l BC-WEDDING-DRESSES21-COX     01-20 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEDDING-DRESSES21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's time for summer brides to find that perfect dress
 &HT;    By Rachel Sauer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. _ Take the average bride-to-be: excited to
be getting married, giddy in love, prone to sentimental daydreams,
with vague romantic notions about her wedding day and her bridal
gown.
</P>
<P>
   But put her in a bridal boutique and what does she see? White. A
whole avalanche of it, bows and beads and ruffles and veils. It can
be a little overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't have to be, though, say bridal boutique owners. The
trend this season is toward simplicity, and if a bride gives
herself enough time to get a gown, it should fulfill all her
fairy-tale fantasies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Less has become more,'' said Janet Lally of A Formal Affair
and Tuxedo Co. ``We're not seeing too much lace or ruffles.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of dresses are getting much simpler,'' said Gayle
Nesbitt of Le Palais Boutique. ``They're not wanting all the beads
and things. Simple is elegant.''
</P>
<P>
   The popular shape for this season is an A-line dress with
natural fitted waistline, she said. Judy Panozzo of Victoria Rose
Bridal Parlor said strapless dresses are gaining popularity, as
well as dresses with spaghetti straps or tank top-style bodices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most girls that walk in here are saying simple, simple,
simple,'' Nesbitt said. ``They like the corset-look bodice, fitted
with nice seams.''
</P>
<P>
   Embroidery is becoming very popular, Lally said. Some dresses
have flowers, butterflies and other simple designs embroidered in
white, ivory or light pink.
</P>
<P>
   Satin remains the most popular dress fabric, particularly
Italian satin, which isn't as shiny as regular satin, Lally said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing some chiffons, too, but the girls like something a
little more sophisticated and drapey, something that hangs
beautifully,'' Panozzo said.
</P>
<P>
   Most brides still choose traditional white gowns, though brides
frequently are choosing dresses in ivory and shades between white
and ivory.
</P>
<P>
   Tiaras are very popular with brides-to-be, though not the
towering princess sort. Simple tiaras in gold or silver, and
sometimes rhinestones, with fingertip veils are popular, though
Nesbitt said some brides are choosing floor-length veils. Panozzo
said many brides are opting for veils with satin piping.
</P>
<P>
   Nesbitt said varying lengths of trains still are popular with
brides, though a bride should make sure the train is bustled or
there is some way she can carry it so it doesn't get stepped on at
the reception.
</P>
<P>
   As for footwear, ``to me, that's a bride's personality,'' Lally
said. ``I'll have some wear sneakers, I've had one wear Tevas, and
you see cowboy boots, combat boots. That's where their personality
comes out. I have one bride who's going barefoot.''
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, brides should begin looking for their gowns at least
six months in advance of the wedding, Panozzo said, because it can
take three months to order the dress and get it to the boutique,
then another six weeks for the seamstress to make alterations. All
three bridal boutique owners said they've done gowns in less time,
sometimes as little as a week, but such situations are very
stressful and a bride might have to settle for less than what she
wants.
</P>
<P>
   When trying on and choosing gowns, a bride should bring with her
someone who will give her an honest opinion and help her choose a
gown that not only suits her coloring and body type, but her
personality.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they bring along a friend that's going to want the bride to
try on styles they would wear, that's not going to work,'' Lally
said. ``Generally a bride brings her mom and a bridesmaid. If you
bring too many girls then everybody's got an opinion and it gets
too confusing for the bride.''
</P>
<P>
   Panozzo advised not buying dresses on the Internet because ``it
may be cheaper, but you need services when you buy a wedding gown.
You need alterations, you need the dress pressed, you need a bridal
bag so you can transport it without getting it dirty. If you have a
problem with a dress you order on the Internet, you can't correct
it, it's your problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Lally said the dress should be fitted for a bride as close to
the wedding as possible, pressed several days before the wedding
and hung somewhere it won't wrinkle or be disturbed.
</P>
<P>
   And then a bride can go back to her giddy smiles and starry-eyed
daydreams. Assuming everything is OK with the cake, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
