<HEADER>
A1266 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-HIASSEN21-COX     01-20 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-HIASSEN21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hiaasen still skewering state with his `Sick' characters
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The title of Carl Hiaasen's latest satirical crime
novel is ``Sick Puppy,'' but the term just as easily could apply to
the Miami Herald columnist.
</P>
<P>
   Hiaasen has populated his plot with some of the most repulsive
characters imaginable. Not surprisingly for the environmentally
concerned author, the worst ones are real estate developers and
their ilk. Shoat, the lobbyist in ``Sick Puppy'' (Knopf, $25),
shoots crippled big game animals at the Wilderness Veldt
Plantation, another character collects recordings of 911 calls and
sets them to music, and another has a fetish for Barbie Dolls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually,'' Hiaasen says, ``the lobbyist in `Sick Puppy' is an
amalgam of six different lobbyists. Each of them could have been a
villain. They have no social conscience and, for a novelist, that
makes an appealing villain. They'll go wherever there's money.''
</P>
<P>
   The 46-year-old Fort Lauderdale, Fla., native was a teen-ager
when he formed a hatred for developers and corrupt politicians who
were, as he put it, ``raping'' his state. ``I watched the
bulldozers move into my neighborhood. One day there was a piece of
forest where you could ride your bike, and the next day there's
concrete. You see every place you went as a child turned into a
shopping mall or a condominium complex. Finally you say, `Enough is
enough. I'm going to fight back.'''
</P>
<P>
   Hiaasen retaliated with a torrent of words. After spending a
couple of years at Emory University and graduating from the
University of Florida in 1974, Hiaasen wrote for a small Florida
newspaper and then landed a job at the Herald as an investigative
reporter. Soon he was writing a twice-weekly metro column and
transforming some real-life situations into best-selling crime
novels such as ``Tourist Season'' and ``Striptease.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you ever get threats from the people you write about in
your novels?
</P>
<P>
   A: They never recognize themselves. It's the people who aren't
in the novels who think they are. I have a character, Skink, who is
an ex-governor who went off the deep end and became a hermit. I've
had several ex-governors suggest to me that they are Skink.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You've done quite well financially with your novels. Why do
you continue to write a column twice a week?
</P>
<P>
   A: Many days I ask myself that question. The column is a very
appealing platform. If you write a book, it's nine months before
it's published. In the newspaper column, you can respond very
quickly and be in the paper the next day. You can keep the
spotlight on issues you think are important. It also keeps me
plugged into the real world. The temptation for any novelist is to
become isolated. The newspaper work fuels the novels and keeps me
angry enough to keep writing novels.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why are so many of your characters bizarre and over-the-top?
</P>
<P>
   A: Really, I don't have to exaggerate much. It's very hard to
compete with what's happening on the street. Whatever you invent as
a novelist, whatever you think is twisted and warped, it will
eventually come to pass. In the new novel, Mr. Gash collects 911
tapes and he plays them in his car and sets them to music. These
are (tapes of) people who are getting stabbed and burned. In Miami,
every night on the news we get treated to the horrifying sounds of
somebody losing their life because their 911 tapes have been
released. I figure it's only a matter of time before somebody
compiles these and puts them on tape. It's not too far from
reality.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you have a favorite character that you've created?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's gotta be Skink. Originally he was in a novel called
`Double Whammy.' He's this ex-governor, Vietnam War hero, who
discovers the state is completely crooked. Constantly frustrated,
he just walked out and went into the woods and eats roadkill and
doesn't come out unless I need him. I get so much mail about him,
people who wish there were a dark avenger like that. We all have
been going down a beautiful stretch of highway and see some guy in
the car ahead of you throw a hamburger wrapper out of the car.
We've all had the urge to run him down and teach him a lesson, but
we don't do it. Skink and my other characters act on these
impulses.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You've been skewering developers and corrupt politicians in
your books and columns for more than 15 years. Do you think you've
made any difference?
</P>
<P>
   A: You want to say there's been progress. I get mail from kids
who are passionate about these environmental issues. You touch
somebody and even if it's just one out of a hundred letters, you
feel you're making a difference in the world. That's what keeps you
going. You have to hope.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
