A1268 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-CHEAP-TRAVEL21-COX     01-20 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHEAP-TRAVEL21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Montreal's affordable secrets well worth uncovering
 &HT;    By Ray Marcano
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Sacre bleu!
</P>
<P>
   That's the reaction some people might get if they take a trip to
Montreal. Even with the favorable exchange rate, Montreal can be
hideously expensive _ unless you know where to get the bargains.
</P>
<P>
   Montreal is certainly worth the trip. It's a large, clean city
that has an air of Europe about it. It's easy to get around, has a
lot of sites worth seeing and a thriving nightlife.
</P>
<P>
   _ Getting there: It costs about $350 for a ticket to Montreal,
but I got two tickets for that price through priceline.com, and
other Internet deals should also yield big savings. And Air Canada
makes the trip very comfortable. The Columbus, Ohio-to-Toronto leg
offers beverage/snack service. On the one-hour flight from Toronto
to Montreal (as well as the return) the airline also served a
``snack'' of _ get this _ a sandwich, salad, cookies and soft
drink, the kind of amenities that put airlines in the United States
to shame.
</P>
<P>
   Make sure you bring your birth certificate or passport; a
driver's license doesn't prove citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   _ Where to stay: Montreal has a slew of hotels, but beware. Some
aren't as opulent as American travelers are used to, and the big
chains are pricey. I generally dislike downtown accommodations,
especially in a city like this that has a clean, reliable and cheap
mass transit system. An alternative: Search the Internet for bed
and breakfasts (see the Web address below). The Au Gite Olympique,
for example, is a two-minute walk to the subway, just 10 minutes
from downtown and offers sparse but clean rooms for reasonable
rates. And with bed and breakfasts you can cut bargains for lengthy
stays. I paid $76.50 a night Canadian (about $52 a night American,
depending on the exchange rate).
</P>
<P>
   _ Getting around: Once in Montreal you can buy a Metro
(subway/bus) card for $12.25 Canadian. That's good for unlimited
rides for a week. You can also buy a three-day tourist pass for
$12. There's no better buy. The bus system is also a terrific way
to see any of Montreal's thriving neighborhoods because buses make
their way through Ontario, Saint-Catherine and Sherebrook streets,
just to name a few of the major boulevards.
</P>
<P>
   _ What to see: As in any big city, there are loads of
attractions that can cost an arm and a leg. But you can also tailor
your trip so you don't spend a bundle. For example, you could do a
tour of the city's churches, incredible structures built in the
1800s with architecture that takes your breath away. The best
example: The Notre-Dame Basilica in Old Montreal (Place de Armes
metro stop) is one of the most spectacular churches you'll ever
see. Some churches give guided tours for a small fee (Notre-Dame
charges $2) and others ask for a donation for a self-guided tour.
Consult any of the readily available travel books for a list of the
other churches throughout the city.
</P>
<P>
   And if you like to walk, there's plenty to see. Start with the
Underground City _ incredible shops and cafes, all underground and
in the heart of downtown (Place de Arts, Peel and McGill metro
stops). Walk through Chinatown, Little Italy, the Latin Quarter,
Old Montreal, the Gay Village. Simply walking _ and seeing the
sites along the way _will take a lot of time, and you'll get
exercise in the meantime. For example, an approximately two-mile
walk down Saint-Catherine Street took two and half hours.
</P>
<P>
   _ Eating: This is the area that ``chews'' up the biggest part of
the budget. You have to add about 30 percent to the cost of the
meal to cover the provincial and federal tax and the customary 15
percent tip (some Montreal restaurants automatically add the
``service'' fee to your bill.) A beer or glass of wine will cost
about $6 and mixed drinks more, and it's not uncommon to spend $100
at Montreal's better restaurants. So you need to do you research
ahead and find places that won't break the bank. Among them: Da
Giovanni's, an Italian restaurant near McGill, where an
all-inclusive meal can be had for as little as $10.99. The dishes
with cream sauce are better than the red sauces, which shouldn't be
a surprise in a French-speaking province. Another way to cut costs:
Eat at the many cafes in the Underground City. You'll find enough
to fit any taste for dishes under $7 Canadian.
</P>
<P>
   _ Useful Web site: www.tourism-montreal.org/ offers information
on accommodations, hotel specials, travel packages, sightseeing
hints, bargains, a calendar and more. You can also call the
province's tourism department toll-free at (800) 363-7777.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
