A1269 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-MODEL-GISELE21-COX     01-20 0524
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MODEL-GISELE21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Supermodels back in 'Vogue' _ and 'W'
 &HT;    By Staci Sturrock
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ For the last couple of years,
supermodels have fronted fashion magazines about as often as
professional wrestlers. Striking poses in their place: Starlets and
singers such as Cameron Diaz, Lauryn Hill and Courtney Love.
</P>
<P>
   The influence of the celebrity-drenched, enormously successful
InStyle magazine is partly to blame, but there's also been a
shortage of true uber-mannequins since Christy, Claudia and Linda
sauntered out of the photo studio. Simultaneously, fashion and
fashion photography went through a minimalistic phase in which
models were required to be little more than glorified clothes
hangers.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Gisele Bundchen, a 19-year-old Brazilian who some say is
scoring one for supermodeldom.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's brought us out of that brief but boring period,'' says
James Scully, an editor with Harper's Bazaar. ``Gisele has made
everything swing the other way.''
</P>
<P>
   In a triple play unusual these days, Gisele decorates the
January covers of Harper's, Vogue and W. On the Harper's cover, a
heavy-lidded Gisele sports a Gucci python-print dress. For W, she
looks sophisticated and sleek in Donna Karan. For Vogue, she dons
more Gucci python for a smirky shot with model Carmen Kass.
</P>
<P>
   (Gisele is one of those rarities: A woman who photographs better
when she doesn't smile. Her December '99 Vogue cover, in which she
bares a perfect row of teeth, was less than flattering _ by
beautiful-and-stick-thin standards, anyway.)
</P>
<P>
   Vogue seems particularly enchanted with the 5-foot-11, 115-pound
stunner, naming her its Model of the Year for 1999. In addition to
the December cover, she shared space with Kate Moss, Lauren Hutton
and Iman on Vogue's November cover. The magazine points out that in
the ``last days of the 20th century, pretty much everybody in the
world wants (Gisele) to look good on his or her behalf.''
</P>
<P>
   That was undeniably true when designers showed off their Spring
'99 collections in New York last fall. Gisele strutted for every
last big name: Ralph Lauren, Oscar de la Renta, Tommy Hilfiger,
Donna Karan, Calvin Klein, Versace, and on and on, more often than
not in the coveted first or last spot in the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after she stepped off spring runways, Harper's Bazaar
tapped Gisele for its January issue (she also fronted the magazine
last summer).
</P>
<P>
   ``She conveys health and sexuality, which we haven't seen in
quite awhile,'' Scully says. ``It's been awhile since we've seen a
girl with breasts and hips.'' Gisele is no ``waif,'' like
supermodel Kate Moss. One fan site clocks her curves at 36-24-35,
and Vogue says she is making flat chests passe.
</P>
<P>
   Scully thinks Gisele will become the kind of model who moves
magazines off the racks by virtue of her mug alone. ``She has the
potential to become a personality,'' he says. ``There's more to her
than just her looks. She radiates a confidence that we haven't seen
in awhile. ... She will be the next Cindy.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
