<P>
   MOVIE NEWS AND REVIEWS
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-ASHES _ Movie review: ``Angela's Ashes.'' From Frank
McCourt's popular novel of gloom and doom and growing up in
Ireland. Grade: B-. (StMurray, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   ANGELAS-ASHES _ Frank McCourt's autobiographical Angela's Ashes
is a remarkable book, rich in colorful, colloquial language,
detailing his destitute family's meager existence with a clear eye
and unexpected passages of genuine humor. A movie version was both
inevitable and unfathomable. Yet director-adapter Alan Parker has
done an exceptional job bringing the cherished bestseller to the
screen. (Erstein, Palm Beach Post). 35.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-CRADLE _ Movie review: ``Cradle Will Rock.'' Tim Robbins'
tale of American theater and reds. It's more a rant than a movie.
Grade: C+. (Ringel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 14.
</P>
<P>
   CRADLEWILLROCK _ Like impassioned Depression-era composer Marc
Blitzstein, who wrote a folk opera that led to the demise of the
government's Federal Theatre Project employment program, film
director-screenwriter Tim Robbins has deeply felt, left-wing
political views and sees the world in shades of black and white.
Like scowling Mexican muralist Diego Rivera, whose Rockefeller
Center panorama depicted the entire world's political struggles,
Robbins attempts too much in his message-laden movie Cradle Will
Rock, but his fervent overreach still manages to be exhilarating
entertainment. (Erstein, Palm Beach Post). 40.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-FELICITY _ Movie review: Down to You. A movie not unlike
``Felicity.'' (Ringel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-MINIREVIEWS _ Mini reviews of all currently playing
movies. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   END-AFFAIR _ A review of ``The End of the Affair.'' 3 stars.
Graham Greene's novel about an obsessive man's encounters with an
ex-lover stars Ralph Fiennes, Julianne Moore and Stephen Rea. Neil
Jordan directs. (Macor, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
