<P>
   These feature stories are moving today to clients of the New
York Times News Service. Stories are for release Friday, January
21, 2000, unless otherwise embargoed.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BUDGET INFORMATION
</P>
<P>
   So specialty editors can focus on one day's budget, CoxNet
produces themed features budgets each day. Here is the schedule:
</P>
<P>
   Monday for Tuesday: Technology
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday for Wednesday: Automotive, personal finance and home &AMP;
garden
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday for Thursday: Food, CD reviews, video reviews
</P>
<P>
   TODAY: Movie reviews, travel, books and fashion
</P>
<P>
   Friday for Saturday: Religion and science &AMP; health
</P>
<P>
   In addition, separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports,
business and commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. An ETA is given if a
story will move after 8 p.m. Eastern.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   SAVE TIME: Stories marked as a CoxNet layout are available for
purchase in paginated form: http://nytsyn.com/syndicate/pageex
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-FORECAST _ Forecasters look at food in the years ahead.
What will we see? (Parham, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-LOOKBACK _ To put the last century in perspective, we take
a look at how our eating habits changed and the food products that
came with those changes, century by century. (Parham, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL
</P>
<P>
   COXNET TRAVEL PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDS: This is the CoxNet Travel page for the current week.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET TRAVEL 0118 -- Three college coeds and a journalist with
not a lot of cash to spend discover there's plenty of fun to be had
in London town. (Brock, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art includes
4-column color photo of the London Bridge and a 2-column color
photo of young women in a London nightclub.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: PRACTICAL TRAVELER -- The minimum amount airlines must pay
passengers whose luggage is irretrievably lost on a domestic flight
will rise this month to $2,500 from its longtime level of $1,250.
The Department of Transportation will review the new minimum in
July every other year and raise the level in increments of $100 if
the rate of inflation requires it. (Wade, N.Y. Times News Service)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TRAVEL BRIEFS -- Vail, Colo., has added 520 acres for
skiers and snowboarders. (N.Y. Times News Service.)
</P>
<P>
   CHEAP-TRAVEL _ Sacre bleu! That's the reaction some people might
get if they take a trip to Montreal. Even with the favorable
exchange rate, Montreal can be hideously expensive _ unless you
know where to get the bargains. Montreal is certainly worth the
trip. It's a large, clean city that has an air of Europe about it.
It's easy to get around, has a lot of sites worth seeing and a
thriving nightlife. (Marcano, Dayton Daily News) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-APALACHICOLA _ APALACHICOLA, Fla. _ Visiting
Apalachicola, a working Panhandle fish town that doesn't drool
after tourists, but welcomes more visitors from Atlanta than from
any other city. It's within 20 minutes of beautiful beaches but
hardly a ``beach town''; rather, an old Southern community that
seems to have drifted down, like a cypress log, to lodge itself
here, out of the stream of time. (Hulbert, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Jan 23.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA-WEBSITES _ Great Web sites and other helpful info for
planning a trip to the Sunshine State.(Hulbert, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Jan 23.
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY-FESTIVALS _ Southern happenings. (Thrasher, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
