u v BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET     01-20 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Thursday, Jan. 20, 2000 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITORS: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Friday. If
you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6320.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (``HNS'' appears in all sluglines.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   UNWANTED-BABIES (San Francisco) _ A proposed state law that
would give unwanted newborns a second chance at life by allowing
their mothers to legally abandon them is winning praise from social
workers, public safety employees, and abortion rights supporters
and opponents alike. By MARSHA GINSBURG.
</P>
<P>
   POLICE-TRIAL (Albany, N.Y.) _ It could cost the city up to $1
million in police overtime and other expenses to handle the crowds
expected in Albany to protest the trial of four police officers
accused of killing Amadou Diallo, according to city officials.
Local activists, New York City clergy members and downstate
legislators have promised to bring busloads of protesters to Albany
for the trial of four white police officers accused of fatally
shooting the unarmed West African immigrant Diallo. Jury selection
begins on Jan. 31. By ELIZABETH BENJAMIN.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MUSICAL-FOSSE (Houston) _ Ann Reinking, who co-directed and
co-choreographed ``Fosse,'' the national touring musical, talks
about the 1999 Tony Award-winning show. By EVERETT EVANS.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-CROWS (Undated) _ It's great being in a band and not being
recognized. Just ask guitarist Dan Vickreyiew of the Counting
Crows. ``Being recognized has its perks and downsides, but
personally it would be weird if I got noticed.'' he says. By
MICHAEL CLARK
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-REVIEW (Undated) _ Reviews of films ``Bowfinger,'' ``An
Ideal Husband'' and ``The 13th Warrior,'' which are being released
on video. By BRUCE WESTBROOK.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-LANG (Undated) _ Jonny Lang, one of the leading modern
blues performers on the music scene today, is in some ways totally
traditional. The 18-year-old grimaces when he plays lead guitar,
growls when he sings, and his idea of R&AMP;B is at odds with the
hip-hop variety of Sean ``Puffy'' Combs. But a long-faced, serious
Eric Clapton-style blues disciple he isn't. By HECTOR SALDANA.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CAREERS-COLUMN (Undated) _ If you are the boss and have a bunch
of unhappy, underachieving workers, where's the first place to look
for help? The biggest factor that affects workers' happiness is the
quality of their immediate supervisor. By DAVE MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   FEATURES/LIFESTYLE (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   KEEPING-WARM (Albany, N.Y.) _ The Albany Times Union staff
pooled its collective winter wisdom and came up with a list of
seasonal tips for surviving until the temperature heads back above
freezing. We also asked a few experts for their advice. By The
Albany Times Union.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ICE-CLIMBING (Keene Valley, N.Y.) _ I spent last Sunday climbing
at the popular and difficult Pitchoff Mountain Quarry Wall, a
75-foot rock face covered top to bottom in thick, sharp icicles. By
ALAN WECHSLER.
</P>
<P>
   BKB-JORDAN (Undated) _ The Washington Wizards, who haven't sold
out a home game in two seasons, should start peddling tickets to
practice. Air Executive will be there, pushing, prodding, going
where no team owner has gone before. To the hoop. To the boards.
Into players' faces, under their skin. Michael Jordan was a
merciless boss to his teammates on the Chicago Bulls, always
blistering someone. What will he be like now that he is really,
formally, officially, the boss? By GWEN KNAPP.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ It's the San Francisco dilemma:
how to love thy neighbor without angering thy neighbors. I'm not
sure there is a way to open a homeless shelter without causing a
ruckus. But here's how to cause a very big ruckus indeed. By ROB
MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ As the latest politician to hop
aboard the anti-gay marriage bandwagon, Gov. Cecil Underwood wants
the West Virginia legislature to print the following on all
marriage license application forms: ``Marriage is designed to be a
loving and lifelong union between a man and a woman.'' Well,
history hasn't always supported that idea. By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-BOY (San Francisco) _ Fidel Castro says the American people
``will react with a spirit of justice'' to the Eliaan Gonzalez
case. Fidel may be wrong on many things, but he's right about this
one. Recent polls by ABC News and CNN-USA Today-Gallup show a
majority of Americans want the boy returned to his father in Cuba.
By SCOTT WINOKUR.
</P>
<P>
   DANIEL-WEBSTER (Danville, Calif.) _ The griping about
politicians is in full roar. We all know the litany: Politicians
are venal. Politicians are hypocrites. They never keep promises.
Tuesday was the birthday this week of a man who epitomizes what can
go wrong when a politician acts on principle. Daniel Webster
(1782-1852) was a heroic statesman, so committed to principle he
put his career on the line to avoid civil war between the North and
South. But he did so at a terrible moral cost. And war came anyway.
By CYNTHIA BASS.
</P>
