<HEADLINE>
FOR THE DISABLED, STYLISH CLOTHING IS NOW AN OPTION  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 By JULIANNE REMINGTON  
 c.2000 HealthSurfing.com  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``It's often hard to find something fashionable to wear when
you're disabled,'' says Kurt Rieback, co-owner of Professional Fit
Clothing in Burbank, Calif. ``We cater to people with physical
challenges. The goal is to give customers a chance to enjoy more
dignity and confidence in their dress.''
</P>
<P>
   Kurt and his partner, Tom Pirruccello, join a growing cadre of
entrepreneurs across the country tuning into the needs of 54
million Americans who have difficulty buy clothing off the rack.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about dignity,'' says Tom. ``Stylish clothes help build
self esteem, and pave the way for smoother social interactions.
</P>
<P>
   CHOICES BUILD SELF IMAGE
</P>
<P>
   As Christopher Flynn, a quadriplegic for 10 years explains,
``Wearing jeans instead of sweats is a personal choice, and that's
what people with disabilities really want. If I go to a nice event,
I don't want to wear sweats and Ug boots. I'd like to wear jeans
just like anyone else, or dress pants.''
</P>
<P>
   Kurt and Tom had clothes modified for Christopher, including
several pairs of jeans. A larger zipper and an elastic waistband
allow easier dressing, and a longer inseam means more comfort while
sitting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it just makes me feel better in the morning,'' says
Christopher. ``Because when I get up, I realize that I'm not going
to wear the same old clothes, you know, sweat pants again. The new
clothes give me options, and that's a huge difference in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Simple alterations like placing Velcro tabs on shirts while
still keeping the buttons on the outside help create a more natural
look. Small openings strategically placed in pants or shirts to
accommodate feeding tubes and drainage bags improves the fit.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was the administrator of a home for people with
developmental disabilities,'' explains Tom, ``I didn't like seeing
clients going around in muumuus, sweats, and shapeless garments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some had a tendency to wear polyester clothes that didn't
match. Maybe the inseams of the pants would be off, maybe higher,
maybe lower. And that's really uncomfortable. Plus, how do you
think people feel in ill-fitting, boring clothes day after day?
It's demoralizing.''
</P>
<P>
   FOCUSING ON ABILITIES
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously being in a wheelchair makes me different,'' says
Christopher. ``But I can try to fit in with everyone else by being
able to wear similar clothes, and by going to the same places. Then
I don't focus on the fact that I have limitations. I feel like I
fit in.''
</P>
<P>
   A polar fleece jacket with a Velcro closure in the back made
Christopher's life easier, for example. ``From the front, it looks
like any other jacket,'' he says. ``But it's designed with wider
armholes, and has a longer zipper. The jacket is just the right
length so I can wear it comfortably while I'm sitting in a
wheelchair.''
</P>
<P>
   People who spend a great deal of time in a seated position often
prefer shirts or blouses with longer backs and shorter fronts.
Pants with a higher back also tend to be more comfortable, while a
low front waist band and longer inseam keep pants from cutting into
the body.
</P>
<P>
   AVOIDING CROWDS AT THE MALL
</P>
<P>
   ``Navigating a shopping mall can be hard in a wheelchair,'' says
Kurt. ``It's also difficult for blind people, and those with mental
retardation or any number of disabilities. ``That's why we make
house calls.''
</P>
<P>
   With racks of Hawaiian shirts, khaki cargo pants, denim jeans,
and designer dresses, Kurt and Tom travel around to nursing homes
and all kinds of group living facilities. Bringing their wares
directly into the privacy of the living room and even the bedroom
when necessary, the two apparel pioneers try to make shopping fun
for residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Customers sometimes tell us their favorite colors so we can
coordinate and personalize their own individual look,'' says Tom.
``Blind people enjoy feeling and choosing their own fabrics, and
we'll help them with the colors. I really enjoy this job because
the customers appreciate us coming so much.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it's not as glamorous as the bikini business,'' says
Kurt, who once sold swimsuits. ``But every day, I get to see how
happy these clothes make people. There's much more meaning in it.''
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   The Web site for Professional Fit Clothing is at
http://www.professionalfit.com. Their phone number is 800-422-2348.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (The HealthSurfing.com Web site at http://healthsurfing.com
contains further information.)
</P>
