<SLUG> BC-CUBA-BOY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SEND ELIAN HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SCOTT WINOKUR  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Cuban President Fidel Castro says the American
people ``will react with a spirit of justice'' to the Elian
Gonzalez case. Castro may be
</P>
<P>
   wrong on many things, but he's right about this one. Recent
polls show that a majority of Americans want the 6-year-old boy
returned to his father in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   You have seen the vivid spectacle of righteous indignation being
orchestrated by some Cuban-American groups, led by the
Cuban-American National Foundation, and you've heard conservative
politicians shamelessly shouting ``Amen!'' in order to curry their
favor.
</P>
<P>
   Be skeptical. Although they're trying to appeal to the emotional
bias in all of us toward helpless kids, I doubt they have a genuine
interest in the human tragedy at the core of this issue. They see
poor Elian as a pawn.
</P>
<P>
   I've felt this way for weeks, but figured I was pretty much
alone on the issue until I saw the polls and learned that here in
San Francisco there are some folks taking to the streets and
saying, hey, not so fast. Maybe the kid should go home.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the Committee to Return Elian Home to Cuba held a
protest at the San Francisco office of the Immigration and
Naturalization Service.
</P>
<P>
   Leading the charge was Gloria La Riva, a longtime newspaper
printer and political progressive of Mexican origin who has met
Castro five times in her capacity as national coordinator of
International Peace for Cuba Appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The keep-Elian-in-the-U.S. crowd, she told me, is ``arguing the
merits of a government, not the child's needs,'' and _ inexcusably
_ showing little concern for the boy's mental state.
</P>
<P>
   ``They haven't done anything to help him. He should be having
continual care,'' La Riva said.
</P>
<P>
   While the federal government seems to be inclined to do the
right thing here _ that is, send Elian home _ it has been
procrastinating. The boy should have been sent back weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's unclear when he'll go (assuming he does).
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though the government has made declarations, asserting
its jurisdiction over the child,'' La Riva said, ``we feel they've
delayed greatly in making and enforcing their decision.''
</P>
<P>
   An interesting document has been prepared by a University of New
Mexico sociologist, Nelson Valdes, entitled, ``Ten Reasons Why
Elian Gonzalez Should Be United With His Father.''
</P>
<P>
   Among them:
</P>
<P>
   _ Keeping Elian violates at least two signed accords between
Washington and Havana designed to discourage unsafe voyages from
Cuba to the United States. They apply in this case and show clearly
that Elian should be returned.
</P>
<P>
   _ A 1980 international accord on child abduction signed by the
United States requires the prompt return of abducted children.
</P>
<P>
   Elian, remember, was taken from Cuba by his mother (who died
crossing the sea) without the consent of his father or Cuban
officials.
</P>
<P>
   _ The 10th and last reason offered by Valdes is perhaps the most
compelling: ``Human decency, family love and common sense,'' he
says, ``dictates that this child and his father should be
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Delvis Fernandez of Hayward, Calif., is the president of the
Cuban-American Alliance Education Fund, a nonprofit organization
promoting relations between Cubans and Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez claims the Cuban-American groups that have gotten the
most attention in this matter aren't representative of the nation's
Cuban-American community.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sad thing about our community is that we're frozen in the
Cold War days,'' he said. ``President Reagan was pretty much
responsible for developing this organization (of anti-Castro
Cubans), the Cuban-American National Foundation, and it has become
an industry in Miami. They are basically calling the shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think the average Cuban-American believes the child
should be with his father. When you talk to people privately, it's
a no-brainer. Despite the dislike many Cuban-Americans have for
Castro and the Cuban government, they say that's the right thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's sad is that for over 40 years we've been fighting
Castro and there are people who are desperate and would reach out
to any issue, at any cost, to turn it into an anti-Castro weapon.
The tragedy is this boy has been turned into a poster child.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
