<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1379 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      01-20 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ILL-ADVISED ADVICE ON MARRIAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ As the latest politician to hop aboard the
anti-gay marriage bandwagon, Gov. Cecil Underwood wants the West
Virginia legislature to print the following on all marriage license
application forms:
</P>
<P>
   ``Marriage is designed to be a loving and lifelong union between
a man and a woman.''
</P>
<P>
   A staff member explained that banning same-sex marriages is ``a
moral issue'' for Underwood. ``He just believes in family values
and family traditions.''
</P>
<P>
   Underwood, a Republican, is hardly the first American politician
to speak so authoritatively about the institution of marriage, what
it was ``designed'' for, when and by whom. Much of Congress weighed
in on the subject in 1996, when it passed _ and President Clinton
signed into law _ the ``Defense of Marriage Act.''
</P>
<P>
   Typical of their thinking was Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, who
opined:
</P>
<P>
   ``The traditional family has stood for 5,000 years. Are we so
wise today that we are ready to reject 5,000 years of history? I
don't think so.''
</P>
<P>
   Although some religious folks insist that modern marriage, as we
know it in the United States, was crafted (like everything else in
the world) by God, reviewable history tells us differently. No
architect, divine or mortal, ever sat down and designed marriage.
It has evolved over the millennia, adapting to and changing for
specific cultures.
</P>
<P>
   For example, though Gramm may not have heard (and conservative
Christians rarely mention it), the kind of official marriage that
existed during the times of the Old Testament isn't around anymore.
(Thank God.) Back then, and for centuries after, marriage wasn't
designed to be a loving and lifelong union between a man and a
woman. It was designed to be a productive and lifelong contract
between a father or brother and a husband for ownership of a
female.
</P>
<P>
   A breakable contract.
</P>
<P>
   Among the grounds then for dissolution of marriage was a woman's
inability to produce children within five years. If her husband
chose, he could send her back to her family as defective goods and
break the contract. Of course, women weren't allowed to employ such
an escape clause; infertility was believed to be all their fault.
</P>
<P>
   As millions of peasants and other socially inconsequential types
could have attested, official marriage stood for centuries as a
privilege reserved for people who had money, property and/or a name
to pass along. The nobodies were expected to just occupy a hut
together and raise their kids.
</P>
<P>
   But let's give Underwood the benefit of the doubt and figure he
meant to say, ``Modern marriage as we know it in the Western world
is designed to be a loving and lifelong union between a man and a
woman.'' Isn't it unfair (and misleading) to put that on a license
application?
</P>
<P>
   Design or no, about half the marriages in our country still do
not make it into the lifelong category. These days, a little more
than 50 percent of children live in family configurations that are
not the traditional mom, dad and kids.
</P>
<P>
   This may be sad or simply an inevitability of post-industrial
society, but it is reality.
</P>
<P>
   So, too, is the widespread incidence of spousal abuse,
infidelity and just plain ``irreconcilable differences,'' all of
which can turn a loving union into a nightmarish one that only a
masochist would choose to stay in.
</P>
<P>
   If some politician wants to imprint a truthful and useful piece
of information on applications for marriage licenses, wouldn't
something like this make more sense?
</P>
<P>
   ``Warning: No matter how much in love you are today, you have a
one-in-two chance of ending up in a divorce court and possibly
despising the woman/man to whom you now join in official matrimony.
But if you work really hard and made a halfway decent choice in a
partner, you MIGHT stay together for the rest of your life. Good
luck.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her electronic mail address
is salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
