<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1380 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-CAREERS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      01-20 1185
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAREERS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SUCCESSFUL BOSSES KNOW THE VALUE OF GOOD EMPLOYEES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAVE MURPHY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   You are a boss with a bunch of unhappy, underachieving workers.
</P>
<P>
   You need help. Where's the first place to look?
</P>
<P>
   Try the mirror.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest factor that affects workers' happiness is the
quality of their immediate supervisor. If your employees aren't
cutting it, part of it may be your fault. And it may be YOUR boss's
fault, too. Companies spend a lot of effort recruiting managers,
then throw it all away by not training them adequately.
</P>
<P>
   Here are 10 things every boss should know:
</P>
<P>
   _ Be a role model. You won't inspire employees if you have
sloppy work habits.
</P>
<P>
   Make sure your office isn't the place where ideas go to die.
Don't make workers ask you a question three times to get a
10-second answer. If you're too swamped to respond to a suggestion
or look over a report anytime in the next week, say so.
</P>
<P>
   Some bosses think working long hours is part of being a role
model, but it can backfire if workers take your efforts for
granted. They'll shrug and think that's what is expected of
managers _ or worse. Maybe they'll think you don't value your time
or you're a workaholic or your simply have no life. They may look
down on you instead of up to you.
</P>
<P>
   Long hours also backfire when a special project comes up. If
you're normally at the office 40 hours a week, you can suddenly
start working more to impress upon people how important the project
is, and how you're all in this together.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly many managerial jobs require long hours, and you want
subordinates to know you're working hard. But for the
non-workaholics to respect you, they have to respect how you live
your life, not just how you do your job. If your job demands long
hours, think about quietly taking some work home so that you at
least maintain the illusion of having a life.
</P>
<P>
   _ Focus on your best people. It's easy to get bogged down
handling troublesome employees, but the best bosses spend more
energy helping their top workers get even better.
</P>
<P>
   With a good boss's help, a mediocre employee will turn into a
prettier shade of mediocre. But a good employee might turn into
something spectacular.
</P>
<P>
   Don't assume they're inspired by the same things that motivate
you. Maybe you love the fancy title and huge paycheck, but your
employee might cherish recognition or opportunities for promotion
or extra time off.
</P>
<P>
   _ Review performances frequently. You don't need a
paperwork-filled affair, but talk about job performance with each
worker at least four times a year.
</P>
<P>
   Remember that you're managing people, not just employees. In
``First, Break All the Rules,'' authors Marcus Buckingham and Curt
Coffman describe one question for managers from a Gallup survey:
``You have a talented employee who consistently shows up late for
work. What would you say to this employee?''
</P>
<P>
   Some managers would shrug it off or give a warning or fire the
worker, but the most effective bosses shared one response: ``I
would ask why.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Use criticism and praise effectively. Make criticism
constructive, and give it as soon as possible after the mistake
happens. Work with the employee to see if there are ways to prevent
the same mistake from happening again.
</P>
<P>
   Don't criticize people in front of others. The anger and
embarrassment will be remembered long after the criticism is
forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   Offer a lot more praise than you do criticism, especially when
you can point to specific things the employee has done. And make
the praise sincere; employees can tell when you're blowing smoke.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't inadvertently build stress. If you send an employee an
e-mail on Friday that says, ``I need to see you Monday at 10,'' you
create the possibility of a paranoid weekend. You know what the
topic will be and how significant it is _ or isn't. But the worker
has no clue.
</P>
<P>
   That note could lead to hours of pondering and lots of water
cooler conversations. Did I do something wrong? Is my budget being
cut? Am I being laid off?
</P>
<P>
   When a couple of workers screw up, don't send a note telling
everyone to clean up their act. Not only are you causing stress for
those who did nothing wrong, but you're wasting their time _ all
because you're too weak of a manager to talk to the problem
employees individually.
</P>
<P>
   _ Make workers feel their opinions count. Survey employees
before you make major decisions. If that's not practical, explain
why.
</P>
<P>
   If you've already made up your mind, but haven't announced your
decision, don't patronize workers by asking for their opinions.
They'll see through the charade.
</P>
<P>
   _ Realize that ``face time'' can blow up in your face. One way
to kill creativity is to micromanage, to tell people not only what
they should do, but how they should do it. Be flexible.
</P>
<P>
   Give employees goals, but let them to figure out how to get
there. Some people do their best work in a cubicle (or so I'm
told). Others do better at home or in the field or even in a bar.
</P>
<P>
   If you evaluate people based on how many hours they spend in the
office rather than their results, you're a lazy manager.
</P>
<P>
   _ Understand that behind every counteroffer is a mistake. If
your competition lures away a valued employee, it means one of
three things: Your company can't compete, you didn't network enough
or you were unfair to her in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   If you network and you know what matters to each employee,
you'll already be offering your top people the most you reasonably
can. If a competitor offers more money or a greater opportunity and
she is ready to take it, keep in mind that things will never, ever
be the same.
</P>
<P>
   If you counteroffer and she stays, there is potential for
resentment on all sides. Other workers can resent what happened or
ask for more money. You might resent having your budget stretched
tighter than you're comfortable with. And the employee might feel
as if you were underpaying her for years before you found the extra
money for the counteroffer.
</P>
<P>
   _ Be clear about how much (or how little) you value diversity.
``Diversity'' is a great employer buzzword, but if all you're
trying to do is jam people of different races and sexes into the
same corporate mold, that isn't diversity.
</P>
<P>
   True diversity involves having a wide range of perspectives,
which encourages creativity within the company and challenges the
old ways of doing things. If all you're looking for is
different-colored faces, you're talking about representation, not
diversity.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't give in to your own insecurity. Hire the most talented
people you can, even if it makes you less indispensable. When they
have good ideas, don't try to steal the credit. If you make a
mistake, admit it and move on.
</P>
<P>
   Great bosses don't just bring out the best in people; they have
people who bring out the best in them.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Murphy is the careers editor of the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is murphy(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
