<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1381 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-MUSIC-LANG-HNS &LR;      01-20 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-LANG-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     OLD-SCHOOL BLUES ARTIST IS TOTALLY MODERN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By HECTOR SALDANA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jonny Lang, one of the leading modern blues performers on the
music scene today, is in some ways totally traditional.
</P>
<P>
   The 18-year-old grimaces when he plays lead guitar, growls when
he sings, and his idea of R&AMP;B is at odds with the hip-hop variety
of Sean ``Puffy'' Combs.
</P>
<P>
   But a long-faced, serious Eric Clapton-style blues disciple he
isn't.
</P>
<P>
   For one, he doesn't mind hanging out with the three brothers who
make up the youth rock group Hanson. Plus, he likes listening to
James Taylor CDs on his tour bus. He has a quirky sense of humor,
is apt to check into hotels using the alias Douglas Fir, and he's
not the hard-living sort, either.
</P>
<P>
   His true nature is quite different from what his poster-boy good
looks exude.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, he's a homebody, content to kick back when he is not on
the road, at his home near Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, he hits a town and checks out bands. Last week at
a Jackson, Miss., tour stop, he caught alternative rockers Tonic,
but more important, he got in a round of golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bring my own clubs. I'm not too bad. I don't really suck,
but I kind of suck,'' he joked in a recent telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   A friendly golf game is his way of relaxing when he's not
promoting ``Wander This World.''
</P>
<P>
   When he is not golfing on the road, Lang will likely be in his
hotel room, finger-picking his acoustic guitar. ``I never get sick
of it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lang remains unfazed about meeting and working with some of the
biggest music stars in the world. In 1999, he played 11 dates with
the Rolling Stones.
</P>
<P>
   He said it is really possible to get close to Mick and the boys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh yeah, they're really nice guys,'' he said, not exactly the
usual description of the big, bad Stones.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm into the Stones. Mick was the guy I got to talk to the
most. He's just a really nice guy. They're not rock star-y at
all.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Lang did not join Keith Richards' infamous, late night
hotel room jams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nah, I just talked to Keith a couple of times. He's a wild
man,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lang dismisses the ``age thing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it's hard to tell if people are being nice or if
they truly respect you, or whatever. It really doesn't matter,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his success (he has sold more than 1.5 million albums),
he still encounters people who think he is too young to sing the
blues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to try to fight it. I set people straight when they're
ignorant. I've come to the conclusion that I really don't care,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   He plans to be in the recording studio in April. Lang says he
never has a plan going into the studio and ``just likes to go in
and see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope I go beyond being a guitar player or just a guitar
band,'' Lang said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he does not worry about misconceptions about him, nor
does he worry about being pegged as a nice guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't heard anything too detrimental. I've never heard,
`Jonny's a smack addict,''' he said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Does he ever fantasize about making a shocking record? ``Not
really, mostly because I don't think people can be shocked anymore.
After Marilyn Manson, I don't think there's anything else to be
scared about.''
</P>
<P>
   Who does he like in the biz? ``I'm telling you, I really like
Hanson. I think they're really talented, and their next record is
great. They actually invited me to play on it,'' he said of the
recording by the Hanson brothers (Taylor, Isaac and Zac), all
younger than Lang.
</P>
<P>
   He is dead serious.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next record is just killin'. It's just rock,'' he said.
``They kind of stepped out of being commandeered by the record
label so much, and being teeny-bopper guys.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're really nice guys, and they're so professional,'' Lang
said. ``Like in the studio, they never argue with each other.
They're just kind of, one guy has an idea, and it's `OK, let's try
that.' They're real pros and they know what they're doing and have
a great sense of musicality.''
</P>
<P>
   On the road, Lang lately listens to James Taylor's ``Hour
Glass'' _ the most listened to album on the bus lately _ and Stevie
Wonder's ``Music of My Mind'' ``I'm really into Dave Matthews Band.
I really like those guys,'' Lang added.
</P>
<P>
   He likes Beck, too, but is a bit lukewarm.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not something I could sit to, and just close my eyes and
sit down and listen to,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, he almost never listens to the blues, ``except for
maybe B.B.''
</P>
<P>
   Lang's approach to blues guitar solos ranks him among the best.
</P>
<P>
   ``The space sounds better than the notes played sometimes,'' he
said, a trick he learned from heroes B.B. King and the late Albert
Collins.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact Hector Saldana by e-mail at
hsaldana(at)express-news.net)
</P>
