r l BC-KEEPING-WARM-HNS &LR;      01-20 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KEEPING-WARM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HOT TIPS ON HOW TO KEEP WARM 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Tims News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The temperature is frigid. It's shockingly cold
and dry, as you'll find out from that jolt of static electricity
each time you shake a hand or plant a kiss. Here is a list of
seasonal tips for surviving the chill.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   AT HOME
</P>
<P>
   _ Use a heating pad on that critical 4-inch length of frozen
pipe leading to your toilet. The blow dryer is the indispensable
thawing tool.
</P>
<P>
   _ Line up winter clothes for younger school-age kids from top to
bottom (hats, scarves, coats, gloves, heavy socks, boots) the night
before. Pack the snow pants in a backpack if they are required by
after-school program. Otherwise, you might be scrambling for that
lost glove or hat, the kids will miss the bus, and you will be
forced to go out in the cold yourself and drive them to school.
</P>
<P>
   _ Crank up the furnace and put on shorts and a T-shirt. Pull a
lawn chair out of the basement, sit in it, kick back with a
tropical drink and read a trashy novel. You'll swear you're on
vacation in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   _ Allow your large fluffy dog on the bed to snuggle.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   BODY PROTECTION
</P>
<P>
   _ Lotion, Static Guard and lip balm. Don't leave home without
'em.
</P>
<P>
   _ Clothes dryer anti-cling sheets will pat flyaway hair back in
place.
</P>
<P>
   _ Going to the gym is tough enough without the prospect of
pulling on clothes that have been freezing in the car all day: Warm
them under the hand dryer or a hair dryer for 10 to 20 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   _ A batch of hot toddies warms your insides _ just remember to
stay indoors.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   AUTOMOBILE ISSUES
</P>
<P>
   _ One way for drivers to keep hands warm: Take two pairs of
gloves with you. Sit on one set; wear the other. When your hands
get cold, put on the pair you were sitting on and warm up the pair
you were wearing the same way.
</P>
<P>
   _ Well-intentioned car owners who wash their salt-caked vehicles
in an attempt to eliminate road salt's corrosive effects can
prevent troublesome door freeze-ups with a few simple advance
procedures: Make sure your car's interior is warmed up fully; spray
your door locks with a standard lubricant such as WD-40, using the
thin nozzle extender so that the spray penetrates the locks. This
displaces moisture. Repeat every week or two in sub-freezing
weather.
</P>
<P>
   Also, spray the rubber gaskets inside your car door with a
standard furniture polish, to prevent them from sticking to the
metal door jamb.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   EMBRACE THE WEATHER
</P>
<P>
   _ Young kids and New York Air National Guard members who have
completed Arctic survival training know a great way to combat
temperatures that drop below zero: snow shelters.
</P>
<P>
   The snow acts as a kind of thermal blanket, providing a fun
place to play along with proven protection against murderous wind
chills. Such shelters are an antidote to cabin fever, too.
</P>
<P>
   The Air National Guard's pilots and crew members who graduate
from ``Cool School'' on pack ice over the Arctic Ocean near the
North Pole learn a variety of building styles _ from digging caves
in drifts to cutting snow blocks and fashioning igloo-style abodes.
</P>
<P>
   Kids can get the same benefits with low-tech digging, piling and
shaping a snow enclosure.
</P>
<P>
   A tip before you get started. Dress in layers and shed a few
outer layers while digging and making the snow shelter. Profuse
sweating is dangerous in sub-zero temperatures. Take frequent
breaks to prevent overheating. And drink plenty of water to guard
against dehydration. (Melting snow by keeping a drinking water bag
on the outside of a thermal shirt is a ``Cool School'' favorite.)
</P>
<P>
   Be sure to leave an entryway and vent hole in your snow shelter.
Make sure your enclosure is far enough from the road to prevent
getting hit by a snow plow. Make it large enough to allow some
movement inside. (Note: Snow caves are probably not a good idea if
you're claustrophobic.)
</P>
<P>
   _ And finally: Fall on the ice, get up, repeat 20 times. You may
warm up or you may just go numb, but either way you won't feel the
cold.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-00 1405EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
