<DOCNO> NYT20000120.0086 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 14:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1392 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV23-C     01-20 0552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: WHY FLAGS MATTER
 &HT;    For release Sunday, Jan. 23.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The rush of bitter feeling over the flying of the
Confederate battle flag brings to mind my visits to Moscow in
Soviet times. Often I would arrange to stay in a hotel room, once
occupied by Vladimir Lenin, that afforded a fine view of the huge
flag that fluttered behind the Kremlin wall.
</P>
<P>
   Television people call that scene across Red Square an
``establishment shot.'' On a chilly night a decade ago, many
Russians wept when they saw the communist hammer-and-sickle symbol
come down, to be replaced by the same tricolor flag that flew there
in czarist times.
</P>
<P>
   The state flags of Alabama, Georgia and Mississippi all bear the
diagonal cross of St. Andrew, the martyred patron saint of Russia,
of Scotland and of the Confederacy. (The combination of the
Christian crosses of St. Andrew and St. George make up the British
Union Jack.)
</P>
<P>
   There are scholars who study the symbolism behind these flags,
which were first widely used a millennium ago in the Crusades. The
overall pursuit is known as vexillology, from the Latin vexillum or
``banner.''
</P>
<P>
   Prodded by the media, the current crop of presidential
candidates have reluctantly become obliged to also ponder the
meanings that lie behind the display of these flags _ particularly
the Confederate battle flag that flies over the state capitol in
South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson has further widened the controversy by
urging contestants in the 2000 Super Bowl, to be played in Atlanta,
to lodge a televised protest over the 44-year-old makeup of the
Georgia state flag, which also incorporates the Confederate icon.
</P>
<P>
   It's not at all surprising that some folks decry the display of
such flags, especially at official sites, as an abhorrent reminder
of slavery and as a racist challenge. Nor is it surprising that
other folks cherish these flags as a precious link to their
mythologized past, what the narrator of ``Gone With the Wind''
termed ``our way of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Flags carry lots of freight. Until modern times, unarmed
soldiers would often march into battle carrying only a tattered
standard in an effort to buck up their frightened comrades.
Nowadays, a majority in Congress favors making it a crime for
anyone to burn the U.S. flag.
</P>
<P>
   When Republican candidates say that a flag's official display
should be viewed merely as a state issue that does not bear on
their quest for the White House, they are ducking their
responsibility in pursuit of votes.
</P>
<P>
   When Democratic candidates denounce these displays as racist or
when Pat Buchanan, the Reform Party hopeful, defends them, they too
are ignoring the complexities of the problem in order to preserve
their standing with their political base.
</P>
<P>
   Serious candidates should be seeking ways to bring polarized
people together, to heal the wounds that divide them and to
negotiate compromises. That process is called leadership. It's a
valuable asset for any occupant of the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-00 1407EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000120.0087 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 14:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1393 &Cx1f; tad-z
r w BC-PRESIDENCY-$ADV23-COX     01-20 1317
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRESIDENCY-$ADV23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WILL GLOBAL TECH TRENDS MAKE PRESIDENTS LESS IMPORTANT?
 &HT;    For release Sunday, Jan. 23.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As President Clinton prepares to deliver likely his
last State of the Union address Thursday, officially slipping into
the twilight of his time in office, many believe the presidency
itself might be on the wane.
</P>
<P>
   The White House, some say, perhaps even government itself, is
losing its steam as an engine of influence, hopelessly outpaced by
the thundering convergence of technology, borderless information
flows and the rise of the global marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   Government at all levels is only beginning to reckon with these
shifts, which old models of law and regulation sometimes struggle
to control even at the margins, if at all.
</P>
<P>
   Amid these changes, though, the presidency too has evolved.
</P>
<P>
   Long regarded as the most powerful institution in the world, the
presidency arguably has assumed more authority and reach than at
any time in its history.
</P>
<P>
   While no one can doubt the growing impact of the Internet,
Silicon Valley and Wall Street on the daily lives of all Americans,
only the president can rally truly global resources around American
ideals to combat the timeless ills of poverty, war and the quest
for equality.
</P>
<P>
   As the world moves increasingly toward becoming a single
interconnected village, it is that unique ability to build and
harness a worldwide consensus that is widening the circle of
presidential power.
</P>
<P>
   ``The presidency will remain as important as it is or will
become more important,'' said presidential scholar Michael Nelson,
professor of political science at Rhodes College in Memphis, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is,'' said Emory University's Robert Pastor, ``the
office does matter.''
</P>
<P>
   The taproot of presidential power is the Constitution, which
designates the chief executive, the only official elected in a
national vote, as the sole representative of all the American
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever authority is conferred by elections in a democracy is
conferred by the whole country on the president,'' said Nelson.
``Nobody else can say that.''
</P>
<P>
   That conferred authority reflects the state of the nation, and
it would be hard to argue that any country in history has possessed
the military, economic and political pre-eminence that this country
now holds.
</P>
<P>
   Militarily, even the closest U.S. allies are a full generation
behind American defense capability. During last year's air war
against Serbs in Kosovo, the United States kept secret from its
NATO allies the highly effective stealth portion of the campaign,
essentially conducting a war within a war.
</P>
<P>
   Economically, the United States kicked out a record $9.5
trillion worth of goods and services last year, far more than any
other country in history and accounting for more than one-fourth of
the entire world's economic output.
</P>
<P>
   And politically, the United States stands as a beacon to
countries caught up in the global move toward democracy.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, the nation's greatest strength as a global power lies
in its ability to build an international consensus around values
and interests important to most Americans.
</P>
<P>
   On Clinton's watch, that ability has been almost constantly on
display as he has patched together multinational responses to war
in the Balkans, despotism in Haiti, economic crises in Mexico,
Russia, Indonesia and South Korea, and humanitarian disasters in
Turkey and Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
   The institutions for putting together coalition-type action _
the United Nations, the North Atlantic Treaty Organization, the
International Monetary Fund, the World Bank and the World Trade
Organization among them _ are hardly tools of American policy.
</P>
<P>
   But the United States commands a dominant, in some cases
decisive, position in each of those institutions.
</P>
<P>
   And it is the president, far more than Congress, that determines
how the United States wants those institutions to be structured and
to perform.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress is a clunky institution of 535 people that can't
negotiate as a unit with global corporations or entities,'' said
Alan Ehrenhalt, editor of Governing magazine. ``It's the president
who is capable of making deals with global institutions.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the president, indeed, who appoints envoys to those
institutions, negotiates the treaties that bind them and delivers
the public and private counsel that helps guide them, leaving the
indelible imprint of American priorities on every major initiative
they undertake.
</P>
<P>
   ``That means, for example, that we can advance our interests in
resolving ethnic conflicts, in helping address the problems of AIDS
in Africa, of contributing to the world's economic development, of
promoting human rights,'' said Pastor, editor of a new book, ``A
Century's Journey,'' that elaborates on the theme.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are American interests,'' said Pastor, ``and through the
United Nations Security Council, we can leverage our power to
encourage other countries, and these international institutions, to
advance them.''
</P>
<P>
   Many scholars argue that global shifts are undermining the
authority of all sorts of traditional institutions, even while
making it possible for non-traditional groups to step in and assume
important new roles.
</P>
<P>
   Nobel Peace Prize winner Jody Williams, for example, used e-mail
to generate a worldwide grassroots consensus for her International
Campaign to Ban Landmines. Her high-tech end run around White House
policy makers left Clinton virtually alone among world leaders in
not supporting the ban, which runs counter to Pentagon strategy in
South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Under Clinton's presidency, the Internet has gone from an
obscure tool of the Pentagon and academia to potentially the most
powerful communications medium in the history of the world.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet, moreover, has both accelerated and come to
symbolize a much broader set of economic, political and social
changes sweeping the world.
</P>
<P>
   _ Nearly $7 trillion worth of goods and services will be sold
across borders this year as workers from some of the poorest
countries in the world bid for a growing share of wealth.
</P>
<P>
   _ Currency traders move an estimated $1 trillion around the
world each day, making decisions about the futures of markets and
entire national economies.
</P>
<P>
   _ Nearly 4 billion people, two-thirds of the Earth's population,
now participate in some form of democratic system.
</P>
<P>
   Put it together, and the world is undergoing a populist
revolution of historic proportions. More and more it is people, not
governments, that are taking control of the issues affecting their
lives, as politicians often appear to be watching from the
sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many respects, political systems are increasingly at the
mercy of technology,'' said presidential scholar Michael Genovese,
political science professor at Loyola Marymount University in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``What it probably will do is make central governments less
important and, therefore, presidents less important,'' said
Genovese, author of 11 books on the presidency, including the
forthcoming ``Power and the American Presidency,'' to be published
this summer by the Oxford University Press.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably in the next 20 years,'' Genovese said, ``we will
increasingly see an institution, the presidency, that is less
significant and less powerful.''
</P>
<P>
   Others counter that the presidency is, by design, resilient to
moments of great change. That, in fact, is part of the genius of
the founding fathers, said Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the 20 years that I've been teaching political science, a
recurrent prophecy is that the presidency is being weakened by this
or that,'' said Nelson. ``It just doesn't seem to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Deans's e-mail address is bobdeans(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
