<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 14:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1406 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-BKN-JORDAN-HNS &LR;      01-20 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-JORDAN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     AIR EXEC MAY WORK MAGIC WITH HAPLESS WIZARDS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By GWEN KNAPP  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Washington Wizards, who haven't sold out a
home game in two seasons, should start peddling tickets to
practice. Air Executive will be there, pushing, prodding, going
where no team owner has gone before. To the hoop. To the boards.
Into players' faces, under their skin.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan was a merciless boss to his teammates on the
Chicago Bulls, always blistering someone.
</P>
<P>
   What will he be like now that he is really, formally,
officially, the boss?
</P>
<P>
   This will be a fascinating saga, and only two things look
absolutely certain. One, Nike will try to market a shoe for the
occasion. And two, Jordan, as always, will be one of a kind.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine the fun, though, if he were a trendsetter.
</P>
<P>
   In Minnesota, Kevin McHale, the Timberwolves' general manager,
has been known to step onto the court and tutor Kevin Garnett and
Joe Smith in the art of the low post. But he isn't a co-owner,
doesn't operate in the rarefied air of the Turners, Steinbrenners,
Reinsdorfs and Huizengas.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan just joined that club, as a junior member.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he's going to fraternize with the help. Or, more likely,
terrorize them.
</P>
<P>
   The only other NBA owner with that sort of nerve is the
Energizer Bunny in Philadelphia, Pat Croce, who made his money as
an uber-personal trainer. Magic Johnson, when he had a small slice
of the Los Angeles Lakers, could have tried the hands-on approach,
but he wasn't the head of basketball operations, as Jordan is in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan says he wants to stare down players, to learn whether
they have the innards of real competitors. He wants to challenge
them, to let osmosis do its thing. This is his chance to show, or
at least the NBA's chance to see, that Jordan didn't excel because
of his vertical leap, his speed or his shooting touch. A lot of NBA
guards have his physical ability. Some have more. No one has his
desire to win.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Russell, in his day, might have come close. He imparted it
to his Boston Celtics teammates, just the way Jordan did to the
other Bulls, making champs of Steve Kerr, of Horace Grant, of Luc
Longley and Bill Wennington.
</P>
<P>
   Now, can he do the same with Mitch Richmond, Juwan Howard and
Rod Strickland, even if he dresses only for practice? The word on
those three is that they are the Wizards' albatross, consuming the
salary cap and converting all that money into loss after
disappointing loss.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a reason they are making so much money. At one
point, not
</P>
<P>
   too long ago, Howard was considered a prize, famously coveted by
Pat Riley. There has to be some of that potential left in him. It
couldn't all have been a mirage.
</P>
<P>
   Put Howard in practice with Jordan and his pride alone should
elevate his game instantly. Jordan is the gold standard to young
NBA players, but only the Wizards will get to measure themselves
against him.
</P>
<P>
   Just as important is this: Very few people can tell the cosseted
youngsters in the NBA that they aren't good enough.
</P>
<P>
   Riley can. Phil Jackson can. Jordan can tell them that they
stink, and rather than sulk, they'll try to prove him wrong.
</P>
<P>
   He can tell them to stand on their heads, pinch their noses and
bark out loud and they'll probably do it.
</P>
<P>
   Already, Strickland has rescinded his let-me-out pleas and said
he wants to work under Jordan. The Wizards may still find a way to
unload him, because Jordan has executive powers and he will surely
wield them as aggressively as he played every game.
</P>
<P>
   But one of the biggest problems in the NBA is the persistent
game of musical rosters. A player isn't happy? Trade him. You'll
probably get another cranky guy in return, but at least you look
like you're doing something.
</P>
<P>
   Those deals rarely work. On good teams, players fear being
traded. On good teams, management doesn't scheme to jettison its
best-paid players. It worries about how to hold onto them.
</P>
<P>
   When dumping players looks like the only way out, a club is
trapped. Jordan can pluck the Wizards out of their predicament just
by being who he is, just by being around.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
