<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR FRIDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Friday, Jan. 21:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-GREECE (Ankara, Turkey) _ Four years after Greece and
Turkey came to the brink of war over a barren islet in the Aegean
Sea, their foreign ministers meet here to sign a series of accords
and pledge themselves to peace. By Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-POLITICS (Dateline to come) _ Israel's attorney general
orders a criminal investigation of President Ezer Weizman over
accusations of financial improprieties, including tax
violations. &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-ARAFAT (Washington) _ President Clinton and Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat scheduled to meet in Washington. By Jane
Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-POLITICS (Hamburg, Germany) _ News that the financial
official of the Christian Democratic Union had committed suicide
interrupts a session of parliament at which the party's leader,
Wolfgang Schauble, apologized for the Christian Democrat's
financial scandal. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-HELMS (United Nations) _ On Sen. Jesse Helms' address to
the Security Council. The conservative chairman of the Foreign
Relations Committee and vocal critic of the United Nations would be
the first legislator from any nation to address the Security
Council. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   TAIWAN-CHINA (Taipei, Taiwan) _ In a move that could ease
tensions between Taiwan and China during the campaign for the
presidential election here, the candidate of the governing
Nationalist Party declines to reaffirm his government's policy of
dealing with China on a ``state to state'' basis. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-BANKING (Beijing) _ The head of China's central bank
describes renewed efforts to turn China's giant state banks and
ailing state enterprises into sound commercial operations, able to
withstand the competitive pressures that will follow China's entry
into the World Trade Organization. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-SECT (Beijing) _ More than 50 followers of the banned
Falun Gong spiritual group are being held at a psychiatric hospital
on the outskirts of Beijing, a Hong Kong humans rights group says.
By Elisabeth Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   YUGO-ARKAN (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ The Serbian paramilitary
leader Zeljko Raznatovic, known as Arkan, is buried. The Yugoslav
press reports that his assassin was arrested. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Dateline to come) _ Chechen rebels have
captured a senior Russian general in Grozny. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CENSUS-KICKOFF (Unalakleet, Alaska) _ Starting the census year
with a northern exposure, the census director himself came to a
snowbound village on the Bering Sea to start the count before the
spring thaw scatters the villagers. After Thursday, the bureau has
to count only an estimated 269,999,970 more people. By Steven A.
Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   CONN-GREENWICH-SLAYING (Dateline to come) _ Discussing the legal
issues surrounding the 25-year-old Martha Moxley slaying, in which
an arrest warrant was issued Wednesday for Michael Skakel, a nephew
of Ethel Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   NJ-SETONHALL-FIRE (Dateline to come) _ Developments in the
investigation of the Seton Hall University dorm fire that left
three dead and 60 injured Wednesday. By Robert Hanley.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON (``w'' code) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FCC-MINORITIES (Washington) _ The Federal Communications
Commission is expected to rule on a requirement that radio and
television stations seek minority job applicants. The commission's
previous affirmative action rule was voided by a Federal appeals
court in April 1998. By Neil A. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-EDUC (Washington) _ President Clinton is expected to
announce a higher education proposal that would encompass a $30
billion, 10-year initiative of tax deductions totaling $10,000 per
family for tuition, fees and training. By Marc Lacey.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   NEB-KERREY (Omaha) _ Sen. Bob Kerrey says he will not seek
re-election. By B. Drummond Ayres Jr.
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN-CAMPAIGN (Undated) _ The New Hampshire primary is less
than two weeks away, but you couldn't tell that by watching John
McCain the past couple of days as he has campaigned in Rhode Island
and Massachusetts and raised money in New York. A Political Memo.
By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-CAMPAIGN (Des Moines) _ Assessing the Bradley campaign
as the senator traverses Iowa on a four-day tour. By Richard L.
Berke.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-CAMPAIGN (Council Bluffs, Iowa) _ On Vice President Al
Gore's scheduled appearance here. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SEXUAL-EVOLUTION (Undated) _ The genes involved in sperm
production have been evolving at a much faster rate than most other
human genes, according to a study being published in the journal
Nature. The finding implies that in the human evolutionary past,
women generally had many sexual partners _ enough that the males'
sperm needed to compete with one another. &UR;  &LR; By Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   TRADE-DEFICIT (Washington) _ The U.S. trade deficit ballooned to
a record in November, fueled by brisk consumer demand, surging
imports from Canada and Europe and the highest oil prices in nearly
three years. By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-TAX-PROPOSAL (Undated) _ Looking at a Clinton proposal
to allow taxpayers to gradually use the personal exemptions they
take for dependents in calculating their obligation under the
alternative minimum tax, as well as the regular income tax. By
David Cay Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   G7-JAPAN-MEET (Tokyo) _ This weekend's meeting of finance
officials of the Group of Seven industrialized nations promises to
be a sleepy affair. At least, that's what the Japanese hosts are
hoping. Compared with the last two years, the global economy is in
a relatively serendipitous state. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   CHILE-ECONOMY (Santiago, Chile) _ Ricardo Lagos was President
Salvador Allende's appointed ambassador to &UR;  &LR;  Moscow at the time of
the bloody 1973 military coup. Now Lagos is poised to become the
second Socialist president in Chile's history. But Lagos will take
office as a friend of business. By Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   TOMMY-HILFIGER (Undated) _ Since July, the stock price for the
once invincible Tommy Hilfiger Corp. has been on the decline. Then,
a week ago, the company announced that it would fall far short of
earnings estimates for the quarter. Behind investors' sudden
distaste for the stock is a fear that the impresario of alternative
all-American fashion is losing his magic powers to connect with the
public _ or at least with the subset of the public that really
matters. By Leslie Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   COLLINS-COLUMN (Undated) _ ``Public Interests'' by Gail Collins.
</P>
<P>
   FRIEDMAN-COLUMN (Undated) _ ``Foreign Affairs'' by Thomas L.
Friedman.
</P>
