<SLUG> BC-TRENDS-NEXT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE) 
 BOOKMARK THESE HOT TEEN WEB SITES 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: THIS MAY BE PUBLISHED ONLY BY SUBSCRIBERS TO
``NEXT,'' A NEW COLUMN ON TRENDS FOR THE UNDER-30 CROWD, WRITTEN BY
JANE RINZLER BUCKINGHAM, PRESIDENT OF YOUTH INTELLIGENCE. FOR
INFORMATION ON BECOMING A CLIENT _ OR TO SEE MORE SAMPLES _ CALL
YOUR NEW YORK TIMES SYNDICATE SALES REPRESENTATIVE AT (888)
269-8796. ALL EDITORS WHO SIGN UP FOR THE COLUMN WILL GET
CUSTOMIZED VERSIONS OF YI'S RESPECTED ``CASSANDRA REPORTS,''
FOCUSING ON WHAT'S HOT AND WHAT'S NOT WITH GENERATIONS X AND WHY? 
</HEADLINE>
  By JANE RINZLER BUCKINGHAM  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Everyone, it seems, is jumping into the Net these days _ and
teens are no exception.
</P>
<P>
   Parents will be happy to know that some of the time teens spend
on-line is devoted to school-related research. But when work is
done and it's time to play, where do teens go? Here are some of the
sites that those in the know are likely to have bookmarked:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; bolt.com &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Think of this as an ivillage.com for teens. Bolt has managed to
create an on-line community for the young that even AOL might envy
_ and it seems to have been built mostly through word of e-mouth.
Though Bolt provides teens with free e-mail and voice mail, the
real draw is that the site is constantly offering fun free stuff,
forums on interesting subjects and links to other cool sites.
 &UR; gurl.com &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This is the big sister a teen always wanted. She gives great
advice and top-secret ``girlie'' info, she introduces you to her
friends and she takes you shopping. Created by young (although not
</P>
<P>
   teen) women, gurl.com features everything from gynecological
information to sports lessons. It provides the tools for visitors
to build their own home pages, and it runs open forums in which
they can sound off on teen-related issues. The tone is smart, savvy
and funny without being preachy.
 &UR; cdnow.com &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For teens, music and the Web are a perfect match. That's why
CDNow is so popular. In addition to allowing visitors to sample and
buy the latest releases, the site enables them to pursue their
passions in music. You can find information about Ricky Martin in
hundreds of places on the Web, but where else can a fan of an
obscure band such as Gay Dad find news and information about that
group as well as other fans to hook up with?
 &UR; alladvantage.com &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What could be better than spending an afternoon surfing the web?
How about getting paid to do it? That's right, AllAdvantage
actually pays people for their surfing time. The catch (you knew
there had to be one) is that you have to agree to add to your
screen a special viewbar that displays banner ads as you move from
site to site. It's not a bad deal, though, because AllAdvantage
creates a ``member profile'' for you designed to bring you
advertising that matches your interests.
 &UR; happypuppy.com &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No, I don't understand the name, but then, I'm not part of the
target audience for this site: teens (and adults) who are into
video games. Billed as the ``true voice of today's gamer,'' Happy
Puppy offers info, updates, tricks and everything else a video-game
junkie needs to survive. If you want to know whether it's worth it
to fly to Japan to score a Sony Playstation 2 (it won't be
available in America till the fall), check out Happy Puppy.
 &UR; theonion.com &LR; ,
</P>
<P>
   The Onion is a satirical newspaper that taps into the absurdity
of life and current events. If you need a laugh or a dose of
sarcasm, this is the place to go. Recent headline: ``AOL Acquires
Time-Warner in Largest-Ever Expenditure of Pretend Internet
Money.''
 &UR; alloy.com &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This is a popular site, though its focus has been a bit
confusing lately. What started out as a fashion site with a bit of
</P>
<P>
   community and content suddenly seems to be a community and
content site with a bit of fashion. Having said that, Alloy
understands what teens are into and gives them a hip place to
discuss it. And since talk is cheap _ and not all of the clothing
brands the site features are _ perhaps it's heading in the right
direction.
 &UR; netsetgoods.com and girlshop.com &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So much of the clothing available on the web looks like what
teens passed over in fashion a year ago. That's why they love the
merchandise NSG and Girlshop offer. These two sites manage to group
together some of the hippest goods around. Girlshop offers cool
designs from Manhattan boutiques, giving trend-forward teens from
other cities a chance to sport the very latest styles. NetSetGoods
is a teen's candy store with products a girl or guy would love to
own but isn't likely to come across in his or her local mall.
</P>
<P>
   Other popular sites include:
</P>
<P>
   HollywoodStockExchange (HSX.com)
</P>
<P>
   Atomfilms.com
</P>
<P>
   MTV.com
</P>
<P>
   ESPN.com
</P>
<P>
   Sony.com
</P>
<P>
   WWF.com
</P>
<P>
   NFL.com
</P>
<P>
   Wb.com
</P>
<P>
   Cosmogirl.com
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BOX: TREND WATCH: BE ON THE LOOKOUT FOR: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Capoeira (a Brazilian combination of dance and fighting moves)
</P>
<P>
   Lee Angel Color Therapy Bracelets (beaded bracelets whose colors
signify themes such as success, peace or happiness)
</P>
<P>
   Turquoise (the color and the stone)
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jane Rinzler Buckingham is the president of Youth Intelligence,
a market-research firm specializing in the 7- to 35-year-old
market. Her company publishes the Cassandra Report, a comprehensive
survey focused on identifying emerging trends among Generations X
and Why?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-00 1441EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000120.0091 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 14:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
