<HEADLINE>
(FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE) 
 BOOKMARK THESE HOT TEEN WEB SITES 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: THIS MAY BE PUBLISHED ONLY BY SUBSCRIBERS TO
``NEXT,'' A NEW COLUMN ON TRENDS FOR THE UNDER-30 CROWD, WRITTEN BY
JANE RINZLER BUCKINGHAM, PRESIDENT OF YOUTH INTELLIGENCE. FOR
INFORMATION ON BECOMING A CLIENT _ OR TO SEE MORE SAMPLES _ CALL
YOUR NEW YORK TIMES SYNDICATE SALES REPRESENTATIVE AT (888)
269-8796. ALL EDITORS WHO SIGN UP FOR THE COLUMN WILL GET
CUSTOMIZED VERSIONS OF YI'S RESPECTED ``CASSANDRA REPORTS,''
FOCUSING ON WHAT'S HOT AND WHAT'S NOT WITH GENERATIONS X AND WHY? 
</HEADLINE>
  By JANE RINZLER BUCKINGHAM  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Everyone, it seems, is jumping into the Net these days _ and
teens are no exception.
</P>
<P>
   Parents will be happy to know that some of the time teens spend
on-line is devoted to school-related research. But when work is
done and it's time to play, where do teens go? Here are some of the
sites that those in the know are likely to have bookmarked:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; bolt.com &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Think of this as an ivillage.com for teens. Bolt has managed to
create an on-line community for the young that even AOL might envy
_ and it seems to have been built mostly through word of e-mouth.
Though Bolt provides teens with free e-mail and voice mail, the
real draw is that the site is constantly offering fun free stuff,
forums on interesting subjects and links to other cool sites.
 &UR; gurl.com &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This is the big sister a teen always wanted. She gives great
