<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 14:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1424 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      01-20 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NATIONAL CRISIS HITS CLOSE TO HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROB MORSE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It's the San Francisco dilemma: how to love thy
neighbor without angering thy neighbors. I'm not sure there is a
way to open a homeless shelter without causing a ruckus.
</P>
<P>
   But here's how to cause a very big ruckus indeed.
</P>
<P>
   First, tell people you're opening a shelter in their
neighborhood, no matter what they think about it. Be perceived as
arrogant, in other words.
</P>
<P>
   Second, don't house the homeless already in the neighborhood,
but bus in new homeless people, young ones with a propensity for
drug use and prostitution.
</P>
<P>
   Third, lay a guilt trip on the liberals of the neighborhood for
caring more about the life savings they've invested in their homes
than the lives of runaway kids they've never met.
</P>
<P>
   This is the bad start the Metropolitan Community Church got off
to more than a month ago when the Rev. Jim Mitulski decided to
house 20 (now 10) ``gay, lesbian, bisexual, transgender, queer and
questioning youth'' at the church's branch on Church Street in Noe
Valley.
</P>
<P>
   The result was a community uproar, a petition against the
shelter signed by hundreds of merchants and residents, and final
approval of the shelter (with $54,290 in funding for three months)
by the city's Board of Supervisors on Tuesday, following a debate
that moved gingerly through a minefield of neighborhood concerns,
gay politics and homeless advocacy.
</P>
<P>
   Ten young people now have a place to get out of the rain, get
showers and get counseling, and things probably will be as placid
as they ever were in Noe Valley.
</P>
<P>
   But if this is what it takes to put a temporary roof over the
heads of the rest of the 14,000 homeless people in San Francisco,
God shelter us all from the storms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never got a reaction like this when I was passing out pot to
protest the ban on medical marijuana,'' Mitulski told me before
Christmas when the uproar started.
</P>
<P>
   That's the kind of minister Mitulski is. He's a self-described
``'70s kind of guy,'' a social activist and you-know-what
disturber. He seemed surprised by the fuss he caused, and said he
didn't mean to seem arrogant in his dealings in Noe Valley. His
idea, he said, was to follow the teachings of Christ.
</P>
<P>
   That's a sure way to get in trouble. You get in even more
trouble if you imply that your neighbors in the city of St. Francis
are behaving ungenerously toward the needy.
</P>
<P>
   In early December, Mitulski's public relations man tried to get
me interested in the issue. (Yes, Mitulski has a PR man, and he
isn't the only minister in town who does.) In my years in San
Francisco I've lived in three houses within a few of blocks of the
proposed shelter, and I was torn.
</P>
<P>
   I no longer live in the neighborhood, but I have old friends and
neighbors who feel the shelter was rammed down their throats by
Mitulski and Supervisor Tom Ammiano, who sponsored the funding
package.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, I priced some homes in Noe Valley and couldn't
afford them. I had to ask myself honestly: If I put everything I
had into a house on Church Street, how would I feel if I found out
a bunch of homeless kids, possible hustlers and drug users, were
going to be my new neighbors?
</P>
<P>
   I had to say I wouldn't be happy, even though I'm familiar with
the good people and good works of the Metropolitan Community
Church. I especially wouldn't like to be guilt-tripped about my
unhappiness, or have it implied that I'm prejudiced against those
who are ``gay, lesbian, bisexual, queer or questioning.''
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to doing the right thing for homeless people,
we're all questioning.
</P>
<P>
   I asked my wife, who generally is disgusted or frightened by
homeless people, what she thought. She surprised me by asking what
difference 10 mixed-up kids would make in the neighborhood,
especially if they were adequately controlled, as the MCC has
promised. She reminded me of some of the Noe Valley neighbors we
had.
</P>
<P>
   There was the redneck with the wrecked cars in his yard, the
teen-ager who shot herself to death, the homeless guy in the
schoolyard, and the dope peddlers who did business there on
weekends. There were Mother Teresa's nuns, the kid who covered
everything with graffiti, and the eccentric but charming
millionaire who had valet parkers running all over the street.
</P>
<P>
   It was a neighborhood that looked a bit like a suburb, but it
was part of a real city where dividing lines are hard to find. For
personal reasons, I had to leave Noe Valley and would be the last
to tell its residents what to think. But, after all this fuss, I
doubt those 10 kids are going to be a problem.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Mitulski seemed chastened by his experience, and
willing to get off to a fresh start.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope what comes out of this is a program that's a success, a
tribute to Noe Valley, and can be replicated in other
neighborhoods,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As I left City Hall, Sister Bernie Galvin, the tireless
campaigner for housing for homeless people, was practically
bouncing up and down with frustration by the experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just recently, the mayor was saying churches should do more
for the homeless, and now we have this,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the churches already do much more than their share,
and churches are located in residential neighborhoods. Loving thy
neighbors takes boundless sensitivity when some have $600,000
Victorian homes and some have wet cardboard.
</P>
<P>
   A national failure in housing and mental health care has led to
a city's police holding action and a needless confrontation between
a liberal church and its liberal neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Ten kids are out of the rain for three months at a cost of
$54,290 and a lot of bad feelings. There must be a better way.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-00 1446EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000120.0095 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 15:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1445 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-UNWANTED-BABIES-HNS &LR;      01-20 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNWANTED-BABIES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BILL WOULD ALLOW MOTHERS TO ABANDON NEWBORNS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARSHA GINSBURG  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A bill that would give unwanted newborns a
second chance at life by allowing their mothers to legally abandon
them is winning praise from social workers, public safety
employees, as well as both opponents and supporters of abortion
rights.
</P>
<P>
   Introduced Wednesday by state Sen. James Brulte and Assemblyman
Ken Maddox, both Republicans, the legislation would allow mothers
with unwanted babies 30 days or younger to drop them off at police
or fire stations, social welfare offices, child protective agencies
or county hospital emergency rooms with no questions asked and no
threat of prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   The only national survey, conducted by the U.S. Department of
Health and Human Services based on searches of news reports, found
that of 65 babies abandoned in 1991, eight died. In 1998, the
number jumped to 105, and 33 were found dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``This law gives babies a second chance,'' said Maddox, who
began looking into legislation after hearing about a baby left in a
garbage container in October. The boy was discovered by two
employees of a Walnut Creek dental clinic. The boy has been put up
for adoption.
</P>
<P>
   Brulte acted at the prodding of a San Bernardino County woman
whose organization recovers the bodies of unwanted babies and gives
them dignified burials.
</P>
<P>
   Social workers and groups on both sides of the abortion debate
say the bill has a good chance of getting the bipartisan support
both legislators are hoping for when hearings begin as early as
this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Although most groups had not seen the specific legislation,
which mirrors a Texas law that became the first of its kind in the
nation last September, they indicated it could save babies' lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very encouraged that legislators are considering
dealing with this heartbreaking issue, and offering a safe haven
for women who would allow their babies to be put up for adoption
rather than discarded,'' said Jan Carroll of the California
Pro-Life Council.
</P>
<P>
   The state chapter of Planned Parenthood agreed, although a
spokeswoman echoed the views of other child advocates who pointed
out that the legislation was not a solution to unwanted children.
</P>
<P>
   ``While this comes far after the fact, when intervention should
be earlier, we don't want women to be further stigmatized by
criminalizing the abandonment,'' said Kathy Kneer, of the state
chapter of Planned Parenthood in Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the real issue is making sure everyone knows their options
in a timely way,'' Kneer said. ``We need to start at the front end
of the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The 12,000-member National Association of Social Workers also
may support the legislation. Denny Ah-Tye, who serves on the
association's child welfare committee, said he would recommend
endorsement from the group's executive committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish we had this when I was doing adoptions 20 years ago,''
said Ah-Tye, a social worker with the San Joaquin County child
protective services division, noting that if mothers had not feared
prosecution, some might not have abandoned children in fields.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS. &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, billboards have sprung up in the Houston area _ where
11 babies were found in a nine-month period _ asking women not to
discard their newborns and telling them where to go for help.
</P>
<P>
   Ah-Tye said getting out information sensitively is as important
as passing the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Maddox said he hopes the bill ultimately will include money for
publicity and public awareness.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Moran, legislative advocate for the Sacramento-based
California State Firefighters Association, a professional trade
organization that represents 27,000 employees, said the proposal
sounds positive, but would need scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people assume fire departments have 20 to 30 guys
working at one time,'' he said, ``but some have three people on
duty. What happens if you get a call and someone's dropped a baby
off?''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, he said, ``we don't want to have abandoned
babies. That's just horrible. We've done worse things than having
to change a diaper.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-00 1506EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
