<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-CROWS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CROWS SOARING HIGH ON `LIFE' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  Eds.: An umlaut is needed over u in Immergluck) 
 
By MICHAEL D. CLARK 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's a stumper of a ``Jeopardy'' category that Alex Trebek can
add to the big board: Band Members.
</P>
<P>
   _ For $200, name any member of Counting Crows other than lead
singer Adam Duritz.
</P>
<P>
   _ For $400, name a person in the Dave Matthews Band other than
the title singer.
</P>
<P>
   It's the curse of being part of the supporting musical cast, as
opposed to a band leader, and dates back to when big bands were
named for frontmen like Tommy Dorsey and Harry James.
</P>
<P>
   In rock, unless a player is a member of the Beatles, the Rolling
Stones or the Spice Girls, he's just a supporting player. Some
musicians can't take that sort of ego check and seek out their own
above-the-marquee status _ Geri Halliwell, Joey McIntyre and former
Go Go Jane Wiedlin, for example.
</P>
<P>
   For others, like Counting Crows guitarist Dan Vickrey, it's a
blessing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being recognized has its perks and downsides, but personally
it would be weird if I got noticed,'' Vickrey said by phone from
his Los Angeles home. ``To be able to eat at restaurants without
being interrupted, it's nice.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a humble response, but if there was ever a case for band
members getting the same recognition as their lead vocalist, it's
Counting Crows.
</P>
<P>
   Since the group formed in 1990, Duritz has been providing
grainy, winsome prose about people who are needed or in need.
Without Vickrey's and David Bryson's guitars, Charles Gillingham's
keyboards, and percussion by bassist Matt Malley and drummer Ben
Mize, however, the words would be just poetry on the page.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Matthews and the band Blues Traveler, Counting Crows
provides one of the largest, layered, improvisational rock-band
experiences currently touring.
</P>
<P>
   Fans are likely to hear favorites like ``Rain King'' lapse into
a chorus of Bruce Springsteen's ``Thunder Road'' or a bluesy,
nearly unrecognizable rendition of the signature hit ``Mr. Jones.''
</P>
<P>
   That's if the Crows stop getting complaints from fans who want
to hear the original upbeat version as played on the group's debut
album, ``August &AMP; Everything After.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't call what people say about the slow version (of
''Mr. Jones``) exactly feedback,'' Vickrey laughed. ``People want
to hear the song they recognize, but Adam has to sing it, and for a
long time he didn't like how it felt.''
</P>
<P>
   Purists will be happy to know that lately, the band has been
playing the uptempo ``Mr. Jones'' with greater frequency _ a
reflection that Duritz and the band are loose, happy and content
with the success of their album ``This Desert Life.''
</P>
<P>
   Look further back in history and you'll see that the live
mutations of ``Mr. Jones'' have always served as the Crows' mood
ring. The group's jubilant, early party versions were symbolic of a
young band whose first big break was filling in for Van Morrison at
the 1993 Rock and Roll Hall of Fame induction _ a group whose first
album went to No. 4 on the Billboard charts and didn't leave the
list for 93 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Months earlier, even Duritz was a virtual unknown. Counting
Crows was a San Francisco phenomenon who had spent several years on
the Bay Area circuit before winning the BMI New Music Showcase in
February 1992 and getting signed by David Geffen's DGC Records.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Counting Crows put my entire show on the map. They had
offers from 12 labels the day after their performance,'' says
showcase organizer Nadine Condon. ``Adam's unique voice helped
invent the AAA (Adult Album Alternative) radio format.''
</P>
<P>
   When ``August &AMP; Everything After'' hit paydirt, the Crows
gleefully did the whole ``it'' band circuit: ``Saturday Night
Live,'' opening for the Rolling Stones, and using their muscle to
get favorite college radio artists like Alex Chilton and Buffalo
Tom to tour with them.
</P>
<P>
   Duritz has called ``August &AMP; Everything After'' the ``mopey
album'' and its follow-up, ``Recovering the Satellites,'' the
``recovering from being mopey'' album. It was a slow healing. The
second album was three years in creation, and the songs were an
L.A. rock fable of being grated across the celebrity scrub board.
</P>
<P>
   ``Recovering the Satellites'' wasn't nearly the commercial
success of the Crows' debut, and the metronome on ``Mr. Jones''
started slowing considerably. By the time the band released its
live double-album, ``Across the Wire: Live in New York,'' it had
become a melancholy harmonica jam with an ironic bit of the Byrds,
``So You Want to Be a Rock &AMP; Roll Star,'' opening the first verse.
</P>
<P>
   ``The live album was a snapshot of where we were at that moment
in time and was generally for the fans,'' Vickrey said. ``I think
Adam's state at the time comes through.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Jones''' return to its original tempo may have to do with
the group enjoying its first official renaissance. Well-rested
following a holiday break, the band is resuming its tour for the
well-received ``This Desert Life.'' Last week the album was resting
at No. 41 on the Billboard 200 after 10 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The Crows had entered their Los Angeles home studio with
absolutely no songs written and came out months later with an album
that sounds neither mopey nor in recovery.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of producer Dave Lowery _ moonlighting from his
job as Cracker's vocalist _ the first single, ``hangingaround,'' is
the first loose band jam since ``Mr. Jones.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Going into the studio with nothing was more stupidity than
anything. I was thinking, `God, this could take years,''' Vickrey
said. ``It happened to work out well, which says a lot about the
current personality of this band.''
</P>
<P>
   The tour has already been to Europe and will continue in North
America and Australia through this year.
</P>
<P>
   Opening for the band on the tour is Joe 90, a junior guitar-jam
ensemble signed to Duritz's label, E Pluribus Unum. Joining
Counting Crows for its set is guitarist and longtime friend David
Immergluck, who played mandolin on the original studio recording of
``Rain King.''
</P>
<P>
   At this point no one in Counting Crows is a nobody, whether fans
know their names or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a good push-and-pull between music and vocals right
now and are very confident with each other,'' Vickrey said. ``That
started in the studio and has continued to be the case on the
road.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
