<SLUG> BC-MUSICAL-FOSSE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FOSSE' REVUE DELIVERS THE OLD RAZZLE-DAZZLE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By EVERETT EVANS 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ ``Fosse.''
</P>
<P>
   One word says it all.
</P>
<P>
   It summons up the man, the career, the choreographic style of
one of the major figures in American musical theater and dance.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Fosse (1927-87) danced in nightclubs and movies, on Broadway
and television.
</P>
<P>
   As director and/or choreographer, he guided some of Broadway's
biggest hits, including ``The Pajama Game,'' ``Damn Yankees,''
``Redhead,'' ``New Girl in Town,'' ``Sweet Charity,'' ``Pippin,''
``Chicago'' and ``Dancin'.'' He directed the films ``Sweet
Charity,'' ``Cabaret,'' ``Lenny'' and ``All That Jazz.''
</P>
<P>
   He won numerous Tony Awards for his Broadway work, an Emmy for
the TV special ``Liza With a Z'' ... and an Academy Award for his
direction of ``Cabaret.''
</P>
<P>
   Fosse's dance style may be the most instantly recognizable of
any choreographer. Among its many signature traits are dancers in
skin-tight black; close-knit groups edging across the stage; cocked
derbies; the elbows-out, knees-in posture; the isolated movement of
an enticing finger, rolling shoulder or waggling hip.
</P>
<P>
   The overall effect usually is sensuous, ironic and insinuating.
Jazzy. Sexy. Fosse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fosse'' is Broadway's current hit made up of numbers from his
shows and films.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Winner of the 1999 Tony Award as best musical, the revue is making
its Houston debut in a touring company playing through Jan. 23 at
Jones Hall.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I think he was brilliant,'' said Ann Reinking,
co-director and co-choreographer of ``Fosse.'' ``His contribution
was huge. He never stopped working. When I came to work on this
project, I was impressed by the wealth of material we had to choose
from.''
</P>
<P>
   Reinking not only performed in many of Fosse's shows but was
also for some years his partner. She choreographed the hit revival
of ``Chicago'' in his trademark style as an homage.
</P>
<P>
   Reinking spoke by phone between breaks in London rehearsals for
``Fosse's'' opening there Feb. 8.
</P>
<P>
   In the show's somewhat complex credits, ``Fosse'' is conceived
by Reinking, Chet Walker and Richard Maltby Jr., directed by
Maltby, with Fosse's choreography re-created by Walker and Gwen
Verdon serving as artistic adviser.
</P>
<P>
   Verdon is the ultimate Fosse interpreter, having starred in
``Damn Yankees,'' ``New Girl in Town,'' ``Redhead,'' ``Sweet
Charity'' and ``Chicago.'' For many years, the director and his
star also were married.
</P>
<P>
   It was Verdon who initiated the project, according to Reinking.
Verdon started a dance lab in New York, at which dancers could
learn Fosse's style while participating in reconstructions of his
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   During that two-year process, Verdon showed the work to agents
and producers. Garth Drabinsky, then chief of Toronto-based Livent
Inc., became interested in producing a show built on Fosse's
choreography.
</P>
<P>
   Reinking, who had participated in helping reconstruct dances
from shows she had performed, was hired by Drabinsky as ``Fosse's''
co-director/co-choreographer as the show moved into a lengthy
workshop phase before its world premiere in Toronto in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough choosing from the 45 or so numbers that Gwen had
re-created,'' Reinking said.
</P>
<P>
   Though there are short pieces from Fosse's early nightclub and
film work, and signature numbers from `50s and `60s shows (``Steam
Heat'' from ``Pajama Game'' and ``Big Spender'' from ``Sweet
Charity''), Fosse seems skewed to his work of the 1970s and '80s _
and usually to the more overtly sexy numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fosse'' faced the same dilemma as 1989's ``Jerome Robbins'
Broadway,'' another retrospective built around a famed
choreographer's career. Could numbers created for a book musical be
as effective in a revue format, detached from their original
contexts?
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to choose numbers that could be lifted out and hold
their own without needing to know the story,'' Reinking said
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps understandably, the show most heavily represented is
``Dancin','' Fosse's plotless, all-dance revue of 1978, which he
choreographed to existing music from varied sources. That's also
the reason there are several numbers Fosse choreographed for TV
variety shows.
</P>
<P>
   If some of Fosse's major Broadway productions (``New Girl in
Town,'' ``Redhead'') are largely unrepresented, that's partly
because the numbers were too plot-oriented to work in the revue
format. Reinking said that the ``Fosse'' team also decided to avoid
having other dancers do any of Verdon's big numbers _ even such
seeming Fosse musts as ``Whatever Lola Wants'' from ``Damn
Yankees'' and ``If My Friends Could See Me Now'' from ``Sweet
Charity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't find anyone who could do them as well in her
style,'' Reinking said. ``It's hard to go up against a legend.''
</P>
<P>
   Does Reinking feel it's an oversimplification to define the
Fosse style solely in terms of hip-swinging sexiness?
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a man terribly interested in innocence, the loss of
innocence and everything in between,'' Reinking said. ``Because of
his better-known later shows, many people would be surprised he
choreographed innocent numbers like ''Real Live Girl`` (from
''Little Me``). His work's not just sexy. ''Big Spender`` has
sexuality, but I find it more comedic than sensual. It's more about
looking tired!
</P>
<P>
   ``What separated him from someone who might be just as good a
craftsman was that Bob dealt with paradoxes. He was always playing
at least two things at same time. His movement could be elegant yet
funky, sensuous yet witty.''
</P>
<P>
   Reinking's next project, a new musical based on Friedrich
Durrenmatt's ``The Visit,'' will place her amid a dream team of
Broadway talent: composer John Kander, lyricist Fred Ebb,
librettist Terrence McNally, director Frank Galati and as star,
four-time Tony winner Angela Lansbury in her long-awaited return to
Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be creating musical staging as opposed to hard-driving
dance in the Fosse style, a nice change. And I am so eager to work
with all these people that I couldn't pass it up.''
</P>
<P>
   If all goes as planned, ``The Visit'' will try out in Chicago in
fall 2000 and open on Broadway in early 2001.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
