<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CITY WANTS STATE HELP FOR DIALLO TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ELIZABETH BENJAMIN   
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ City officials say it could cost up to $1 million
in police overtime and other expenses to handle the crowds expected
in Albany to protest the trial of four New York City police
officers accused of killing an unarmed man.
</P>
<P>
   Albany Mayor Jerry Jennings said he has asked the state Office
of Court Administration to reimburse the city for overtime costs
incurred during the trial. Jury selection begins on Jan. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Activists, members of the clergy and lawmakers from New York
have promised to lead busloads of protesters to Albany for the
trial of four white police officers accused of fatally shooting
Amadou Diallo, a 22-year-old West African immigrant, last February
in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fairness to my taxpayers and this city, I would think they
would make the appropriate accommodations,'' Jennings said
Wednesday. ``There are extenuating circumstances, and we had
nothing to say about the change of venue.''
</P>
<P>
   Jennings also said he plans to push for cameras to be allowed in
the courthouse during the Diallo trial. Under current state law,
cameras are banned from all trial courtrooms. The cable network
Court TV has a motion pending in state Supreme Court to allow
television cameras into the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings said he hopes the proceedings would at least be
broadcast via closed-circuit television to a large venue, such as
the Empire State Convention Center, because the Albany County
Courthouse cannot accommodate the crowds of people expected at the
trial.
</P>
<P>
   The crowds could put a serious strain on the city's finances if
Albany is not reimbursed by the state for all or part of the
expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Without the additional expense of the trial, the city expects to
spend $1.6 million in police overtime this year, $400,000 of which
would be reimbursed by private companies that hire off-duty
officers to provide security.
</P>
<P>
   Protest organizers have estimated their numbers could reach as
high as 15,000 people a day throughout the trial, but Jennings on
Wednesday said he does not expect that many.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings, Deputy Mayor Philip Calderone and City Treasurer Betty
Barnette _ the city's highest ranking African-American elected
official _ said they are determined to send a message that Albany
will not allow the Diallo trial to overtake or divide it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The minority elected officials are very concerned that this
not turn into a black versus white issue or us versus them or
downstate versus upstate,'' Barnette said. ``We are just as
committed to justice as anyone, anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   A judge ordered the trial moved to Albany, saying the officers
could not get a fair trial in the Bronx because of all the
publicity surrounding the case.
</P>
<P>
   The officers _ Kenneth Boss, Sean Carroll, Edward McMellon and
Richard Murphy
</P>
<P>
   _ are charged with murder and reckless endangerment in the Feb.
4, 1999, shooting of Diallo. Diallo was in the vestibule of his
Bronx home when he was hit by 19 of the 41 bullets fired by the
officers who said they believed the man was armed and dangerous.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
