   Sports stories from The New York Times News Service for  &UR; FRIDAY,
Jan. 21 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   BBO-VECSEY-COLUMN (Undated) _ Sports of the Times column on the
major league baseball owners, who have now granted Commissioner Bud
Selig new powers to act in the ``best interest'' of the game,
including the powers to block trades and redistribute some of the
wealth to help restore competitive balance. By George Vecsey.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-JETS-BELICHECK (Undated) _ NFL Commissioner Paul Tagliabue
is expected to rule today on whether Bill Belichick has a valid
contract with the Jets that prevents him from bolting to the New
England Patriots and becoming that team's new coach and general
manager. By Gerald Eskenazi.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-JACKSONVILLE-TAYLOR (Jacksonville, Fla.) _ Feature on Fred
Taylor, the standout running back of the Jacksonville Jaguars. By
Thomas George.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-RAMS-VERMEIL (St. Louis) _ On Pro Football column on the
Rams' Dick Vermeil, who has shown surprising flexibility in his
second go-round as an NFL coach. By Michael Freeman.
</P>
<P>
   GLF-HOPE-CLASSIC (Bermuda Dunes, Calif.) _ Second round of the
Bob Hope Chrysler Classic. By Clifton Brown. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TEN-AUSTRALIA (Melbourne) _ The Australia Open continues.
</P>
<P>
   BOX-ORGANIZATION (Undated) _ Many critics say the pivotal
problem in boxing today is that there is no central governing body,
as there are in other professional sports, that would enforce
safety rules, create credible rankings and ensure that the best
fighters rise. In short, no one is in charge.
</P>
