<P>
   Weekend Section stories from The New York Times News Service for
Friday, Jan. 21.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NEW-MUSIC-SOLOISTS (Undated) _ Ensembles that play only new
music are plentiful these days, but soloists who play recitals
devoted entirely to newly commissioned works are scarce enough to
seem heroic or eccentric, or perhaps a bit of both. By Allan
Kozinn.
</P>
<P>
   THEATRICAL-WRITER (New York) _ One afternoon about three years
ago, Claudia Shear got the type of call young writers dream about.
Thus began a most unlikely creative partnership, between James
Lapine, the respected Broadway director and writer, and Ms. Shear,
the manic comic actress whose autobiographical play, ``Blown
Sideways Through Life,'' became an unexpected off-Broadway hit in
1993. The result of their three-year collaboration is ``Dirty
Blonde,'' an affectionate look at the lives of Mae West and two of
her most ardent admirers. By Jesse McKinley.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-ART (Undated) _ The history of American art at the end of
the 20th century is at least in part the history of AIDS. Despite
all this, AIDS went all but unmentioned in the recent rash of
retrospectives. One reason is simply that, with the successful use
of expensive palliative drugs since the late 1990s, the disease has
lost its aura of emergency for middle-class whites in the United
States. This is not the case, however, for the rest of the world,
where the devastation from AIDS has assumed hurricane force. And
that fact is evident in ``Bodies of Resistance,'' an exhibition at
Real Art Ways in Hartford organized by Visual AIDS. By Holland
Cotter.
</P>
<P>
   SKI-N-SHOP (Undated) _ Zermatt it's not. It's not Vail or even
Stratton, its tonier neighbor in the Green Mountains of southern
Vermont. But Bromley, a four-hour drive north of Manhattan, offers
congenial family skiing and snowboarding with a bonus: proximity to
the outlet mecca of Manchester Center with its designer shops of
discounted Giorgio Armani, Calvin Klein, Gianni Versace, Dansk,
Godiva and other haut-branded fashions, housewares and edibles. In
short, all the makings for a perfect ``ski 'n' shop'' excursion. By
Ralph Blumenthal.
</P>
