<HEADER>
A1471 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e BC-IVOR-QUIZ-SHOW-MANIA-     01-20 1505
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVOR-QUIZ-SHOW-MANIA-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE QUIZ SHOWS THAT ROSE FROM THE DEAD 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
entertainment column.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 Includes black-and-white photos and color slides of Regis Philbin
in a scene from ``Who Wants to be a Millionaire.'' 
 By IVOR DAVIS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    In case you've been on an extended tour of the Himalayas for the
past couple of months, an epidemic is raging through the land _
more insidious than Pokemon, more virulent than the flu.
 &HT;    It's Quiz-Showitis, and it's making the television industry very
nervous.
 &HT;    Imagine you're Leslie Moonves, president and CEO of CBS, and you
wake up one morning to find that the folks over at ABC have
virtually abolished their entire nightly schedule, filling their
prime-time airwaves with an imported British quiz show based on
multiple-choice questions a 3-year-old could answer. Sample: ``What
color is an Oreo cookie?''
 &HT;    Naturally, you're delighted _ clearly, the decision-makers at
one of your chief competitors have gone stark, staring mad.
 &HT;    You're still rubbing your hands in glee when the ratings come in
... showing that, in its summertime trial run of two weeks, ABC's
``Who Wants To Be A Millionaire'' raked in a staggering 14 million
viewers a night.
 &HT;    Thereafter, the news just gets worse: A November sweeps series
of ``Millionaire'' and then a January run _ which attracts a
whopping 33.7 million viewers _ turns ``Is that your final
answer?'' into, heaven help us, the first catch phrase of the new
century and, oh yes, turns television programming on its head.
 &HT;    If you're Moonves, there's only one thing you can do: Jump on
the bandwagon just as quickly as you can, even though you know you
shouldn't. You have to react quickly because, if you don't, ABC
will win every ratings sweep into the next millennium.
 &HT;    Talking to a January meeting of television critics in Pasadena,
Calif., Moonves is almost apologetic in announcing his plans to
dive into the game-show fray with a new CBS show, ``Winning
Lines.'' And, just in case game shows stay hot, the network also
plans to revive the 1960s-vintage ``The $64,000 Question'' and
``What's My Line?'' as soon as possible.
 &HT;    ``I'm not in favor of it,'' Moonves admits. ``I made a statement
a few months ago that every half-hour of a game show that's on the
air means 100 people are out of work, and by that I mean writers,
producers, directors.
 &HT;    ``And if it expands from three to five to seven nights _ which,
judging from these numbers, it very well might _ I don't
necessarily think it's good for television.''
 &HT;    Garth Ancier, president of NBC's entertainment division, agrees.
Though he and veteran NBC producer Fred Silverman quickly decided
to drag the scandal-plagued 1950s series ``Twenty-One'' from the
network vaults, dust it off, dumb it down and stick Maury Povich in
front of those soundproof booths, Ancier is no game-show fan.
 &HT;    In fact, he compares quiz shows to crack cocaine.
 &HT;    ``It's an addictive substance that gives you high ratings but
may not in the long term be good for you,'' Ancier says.
```Millionaire' has changed everything. It's probably the most
significant program change in the history of television.''
 &HT;    And indeed, with the jagged music, the hyped-up tension and
their sweaty pallors, ``Millionaire's'' contestants do bear more
than a passing resemblance to victims of a controlled substance.
 &HT;    Over at the Fox network, whose contender in the game-show stakes
is ``Greed'' _ give them, at least, points for honesty _ Sandy
Grushow, chairman of the network's entertainment group, faces the
unpleasant task of defending a show whose contestants climb ``the
tower of greed'' as host Chuck Woolery challenges, ``Do you feel
the need for greed?''
 &HT;    Apparently they do _ successful ``Greed'' contestants can go
home with $2 million.
 &HT;    Grushow didn't give ``Greed'' a big buildup to the assembled
critics, and doesn't mince words explaining why.
 &HT;    ``These sessions are really designed to put our best foot
forward and show you the stuff that we feel you're going to get the
most excited about,'' he says. ``Obviously, we're the second game
show in the marketplace and we'd rather be first. We love the
numbers, but this network historically has been about taking risks
and being innovative, and we wanted to be out there first.''
 &HT;    So if nobody wants it _ except, of course, ``Millionaire'' host
Regis Philbin and the folks at ABC _ why is it happening? Why has
``Millionaire'' turned the networks into mindless copycats, and how
do they account for the phenomenon?
 &HT;    Philbin himself says the reason is simple.
 &HT;    ``Every American dreams of becoming a millionaire,'' he says.
``Now you can do it _ on TV and in one night.''
 &HT;    For Nancy Tellem, president of CBS' entertainment division, it's
about our culture.
 &HT;    ``It has money, the questions are so accessible that my
8-year-old, my 11-year-old and my 15-year-old can answer most of
them,'' she says, ``and I think people feel good about it.''
 &HT;    Maury Povich, who will host ``Twenty-One,'' thinks it's really
about family values.
 &HT;    ``You're talking about a show that, for the first time, young
people and their parents can watch together,'' Povich says, ``and
you get the entire family around the television set, the way it was
when these game shows were popular in the '50s.''
 &HT;    Silverman thinks ``Twenty-One'' is like social promotion in high
school: Answer the dumb question and pass on to the next level. He
says he never even considered keeping the show's original format,
in which intellectual heavyweights wrestled with amazingly arcane
questions.
 &HT;    ``No,'' he says bluntly. ``We rejected it because we didn't
think it would work. We looked at those old tapes, and they were
really boring _ you really had to be a Ph.D to answer those
questions.''
 &HT;    Nevertheless, Ancier insists with a straight face that the
attraction of game shows is educational.
 &HT;    ``I'm not kidding,'' he says. ``When they held focus groups for
`Wheel of Fortune,' which is simpler to play than `Twenty-One' or
`Millionaire,' people said they watched it because they wanted to
learn new phrases. That was the No. 1 reason our focus groups gave:
They want to get smarter.
 &HT;    ``And I think they like the idea of being able to see somebody
else become rich,'' he adds. ``People say, `I could have been a
millionaire. I could answer all those questions.'''
 &HT;    It was Michael Davies, a transplanted Brit, who was responsible
for shipping ``Millionaire'' across the Atlantic. He plans to
follow it up with another long-running British staple,
``Mastermind,'' which captured the English imagination by the
difficulty of the questions posed.
 &HT;    By the time the show lands on American soil, however, it's
likely that the questions will be more high-school freshman than
postgraduate.
 &HT;    Television executives are reluctant to speculate how long the
game-show mania will last. It may even turn out to be a one-show
phenomenon, with only ``Millionaire'' itself surviving.
 &HT;    But if the trend lasts beyond a couple of seasons, it poses
long-term risks for the industry. Sitcoms will need to draw huge
numbers to compete. Shows that appeal to smaller groups will go
under quickly, and _ one blessing _ the wall-to-wall nightly news
magazines are already biting the dust, because game shows are even
cheaper to produce.
 &HT;    And if that comes to pass, when the boom inevitably fades,
networks could find themselves with gaping holes in their schedules
and nothing in the pipeline to fill those holes.
 &HT;    Could ABC, whose complete reliance on ``Millionaire'' makes it
especially vulnerable, live to regret it if, a couple of seasons
down the line, the show fades out and leaves nothing else that's
been developed for the network?
 &HT;    Over at CBS, Leslie Moonves smiles.
 &HT;    ``God,'' he says, ``I hope so.''
 c.2000 Ivor Davis  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter and columnist.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: Don't forget to visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site
at http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on Hollywood
Stars and other features. &QL; 
