<SLUG> BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.2000 Special for The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are Anne Stephenson's  &UR; NEW &AMP; NOTABLE capsule book reviews:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; ``YUKON ALONE'' &QL; 
 &UR; By John Balzar (Holt, $25) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   New &AMP; Notable is a sucker for adventure stories, particularly _
given a certain publishing orgy of late _ any story that does not
take place on Mount Everest or involve bodies that will never be
found. We were happy to discover that the Yukon can be just as cold
as Everest and is not nearly so trendy. In fact, the sled dog race
called the Yukon Quest was established 15 years ago by traditional
mushers in answer to the increasingly chic Iditarod, which has
given rise to competitors (Balzar calls them ``big names in dog
mushing'') who dress like race-car drivers and have dog handlers in
matching uniforms. Not so the mushers of the Quest. They are an
odd, scruffy lot, and their race is an odd, lonely ordeal: 1,023
miles from Canada's Yukon Territory to Fairbanks, Alaska, in the
long darkness of February. Balzar spent months among these people
to profile the 1998 Quest for the ``Los Angeles Times.'' His book
is about a place where priorities are different and life is
demanding, and both are what you make of them. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ``SUNDANCING'' &QL; 
By John Anderson (Spike, $12.50) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This is a behind-the-scenes story of the Sundance Film Festival,
and it isn't pretty. It is crowded, commercial, competitive and
very, very important to the independent filmmakers who come to
Sundance like pilgrims to a glitzy, overproduced mecca of their
dreams. They come in search of success, something that became
associated with Sundance after 1989, when Steven Soderberg's film
``sex, lies and videotape'' changed the face of both the festival
and the independent film itself. Anderson, film critic for
``Newsday,'' went to Sundance last year and spent lots of time
listening to people talk about it _ everyone from actors, writers
and directors to journalists, publicists and even a police officer
who impounded Clint Eastwood's car (``He was very personable, a
very nice person to visit with. He had his picture taken with us
and seemed to be enjoying himself.''). We must make do with the
implied presence of Robert Redford, whose reticence is notorious
and who is, one director says, like a ``phantom'' at his own
festival. Not surprisingly, he and the Sundance Institute declined
to be involved with this book. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ``MONSTER'' &QL; 
By Jonathan Kellerman (Random House, $25.95) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kellerman is a psychologist. That gives him the upper hand in
this thriller, which begins in the exercise yard of a hospital for
the criminally insane. Kellerman's recurring character, Alex
Delaware, himself a psychologist, has come with Detective Milo
Sturgis to search for clues in the brutal slaying of Dr. Claire
Argent, who worked among the strange and frightening inmates of the
hospital. These men are incarcerated for life, having killed people
for no logical reason and with particularly disgusting and
blood-splattering abandon. How then could one of them have been
involved in a murder that occurred on the outside? You begin to
suspect the answer to this question around about Page 79, but then
suspense is not the strong suit of this book. That honor belongs to
its portrayal of these seriously dangerous men, their taste for
violence and their relationships with the people who treat them.
Delaware and Sturgis discover that Argent's murder has roots in a
dreadful crime committed nearly two decades earlier. We relive
every gory detail of it and more. Enjoy. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``LIFE STORIES'' &QL; 
Edited by David Remnick (Random House, $26.95) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Light the candles, practice the song, the ``New Yorker'' is 75
and Remnick wants you to make a fuss. By way of encouragement, he
has edited two delectable volumes. This is a collection of
profiles, biographical pieces for which the magazine is justly
famous. Included, among others, are Lillian Ross' look at Ernest
Hemingway, Truman Capote on Marlon Brando, Roger Angell on
baseball's Steve Blass, Calvin Trillin on Edna Buchanan, Henry
Louis Gates Jr. on Anatole Broyard, A.J. Liebling on Floyd
Patterson, and Susan Orlean's hilarious profile of a show dog
called Biff Truesdale. Remnick's second offering is ``Wonderful
Town'' (Random House, $26.95), a collection of short stories set in
New York and published over the years in the ``New Yorker.'' A
partial list of contributors: Philip Roth, Woody Allen, James
Thurber, John Cheever, John O'Hara, Deborah Eisenberg, John Updike,
Dorothy Parker, William Maxwell, E.B. White, Saul Bellow, S.J.
Perelman, Vladimir Nabokov, Lorrie Moore . . . we could go on and
on. Excuse us while we locate our matches and don our paper hats. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
