<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 16:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1474 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-ICE-CLIMBING-2TAKES-H     01-20 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ICE-CLIMBING-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ADVICE FOR VERTICLE CLIMBS: TAKE IT EASY ON THE ICE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ALAN WECHSLER  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KEENE VALLEY, N.Y. _ Less than 30 feet up the ice face, and
already I could feel the burn.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to be aware of your body when the temperature is in
the 20s, the wind is blowing snow sideways and you're clad in
numerous layers of fleece and Gore-Tex. Nevertheless, as I stood
there gripping ice tools, I slowly became aware that the strength
in my arms was rapidly fading. My swing was weakening, and I could
barely make a dent with my ax in the bullet-proof ice. My glasses
were fogging. My feet, perilously clinging to the ice face by the
sharp front points of a pair of crampons, seemed ready to skate
off. There was a good ledge _ a rest position _ about 10 feet above
my head, but I knew I wouldn't make it. Earlier in the day, a
fellow climber had described how his arms were once so exhausted he
thought his biceps would burst into flame. I knew how he felt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tension!'' I yelled down to my belayer _ the person on the
ground who controls the rope _ and he tightened the rope attached
to the harness at my waist. I let my body fall off the cliff, onto
the rope, and dangled there, holding my useless arms behind my back
to help blood flow. The burn had claimed another victim.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Sunday, I spent the day climbing at the popular and
difficult Pitchoff Mountain Quarry Wall, a 75-foot rock face
covered top to bottom in thick, sharp icicles. It was the second
day of the Fourth Annual Adirondack International Mountainfest, and
I was taking a course with the legendary Don Mellor. More than 100
climbers took part in various seminars over the weekend, paying for
sessions led by world-famous climbers such as Greg Child and Mark
Synnott, whose first-ascents of mile-high cliff faces have been
documented on television and in National Geographic magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Mellor, a schoolteacher from Lake Placid, who has
climbed only in the Northeast. Nevertheless, he is known here as
the ``Dean of Adirondack Climbing,'' and has put up more than 100
first ascents in the Adirondacks in the past 20 years. He is the
author of ``Climbing in the Adirondacks,'' the only guide to rock
and ice routes in these mountains. The guide is in its third
printing.
</P>
<P>
   He is also, apparently, a wimp.
</P>
<P>
   The title of his course was ``Steep Climbing for the Weak and
Chicken-Hearted.'' The theme was this: ice climbing is hard and
scary, and the best way to climb safely _ the best way to avoid the
burn _ is to climb as efficiently as possible. Mellor's goal was to
teach us how to rest in unusual ways while clinging to a vertical
ice face, so we could enjoy climbing instead of suffering through
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever works, do it,'' he told the class early on, advising
us to ignore long-practiced style rules like ``don't use your
knees,'' ``always keep your ankles down'' or ``always have three
points of contact on the ice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are absolutely no rules to climbing,'' he said. ``Just
climb!''
</P>
<P>
   Ice climbing is far less subtle than rock climbing, its
warm-weather equivalent. You use two ice axes, wicked devices with
short handles and a jagged, curved pick that you drive into the
ice. The axes also have wrist leashes, which you hang off to rest
over-gripped fingers.
</P>
<P>
   Climbers also wear plastic or very stiff leather boots and
crampons with front points, a set of spikes that allow a climber to
stand on ice in many different ways.
</P>
<P>
   Ice climbing is certainly more dangerous than ascending rock.
Pieces of ice are constantly knocked down. In certain areas,
avalanches are a possibility. Frostbite or hypothermia is always a
threat. And there are other dangers _ a few years ago, while
climbing a popular low-angle slab at Chapel Pond, Mellor found
himself in the air when the ice he was on exploded. The water
beneath had built up enough pressure so that as Mellor climbed, a
plate of ice cracked off and blew him into the air. Luckily the
beginner at the other end of the rope held his fall. Last winter, a
climber was killed rappelling near that same route.
</P>
<P>
   While rock-climbing has been extremely popular for more than 20
years, ice climbing really came of age in the 1990s. Technological
improvements such as aggressively shaped ice axes and crampon
points have helped climbers ascend routes never before thought
possible, even on faces without ice (using a perilous technique
known as dry-tooling).
</P>
<P>
   (MORE MORE)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KEENE VALLEY, N.Y.: x x x known as dry-tooling). &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mellor began climbing in the old days, teaching himself by
reading alpine pioneer Yvon Chouinard's ``Climbing Ice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so dogmatic, it was unbelievable,'' he said. ``You had
to use a 77-millimeter ax, you had to bend your ankles. People are
still out there using those French terms. We just wanted to
climb.''
</P>
<P>
   So Mellor and his buddies began to ignore the advice of the
climbing ``gods'' and invented their own techniques. And now, he
was teaching them to us.
</P>
<P>
   Once at the cliff, after climbers had a chance to warm up (or in
my case, flame out), we gathered around the Dean for a lesson in
climbing without breathing hard.
</P>
<P>
   His technique was completely efficient. He centered his body
over his ice tool, taking advantage of every natural rest he could
find. If there was a block of ice at his back, he would bend his
knee and kick his heel in behind him, sitting down on the top of
his boot. At a ledge, he'd throw his knee over the lip and almost
lie down, letting his arms dangle. His feet almost never skipped
off the ice, his tool placements were straight and true and rarely
required more than one swing for a solid placement.
</P>
<P>
   And, most importantly, he paused at almost every move. The idea
was to rest on the easy stuff, so when you reach the hard section,
you've still got energy left.
</P>
<P>
   ``At every possible rest, top off your tank,'' he said. ``People
who are not patient enough will climb through the easy stuff and
wonder why they can't get through the hard part.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time he was done, the snow had intensified. Wind poured
down from Cascade Pass and our jackets were coated with frost.
Nevertheless, I picked up a set of ice axes and tied into the rope
for one more trip up the cliff.
</P>
<P>
   The route I picked was steeper than the first, with fewer
footholds and some overhangs to surmount. Attempting to emulate
Mellor's techniques, I tried to let my body flow over the ice,
resting at every opportunity. At a tiny ice cave, I wedged my body
between the rock and the ice, keeping my arms free to dangle, as my
belayer shouted encouragement from below.
</P>
<P>
   And when the burn finally came, in all its fiery glory, I was
almost at the top, and I knew this weak and chicken-hearted climber
had learned a few things.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   THE STEEP COST ICE CLIMBING
</P>
<P>
   Interested in ice climbing? It's not cheap. Mountaineering boots
run from $300 to $450, a pair of crampons from $100 to $180, and
ice tools from $100 to $300 each (you need two). A helmet also is
mandatory, along with warm and waterproof (that is to say,
expensive) clothing. You can rent boots and crampons, but rentable
ice tools are hard to find. You also need a harness, rope and other
rock-climbing gear.
</P>
<P>
   The best way to get started is to hire a guide (much safer than
trying to teach yourself, even if you are familiar with
rock-climbing rope techniques, plus the guides provide gear). Ice
climbing is available in both the Adirondacks and Catskills.
</P>
<P>
   In the Adirondacks, Adirondack Rock and River of Keene employs a
number of top-notch guides, including Don Mellor. He can be reached
at 518-576-2041.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby is Adirondack Alpine Adventures, which has a series of
courses available for ice climbers of different abilities. Call
518-576-9881.
</P>
<P>
   In the Catskills, there's North America Guide Service, which
also guides in the Adirondacks. Call 914-687-2049. And there's
Mountain Skills, which stays more in the Catskills. Its number is
914-687-9643.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
