<DOCNO> NYT20000120.0106 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 16:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1476 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-DESERT-BOOK-AZR &LR;      01-20 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DESERT-BOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GLORIOUS DESERT _ AND THEN SOME: AUTHOR'S PURPLE PROSE STILL
RESONATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 RESENDING  // 
 BOOK REVIEW of:
 ``The Desert:  Further Studies in Natural Appearances'' 
 By John C. Van Dyke (Johns Hopkins, $16.95) 
 &HT;     By RICHARD NILSEN  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   John C. Van Dyke's ``The Desert'' has been a classic since it
was first published in 1901. Beaten, frayed copies of the book's
many editions sell for good money in used bookstores to those
connoisseurs who appreciate Van Dyke's peculiar brand of
lunacy-genius.
</P>
<P>
   For Van Dyke _ an art critic and professor at Rutgers University
at the turn of the century _ was a master of over-the-top, purple
prose: descriptive enthusiasm as literature. He is so extreme, he
is brilliant.
</P>
<P>
   In describing the desert, in minute detail and in raptures of
syntax, he has few peers. He manages to take one tiny bit of
observation and make it seem, at any given micromoment, the whole
of creation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Desert'' belongs in the library of every reader who loves
the dry areas of the Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   This new paperback edition is graced with a critical
introduction by Peter Wild, who makes quite clear that Van Dyke
was, in some ways, a fraud. Rather than the farsighted ecologist he
makes himself out to be, he was an effete Easterner, and probably a
bag man for robber baron Andrew Carnegie _ who is the dedicatee of
the book.
</P>
<P>
   Van Dyke pretended he had spent two years wandering the deserts
of Arizona, California and Mexico. In reality, he visited his
brother in California, traveled across Arizona on train and carried
a bribe from Carnegie to a former union agitator who had fled to
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the truth of Van Dyke's biography, he was a profound
observer of what he saw, and a brilliant writer.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to quote small bits of Van Dyke's special brand of
prose. It flows on like a great river, carrying all before it in
cascades of paean. You cannot swim against its current.
</P>
<P>
   When he talks about the adverse effect of human habitation on
the environment, he says, ``Even the grizzly, secure in the
chaparral of his mountain home, flinches as he crosses the white
man's trail. The boot mark in the dust smells of blood and iron.''
</P>
<P>
   In that simple phrase, ``blood and iron,'' he manages to imply
the entire 2,000-year history of war and technology that has been
the European legacy.
</P>
<P>
   One of my favorite sections of the book is Van Dyke's
description of the color of the air in the desert. He goes on for
pages describing minute distinctions in the cast of color the air
gives the landscape, and he manages to describe the effect so
accurately, that anyone who has spent time in the desert recognizes
the truth of Van Dyke's eyesight.
</P>
<P>
   In the chapter ``Desert Sky and Clouds,'' he describes the
stratus clouds: ``This veil of sheet-cloud might be called a
twilight cloud, giving out as it does its greatest splendor after
the sun has disappeared below the verge. It then takes all colors
and with singular vividness. At times it will overspread the whole
west as a sheet of brilliant magenta, but more frequently it blares
with scarlet, carmine, crimson, flushing up and then fading out,
shifting from one color to another; and finally dying out in a
beautiful ashes of roses. When these clouds and all their
variations have faded into lilac and deep purples, there are still
bright spots of color in the upper sky where the (cirrus clouds)
are receiving the last rays of sun.''
</P>
<P>
   The popular objection to purple prose comes from the inexact and
hyperbolic verbifications of inferior scribes, who use the fancy
words in place of having something to say. But when a baroque
literary sensibility, such as Van Dyke's, meets a genuine subject,
the verbal fireworks are, in fact, more accurate, and more moving,
than any calculated understatement. &QL; 
Reach the reporter at Richard.Nilsen(at)ArizonaRepublic.com or
(602) 444-8823. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-00 1606EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000120.0107 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 16:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1477 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k BC-VALUES-AZR &LR;      01-20 1425
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VALUES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE VIRTUOUS LIFE, WITHOUT THE RULES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
 RESENDING THIS STORY 
 
 By RICHARD NILSEN  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: STORY ALSO MOVING IN THE ``L'' CATEGORY) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I don't like Bill Bennett. I think he is a very unpleasant man.
In fact, every time I see the former education secretary and ``drug
czar'' on ``Face the Nation'' or ``Larry King Live,'' his smug,
unctuous face makes my blood boil.
</P>
<P>
   There are few faces that scream out louder: sanctimonious prig.
</P>
<P>
   He makes his pronouncements about cultural values with an
insulting certainty, speaking as if he had personally been up on
Mount Sinai getting the tablets from Jehovah. His dicta are as
irritating as those of any name dropper. And if the name he drops
is God's, it is all the more obnoxious.
</P>
<P>
   It is his certainty that bugs me more than anything else. It is
a quality that inhabits a certain kind of male: A certainty that
whatever position he takes is the true one, simply by virtue of his
taking it. It is a very male thing, and reminds me once again that
testosterone is a hallucinogen.
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons he makes me so angry is that the cause he has
latched onto is an important one. Our values need to be discussed.
</P>
<P>
   But his version of them is deeply distorted by that inflexible
certainty.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett knows what the virtues are we should maintain: He has
made a list. In his ``Book of Virtues,'' he includes self
discipline, compassion, responsibility , friendship, work, courage,
perseverance, honesty, loyalty and faith.
</P>
<P>
   It seems a measure of Bennett that humility is not among these
virtues.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these seem obvious and inarguable. Others less so. And
in reality, such categorical expectations cannot be convincingly
maintained. There are times when loyalty conflicts with honesty,
times when faith conflicts with compassion. If you are a Sufi
mystic, self discipline may be just the opposite of what you
require. Perseverance is sometimes merely stupidity. Sometimes
diplomacy outranks honesty, for the good of all.
</P>
<P>
   And work, as Bennett outlines it, smells suspiciously of the
Victorian principle espoused by such moralists as Andrew Carnegie
and Henry Ford, who made millions because other people worked long
virtuous hours.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the opposite is truly the virtue. At least Henry Thoreau
made a convincing case in ``Walden.'' ``We are made to exaggerate
the importance of what work we do,'' he wrote. ``But men labor
under a mistake. The better part of the man is soon plowed into the
soil for compost.''
</P>
<P>
   Americans already work like dogs. It is the quality of their
leisure that needs improving.
</P>
<P>
   But it is not the individual virtues on Bennett's list that I
take exception to, but the list itself.
</P>
<P>
   For too often, we think of virtues as being something as simple
as a list: A series of words.
</P>
<P>
   Virtue, for Bennett in his book, ``involves rules and precepts _
the dos and don'ts of life with others.'' In other words, we are
good because we do what we are told.
</P>
<P>
   He reiterates his position in his followup book, ``The Moral
Compass,'' by asserting, ``Moral education must involve following
rules of good behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, virtue is etiquette.
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I find this view trivializing, and worse, I suspect
that it is propounded merely to perpetuate an economic and
governing system that makes it possible for Bennett and people of
his economic and educational advantage to live comfortable lives.
</P>
<P>
   There are other possible lists of virtues.
</P>
<P>
   The Roman Catholic church lists the Theological Virtues of
Faith, Hope and Charity; the Cardinal Virtues of Prudence, Justice,
Temperance, and Fortitude; and the Evangelical Counsels of Poverty,
Chastity and Obedience.
</P>
<P>
   I doubt Bennett considers poverty a virtue.
</P>
<P>
   Or the list in Laurie Anderson's song, ``Forgetting'':
``Bravery, Kindness, Clarity, Honesty, Compassion, Generosity,
Dignity.''
</P>
<P>
   Of these, Clarity is the least often observed.
</P>
<P>
   But whichever list we observe is ultimately forced upon our
lives in the style of Procrustes. We are not meant to think about
them, but to obey them.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, rules are always insufficient. There are always
circumstances that require our disobeying.
</P>
<P>
   William Blake, for instance, wrote in his ``Marriage of Heaven
and Hell'' how Jesus of Nazareth broke each of the 10 Commandments,
ennumerating them, one by one. Jesus was good, Blake says, because
``Jesus was all virtue, and acted from impulse, not from rules.''
</P>
<P>
   For Blake, Jesus's impulses were good impulses. The rules were
dead and deadening.
</P>
<P>
   He sums it up in one of his ``Proverbs of Hell:'' ``One rule for
the lion and ox is oppression.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Bennett and his followers sum up the good in another phrase
from one of Blake's villains, the shortsighted god, Urizen: ``One
command, one joy, one desire,/ One curse, one weight, one measure,/
One King, one God, one Law.''
</P>
<P>
   As if everyone were a uniform cog in one of Ford's
mass-production lines.
</P>
<P>
   One thing that has happened is a change in the meaning of the
word ``virtue.''
</P>
<P>
   It has meant different things at different times. If it now
means righteous behavior, it once meant something less rigid.
</P>
<P>
   For the Greeks, and later the Romans _ who gave us the word _
virtue meant to be yourself in the utmost. That is, if you were a
soldier, to be brave and fight skillfully; if you were a scholar,
to read deeply and widely.
</P>
<P>
   Each person had his own virtue: to be who he was with every
fiber of his being. Presumably, if you were a villain, you were
virtuous to the extent that you did the most evil.
</P>
<P>
   Ulysses was virtuous for his ability to lie; Achilles for his
ability to kill people.
</P>
<P>
   The best modern equivalent of the term might be
``authenticity.'' Being true to yourself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Virtue'' didn't take on its acrid sanctimoniousness until the
Victorian age, when it was used to approve of behavior that
furthered the goals of Colonialism and jingoism.
</P>
<P>
   For the Victorians, virtue meant not having sex. It's a long way
from Achilles to Elsie Dinsmore.
</P>
<P>
   The word ``values,'' that is bandied about so glibly by
politicians now, has also undergone such a change.
</P>
<P>
   It tends to be used by conservative politicians to mean those
narrow and ethnocentric strictures that make life comfortable for
them. ``Values'' means THEIR values. They are something you inject
like a flu shot into your children in hopes it will keep them out
of jail.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, there is little that is as basic to our sense of our own
humanity than our values. The question is vitally important.
</P>
<P>
   But before the term was belittled by politicans, our values were
those things we felt had intrinsic worth. They are called values
because we VALUED them; they were things you could count on, like
solid currency. They were not an abstract yardstick to measure
behavior, but rather the very concrete reality on which we built
our lives.
</P>
<P>
   For something to count as a human value, it has, above all, to
be true. Anything else will prove false in the long run.
</P>
<P>
   Our values are those things we take as the rock-bottom basic
truths that experience gives us, that we can count on and therefore
can act in the world with the expectancy that particular behaviors
will result in particular outcomes.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, our values are not written down on paper
somewhere, but found in the world around us, the world we
experience, the lives we live. And instead of turning out to be as
vaporous as the words of a list, values are as solid as the oak
tree that grows in the yard. Indeed, they may be the oak tree. Or
the birds roosting in it.
</P>
<P>
   Our values include what we believe our families to be, our
awareness of cause-and-effect in the natural world, our sense of
outrage when injustice is aimed at us _ or at someone we share
sympathy with.
</P>
<P>
   If you live in the American South, whether you are White or
Black, the red dirt is one of your values. If you live in New
Jersey, pizza is part of your value system. These are never merely
words, but the truth of the universe you inhabit, as you are given
the ability to see them.
</P>
<P>
   If a so-called value handed down to us is proven false by
experience, we must either forsake the value or live an inauthentic
life. Many of the values Bennett would foist on us no longer ring
true. Perhaps some still do. But we must find them out for
ourselves. It is one of our life's tasks. &QL; 
Reach the reporter at richard.nilsen(at)ArizonaRepublic.com or
(602) 444-8823.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-00 1608EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
