<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 16:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1481 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-ART-N     01-20 1175
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FURNITURE TO THE MANNER FASHIONED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Pa., Md., Conn.)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By WENDY MOONAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Michael Flanigan, an antiques dealer in Baltimore,
recently offered a tip to aficionados of early-19th-century Boston
antiques.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you walked into a booth of Empire furniture at an antiques
show, and you weren't wearing your reading glasses so you couldn't
read the labels, you could pick out the Boston pieces,'' he said.
``All you would have to do is pretend you were at a cocktail party
and were looking for the most conservative but highly refined
person there. He wouldn't be shouting or loud. He'd be well
educated and well bred. That's the Boston piece.''
</P>
<P>
   Flanigan's advice was in response to the show on Boston
neo-Classicism at the Hirschl &AMP; Adler Galleries in New York through
Feb. 5. The show has spawned a new parlor game: trying to determine
how furniture made in Boston between 1800 and 1840 differs from
contemporaneous pieces made in New York, Philadelphia and
Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   American neo-Classical furniture was inspired by models that
emerged in France after the 1750s. The French prototypes were
dignified and restrained, with simple geometric forms, spare
ornamentation and a preference for linear, flat decoration. Under
Napoleon such designs became known as the Empire style. In England
they were termed Regency.
</P>
<P>
   Friday begins Americana week in the city and the Winter Antiques
Show, which runs through Jan. 30 in Manhattan. Auction houses are
including neo-Classical pieces in their Americana sales Friday and
Saturday and a few special gallery exhibitions are going on as
well.
</P>
<P>
   There are only a handful of specialists in early 19th-century
American furniture and they offer some clues about how to
distinguish Boston furniture from the rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can pick out a piece made in Boston from a mile away,'' said
Carswell Rush Berlin, a private New York dealer who specializes in
high-style neo-Classical American antiques. ``Boston furniture is
more conservative than New York, Philadelphia or even Baltimore at
this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Berlin has an upholstered armchair, a pair of pier tables, a
sewing table and a gueridon, or pedestal table, made in Boston in
his stand at the Winter Antiques Show. ``Wood and carving are very
important,'' he continued. ``The quality of the wood is almost
always outstanding.''
</P>
<P>
   John Hays of Christie's added: ``There's a purity and simplicity
to Boston furniture that doesn't exist in New York or Philadelphia.
There is a beauty in that simplicity.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americana sale at Christie's Friday includes a Boston
drop-leaf mahogany dining table with tapering cylindrical supports
that rest on splayed saber legs. Made around 1810, the handsome,
solid table has only one kind of decoration: tight ring turnings on
the supports. It is expected to sell for $20,000 to $30,000.
</P>
<P>
   Albert Sack, dean of Manhattan's Americana dealers, could almost
have been describing that piece: ``Boston neo-Classical furniture
is not flamboyant,'' he said. ``It's understated. The furniture
makers concentrated on superb grains and woods.''
</P>
<P>
   Flanigan put it another way: ``You see tremendous control. There
are no exuberant edges. Carving is tight. In Boston, decoration is
not emphasized. It's always subsidiary to the form.''
</P>
<P>
   Stuart Feld, the president of Hirschl &AMP; Adler, organized its
show, ``Boston in the Age of Neo-Classicism.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In Boston furniture, you don't see a lot of painting and
gilding as you do in Philadelphia and New York,'' he explained.
``Instead, you see mahogany veneers of extraordinary quality, often
displayed in matchbook fashion. Boston furniture is as identifiable
as a pot of Boston baked beans.''
</P>
<P>
   In style Boston furniture is more English than French. ``Boston
cabinetmakers were more into English pattern-book design,'' Feld
said. ``They used classical motifs and had a style of carving that
was more William IV than French.''
</P>
<P>
   This contrasts with New York furniture, which Berlin described
as being more fashion-forward and influenced by the French.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Carey, of F.J. Carey III Antiques in Ambler, Pa., has
several Boston pieces for sale in his warehouse. ``Bostonians were
Anglophiles,'' he said. ``In Pennsylvania we had German and French
cabinetmakers in the early 1800s, so there were more design sources
to pull from. Boston did not have as many immigrants from different
places.''
</P>
<P>
   Carey advised studying secondary woods in furniture. ``In
Boston, it might be chestnut, white pine or tulip poplar,'' he
said. ``In New York, Philadelphia and Baltimore it could be ash.''
All the cities imported mahogany and rosewood, added.
</P>
<P>
   David Dunton, a dealer with Boston furniture from Woodbury,
Conn., pointed out that only Boston furniture makers made
flattened, often ebonized ball feet.
</P>
<P>
   Who buys neo-Classical furniture these days? ``Maybe one out of
1,000 visitors is a potential buyer,'' Berlin said. ``Selling this
period is hard because the market is very thin. The market says
earlier styles like Hepplewhite are more valuable, but I find them
less interesting. On the other hand, my pieces, relatively
speaking, are more affordable.''
</P>
<P>
   The record price for a piece of neo-Classical American furniture
sold at auction is $704,000, paid for a stamped Charles-Honore
Lannuier marble-top pier table at Christie's in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Like other dealers, Berlin goes beyond the famous makers of the
period _ Anthony Quervelle of Philadelphia and Lannuier and Duncan
Phyfe of New York. He is studying John and Hugh Finlay of Baltimore
and Allison, Deming &AMP; Bulkley of New York, among others. ``One of
the exciting things about this period is that we don't know
everything yet,'' he said. ``There are still a lot of dots left to
connect.''
</P>
<P>
   ANIMALS' ESSENCE
</P>
<P>
   There are several fine lots of Chinese export porcelain in
Sotheby's ``Important Americana'' sale Friday and in Christie's
``British Interior'' sale on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   One particularly striking lot at Christie's is a pair of teal
stag head wall trophies. About 21 inches high, the 19th-century
heads have white eyes with black-glazed pupils and white teeth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chinese knew how to get the essence of an animal without
being slavishly realistic,'' said Becky MacGuire, Christie's expert
in Chinese export. ``These must have been made for a grand hunting
lodge or schloss somewhere in the Austro-Hungarian Empire.''
</P>
<P>
   In China, the deer is an auspicious animal, symbolizing wealth
and longevity. ``Only deer can root out the sacred fungus
associated with one of the immortals,'' Ms. MacGuire said. ``This
blending of Eastern reverence for deer and the Western trophy
tradition is rare.''
</P>
<P>
   The estimate for the pair is $6,000 to $9,000. The last set of
great porcelain stag heads, from the collection of Thomas Mellon
Evans, sold at Christie's in June 1998 for $75,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
