<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBUM-OF-THE-WEEK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPOTLIGHT ON NEW ALBUMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By ANN POWERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUE GARNER AND RICK BROWN ``Still'' (Thrill Jockey). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RICK RIZZO AND TARA KEY ``Dark Edson Tiger'' (Thrill Jockey). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The notion of old friends gathering to make music often gives
rise to all-American cliches about hoedowns and bluesy jam
sessions. But these two new relaxed collaborations reach widely
forward instead of backward.
</P>
<P>
   Sue Garner and Rick Brown are accomplices in marriage as well as
in music, and the freedom palpable on ``Still'' comes from
long-held trust. The tracks range from the nervous New York punk of
``Bomb Squad'' to the languor of ``Swimmingly,'' sung by Ms. Garner
in a voice that descends like a cloud of seduction.
</P>
<P>
   Several friends and fellow postpunk veterans help the couple
explore a sometimes abstract but always engaging soundscape dotted
with signs of their previous travels through country and art rock.
</P>
<P>
   One such friend is the guitarist Tara Key of Antietam, who
forges a musical alliance on ``Dark Edson Tiger'' with Rick Rizzo
of Eleventh Dream Day.
</P>
<P>
   The two wield their guitars gingerly on this instrumental album,
exploring nuances of feedback and sustain. Again, old pals
(including Brown and Ms. Key's husband and bandmate, Tim Harris)
flesh out the duo's ideas.
</P>
<P>
   These albums are homey in the best way; their makers are
comfortable enough to let their minds run free.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
