<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN BRIEFS: SLOGAN ENHANCEMENT; DEFECTIONS IN MINNESOTA;
RUNNING CLEAN IN MAINE; DISTRACTED IN SOUTH CAROLINA 
</HEADLINE>
  (js/mk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE DEMOCRATS: RUNAWAY SLOGAN
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore is taking Bill Bradley's campaign slogan
and turning it to his own advantage. ``It Can Happen,'' the Bradley
homage to idealism and outside chances, has morphed into Gore's
more assertive ``It Will Happen.'' The new slogan is emblazoned on
the back of another new prop in the Gore campaign, a big, cushy
bus.
</P>
<P>
   THE MIDWEST: FROM ELEPHANTS TO DONKEYS
</P>
<P>
   Complaining that the party has become too conservative, two
high-profile Republicans in Minnesota have defected to the
Democratic Farmer-Labor-Party. State Auditor Judy Dutcher disclosed
in a letter to Republican Party officials on Monday that she would
be switching to the Democrats, a party she described as ``more
accepting of divergent points of view.'' A week ago, the former
state Senate minority leader, Dean Johnson, switched to the
Democrats after a dispute over gay rights.
</P>
<P>
   NEW ENGLAND: THE $5 CANDIDATE
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Cummings, director of a nonprofit educational group in
Portland, Maine, has become the first candidate to qualify for
public financing under Maine's new ``clean elections'' system.
Under the system, Cummings, who is running for the Maine House of
Representatives, had to gather 50 contributions of $5 each to show
the breadth of his support, and to pledge to accept no other
donations. In return, he is eligible for about $4,400 in state
money to run his campaign, a sum that could triple if an opponent
vastly outspends him, said John Brautigam, a leading Maine advocate
of campaign finance reform. Cummings said some people offered him
more than the allowable $5, and ``it's the first time in my life
when I've turned away money.''
</P>
<P>
   THE SOUTH: FLAG FIXATION
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jim Hodges of South Carolina, a Democrat, used his State of
the State speech Wednesday night to add a sense of urgency to the
Confederate battle flag debate, imploring lawmakers to reach a
compromise that would move the flag off the Capitol dome to a spot
elsewhere on the Statehouse grounds. The flag dispute is diverting
the state's attention from more urgent issues, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
