<SLUG> BC-TREK-JERI-RYAN-IN-STAR-TREK-VOYAGER-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JERI RYAN GOES TO THE MAT IN `TSUNKATSE' 
</HEADLINE>
  (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Inside Trek, a
weekly science-fiction column with color and black-and-white art.)
 (Includes a color slide and a black-and-white photo of Jeri Ryan in
a scene from ``Star Trek: Voyager.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    The time is right for Seven of Nine.
 &HT;    Back when Jeri Ryan joined the cast of ``Star Trek: Voyager''
during its fourth season, the actress most feared that Seven might
become too human too quickly. Now, with each passing episode, Seven
edges closer to regaining the humanity she lost upon Borg
assimilation.
 &HT;    ``I'm three years into the character, and she's absolutely ready
to explore her human side,'' Ryan says. ``You don't want her to
become stagnant as a character.
 &HT;    ``And it's not been a rapid change,'' the actress adds. ``We've
done a few episodes where she's been pretty perplexed and had to go
back to her Borg structure in order not to feel so uncomfortable
with the emotions around her.
 &HT;    ``We've just done an episode called `Collective,' and there you
have Seven put in charge of some Borg children we've brought aboard
the ship,'' Ryan adds. ``She has a real hard time with these kids
being so disorderly and unpredictable.
 &HT;    ``Watching her deal with the emotional aspects of the kids'
personalities, watching her have to go back to Borg structure and
routine just to stay sane, that's fun,'' she says. ``It's fun to
see where Seven is now, compared to where she was when she came on
board.''
 &HT;    But we're getting light years ahead of ourselves here _
`Collective'' won't air until Feb. 16. The reason for this
conversation with Ryan is actually ``Tsunkatse,'' a sweeps episode
that will beam into living rooms on Feb. 9.
 &HT;    The action-packed hour features guest spots by ``Deep Space
Nine'' favorites Jeffrey Combs and J.G. Hertzler. And, in a bit of
unapologetic UPN synergy, ``WWF Smackdown'' wrestling icon The Rock
turns up as well.
 &HT;    ``The crew is on shore leave, and everybody but Seven and Tuvok
(Tim Russ), who have no interest in recreation, is pretty excited
to be on this planet,'' Ryan says, speaking by telephone from her
mother's home in the Los Angeles area. ``Chakotay (Robert Beltran)
and Torres (Roxann Dawson) discover this sport called tsunkatse,
which is sort of a gladiator-type fighting event, with lots of
people coming into an arena to watch.
 &HT;    ``Seven and Tuvok, who went off on an away mission, are captured
and Seven is forced into playing the sport,'' she says. ``You soon
realize that the people who are doing the fighting are not there by
choice.''
 &HT;    Chakotay and several other Voyager crew members discover that
fact for themselves when they see Seven step into the arena. As her
crewmates endeavor to save her, Seven must deal with the
machinations of Penk (Combs), the ruthless tsunkatse promoter who
salivates at the money to be made through a death match featuring
Seven.
 &HT;    ``Fighting is very much against Seven's nature because, for the
last three years, she has tried to stifle her aggressive side,''
Ryan says. ``And now she is forced to be violent and aggressive in
order to survive and save Tuvok.
 &HT;    ``I can't tell you too much more without giving it all away.''
 &HT;    Ryan says she's generally pleased with season six of
``Voyager,'' and she waxes enthusiastic about several Seven-heavy
episodes, including ``One Small Step'' and another upcoming hour
involving the Borg kids.
 &HT;    Even when she's away from the set these days, ``Voyager'' isn't
far from Ryan's side: She and producer/writer Brannon Braga are
romantically involved.
 &HT;    ``It's not a secret,'' Ryan says. ``We are dating, and we're
very happy.''
 &HT;    As the conversation draws to a close, the actress reiterates her
opinion that Seven continues to be a well-developed character.
 &HT;    ``She's done a lot,'' the actress says. ``She's been a mom,
essentially. She has made friends among the crew and, through Naomi
Wildman (Scarlett Pomers), she's learning how to play and lighten
up a little bit.
 &HT;    ``She's really gone through most of the stages of life at this
point,'' Ryan says. ``And that's great.''
 &HT;    One thing she hasn't done yet, however, is to explore her sexual
side.
 &HT;    ``We've had guys with crushes on her _ the Doctor (Robert
Picardo) and Harry Kim (Garrett Wang) both were attracted to her _
but she hasn't had a real romance,'' Ryan admits. `I understand,
from inside sources I might know, that could change at some point
this season.
 &HT;    ``And that will be exciting.'' 
 c.2000 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Star Trek: Voyager,'' consult
the official Website at www.startrek.com. And don't forget to visit
The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on Inside Trek and
Sci-Fi and other features. &QL; 
