<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-AD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH AD IS SHARPEST YET ON MCCAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In his most pointed allusion to a rival to date, Gov. George W.
Bush began running a 30-second spot Wednesday in New Hampshire that
criticizes parts of a tax plan offered by his chief Republican
opponent, Sen. John McCain of Arizona. The commercial was taped on
Tuesday at a news conference in Pittsfield, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCER: Maverick Media
</P>
<P>
   SCRIPT: Bush: ``My opponent trusts the people of Washington to
spend money. I trust the people of New Hampshire to make the right
decisions for their families. If he says something I don't agree
with, I am going to point it out. I darn sure don't agree with
saying you're going to take $40 billion of employer-related
benefits and have people pay taxes on them _ think that is a
mistake. If you abolish employer-related benefits to pay for a tax
cut, it means working people will have to pay those benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   ACCURACY: Although McCain's name is never mentioned, the crux of
the spot is an assertion that his campaign vigorously disputes,
that a McCain proposal for cutting taxes by nearly $240 billion
includes a hidden increased cost to taxpayers of $40 billion. That
additional burden would be imposed, Bush claims, because the
proposal would end some deductions that employers now take on
tax-exempt benefits. In a detailed response, the McCain campaign
said Wednesday that the plan would eliminate or limit only
corporate deductions for expenses like employee parking, meals,
transportation, spa memberships and tickets to sports events. That
would result in less than $3.9 billion in revenues over five years,
it said. The plan, the McCain campaign added, does not impose taxes
on employee child care or health care benefits.
</P>
</TEXT>
