A1489 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-WASTE-ENVIRONMENT21-C     01-20 0425
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WASTE-ENVIRONMENT21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COALITION CITES POLLUTERS' PORK
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ An alliance of private groups Thursday criticized
Congress for failing to halt seven ``environmentally harmful''
projects and subsidies costing hundreds of millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The Green Scissors coalition, which includes environmental and
budget watchdog groups, criticized lawmakers who voted last year
for subsidies for hard rock mining, oil and timber industries,
protections for the sugar industry, and research for fossil fuels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Members of Congress squandered seven opportunities to slash
programs that threaten our environment,'' said Erich Pica, a
spokesman for Friends of the Earth Action, which participated in
the study of the congressional votes.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition found ``little progress'' toward ending subsidies
it opposes. ``Despite some victories in Congress, and an
administration that supports several Green Scissors
recommendations, wasteful government spending that is harmful to
the environment still runs rampant in Washington,'' concluded the
study.
</P>
<P>
   In the study of a handful key votes last year, only 11 senators
and eight House members rated a perfect score in fighting
``polluters' pork,'' according to the Green Scissors' scorecard.
</P>
<P>
   In the selected votes, the House considered programs with a
maximum cost of $831 million on seven separate votes. The study
included four selected votes in the Senate, with a maximum cost of
$732.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the vote study, the coalition issued its annual
list of 77 projects and subsidies that they charge damage land and
waterways and cost a total of $50 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The group added five new items to its hit list, including:
</P>
<P>
   _ Plans to increase federal subsidies to dredge harbors,
including the one at Savannah, Ga., so that they will be able to
accommodate new, larger tankers. The group warned of a costly
``race to the bottodies for crop insurance, which the group says
will encourage more farming in marginal areas.
</P>
<P>
   _ Deepening the Columbia River near Portland, Ore., at a cost of
$200 million.
</P>
<P>
   _ Paving national forest roads at a cost of $405 million.
</P>
<P>
   _ A Navy plan to broadcast low-frequency sound waves into the
ocean to search for submarines. The sound waves could harm whales,
dolphins and other sea life, the group says.
</P>
<P>
   Julia Malone's e-mail address is juliam(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
