A1492 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SWEET-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT     01-20 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWEET-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE NEW SWEET STYLE:' A RUSSIAN DISSIDENT IN PURSUIT OF THE
AMERICAN DREAM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Russia)  (Eds: Publication notes are at end of review.) 
(DW) 
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In ``The Burn,'' the novel that made his name in the West in the
early 1980s, Vassily Aksyonov created a wild, kaleidoscopic picture
of life in the Soviet Union, chronicling the heady years of the
1960s when the country's intelligentsia still cherished hopes of a
political thaw, and the cruel dashing of those hopes with the 1968
invasion of Czechoslovakia. The book's nervous surrealism captured
the strange Kafkaesque mood of those years, even as its jazzy,
improvisational style _ by turns ironic and meditative, slapstick
and somber _ suggested the precarious nature of life under the
watchful eyes of Big Brother.
</P>
<P>
   Aksyonov employs a similar blend of satire, phantasmagoria and
rumination in his latest novel, ``The New Sweet Style,'' a book set
largely in America. Although there is an engaging love story at the
heart of this tale, the book's postmodern pyrotechnics lack
conviction, as do Aksyonov's efforts to create a Tom Wolfe-style
portrait of America in the '80s and '90s.
</P>
<P>
   His supporting cast of characters, meant to provide a panoramic
group portrait, consists of people who feel more like a collection
of cliches than real human beings or original satiric types: a
billionaire who wants to give all his money away; an ambitious
yuppie who succeeds in marrying his boss' daughter, and an
assortment of Hollywood movers and shakers who scheme and maneuver
and preen.
</P>
<P>
   In part, the problem is that Aksyonov does not possess the
intimate knowledge of this country that might fuel this sort of
satire. In part, the problem is that his surreal embroiderings on
reality are divorced from any larger vision of the world he is
trying to depict. Whereas ``The Burn'' used antic invention and
mythic allusions to create a darkly hued portrait of the yearning,
desperation and absurdity of life in the Soviet Union, ``Sweet
Style'' simply gives us a series of cartoonish snapshots of people
trying to pursue the American dream _ a predictable collection of
vignettes showing them trying to juggle a surfeit of freedom and
money and sex.
</P>
<P>
   Like Aksyonov, the picaresque hero of ``Sweet Style'' _ one
Aleksandr Zakharovich Korbach _ is a dissident whose notoriety in
Moscow avant-garde circles has drawn the wrath of Soviet officials.
Like Aksyonov, Alex is forced to leave the country in the early
1980s and winds up beginning a new life in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Alex's adventures here, however, have the brightly colored _ and
often ludicrous _ quality of a comic book. He goes to Los Angeles
and, despite his impressive credentials as a theater director,
songwriter and actor, gets a job as a parking-garage attendant. To
make extra money he begins selling drugs on the side. When he gets
an apartment in Marina del Rey, he thinks, ``an idiot's dream has
come true, you finally live the way that people with their eternal
Soviet head colds imagine life abroad.''
</P>
<P>
   There are runs-in with a beautiful Soviet agent who threatens to
blackmail him, and worries about his ex-wife, who has moved to
Haiti and become a voodoo priestess. Yet as things happen in this
sort of novel, good luck soon turns the tide. Through a chance
encounter Alex meets a fabulously wealthy businessman named Stanley
Korbach who has determined that Alex is one of his long-lost
cousins. It's not long before Alex has become a director in
residence at a Washington university and has won a lucrative
contract to write a movie based on the life of Dante. After the
collapse of Communism in the Soviet Union, he will return to visit
Moscow, and travel to Israel.
</P>
<P>
   While Stanley is taking Alex under his wing, Alex is falling in
love with Stanley's daughter Nora, an archaeologist who has been
chosen to become one of the first women to go into space. Their
tempestuous romance, which will span decades in starts and stops,
provides this novel with its one compelling narrative strand, even
though it is burdened with heavy-handed comparisons to Dante's love
for Beatrice.
</P>
<P>
   For that matter, most of the book's allusions to Dante feel
artificial and contrived. Although both Alex and Dante suffer exile
for their political beliefs, further parallels do not hold up: Alex
does not regard Nora as a source of inspiration for his work; their
love is carnal, not idealized; and Alex, for all his talents, does
not come close to creating a masterwork like ``The Divine Comedy.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Aksyonov's incessant authorial asides about the nature of
storytelling, they do little to enhance Alex's story. Rather, they
read like postmodernist garnishes used to rationalize the novel's
unwieldy digressions and improbable subplots. Aksyonov's more antic
inventions (like having Nora randomly dial a phone booth in a ghost
town and reach her long-lost love, Alex) also fail to become an
integral part of the narrative.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the innovations in ``The Burn'' and other earlier
Aksyonov works, such passages feel less like daring, formalistic
experiments than gratuitous bits of whimsy grafted onto a
less-than-successful picaresque story. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE NEW SWEET STYLE'
</P>
<P>
   By Vassily Aksyonov. Translated by Christopher Morris.
</P>
<P>
   482 pages. Random House. $29.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-00 1628EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000120.0119 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 16:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1493 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV2     01-20 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV23-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SUPREME COURT TAKES UP ISSUES OF ABORTION AND GAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, Jan. 23)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In its historic role as arbiter of constitutional
conflict, the Supreme Court is preparing to plunge into a thicket
of controversy by deciding whether states have the right to ban
late-term abortions and whether gays have a right to serve in the
Boy Scouts.
</P>
<P>
   Both issues _ abortion and gay rights _ are so packed with
dynamite that the justices are bound to be denounced however they
may rule.
</P>
<P>
   If they decree that only federal law and not state law can
prohibit partial birth abortions, they will be damned by highly
vocal foes of abortion. If they rule that the states have the power
to prevent partial birth abortions, they will be attacked by the
equally vocal defenders of a woman's right to choose.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the justices will run into a rhetorical fire storm
when they rule on a New Jersey Supreme Court decision that the Boy
Scouts of America can refuse to permit a homosexual to serve as
scout master.
</P>
<P>
   Those two issues also will figure prominently is this year's
battle for the presidency. The Republican frontrunners, Texas
Governor George W. Bush and Arizona Senator John McCain, oppose
abortion, although not as fervently as some of their conservative
brethren such as Gary Bauer and Steve Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Bush nor McCain is willing to pledge that, if he becomes
his party's nominee, he would select only a foe of abortion, as his
running mate. Both appear to understand that there is little hope
of winning congressional approval for a constitutional amendment
outlawing all abortion.
</P>
<P>
   The two Democrats vying for their party's nomination _ Vice
President Al Gore and former New Jersey Senator Bill Bradley _
support abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   None of the four is a gay rights basher. But Gore and Bradley
have been especially vocal in support of gays in the military.
</P>
<P>
   Because the partial birth procedure is so gruesome, many
individuals who are not against all abortions oppose it. Under the
procedure, a woman's cervix is dilated so that the fetus, which may
be only a few weeks from birth, may emerge and be killed by
removing its brain tissue. The rest of the now-dead fetus is then
removed.
</P>
<P>
   The case that the high court will review involves Nebraska's
appeal of a lower court's declaration that the state law banning
late-term abortions is unconstitutional. Some proponents of
abortion rights fear that if late term abortions were banned, the
court would turn its back on its 1973 landmark Roe v. Wade decision
and ban all abortions.
</P>
<P>
   Under the leadership of Chief Justice William Rehnquist, who has
been a member of the high bench since 1972 and chief justice since
1983, the Supreme Court has been less controversial than it was in
the recent past. Today's court is not adorned with judicial
activists in the mold of William Brennan, Louis Brandeis, Hugo
Black, Benjamin Cordozo, Oliver Wendell Holmes or Chief Justice
Earl Warren.
</P>
<P>
   The justices now serving on the court tend to be more restrained
in their interpretation of the Constitution than some of their
predecessors who found hidden meanings in that document and painted
their decisions in broad, vivid brush strokes.
</P>
<P>
   For example, during Earl Warren's 16-year tenure as chief
justice, the Supreme Court outlawed racial segregation in public
schools, decreed that both houses of state legislatures be
apportioned on the basis of `one man, one vote;'' and declared in
the famous Miranda v. Arizona case that a person's confession
cannot be used against him unless he has been advised of specific
steps to avoid self-incrimination,
</P>
<P>
   It was during the chief justiceship of Warrren's successor,
Warren Burger, however, that the court in Roe v. Wade declared that
a pregnant woman has the right to choose an abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Burger and Rehnquist are two of the four justices named to the
court by Richard Nixon. The other two were Harry Blackmun who wrote
the court's decision in Roe vs. Wade and Lewis Powell.
</P>
<P>
   Of the four, Rehnquist probably comes closer than the others to
meeting Nixon's ideal of a `strict constitutional
constructionist.'' In recent years, conservatives have sought the
appointment of jurists who would seek to adhere to the `original
intent'' of the Founding Fathers.
</P>
<P>
   But the truth of the matter is that once an individual has been
granted lifetime tenure on the Supreme Court, that individual is no
longer bound by the political philosophy of the president who
nominated him or her.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, conservatives have been highly critical of the
Supreme Court. But back in 1937, Franklin D. Roosevelt sought to
enlarge the court so that it no longer would be under the control
of justices who sought to scuttle his New Deal programs, it was the
liberals who denounced the `nine old men'' who sat on the court.
</P>
<P>
   FDR failed to get congressional approval for his court packing
scheme, but by the time his presidency ended in 1945, he had
elevated Harlan Fisk Stone to chief justice and named the remaining
eight members of the court.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Robert E. Thompson can be contacted at 202-298-6920.
</P>
</TEXT>
