<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DANIEL-WEBSTER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PRINCIPLES VS. PRINCIPLED 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CYNTHIA BASS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DANVILLE, Calif. _ The griping about politicians is in full
roar. We all know the litany: Politicians are venal. Politicians
are hypocrites. They never keep promises.
</P>
<P>
   While it's true _ and not surprising _ that politicians often
act like politicians, there's a much deeper problem voters have to
consider when choosing candidates. The problem of principles.
</P>
<P>
   We hear constant complaints that our politicians have no
principles. This is untrue; most politicians _ past and present _
have deeply held principles, and are sincere and steadfast in their
core beliefs throughout their political
</P>
<P>
   lives. So we'd better be certain we understand just what our
candidates really value and really believe in _ because it's likely
they'll act, for better or worse, on those values and beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   A man who epitomizes what can go wrong when a politician acts on
principle is Daniel Webster (1782-1852). He was a heroic statesman,
so committed to principle he put his career on the line to avoid
civil war between the North and South. But he did so at a terrible
moral cost. And war came anyway. Born in New Hampshire and a
graduate of Dartmouth, Webster (like most politicians today) was a
lawyer; unlike most of those today, however, he continued his
private practice while in office.
</P>
<P>
   As a lawyer, he was brilliant, arguing (and winning) many
Supreme Court cases, including his most famous victory, McCulloch
vs. Maryland (1819), in which he proclaimed the supremacy of the
federal government over individual states _ a legal cornerstone of
our current system of national governance. (Although he is often
confused with another New Englander of the time, lexicographer Noah
Webster, the two were not related.)
</P>
<P>
   As a politician _ first a congressman from New Hampshire
(1813-17), then a congressman (1823-27) and senator (1827-41;
1845-50) from Massachusetts _ Daniel Webster was, in most matters
of state, about as principled as the political realities of his era
allowed him to be.
</P>
<P>
   Take, for example, the issue of global trade. As sensitive a
topic then as now, globalization in the 19th century manifested
itself in an ongoing argument over protective tariffs. Early in his
career, Webster heartily opposed tariffs. Later, in a classic
political flip-flop, he supported them. Was it only coincidence
that this reversal made him extremely popular with the
manufacturers who had become his major donors?
</P>
<P>
   Yet there was one principle to which Webster remained loyal
throughout his mature political life. That was his dedication to
the Union. Indeed, one of the events we most remember him for is
his fantastic pro-Union speech of 1830, whose ringing conclusion _
``Liberty and union, now and forever, one and inseparable!'' _ made
him a Northern hero.
</P>
<P>
   The other event for which Webster is still remembered is far
less wonderful: his role in the Compromise of 1850. It was here,
with the expansion of slavery up for grabs in the Senate, that
Webster's full dedication to principles led him to turn his back on
morality.
</P>
<P>
   Fearful that a firm rejection of the extension of slavery would
lead to a civil war, Webster repudiated his Abolitionist supporters
and deliberately offered an obnoxious proposal in order to save the
Union. And ``obnoxious'' is just the word.
</P>
<P>
   Webster not only contended that no new law was needed to halt
the spread of slavery, he also approved the repugnant Fugitive
Slave Act, which required the federal government to return runaway
slaves in the North to their masters in the South. His proposal was
accepted. The Union held.
</P>
<P>
   Webster died two years later, diminished in popularity but
confident that he had done the right thing by preserving the Union
at any cost. He never would know the fragility of his Compromise,
or that it would last only eight more years.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Webster was not just a consummate politician, but also a
man of principle. And it's equally clear that, while adhering to
his principles in the face of political peril, he did the wrong
thing.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson for us as voters in this election year is simple,
although not easy. We must take our candidates very seriously and
consider well the deepest principles they hold. More often than we
credit them for, politicians follow their principles. It's up to us
to elect those people who are not only principled, but whose
principles are right.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Cynthia Bass is a historian and columnist for the San Francisco
Examiner.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
