<HEADLINE>
GILBERT &AMP; SULLIVAN FANS WILL LOVE `TOPSY-TURVY' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It would be hard to immediately think of a more unlikely
director for a splashy biography of Gilbert &AMP; Sullivan than Mike
Leigh, who made his name with a series of bleak kitchen-sink dramas
set in a culture-shocked contemporary England (``Naked,'' ``Secrets
&AMP; Lies'').
</P>
<P>
   But his new film, ``Topsy-Turvy,'' is a colorful tribute to the
most successful musical team of the late Victorian era _ less a
standard biography than a lively celebration of the duo, the spirit
of their music, and their unique contribution to the history of
musical theater.
</P>
<P>
   The film opens in 1884, as the pair have already established
themselves with such hits as ``The Pirates of Penzance,'' ``HMS
Pinafore'' and ``The Sorcerer,'' and are just launching ``Princess
Ida,'' another financial hit but one that strikes some critics as a
rehash of their earlier work, and a signal of the wan of
inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   Composer Sir Arthur Sullivan (Allan Corduner) _ ravaged by
kidney stones, creatively depleted and stinging from the stigma of
working in a ``low'' art form (what one critic calls
``topsy-turvydom'') _ decides to break up their phenomenally
successful collaboration and devote his time to composing operas
and other ``serious'' works of music.
</P>
<P>
   Lyricist William Gilbert (Jim Broadbent), in many ways the
leader of the team, is appalled by Sullivan's defection, and so is
the manager of the Savoy Theater (Ron Cook), where the G&AMP;S musicals
draw a steady queue. But nothing can change Sullivan's mind, and he
especially loathes Gilbert's libretto for a proposed new musical.
</P>
<P>
   Then, while visiting an exhibition of Japanese culture, Gilbert
suddenly gets the idea for ``The Mikado,'' Sullivan comes around,
and the rest of the film is a kind of simulated ``making of''
documentary that follows the cast and creators through the staging
of their greatest comic opera _ from early rehearsals to opening
night.
</P>
<P>
   At 160 minutes, it's a bit long and uneventful for anyone who is
not at least a moderate fan of these distinctive musicals, and
Leigh thinks nothing of recreating a full scene at random from
``Ida,'' ``The Sorcerer'' and ``The Mikado,'' or devoting a full
reel of film to depicting a group of actors fumbling through a
rehearsal.
</P>
<P>
   But it's the movie that G&AMP;S fans _ and there are legions of
them, with near-fanatical G&AMP;S Societies all over the globe _ have
been waiting for: much more authentic, flavorful and
psychologically shrewd than its only predecessor, Sidney Gilliat's
1953 ``The Story of Gilbert and Sullivan.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously a big fan himself, Leigh has approached the subject
with immense respect for accuracy (with many of the scenes
recreated on the very stage of the Savoy Theater), an awe for the
genius of the G&AMP;S collaboration and a surprising _ considering his
rather understated and static earlier films _ visual flair.
</P>
<P>
   He's also gathered a uniformly excellent cast and coaxed a
stand-out performance from Broadbent (``Life is Sweet''). As the
petulant, practical and intensely driven W.S. Gilbert, he's so
quietly captivating that he would seem to have at least an outside
chance this time next month at his first Oscar nomination.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, the film was named best picture of the year by the
New York Film Critics Circle and shared the top picture honors with
``Being John Malkovich'' in the year-end awards from the National
Society of Film Critics. Both groups also named Leigh best
director.
</P>
<P>
   Topsy-Turvy. Directed and written by Mike Leigh. Cast: Jim
Broadbent, Allan Corduner, Timothy Spall, Ron Cook, Wendy
Nottingham, Kevin McKidd. USA Films. 160 minutes. Rated R for some
nudity.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
