<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUND-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HELLHOUNDS ON MY TRAIL': BLUESMAN ROBERT JOHNSON IS RECALLED 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the more colorful legends surrounding Robert Johnson, the
Delta blues pioneer who died in 1938, is that he sold his soul to
the Devil at a crossroads in exchange for his musical mastery. And
if you listen to Johnson's original recordings, which profoundly
influenced the 1960s generation of rockers, most notably Eric
Clapton and the Rolling Stones, it is almost possible to believe in
such a transaction. Johnson's sliding acoustic blues riffs shiver
with fatalistic intimations of fire and brimstone, and his taut,
piercing tenor keens with a grim, fearful exhilaration.
</P>
<P>
   The truth of the legend, along with speculation as to the
whereabouts of that mythical crossroads and the cause of Johnson's
death (was he poisoned by a jealous husband; did he die of
pneumonia or syphilis?) are among the questions addressed in Robert
Mugge's earnest, absorbing documentary ``Hellhounds on My Trail:
The Afterlife of Robert Johnson.'' The movie focuses on a weeklong
tribute to Johnson presented in September 1998 by the Rock and Roll
Hall of Fame and Museum in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Part academic study, part concert film, the movie features some
wonderful performances of Johnson's music. Robert Lockwood Jr., his
stepson, offers a mournful ``Love in Vain,'' and the guitarist and
singer Chris Whitley delivers a sinewy, snarling ``Hellhound on My
Trail,'' a doom-ridden blues dirge filled with terrifying images of
hail and howling wind.
</P>
<P>
   Other notable performances belong to Rory Block; a vocal trio
made up of Tracy Nelson, Marcia Ball and Irma Thomas; and Bob Weir
of the Grateful Dead, working with bassist Rob Wasserman.
</P>
<P>
   Like other documentaries by Mugge, who specializes in austere
celebrations of roots music, the movie is remarkable for its lack
of hyperbole. When various musicians who are interviewed discuss
Johnson's music, instead of heaping on the superlatives, they
analyze his hard-to-imitate slide technique and spiky off-center
beats.
</P>
<P>
   The word afterlife is a key to the film, which is not an attempt
at a biography of Johnson (the soundtrack includes none of his
original recordings) but an investigation of his legacy, with
special attention to the lucrative Robert Johnson industry that has
flowered since a handful of his recordings were reissued on a Delta
blues collection in 1961. The movie assumes the viewer has some
knowledge of blues and rock history. There is no discussion of
blues lineage or of how the music made its way north from the
Mississippi Delta.
</P>
<P>
   Interwoven among the stirring live performances are excerpts
from a symposium on Johnson (featuring a clear-eyed keynote address
by the writer and music scholar Peter Guralnick) and visits to
Helena, Ark., and to the Delta. The movie's journalistic
centerpiece is an extended interview with Willie Coffee, Johnson's
childhood friend, who gently debunks the notion that he might have
made an actual Faustian bargain.
</P>
<P>
   Another central figure in the film is Stephen C. La Vere, the
self-appointed lawyer for the Johnson estate and a blues aficionado
who had a major hand in creating the Robert Johnson industry. After
traveling to the Delta and contacting various Johnson relatives, La
Vere took the guitarist's music out of the public domain and
demanded that the musicians who had recorded it begin paying for
it. Clapton, he notes approvingly, was quick to oblige. The estate
has since built up a reservoir of more than $1 million in
royalties.
</P>
<P>
   The movie, which is unrated, takes one odd tangent in its
investigation of a rare film that surfaced, which some believed
showed Johnson playing the guitar. In proving beyond a doubt that
the film was made in 1942, four years after Johnson died,
``Hellhounds on My Trail'' dispels that rumor. But to those who are
not privy to the machinations of the Robert Johnson industry, it
looks as if the screen time devoted to dispelling a rumor would
have been better spent elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `HELLHOUNDS ON MY TRAIL: The Afterlife of Robert Johnson'
</P>
<P>
   Directed and edited by Robert Mugge; director of photography,
Lawrence McConkey; music direction by Robert Santelli; produced by
Mugge and Jeff Sanders; released by Nonfiction Films and Mug-Shot
Productions.
</P>
<P>
   RUNNING TIME: 95 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   RATING: This film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   INTERVIEWS WITH: Peter Guralnick, Stephen C. La Vere and Willie
Coffee.
</P>
<P>
   MUSICAL PERFORMANCES BY: Bob Weir and Rob Wasserman, Robert
Lockwood Jr., David Honeyboy Edwards, Henry Townsend, Tracy Nelson
with Marcia Ball and Irma Thomas, Peter Green with Nigel Watson,
Joe Louis Walker with Billy Branch, Keb' Mo', Chris Whitley, G.
Love and Special Sauce, Guy Davis, Gov't Mule, Alvin Youngblood
Hart, Roy Rogers, Rory Block, Sonny Landreth and Bill Morrissey. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
