<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-BONE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PLAY IT TO THE BONE' DESERVES A 10-COUNT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The only extraordinary thing about ``Play It To the Bone'' is
that it may be the only boxing movie ever made by Hollywood that is
not an anti-boxing movie. It actually likes the sport, and finds a
Hemingway-esque nobility in the spectacle of two men pounding each
other into hamburger.
</P>
<P>
   But even the most die-hard ring fan is likely to be turned off
by the 100 minutes of bad humor that surrounds the film's one epic
fight scene. Indeed, none of writer-director Ron Shelton's sports
comedies (even the less-successful ones like ``Cobb'') has ever
fallen quite this flat.
</P>
<P>
   A long time labor-of-love for the former Seattle-resident
filmmaker that he spent much of the '90s trying to get off the
ground, the film is about two long-over-the-hill pugilist pals
(Woody Harrelson and Antonio Banderas) who get a last shot at the
big time.
</P>
<P>
   When the two middleweights scheduled to fill the lower card of a
Mike Tyson championship fight in Las Vegas are suddenly indisposed
by overdose and death, respectively, the desperate promoter (Tom
Sizemore) calls on the pair to substitute _ in only six hours time.
</P>
<P>
   The bulk of the movie takes place as they drive from L.A. to
Vegas in the company of their joint ex-girlfriend (Lolita
Davidovich) bickering with and insulting each other and everyone
else they encounter, and reliving their past hard-knocks in
flashbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Once the now-estranged friends finally get in the ring, this
dead movie takes on a ghoulish fascination _ and, finally, a kind
of life _ as Shelton goes all out to out-rage ``Raging Bull'' with
10 full rounds of the most bloody and brutal fight scenes
imaginable.
</P>
<P>
   But almost none of the film's humor works. Banderas has a
winning moment or two, but Harrelson is almost too annoying to
endure, none of the other casting really clicks, and all the
characters seem stupid, unpleasant and about as charming as a
smelly gym sock.
</P>
<P>
   As a director, Shelton always walks a brave, fine line. When he
remains upright _ and has a star as likable and inoffensive and
effortlessly charming as Kevin Costner at his best _ in films like
``Bull Durham'' and ``Tin Cup,'' his daring work can be sublime.
</P>
<P>
   But when he falls, he falls hard. His gags can descend into an
excruciating litany of macho drivel _ anti-gay and sexist
one-liners, and the lowest variety of locker-room butt-slapping. In
this movie, he falls so hard he becomes, for the first time in his
career, genuinely offensive.
</P>
<P>
   Play It to the Bone. Directed and written by Ron Shelton. Cast:
Woody Harrelson, Antonio Banderas, Lolita Davidovich, Tom Sizemore,
Robert Wagner. Touchstone. 120 minutes. Rated R for language,
nudity and violence.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-00 1648EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
