<DOCNO> NYT20000120.0127 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1506 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BOSTON-DECORATIVE-ART     01-20 1238
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSTON-DECORATIVE-ARTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON ART REVIEW: POISED AND ELEGANT, LIKE THE BRAHMINS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Exhibition notes are at end of review.) 
 (bl)  
 By GRACE GLUECK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ No one could accuse Boston of being a hotbed of the
avant-garde. From early on, its prominent citizens, many of them
arrivistes themselves, evinced a snooty disdain for the new in
their houses and furnishings, opting instead for conservative
environments that were dignified, elegant and ``tastey,'' as a
prominent Boston textile merchant, Nathan Appleton, put it.
</P>
<P>
   The solid but unchallenging objects they chose are on view in
``Boston in the Age of Neo-Classicism: 1810-1840'' at the Hirschl &AMP;
Adler Galleries. A small but choice survey of the fine and
decorative arts in that city at that time, it reveals how the
leading lights _ architects, furniture designers and upscale
citizens _ shunned the flamboyance of New York and Philadelphia for
objects that were ``restrained and tasteful, consisting of a
limited but aesthetically pleasing vocabulary of form and
ornament,'' writes Page Talbott, a historian of Boston furniture,
in the show's catalog.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition, organized by Stuart P. Feld, president of
Hirschl &AMP; Adler and a specialist in the field of American
neo-Classical decorative arts, is dedicated to the American Wing at
the Metropolitan Museum in honor of its 75th anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   Said to be the first show ever devoted exclusively to this
period of Boston's artistic heritage, it includes furniture,
silver, lighting, glass, porcelain and metalwork, along with
paintings, drawings, sculpture and prints. But the emphasis is on
furniture: handsome, beautifully finished pieces in neo-Classical
style that, taken all together, seem to resemble the attractive
members of a rather staid family.
</P>
<P>
   In fact the furniture, Ms. Talbott points out, was as
homogeneous as Bostonians themselves, whose ancestry was
overwhelmingly British. Like a family, the furniture shares the
same characteristics, modeled on English and French precedents.
Pier tables, for instance, are likely to have flattened ball feet,
round veneered columns with ormolu capitals and bases, and applied
ormolu mounts in the French style. English pattern books provided
archetypes for the carving on neo-Classical chairs.
</P>
<P>
   The lyre, a Greek symbol of music and poetry, was almost a
genetic motif, used in wall clocks, table supports, chair backs and
gilt ornamentation. A particularly soigne mahogany work table
(circa 1812-14) with rounded end drawers and an oval top _
attributed to the cabinetmaker Thomas Seymour _ has as its base a
pair of carved wood lyres framed by slim columns and actually
strung with metal. A fussy pair of upholstered mahogany side chairs
each has as a back a stylized, intricately carved lyre.
</P>
<P>
   In short, a visitor to Beacon Hill, home of Brahmins and
would-be's, would certainly not meet with rude surprises in decor.
At its best, such a setting might include items in the show like
the huge, haughty mahogany closed-door bookcase (1820-25),
influenced by English Regency furniture, whose dazzling effect lies
in the extraordinary display of matching veneers on its facade.
</P>
<P>
   It also could have encompassed the stunning mahogany gueridon,
or small-top table (about 1835), whose white marble slab is
supported by three graceful, arching legs set on a base. And the
gaming table (about 1815-20) with the checkerboard top of inlaid
marble and pull-out candle-stands supported by a mahogany trestle.
And the poised neo-Classical sofa (about 1820), whose delicately
carved mahogany frame _ upholstered in red silk brocade _ sits
confidently on winged-paw feet and turns at each arm in a charming
curve.
</P>
<P>
   Illumination for the upper-caste Boston home was chosen as
carefully as the furniture. Among the showier items in the
exhibition is a stately four-light Argand chandelier _ a lamp
fueled by a tank (usually of whale oil) and named for Aime Argand,
the Swiss chemist who invented it _ made in England by Thomas
Messenger &AMP; Sons about 1830. A bronze ring, suspended from the
ceiling by bronze rods, supports an urn-shaped lamp mechanism and
four glass lanterns from which cut-glass tinklers dangle.
</P>
<P>
   A more common source of light was the sinumbra table lamp,
so-called because it worked without casting a shadow, by means of a
flattened oval globe that topped a candlesticklike stem. An
arresting example here is one with a stem of black amethyst pressed
glass and a frosted-glass shade with delicate wheel-cut motifs,
possibly made by the New England Glass Co. of Boston about 1830.
Then there was the rarer ``student'' lamp, a burner with a shade
and glass chimney that juts out from a straight rod holding its
flattened fuel tank. A gilt brass pair was made between 1832 and
1835 by Henry N. Hooper of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Outstanding silver includes an ugly but dignified tea and coffee
service (about 1813) made for the Appleton family by Boston
silversmiths who emigrated to Philadelphia, Thomas Fletcher and
Sidney Gardiner. The four pieces are engraved with the Appleton's
crest of an elephant's head spouting a snake that wraps around its
trunk. The tea and the coffee pot have eagle heads for spouts, and
cast heads serve as handles for the covered sugar bowl.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast is a graceful silver presentation urn (1816) in late
Federal style, made by the partnership of Jesse Churchill and
Daniel Treadwell and inscribed to a prominent Mason, Thaddeus
Harris (1768-1842). It is distinguished by a scalloped lid,
eagle's-head handles and dainty paw feet.
</P>
<P>
   Metalwork _ including an early patented alarm clock (1819-24) by
Simon Willard, mounted on a mahogany pedestal in the shape of a
lighthouse _ as well as mirrors, glass and porcelain objects add to
the show's luster.
</P>
<P>
   As for the group of paintings chosen to accent the furniture,
it's a mixed bag. A fine Gilbert Stuart portrait shows off the
charms of Mrs. Harrison Gray Otis (1809), a fashionable and
vivacious Bostonian whose gown sports a risque plunging neckline.
An intriguing group of miniatures includes a trio of relief
portraits (1810) of the Nahum Piper family, a rare endeavor in
colored wax on painted glass by Johann Christian Rauschner.
</P>
<P>
   But the most interesting portrait is that of one Elizabeth Trull
(1831) by Henry Cheever Pratt. Done in the elevated, high-flown
style known as Grand Manner, it depicts the subject in a perky red
bolero bodice with flared sleeves, standing next to a Chickering
piano with her hand on a sheet of music, evidence of her culture
and refinement. In her left hand she holds a peacock feather fan.
An operatic curtain behind her is open to reveal a glimpse of a
classical vista.
</P>
<P>
   Several landscapes (prints and paintings) show Boston as it
looked in that era. Thomas Cole's sweeping ``View of Boston''
(around 1837) gives a hint of the city at a distance across a
pastoral landscape. ``View of the City of Boston From Dorchester
Heights'' (1841) by Robert Havell Jr. brings it up closer, a
village with slews of church spires dominated by the state capitol.
Other paintings by Bass Otis, Robert Salmon, George Loring Brown
and Washington Allston keep pleasant company with the furniture.
</P>
<P>
   EXHIBITION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   ``Boston in the Age of Neo-Classicism: 1818-1840''
</P>
<P>
   At Hirschl &AMP; Adler Galleries, 21 E. 70th St., (212) 535-8810,
through Feb. 5.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-00 1649EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
