<HEADER>
A1507 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-WIREY-FILM-REVIEW-NYT     01-20 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIREY-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WIREY SPINDELL': PROBLEMS, PROBLEMS; AND HE'S A CREEP, TOO 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
(af) 
 By A.O. SCOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Poor Wirey Spindell. He's engaged to a beautiful woman named
Tabatha (Callie Thorne), whom he professes to adore and with whom
he shares a spacious, tastefully underfurnished apartment somewhere
in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   But Wirey (Eric Schaeffer, who also wrote and directed) is
tormented by the fact that, as he puts it, he can't make love to
the woman he loves. For her part, Tabatha is leery of marrying a
man unable to fulfill his conjugal duties. Can they work it out in
time for the wedding?
</P>
<P>
   If this question doesn't pique your curiosity or arouse your
sympathy, too bad, because for a very long hour and 41 minutes
Spindell would like to tell you the story of his life. ``My problem
is that I'm a man,'' he explains, by way of preface. This is a
slander against half the human race. His problem is that he's Wirey
Spindell. It's also Tabatha's problem. And if you see this movie,
it will be yours.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is not simply that Wirey is a self-absorbed creep
whose emotions run the gamut from self-pity to passive aggression.
There have been plenty of good movies about self-absorbed creeps _
one or two of them directed by people other than Woody Allen. The
real problem is that the movie, rather than reflecting upon Wirey's
narcissism, simply reflects it. Being endlessly interested in
yourself is not the same as being endlessly interesting. ``Wirey
Spindell'' is as deep as the average male bellybutton, and its
contents are about as appealing.
</P>
<P>
   Schaeffer's first feature, ``My Life's in Turnaround'' (1994),
upheld one of the core principles of American independent cinema in
the early and mid-1990s: that any young, heterosexual white man
with woman trouble, a career crisis and a credit card could make a
movie _ more often than not a movie about his woman trouble and his
career crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Like other films in this vein _ ``The Brothers McMullen,'' say,
or ``Kicking and Screaming'' _ ``My Life's in Turnaround'' got a
lot of mileage from its scruffy, seat-of-the-pants charm. And
Schaeffer's pluck and resourcefulness as a director, as well as his
manic, vulnerable onscreen presence, camouflaged the fact that the
movie was, at bottom, a fairly conventional (that is, a wildly
implausible) romantic comedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wirey Spindell,'' which follows Schaeffer's more ambitious,
less critically indulged subsequent efforts (``If Lucy Fell'' and
``Fall''), clings desperately to its romantic comedy plot in a
doomed effort to give coherence, and meaning, to its episodic
central narrative.
</P>
<P>
   Young Wirey, born to ``hippie parents'' in 1962, spends the
early part of his childhood living with his mother in a dark Upper
East Side apartment, tasting the pleasures of snack cakes and cold
milk, pilfered red wine, and precocious sex play. In junior high,
he flees to his father's house in Vermont, where he graduates to
hallucinogens and intercourse with his basketball coach's
19-year-old daughter.
</P>
<P>
   His college years consist of more sexual experimentation and
more drug use, culminating in a broken heart and a trip to rehab
(though not in that order), after which Wirey returns to New York,
where he and Tabatha meet, as the saying goes, cute.
</P>
<P>
   At each stage of his life, Wirey is played by a different actor,
who has the privilege of intoning the film's increasingly verbose,
unstintingly pretentious voice-over narration. This device works
well enough with the 6- and 13-year-old Wireys (Zane Adlum and
Devin Matthews-Johnson, respectively), but Wirey from 17 through 25
is played by Eric Mabius, a pouty, pretty actor who looks nothing
like Schaeffer.
</P>
<P>
   Tabatha, who is played by Ms. Thorne throughout, must therefore
fall for a man whose mannerisms and appearance will change
completely, and not for the better, in the course of their
relationship. Maybe that's the real problem.
</P>
<P>
   It may be, of course, that everything that happens in ``Wirey
Spindell'' is based on a real-life event, except the ending, which
is ludicrously unconvincing even by the lax standards of the genre.
</P>
<P>
   But to say that this movie is true to life is only to say that
it's banal, boring and confusing. According to its publicity
material, the film was adapted from a novel Schaeffer wrote some
years ago, which was greeted with ``rejection letters and
return-to-sender postmarks.''
</P>
<P>
   This useful information allows me to end on a positive note.
``Wirey Spindell'' is a movie that will restore your faith in
American publishing. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `WIREY SPINDELL'
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Eric Schaeffer; director of photography,
Kramer Morgenthau; edited by Mitch Stanley; music by Amanda Kravat
and Peter Millrose; production designer, Mark Helmuth; produced by
Schaeffer, Dolly Hall, Lloyd Segan and Terence Michael; released by
Winstar Cinema. Running time: 101 minutes. This film is not rated. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With: Eric Schaeffer (Wirey Spindell), Eric Mabius (Wirey at
17), Devin Matthews-Johnson (Wirey in junior high), Zane Adlum
(Wirey at 6), Callie Thorne (Tabatha), Samantha Buck (Samantha),
Jennifer Wiltsie (Wirey's mom, young), Peggy Gormley (Wirey's mom,
mature) and John Doman (Wirey's father). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-00 1651EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
