<DOCNO> NYT20000120.0129 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 16:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1509 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BONE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      01-20 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PLAY IT TO THE BONE': JUICY DIALOGUE IS UNDERMINED BY SHALLOW
PLOT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes at end of review.) 
(lh) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ron Shelton's screwball boxing comedy ``Play It to the Bone'' is
so constrained by its formulaic plot that the movie's juicy,
freewheeling dialogue feels shoehorned into a story that makes more
sense mathematically than psychologically. If the movie (which is
predictable right down to the outcome of its climactic bout) had
been allowed to take one quirky left turn, it might have come
closer to matching the power of Shelton's baseball film, ``Bull
Durham,'' or his golf film, ``Tin Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   But the barrage of macho, sports-smart wisecracks slung by its
charismatic stars, Woody Harrelson and Antonio Banderas, barely
camouflage the weaknesses of a story built on some highly
questionable premises.
</P>
<P>
   This shallowness is unfortunate, since Shelton is one of the few
Hollywood filmmakers at home in the world of professional sports.
Each of his sports films (``Play It to the Bone'' is the fifth)
offers an insider's view of a world that shrouds itself in a
self-protective macho mystique. ``Play It to the Bone'' makes no
apologies for the low-down sleaziness of professional boxing, Las
Vegas-style. In its behind-the-scenes portrait of a world of
corrupt promoters, shady lawyers, lecherous hotel owners and
strutting high rollers, athletes are viewed as little more than
dumb trained animals to be patronized and outsmarted by the sharks
who profit from their sweat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Play It to the Bone'' begins promisingly as it observes the
hysterical, inept negotiations of two slightly over-the-hill
fighters and best friends, Cesar Dominguez (Banderas) and Vince
Boudreau (Harrelson), living in Los Angeles, who are called upon to
fight each other as last-minute opening-act replacements at a
heavyweight title bout in Las Vegas. Although the money is good
($50,000 a man), what really motivates Cesar and Vince to accept
the offer is the chance to redeem their professional reputations
after failures that stalled their once-promising careers. Whoever
wins, they insist, must be contractually guaranteed a shot at the
middleweight title, although we're let in on the fact that their
contracts have built-in loopholes that make that prospect unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of seriously delving into the absurdities of
professional boxing, ``Play It to the Bone'' quickly turns into a
brittle three-way buddies-on-the-road movie, which follows Cesar
and Vince from Los Angeles to Las Vegas in a car driven by their
biggest fan, best friend and mutual ex-lover, Grace Pasic (Lolita
Davidovich).
</P>
<P>
   Early in the film, when Grace breaks up with Cesar, her
boyfriend of six months, he jumps out of the car and dashes out
into a desert to vent his grief, returning minutes later
miraculously purged. At various points in the journey, Grace,
goading the fighters to do their best, warns each one that the
other is likely to win. She also privately reassures each one that
he was the superior lover. The notion that these three could
actually be pals given their romantic histories (Vince still cares,
in his way), flies in the face of human nature.
</P>
<P>
   Of the three, Banderas' Cesar is the least defined. Born in
Madrid, Spain, he moved to the United States to become a
prizefighter and settled in Philadelphia, where his career ascended
until a disastrous match that its promoter (the same promoter
booking the Vegas bout) accused him of throwing. In Vince, a former
middleweight contender whose title bout ended in a draw, Harrelson
has another one of his lusty wild-man roles. Played by the actor as
an electrical spasm of macho impulsiveness, Vince has survived
years of drug and alcohol abuse and numerous car accidents. Since
the last nearly fatal car crash, in which he found Jesus (who
appears to him more than once in the film), he has calmed down a
bit.
</P>
<P>
   The movie brings up homophobia in professional sports by having
Cesar admit early in the journey that after his humiliating defeat
he experimented with gay sex. Pouncing on this information, Vince
declares more than once his shock that his best friend has turned
out to be a ``fag.'' But having brought up the issue, the movie has
no idea what to do with it.
</P>
<P>
   The feisty, independent Grace, who throws two serious punches at
different characters in the film, is a refreshingly self-assured if
not very believable screwball heroine. An inventor of items like a
periscope for watching television while lying flat in bed, she
dreams of finding a high-rolling Las Vegas investor for her dubious
schemes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Play It to the Bone'' is so busy being cute and smart-alecky
that when Cesar and Vince finally enter the ring for a bout that
turns out to be long and exceptionally brutal, what should have
been an emotionally loaded battle has little resonance, despite the
insertion of flashbacks and hallucinations that portray the match
as a turning point in the fighters' lives. Are they fools or
heroes? Because the movie can't decide, neither can we. And without
an emotional payoff, ``Play It to the Bone'' ends up stranded in
serio-comic limbo.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `PLAY IT TO THE BONE'
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Ron Shelton; director of photography,
Mark Vargo; edited by Paul Seydor; music by Alex Wurman; production
designer, Claire Jenora Bowin; produced by Stephen Chin; released
by Touchstone Pictures.
</P>
<P>
   With: Antonio Banderas (Cesar Dominguez), Woody Harrelson (Vince
Boudreau), Lolita Davidovich (Grace Pasic), Tom Sizemore (Joe
Domino), Lucy Liu (Lia) and Robert Wagner (Hank Goody).
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 124 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Play It to the Bone'' is rated R (under 17 requires
accompanying parent or adult guardian). Its boxing sequences are
brutal, and it includes strong language, nudity and sexual
situations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-00 1653EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
