<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Trip to Sunshine State starts with surfing the Web
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Jan. 23.
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you are contemplating a trip to the Sunshine State, www
</P>
<P>
   .flausa.com will get you going in the right direction.
</P>
<P>
   We're talking one-stop vacation shopping at this extensive and
well-organized site maintained by Visit Florida, the state's
official tourism promotion agency. From the home page, you can take
a colorful tour of the state region by region, check out a series
of driving tours, and link to sites such as Sarasota, Florida's
cultural coast, and St. Augustine, Ponte Vedra and the beaches. And
there's a detailed section on Florida's multicultural heritage,
which provides historical and cultural information on diverse
groups such as Cuban Americans, African-Americans and Native
Americans as well as biographies of notable figures.
</P>
<P>
   Click on ``travel planning'' for activities, events,
accommodations, weather and Florida for kids. Check out ``fun
stuff'' for information on such goodies as a free vacation planner,
virtual postcards and screensaver.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you aren't Net savvy, you can request a 260-page FLAUSA
Visit Florida planner, which includes a state map, by calling
1-888-735-2872. You can also request brochures from the Worth the
Drive Day Trips series, which includes specialized itineraries for
African-American heritage, Native American heritage, Cuban
heritage, art museums, outdoor adventure, birding and lighthouses.
</P>
<P>
   These sites are also recommended:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Absolutely Florida: Go to www.funandsun.com to connect with
this lively site that bills itself as ``Florida's largest portal.''
The site promises to put Florida at your fingertips, and it does a
good job. You'll find an event calendar plus Major League
Baseball's spring training schedule. Also included are online
accommodations and airfare booking, information on transportation,
nature and recreation, dining, entertainment and the arts.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  See Visitors Magazines: Check out www.see-florida.com. The
publisher of a series of handy visitor guides hosts this
comprehensive site that provides a region-by-region tour of the
state, plus lodging, attractions, recreation, camping and state
parks. We like the easy-to-use pull-down menu listing dozens of
popular cities that can be accessed with a quick click of the go
button.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Disney World: You'll go directly to the Disney World site,
when you visit www.disneyworld.com. Currently the site focuses on
the Millennium Celebration continuing through the end of the year.
You can tour the complex, find out what's new for 2000, book a trip
and plan a day-by-day itinerary. Or call 407-934-7639.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Universal Studios Escape: Visit www.uescape.com or
www.universalstudios.com to catch up with all the latest on this
movie studio-themed attraction, including the Islands of Adventure,
CityWalk and the new Portofino Bay Hotel resort. Or call
1-800-447-0679.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Sea World: Read all about Kraken, ``the fastest, highest,
longest and wildest roller coaster in Orlando,'' at
www.seaworld.com. The coaster is scheduled to open this spring. Or
call 1-800-423-8368.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
