<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 17:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1524 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-SKUBE-ON-BOOKS23-COX     01-20 1096
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKUBE-ON-BOOKS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Scouting out Oglala Sioux's ennobling past, long gone
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Jan. 23.
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The idea of the Noble Savage is as old as the Greeks, a
recurrent longing for a time when man lived in harmony with nature
and misery evaporated like the morning mist over a meadow. In our
own time, the Romantics sought in an imagined past refuge from
social instability and economic uncertainty. Rousseau, patron saint
of Romanticism, believed we are born pure as snowflakes but
corrupted by civilization.
</P>
<P>
   Dissatisfied with the present, we envy the freedom of the Noble
Savage in his loincloth. The term was coined in the 17th century by
John Dryden, who imagined ``guiltless men, that danced away their
time/Fresh as their groves and happy as their climes.''
</P>
<P>
   Ian Frazier, in his new book ``On the Rez,'' follows in a long,
often illustrious line of writers whose sympathy for the Indian
becomes a kind of personal search. Frazier wants to be an Indian;
he wants, in particular, to be a member of the Oglala Sioux, one of
the Great Plains tribes that joined almost on impulse one day in
the summer of 1876 to defeat Custer in the Battle of Little Big
Horn.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm driving across a field near the town of Oglala on the
Pine Ridge Reservation and I see my friend Floyd John walking
across it the other way,'' Frazier writes, ``I stop, and he comes
over to the car and leans in the window and smiles a big-tooth grin
and says, `How ya' doin', wannabe?'''
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't want to pray in a sweat lodge or dance in a sun dance
or go off into the desert in search of a vision. ``The power of
these ceremonies has an appeal,'' Frazier says, ``but I'm content
with what little religion I already have.'' What he wants is even
more spiritual: ``That self-possessed sense of freedom is closer to
what I want; I want to be an uncaught Indian like them.''
</P>
<P>
   Frazier is utterly guileless. Nothing in the pre-Columbian past
could dissuade him, neither tribal warfare nor the winters that a
not-so-benevolent nature brings to the plains. A golden age was
once here, and Indians are the proud custodians of its memory,
pitiable figures now on isolated reservations like Pine Ridge.
</P>
<P>
   One can _ and probably should _ argue with the details, but the
spirit of his book stands on its own. The Indian is the native
American and unassimilated American, the conditions of his life
testimony to the wrongs done him.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years ago, Frazier befriended an Oglala Sioux named Le
War Lance, whose peregrinations had taken him from Hollywood to
Manhattan, with many a drink along the way, and back to the
reservation in South Dakota _ the rez. He introduced this bizarre
character in his 1989 book ``Great Plains.'' Now, moving with his
wife and children from Brooklyn to Montana, he hooks up with his
old friend again, and in ensuing months witnesses the tragedy as
well as the durability of life on the reservation. He tells us
poignantly of the pride the Oglala take in their girls' high school
basketball teams and of the solace they take from the white man's
alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   Both, sooner or later, end in sorrow. Frazier's story of SuAnne
Big Crow, star of the Pine Ridge High Lady Thorpes, is an affecting
paean to a young woman who was a hero among a people who had not
known a hero since Crazy Horse. She was not only a basketball star,
but, from all evidence, an unusually mature young woman whose
vision for her people extended beyond the court to the larger,
non-Indian world. An NBC Nightly News crew dropped by the week the
Pine Ridge team was going to the state tournament. None of that
caught the network's interest. Instead it filmed the familiar
story: the idleness, the bleakness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Undeniably,'' Frazier concedes, ``many sad facts of the
reservation can be told with bleakness as the text. But the NBC
story irritated people on Pine Ridge no end, especially SuAnne. She
talked to anyone who would listen about all the good on the
reservation that NBC had overlooked, and about the unfairness of
showing only the suffering and apparently hopeless side.''
</P>
<P>
   Even more than playing basketball, she wanted to change
outsiders' perceptions of Indians and instill in Indians the
courage they had lost.
</P>
<P>
   And then, in February 1992, at age 19, SuAnne Big Crow was
killed in an auto wreck, an everyday occurrence in the Black Hills
but a calamity that reverberated long afterward among those who saw
in her example hope and a way out.
</P>
<P>
   For most, there is no way out, and will not be. They live on the
memory of past glory. A picture of the Battle of Little Big Horn
adorns every Indian bar, Sitting Bull and Crazy Horse in triumph, a
dying Custer amid the swarm of Sioux and Cheyenne warriors and the
panic of U.S. cavalry horses with empty saddles.
</P>
<P>
   It is a melancholy image. Frazier resists editorial comment and
provides instead the telling anecdote. ``On the reservation and
elsewhere in Indian country,'' he writes, ``you get used to seeing
images of the Budweiser brand. If you notice a speck on the
roadside up ahead and guess that it is an empty Budweiser case,
very often you will be right.''
</P>
<P>
   This country where the buffalo once roamed and the great Sioux
were free _ this is Bud country:
</P>
<P>
   ``People sometimes say they'd like to buy a whole beer truck
full of Budweiser and drink it dry. On the Standing Rock Sioux
Reservation in northern South Dakota, a man from the town of
Bullhead did. Some years ago the man received an oil settlement of
$30,000 and spent $25,000 of it on a Budweiser delivery truck
stocked with 300 cases of beer. He parked the truck beside his
house, which it was longer than, and had a nonstop party until all
300 cases were gone.''
</P>
<P>
   When the last bottle was upturned, the last drop of hope was
drained away with it. But there would be a long sleep, and
somewhere down the road more would turn up _ not a truck full but
enough for a night. They would be enough to get by, and to dreamily
imagine, perhaps, what it must have been like in the picture on the
wall.
</P>
<P>
   But this, too, is part of the tragedy of the rez. Past, present
and future have no connection with each other. SuAnne Big Crow, who
understood something of all three, is gone just like Crazy Horse,
and all that remains is the illusion of a freedom that never was.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  On the Rez. By Ian Frazier. Knopf. $25.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
