<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 17:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1528 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e BC-TV-FELICITY-SPI &LR;      01-20 0415
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FELICITY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TWILIGHT ZONE' PUTS SPIN ON `FELICITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   An autographed photo of Rod Serling hangs in the office of J.J.
Abrams, co-creator and executive producer of ``Felicity.'' Judging
from Sunday's un-``Felicity''-like episode, he probably has a
glossy of Franz Kafka in his wallet.
</P>
<P>
   Abrams thinks ``The Twilight Zone'' was and is the best thing
television ever introduced to the masses. In Sunday's special
presentation, a Kafka-esque anxiety-and-alienation fantasy titled
``Help for the Lovelorn,'' he pays homage to Serling's legacy with
a mesmerizing black-and-white tribute that accurately captures the
spooky spirit of the ``Zone'' while poking affectionate fun at his
own creation.
</P>
<P>
   Any ``Felicity'' fan knows that Felicity Porter, college
sophomore, is a card-carrying romantic whose heart is so out there
she needs fishing tackle just to get it back on her sleeve. Any
follower of ``The Twilight Zone'' knows the scariest thing in the
anthology series was always a product of the protagonist's own
imagination.
</P>
<P>
   Abrams and his partner, Matt Reeves, combine elements of the two
shows not only create a collectible stand-alone episode, but
something ``Felicity'' followers will love because it advances the
story in a way that probably couldn't be done conventionally.
Specifically, it gives us a peek inside the box that Felicity's
roommate, Meghan Rotundi (Amanda Foreman), guards ever so
jealously.
</P>
<P>
   ``Help for the Lovelorn'' centers on Felicity's desire to get
past her failed relationships with Noel (Scott Foley) and Ben
(Scott Speedman). At the invitation of a mysterious woman, she
visits ``the clinic'' to undergo ``the procedure,'' guaranteed to
mend a broken heart.
</P>
<P>
   But is the cure worse than the ailment? ``Zone'' fans know the
answer _ and that the real fun is in discovering the surprise at
the end. With help from director Lamont Johnson, a veteran of many
``Twilight Zones,'' Abrams and Reeves set the hook beautifully.
Most appealing is Johnson's use of shadowy close-ups that run
counter to the soft, long-lens style of ``Felicity,'' allowing
viewers to see characters in a different light. You might call it a
metamorphosis. No doubt Kafka would.
</P>
<P>
   Help for the Lovelorn. Special episode of ``Felicity'' evoking
memories of ``The Twilight Zone.'' Sunday on The WB. Parental
guideline rating: TV-PG.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
