<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1529 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-YOUNG-COLUMN21-COX     01-20 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Arrogance in Dixie leads to one of biggest protests in decades
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ We had Alabama city buses in the '50s, North
Carolina diner stools in the '60s, yellow school buses in Boston in
the '70s. And, in the 2000s ...
</P>
<P>
   Cots in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   After decades in search for a new symbol, people who know racism
to be a living American presence found one in Columbia, S.C.: cots,
sleeping implements of cloth and sticks.
</P>
<P>
   As part of a state boycott, protesters from out of state slept
on cots in church basements and on living room floors, any place to
avoid pumping a dollar into a state government that continues to
insult black people with an offensive symbol.
</P>
<P>
   An appealing twist. Once upon a time merchants of separatism
wouldn't have allowed any of the black protesters in South Carolina
to have stayed in their inns. The snub is on the other foot.
</P>
<P>
   All of this over the Confederate battle flag flying over the
South Carolina Statehouse.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's protest drew 46,000 people, the largest march in
Columbia's history. It must have been a glorious day. And for a
glorious cause.
</P>
<P>
   A state government that rubs into the face of a large sector of
its population a symbol that offends so many so deeply _
generations deep _ deserves recrimination.
</P>
<P>
   One can accept the fact that to many Southerners, the
Confederate battle flag is no symbol of racism or slavery but of a
proud heritage, and yet one can still not accept the flag being
flown over a state capitol. The flag has only flown there since
1962, and then only as an observance of a Civil War centennial. Of
course, we know what was happening in the '60s, what threats were
then perceived to the Jim Crow way of life. Had a new battle been
joined? And is it still waged?
</P>
<P>
   If so, observers should worry about whose side some of our
presidential candidates are on.
</P>
<P>
   Republican John McCain, for whom South Carolina's primary is
considered one of a couple of do-or-die tests, said he considers
the flag personally offensive, but avoided controversy by following
up that it's a ``symbol of heritage'' and of soldiers who ``fought
honorably.''
</P>
<P>
   I don't think either statement is arguable. Neither, though, is
it arguable that to black Americans the flag is a symbol of
oppression. That should be enough to remove it.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush and Steve Forbes have painstakingly avoided the
issue, leaving the Party of Lincoln on the wrong side of history on
this issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American flag heals us, and the Confederate flag divides
us,'' said Vice President Al Gore. Well put.
</P>
<P>
   The best statement came from Bill Bradley, who said the flag
``offends our common humanity, and it is not the future of our
country.''
</P>
<P>
   So true. What does the future hold? Diversity, the American
essence.
</P>
<P>
   The Census Bureau's recent forecast of a population that doubles
in the next 100 years pointed out what's been known all along _
that whites will become outnumbered by combined minority groups
while retaining majority status.
</P>
<P>
   One imagines what the future holds for a major political party
whose politics preclude its standard-bearers from acknowledging and
addressing the hurt of a whole race of people. Throw in such
gambits as ``official language'' and immigrant-bashing ballot
measures, and one wonders when the weight of numbers will make this
type of politics a fatal flaw on the national scene. (Bush, to his
credit, refuses to play the immigrant-bashing game.)
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens in national politics, it is heartening to see
46,000 people protesting an atrocious practice in South Carolina.
Some will say it's a little thing, that flag, that people should
concern themselves with big issues. Diner stools were small things,
too.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: jyoung(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
