<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 17:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1533 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      01-20 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     THE LAW IS NO PATSY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ During my years in law school, my favorite story
was the tale of a defendant who had killed his parents. When he
came to trial, he threw himself on the mercy of the court because
he was an orphan.
</P>
<P>
   That silly story was, I assumed, apocryphal, meant merely to
amuse credulous students.
</P>
<P>
   But nowadays I'm not so sure. Maybe it really happened.
</P>
<P>
   In our litigious society, creative legal defenses are becoming
standard operating procedure, regularly raised to fend off
punishment for all sorts of alleged crimes. Such inventive
exercises don't seem to impress juries very much, but desperate
folks are bound to try desperate measures.
</P>
<P>
   The explosion of fanciful excuses first came to public attention
in 1978, when a San Francisco man who admitted killing Mayor George
Moscone and Supervisor Harvey Milk claimed he was overexcited
because he had been eating too many sugary foods, including Hostess
Twinkies. The so-called Twinkie Defense didn't catch on, except
with stand-up comics; he was found guilty anyway, although on a
reduced charge of voluntary manslaughter.
</P>
<P>
   A teen-aged Florida boy recently pleaded not guilty to
threatening a student present at the shooting rampage at Colorado's
Columbine High School last April. The Florida boy admitted sending
the ominous e-mail message through an on-line chat room but blamed
it on ``an addiction'' to the Internet, saying he was so used to
the make-believe world of virtual reality he didn't understand the
impact of what he was doing.
</P>
<P>
   This is reminiscent of a similar defense offered 20 years ago by
a teen-ager charged with murdering an elderly woman. He claimed to
be driven by ``television intoxication'' and couldn't tell the
difference between violence on the screen and the real thing. But
the jury didn't buy it and he was convicted anyway. Not
surprisingly, the ``intoxicated'' kid had the same lawyer the
``addicted'' kid does.
</P>
<P>
   Another howler is the case of an Arizona man who killed his wife
by stabbing her 44 times with a hunting knife and dragging her to
their swimming pool to hold her head under water to be sure she
wasn't breathing. A neighbor watched over a wall as he pulled on
gloves and motioned to his dog to lie down before he hauled the
body to the pool. Then he put on a fresh set of clothing and hid
the bloody ones he wore during the murder.
</P>
<P>
   His defense? He claimed to be sleep-walking and couldn't
remember a thing. The jury called that baloney and the judge gave
him life in prison without parole.
</P>
<P>
   Another unusual case is that of a 19-year-old Virginia woman who
placed her infant son in a microwave oven, programmed it to start
and cooked him to death. She contends she was in the middle of an
epileptic seizure and didn't realize her son was not a pot roast.
Her trial on a charge of murder is pending.
</P>
<P>
   In a much different context, a judge in Fairfax, Va., cut in
half a $350,000 jury award to Karen Santorum, the wife of Sen. Rick
Santorum, in a malpractice suit against a chiropractor whose
treatment she claimed worsened her lower back pain. In this case,
she was the plaintiff, not the defendant, and it was her chief
witness that provided the creativity.
</P>
<P>
   You might call it the Political Spouse Indispensability
Argument.
</P>
<P>
   The senator, a Republican from Pennsylvania, testified that a
big financial award was justified since the injury hurt his
prospects for re-election this year, forcing him to campaign alone
because his wife was in too much pain to help. The senator's whine
was a compliment to his wife's political usefulness but raised
doubts about his own independence. Senators are supposed to be able
to legislate, campaign and think for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The jury sympathized, but the judge was not similarly smitten
with Santorum's re-election problems. Perhaps the judge had heard
the senator is leading a congressional effort to limit the size of
malpractice awards for everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   And so it goes. The law, as Charles Dickens' Mr. Bumble said in
``Oliver Twist,'' ``is a ass _ a idiot.'' But it's not as big a
patsy as some folks think.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means' e-mail address is means(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
