<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON THE ART WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Calif., Great Britain)   (af)  
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Philadelphia Museum of Art has just received the largest
cash gift in its 115-year history. Raymond Perelman, a trustee
since 1975 and chairman of the museum's board, and his wife, Ruth,
have donated $15 million to the museum.
</P>
<P>
   The money will go toward the acquisition and renovation of the
Reliance Standard Life Insurance Co. building, a 1926 Art Deco
structure on a two-acre site across the street from the museum,
which it bought for $17 million in October.
</P>
<P>
   The Perelmans are the parents of Ronald O. Perelman, the
chairman of Revlon and a former president of the board of the
Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum.
</P>
<P>
   Gail Harrity, the Philadelphia museum's chief operating officer,
called the gift unprecedented. ``We have enjoyed large gifts of art
over the years,'' she said. ``But not cash.''
</P>
<P>
   With the addition of the new building, which will add 100,000
square feet of space, the museum's ``potential is mind-boggling,''
Raymond Perelman said. The city is contributing $2 million of the
building's purchase price. The museum is still doing feasibility
studies to determine the cost of renovations and the direction the
design will take.
</P>
<P>
   ``Philadelphia is no longer an industrial city but a cultural
city, and the museum is its crown jewel,'' Perelman, 82, an
entrepreneur and lifelong Philadelphian said. He and his wife
collect modern art and own works by Picasso, Dubuffet and Miro.
</P>
<P>
   ``Collecting is a relative term,'' Perelman said. ``I guess if
you put all our family's art together, then it would be a
collection. We don't buy as much as we used to.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, he is channeling his energies into the museum. ``With
the expansion of the museum and the new performing arts center that
is being built here,'' he said, ``Philadelphia is getting on the
map culturally.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   London Inspiration
</P>
<P>
   The National Gallery in London has asked 24 contemporary artists
from Britain, Europe and North America to choose works from its
permanent collection as inspiration for works of their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``Encounters: New Art from Old,'' to run from June 14 to Sept.
17, is the first show of its kind at the National Gallery.
</P>
<P>
   It will also be the largest, occupying all the temporary
exhibitions space in the Sainsbury Wing in addition to several
other adjoining galleries. The show is being organized by Richard
Morphet, a recently retired curator of modern art at the Tate
Gallery.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we move into a new century, we really wanted to make it
clear that the National Gallery's collection is a source of live
interest now and in the future,'' Morphet said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the artists participating are painters, sculptors,
photographers and video artists, including many of today's
best-known names: Balthus, Louise Bourgeois, Anthony Caro,
Francesco Clemente, Karen Finley, Lucian Freud, Jasper Johns,
Anselm Kiefer, Claes Oldenburg and Coosje van Bruggen, Cy Twombly
and Bill Viola.
</P>
<P>
   ``Balthus is the oldest; he was born in 1908,'' Morphet said.
``Clemente is the youngest; he was born in 1952. So the show will
represent three generations of artists.''
</P>
<P>
   The works chosen are often unexpected: Johns, for instance, has
selected Manet's ``Execution of Maximillian'' (circa 1867-68).
</P>
<P>
   Balthus is getting ideas from Poussin's ``Sleeping Nymph
Surprised by Satyrs'' (1626-27), and Oldenburg and Ms. Bruggen have
selected Vermeer's ``Young Woman Standing at a Virginal'' (circa
1670). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles Competes
</P>
<P>
   Trustees at the Museum of Contemporary Art in Los Angeles have
acquired 120 works in the last year in an attempt to strengthen the
museum's permanent collection.
</P>
<P>
   The effort is in large part a competitive one. The Los Angeles
museum is trying to keep up with the San Francisco Museum of Modern
Art, which in the last two years has acquired art worth more than
$125 million. (Officials at the Los Angeles museum won't say how
much the total of their acquisitions are worth.)
</P>
<P>
   ``We know there's been a lot of activity in San Francisco
recently, and our trustees have taken note of it,'' said Paul
Schimmel, chief curator in Los Angeles. ``The acquisitions fall
into two separate groups. One is part of our ongoing acquisitions,
and the other is 17 works given in honor of our new director,
Jeremy Strick.''
</P>
<P>
   Strick began his job in July, replacing Richard Koshalek, who
became president of the Arts Center of Design in Pasadena, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Among the works given to the Los Angeles museum in honor of
Strick's arrival are ``Steel-Zinc Dipole'' (1989) by Carl Andre; an
untitled 1983 drawing by Jasper Johns; a 1964 work on paper,
``Brass Tube (Galvanized Iron Tubes, Painted H-D Blue),'' by Donald
Judd, and ``Sea Painting II,'' by Brice Marden, from 1973-74.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Marden is a classic early work,'' Schimmel said. ``The
Andre is a floor piece, and we only have small pieces by him. And
the Judd is an important work on paper.''
</P>
<P>
   The museum is also buying works recently featured in exhibitions
at the museum, including an untitled installation work by Robert
Gober that was commissioned for the museum in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Works by some controversial younger artists have also entered
the collection, among them a painting by Chris Ofili, the British
artist whose ``Holy Virgin Mary'' in the ``Sensation'' show at the
Brooklyn Museum of Art prompted Mayor Rudolph Giuliani to try to
cut city support to the museum. A painting the Los Angeles museum
has just bought, ``Monkey Magic: Sex, Money and Drugs'' (1999),
depicts a monkey holding an urn from which three wads of elephant
dung, labeled ``sex,'' ``money'' and ``drugs,'' float upward on the
canvas. The work also incorporates acrylic paint, colorful glitter,
resin, pencil and map pins.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
