<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWICE THE FUN FROM MURPHY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BRUCE WESTBROOK 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   `BOWFINGER'
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Murphy is spoiling us. Here, as in ``The Nutty
Professor,'' he multiplies the mirth by playing extra roles.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, he's both an action-film superstar and a geeky
gofer hired by a bottom-feeder producer (Steve Martin) to
impersonate the star in a movie.
</P>
<P>
   It's a shaky shoot. Filming from a distance _ and without
permits _ Martin stages scenes with low-rent actors accosting the
unsuspecting superstar on the street or in restaurants. He then
stitches these into his alien-invasion premise.
</P>
<P>
   Sound like a modern-day ``Ed Wood?'' It should. Martin's motley
troupe of nobodies has a sad-sack soulfulness, and his
``creativity'' is similarly twisted, grasping and pathetic.
</P>
<P>
   But he also has the dogged enthusiasm that Johnny Depp brought
to Wood, giving ``Bowfinger'' a jaunty can-do spirit to go with its
wackiness.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy is funny as the underling who's embarrassed by nude
scenes and frightened by action stunts. His superstar character is
more of a Hollywood in-joke, with stabs at Tinseltown's fads, greed
and pretentiousness.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Bowfinger'' has ample affection for movie-biz underdogs,
exalting the scrappy idealism of an indie with a dream.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 stars.
</P>
<P>
   1999, R, Universal, CC, VHS priced for rental, DVD $27.98 &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
`AN IDEAL HUSBAND' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An ideal movie is more like it, if you enjoy Oscar Wilde's
drawing-room comedies _ not to mention performances by Rupert
Everett.
</P>
<P>
   Here he plays an aristocratic playboy in London's high society
of the 1890s.
</P>
<P>
   Wild complications arise when his former lover (Julianne Moore)
returns from the Continent to blackmail Sir Robert (Jeremy
Northam), a rising star in Parliament, for a long-buried youthful
indiscretion.
</P>
<P>
   His secret is all that keeps Sir Robert from embodying the
perfection seen in him by his loving and loyal wife (Cate
Blanchett). Torn between living up to her high standards and doing
the honest thing, he turns to Lord Goring (Everett) for help.
</P>
<P>
   Society's rigid strictures of honor and decorum toss their lives
into turmoil, with intelligently comical, sophisticated and
sometimes soulful results.
</P>
<P>
   The cast is impeccable; if this had been released at year's end,
it would be getting Oscar buzz now.
</P>
<P>
   Everett is amusing but not as casually self-serving as he seems
with such lines as, ``To love oneself is to begin a lifelong
romance.''
</P>
<P>
   His co-stars have an almost fierce conviction, and the
Northam-Blanchett romance is truly touching.
</P>
<P>
   If this sounds up your alley, prepare for an ideal rental.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 4 stars.
</P>
<P>
   1999, PG-13, Miramax, CC, VHS priced for sales, DVD $29.99
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NO `PHANTOM' DVD &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DVD is booming, but George Lucas refuses to issue ``Star Wars:
Episode I'' _ The Phantom Menace on disc when it reaches tape April
4.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the film may not hit DVD until he completes the prequel
trilogy in 2005.
</P>
<P>
   Lucasfilm spokeswoman Lynne Hale says her boss wants to do
something ``special '' for ``Phantom Menace'' on DVD, but lacks the
time due to ongoing work on the trilogy.
</P>
<P>
   One problem: That's no reason to delay release of ``Phantom
Menace'' on DVD with no bells and whistles. Just the movie would do
nicely, thank you.
</P>
<P>
   It's not as if DVD extras (trailers, documentaries) are required
by law or can't appear on a reissue. ``Titanic'' emerged on a
movie-only disc last year and eventually will return with added
features.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Phantom Menace'' could do the same. For now, the extras
can wait, but why should the movie?
</P>
<P>
   Lucas' refusal is also painfully ironic. This is the same man
who made strict demands of exhibitors about picture and sound
quality before sending ``Phantom Menace'' to theaters.
</P>
<P>
   If he's so concerned about fans, and so determined they see and
hear his film properly, why doesn't he extend that concern to home
video, where DVD is superior to VHS?
</P>
<P>
   Blaming the delay on preparing extras is no excuse. The movie is
ripe and ready for DVD now.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
CELEBRATE WITH CNN &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's misnamed (the new millenium begins Jan. 1, 2001), but CNN
has issued ``CNN Millennium 2000 _ Incredible Moments From the
Worldwide Celebration.'' The two-hour tape costs a suggested
$14.95.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; VIDEO RATINGS &LR;  &QL; 
4 stars _ Excellent &QL; 
3 stars _ Good &QL; 
2 stars _ Fair &QL; 
1 star _ Poor
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
