<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1537 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN21-CO     01-20 0532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: Under a microscope in a small town
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ I was in the front yard, wondering what I was
going to do about a limb that was scraping the roof of the house.
An old friend stopped by in his new pickup truck. We stood and
talked awhile.
</P>
<P>
   He said the truck actually wasn't all that new. He'd had it six
months or so. I guess I hadn't been paying good attention.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that we live just around the block from one another.
Never mind that we have been best of friends since junior high. But
we don't get together as much as we ought to.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, he stays busy working hard, always has, even back
when we were teenagers. He was one of the few of us who could pay
his way through college without depending on his parents.
</P>
<P>
   He worked hard in college, too, and as a result he can put
``Dr.'' in front of his name. Over the years he has built up a
solid reputation and a good practice, well respected and widely
admired in his profession and in the community. He even served on
the school board for a couple of terms.
</P>
<P>
   What with 60 creeping up on us, he has been wanting to find
somebody to share his practice, with the idea of eventually taking
it over. One fellow made a stab at it, but it didn't work out.
</P>
<P>
   Problem is, not everybody can fit into small-town life.
</P>
<P>
   That's what we usually say when one person or another lives here
awhile and then decides to move on. We'll say, ``Well, I guess they
couldn't fit in.''
</P>
<P>
   I don't think we ever say, ``Well, I guess we didn't fit them.''
</P>
<P>
   I had a good friend who moved here from the city. But he found
it uncomfortable, even a bit unnerving.
</P>
<P>
   He told me this story as an example, about eating breakfast one
morning in a local cafe by himself, not particularly paying
attention to anybody else who was there.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day a fellow he knew only slightly came up to him
on the street, big grin on his face.
</P>
<P>
   ``How'd you like those eggs this morning?'' he asked him.
</P>
<P>
   My friend was dismayed. ``Good grief,'' he told me. ``If they
know what I had for breakfast, what else do they know about me?''
</P>
<P>
   A mutual acquaintance of ours, who had also made the move from
big city to small town, tried to reassure him.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll get used to it after a while, everybody knowing the
most intimate details about your life,'' she said. ``Of course, by
then something deep inside of you will have died.''
</P>
<P>
   Lufkin is a good place. I recommend it. Anybody like me, who was
born here and has never lived anywhere else, will tell you the
same.
</P>
<P>
   P.S. My doctor friend also took note of the limb on the roof. He
said I ought to do something about it as soon as possible. I guess
I'd better. I know he'll be checking on it every time he passes by.
He never did think I worked hard enough.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(at)lcc.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
