<HEADER>
A1545 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-THEATER-NOTES-NYT &LR;      01-20 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON THE THEATER WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   My Kingdom for a House!
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With well over four months till the Tony deadline,
the spring season on Broadway is already almost completely set,
with every Broadway house either currently lighted or awaiting a
show.
</P>
<P>
   That theater crunch was given special emphasis this week when
the producer Cameron Mackintosh, an 800-pound gorilla if there ever
was one, said even he couldn't get a house for his musical ``Martin
Guerre,'' though Broadway wags suspected that decision may have had
more to do with mediocre reviews than lack of clout.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Lyceum, one of Broadway's least-used theaters, appears
to have a tenant, the coming Lincoln Center Theater production of
``Rose.''
</P>
<P>
   There are, of course, a few shows with weak box-office numbers,
namely the plays ``The Price'' and ``Wrong Mountain,'' and to a
lesser extent, ``Amadeus.'' But the theaters in which those plays
are running are already on the short list of other productions,
like ``Copenhagen,'' that have set spring openings.
</P>
<P>
   That said, there may still be a few surprises. Preparation for
David Mamet's ``Boston Marriage'' is moving ahead, with names of
stars (Sharon Stone) and directors (Howard Davies) being dropped
with fair regularity. A closing of any sort might also cause a mad
shuffle of shows to different theaters, each angling for more
attractive houses.
</P>
<P>
   Two other plays, ``Birdy'' and ``Trudy Blue,'' have also stated
a desire to come to Broadway, though their prospects are uncertain.
And the musical ``Jane Eyre,'' a hit last summer in San Diego, may
still find its way here, though next season might be an easier sell
in a year packed with new musicals.
</P>
<P>
   While the set schedule is a boon for amateur prognosticators _
let the Tony guessing begin! _ it leaves little room for that old
romantic notion of a little show with great reviews making a big
leap to Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   Such scenarios are being posited by some Internet gossips for
the early Stephen Sondheim musical ``Saturday Night,'' getting its
New York premiere next month at Second Stage.
</P>
<P>
   This talk, of course, comes sight unseen. The first preview of
``Saturday Night'' is Friday night. The show, delayed a day for
technical demands, is the first at Second Stage to use a fly
system. Still, even if the reviews are dandy, where might it go? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Doing Fine, Thank You
</P>
<P>
   When she was stricken by a stroke in March, just before the
opening of ``Ring Round the Moon,'' Irene Worth promised that she
would be back before the end of that play's Broadway engagement.
</P>
<P>
   She wasn't. But now comes word that Ms. Worth is, thankfully,
returning to the New York stage. Beginning on Feb. 6, the
three-time Tony winner will be seen as the grandmother in
``Ancestral Voices,'' A.R. Gurney's drama about a dissolving
marriage. Performances are Sunday and Monday evenings at Lincoln
Center's Mitzi E. Newhouse Theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a wonderful grandmother, written as a real human being
not just some old trout who wears glasses,'' she said. ``It's nice
for women to be real and not just elderly.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Worth said she was feeling quite well, thank you, but would
rather not have her age printed on advice from her old friend Sir
John Gielgud. ``He says they'll never give you parts if they
know,'' she said. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Nightcap, of Sorts
</P>
<P>
   You can call David Hirson a lot of things _ and the critics have
_ but you can't say he's chicken. It was just last week that
Hirson's second play, ``Wrong Mountain,'' received the type of
critical drubbing that would send many writers into permanent
hibernation.
</P>
<P>
   Not Hirson. In fact, the boyish 41-year-old playwright has
decided that he will appear every night after the show for informal
discussions with the audience. The idea, he said, came after he was
besieged by questions about his admittedly heady play after a
recent performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it might just be healthy to make myself available to
the audience,'' he said. ``I don't always believe the author is the
best person to analyze the play, but he may be able to help.''
</P>
<P>
   And maybe, in turn, audiences can help him. Without positive
reviews, the producers of ``Wrong Mountain,'' the only new play on
Broadway, are depending on word of mouth, any word of mouth, to get
people to buy tickets. Its gross sales were the lowest of any on
Broadway last week.
</P>
<P>
   Long a staple of nonprofit theaters, the postshow discussion is
a rare bird on Broadway. But then again, so are new plays. ``I'll
do it every night,'' said an upbeat Hirson. ``And if it's a night
when only five people stay, we'll all go out for a drink
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Making the Rounds
</P>
<P>
   The last time New Yorkers heard from Eddie Izzard, the eccentric
British comic was going on about all sorts of topics, including the
moon landing (``It's all sticky''), the naming of Engelbert
Humperdinck and, of course, the French.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, it's circles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea, basically,'' he said, winding up, ``is to get at,
loosely, the idea of huge space stuff, that space is curved and the
planets' orbits are curved. The Native American religion is also
all about circles. I will nip that in at one point. And, oh yes,
the Renaissance period.''
</P>
<P>
   This list should come as no surprise to anybody who has
experienced Izzard's ream-of-consciousness style. Audiences will
have a brief window to check it out themselves, April 4-8, when
Izzard arrives with a new show, ``Circles,'' at Westbeth Theater
Center, where his last show, ``Dress to Kill,'' was a hit in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The weeklong stint is part of a two-month tour that will include
a trip to Australia, as well as American stops in Philadelphia,
Boston, Los Angeles and a city he called that ``little bit up
there,'' known to many as Seattle. Then, Izzard said, he will
return to New York in June for a longer run in a larger theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think maybe comedy should be road tested,'' he said. ``Rock
bands make shows and tour them. I think I tour the whole show to
write it.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Like Flynn
</P>
<P>
   Clarke Peters, last seen on Broadway in ``The Iceman Cometh,''
will take over for Robert Urich in ``Chicago'' on Tuesday. A
spokesman for the show said Urich had opted out of his contract,
but might return in the summer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
