<DOCNO> NYT20000120.0148 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1549 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-3TAKE     01-20 1182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AND NOTEWORTHY MOVIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is a selective listing by critics of The New York Times of
new or noteworthy movies currently playing in theaters. Running
times and ratings of films are in parentheses.
</P>
<P>
   `AMERICAN BEAUTY,' starring Kevin Spacey, Annette Bening, Chris
Cooper, Wes Bentley and Thora Birch. Written by Alan Ball. Directed
by Sam Mendes (R, 116 minutes). With heavenly finesse Spacey plays
a buttoned-down 42-year-old suburbanite who flips his lid for a
teen-age cheerleader. And he never gets it back on. The midlife
crisis motif is familiar, but the stage director Sam Mendes brings
terrific visual flair and dry humor to this barbecuing of the
bourgeoisie. All the actors display coolly expert timing,
especially Ms. Bening as the antihero's grasping wife. Although the
story spreads itself thin among many characters, the film coalesces
for a devastating finale (Janet Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `ANGELA'S ASHES,' starring Emily Watson, Robert Carlyle, Joe
Breen, Ciaran Owens and Michael Legge. Directed by Alan Parker (R,
120 minutes). Anyone who thinks poverty is not pretty would have to
think twice after seeing this artfully desolate-looking film
version of Frank McCourt's boyhood memoir. The movie describes dire
suffering alongside inspiring, uplifting episodes. Directed
reverently by Parker, it parades forth a series of familiar
anecdotes from McCourt's book without taking on much weight. This
is the kind of film about hardship in which nobody has indoor
plumbing, but everybody has clean hair (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `ANY GIVEN SUNDAY,' starring Al Pacino, Cameron Diaz, Dennis
Quaid, James Woods and Jamie Foxx. Directed by Oliver Stone (R, 160
minutes). Stone's brawling, hyper-macho professional football film
has enough in-the-thick-of-it playing-field action to satisfy the
fantasies of most armchair players. In the style of Stone's ``Wall
Street,'' the movie is also a crude morality play that pits the old
ways against the new with the veteran coach Tony D'Amato (Pacino)
embodying tradition and a young hotshot quarterback, Willie Beamen
(Foxx), the new. Although the acting is uneven (Ms. Diaz is
disappointing as a tough team owner), and the final scenes are
shamelessly ``Rocky''-ish, the movie delivers a credible,
action-charged vision of the frenzied world of professional sports
as a metaphor for the volatility of American culture (Stephen
Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `BICENTENNIAL MAN,' starring Robin Williams, Embeth Davidtz, Sam
Neill and Oliver Platt. Directed by Chris Columbus (PG, 132
minutes). This gushy Robin Williams star vehicle follows the
200-year quest of a household robot named Andrew to become human.
Directed by the schmaltzmeister Chris Columbus, who steered this
star through ``Mrs. Doubtfire,'' the movie is a joke-strewn,
sentimental man-machine allegory determined to make us feel good
about being human. Corny speeches exalting freedom, the joys of sex
and the mystery of mortality punctuate the tale. Except for
Williams, the acting is strictly of sitcom caliber (Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `BOYS DON'T CRY,' starring Hilary Swank and Chloe Sevigny.
Directed by Kimberly Peirce (R, 114 minutes). This stunning debut
feature tells the strange and resonant story of Brandon Teena, who
despite being born Teena Brandon went on to create a charismatic
identity as a young man. Brandon's ultimately wrenching tale may
sound tabloid-ready, but on screen it turns into Theodore Dreiser's
idea of American tragedy. The film makes it hauntingly real and
even tenderly romantic, with the astonishing acting needed to make
it work. One of last year's best (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `THE CIDER HOUSE RULES,' starring Tobey Maguire, Charlize Theron
and Delroy Lindo. Directed by Lasse Hallstrom (PG-13, 125 minutes).
Radically downsized in scope, and its examination of the issue of
abortion greatly softened, John Irving's sixth novel (with a
Dickensian screenplay by the author) has been turned into a lovely
World War II-era fable about a young man venturing out into the
world. Maguire is Homer Wells, a doleful innocent raised in an
orphanage by Dr. Wilbur Larch (Michael Caine), who performs
abortions. Fleeing the institution with a golden young couple (Ms.
Theron and Paul Rudd), he becomes an apple picker. Sentimental but
smart, the movie has the sweetness and narrative drive of a 1940s
``David Copperfield'' (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   `CRADLE WILL ROCK,' starring Emily Watson, John Turturro, Ruben
Blades, John Cusack, Joan Cusack, Susan Sarandon, Bill Murray and
Vanessa Redgrave. Written and directed by Tim Robbins (R, 132
minutes). This huge Depression-era story features well-known
figures from Orson Welles to Nelson Rockefeller to Diego Rivera,
and it works them into an ambitious ``Ragtime''-like tableau.
Though too many figures in this landscape are reduced to naive
caricature, Robbins and his impressive cast bring strong passions
to bear upon this (mostly) true story of a legendary event: the
trouble-fraught production, by Welles and John Houseman, of Marc
Blitzstein's banner-waving 1936 agitprop musical ``The Cradle Will
Rock.'' Robbins and his cast play out all sides of this event with
the certitude that its importance lives on (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `THE END OF THE AFFAIR,' starring Ralph Fiennes, Julianne Moore,
Stephen Rea and Ian Hart. Directed by Neil Jordan (R, 105 minutes).
Jordan's intoxicating version of Graham Greene's 1951 novel, in
which an illicit affair becomes a far greater gamble than either
lover could have imagined. For this fearlessly eclectic filmmaker,
this is one more intelligent, brooding love story with a secret
twist. Fiennes and Ms. Moore breathe life into it with a dreamy,
erotic intensity that in no way trivializes the film's underlying
ideas about religious faith. Period detail (the setting is London
in the mid-1940s) is sumptuously heightened by the inspired costume
designer Sandy Powell (``Shakespeare in Love'') (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `FANTASIA/2000,' with James Levine and the Chicago Symphony
Orchestra and introductions by Steve Martin, Bette Midler, Levine,
Itzhak Perlman, James Earl Jones, Angela Lansbury, Quincy Jones and
Penn and Teller. Various directors (G, 75 minutes). The new
millennial version of Disney's 1940 groundbreaking fusion of
animation and classical music includes seven new segments and keeps
one from the original film (the wonderful ``Sorcerer's
Apprentice,'' starring Mickey Mouse). Despite the science-fiction
title and the Imax-size screen on which it is shown,
``Fantasia/2000'' is more backward-looking than futuristic. The two
best segments are ``Rhapsody in Blue,'' a witty
Manhattan-in-the-Jazz-Age homage to the caricaturist Al Hirschfeld
set to the music of Gershwin, and the finale (set to Stravinsky's
``Firebird Suite'') in which a cometlike sprite whooshes around the
globe explosively creating, destroying and renewing the planet's
life forms. Movie star introductions lend the film the feel of a
deluxe corporate promotion (Holden). &QL;
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   `GALAXY QUEST,' starring Tim Allen, Sigourney Weaver and Alan
Rickman. Directed by Dean Parisot (PG, 102 minutes). Whether you
love ``Star Trek'' or laugh at it, your starship has come in,
docking in the form of this amiable comedy that simultaneously
manages to spoof these popular futuristic space adventures and
replicate the very elements that have made them so durable. The
film spins out of a single joke, about a bunch of washed-up actors
from a canceled television series who are enlisted by some
credulous interplanetary simpletons to champion them in a conflict
with a scaly, bellicose villain who has all but exterminated their
people. And soon they are off on a genuine space adventure. If
``Galaxy Quest'' never attains consistently giddy heights as it
plays out its combination of knowing satire and heroic adventure,
it keeps its tongue firmly in its cheek, offers a few genuine
laughs, moves swiftly if not at warp speed, and is led by a
talented cast (Lawrence Van Gelder).
</P>
<P>
   `GIRL, INTERRUPTED,' starring Winona Ryder and Angelina Jolie.
Directed by James Mangold (R, 120 minutes). Except for being
several years too old for the role, Winona Ryder, an actress who
oozes high-strung intelligence, is ideally cast as Susanna Kaysen,
a precollege-age girl who lands in a Cambridge mental institution
in 1967 after a halfhearted suicide attempt. (The movie is based on
Ms. Kaysen's memoir.) The period details are perfect, and Ms. Ryder
has the courage to make her character a pain in the neck. But the
small, introspective movie is nearly stolen by Ms. Jolie as a
charismatic, brutally truth-telling sociopath who becomes Susanna's
best friend (Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `THE GREEN MILE,' starring Tom Hanks, Michael Clarke Duncan,
David Morse, Doug Hutchison, Sam Rockwell and Bonnie Hunt. Written
and directed by Frank Darabont (R, 180 minutes). In adapting the
death row drama that Stephen King wrote in multiple installments,
the director of ``The Shawshank Redemption'' could have managed
more economy and fewer talky bits of business around the cellblock.
Still, this lengthy film is vivid and well played. Smooth ensemble
acting builds up to the discovery that a gigantic condemned man
(Duncan) is a prisoner with very special abilities, which gives the
film its mixture of religious overtones and mild horror. Hanks, as
a wry Southern prison guard, is so unaffectedly good that it's
redundant to say so (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `HOLY SMOKE,' starring Kate Winslet and Harvey Keitel. Directed
by Jane Campion (R, 95 minutes). Having roamed so gorgeously
through North Africa as a young hippie mother in ``Hideous Kinky,''
Ms. Winslet this time appears in India as Ruth Barron, a headstrong
young Australian seeking enlightenment. Eventually Ruth's mother
coaxes her home, where a ``cult exiter'' named P.J. (Keitel) is
waiting to wean Ruth away from her Indian guru. But as the film
moves from its early mix of rapture and humor into this more
serious, confrontational stage, it runs into trouble. It doesn't
help that Ms. Winslet's obvious strength and beauty leave Keitel's
P.J. looking overmatched (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `THE HURRICANE,' starring Denzel Washington. Directed by Norman
Jewison (R, 120 minutes). The life story of Rubin (Hurricane)
Carter, a middleweight contender who spent nearly 20 years in
prison for a triple murder he didn't commit, is a big, schmaltzy
ballad of a movie redeemed by Washington's moving, bone-deep
portrayal of the boxer from Paterson, N.J. But the movie plays fast
and loose with the facts, giving far too much credit to the members
of a Canadian commune who took up Carter's cause and all but
eliminating his heroic codefendant John Artis from the story. And
the minor characters are either saints or monsters. Yet the story
of a man heroically fighting his demons and winning his freedom is
still inspiring (Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `THE INSIDER,' starring Al Pacino, Russell Crowe and Christopher
Plummer. Directed by Michael Mann (R, 155 minutes). Mann directs
this taut thriller about the tobacco industry whistle-blower
Jeffrey Wigand with pulse-quickening panache. And he illustrates
why, in the corporate climate of the '90s, truth-telling is a
riskier business than it was circa ``All the President's Men.''
While Pacino delivers galvanizing moral outrage as a producer for
``60 Minutes,'' and Plummer wickedly mimics Mike Wallace, Crowe
movingly captures the complexity of Wigand's situation. Shaky
docudrama ethics cloud the film's take on ``60 Minutes.'' But this
is an inordinately well-played thriller, with Mann's stylistic brio
at its best (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `MAGNOLIA,' starring Tom Cruise, Melinda Dillon, Philip Seymour
Hoffman, William H. Macy, Julianne Moore, John C. Reilly and Jason
Robards. Written and directed by Paul Thomas Anderson (R, 180
minutes). In ``Magnolia'' the colossally talented Anderson has set
up an artfully orchestrated symphony of intersecting L.A. stories,
with many of the cast members from his ``Boogie Nights'' assembled
to form a charismatic ensemble. The movie is saved from its own
worst ideas by the intimacy of the performances. Its single biggest
surprise is Tom Cruise in the role of a strutting,
obscenity-spouting cult figure named Frank Mackey (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `MAN ON THE MOON,' starring Jim Carrey, Courtney Love, Danny
DeVito and Paul Giamatti. Directed by Milos Forman (R, 118
minutes). Andy Kaufman: genius or creep? This biography takes the
more positive view and minimizes the kinkier aspects of Kaufman's
misanthropic performance art, preferring a big, vibrant collection
of greatest hits. Carrey channels his character brilliantly and
makes his material funnier and tighter than it was in fact. And
Forman directs with the same enthusiasm for outlaw Americana that
he brought to ``The People vs. Larry Flynt.'' But the writers, who
also wrote that film and ``Ed Wood,'' can't easily find an
unself-conscious side of the late comic artist to work with. This
feels like the authorized version. It has no real answer to the
question of who Kaufman was and how he got that way (Maslin).
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   `SNOW FALLING ON CEDARS,' starring Ethan Hawke, James Cromwell
and Max Von Sydow. Directed by Scott Hicks (PG-13, 130 minutes).
This director's follow-up to ``Shine'' is the cinematic equivalent
of an arty coffee-table book. It is so busy illustrating the story
(with elaborate flashbacks and montage sequences) that it forgets
to be dramatic. Set in the Pacific Northwest in 1950, the movie
looks back to World War II and the charged relationships between
Japanese-Americans and whites on an island north of Puget Sound.
Hawke is the brooding reporter covering the trial and Von Sydow the
defense lawyer who is the film's official conscience. Robert
Richardson is responsible for the gorgeous cinematography
(Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `STUART LITTLE,' starring Geena Davis, Hugh Laurie and Jonathan
Lipnicki. Directed by Rob Minkoff (PG, 92 minutes). E.B. White's
1945 children's classic has been adapted into a lovely family film
about a little mouse (with the voice of Michael J. Fox) who is
adopted by humans but runs afoul of their fluffy white Persian cat,
Snowbell (Nathan Lane). The movie creates an enchanted storybook
version of New York and has what may be the most exciting toy-boat
race (in Central Park) ever filmed. Thanks to Lane's sly, wise-guy
vocal impersonation, Snowbell nearly steals a movie that is funny
and sweet but never cloying (Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `SWEET AND LOWDOWN,' starring Sean Penn, Samantha Morton and Uma
Thurman. Directed by Woody Allen (PG-13, 95 minutes). In homage to
the kind of jaunty 1930s jazz that has been heard on many of his
other films' soundtracks, Allen imagines a consummate jazz
character: Emmet Ray (played with gusto by Penn), who can play the
guitar as gorgeously as Django Reinhardt but lacks certain
interpersonal skills when it comes to his private life. Borrowing
attributes of various real musicians, the film turns Emmet into
another one of Allen's cad-geniuses and gives him a long-suffering
mute laundress as a sweetheart. (Ms. Morton works miracles in her
wordless role.) But on the storytelling level, the film remains
flimsy. It's the musical interludes, frequent and lovingly
presented, that keep it alive (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `THE TALENTED MR. RIPLEY,' starring Matt Damon, Jude Law,
Gwyneth Paltrow, Cate Blanchett and Philip Seymour Hoffman. Written
and directed by Anthony Minghella (R, 135 minutes). There are
diabolically smart surprises wherever you care to look in this
glittering thriller. Proving that the brilliance of ``The English
Patient'' was no fluke, Minghella shapes a hypnotic, sensually
charged adaptation of Patricia Highsmith's fascinatingly reptilian
murder story. The traffic-stopping cast includes Damon as the
dangerous chameleon of the title and, in a star-making role, the
English actor Jude Law as a rich dilettante who exerts a homoerotic
magnetism. Ms. Paltrow plays the odd woman out with the shrewdness
of a fine character actress, while Ms. Blanchett makes the
delirious most of her role as a needy American post-debutante. As
the story's odious playboy-snob, Hoffman is scene-stealingly
wonderful. Gorgeously photographed in Italy by John Seale (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `TITUS,' starring Anthony Hopkins, Jessica Lange and Alan
Cumming, Harry Lennix and Jonathan Rhys Meyers. Directed by Julie
Taymor (R, 160 minutes). Ms. Taymor, the theater director and
puppeteer who created transfixing stage pictures in ``The Lion
King'' and ``Juan Darien,'' has turned Shakespeare's goriest
tragedy, ``Titus Andronicus,'' into a powerful contemplation of
murderous revenge enacted throughout history. Hopkins is ghoulishly
funny and tragic as the title character, whose political stupidity
sets in motion a devastating chain reaction of killing, torture and
retaliation. Ms. Lange is Tamora, the captured Goth empress who
strikes back. Although the movie's British theatrical and American
film acting styles don't mesh, Ms. Taymor's vision is realized with
a shattering force in time-traveling imagery that blends ancient
Rome with Mussolini's Italy and contemporary cyberpunk flash
(Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `TOPSY-TURVY,' starring Allan Corduner and Jim Broadbent.
Directed by Mike Leigh (R, 161 minutes). Leigh's grandly
entertaining ``Topsy-Turvy'' is one of those films that create a
mix of erudition, pageantry and delectable acting opportunities,
much as ``Shakespeare in Love'' did last year. Instead of a
love-struck young playwright, it presents the curiously matched
personalities of the librettist William Schwenk Gilbert and the
composer Arthur Sullivan in the midst of a robust, knowing,
frequently hilarious look at the musical theater over which they
held sway (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `TOY STORY 2,' with the voices of Tom Hanks and Tim Allen.
Directed by John Lasseter; a Pixar Animated Studios film (G, 98
minutes). A wonderfully playful sequel, sustaining the first film's
wit and novelty while bringing new sophistication to
computer-generated animation. And here is welcome proof that
Hollywood can still make movies to please audiences of any age or
persuasion. From its opening (a perfectly adorable ``Star Wars''
parody) to its Capra-esque conclusion, this is a seamless work with
more metaphorical cleverness than that usually found in the toy
bin. Colorful new characters and more adventurous action enhance
the story of how Woody falls into the clutches of a sleazy toy
dealer, experiences newfound celebrity and needs to be rescued by
his fabulous old friends (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   FILM SERIES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE AMERICAN PLACE: LANDSCAPE IN THE EARLY WESTERN (AND A FEW
LATER CLASSICS).' An opportunity for a new look at the Old West is
at hand at the Museum of Modern Art in New York, where a monthlong
series highlighted by early westerns began Friday. Spanning the
history of the genre, the series features more than 50 films in 30
programs, including works that extend from Edwin Porter, D.W.
Griffith, Thomas H. Ince, John Ford, Charles Chaplin and Allan Dwan
to Victor Fleming, Victor Seastrom, Sam Peckinpah, Mel Brooks,
Clint Eastwood and Jim Jarmusch. One half of a choice double bill
this weekend consists of ``The Great Train Robbery'' (1903),
Porter's 11-minute seminal work about a deadly holdup, with the
woods of New Jersey substituting for the wild West. The other half
is ``The Wild Bunch'' (1969), Peckinpah's violent chronicle of the
adventures of a band of outlaws who have outlived their time. The
films will be shown at 2 p.m. on Sunday. Continuing through Feb.
24, at the Museum of Modern Art, the series is free with museum
admission: $10 for adults, $6.50 for students and people 65 or
older; free for visitors under 16 accompanied by an adult. Pay what
you wish on Fridays from 4:30 to 8:30 p.m. Information and
screening schedule: (212) 708-9400 (Van Gelder).
</P>
</TEXT>
