<HEADER>
A1555 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-ANGELAS-ASHES21-COX     01-20 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANGELAS-ASHES21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    McCourt's memoir survives on-screen
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Frank McCourt's autobiographical
``Angela's Ashes'' is a remarkable book, rich in colorful,
colloquial language, detailing his destitute family's meager
existence with a clear eye and unexpected passages of genuine
humor. A movie version was both inevitable and unfathomable.
</P>
<P>
   Yet director-adapter Alan Parker has done an exceptional job
bringing the cherished best seller to the screen. He understandably
sacrifices its flavorful verbal texture for a stark visual
representation of the dreary, drizzly world of Limerick, Ireland,
but it is a reasonable trade-off. Lovers of the book and newcomers
to the story should both be able to appreciate this cinematic
depiction of McCourt's coming of age, his struggles, setbacks and
triumphs amid unspeakable conditions.
</P>
<P>
   The movie begins in 1935 Brooklyn, where 5-year-old Frank and
his three younger brothers live in poverty and hunger with his
unemployed father Malachy (Robert Carlyle) and his poor, put-upon,
perpetually pregnant mother Angela (Emily Watson). When a fifth
baby, a girl, arrives and quickly dies, the McCourts pack up and
head to Ireland, a nation in even greater financial despair than
the United States. As Frank observes with typical McCourt
puckishness, ``We must be the only family in Irish history to say
goodbye to the Statue of Liberty.''
</P>
<P>
   Their reception is anything but warm, in part because of
Malachy's roots in the Protestant North country. They settle in a
house whose first floor is always flooded and furnished with
flea-infested hand-me-downs. Then Frank's younger brothers also
die, Angela withdraws further into her shell, and Malachy withdraws
into drink. Unable to keep a job longer than a day, he abandons the
family for London. Angela is reduced to begging for public
assistance and Frank helps out by delivering coal, under such
dreadful working conditions that he nearly goes blind.
</P>
<P>
   Life is so grim and hunger so prevalent that at one point, Frank
licks the newspaper of someone's fish and chips ``till my face was
as black as Al Jolson's.'' There is humor here, much of it stemming
from the Catholic Church and the mysteries of communion and
confession, as well as the more alluring mysteries of sex.
</P>
<P>
   Although these are his memoirs, McCourt does not leave himself
unindicted. In a particularly brutal scene, a teen-age Frank has
his first pint of beer at the pub _ a rite of passage _ and returns
home and pummels Angela, just as he had seen his father do so
often.
</P>
<P>
   Depicted from age 5 to 16, Frank is portrayed by three
expressive young actors _ Joe Breen, Ciaran Owens and Michael Legge
_ close enough in looks to make the transitions believable. This is
Frank's story, but the soul of the movie is Angela, played with
such pitiable passivity, yet a determination to survive, by the
wondrous Watson. As Malachy, Robert Carlyle is consumed by demons,
which he tries unsuccessfully to drown in beer. He deserts the
family when he is unable to provide for them, yet Frank can only
recall him with admiration.
</P>
<P>
   Director Parker has had an eclectic career, with films ranging
from ``Midnight Express'' to ``Evita,'' as well as the Irish
working-class comedy, ``The Commitments.'' Here, with
cinematographer Michael Seresin, he captures the muted, misty gray
landscape of Limerick, hopeless yet idealized by distance and
memory.
</P>
<P>
   His script (co-written with Laura Jones) follows the book
faithfully, which is to say it is largely a dark, downward spiral.
Yet the message of ``Angela's Ashes'' is the resolve that peers
through the gloom, the triumph of the human spirit, the will to
keep going despite the misery. As an older Frank observes in
voiceover, ``It was, of course, a miserable childhood, but a
childhood not miserable is not worth telling.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
