<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1556 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-CRADLEWILLROCK21-COX     01-20 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRADLEWILLROCK21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tale of '30s artistic suppression makes the most of too much
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Like impassioned Depression-era composer
Marc Blitzstein, who wrote a folk opera that led to the demise of
the government's Federal Theatre Project employment program, film
director-screenwriter Tim Robbins has deeply felt, left-wing
political views and sees the world in shades of black and white.
Like scowling Mexican muralist Diego Rivera, whose Rockefeller
Center panorama depicted the entire world's political struggles,
Robbins attempts too much in his message-laden movie ``Cradle Will
Rock,'' but his fervent overreach still manages to be exhilarating
entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   As we learn in a preface intended to let Robbins off the hook
for his considerable excesses, the yarn we are about to receive is
``a (mostly) true story.'' In fact, the mini-rebellion surrounding
the opening night of Blitzstein's 1937 musical labor lament, staged
by a cartoonishly brash Orson Welles and produced by an equally
blustery John Houseman, is saga enough to fill an overstuffed
movie. But Robbins has larger, wider ambitions, yearning to create
a thick slice of period agitprop populated by the era's famous and
influential, as well as the fanciful and fictional, in the manner
of a frantic E.L. Doctorow.
</P>
<P>
   The reality of the government's attempt to silence the show it
bankrolled by locking the actors out of their theater is so full of
drama, it is a shame its impact is diluted by Robbins' more
preposterous inventions. Nevertheless, those who wade through this
uneven mosaic will be rewarded with an armful of juicy performances
and a cry for artistic freedom, either in the turbulent '30s or
today.
</P>
<P>
   Spurred on by ghostly visions of Bertolt Brecht, starving artist
Blitzstein (a dewy-eyed Hank Azaria) peddles his magnum opus to
Federal Theatre Project, headed by radiant do-gooder Hallie
Flanagan (Cherry Jones, finally getting a movie role worthy of
her). Meanwhile, a callow Nelson Rockefeller (John Cusack)
commissions Rivera (Ruben Blades) to design and paint an upbeat
mural for his new corporate complex, and is taken aback by the
prominent image of Lenin on the wall. Both artistic efforts seem
doomed, in part by the government's anti-Communist zeal,
spearheaded by Congressman Martin Dies and his witch hunt hearings.
</P>
<P>
   Wait, there's more. Media magnate William Randolph Hearst is
buying Italian art in an effort to launder money to Mussolini's
fascist regime, a deal brokered by an extravagant Susan Sarandon
and paid in part by a fictional capitalist's wife (a giddy Vanessa
Redgrave). On the other side of the political fence are
well-meaning whistle-blower Hazel Huffman (Joan Cusack), ready to
testify against the Commies in the theater company, and an
overwrought, disgruntled vaudeville ventriloquist (Bill Murray).
Remarkably, Robbins keeps most of these balls juggling in the air,
even if they come at us in wildly disparate moods and acting
styles.
</P>
<P>
   If ``Cradle Will Rock'' had a center, it would be the performers
of Blitzstein's pop opera, typified by stage-struck wannabe Olive
Stanton (perpetual waif Emily Watson, fresh from the gloom of
``Angela's Ashes''). The hodge-podge concludes with the locked-out
cast marching through the streets to another theater where the show
defiantly goes on, a momentary victory for art. And in case we
didn't get the point, a final heavy-handed image underscores the
point that the cultural battle continues in the present.
</P>
<P>
   Robbins is clearly a filmmaker of the ``more is more'' school,
but Blitzstein and Rivera would recognize a kindred spirit in his
boat-rocking political vehemence.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
