<HEADER>
A1560 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-HOME-VIDEO-2TAKES-NYT     01-20 1048
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-VIDEO-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME VIDEO: `MOONLIGHTING'; NEW VIDEO RELEASES 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: in reference to ``M.A.S.H'' please replace points with
asterisks)  
 (bl)  
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   `Moonlighting' And an Audition
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Gordon Caron's ``Now and Again,'' a show about a
middle-aged man in a young man's body, is now in its first season
on CBS. ``Knock wood we'll get a second season,'' he said the other
day. In 1985 he was wishing the same for another show of his:
``Moonlighting,'' whose run as one of the top series ever was by no
means preordained in its first year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had about the same ratings as the show that preceded us in
that slot,'' he said. That was ``MacGruder and Loud,'' about two
police officers who married each other against regulations. ``The
wisdom was that they'd renew them and let us go,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly. On Tuesday, Anchor Bay will release the 93-minute
``Moonlighting'' pilot on tape and DVD. The disc also includes
commentary by Caron and Bruce Willis, whose smirk and ``real guy''
demeanor as the private detective David Addison set him up for fame
in future film roles. In those days, masculine characters on
television tended to be sensitive types, like Alan Alda in
``M.A.S.H'' had been. ``I was more interested in writing a guy who
planted his feet and said what was on his mind,'' Caron said.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere to be heard on the disc is Cybill Shepherd, who as the
prickly Maddie Hayes helped generate enough frustrated sexual
tension between her and Addison to drive the nation to distraction
for a couple of seasons. Finally, in an episode that ranks with the
revelation of who shot J.R., the coming out of Ellen DeGeneres and
the retirement of Jerry Seinfeld, they ``got horizontal,'' as the
writers put it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a mistake maybe,'' Caron said in an interview. Ms.
Shepherd was pregnant with twins at the time, which definitely took
some steam out of the proceedings. Critics contended that the
consummation did the same for the series, but Caron said that
decline wasn't inevitable. ``There were good stories to tell after
that,'' he said. Two years later, in May 1989, the show left the
air.
</P>
<P>
   The disc also presents Willis' screen test. He and Caron were
close, and at first so were Caron and Ms. Shepherd. ``There came a
time when that wasn't the case,'' Caron added.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the disc makes a fine artifact without the other
half of Hayes and Addison. On the show Maddie was a supermodel
turned detective agency owner. ``Cybill said it was a Hawksian
comedy,'' Caron said of the mix of the screwball and the gangster
in Howard Hawks' films in the 1930s and '40s. ``Moonlighting''
reviewers were sometimes bothered by the dual personality. ``They
wondered what the show wanted to be a comedy or a drama,'' Caron
recounted.
</P>
<P>
   Like movies of the '30s and '40s, the show burst with dialogue.
``I had them watch those films to see really how fast you could
talk and not worry about people understanding,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Would the show work today? Certainly the sexual tension still
applies, and then some. (For a look at the '90s scene there is
``Ally McBeal: Sex and the Single Life,'' a two-disc set of six
episodes from Fox.) ``Moonlighting'' reruns are on Bravo, and there
are plans to release more videos. ``We haven't finalized anything,
but I'm hopeful,'' Caron said.
</P>
<P>
   NEW VIDEO RELEASES
</P>
<P>
   ILLUMINATA
</P>
<P>
   Conjuring some familiar stage types, John Turturro's film pays
knowing homage to actors and the New York theater circa 1900. As
the aging diva Celimene, Susan Sarandon twits ingenues. A master of
casual cruelty, the lofty critic Bevalaqua, hilariously played by
Christopher Walken, falls for a bit player with long eyelashes,
amusingly portrayed by Bill Irwin. Lending heart and ballast to the
story are the aspiring playwright Tuccio ( Turturro, above) and the
star of the company, Rose, played by Katherine Borowitz (
Turturro's solemnly beautiful wife). Directing well enough to make
one forget he's directing, Turturro does ``a fine job of drawing
his cast into the spirit of celebration,'' Janet Maslin wrote in
The New York Times. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1999. Artisan. $83.33; DVD, $29.98. 111 minutes. Closed
captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
   MY SON THE FANATIC
</P>
<P>
   ``They say integrate _ but they live in pornography and filth
and they call us backward,'' says Farid (Akbar Kurtha), a young
Pakistani trying to live in the north of England. Angrily breaking
off his romance with the daughter of an English police officer,
Farid is less patient with racist treatment than his more liberal
father, Parvez (the Indian actor Om Puri), who drives a taxi
frequented by prostitutes and their clients. Written with delicacy
and wry humor, Udayan Prasad's film is filled ``with loosely
sketched characters who still come fully to life'' (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   1999. Miramax. $104.16. 86 minutes. R. Release date: Jan. 25.
</P>
<P>
   BLACK CAT, WHITE CAT
</P>
<P>
   In a mad, Felliniesque scramble through his own imagination,
Emir Kusturica employs a flock of geese and a nonprofessional cast
in a tale of two patriarchs and a lot of young connivers.
</P>
<P>
   There's a heist caper and misdirected passions leading to a
wedding with a barefoot bride who disguises herself as a tree
stump. Just ``give this man the Danube, Gypsy musicians and a
camera and you've got a party'' (Maslin). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1999. U.S.A. $106.99. 135 minutes. Serbo-Croatian and Romany
with English subtitles. No rating.
</P>
<P>
   MY LIFE SO FAR
</P>
<P>
   A more genteel view unfolds in Hugh Hudson's film about life in
Argyll, Scotland, in the late 1920s. Not that the story, as seen
through the eyes of a 10-year-old boy (Robert Norman), lacks
troubling situations. His father, Edward (Colin Firth), is an
eccentric inventor and passionate nonconformist who clashes over
priorities with his brother, Morris (Malcolm MacDowell), a
hard-headed businessman. Then Edward is smitten with Morris' much
younger French wife (Irene Jacob). But this is ``such a muted,
smoothly textured swatch of British nostalgia, you feel no qualms
about languishing in its `Masterpiece Theater' vision of a safer,
more shining path'' (Stephen Holden).
</P>
<P>
   1999. Miramax. $104.16. 93 minutes. Closed captioned. PG-13.
Release date: Jan. 25.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release, appeared on television or been on videocassette in
earlier editions &UR; : &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HORATIO HORNBLOWER
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Duel,'' the first film of a four-part series, the
seafaring is none too rollicking for C.S. Forester's famed
midshipman (Ioan Gruffud) as he sets sail with the Royal Navy. With
too little to do _ it being 1793 and the English between set-to's
with the French _ the crew of the Justinian is proving to be its
own worst enemy. Seasick by the time he reaches the ship's decks,
Horn-blower falls prey to the sadistic Jack Simpson (Dorian Healy),
with whom he eventually conducts the altercation of the title. The
problem is, subsequent battles and all, Hornblower and the rest
never snap to throughout the entire series. ``If you can imagine a
young Al Gore in a Napoleon hat, you've got the picture,'' Ron
Wertheimer wrote in The New York Times. 1999. A&AMP;E. A boxed set of
four DVDs. $59.95. 400 minutes. Release date: Jan. 25.
</P>
<P>
   IN SEARCH OF KUNDUN
</P>
<P>
   With interviews of its creative participants, Michael Henry
Wilson's documentary clarifies the aim of Martin Scorsese's
``Kundun,'' a visually enthralling film that used few words to
convey the spirit of Tibetan Buddhism. Interspersing scenes of
Scorsese at work with comments by the Dalai Lama, the film is
unapologetically puffy, but, Stephen Holden wrote in The New York
Times, still makes a ``valuable and informative footnote.'' 1999.
Hollywoodn't. $19.95. 84 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   EVEN DWARFS STARTED SMALL
</P>
<P>
   In Werner Herzog's second feature film, dwarfs take over a
correctional institution and try to break free of a society that
mocks them. 1970. Anchor Bay. $19.98. 96 minutes. German with
English subtitles. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
