<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000120.0159 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1572 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-     01-20 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT THE MOVIES: CROWDED OSCAR FIELD; RESTORATION; FOREIGN PICKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RICK LYMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ The meeting took place in the cafe of the Four
Seasons Hotel in Beverly Hills, the power breakfast site of choice.
Mike Leigh, director of ``Topsy-Turvy,'' a love sonnet to the
theater in the form of a biography of Gilbert and Sullivan, waved
across the room to Anthony Minghella, director of ``The Talented
Mr. Ripley,'' the lavish adaptation of the Patricia Highsmith novel
about a chameleonlike serial killer.
</P>
<P>
   Flashback: Three years ago, Minghella's previous film, ``The
English Patient,'' was a front-runner for the Oscar for best
picture, which it eventually won, while Leigh's ``Secrets and
Lies'' was a potential dark-horse spoiler.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Minghella's film _ along with Sam Mendes' ``American
Beauty'' and Michael Mann's ``Insider'' _ is mentioned as a likely
winner of the Oscar for best picture.
</P>
<P>
   And Leigh's ``Topsy-Turvy,'' which won the National Society of
Film Critics and the New York Film Critics Circle awards for best
picture of 1999, is a potential dark-horse candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was waiting for the National Board of Review to announce its
best-picture choices,'' Leigh told Minghella, whose film placed
second to ``American Beauty'' on the board's list. ``And when it
came out, and I saw your film in there, I thought, `Uh-oh, here we
go again.'''
</P>
<P>
   Leigh remembered his previous Oscar experience as a bittersweet
affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``You fly all the way over to Los Angeles, and you stay in a
fancy hotel, and by the time they take you over to the Oscar
ceremonies in your limousine, and you walk down that long gantlet
outside and are sitting in the hall, you've bought into it,'' he
said. ``You might just win. And then they started announcing the
winners, and it became gradually clear that it wasn't to be.''
</P>
<P>
   This year when there is no clear single front-runner (as there
was with ``Titanic'' two years ago) or even a race between two
favorites (``Saving Private Ryan'' and the eventual winner,
``Shakespeare in Love,'' last year), the hopes of dark horses are
raised even higher.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it also means the field is more crowded, with such
potential long-shot nominees as ``Being John Malkovich'' and
``Three Kings'' lurking in the shadows. ``It seems to me that
people have been able to put out some really interesting things''
is the way Leigh put it.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Leigh said, he must face another Academy Awards season with
a film, at least potentially, in the running. He even faltered over
naming the awards. ``I can hardly get the name out of my mouth,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Leigh said he was delighted with the way ``Topsy-Turvy,'' a
fondly imagined period piece, had been embraced by filmgoers who
might have been alienated by some of his harder-edged urban films
like ``Naked'' and ``High Hopes.''
</P>
<P>
   If the film is nominated for Academy Awards this time around,
Leigh says, he has learned his lesson. When people come up to him
and assure him that he will win, he will maintain his skepticism.
``I think I have learned to be a little less gullible,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A Clearer `Window'
</P>
<P>
   Robert A. Harris and James C. Katz, the film restoration wizards
who have already done the holy work of fixing, saving and ennobling
deteriorating classics like ``Lawrence of Arabia,'' ``Vertigo'' and
``My Fair Lady,'' are back in theaters this week with their latest
effort: a lush, vividly colored restoration of Alfred Hitchcock's
``Rear Window,'' made in 1954.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, ``Rear Window,'' starring James Stewart, is unlike the
team's other efforts, being more of a chamber piece in comparison
with the big-screen bombast of David Lean's epic ``Lawrence'' or
Hitchcock's emotionally twisted ``Vertigo.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was much needed, Katz said recently, because the original
negative of the film had fallen into such disrepair and because the
film was a technical landmark for Hollywood. ``Rear Window'' was
the first movie to use a Technicolor dye-transfer color process
that later fell into disuse.
</P>
<P>
   A result, Katz said, is that those who have seen the film in
recent years may not recognize the electric brightness of some of
the colors they will see in this restored version.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood studios should come to an agreement about what
constitutes a restored film, he said. Too many movies are sent out
into theaters with little more than a fresh print of an old
negative and advertised as restored, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we finish with a film, there is a brand-new, perfect
negative,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the team will decide what project to take on next. So many
classics are in need of attention, but there is only so much time.
The men say they can work on only one film at a time.
</P>
<P>
   And what they do is also dictated by the willingness of the
studio that owns the film to hire them to undertake the work. Maybe
Hitchcock's ``North by Northwest''?
</P>
<P>
   Katz's face lighted up. ``Oh, we'd love to get our hands on that
one,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Favorite Foreign Films
</P>
<P>
   Landmark Theaters, the nation's largest chain of art-house
cinemas, celebrated its 25th anniversary with a poll of the
nation's favorite foreign-language films. Visitors to Landmark's
cinemas as well as Borders Books branches were invited to cast
their votes as were visitors to an Internet site, and 35,000 votes
were eventually tallied. The results were announced last week.
</P>
<P>
   As might be expected in such an unscientific poll of
contemporary moviegoers and bookstore browsers, the largest number
of votes went to the most recent foreign-language box-office
favorites. ``Life Is Beautiful'' ended up in first place, followed
by ``Cinema Paradiso'' and ``Il Postino,'' all films of the last
decade. One has to go down to No. 8, Akira Kurosawa's ``Seven
Samurai'' (1954), to find a film made before the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   The other films in the poll's top 10 are ``Like Water for
Chocolate'' (1992), ``Das Boot'' (1981), ``Babette's Feast''
(1987), ``The Gods Must Be Crazy'' (1981), ``Shall We Dance?''
(1996) and ``The Bicycle Thief'' (1948).
</P>
<P>
   Where is Federico Fellini's ``8{?'' Sorry, No. 39. Francois
Truffaut's ``Jules and Jim''? No. 54. Jean Renoir's seminal ``Rules
of the Game''? No. 98. And Michelangelo Antonioni's
``L'Avventura,'' once chosen by a poll of British film critics as
the second-best movie ever made (after ``Citizen Kane'')? Nowhere
in the top 100.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not the point, argued Cary Jones, the theater chain's
vice president for marketing. ``Part of the point was to stimulate
discussion of foreign-language films and to get people to begin
thinking about them,'' especially young people, Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   About 20 percent of Landmark's revenues come from showing
foreign-language films, he said, although this number is fewer than
it had been in earlier years before American independent films
began to squeeze foreign films out of most of America's art houses.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the challenge,'' Jones said, ``making foreign films the
hip and cool thing again.''
</P>
<P>
   Tale of a Dog
</P>
<P>
   Jay Russell, who had already had one Hollywood incarnation in
``development hell'' at two production companies, Imagine
Entertainment and TriStar Pictures, was making television
documentaries when he came across the writer Willie Morris at home
in Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went over to his house and interviewed him there, and he
was one of these larger-than-life characters,'' said Russell. ``I
immediately just fell for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Morris, who died in August, was best known for his memoirs of
growing up in the Deep South (``North Toward Home'') and working in
Manhattan literary circles (``New York Days''), but Russell said he
was drawn to a short memoir Morris wrote about the best dog he ever
had.
</P>
<P>
   This resulted in ``My Dog Skip,'' a frankly sentimental film
about a boy and his precocious dog in small-town Mississippi that
opened a couple of weeks ago on a handful of screens in New York
and Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   If it does well, it may expand to more markets, Russell said.
</P>
<P>
   Russell studied at Columbia University under the director Milos
Forman. Later at the Sundance Institute Film Workshop he was able
to develop his first film, ``End of the Line,'' starring Wilford
Brimley and Mary Steenburgen. This led to the Hollywood development
deals that after much effort resulted in no films being made.
</P>
<P>
   When the offer came along to make documentaries, Russell said,
he jumped at it. ``At least I was out there doing what I wanted to
do, making movies,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996 he was working on a five-hour miniseries for PBS called
``Great Drives,'' interviewing people about the famed Highway 61
that runs through the heart of the Mississippi Delta, when he met
Morris.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of his writing is sentimental, but he never considered
`sentimental' to be a negative term, and neither do I,'' Russell
said. ``There's a simplicity to it that touches the heart.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
