<P>
   TEXASDEMS _ As they trudged through Iowa and New Hampshire this
week, Democratic presidential hopefuls Al Gore and Bill Bradley may
have missed an important development in Pasadena, Texas: Ceole
Speight has started wearing a campaign button.Speight, an AFL-CIO
employee, was undecided for months. But after hearing about Gore at
the Texas AFL-CIO convention in Austin this week, Speight finally
picked her pin: Gore 2000. Her choice may be emblematic of larger
trends in Texas, which will hold its presidential primary on March
14. Several months ago, as Bradley surged in the polls and the Gore
campaign lurched toward a much-needed overhaul, the Texas race
looked like a toss-up. But Gore has since solidified his position
with organized labor, Hispanics, and other traditionallly
Democratic constituencies, and now he looks tough to beat in the
Lone Star State. (Greenberger, Austin American-Statesman). 25.
</P>
