<HEADER>
A1575 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MAP-FILM-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      01-20 0601
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAP-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`A MAP OF THE WORLD': PUSHED TO THE BRINK 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   So many sudsy made-for-Lifetime dramas about families in crisis
flood the market that when a film appears like ``A Map of the
World,'' the devastating screen adaptation of a novel by Jane
Hamilton, it can be easily overlooked.
</P>
<P>
   But this film about a family in the Midwest that endures a
grotesque one-two punch of misfortune has an emotional depth and
psychological acuity that place it in a category by itself.
</P>
<P>
   The central character, Alice Goodwin (Sigourney Weaver), is a
mother of two and part-time school nurse who has moved from the
city to help her husband, Howard (David Strathairn), run a farm in
rural Wisconsin. The Goodwins' harried life is turned upside down
one day when Alice is minding the children of her best friend and
neighbor, Theresa Collins (Julianne Moore), and Theresa's
2-year-old daughter, Lizzy, strays into a pond and drowns.
</P>
<P>
   Alice has barely begun to recover from the event, which has left
her guilt-stricken and filled with self-hatred, when she is
arrested and accused of sexually abusing a young boy at her school.
Already on the verge of a nervous breakdown, she is plunged into a
nightmare. A pariah in the community, spat on by her neighbors, she
languishes in prison after Howard can't raise the money for bail.
</P>
<P>
   Where an ordinary film would turn Alice's predicament into a
heartbreaking sobfest, ``A Map of the World,'' which reopens Friday
in Manhattan after a brief run in December, doesn't make it so easy
for us. Headstrong and mercurial, Alice reacts to misfortune with a
perverse, zany combativeness.
</P>
<P>
   Although she is clearly innocent of wrongdoing, she can be
infuriating. And Ms. Weaver's extraordinarily penetrating
performance captures every shade of self-hatred, defiance, guilt,
exasperation and impatience that Alice experiences, as well as
showing us her love for her family.
</P>
<P>
   Every character in the movie, from Alice's basically
well-meaning but ruthless lawyer to her embattled but loyal husband
(who begins to worry that his wife might actually be guilty), has
many dimensions. Ms. Weaver's Alice is matched in depth by Ms.
Moore's radiant, grief-stricken Theresa, who is overcome with rage
over her loss but who also understands that these things happen and
that it wasn't Alice's fault.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Elliott, a New York theater director who is making his
screen debut with ``A Map of the World,'' has won acclaim for the
hyper-realistic ensemble performances he puts on the stage. He
brings the same microscopic psychological detail to bear here,
plunging us into the near chaos of family life with young children
and making us feel its stress as well as its joy.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's portrait of a marriage that already has its cracks
and seams being put to an ultimate test is wrenching. When Alice
goes to prison, the film's vision of it as a place peopled largely
by volatile underclass women who are barely out of their teens and
emotionally are children is a little shocking and entirely
believable.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Map of the World'' has its flaws. The voice-over narrations
that preface and end the movie are stiff and not clear enough. And
when Alice finally gets her day in court, the trial is dispensed
with too quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Still, not since Fred Schepisi's 1988 film ``A Cry in the Dark''
has a movie gotten this deeply under the skin of a woman who finds
herself a modern-day Salem witch. And Ms. Weaver's amazingly
self-effacing performance, like Meryl Streep's in the earlier film,
is a marvel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
