<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1577 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-STUTTGART-DANCE-REVIE     01-20 1032
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STUTTGART-DANCE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DROPPING THE LITERARY FOR PRESENT-DAY HIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Better choreography, to put it mildly, would have
helped the Stuttgart Ballet on Wednesday night when the German
company opened a run, through Saturday, at City Center.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the program of two New York premieres and the
familiar ``Initials R.B.M.E.'' by John Cranko showed off a handsome
crop of young dancers and the troupe's rarely seen contemporary
side.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not ``Delta Inserts'' by the American choreographer
Kevin O'Day and ``Dos Amores'' by Christian Spuck, a German
choreographer new to New York, are works that fully make his point,
Reid Anderson, the company's Canadian artistic director, is on the
right track.
</P>
<P>
   He knows that the Stuttgart cannot be a single-image company,
fossilized in the handful of Cranko story ballets that rocketed the
troupe to international fame in 1969. Since then, the Stuttgart has
been associated with the full-evening ballets Cranko fashioned out
of literary classics.
</P>
<P>
   After a long absence from New York, the company appeared
typically at Lincoln Center Festival '98 with ``Onegin'' and
``Romeo and Juliet,'' sure-fire Cranko staples.
</P>
<P>
   But Cranko occasionally created plotless pieces in a
contemporary style.
</P>
<P>
   ``Initials R.B.M.E.'' (1972) is the best known, the
choreographer's tribute to the four dancers he guided to fame as he
remolded the Stuttgart's artistic profile. The initials refer to
the first names of these dancers: the American Richard Cragun, the
German Birgit Keil, the Brazilian Marcia Haydee and the Dane Egon
Madsen.
</P>
<P>
   Here was a compelling acknowledgment that a choreographer
collaborates with his dancers. That Jiri Kylian, John Neumeier and
William Forsythe emerged from the Stuttgart under Cranko's
direction and later Ms. Haydee's to become Europe's three leading
choreographers today is testimony to a body of creativity.
</P>
<P>
   But none of these three choreographers produced their best work
at the Stuttgart, and all now head other companies. Anderson, who
danced with Kylian and Neumeier in the company before directing
Ballet British Columbia and the National Ballet of Canada, seems
therefore intent on giving new choreographers a free hand.
</P>
<P>
   One would nonetheless hate to have a newcomer to ballet think
that the quality of choreography in this program is the kind
audiences normally encounter. O'Day has produced what may be his
weakest work, uncharacteristically academic under its familiar cool
veneer. Atypically, he has been infected with the bug of the
stop-and-go style that Forsythe has pioneered to more brilliant
effect.
</P>
<P>
   Spuck, a dancer in the company, is a talent worth developing
and, despite a restricted idiom, he has an expressive fluency. Yet
here, too, there are influences from choreographers who simply work
on a higher level.
</P>
<P>
   To see corseted men suddenly reappear in Baroque skirts is to
recall similar Kylian images just as Spuck's clay-figure duets,
full of flexed feet, owe much to the Spanish choreographer Nacho
Duato.
</P>
<P>
   If there is something to applaud vehemently, it is the new
classical style that Anderson has given to the company. Body
placement is perfect and the men, stronger than the women, are
superb.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Delta Inserts,'' O'Day again explores relationships with a
tinge of alienation, as he has done more persuasively in works for
the New York City Ballet and modern-dance troupes. This time, the
malaise is drowned in the clattering cascade of sound that the
experimental composer John King has written for the piece.
</P>
<P>
   It is one thing for King to compose for Merce Cunningham, where
the score is deliberately ignored by the dancers. It is another
when the music is used as rhythmic support by O'Day, who is wedded
to the beat.
</P>
<P>
   Structurally, the ballet divides an ensemble into four
successive duets, each longer than the other. Strangely, the
choreography often resembles an adagio (or partnering) class with
the women on toe displaying a classroom silhouette.
</P>
<P>
   Each couple has a different relationship, but one partner often
taps another on the noggin or other parts of the body. Elena
Tentschikowa hits Ivan Gil Ortega on the shoulder after he tumbles
through a burst of metallic riffs.
</P>
<P>
   Roberta Fernandes, somewhat passive, and Eric Gauthier, swift
and darting, give a hint of the manipulative partnering that
follows with Douglas Lee and Bridget Breiner.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Conn and Julia Kramer have a duet that is finally
something to write home about. She is lifted from under his legs
and clambers up his calf. After they dance in unison, Conn staggers
about and Ms. Kramer knocks him over with a tap to his forehead:
the fragility of relationships. Generally, the choreography for the
men is more challenging.
</P>
<P>
   Cranko, feeling compelled to use all of Brahms' Second Piano
Concerto, created a more persuasive ode to friendship in ``Initials
R.B.M.E.'' Vladimir Malakhov, usually seen with American Ballet
Theater, brought his purity and playfulness to the Madsen role.
Cragun's specialty was triple turns in the air. Robert Tewsley does
not have this technique, but he substituted a lyrical elegance in
the Cragun solos.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kramer in the Keil role and Ms. Breiner in the Haydee role
both needed stronger projection, but Ivan Cavallari, as Ms.
Breiner's partner, gave every arabesque and yearning gesture a
magnificent power.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dos Amores'' is a collage. The music is by the European
experimental composers Thierry de Mey and Dieter Fenchel as well as
Vivaldi. A love poem by Pablo Neruda is recited in Spanish. Six
couples supposedly explore aspects of love. Steps as such and toe
work do not interest Spuck. Enigmatic images do. The plumb lines
attached to silver cones onstage seem more like props than symbols,
and the occasionally blindfolded dancers look as spliced-in as the
men who dance to Vivaldi, bare chested in Baroque skirts.
</P>
<P>
   At his best, Spuck knows how to put movement together. There is
a polish to the partnering. A woman in an overhead lift wraps
smoothly around her partner's neck and flows into a curled position
in his arms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-00 1754EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000120.0164 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1580 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-HEDWIG-THEATER-REVIEW     01-20 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEDWIG-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HEDWIG AND THE ANGRY INCH': LAST DOUBLE-ENTENDRE OF A GENDER
BENDER? 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: Production notes appear at end of review.) (DW) 
 By BEN BRANTLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Do we really have to say goodnight to Hedwig?
</P>
<P>
   It's true that this stitched-together collage of a woman has put
in close to two years down there on the waterfront, where she has
turned the Jane Street Theater into her personal confessional. But
as of last Wednesday night, she was looking awfully healthy for
someone who describes her own exterior as a ``paper shroud,'' and
she was still wearing her scarred heart like a rhinestone
lavaliere. That heart still glitters; it still hypnotizes.
</P>
<P>
   The closing notice was posted recently for ``Hedwig and the
Angry Inch,'' John Cameron Mitchell and Stephen Trask's remarkable
musical about a ``slip of a girlyboy'' from East Berlin who grew up
to become an ``internationally ignored song stylist'' and, thanks
to a botched sex-change operation, someone of unclassifiable
gender.
</P>
<P>
   The show, which quickly became the coolest ticket in town after
opening with Mitchell in the title role in February 1998, has been
losing momentum of late. The gamble of casting Ally Sheedy, the
adventurous film actress, in the part last fall turned out to be,
by all accounts, unfortunate. Ms. Sheedy left the show six weeks
before her contract ended, and ``Hedwig'' is now scheduled to close
on Jan. 30. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But this breathtakingly original musical is, one should
remember, about survival through self-reincarnation, centered on a
character who, in concert with her ragtag rock band, the Angry
Inch, describes herself as harder to tear down than the Berlin
Wall. In the person of Matt McGrath, who took over the part last
month, Hedwig has found an avatar worthy of her infinite, er,
variety. The show feels new-born. Mitchell is the only previous
Hedwig I had seen (others include Michael Cerveris, Kevin Cahoon
and Donovan Leitch), and I wasn't sure I wanted to cloud my
memories of what registered as an unmatchable portrait. Yet
McGrath, who played the terminally sensitive and sullen gay sons of
``A Fair Country'' and ``Minutes From the Blue Route,'' brings a
sly, rejuvenating shift of emphasis to a role that is, after all, a
composite of so many unlikely elements.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't start off with the confrontational confidence or
insolence of Mitchell. There's a vulnerability, even a slight
shakiness, right on the bespangled, bewigged surface of McGrath's
Hedwig, so that when she announces to her audience that she's
``wide open,'' you don't just snicker. This is a Hedwig swimming in
Weltschmerz, and the sparkling makeup on her lips, cheeks and
eyelids suggests accumulated tears as it glistens in the light.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean that McGrath, a sure and fluid singer, doesn't
land each of the lewd double entendres that make Hedwig's act such
a down-and-dirty pleasure. But he brings a slow hand to his
delivery, with droll, molasses-paced double takes to match. Even
more than Mitchell, he finds a startling individuality in the
different voices within Hedwig: of those who used and abused her in
the past; of her own crazy salad of selves; and of Trask's
deliciously eclectic score, which ranges from country and western
to glam rock.
</P>
<P>
   The production itself, directed by Peter Askin, feels newly
tightened and muscular. The backup band is first-rate, as is Maggie
Moore as Yitzak, Hedwig's hangdog immigrant husband, equally ready
to snarl and whimper. The metamorphoses of Hedwig and Yitzak at the
show's end have a truly magical inevitability.
</P>
<P>
   For ``Hedwig,'' for all its gleeful satire of the ego-driven
``business we call show,'' is ultimately as affecting as it is
funny. Even more than, say, ``Rent,'' it's the perfect musical for
a generation that grew up refusing to draw a line between irony and
sincerity and that knows that striking a pose doesn't mean you have
to freeze yourself in it. Identity is endlessly scrambled in
``Hedwig''; McGrath's performance, like that of Mitchell, makes it
clear that this can be as much of a blessing as a curse.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `HEDWIG AND THE ANGRY INCH'
</P>
<P>
   Book by John Cameron Mitchell; music and lyrics by Stephen
Trask; directed by Peter Askin; sets and projections by James
Youmans; costumes by Fabio Toblini; lighting by Kevin Adams; sound
by Werner F; musical staging by Jerry Mitchell; hair and makeup
design by Mike Potter; production stage manager, Jason Eagan.
Presented by Susann Brinkley Productions, Samjack Ltd. and J.B.F.
Producing Corp. At the Jane Street Theater in New York.
</P>
<P>
   With: Matt McGrath (Hedwig), Maggie Moore (Yitzak); Jeremy
Chatzky, Joe Pecorino, Jon Weber and Chris Weilding (Angry Inch
band members).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
