<HEADER>
A1581 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-ART-6     01-20 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-ART-660&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENIOR RUSSIAN GENERAL REPORTED MISSING IN CHECHNYA
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOZDOK, Russia _ A senior Russian general Thursday became an
unfortunate symbol of the difficulties Russian troops have endured
in their campaign to take the Chechen capital, Grozny, when he was
reported missing there.
</P>
<P>
   Maj. Gen. Mikhail Malofeyev vanished on Tuesday, the first day
of a renewed Russian ground onslaught on the city in the breakaway
southern Russian republic.
</P>
<P>
   Russian commanders said the general had probably been killed in
a fierce clash, but the Chechen militants on the other side of the
fighting insisted that he had been captured alive and was being
interrogated at a rebel hide-out in the Chechen highlands.
</P>
<P>
   As the deputy commander of the Northern Group of Russian forces
in Chechnya, Malofeyev was an important commander. Thursday night,
his fate was the lead item on Russian television news.
</P>
<P>
   The news broadcasts showed a video of the 44-year-old officer as
he stood in a trench near Grozny in early January and gave orders
to his subordinates. His disappearance came among reports that
Russian troops were encountering determined rebel resistance.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officers are no longer boasting that they will seize the
city in four days. Instead, they emphasized that there is no
deadline for what could be a protracted and costly operation.
</P>
<P>
   One of the largest cities in the North Caucasus, Grozny is a
sprawling settlement. Russian officials said that as many as
several thousand militants occupy the city and are fighting from
cellars and well-fortified positions along the Russian routes of
advance. Thousands of civilians still inhabit the city,
complicating the Russian attack.
</P>
<P>
   Russian troops have sought to penetrate the city from the north,
east and west. However, unlike the earlier war in Chechnya, from
1994 to 1996, the Russian military is not rushing vulnerable
armored columns into the city. That war ended badly for the Russian
military, with de facto independence for the Chechens.
</P>
<P>
   Russian armored personnel carriers and tanks found it difficult
to maneuver through Grozny's streets during that conflict. Chechen
rebels would typically attack the first and last armored vehicle in
a column, trapping the rest of the formation. Then they would
destroy the vehicles with grenades.
</P>
<P>
   So this time the Russian military is using different tactics.
Tanks and armored personnel carriers are largely used on the city's
outskirts, where there are none of the multistory houses that are
convenient hiding places for the militants.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Russian artillery and warplanes have carried out a
withering barrage of suspected rebel positions. Then Interior
Ministry troops and soldiers have moved into the city, checking
each building for rebels and arms.
</P>
<P>
   The new approach, however, has not produced a speedy
breakthrough. The Russian military did not allow Russian television
crews and Western reporters to observe the fighting in Grozny
Thursday, and accounts of the Russian offensive there are
fragmentary.
</P>
<P>
   After several days of fighting, however, there was still no
confirmation that Russian forces had established control of Minutka
square, close to the center of Grozny.
</P>
<P>
   Fighting was reported at a bridge over the Sunzha River, which
bisects the city. Russian authorities said they had seized the
bridge, which the militants used to supply their units and for
communications, two days ago.
</P>
<P>
   Grozny is a ruin, with wrecked apartment houses covered by a
pall of black smoke, observers and officials said here.
</P>
<P>
   Russian authorities insist their casualties are minimal: four
killed and four wounded for the last 24 hours. But many soldiers
believe the official statistics grievously understate actual
losses.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels reported on their web site that they lost 45 fighters
over three days. That, too, is probably an understatement, but it
is considerably higher than previously acknowledged rebel losses,
reflecting the intensity of the recent fighting.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Malofeyev was born in Nakhodka in the Russian Far East. He
graduated from Frunze, one of Russia's premier military academies
and then served in the Leningrad military district.
</P>
<P>
   The general participated in the first Chechen war. And in
October 1999, he was transferred to the Northern Caucasus as Russia
stepped up its military campaign against the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Officials here provided conflicting accounts of what might have
happened to Malofeyev. According to one account, he was with the
245th Motorized Infantry Regiment in a neighborhood in the Western
outskirts of the capital. Malofeyev was hiding in a building with
some officers and soldiers when the unit was attacked by militants,
and the general later failed to return.
</P>
<P>
   Another account holds that Malofeyev was shot when he found
himself trapped in a rebel crossfire as he sought to rally his
troops, who were lying on the ground because of the fierce fire.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, the general's disappearance was an embarrassing
setback for the Russian military and illustrated the grave dangers
for Russian troops in Chechnya. It was not the only example.
</P>
<P>
   Nikolai Koshman, the Russian vice minister who administers the
Russian-controlled areas of Chechnya, recently moved his
headquarters from the Russian military base here, several miles
northwest of Chechnya, to Gudermes, Chechnya's second largest city.
</P>
<P>
   A Russian official said Thursday night that one of the convoys
of trucks that moved Koshman's headquarters was shot at along the
way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
