<HEADER>
A1586 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-HISPANIC-HEALTH-HNS &LR;      01-20 0548
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HISPANIC-HEALTH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HISPANIC BUSINESS LEADERS CALL FOR BETTER HEALTH CARE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By JUDY HOLLAND   
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hispanic business leaders on Thursday urged
Congress to approve pending legislation that they said would
improve health care for low-income workers and small businesses.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference in the Capitol, the Hispanic Business
Roundtable released a January telephone survey of 1,000 Hispanic
adults in California, Florida, New York and Texas, in which
one-third said they have no health insurance, mainly because their
employers didn't provide it.
</P>
<P>
   That is consistent with recent U.S. Census Bureau statistics
showing 34 percent of Hispanics are uninsured, compared to only 12
percent of non-Hispanic whites.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, conducted by QEV Analytics Inc., a Washington public
opinion research firm, also showed that 89 percent of those
surveyed believe that Congress's highest priority on health care
should be making health insurance more available and affordable for
the uninsured.
</P>
<P>
   The study also showed that 33 percent of respondents said access
to quality health care was a ``serious'' problem. The survey has a
margin of error of 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether it's access to affordable health care insurance or
access to more choices and prescription drug coverage for
low-income seniors, Hispanics want Congress to act,'' said Robert
G. Deposada, executive director of the Hispanic Business
Roundtable. ``Failure to do so could energize a massive turnout
against congressional incumbents in fall elections.''
</P>
<P>
   Deposada said only 38 percent of Hispanics working in
small-to-medium size companies have health insurance compared to 63
percent for non-Hispanic white workers. That's because Hispanic
workers are heavily concentrated in the service industry and in
smaller businesses that can't afford to offer health benefits, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The business roundtable announced its support for this
legislation in Congress:
</P>
<P>
   _ The Fair Care for the Uninsured Act, sponsored by House
Majority Leader Richard K. Armey, R-Texas, which would create tax
credits of $1,000 for individuals and $3,000 for families to buy
private health insurance. This is for uninsured workers who do not
have access to employer-based health plans. The study showed 80
percent of Hispanics surveyed support Armey's legislation.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Medicare Preservation and Improvement Act, sponsored by
Sens. John B. Breaux, D-La., Bill Frist, R-Tenn., Chuck Hagel,
R-Neb., and J. Robert Kerrey, D-Neb., which would provide a
prescription drug benefit through Medicare for low-income seniors
and allow beneficiaries to choose among competing health-care
plans.
</P>
<P>
   The study showed 86 percent of Hispanics surveyed said they
support this legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The survey also showed that Hispanics believe the most important
health-care problems in their communities are the rising cost of
health care, fixing the Medicare system and getting better access
to quality care.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly there is no urgency in the Hispanic community to pass
the so-called Patients Bill of Rights,'' Deposada said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Judy Holland can be reached at 202-298-6920 or via e-mail:
judy(at)hearstdc.com
</P>
</TEXT>
