<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, Jan. 21, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A powerful storm south of Nova Scotia will draw bitter arctic
chill into the Northeastern states. Winds from the northwest will
gust frequently over 30 miles an hour from the central Appalachians
to the coast. Periods of snow will gradually taper off Friday
morning near the southern New England coast, but the piercing winds
will produce widespread blowing and drifting snow. Wind-driven snow
will continue to fall in parts of eastern Maine through the day.
Farther west, the interior Northeast will have variable clouds with
some snow showers, especially near the eastern Great Lakes and over
the hilly terrain. Overnight, winds will gradually diminish across
the interior where temperatures will plunge below zero in many
areas.
</P>
<P>
   The Southeast will be dry and chilly as high pressure moves
eastward across the region. Onshore winds will develop near the
western Gulf of Mexico coast resulting in an expanding area of low
clouds and a bit of drizzle near the southern Texas coast. The
clouds will spread into the southern Mississippi Valley overnight
as a disturbance from the Rockies draws moist air from the Gulf of
Mexico northward.
</P>
<P>
   Snow will be common along many west-facing mountain slopes from
northern California to the central and northern Rockies as moist,
vigorous high-level winds persist. Locally heavy snow will occur in
the mountain of Utah and Colorado as well as over the southern
Cascades and northern Sierra. Farther north in the Pacific
Northwest, generally light coastal rain and mountain snow will
occur.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Bomb
</P>
<P>
   Thunderstorms erupted off the North Carolina coast Thursday,
offering the classic signature of a very rapidly developing low
pressure system. Storms that explosively intensify along the East
Coast in winter are called ``bombs'' by forecasters. The fuel for
such explosive storms is moist, mild air that overlies the tepid
waters of the Gulf Stream. The match used for detonation is
typically an upper-level disturbance, which vigorously lifts mild,
moist ocean air. Computer simulations project the low to approach
Nova Scotia on Friday evening as a storm as powerful as a
Category-3 hurricane. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
