<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1588 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-THEATRICAL-WRITER-ART     01-20 1283
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATRICAL-WRITER-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PHONE RINGS AND A CREATIVE PARTNERSHIP BEGINS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT 2 and 3 are being sent. Non-subscribers can
purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One afternoon about three years ago, Claudia Shear
got the type of call young writers dream about.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember it perfectly,'' she said recently, beaming. ``I'm
standing in my kitchen making beans, and the phone rings. I picked
it up, and someone said, `Hi, this is James Lapine.' It was one of
the great moments of my life.
</P>
<P>
   ``And he said, `How are you?' And I said, `Surprised.'''
</P>
<P>
   Thus began a most unlikely creative partnership, between Lapine,
the respected Broadway director and writer, and Ms. Shear, the
manic comic actress whose autobiographical play, ``Blown Sideways
Through Life,'' became an unexpected Off Broadway hit in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The result of their three-year collaboration is ``Dirty
Blonde,'' an affectionate look at the lives of Mae West and two of
her most ardent admirers. The play opened to favorable reviews last
week at the New York Theater Workshop, where it has been extended
until Feb. 13. The producers are mulling a move to a larger
theater.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways the story of the play's development fits into the
classic mold of the theatrical process: the germ of an idea, a
writer's obsession, workshops, rehearsals, an opening. But in the
case of ``Dirty Blonde,'' many of the elements were decidedly
unorthodox.
</P>
<P>
   The concept for the play, for instance, came not from Ms. Shear,
the playwright, but from Lapine, the director, who had, in turn,
been inspired by a magazine article. Unusual, too, was the play's
financial support, a combination of development money from the
Shubert Organization, Broadway's biggest theater owner, with
performing space and other creative support provided by the
nonprofit theater workshop. The project's most peculiar element was
the teaming of Lapine and Ms. Shear.
</P>
<P>
   In one corner was Lapine, a mellow perfectionist with an
admittedly short attention span and a professor's love of
structure. In the other was Ms. Shear, a self-proclaimed
``whiner-weeper'' with a ravenous appetite for trivia, whose
cut-and-paste creative process is part art, part Cuisinart.
</P>
<P>
   While Lapine writes his notes on a special pad, Ms. Shear is
prone to bringing in ideas scribbled on lunch bags, candy wrappers,
even her palms. Lapine speaks quietly; Ms. Shear does not. He calls
her Claudia, she calls him Lapine.
</P>
<P>
   It is a relationship that Ms. Shear variously described as
teacher to student, veteran to rookie and sometimes adult to child.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have parents who spend tens of thousands of dollars a
year to send their kids to graduate school,'' she said. ``I just
got Lapine.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not a completely bump-free process. Hundreds of pages of
dialogue were written and trashed. Characters were created and
killed off. At least one title and one fully designed set were
dumped in the weeks leading up to opening night.
</P>
<P>
   In a play about obsession, there was more than a little creative
obsessing going on. Ms. Shear, for instance, said she became
fixated on the word ``good,'' as in West's quip, ``When I'm good,
I'm very good, but when I'm bad, I'm better.'' Other fixations
included Ms. Shear's love of mirrors and the lives of turn-of-the
century bad girls.
</P>
<P>
   Lapine was less concerned with the facts and figures of West's
life. (``I don't really like to know a lot,'' he said
matter-of-factly.) But he admitted to a few preoccupations of his
own, including the play's final image, two characters in a kiss, a
tableau that he said came to him early, and that he never let go.
</P>
<P>
   Those who were privy to the rehearsal process say Lapine was
also highly protective of Ms. Shear's writing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was pretty intensely James and Claudia meeting,
with periodic telephone reports,'' said James Nicola, the artistic
director of the New York Theater Workshop. ``And the great thing
about Claudia is that she knows who to listen to.''
</P>
<P>
   It all apparently worked out fine. An audience came; the critics
applauded. It wound up with a kiss.
</P>
<P>
   In the beginning ``Dirty Blonde'' could have been a musical. In
November 1996 Lapine was approached by Scott Shukat, a theatrical
agent, who wanted Lapine and his friend Alan Menken, the composer,
to consider developing a musical based on West's life. The idea,
Lapine said, had come from an article in The New Yorker by Claudia
Roth Pierpont.
</P>
<P>
   Menken wasn't interested. But Lapine was still intrigued, and in
a moment of inspiration he thought of Ms. Shear, a performer and
writer who might be able to do double duty on the project, both
behind the typewriter and in front of an audience.
</P>
<P>
   So he called her.
</P>
<P>
   He also spoke to Dessie Moynihan, director of creative projects
at the Shubert Organization, where Lapine keeps an office and has
an assistant. Ms. Moynihan agreed to provide enhancement money for
the project.
</P>
<P>
   A month later _ Ms. Shear said it felt like six months _ she met
with Lapine and Ms. Moynihan at a restaurant in Chelsea to talk
through the piece.
</P>
<P>
   Almost nothing was set. Lapine had an image of a male Mae (a man
in drag) and a female Mae. And that kiss. He also envisioned a
two-person cast. Beyond that, it was all up to Ms. Shear's
imagination.
</P>
<P>
   She said she already knew a little about West from prior
obsessions she had had with the comedian Buster Keaton and the Marx
Brothers but as she began reading biographies of West _ nine of
them _ her opinion of the woman began to grow.
</P>
<P>
   Fed by the image of West as a ``tough girl,'' which would become
the piece's working title, Ms. Shear dug into histories of other
female performers ahead of their time. She did research on
vaudeville and read the work of Damon Runyon and Ring Lardner. She
discovered little-known characters in West's life, like Ed Hearn, a
female impersonator, and Joe Frisco, a vaudevillian who was the
only comic West regularly quoted (besides herself, of course).
</P>
<P>
   All of which, Ms. Shear said, also informed her knowledge of
obsession as a concept itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing interesting about obsession is that when you become
obsessed, you don't just become obsessed with the person, you
become obsessed with everything around it,'' she said. ``You eat so
much of the main course that you're looking at the periphery, at
the tiny side dishes, because nothing is enough.''
</P>
<P>
   As Lapine worked on other projects, including the plays ``The
Diary of Anne Frank'' and ``Golden Child,'' Ms. Shear began
writing, sitting at the kitchen table in her Brooklyn apartment and
churning out reams of material. Early on, most of it took the form
of monologues or dramatizations of real events, almost all to do
solely with West. Ms. Shear periodically showed snippets of what
she had written to Lapine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of great because I didn't have to show anybody
anything,'' she said. ``All I had to do was spend days and days and
days alone with little gloves on, going to archives, or sitting
alone in my apartment watching the same movie 75 times. And then I
would get together with Lapine and rant about Mae West, and he'd
nod politely.''
</P>
<P>
   Diligently Lapine would pore over the drafts, marking notes in
the margins in red pen. More often than not he wrote, ``No.'' Once,
only once, Ms. Shear said, there was a smiley face.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not the encouraging sort,'' Lapine said, dryly. ``But the
great thing about Claudia is that she's so prolific. Sometimes she
would write a whole monologue, and I'd find one line, and she'd
take that and run with it.''
nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   In one case Lapine underlined a line referring to Frisco's
helping West into her car for dinner at a Chinese restaurant.
Although Lapine nixed the car scene, the resulting scene Ms. Shear
wrote about the restaurant remains.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   In late 1997 Ms. Shear turned in her most complete draft of the
play to date. She was extremely nervous. ``I had to call Paul
Rudnick to talk me down,'' she said, referring to her friend and
fellow playwright. ``I somehow knew.''
</P>
<P>
   In December she went to Lapine's apartment on the Upper West
Side. The two sat near the window, overlooking Central Park. Lapine
was straightforward.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `You have to write in your own voice,''' Ms. Shear
recalled. ``And I broke into tears.''
</P>
<P>
   Her fear, Ms. Shear said, was of repeating herself. ``Blown
Sideways,'' after all, had been autobiographical, very much in her
own voice. Who, she thought, wanted more of that?
</P>
<P>
   I do, Lapine said.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it was realizing why I wanted her to do it,'' he said.
``When she started writing the Mae West play, well, anybody could
do that, so why you? She had to write the Claudia Shear Mae West
play.''
</P>
<P>
   What that meant in practical terms was the enhancement of two
modern-day characters to act as counterpoint to the historical
scenes with West: Charlie, the male lead, and Jo, a none-too-veiled
stand-in for Ms. Shear.
</P>
<P>
   The first scene Ms. Shear wrote after that December meeting was
the real story of visiting Ms. West's grave in Cypress Hills,
Queens. It remains the first monologue in the show.
</P>
<P>
   For Charlie, Lapine brought in the actor Kevin Chamberlin, with
whom he had worked on a failed musical project called ``Muscle''
several years before. What was the pitch?
</P>
<P>
   ``When we first started to work on it, James kept saying, `It's
weird, I want it weird,''' Chamberlin said. ``So I'm looking at it,
and it's so weird that I'm gravitating toward it.''
</P>
<P>
   Originally Ms. Shear conceived of Charlie as a gay drag queen
and, not surprisingly, did some obsessive research on the topic.
The deeper she went, however, the more she wanted the character to
be romantically interested in Jo, an idea that Lapine did not
immediately trust.
</P>
<P>
   The two fought over the topic, with Ms. Shear prevailing because
of what Lapine called the Stephen Sondheim principle: ``Whoever
cares most, wins.'' (Lapine should know. He was Sondheim's
collaborator on ``Sunday in the Park With George'' and other
shows.)
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Shear also continued to weave real biographical detail into
her characters. One afternoon, while sitting with Chamberlin, she
noticed a series of small, white scars on his knuckles. ``Where did
those come from?'' she asked. Wrestling, he replied. Thus, Charlie
became a wrestler.
</P>
<P>
   For his part Lapine began arranging the scenes into a cohesive
narrative, weaving the story of West's life with that of the
budding romance of Jo and Charlie. For this he relied on index
cards.
</P>
<P>
   On a big table in a boardroom at the Shubert Organization,
Lapine began to piece together the structure, using different
colored cards for each character and short descriptions of their
action. (``Jo goes to the library,'' for instance.) Where there
were narrative gaps, Lapine put a blank white card.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Shear had no idea what Lapine was doing. ``He said, `What do
you think?''' she said. ``I said, `Well, it looks nice.'''
</P>
<P>
   He told her to keep writing.
</P>
<P>
   By the summer of 1998 the cast was set: Ms. Shear, Chamberlin
and Bob Stillman, who was to play a number of smaller roles.
Together they traveled to Martha's Vineyard to put a rough version
of the piece on its feet. They stayed at Lapine's house _ clam
bakes included _ and they rehearsed in the music room of a local
elementary school. (Ms. Shear remembered a dirty carpet and music
primers.)
</P>
<P>
   After a week's rehearsal they presented the first public
performance at the Vineyard Playhouse, a workshop production
financed by the Shuberts. There were almost no costumes and a
less-than-packed house. Still, Ms. Shear said, ``it was like one of
those sci-fi movies where they have the organism and grow something
around it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't fully formed, and it couldn't go out on its own,''
she said. ``But it was alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Lapine was slightly more analytical.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we discovered about it at Martha's Vineyard was that it
was very expositional,'' he said. ``There was a lot of standing and
talking to the audience. It wasn't theatrical. It was like watching
`Biography.'''
</P>
<P>
   So the order came down: Take out all the exposition. If it
cannot be expressed through action or conversation, cut it. Gone
were dozens of little things _ West's biggest salary, her biggest
flop _ that Ms. Shear had obsessed about.
</P>
<P>
   Nicola, who had seen the show on Martha's Vineyard, set a
production date for the New York premiere: the first preview would
be on Dec. 12, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   As the date approached, the intensity of work increased.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of centrifugal,'' Lapine said. ``As you get closer
and closer to the moment, it becomes clearer and clearer what
needed to be done to pull it together.''
</P>
<P>
   That clarity of thought can be painful, though. One such
occasion occurred just days before rehearsals were to begin in
November.
</P>
<P>
   During a final presentation of design elements, Lapine said he
was staring at an elaborate set design made up of dozens of
different curtains when he suddenly felt a thick lump in his
stomach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Can everybody leave the room, please?''' Lapine said,
still wincing a little at the thought. ``It was one of those
horrible moments where you're sitting looking at something and
thinking, `Just be brave and throw it out.'''
</P>
<P>
   They did. A new design, a simple pink box with a curtain in
front and one behind, was built instead.
</P>
<P>
   The delicate act of tinkering continued through rehearsals and
into previews. Inspiration came from unlikely sources. A mink head
muff Ms. Shear wore in the theater one day worked its way onstage.
(You'll know it when you see it.)
</P>
<P>
   Just after Christmas Lapine conducted a four-hour rehearsal with
his cast, an afternoon of creative microsurgery: cutting a line
here, timing blackout there, suggesting a change in an actor's
cadence. It is a strange science, directors will tell you, toying
with the tiny elements that can make a show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes those little things,'' Lapine said, ``those little
pieces of direction, a little line or a little word, can pull a
whole show together.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a process that was not complete until the week the
critics came, when a flurry of cuts shortened the play by 10
minutes. One moment cut out was the first scene Ms. Shear had
written, more than two years before, depicting a young woman
seducing her teacher. ``I loved that scene,'' Ms. Shear said.
</P>
<P>
   On opening night, after the show, as the reviews came in, Ms.
Shear held court in an East Village restaurant as her admirers
swarmed. Lapine had left early.
</P>
<P>
   Several days later the two got together again, to discuss how
``Dirty Blonde'' came to be. As Lapine sat and smiled, Ms. Shear
got in the last word.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a line for James in the play,'' she said, ``where Mae
says: `I got all the pieces together. You can read it right now.' I
wrote that for James.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
