<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BOXER PLANS TO TAP INTERNET FOR HER PAC 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By JUDY HOLLAND   
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. Barbara Boxer launched a website Thursday for
her political action committee that she hopes will raise $1 million
for House and Senate Democrats to help her party win a majority in
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Boxer said she decided to create the ``PAC for a Change''
because she has realized ``we can't change the world the way we
want to unless we have more Democrats in both houses.''
</P>
<P>
   She said her so-called leadership PAC is the first of its kind
to focus on fundraising for candidates in both chambers.
</P>
<P>
   Boxer said she has already raised more than $415,000 for other
candidates by calling supporters. She said she expects that
launching the new site _ www.changethecongress.com _ will enable
her to raise more without spending money on costly mailings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a following and I'm happy and willing to share it with
those who share my agenda,'' Boxer told reporters. She said she
thinks Internet fund-raising ``is the wave of the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal election laws limit to $10,000 the amount of money that
a political action committee can contribute to an individual
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Boxer said she plans to donate the $10,000 maximum to at least
20 Democratic candidates in tight races, including Hillary Clinton,
who is running for a New York Senate seat, and Sen. Dianne
Feinstein, D-Calif., who is up for re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Boxer is also helping such California House candidates as state
Sen. Adam Schiff who is challenging Rep. Jim Rogan, a Republican;
Jane Harman, a former member of Congress who wants to reclaim her
old seat from Republican Rep. Steve Kuykendall; and Susan Davis, a
state assemblywoman who is challenging Republican Rep. Brian
Bilbray.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're harnessing the power of the Internet to fundamentally
change the Congress,'' Boxer said. ``Not only will people be able
to make a donation, they will be able to get information and get
involved.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a great opportunity to take back the Congress this
year and put it back on the side of the people,'' Boxer said. ``The
current Republican Congress is out-of-step with mainstream America
and it's time for a change.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans outnumber Democrats 55 to 45 in the Senate and 222
to 212, with one independent, in the House
</P>
<P>
   The website includes descriptions of Republican positions on
issues such as abortion and shows the faces of GOP chairmen
morphing into the faces of Democrats who would occupy the positions
if the Democrats won control.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Judy Holland can be reached at 202-298-6920 or by e-mail at
Judy(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
