<HEADLINE>
BUSH CALLS ROE VS. WADE ABORTION RULING A CONSTITUTIONAL `REACH' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PELLA, Iowa _ Fighting for support Thursday from socially
conservative Iowa Republicans, George W. Bush defended himself
against a rival's charge that he is a ``pro-life pacifist'' and
declared that the 1972 Supreme Court ruling legalizing abortion was
a constitutional ``reach.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Roe vs. Wade was a reach, overstepped the constitutional
bounds as far as I'm concerned,'' Bush told a news conference in
his strongest anti-abortion comments so far in his presidential
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But the Texas governor still refused to say whether as president
he would appoint Supreme Court justices who would overturn Roe vs.
Wade. GOP presidential rivals Gary Bauer and Steve Forbes have
criticized Bush for refusing to join them in a promise to appoint
justices dedicated to outlawing abortion.
</P>
<P>
   A day earlier, Forbes called the landmark ruling ``an
out-of-date injustice supported by the flimsiest of scientific
prejudices. It must be reversed, and it will take a principled,
activist Republican president _ not a pro-life pacifist afraid to
offend _ devoted to the rights of the unborn to start the
process.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also said Thursday he would oppose U.S. Food and Drug
Administration approval of the RU-486 abortion pill. The FDA is in
the final stages of approving the drug that can end a pregnancy up
to seven weeks after contraception.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be inclined not to accept that ruling by the FDA. It's
abortion,'' said Bush, but he refused to say whether a Bush
administration would rescind RU-486 authorization. ``That's too
hypothetical.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he would appoint ``strict constructionists'' to the
Supreme Court, justices who would not use the Constitution to
legislate. Bush said Forbes does not understand his record as Texas
governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been a pro-life governor,'' Bush said. ``I've got a
record of adoption, promoted adoptions in the state of Texas,
signed a parental notification law, promoted abstinence education.
I've got a good strong record.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush grew testy when reporters asked him whether members of his
family agree with his abortion views. He said he could not remember
the last time he discussed the issue with his mother, former first
lady Barbara Bush.
</P>
<P>
   And even though he discussed the opposition of one of his
daughters to his support for the death penalty outlined in his
autobiography, he refused to say whether his twin 18-year-old
daughters backed him on abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to talk about my daughters' point of view. My
daughters are part of my private life,'' Bush said. ``That
(autobiography reference) is an example of something, but I'm not
going to talk about my daughters in the course of the campaign. I
appreciate you respecting their privacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he would tell a friend who became pregnant by rape,
Bush said, ``That's up to her.'' Bush supports abortion rights in
cases of rape or incest or to protect the mother's life.
</P>
<P>
   Bush holds a major lead in Iowa public opinion polls, and he is
predicting that he will break Bob Dole's 1988 record by getting
more than 37 percent of the turnout Monday. But he admitted that
overconfidence among his supporters could leave him with a
``less-than-expectations'' finish if they do not show up at their
caucus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes victory does not mean victory. I hope it does in my
case,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has been pushing hard to win the support of social
conservatives, who in past elections have distrusted the sincerity
of his father, former President Bush, on their issues.
</P>
<P>
   At least some are sold on the Texas governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the scandals that have been going on, we know that won't
happen with him,'' said Coletta Ivy, 47 of Dubuque, Iowa. ``It's
his morals, honey.''
</P>
<P>
   One flier that Bush is distributing in Iowa plays to social
conservatives by indirectly criticizing President Clinton's sex
scandals.
</P>
<P>
   ``A champion for families...'' the Bush flier declares above a
photograph of Bush walking down a street with his wife, Laura.
``who will restore dignity and honor to the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   In an open letter inside the flier, Bush speaks of his religious
faith as a foundation for his politics, noting his personal
relationship with Billy Graham.
</P>
<P>
   ``My faith frees me; frees me to put the problems of the moment
improper perspective; frees me to make decisions that others might
not like,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   The flier touts support from the National Right to Life
Committee and the fact that National Abortion Rights Action League
``is already attacking him in TV ads.''
</P>
<P>
   But at a Des Moines citizen-question session at the Principal
Financial Group, Bush refused to be drawn into an in-depth
criticism of Clinton's actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``My opponent is not going to be the president. My opponent, if
I am the nominee,and I'm taking nothing for granted, either one of
the two Democrats,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I, like a lot of people, was embarrassed for our country, but
it's time to get over that embarrassment and head to the 21st
century carrying a positive message that is hopeful and
optimistic,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
