<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1605 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-SKI-N-SHOP-2TAKES-NYT     01-20 1169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKI-N-SHOP-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEEKEND EXCURSION: TO SCHUSS, TO SHOP 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Addresses, hours and other information at end of 2nd take.) 
(lh) 
 By RALPH BLUMENTHAL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Zermatt it's not. It's not Vail or even Stratton, its tonier
neighbor in the Green Mountains of southern Vermont. But Bromley, a
four-hour drive north of New York City, offers congenial family
skiing and snowboarding with a bonus: proximity to the outlet mecca
of Manchester Center with its designer shops of discounted Giorgio
Armani, Calvin Klein, Gianni Versace, Dansk, Godiva and other
haut-branded fashions, housewares and edibles. In short, all the
makings for a perfect ``ski 'n' shop'' excursion.
</P>
<P>
   The danger, of course, aside from flying down a snow-slick hill
with long slippery things on your feet, is all too clear. Combining
the already luxe sport of skiing with recreational shopping a mere
six miles away is really asking for it. And trying to placate an
antsy, ski-blitzed child while combing the racks for bargains is a
double-diamond challenge all its own. I suspected we had gone too
far when, during our second foray to the shops after a morning on
the slopes, our 9-year-old daughter, Sophie, inquired from the back
seat, ``Is Kenneth Cole alive?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' my wife, Debbie, answered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is Calvin Klein alive?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Is Cole Haan alive?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Cole Haan isn't a person, dear, it's a store.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Is Anne Klein alive?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why not?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know. She's not.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Is Calvin Klein related to Anne Klein?'' I couldn't stand it.
``Stop!'' I yelled. ``What does it matter?''
</P>
<P>
   Even for die-hard skiers and shoppers, the trip to Bromley
requires an extended weekend, especially factoring in worthwhile
stops en route like Bennington's Potters Yard and the Bennington
Museum, which displays the largest public collection of works by
Grandma Moses in an 1834 schoolhouse she once attended.
</P>
<P>
   We took four days, beginning on Christmas, that we had arranged
weeks earlier fully confident that the season would see Vermont
cloaked in winter white. Alas, there was no snow, dooming Debbie's
hopes of cross-country skiing. But as we pulled up to the base of
Bromley Mountain (elevation: 3,284 feet) on Route 11 in Peru, we
were relieved to see lifts running and the trails afluff with
man-made powder.
</P>
<P>
   After research on the Internet, we had booked three nights at
the Alpinish-looking Bromley Sun Lodge with convenient
ski-in/ski-out accessibility at a premium holiday rate of $219 a
night plus tax, including buffet breakfast. At our first view of
the pitch-roofed inn with its wooden balconies, we congratulated
ourselves, delighting, too, in the cozy lobby with a blazing hearth
and lounge with pool table. But our spirits sank as we loaded our
luggage onto a cart and made our way down a forlorn hall that cried
out for spiffing up.
</P>
<P>
   Our patio level room was a lackluster motel unit with
coral-patterned wallpaper plastered bumpily over textured stucco
walls, two less-than-firm double beds, dim lights, including an
impromptu hanging lamp, a clothes rod, a bureau with drawers that
fell out when you opened them (nice comic touch, that), a
temperamental toilet and miserable television reception. But the
room was clean, and behind a curtain, a sliding rear door opened to
crisp air and refreshing vistas of cottony slopes.
</P>
<P>
   Eager to salvage the afternoon for skiing, we walked the few
steps to the Bromley base lodge, where we rented skis, boots and
poles and bought half-day lift tickets, available on weekend and
holiday afternoons. The holiday had kept the crowds down, so there
were no lines at the counters and no lines outside for the lifts.
We started tentatively on some of the easier runs and soon were
taking the swift quadruple chair to the wind-blown summit, which
offered one particularly easy descent for a fervent snowplower like
Sophie, who often beat me down to the bottom, zigzagging around
nonplussed snow-boarders.
</P>
<P>
   We took a couple of warming breaks in the base lodge, which
offered a congested cafeteria and the rather quieter Wild Boar
Tavern and deli, the requisite cheery fireplace and a well-stocked
ski shop. When the sun dipped behind the mountain, we skied over to
the Sun Lodge and stowed our gear in a convenient storage room.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Lodge advertised an indoor heated pool, and Sophie
couldn't wait to take a dip before dinner. Well, there was a pool
and it was heated, or, rather, warmed, but in the phosphorescent
gloom of weak lighting it looked decidedly uninviting. Clammy used
towels scattered over some of the chairs didn't add to the allure.
But several families were splashing around in the shallow water,
and we joined in, Sophie warily avoiding a far corner enveloped in
dark shadows. Outside the windows, the lights glistened merrily off
the remade snow.
</P>
<P>
   Passing up dinner at the hotel, we had made reservations for an
extravagant holiday buffet ($50 per adult and $22 for children) at
the Equinox, the renowned 230-year-old resort and spa on 2,300
acres in Manchester Village, which among others things, offers
schools for off-road Land Rover driving and falconry.
</P>
<P>
   Driving on-road in a Buick from Avis (and darned, if we hadn't
left our falcon at home), we made the Equinox in about 15 minutes,
scouting, as we whizzed past, Mikasa, J. Crew, Escada, Baccarat,
Donna Karan, Orvis and many of the other outlets on Routes 11 and
30 and 7A that we were determined to explore later.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the white-columned Equinox, we stepped into a Ralph
Lauren world of burnished wood, crackling fireplaces, swagged
drapes and trophy cases, a veritable Yankee Versailles. In a nook
by a fire, two girls in black velvet dresses and red hair were
getting their portraits drawn.
</P>
<P>
   We were seated in the Colonnade Room, a confection of maroon
Wedgwood and cut-glass chandeliers where a pianist serenaded, and
left to forage among the Lucullan splendor: tureens of shrimp
bisque and eggnog soup, platters of snow crab legs, raw oysters and
unpeeled shrimp on beds of seaweed, breads, fruit, pates, cold
cuts, chafing dishes of salmon with creamed oysters, spinach
ravioli, roast turkey, goose with red cabbage and a carving block
with sliced prime rib.
</P>
<P>
   Sophie returned to the table with a croissant, a $22 croissant.
We made her go back for some turkey, if only in armament against
the onslaught of desserts: pies, cakes, cookies, fudge, cherries,
kumquats, warm trifles and mint chocolate puddings.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing like a big evening feast to stimulate a
morning's appetite, and by breakfast we were ready for our own
hotel's substantial buffet: scrambled eggs and bacon, potatoes,
French toast, pancakes, melon, grapefruit, muffins, juice and
coffee. Fortified, we returned to the gear room, donned our boots
and headed to the lifts, which were once again blessedly free of
crowds. By midday we had made over a dozen runs and burned the
excess calories.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
