<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1606 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-BRADLEY-IOWA-HNS &LR;      01-20 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-IOWA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BRADLEY `UPBEAT' ABOUT IOWA CAUCUSES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAN FREEDMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ Battling overwhelming poll numbers and his
own comments dismissive of the upcoming Iowa caucuses, former Sen.
Bill Bradley put a brighter face on his presidential campaign
Thursday, saying he is ``upbeat'' about his chances here against
Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   With Bradley campaign leaders in 1,000 of 2,100 election
precincts holding caucuses Monday night, ``the real question is who
will actually show up,'' the candidate told reporters. ``We're
feeling good about what we've accomplished.''
</P>
<P>
   The former senator from New Jersey has been dogged by polls
showing he trails Gore by 20 points in Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley himself sought to lower expectations this week by saying
he would feel good if he captured 31 percent of the Democratic
caucus vote _ the same result Sen. Edward Kennedy of Massachusetts
achieved in his 1980 bid against President Jimmy Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley went a step further Wednesday evening in New Hampshire,
where he is running even with or ahead of Gore, calling Iowa ``a
state that rewards entrenched power.'' Talking to reporters after a
meeting Thursday with some 100 senior citizens at a swing-era dance
hall, Bradley reiterated how he believed ``entrenched power'' is
``what we're dealing with'' in Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Gore enjoys the support of most prominent Democrats in the
state, including Sen. Tom Harkin, as well as organized labor. With
100,000 members _ about half of them registered Democrats _ labor
could bring out as much as a tenth of the total Democrat vote on
caucus night.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's comments about ``entrenched power'' suggested he was
blowing off the Iowa caucuses, a process in which each party holds
precinct-by-precinct meetings for the purpose of selecting a
presidential nominee. The caucus votes are several steps removed
from the actual delegate-selection process in Iowa, but they have
symbolic value as the first voting exercise in the 2000
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire holds the nation's first primary on Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley went out of his way to deny he intended any disrespect
for the Iowa caucuses. ``The reason I'm in the Iowa caucuses is
that I respect the people of Iowa,'' Bradley said. ``And the reason
I've been here 30, 35 times is that I respect the people of Iowa.''
</P>
<P>
   Countering Gore's support among union leaders and the party
establishment will require some luck and skill in bringing out
``people who have not been a part of the process before,'' Bradley
said. ``Hopefully (they) are going to turn out for caucuses. I'm
upbeat about this, quite frankly.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said some Iowa voters ``might have been swayed'' by Gore
television ads characterizing Bradley's $55-billion-to-$65-billion
health plan as too costly and dangerous to poor families. ``But
we're countering that now.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Bradley said, he has no illusions about Gore's power. The
vice president spent Thursday campaigning in western Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is that when somebody has support of the president
of the United States ... as well as most Democratic Party
fund-raisers, has the backing of the leadership of organized labor
and rides on Air Force 2, that's entrenched power.''
</P>
<P>
   Compared to New Hampshire where he is doing much better against
Gore, Iowa is ``a bigger state (with) more media markets (where
I'm) not as well known,'' Bradley said. We used to think it a great
success if we got 10, 11 people in a room. Now we're getting much
more than that.''
</P>
<P>
   The 100 or so senior citizens who turned out to see Bradley at
the classic Val Air Ballroom are a key ingredient in Bradley's
strategy. Many younger Iowans have gone elsewhere for jobs and
opportunity, leaving the state's population grayer than average.
</P>
<P>
   According to the American Association of Retired Persons, which
sponsored the Thursday meeting with Bradley, only Florida,
Pennsylvania and Arizona have more people age 50 and over.
</P>
<P>
   And senior citizens are politically active. According to AARP,
with 360,000 members in Iowa, 60 percent of senior citizens turn
out for the caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley appeared at ease before the group, cracking a joke about
a New Jersey diner and employing many of his stock lines, such as
his desire to be president in ``a world of new possibilities guided
by goodness.''
</P>
<P>
   On Medicare, a key issue to seniors, Bradley said the federal
health benefit for the elderly is fiscally sound until 2015 at the
earliest, and that future economic growth may extend the system's
life without federal support.
</P>
<P>
   He called Social Security a ``sacred trust'' and ``the most
successful government program in our nation's history.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that as president, he would not include the Social
Security trust fund in the overall federal budget, as the
government has done every year since 1967. Over the next 10 years,
he would pump $2 trillion into it to ensure its solvency for at
least 75 years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS. &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bradley defended his health plan as bold and visionary while
charging that Gore's more modest approach ``nibbles around the
edges.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said ``I'm convinced we're at a time in our history now
where this economic growth (will) give us enormous possibilities,
but if you are not bold you will not be able to use those
possibilities to achieve your objective.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Bradley's plan, the health insurance program for federal
employees would be expanded to include non-government workers and
the poor would receive subsidized health coverage. People with a
major illness and inadequate insurance coverage also would be
eligible for federal assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Under Gore's plan, the Clinton administration's health insurance
program for children would be expanded to include parents, and it
would be opened to children in families closer to the middle-income
range.
</P>
<P>
   Health care was not uppermost in the minds of all those who
listened to Bradley. ``I think he shows a leadership ability and a
moral fiber which I need to have in my next president,'' said Peggy
Patrick, 76, a retired art gallery administrator who spent a year
in the Peace Corps in Sierra Leone. ``If he turns in a respectable
showing here, it will help him in other states.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-00 1843EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000120.0178 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1607 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-SKI-N-SHOP-2NDTAKE-NY     01-20 1269
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKI-N-SHOP-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: excess calories.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now we were ready to exercise something else: our American
Express cards. Stop one in Manchester Center was the Giorgio Armani
General Store, where on a previous visit some years ago I had
picked up a lightweight wool tan patterned sports jacket for under
$300, less than half price. Now, post-Christmas, the stock looked
pretty well picked over. There were a few navy suits in my size,
half off at $1,000, shirts for around $50 and some ties as low as
$15 _ 75 percent off. Debbie considered a gray pantsuit, more than
half off at $800. But in the end, goaded by Sophie, who was
impatient to assault the Levi's outlet across the corridor, we
moved on.
</P>
<P>
   Next door, Brooks Brothers was selling shirts for $42 and ties
for $24 with any second item half-price. We also surveyed J.
Peterman, where clothing, housewares and shaving supplies were 25
percent off; Versace, where some rakish high-button suits were
going for about $500; and Eastern Mountain Sports, where we made
our first score: a green knitted hat for Sophie for $10, a third of
what we later saw it priced at in the Bromley ski shop.
</P>
<P>
   In Donna Karan on Route 7A South, Debbie picked out a pair of
gray slacks for $112, well off the already discounted price of
$159. In the nearby Garnet Hill shop, I succumbed to a pair of
Italian leather hiking boots for $127 ($240 in the catalog) while
Debbie bought a set of flannel bedding including duvet cover for
$84.
</P>
<P>
   We reconnoitered at adjoining Cole Haan, where leatherware,
shoes and particularly boots were substantially marked down; nearby
Dansk, where we searched in vain for some fluted glasses to
supplement a set at home; and the Seiko Co. Store, where some
self-winding watches were temptingly going for substantial
reductions below the already discounted $119 price.
</P>
<P>
   We had made reservations for dinner at another locally
recommended restaurant, Johnny Seesaw's, a quarter-mile west of
Bromley on Route 11.
</P>
<P>
   A log roadhouse remodeled in 1938 as one of the first ski lodges
in the East, it came with its own colorful legend going back to its
origins in the 1920s as the moonshine retreat of a Russian logger,
Ivan Sesow. In more recent times, it played host to annual reunions
of famous Yalies, including President Gerald Ford, Cyrus R. Vance
and Potter Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   From its look, it might still have been a Prohibition hideaway
with its ``sin cabins'' out back and a brawny circular fire pit
dominating the room of couches and rustic tables. ``I want to eat
there,'' said Sophie, pointing to a couch.
</P>
<P>
   The owner, Gary Okun, tactfully steered us in another direction.
``I have an even better table,'' he said, seating us by an aquarium
with tropical fish and positioning me with a lady on each hand _
``the thorn between two roses,'' as he put it.
</P>
<P>
   Waiting for our onion soup, salad, scallops and veal piccata,
Sophie let out a groan. ``There's nothing to do,'' she said,
jumping up to get her Game Boy from the pocket of her coat in the
vestibule.
</P>
<P>
   Back on the mountain as usual the next morning, with crowds now
starting to build, I persuaded Sophie to take a group lesson while
I set out solo and Debbie did some reading in the lodge. When the
class returned, the ski instructor looked grave. ``She doesn't turn
enough,'' she said. ``She goes down too fast.'' Sophie, however,
was beaming.
</P>
<P>
   Figuring it was time to quit while we were ahead, not to say
intact, we doffed and stowed our skis and returned to town for a
last run at the stores and a lunch of soup and salad at the Buttery
in the Jelly Mill, a foodstuff and kitchenware shop on Route 7A,
where Sophie replenished her candy supply.
</P>
<P>
   For dinner that night we scouted out another historic hostelry,
Mark Anthony's Ye Olde Tavern, dating from 1790, on Route 7A in
Manchester Village. We ate tasty smoked trout and gravy-smothered
pot roast by a roaring fire and sipped drinks out of canning jars.
</P>
<P>
   Returning our ski gear the next morning in the Bromley base
lodge proved far more chaotic than getting it. With a horde of
holiday-week schussers checking out equipment, hapless checkers-in
like us were consigned to ski-rental hell. We finally pressed the
skis, boots and poles and receipt on a harried clerk and fled. We
had to get going. There were a few last stores to hit.
</P>
<P>
   BROMLEY MOUNTAIN AND NEARBY ATTRACTIONS:
</P>
<P>
   Bromley Mountain in Vermont is about 220 miles north of New York
City. Here is a sampling of attractions in the Bromley and
Manchester areas, as well as travel information.
</P>
<P>
   SKIING:
</P>
<P>
   BROMLEY MOUNTAIN, Route 11, Peru, Vt., six miles from
Manchester, Vt. (802) 824-5522; for lodging at Bromley Village,
(800) 865-4786. Lift ticket, daily $47; $40 for ages 13 to 17; $31
for ages 7 to 12; free for ages 6 and younger. Multiple-day lift
ticket, $77; $67 for ages 13 to 17; $52 for ages 7 to 12. Daily
equipment rental, $28; $20 for children. Each additional day, $21;
$14 for children. There are also one- to four-bedroom condominiums
available for rental; a two-night stay ranges from $585 for a
one-bedroom unit to $1,010 for a four-bedroom unit.
</P>
