<SLUG> BC-FBC-SENIOR-BOWL-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL TESTS SENIORS ON MORE THAN SKILLS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By TOMMY DEAS   
 The Tuscaloosa (Ala.) News   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOBILE, Ala. _ Every day in practice this week, college
football's elite are tested in every phase of the game on the
Senior Bowl practice fields to see if their skills will make the
grade in the NFL:
</P>
<P>
   _ Blocking and tackling.
</P>
<P>
   _ Throwing and catching.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reading and reacting.
</P>
<P>
   But before they step on the field at Ladd-Peebles Stadium for
Saturday's 1:30 p.m. game, however, the 120-plus players selected
for the 51st all-star classic will have been subjected to a battery
of off-the-field tests that may be just as important in deciding
their professional futures:
</P>
<P>
   _ Intelligence tests.
</P>
<P>
   _ Personality profiles.
</P>
<P>
   _ Psychological probes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're killing us,'' said Alabama offensive tackle Chris
Samuels, who is taking part in the testing and other activities but
will miss the game with a knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   Away from the practice field and team meetings, players don't
have much time for leisure activity. They're too busy taking tests
that NFL teams use to decide who they will consider for April's NFL
draft.
</P>
<P>
   On the practice field, teams learn about football talent.
Through the off-the-field tests, they try to determine who will
best be able to master playbooks that number hundreds of pages.
They also want to learn in advance what kind of problems they may
encounter, so they can avoid drafting the next Rae Carruth or
Lawrence Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   Some teams put more stock in tests than others. There's nothing
new to the process, but it seems to get more intricate every year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something that's gone on for years,'' said Carolina
Panthers head coach George Seifert, who is coaching the North
squad. ``You just see and hear more about it now.''
</P>
<P>
   Gunther Cunningham, head coach of the Kansas City Chiefs, would
rather rely on what he can learn through direct contact with
players as head coach of the South squad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having the ability to coach in the Senior Bowl is as valuable
a tool as there is,'' he said. ``You can't get that through
psychological testing or any other kind of workout. You live with
the players for a week. You get to know them.
</P>
<P>
   ``All this testing, who creates those tests? What are they
designed to learn? How reliable are they?''
</P>
<P>
   Not all of the tests are of the mental variety. The first
official event of the Senior Bowl is the weigh-in, where players
are measured fingertip-to-fingertip and head-to-toe. They then
strip to their underwear and parade in front of hundreds of NFL
coaches and scouts eager to see their physiques without pads and
uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``And now you know what it's like to be a swimsuit model,'' said
North quarterback Giovanni Carmazzi of Hofstra. ``I don't think
there's many swimsuit models in this bunch. It's awkward. It's a
little bit weird. ``
</P>
<P>
   Players find some of the written tests just as perplexing.
</P>
<P>
   Auburn lineman Jeno James went through most of the tests
preparing for the Blue-Gray game, so he got a preview of what to
expect. He took more than a dozen tests in the week before that
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of them are true-false,'' he said. ``Some of them are
multiple choice. Some of the questions they give you are like, `If
a tree falls in the forest, do you hear it?' You wonder where some
of these questions come from.''
</P>
<P>
   The players go along whether or not they understand the reasons
for the tests.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the tests, I guess I know what they're doing,''
Samuels said. ``They're trying to find out about who you are.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the questions, I think, are silly. `Are you
good-looking?,' `Do you feel attractive?' stuff like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Another test is even more perplexing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to see how fast we could recite a couple of lines of
words,'' Alabama wideout Shamari Buchanan said. ``The words were
all colors and they were all a certain color. The word `r-e-d' was
spelled out in yellow, and so on. There were about seven words per
line and about 14 or 15 lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we came back, we had to recite the color they were
spelled out in. It was very funny just to listen to the other guys.
That's the test everybody was talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham will have access to a lot of testing data before the
draft, but he'll probably rely on personal observations.
</P>
<P>
   ``You develop personal relationships I wouldn't ever trade,'' he
said. Instead of spending money on tests, he said, ``we ought to
have about 18 of these games a year. Then you'd really know the
players.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever they think of the actual tests, players agree that
they're happy to take them. They understand it's part of the
process of making it to the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather for them to want me to take the test,'' Samuels
said, ``than for them not to want me to.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Alabama running back Shaun Alexander: ``They ask us
questions and we answer them. It's just a long process. That's
about it. I guess they should if they're going to pay you all that
money.''
</P>
<P>
   (The News in Tuscaloosa, Ala., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
