<SLUG> BC-DELTA-SURCHARGE21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delta adds $20 gas surcharge
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Even though it has avoided the brunt of jet fuel price
hikes so far, Delta Air Lines joined an industry move to add a $20
fuel surcharge to most domestic round-trip bookings.
</P>
<P>
   The move comes after fourth-quarter profits at Delta and other
carriers dropped because of higher fuel costs, driven by rising oil
prices.
</P>
<P>
   Continental initiated the surcharge, and on Thursday, Delta and
Northwest joined United and American in matching. Delta's fee took
effect immediately and is included in published fares, though it is
technically a separate charge.
</P>
<P>
   Other carriers are applying the surcharge to travel starting
Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
   AirTran Airways, Delta's primary rival in Atlanta, said it has
no plans to add the surcharge.
</P>
<P>
   Delta has been hurt less than other airlines by rising fuel
prices. It is buying most of its fuel under purchasing contracts
negotiated when prices were low.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of short-term economics, it's clearly disingenuous to
tack on a surcharge given their very effective fuel hedging
program,'' said PaineWebber analyst Sam Buttrick. ``But let's face
it, the average consumer has little insight into hedging programs.
All they hear is that fuel's gone up.''
</P>
<P>
   In its quarterly profit report, Delta said it paid an average of
53.6 cents a gallon for fuel, up 2 cents from a year earlier _ far
less than the increases at other carriers whose hedging contracts
weren't as well timed.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Delta's contracts run out later this year, but the
airline said in its profit report that they will ``continue to
limit jet fuel price volatility in fiscal 2000,'' which ends June
30.
</P>
<P>
   Delta spokesman John Kennedy said the surcharge ``is not solely
related to fuel expenses.'' Asked what other factors prompted it,
he cited ``other costs'' but declined to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Buttrick said Delta is simply taking advantage of the chance to
reap the benefits of a price hike advanced by other carriers. But
he noted that generalized increases prod travelers to shop harder
for deals, so the effect on average fares paid is often less than
carriers hope.
</P>
<P>
   The surcharge is the first of its kind since the early 1990s,
when the Gulf War drove jet fuel prices to more than $1 a gallon
and sent airline profits into a tailspin for three years.
</P>
<P>
   The recent run-up in fuel prices has fogged profit forecasts for
2000.
</P>
<P>
   Buttrick expects major airlines to collectively post flat or
reduced profits in the first and second quarters, then resume
profit growth in the second half of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's entirely conditioned on a retreat in fuel prices,'' he
added. Fuel is the second-highest expense at most airlines, after
labor.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
