<SLUG> BC-WINE-BORDEAUX-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINE SURVIVES STORMS IN BORDEAUX  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By KATHLEEN BUCKLEY   WineToday.com   c.2000 N.Y. Times News
Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BORDEAUX, France _ Bordeaux landmarks took a beating in the
region's worst storms of the 20th century, but vintners report
little wine was lost when 120-mph winds roared across Europe last
month.
</P>
<P>
   At Chateau Lafite Rothschild in the Medoc, winds snapped a
majestic cedar tree that stands tall on the label of the grand
estate. In Pomerol, the legendary ``Le Pin'' is now le matchstick.
</P>
<P>
   ``The famous tree is stripped with just one lone branch left
dangling _ luckily Jacques planted a second one a couple years ago
so we will have to rely on that,'' said Fiona Morrison Thienpont,
wife of Chateau Le Pin proprietor Jacques Thienpont.
</P>
<P>
   Chateau owners report scant damage to wines in cellars and
vines, though building damage is widespread.
</P>
<P>
   The storms hit over the Christmas holidays and New Year revelers
celebrated by candlelight with bottled water and wine served to
heavily bundled guests huddled before massive hearths, the only
heat in the 17th, 18th and 19th century stone estates.
</P>
<P>
   At Chateau Pichon Longueville Comtesse de Lalande in Pauillac,
the estate became an impromptu dormitory during a week without
power, water or telephone. Though normally an elegant museum piece
with rooms restored to a 1850s style, the chateau supplied the only
light for miles.
</P>
<P>
   At Chateau Pontet-Canet, ``the park looks like it was bombed,
most of the great cedars are on the ground'' said Pauillac neighbor
Jean-Michel Cazes, whose properties were also damaged.
</P>
<P>
   The Cazes family sustained roof damage to fermentation vat
buildings. Chateau Pichon Longueville, Chateau Ormes, Chateau
Cantenac-Brown and the Michel Lynch brand warehouse _ estates that
Cazes manages for the giant AXA insurance company _ also sustained
serious, but reparable, building damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The disaster can be seen in the park where the damages are
heartbreaking,'' Cazes said of Cantenac-Brown. ``An impressive
number of trees fell and, unfortunately, among them, several big
beautiful cedars.''
</P>
<P>
   A few miles away in Saint-Julien, only a few trees surrounding
Chateau Talbot survived; the landscape has totally changed.
Historically, fir trees were planted around the chateaux to protect
them from wind and to soften the barren winter landscape of the
vast Medoc vineyards. Many of the trees were more than 100 years
old.
</P>
<P>
   A few wine cellars were flooded in the Blaye region when dikes
broke, threatening the core of a nuclear reactor across the Gironde
river from Pauillac in the Medoc. Vineyards, dormant at this time
of year, were unscathed except in isolated patches where trees fell
onto vines or where flood water damaged trellises.
</P>
<P>
   In central Bordeaux, stone parapets fell from the towers of the
Cathedral of St. Andre, the city's central park sustained severe
tree damage and some flooding was reported, but within days the
streets had returned to normal.
</P>
<P>
   The storms hit hardest from the northern reaches of the Medoc,
felling hundreds of thousands of fir trees from beachside Lacanau,
site of the summer European surfing championships, through the
Cognac region and into the massive central forests of France.
Cognac distillation came to a halt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trees were flung into the alambic stills.'' said a spokeswoman
for the Pineau de Charentes wine bureau. ``With no electricity, we
had to stop distillation.''
</P>
<P>
   This is normally the most active time for distilleries, as all
wine destined to become cognac from the 1999 white grape harvest
must be distilled by the end of March.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Hine &AMP; Co. in Cognac reported building damage as a result
of falling trees, but its parent firm, Hennessy escaped with just
one tree down and no building damage, according to a spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Various regions were without electricity, water and telephone
for one to three weeks. Utilities have just returned to normal in
Cognac, the world's largest white-wine production center.
</P>
<P>
   Officials estimate that 40 percent of French forests were
toppled as a result of the storms. The French government last week
issued an emergency Europe-wide plea for forestry and plant nursery
experts to assist with clearing and replanting.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of chateaux in the Medoc, Sauternes, Graves, Pomerol,
Saint-Emilion and throughout the region report roof, building and
parkland damage. No official estimate of chateaux damage is being
compiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``People dare not complain too much. They say that compared to
the rest of the people who lost everything _ and even lives _ I am
very lucky,'' said Florence Raffard, spokeswoman for the Bordeaux
Wine Bureau and tourism center.
</P>
<P>
   Officials are meeting to assess how tourism will be affected.
Some forests will be off-limits and campgrounds will be closed in
many regions of France.
</P>
<P>
   Some chateaux tours have been halted or limited until cleanup
and repairs are completed. For the visitor to Bordeaux, the main
difference will be in the suddenly open vistas from the steps of
the chateaux. The wine will remain the same.
</P>
<P>
   (Kathleen Buckley writes for Winetoday.com, a daily Internet
wine publication of the New York Times Co. The Web address is
www.winetoday.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
