<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-LORDS-340&AMP;ADDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN MAKEOVER OF HOUSE OF LORDS, PANEL WANTS SOME ELECTED 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By SARAH LYALL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The House of Lords should include, for the first time
in history, some members who have been elected by the British
public, a commission studying the future of the Lords recommended
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But the commission stopped well short of suggesting that the
chamber be wholly elected, saying that the vast majority of its
members should be appointed by a special board that would be free
of political control.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to ensure that the reformed second chamber will no
longer be a source of political patronage,'' said Lord Wakeham,
chairman of the Royal Commission on the Reform of the House of
Lords, presenting a fat report filled with proposals at a news
conference Thursday morning. ``The prime minister will no longer be
able to control the size, political balance or individual
membership of the second chamber.''
</P>
<P>
   The House of Lords has been existing in a strange holding
pattern since November, when Prime Minister Tony Blair's Labor
government ended hundreds of years of history by removing the right
of hundreds of hereditary peers, whose titles pass from generation
to generation, to sit and vote in the chamber.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the Lords has been made up of 92 hereditaries, as
they are called, and 544 life peers, appointed over the years by
the government in power at the time, who hold their seats, and
their titles, until they die.
</P>
<P>
   No one has been particularly satisfied with this interim
arrangement: not the Labor Party, which wants all the hereditaries
gone for good; not the Conservative Party, which saw much of its
power leave along with the hereditaries, and not the peers
themselves, who know they are living on borrowed time.
</P>
<P>
   But the question of what to do now with Parliament's upper
house, a historically powerful body that was stripped of most of
its authority nearly 100 years ago, has proved a troublesome one
for Blair. He is not eager for a reconstituted house to have
increased responsibilities and power that can challenge his
political sway.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The proposals by Lord Wakeham's 12-member committee seek to
alter the Lords without effecting particularly radical changes.
According to the report, a small percentage of Lords _ either 65,
87, or 195 people, depending on various models it sets out _ should
be elected from among regular Britons in various regions. The rest
of the members should be appointed by an independent commission,
with 20 percent of them to have no party affiliation and at least
30 percent to be women.
</P>
<P>
   The chamber would still include church representatives. But in
an effort to reflect Britain's changing demographics, some of the
current ones, who are all Anglicans, would be replaced by
non-Anglican Christians and five would be added from non-Christian
religions.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, no one would become a member of the Lords
because of heredity or because of an appointment by the prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new second chamber should bring a far wider range of
experience and expertise to bear on the consideration of proposed
legislation and other policy issues,'' Lord Wakeham said. ``It's
members should come from all walks of life and be representatives
of the whole of British society.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposals, the new upper chamber would not have
substantially greater power than the old one, which is allowed to
delay legislation for up to a year but cannot kill it. But Lord
Wakeham said the Lords should be given a broader mandate to
scrutinize constitutional and human-rights legislation and to hold
the House of Commons to account in its handling of European Union
business.
</P>
<P>
   (STORY CAN ALSO END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the proposals said that the commission had wasted a
one-time-only chance. ``People have been going on in this country
for decades about Parliament being too weak and too much power
residing in the executive,'' said Robert Blackburn, a professor of
constitutional law at King's College, London, who supports the
formation of a wholly elected second chamber with greater authority
over legislation. ``This would have been a great opportunity to
redress the balance.''
</P>
<P>
   The government said it would study the report and then decide
whether to acton the recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This provides a sound platform for moving forward on a genuine
cross-party basis,'' said Baroness Jay, the Labor leader of the
House of Lords, adding that the government would ``need time to
consider'' the substance of the report.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, the Conservative Party said that it doubted
whether Blair's government was committed to real reform at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I doubt very much that they are going to want to take this
on,'' said Lord Strathclyde, the Tory leader in the House of Lords.
``They have got the house they want, a sort of crony house, and I
think that will continue for many years indeed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-00 1853EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
