<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 19:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1628 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a l BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV27-     01-20 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV27-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOT-COM IS ENVY OF THE NEW RICH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Thursday, Jan. 27)  
(lh) 
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of course, we know that coveting your neighbor's wealth isn't
pretty. We can usually rise above it. But now that I've heard
others express it, I can finally admit to similar shallow feelings.
I'm talking about dot-com envy, which might be defined as jealousy
and slight resentment for people who are suddenly and hugely
wealthy because they're an online darling.
</P>
<P>
   Every day ordinary people like yourself are suddenly cyber-rich.
Your kids' friends are e-tycoons at 30. Suddenly there are new ways
to become rich, and you're not even sure how it works, but you
suspect you should have found out long before now.
</P>
<P>
   Did we somehow miss the chance? Did it sound too good, and we
blew it off. Maybe it came in the mail looking like Publishers
Clearing House and was thrown in the trash before we saw it was a
chance to invest in a start-up company.
</P>
<P>
   You wonder how many psychiatrist couches are filled with people
trying to get past their resentment of 28-year-old Web
zillionaires. Or dealing with negative feelings for their cousin
who owned shares in a little-known company whose stock soared more
than 1,000 percent when it was bought by a telecom giant. Or
kicking themselves for settling for a regular merit increase with
two more holidays when they could have gone with the company's
e-division.
</P>
<P>
   There have always been very wealthy people around, but they
didn't stir up the same kind of envy. They were just rich. They
lived up on the hill in white houses with pillars. You could
explain their wealth and therefore rationalize your non-wealth.
They inherited old oil money. He built subdivisions. Her uncle
invented the Post-it. You couldn't be them if you tried.
</P>
<P>
   You could envy them in a general way. You could pout and say, if
your parents had that kind of money you too might have gone to a
major university and now be sitting in a leather chair smoking
cigars. Or reason that had you really wanted comfort you should
have studied brain surgery instead of journalism.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet has changed that. Some reporters who dumped the
newsroom for cyberspace are raking it in. As are former professors,
grad students and office workers who defected to the Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rich,'' it has been said, ``are different from you and
me,'' but today's rich are just like us with pre-IPO stock options.
</P>
<P>
   High-tech workers are the nouveau riche. So are former computer
nerds and some members of the generation once called slackers.
Success is being controlled and fortunes are being made in an
industry that most people didn't know of 15 years ago and some
people still doubt has much more of a future.
</P>
<P>
   For those not in the Web, it's a mystery. We don't really see
what these online companies produce. Some help people sell their
Beanie Babies. Some let people read about something on a computer
screen instead of on paper. Yet, some are famous and successful for
not making any money at all. Amazon.com, the virtual book store,
brags about losing millions of dollars but at the same time it has
sucked the life out of some very real bookstores.
</P>
<P>
   People continue to quit their traditional jobs to start new
online businesses, with the hope of getting rich, but how many
online businesses is the world clamoring for?
</P>
<P>
   Apparently a lot. Last week a service known only for its ability
to hook us up with Massachusetts became an equal partner in the
largest corporate merger in history. More overnight billionaires.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, we who do not play in that world and who get prickly
when we hear that the Web has scooped up the best and brightest are
going to have to get over it.
</P>
<P>
   For us, it remains business as usual. Do some good, have fun,
remember that money isn't everything. And look for a 25-year-old
venture capitalist orphan to adopt.
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Swartz's e-mail address is sfswartz(AT)pressdemo.com. The
Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
