<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 19:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1648 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-MATCHUPS-NYT &LR;      01-20 0625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MATCHUPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONFERENCE CHAMPIONSHIP MATCHUPS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NFC CHAMPIONSHIP GAME, SUNDAY, JAN. 23, 12:35 p.m. (ET)
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay (12-5) at St. Louis (14-3)
</P>
<P>
   Key Stat: The Buccaneers have the second-ranked pass defense;
The Rams have the first-ranked pass offense.
</P>
<P>
   Comment: Tampa Bay's defensive unit is one of the most
impressive in the NFL in recent years. The Buccaneers give up just
14.6 points a game, only 119 passing yards a game and a meager 87
on the ground. The team has an amazing 21 interceptions. Such
numbers are almost unheard of in modern football. Tampa Bay's
defense is a reflection of its head coach, Tony Dungy, an
intelligent, even-keeled man who practices what he preaches. Dungy
tells the defense to always stay cool, no matter what the score is
or how well an offense may be moving the ball. Stay patient and
play hard, and you will get a turnover. It is a smart way to play,
but the philosophy will be truly tested against St. Louis, which
has scored 31 points or more 12 times this year, including last
week's playoff game against Minnesota. The Rams play pinball, and
even a defense as good as Tampa Bay's won't be able to shut them
down forever. Here is the problem for Tampa Bay. The Buccaneers
held Washington, a powerful offense in its own right, to 157 total
yards and no offensive touchdowns. But that game was on grass, and
now Tampa Bay must travel to St. Louis and play on the speedy turf.
Thus the Buccaneers, even if they play their best game of the year,
will likely give up at least 17 points, and probably more. And
Tampa Bay's offense is unlikely to match that. The offense is
ranked 28th in the NFL and scored only 270 points during the
regular season. The Buccaneers need some kind of offense, any
offense. But they don't have enough. The Rams make it to the Super
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Score: Rams, 28-10
</P>
<P>
   _ MIKE FREEMAN
</P>
<P>
   AFC CHAMPIONSHIP GAME, SUNDAY, JAN. 23, 4:15 p.m. (ET)
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee (14-3) vs. Jacksonville (15-2)
</P>
<P>
   Key Stat: The Titans have three consecutive victories over
Jacksonville, while the Jaguars have a record of 30-4 in their last
34 home games.
</P>
<P>
   Comment: Not only did Tennessee sweep Jacksonville this season,
but the Titans also beat Jacksonville in their final meeting of the
1998 regular season. Jacksonville says that one mattered little
since the Jaguars played two backups at quarterback. This season,
Tennessee won in Jacksonville, 20-19, back in September in a
rain-soaked game and then trashed the Jaguars, 41-14, a day after
Christmas in Tennessee in a game where Steve McNair tossed five
touchdown passes. McNair flourished, the Jaguars say, because they
allowed him too frequently to break containment and play the game
on the edges, throwing passes short and long while rolling right
and left. This time, the Jaguars' plan is to keep McNair inside the
pocket and force him to make his reads with pressure directly in
his face. It is a nice plan, but it will be difficult to implement
because of McNair's strong legs and mobility. Does Tennessee own
the mental edge over Jacksonville? Do the Jaguars think too much
and play too softly when they meet the Titans? In the teams' last
two meetings, the answer to both questions was yes. But this time,
Jacksonville is prepared to show its deep talent in every phase,
especially in a passing game that includes running back Fred Taylor
and in kick returns, where punt returner Reggie Barlow figures to
be a game breaker. This is Jacksonville's second AFC championship
game in four years. The last time it lost to the New England
Patriots and missed a trip to the Super Bowl. This opportunity will
not slip away.
</P>
<P>
   Score: Jaguars, 27-23.
</P>
<P>
   _ THOMAS GEORGE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-00 1933EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
