<DOCNO> NYT20000120.0204 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1649 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     01-20 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: SELIG SHOULD MAKE THE DESIGNATED HITTER DISAPPEAR
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now that Bud Selig has been made Consolidated Imperial High Lord
Overseer, here is a modest proposal for something in the best
interests of baseball.
</P>
<P>
   If baseball is going to dismantle the old rivalry between the
American League and the National League, it should get rid of the
most odious symbol of the gap between the leagues. Bud's got the
big irons strapped on his spindly hips. He should puff out his
chest and growl, ``Feel lucky, punk?'' to the first union lawyer he
sees. He should deep-six the designated hitter.
</P>
<P>
   In case you missed it, what with the Parcells frolics and all,
on Wednesday the owners gave Selig powers that haven't been seen in
a baseball commissioner since Kenesaw Mountain Landis shook his
white mane and roared, ``Off with their heads.'' Didn't matter
whose heads. Landis just roared it.
</P>
<P>
   Maximum Bud even has the power to redistribute some income to
equalize the gap between big- and small-market teams. The
commissioner as Robin Hood. Having run the Milwaukee Brewers for
ages _ his family now runs it, wink-wink _ the Big Guy should have
a feel for disenfranchised franchises. Handing Bud the Ultimate
Deterrent is part of the continuing merger between the old leagues.
What is a century of tradition down the drain?
</P>
<P>
   If the owners had scrapped the two-league system to get the
umpires back into some semblance of control, that would have been a
noble cause. In reality, the biggest damage done to the umpires
came from their own union chief, Richie Phillips, who provoked an
insane Career Kool-Aid Drinking Contest last fall. That gaffe
provided baseball the blind-luck excuse to fire umpires left and
right, and to force Phillips out of his job. Finally, as the saying
goes.
</P>
<P>
   In this power vacuum, baseball now has the opportunity to
coordinate strike zones, uniforms, techniques, equipment and
attitude, without letting two sets of umpires whipsaw the leagues
back and forth.
</P>
<P>
   The old rallying cry of ``this is a league matter'' was not all
bad, by the way. The American League was the domain of DiMaggio and
Williams and Greenberg, serious sluggers. The National League was
the domain of Robinson and Mays and Clemente, the feisty next
generation. Back a few decades, there really were stylistic
differences between leagues. When Hal McRae was traded from
Cincinnati to Kansas City in 1973, American Leaguers were aghast at
his aggressive slides into second base. In essence, he replied,
That's the way the Reds do it over there. When the leagues rolled
out the bunting in October, this sun-dappled exercise was called
the World Series. It meant something. Teams that never saw each
other all season were now paired in a kind of a civil war, only
with mustard on the fans' fingers.
</P>
<P>
   People really cared. When the National League lost an All-Star
Game, loyal presidents like Warren C. Giles and Charles S. Feeney
moped right through the cocktail hour. When the American League
lost a World Series, true believers like Lee MacPhail and Robert O.
Fishel limited themselves to gruel and hardtack until Thanksgiving.
Free agency has cut down on the differences between leagues, to be
sure. Now they play interleague games during the summer, and then
conduct relatively endless playoffs, with the World Series turning
out to be anticlimactic. One should think carefully before killing
tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Hockey has the Stanley Cup, but the old regional splits don't
mean much in the international age. Basketball has four divisions
based on geography, with the West leaning toward ballet and the
East toward pro wrestling, but no true rivalry. Pro football has
the Super Bowl, but the old divisions have been lost. After the
merger between leagues in 1970, the American Conference lads vowed
to win one for good old Al Davis, and the National Conference lads
vowed to win one for good old Pete Rozelle, but that has pretty
well faded now in the ascendancy of Jacksonville and Tennessee.
Quick: which conferences are they in?
</P>
<P>
   Only baseball _ good old tottering baseball _ has a century of
tradition, which it abuses just about every chance it gets. By
installing the hideous designated hitter rule in 1973, the American
League has been playing nearly three decades of lumbering,
unimaginative ball, while the National League continues to
encourage a certain amount of cerebral effort from its managers and
athleticism from its pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   Having made the statesmanlike shift from the American to the
National League, Selig has the credentials to be Commissioner for
All People. His first act should be giving free gloves to all
designated hitters and telling them to go shag a fly. Baseball
wants to be entertaining? That would qualify.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
