<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Home Depot dumps Whirlpool appliance roll-out
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Home Depot is pulling the plug on a large-scale
rollout of Whirlpool appliances.
</P>
<P>
   Less than two months after announcing the launch of Whirlpool
and General Electric appliance sales, the Atlanta-based retailer
has stopped ordering from Whirlpool because of kinks in the new
partnership.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot is continuing a rollout of General Electric
appliances, which should arrive in nearly 300 stores by early
February and all Home Depots by August.
</P>
<P>
   Neither company would say why Whirlpool is being left out of the
launch, but apparently Home Depot has doubts that Whirlpool can
keep stocked its growing warehouse stores.
</P>
<P>
   Whirlpool, the nation's top maker of refrigerators, stoves and
other home appliances, faced delays in shipping products to smaller
customers last fall due to computer software problems. Analysts
said the manufacturer may have irked Home Depot, the nation's
largest home improvement retailer, by not meeting its rigorous
stocking requirements.
</P>
<P>
   ``Home Depot doesn't take any beef, and they don't forget
mistakes,'' said Nicholas Heymann, a Prudential Securities analyst.
``There have been some big delays with some vendors, and Home Depot
doesn't have patience for that.''
</P>
<P>
   A Whirlpool spokesman said Thursday that its glitches with Home
Depot related more to business matters than technology problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is absolutely not a computer issue,'' said Christopher
Wyse. ``We're continuing our negotiations and discussions for a
longer-term relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Some industry estimates peg Home Depot's potential appliance
sales at $1 billion within two years. So whatever the reason, Home
Depot can't risk running out of an appliance, which is typically
the last piece of a new home or kitchen remodel, Heymann noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you build kitchen cabinets to accommodate a refrigerator
or a dishwasher, and it's not in stock when you need it, you can't
just go to the next store to buy a replacement,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Benton Harbor, Mich.-based Whirlpool won't get many chances to
get its foot in the door. Home Depot is ruthless when a supplier
lets a shelf go bare.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, for example, General Electric lost a deal as Home
Depot's exclusive light bulb supplier when it didn't maintain the
stock. Home Depot canceled tens of millions of dollars in orders
with General Electric and switched to Philips. It took two years
for General Electric to get back into Home Depot's good graces.
</P>
<P>
   General Electric has apparently learned its lesson. The nation's
No. 2 appliance maker is ``jumping through hoops'' to fill Home
Depot's appliance needs, said Mark Healy, Home Depot's national
product merchant for kitchen and bath.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are doing everything to get the quantity and (products)
we need to move forward,'' said Healy, who noted that Whirlpool is
still a part of long-range plans. ``We're not saying we're going to
stop doing business with Whirlpool. But we're looking at other
manufacturers, just as we would with any products.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Maytag, the third-largest appliance maker, would
be a likely supplier.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot's move into appliance sales will take another bite
out of Sears, Roebuck and Co. Sears' share of appliance sales has
been slipping in recent years, Heymann noted, and Home Depot and
Lowe's Cos. are expected to pick up the runoff.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe's, Home Depot's No. 1 rival, sells appliances made by
Whirlpool, General Electric, Maytag and others.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
