``Angela's Ashes,'' will love the move version as well. But for the
rest of us, all this misery crammed into 145 minutes makes for one
rough sit.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-TITUS (Undated) _ ``Titus'' is based upon Shakespeare's
tragedy ``Titus Andronicus,'' is one of his least performed plays
and not for the faint-of-heart. Though it was popular in its day,
its brash violence, nihilism, rape, mutilation, torture and
cannibalism have often proved too traumatic and melodramatic for
audiences. Until today. For all its destruction, despair and death,
concludes on an optimistic and vibrantly alive note.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-BONE (Undated) _ ``Play It To the Bone'' may be the only
boxing movie ever made by Hollywood that is not an anti-boxing
movie. It actually likes the sport, and finds a Hemingway-esque
nobility in the spectacle of two men pounding each other into
hamburger. But even the most die-hard ring fan is likely to be
turned off by the 100 minutes of bad humor that surrounds the
film's one epic fight scene.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   TV-FELICITY (Undated) _ An autographed photo of Rod Serling
hangs in the office of J.J. Abrams, co-creator and executive
producer of ``Felicity.'' Judging from Sunday's
un-``Felicity''-like episode, he probably has a glossy of Franz
Kafka in his wallet.
</P>
<P>
   By John Levesque. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN (Undated) _ On the seven-year, $118 million
deal offered to Yankees shortstop Derek Jeter. It sounds good now,
but wait til Alex Rodriguez hits the market next winter.
</P>
