<HEADER>
A1655 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-SAFRICA-WINE-ART-460&AMP;     01-20 1153
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-WINE-ART-460&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DECLINE IN QUALITY OF SOUTH AFRICA'S WINE CREATES UNSALABLE
SURPLUS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 (bl)  
 By RACHEL L. SWARNS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SIMONDIUM, South Africa _ Ah, harvest time in the wine country!
The lush vines twist on wooden gables, the green leaves unfurl in
the warm summer sun and the sweet grapes hang heavy and ripe in the
shadow of the craggy Drakenstein mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Gideon Malherbe, a farmer, gazes at his acres and acres of plump
white wine grapes _ and dreams of hacking and killing each and
every vine. ``It doesn't make sense to harvest,'' he said with a
sigh. ``There's no money in it.''
</P>
<P>
   South Africa's wine producers are expecting a bumper crop of
grapes this year, but many couldn't be gloomier. About 21 million
gallons of white wine _ nearly 20 percent of last season's drinking
wine harvest _ is still sitting unsold and unwanted in cellars
across this region. The glut has sent prices plunging, and many
fear the new crop will make matters worse.
</P>
<P>
   A ton of white wine grapes sold for $164 last year but now goes
for about $123, farmers say. Nationally, producer profits fell 15
percent in 1999 from the year before. And all over the country,
farmers like Malherbe are choosing to uproot their bountiful vines
while wine dealers sell what they can at deep discount.
</P>
<P>
   Why isn't the country _ or the world _ clamoring for these
vintages, which are flooding markets here in bottles, boxes and
bags marked at 30 percent to 40 percent off the average price of $4
or $5?
</P>
<P>
   The problem, politely put, is that the surplus wine is not the
tastiest, merchants and wine farmers say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who wants to drink plonk?'' asked Craig Hughes, the liquor
merchandise manager for Makro, a local chain of wholesale stores
that spends $13 million a year on wine. ``Most of this surplus wine
we've turned down. A lot of that wine is not very drinkable.''
</P>
<P>
   To some people this may come as a surprise. After all, what
could be sweeter than a fine South African wine? The intoxicating
liquid tickled Thomas Jefferson's tongue at Monticello and pleased
Louis XVI's palate in Paris. And until two years ago, wine profits
were booming as drinkers in Europe and America rushed to taste the
fruits of this nation's new democracy.
</P>
<P>
   But farmers were perhaps too eager to enter world markets after
trade sanctions imposed on the all-white government in the 1980s
ended in 1992 and 1993. Hoping to capitalize into the bargain on
local demand for brandy made from white wine, many planted grapes
cheaply and easily cultivated here but less popular (and often less
tasty) than those preferred in Europe and America.
</P>
<P>
   Foreigners cheerfully sipped mediocre brands in the heady days
after Nelson Mandela was elected president in 1994, but they are
choosier now, wine merchants say. That means the surplus wines
cannot be sold abroad. Frankly, it's hard even selling them here.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Some wineries in this region of rolling hills and green
vineyards still produce high-quality wines, of course. Well-known
brands still sell briskly and at full price (anywhere from $8 to
$12 a bottle) here and abroad.
</P>
<P>
   And bulk exports of higher-quality white wine, which in 1998
dipped slightly in Britain, South Africa's biggest foreign market,
seem to have rebounded last year, according to SA Wine Industry
Information &AMP; Systems, a trade group.
</P>
<P>
   But there is little doubt that the foray into the free market
was tougher than expected for most producers, who had dizzyingly
high hopes after watching profits soar nationally, to $240 million
in 1997 from $142 million in 1994, according to the trade group.
Last year profits fell to $198 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many people were excited about getting into the market
after so many years that some brands and labels were put into the
market which could have had more thought put into them,'' said
Lynne Sherris, commercial director of Vinfruco Ltd., which imports
about 2.6 million gallons of South African wine to Britain every
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now a lot of exporters are going about things with more
prudence,'' Ms. Sherris said. ``We're telling them, `Look we've
tried that and that doesn't work.'''
</P>
<P>
   It was a bruising lesson, but farmers are quickly shedding old
habits. In the past, the tightly regulated industry rewarded
growers for producing large quantities of grapes, with less
emphasis on quality or popularity, farmers say. Growers who
overproduced paid few penalties because the national wine
cooperative took responsibility for selling all surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Now the market and consumer preferences rule. And the national
wine cooperative, which has privatized, buys much of its brandy
from France.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, many farmers are pulling up white grapevines and
replanting red, recognizing that more and more drinkers locally and
abroad are choosing merlots over chardonnays. Red wine grapes
currently sell for about $738 a ton, compared with $123 a ton for
white grapes, farmers say.
</P>
<P>
   When they do plant white, they often plant sauvignon blanc and
other brands known overseas instead of focusing on local varieties
like chenin blanc and colombard.
</P>
<P>
   Jannie Le Roux, whose family has grown wine grapes in nearby
Paarl for 10 generations, pointed proudly at his young merlot
vines. He still has some unpopular varieties of white grape, but he
plans to uproot them later this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to get out of the mass market,'' Le Roux said. ``The
only thing that will sell now is quality, quality, quality.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, at Malherbe's farm, workers are already busy hacking
and uprooting his healthy colombard vines. He, too, has started
growing red wine vines, although the first grapes will not appear
for three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all must change very fast,'' said Malherbe, whose grapes
are 80 percent white. ``I want to be 100 percent red.''
</P>
<P>
   Both men feel the pinch of falling prices, but they consider
themselves lucky. They have enough money to replant and regroup.
</P>
<P>
   Albe Treurnacht is less fortunate. He produced about 1.6 million
gallons of white wine last season. Today, half of it is still
sitting in tanks in his cellar.
</P>
<P>
   He says it is all spoken for. (No self-respecting winemaker, he
says, will acknowledge a surplus. It is too devastating to the
image.) But much of this wine will be sold in foil bags to
customers who pull up in pick-up trucks and supply taverns in poor
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Treurnacht guides a visitor to the packaging room and shrugs
sheepishly as a shiny machine pumps bag after bulging bag of white
wine. He still likes to think of himself as a man who only makes
wine fine enough to be sold in bottles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not proud of this,'' he said glumly. ``It's survival.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
