<HEADER>
A1661 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-OBRIEN21-COX     01-20 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-OBRIEN21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    An Irish woman wildly attuned to the writer's art
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ From the lobby of the Emory University Conference
Center Hotel, Edna O'Brien is gazing out a window at pretty much
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   It is an ordinary winter day, skies gray, trees bare. A building
in the near distance, beyond the trees, is nondescript as could be.
Nothing else is visible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who would do this?'' she asks. ``Who would sit here and try to
describe that? Try to describe the effect of those trees.''
</P>
<P>
   She is talking about why writers write, an old subject and
sometimes a tired one but one that quickens her already quick
conversation and brings her forward in her chair, her green eyes
alight with interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the wound,'' she says. ``You don't fully understand it or
you wouldn't write. You grope toward it. It's both unreachable and
unfindable. But it is there, from the earliest age. It is a
dissatisfaction or anguish with life that only words can cure.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the cure _ the searching for those words, for exactly the
right ones _ is a terror every time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Writing is something you try to postpone,'' she says,
reassuring anyone who's ever wondered why the one thing he wanted
to do was the one thing he would put off and put off. ``It's a
terror that you won't bring it off.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien, whose papers have been acquired by the special
collections department of Emory University's Robert W. Woodruff
Library, read Thursday night from her new novel, ``Wild
Decembers,'' which will be published in the United States this
spring by Houghton Mifflin. A day earlier, tired from a
trans-Atlantic flight that arrived later than expected, she sat
over tea in her hotel's stately lobby, a woman who was once called
Ireland's most banned novelist after James Joyce.
</P>
<P>
   As literary mantles go, one can do worse.
</P>
<P>
   She confesses to being private about certain things. One is a
marriage that ended in divorce in 1958 and the two sons that came
of that marriage. Another is her age. But it is a matter of record
that she was born in 1936.
</P>
<P>
   She was 23 when her first novel, ``The Country Girls,'' was
published. It celebrated her divorce and scandalized her parish
priest in County Clare, who burned it on the chapel grounds. It was
her mother's disapproval that hurt more. After her mother died,
O'Brien found the novel wrapped in a bed sheet in an outhouse,
every offending word and passage censured with thick black ink. ``I
both wept and screamed,'' she recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a long time, she had a reputation as a writer outside the
pale of accepted culture,'' says Ron Schuchard, professor of
English at Emory. ``Today, many people would say she has helped
pave the way for a lot of Irish women.''
</P>
<P>
   More than any Irish writer of her time, O'Brien has written
frankly, often exuberantly, of the repressed erotic side of women's
lives, of their silent anger and unrequited passion. ``I was
brought up by my mother always to be mindful of the shame of sex,''
she says, leaving you to infer that she thought otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Country Girls'' was banned when it was published in 1960,
and so were the next six novels.
</P>
<P>
   If Edna O'Brien paved the way for other Irish women, the price
was self-exile.
</P>
<P>
   James Joyce, one of her heroes (her biography of Joyce was
published in November by Lipper/Viking's Penguin Lives), both loved
and hated Ireland and had to get away from its obsessive piety, its
famines, its unending heartache to portray it.
</P>
<P>
   Joyce left for Paris, O'Brien for London. Neither was ever fully
reconciled to Ireland, and yet neither could be anything but Irish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say every writer I have admired,'' she said once,
``regardless of their particular daily history, has a loneliness
and a depth of feeling that cannot be corresponded to, and that's
why they write.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the wound that never completely heals, and impels a
certain kind of person to seek connection and contact through
words.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here was a man,'' she says of Joyce, ``who had written
`Ulysses,' who, for 17 years, every day and sometimes night, with
his eyesight almost gone and having to feel words and use color
pencils and crayons, went into the Hades and the paradise of his
mind and his imagination to write `Finnegans Wake.'''
</P>
<P>
   She accepts the reality that not everyone might wish to
accompany a writer on a journey so daunting. At a certain pitch,
the writer alone can hear the music of the words sometimes. But
other times, at a more accessible level, as in the famous
concluding paragraph of Joyce's short story ``The Dead,'' the music
fills head and heart like a hymn at a requiem High Mass, with its
image of snow ``falling on every part of the dark central plain, on
the treeless hills ... upon every part of the lonely churchyard ...
on the spears of crooked crosses and headstones, on the spears of
the little gates, on the barren thorns.''
</P>
<P>
   She knows them well, almost as well as her own.
</P>
<P>
   ``The words,'' O'Brien is saying, ``are incantatory.''
</P>
<P>
   If there is a terror in facing the blank page, there is also,
she says, an ecstasy like no other. ``Something comes over you and
the words move. They take wing. When that sequence of words, that
moment of narrative, carries you along, you are in another world.''
</P>
<P>
   She lives in two worlds, one the workaday world most of us know,
the other in her imagination. If she has not always been entirely
at home in the one, she knows there is sanctuary in the other,
whatever its terrors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Writers don't always enjoy what they do, like brain
surgeons,'' she says. ``But if I were born again, I would still ask
to be a writer. When you're finished, you look back on it and
there's nothing like it. Others can have their judgment and, as we
all know, that can be a slaughterhouse. But you know what you were
meant to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
