<SLUG> BC-FELICITY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A bemused `Felicity' enters `Twilight Zone'
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   J.J. Abrams, creator of ``Felicity,'' has an autographed picture
of Rod Serling hanging on his office wall. This bit of office decor
trivia is submitted for your approval as partial explanation for
Sunday night's episode of ``Felicity,'' a homage to Serling's ``The
Twilight Zone'' that is really pretty inexplicable but still grand
fun.
</P>
<P>
   The episode, ``Help for the Lovelorn,'' is never all that
frightening, but the attention to detail is downright scary. The
black-and-white cinematography, filmed on vintage cameras, throws
shadows into high relief. The music is hokey, the cast dresses in
early-'60s period clothes (their fresh, modern faces made
artificially old-fashioned call to mind scenes from the film
``Pleasantville''), and the dialogue sometimes has that sing-songy
quality that was Serling.
</P>
<P>
   Abrams even got Lamont Johnson, director of many of the original
``Zones,'' to direct.
</P>
<P>
   In the show, Felicity (Keri Russell) is told by a mystery woman
to go to ``The Clinic'' for ``The Treatment'' _ a method of curing
incurable romanticism and a tendency to wear her broken heart on
her sleeve _ two afflictions that Felicity suffers from mightily.
The clinic is a creepy, menacing place, and she can't get anyone to
give her a straight answer as to what ``The Treatment'' consists
of. When she finds out ... ooh, it's not to her liking.
</P>
<P>
   Not only is ``Lovelorn'' a dead-on ``Zone'' tribute, it's a
spoof of ``Felicity'' itself. It mocks her tendency toward
indecision. It plays (quite cleverly) with the show's ongoing
mystery of what her zonky roommate, Meghan, keeps in her lockbox.
It even goofs on the tape recorder that Felicity gushes her every
thought into.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with the episode is that some things are left
unresolved _ the old ``Zones'' were always resolved _ and viewers
may feel cheated.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to tell what folks will make of this extraordinarily
bizarre outing. Most regular fans of ``Felicity'' are too young to
know ``Zone'' as anything more than a name from the distant past,
and most ``Zone'' fans probably don't watch ``Felicity,'' so Abrams
may have made a show for just a small group of people who like
twisted TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``You unlock this door with the key to imagination,'' Serling
used to say in his intros. ``Felicity's'' Abrams has provided a new
door, and it's up to viewers to let their imaginations unlock it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Felicity''
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m. Sunday on the WB
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
