<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1666 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-GOLDEN-GLOBES21-COX     01-20 0552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLDEN-GLOBES21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Enjoy Sunday show; few take it seriously
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   By the end of the Golden Globes on Sunday night, most people
watching the NBC broadcast still won't know who's responsible for
handing out the prizes.
</P>
<P>
   There's not much reason to care, either. Enjoy the outfits and
the usually lively pace of the trophy toss. Just don't take it too
seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Even the winners don't, and their acceptance speeches show it _
like Michael Caine last year, 'fessing up that he ``made a lot of
crap'' in the course of his acting career. Also last year,
presenter Christine Lahti turned up dragging toilet paper on her
shoe, a reference to missing her own previous win because she was
in the loo when they called her name.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, the Globes are thrown by an elusive little group
called the Hollywood Foreign Press Association. They're a cabal of
some 90 part-time journalists who write for overseas publications
you've never heard of (in some cases, not many people in Europe
have, either).
</P>
<P>
   Even though celebs are happy to accept their prizes, not many
particularly respect the Hollywood Foreign Press Association. Its
members seem a little too happy to accept free meals, hotel rooms,
gifts and access to stars during the junkets studios host to
generate buzz about their movies.
</P>
<P>
   In the trade magazine Variety, Joan Rivers quipped of the HFPA,
``I know them all, because they wait on me during the year in
various restaurants.''
</P>
<P>
   Ouch.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, so now you know who's behind Sunday's show. The main
reason to watch is to handicap the Oscars.
</P>
<P>
   The Globes are seen as a semi-reliable barometer for Oscar
nominations. That's not because the HFPA's voters are especially
shrewd. It's just that they hand out nearly twice the number of
big-category awards that Oscar does, so they have plenty of room to
seem prescient.
</P>
<P>
   Voters from the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences
nominate only five movies for best picture, with the emphasis
usually on more somber than comic fare. Last year's nomination (and
surprise win) for ``Shakespeare in Love'' was a rare exception.
They also have only five slots for best actor and actress. By
contrast, the HFPA breaks movies into two categories: drama and
musical/comedy. In other words, 10 pictures, 10 actors and 10
actresses compete for the gold.
</P>
<P>
   This year, that results in Julianne Moore being nominated twice
as best actress (for the comedy ``An Ideal Husband'' and the drama
``The End of the Affair''). All five Globe nominees for best
picture in the drama category stand pretty good shots at getting
Oscar nods. But it's unlikely that the academy's nomi-
</P>
<P>
   nations Feb. 15 will include the HFPA's popcorn picks in the
musical/comedy category, ``Analyze This,'' ``Notting Hill'' or
``Toy Story 2.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and if the movie mix wasn't already excessive, don't forget
that Sunday's show also honors TV shows and stars. Really, it must
be hard to go to anybody's home in Los Angeles without tripping
over Globes in every room.
</P>
<P>
   ON TELEVISION
</P>
<P>
   ``The 57th Annual Golden Globe Awards''
</P>
<P>
   8 Sunday night on NBC.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
