<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1668 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-TRAVEL-APALACHICOLA1S     01-20 1540
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-APALACHICOLA1STTAKE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Off-the-beaten-track Panhandle town a step back in time _ slow
and warm and gloriously relaxing
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Jan. 23.
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   APALACHICOLA, Fla. _ It's one of those mild, breezy Saturday
afternoons, deep in the off-season, when this entire town seems to
be sleeping off a big oyster lunch.
</P>
<P>
   The only sounds along Water Street _ 150 years ago, the busiest
waterfront between New Orleans and Charleston _ are the mutter of a
shrimp boat engine and a seafood plant's exhaust fan. Water sloshes
under the skeletal remains of a wharf. Gulls caw testily. Wind
riffles the reeds in Apalachicola Bay, where the fresh waters of
the Apalachicola River and the salt of the gulf swirl together to
create ideal conditions for the succulent oyster that bears the
bay's name.
</P>
<P>
   Brown pelicans crouch on the docks with the goofy, stupefied
look of people who've overdone it on the shellfish. On a downtown
street, built wide as an interstate in 19th-century style, two
women pull their car windows even to gossip; there's no one to honk
at them. Cats stalk sidewalks in the winter sun; there's even one
sacked out on the registration desk of the 93-year-old Gibson Inn.
Dogs loll with impunity.
</P>
<P>
   Apalachicola _ a working Panhandle fish town that doesn't drool
after tourists, but welcomes more visitors from Atlanta than from
any other city _ is dozing. Dreaming of its past. Beautiful dreams
of steamboats packed with cotton bales and cypress logs, top-hatted
barons of commerce and bejeweled ladies laughing in the flare of
gaslights.
</P>
<P>
   Ghosts walk here even in broad daylight.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a mystique about Apalach,'' says Ralph Brooks, 54,
who, like everyone else, conserves energy by ignoring the last
three syllables of the name. ``I guess it's the history; it's
something I can't quite put my finger on.''
</P>
<P>
   The carpenter is taking a cigarette break in the hangar door of
Benign Boats, soaking up the low-slant sun that even now, in
January, is toasty. ``When I was 18, there was absolutely nothing
to do here, but every girlfriend I brought home from college fell
in love with the place _ never wanted to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks blows out his smoke, sums up his hometown: ``It's a
feeling you get, more than anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Bickel, 47, a photographer who relocated here from
Pittsburgh and patched up a grand Edwardian house with his wife,
Susan, says the soul of the area comes through in its images _
``vignettes of old Florida.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's natural beauty ... hand labor ... rickety docks made
of twigs and boards ... half-submerged craft ... lagoons so far
back you can't believe it when you find boats there,'' says Bickel,
who has a gallery of his pictures in the restored Grady Market
building and likes to shoot oystermen from his kayak. ``It's not so
much what's here, it's what isn't.''
</P>
<P>
   The talk of the town, says Susan Bickel, is owls: ``It's a wild
year for them!'' A snowy owl, fluky visitor from way north,
inexplicably settled on nearby St. George Island and is stopping
traffic. In the Chestnut Street Cemetery, where Spanish moss
shrouds the slanted gravestones of shipwreck victims and
Confederate soldiers, native hooters screech night after night,
keeping the Bickels awake.
</P>
<P>
   Laughing gently, the photographer says, ``I wonder what it all
means?''
</P>
<P>
   My wife, Cathy, and I succumbed several years ago to the
gracious and funky charms of Apalach. Midsummers are sweltering,
but the other months are seductive. The place is within 20 minutes
of beautiful beaches but is hardly a ``beach town''; rather, an old
Southern community that seems to have drifted down, like a cypress
log, to lodge itself here, out of the stream of time.
</P>
<P>
   Ninety miles southwest of Tallahassee, Apalach is the center of
what tourist authorities call the Forgotten Coast, served by no
convenient interstate or airport. Sixty miles west is Panama City
and the slick, noisy beach-culture strip stretching practically to
Bourbon Street. But Apalachicola, which had a French consulate when
the sailing ship was king, now feels as far off the world's radar
as you can get in a seven-hour drive from Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The town of 3,000 was a handy base of operations for our
three-day exploration of the area.
</P>
<P>
   The hamlet of Indian Pass, 17 miles to the west, is so deep in
gator country that you find yourself nervously wondering about the
spare tire as you zip down the flat straight blacktop through the
slash pine and cabbage palm.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, as you walk into the Indian Pass Raw Bar, built in 1929
as a company store for the workers who made ``catface'' scratches
on pines to drain turpentine, you are greeted with a sign strung
across the store on a clothesline: ``This is Gator Country.'' It
refers not only to the fanatical following of University of Florida
football but also to a waiter-shucker named Gator Weiland who
peddles a blazing condiment called Insanity Sauce and is so surly
that newspapers celebrate the fact. We missed Gator (shucks!) but
we did meet his warm cohort Audrey, who's coming up on her 4
millionth oyster shucked.
</P>
<P>
   At $4.50 a dozen, the raw mollusks were laughably succulent, the
gumbo savory. You fetch your own beer from the wall cooler; ceiling
fans turn slowly on the end of long pipes.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby is the Turtle Beach Inn, as in love with turtles as the
bar is with gators. As our car crunched onto the shell driveway, we
were greeted by a leaping chocolate Lab named Turtle. Since the inn
sits at the edge of a loggerhead turtles' nursery beach (hatchings
can be witnessed in late summer), those ancient creatures are
saluted throughout the inn with carvings in metal, ceramic and
driftwood. The 2-year-old inn is so immaculate that the scent of
pine floors jumped up in our noses as we opened our spacious room
with a commanding view of the beach.
</P>
<P>
   Innkeeper Trish Petrie is a likable Nashvillian who passed
through the area and decided to build the inn, ``so that I could
afford never to leave the place.'' We heard many variations of this
end-of-wandering tale on the Forgotten Coast.
</P>
<P>
   That night, with anchored shrimp boats puttering a lullaby
offshore, the stars were so bright that I could pick out five of
the Pleiades _ the ``7 Little Sisters'' that only show up as a
single smudge through Atlanta smog.
</P>
<P>
   First on the morning agenda was horseback riding on the beach.
We saw dolphins barely 10 yards from shore make their way along,
rising and diving, as if to an oceanic heartbeat. We saw the
remains of Portuguese man-of-war jellyfish with bells as large as a
bicycle helmet. We saw shrimp boats like fat airplanes with their
net booms extended over the water, seabirds swirling in their wake.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people want to leave here because it's so small,''
said Julie Faircloth, 17, our friendly guide. ``I don't know what
they think they'll find.''
</P>
<P>
   We motored into Apalachicola for lunch (with heavenly clam
chowder) at the Owl Cafe. We checked into the rambling, charming
Gibson Inn (1907), which looks like a grounded riverboat with its
wraparound verandas. After picking up a walking-tour map at the
nearby Coombs House, a handsome B&AMP;B in a lumber baron's 1905
mansion, we commenced to mosey.
</P>
<P>
   Something amusingly eccentric _ even a touch gothic _ flavors
this community of gracious homes, gardens and churches. There's a
tiny museum, perfectly priced at $1 admission, devoted to John
Gorrie, inventor of the ice machine. An 1899 monument to Gorrie
across the street was erected by a ``Most Worshipful Lodge'' of the
Masons. All around are Queen Anne, Colonial Revival and
Plantation-style homes being restored, next to ones slumping into
the marshy ground.
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to walk far before you're among sun-scorched
shotgun shacks, with streets that flood in the rain.
</P>
<P>
   Two minutes' drive, at the north end of town, is Sipio Basin,
where a bevy of weathered, shrimp-redolent boats _ with names like
Linda Fay, Mrs. Ruby, Lady Diane, Karol Ann _ tie up. Nearby is a
national research center on wetland life and its public exhibit,
the Estuarine Walk, containing tanks of such colorfully named
critters as Gulf toadfish, alligator snapper, yellow-bellied slider
and Suwannee cooter (the last three are turtles). The kids will get
a few minutes of free diversion here, but let's face it: Apalach is
no Disney World.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is there any night life to speak of _ but who needs it when
you've got Boss Oyster? The Water Street eatery looks like nothing
more than an old mortar dive attached to a tin ``shuck house.'' But
step through the screen doors and out again on the dockside dining
area, and Boss casts its spell _ an enchantment of funkiness. Order
a frosty brew and some oysters (steamed, fried or raw, $6.50 a
dozen), grouper or soft-shelled crab. Everybody gets a battery of
hot sauces and a roll of paper towels.
</P>
<P>
   There's even a floor show. At sunset the light comes over your
shoulder and dabs tarnished gold on the shrimp boats chugging out
to the bay, each with its inebriated-looking pelican riding shotgun
in the rigging.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
