<HEADER>
A1669 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-TRAVEL-APALACHICOLA2N     01-20 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-APALACHICOLA2NDTAKE-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   APALACHICOLA, Fla.: On our last day we headed out to St. George
Island, spending most of the 20-minute trip over water on two
causeways. From that vantage we saw oystermen in their little
boats, hauling in their rough-shelled catch with the 9-foot tongs
unchanged for generations.
</P>
<P>
   At St. George Island State Park we took a four-mile walk over
sugary sand beside a two-toned sea, bottle green in the shallows,
deep blue farther out. We passed four other people. Slat fences
twisted and submerged beneath the drifting dunes.
</P>
<P>
   After a lunch of soft-shell-crab po-boys (fit for a king!) at
the nearby Blue Parrot Cafe, whose grass-hut beachside bar is the
nerve center of St. George, we rented a two-person kayak. Skimming
a lagoon, we saw two great blue herons. The first, standing 4 feet
tall with long white breast feathers fluttering in the wind, looked
eerily like a shaman in a bird costume. The second rose from the
reeds in a slow-motion spectacle of unfurling wings, endless legs
streaming behind it.
</P>
<P>
   When we returned the kayak, despite my assurances that
alligators couldn't live in a salt lagoon, Cathy asked rental
proprietress Jeanni McMillan about the reptiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, there's a few little ones,'' she said to our thunderstruck
faces, ``but they never bother anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it seems everyone in the area has sighted a gator, but
no one's ever heard of an attack. The key is to avoid grassy banks
where their nests might be hidden. Still, it's worth remembering
what an old-timer said to Bickel in his kayak: ``To a gator, you're
an oyster on a cracker.''
</P>
<P>
   Water, earth and air are in balance, perfectly mixed in the
bracing cocktail that is Apalach life. One sees, moving among all
three realms, terns, oyster-catchers, plovers, egrets, ospreys.
</P>
<P>
   And moving right into town, this odd winter, is a surplus of
owls. We know because one swooped just inches above our heads as we
stepped out of the Gibson one evening.
</P>
<P>
   After a stylish dinner at Tamara's Cafe Floridita _ named for
its chef, a former TV personality from Venezuela _ we were chatting
with her over coffee. A cook summoned us outside with these words:
``He's back.''
</P>
<P>
   There, on a satellite dish in an empty lot across the street,
sat a brown owl, as if to compose a surreal photograph. Or was it
tuned to vibrations from the Great Beyond? As we chattered just a
few feet from the bird, it swiveled its head like a gun turret to
shoot us a baleful look.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call him Chico _ means `boy' in Spanish,'' Tamara Suarez
said with a laugh. It was only 9 on a misty Sunday evening, yet
Apalach seemed deserted. Once again, dreaming.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the stars!'' exclaimed Tamara suddenly, and we all
raised our heads without a word.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good fishing tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   It's a seven-hour drive from Atlanta. Take I-75 south to Tifton,
Ga., U.S. 319 south into Florida, U.S. 98 west to Apalachicola.
</P>
<P>
   ACCOMMODATIONS
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Gibson Inn (1907) is the heart of Apalachicola life. With
most of its 31 rooms in the $80-$90 range, it's an excellent value
with no-nonsense charm, piano bar and rocker porches, though thin
walls in some rooms can cause a noise problem (850-653-2191).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Coombs House Inn, a 1905 lumber baron's mansion on an
Apalachicola residential street, is an elegant bed-and-breakfast
with 19 rooms, mostly in the $100-$129 range (850-653-9199).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Turtle Beach Inn, a B&AMP;B, is part of the secluded Indian Pass
community with limited services but a beautiful natural setting on
the beach; four rooms, $95-$145, are spacious and immaculate
(850-229-9366).
</P>
<P>
   THINGS TO DO
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Broke-A-Toe's Outdoor Services of Apalachicola rents kayaks,
canoes and sailboats, leads trips to nearby barrier islands (Cape
St. George, St. Vincent Island Nature Reserve) and arranges
two-hour horseback rides at $55 per person (850-229-9283).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Jeanni's Journeys on St. George Island rents those craft and
leads similar trips; also children's outings (850-927-3259).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Estuarine Walk in a nature research center has free
child-friendly exhibits of local wildlife (850-653-8063).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Governor Stone, a restored 1877 schooner anchored on the
Apalachicola waterfront, has two-hour afternoon cruises for $20 per
adult, $10 per child (850-653-8700). Dixie Theatre in downtown
Apalachicola, a revamped 1912 playhouse, features local productions
(850-653-3200).
</P>
<P>
   INFORMATION
</P>
<P>
   Apalachicola Bay Chamber of Commerce, 850-653-9419. Or go online
at www.baynavigator.com/
</P>
<P>
   _Dan Hulbert writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
