<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY LOSING GROUND IN BAY STATE, NEW POLL SHOWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK PHILLIPS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Bill Bradley, who is depending on strong support in the
Northeast to keep his presidential candidacy competitive, is losing
ground in Massachusetts to Al Gore, a new University of
Massachusetts poll shows.
</P>
<P>
   According to the survey taken Jan. 13-16, the vice president has
bounced back among Massachusetts Democrats, earning support from 42
percent of poll respondents, while Bradley received 36 percent.
Another 19 percent were undecided; the remaining 3 percent refused
to answer. A similar UMass poll in October showed Bradley leading,
43 percent to 35 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Lou DiNatale, director of the quarterly UMass poll, which first
picked up Bradley's surge in the Bay State in June, said the swing
to Gore spells trouble for the former New Jersey senator with
Massachusetts's primary looming March 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Bradley can no longer count on winning Massachusetts,''
DiNatale said.
</P>
<P>
   Because the poll's margin of error is 6 percent, the Democratic
rivals are actually in a statistical dead heat.
</P>
<P>
   The turnaround comes even after Bradley spent twice as much as
Gore on television advertising in Boston aimed for the most part at
New Hampshire voters. Bradley has aired $2.2 million worth of ads
since early November.
</P>
<P>
   The poll also shows that both Democrats enjoy leads over the top
Republican candidates. Gore leads Texas Governor George W. Bush 52
percent to 28 percent with 15 percent undecided, a major reversal
from October's survey in which Bush lead Gore 46 percent to 38
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley also beat Bush in Massachusetts, 51 percent to 31
percent, with 14 percent undecided. Those figures were similar to
Bradley's October lead of 48 percent to 34 percent. Bradley tops
Arizona Senator John McCain 49 percent to 30 percent, with 19
percent undecided. In October, Bradley was leading McCain 51
percent to 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who trailed McCain in October by 5 percentage points now
leads him 47 percent to 29 percent, with 19 percent undecided.
</P>
<P>
   Four hundred people participated in the poll, conducted by the
school's McCormack Institute.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-00 1948EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000120.0220 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1672 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-COKE21-COX     01-20 0700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coca-Cola shuffles European operations
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ So far, Douglas Daft is sticking to his word.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview just a few days after becoming Coca-Cola's
president last month, Daft said he would follow the advice of the
company's late chairman, Roberto C. Goizueta.
</P>
<P>
   Goizueta, he said, taught him the value of focusing on a ``short
and critical agenda,'' and moving quickly to deal with key issues.
</P>
<P>
   Once again Thursday, the company made a decisive move by
creating two new business units _ one for Western Europe and the
other for Central Europe and Eurasia _ to more effectively deal
with its operations there. Last summer in the region, Coke
experienced the biggest product recall in its 113-year history.
</P>
<P>
   ``This new structure for Greater Europe reflects our strong
desire to make sure we are managing our business on a local
basis,'' said Charles Frenette, president of the Greater Europe
business, which encompasses 866 million potential consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Since being named company president, Daft has stressed the
importance of becoming more locally focused and decentralized,
especially since Coca-Cola sells soft drinks in some 200 nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Daft is continuing to decentralize the regional management to
keep attuned to the demands of the market, including demographics,
marketing and bottler issues,'' said Andrew Conway, an analyst with
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Bill Pecoriello of Sanford Bernstein said the company is
simplifying its European operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of layers in the former structure,''
Pecoriello said. ``Now, there will be less bureaucracy and more
streamlined communication.'' Similar moves, he predicted, are
likely to take place in other parts of the globe.
</P>
<P>
   Less than two weeks ago, Daft announced he was shifting Frenette
from his job as chief marketing officer to head the company's
European operations, which will now be based in London. Those
operations had been based in Atlanta and led by William Casey, who
retired.
</P>
<P>
   The heads of both new business units will report to Frenette.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the move makes a lot of sense,'' Conway said. ``I
think Daft is aligning his midlevel management to the anchor
bottlers of the region.''
</P>
<P>
   In Western Europe, Coca-Cola Enterprises is the key bottler. The
new unit there _ which includes Belgium, France, Germany, the
United Kingdom and 10 other countries _ will be based in Madrid and
headed by Jose Nunez Cervera, 59. He was previously responsible for
operations in Spain and Portugal.
</P>
<P>
   The new Central Europe and Eurasia Group covers 35 nations,
including Austria, Poland, Hungary, Russia and Greece. It will be
headed by Cem Kozlu, who will be based in Vienna. Previously,
Kozlu, 54, was in charge of operations in Turkey, Caucasus and
Central Asian Republics.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the key bottlers operating in Kozlu's area, Hellenic
Bottling and Coca-Cola Beverages, are attempting to merge. The
deal, which the European Union is scrutinizing for antitrust
reasons, would create the Coke system's second-largest bottler
after Atlanta-based CCE.
</P>
<P>
   ``Europe is a real priority for the company,'' said Coke
spokesman Rafael Fernandez. ``Both new units are headed by
executives with international business experience who have a very
clear European understanding.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to this latest move, Daft made several others this
week. On Tuesday, for example, he selected Jack Stahl to become
president and chief operating officer in April, when Daft ascends
to the top spots of chairman and chief executive officer. Current
Chairman M. Douglas Ivester is retiring then.
</P>
<P>
   Daft also named a new head of the company's Japanese operations,
Mary Minnick, who becomes the first woman in that role.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the company's board elected five executive vice
presidents, who will serve on a six-member executive committee that
Daft chairs. The top management committee will set company policy
and establish a strategic direction.
</P>
<P>
   The company's stock rose 62 1/2 cents Thursday, closing at
$65.87 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
