u i BC-MIDEAST-DIPLOMACY-BOS     01-20 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-DIPLOMACY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US MOVES TO SPEED UP MIDEAST PEACE PROCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With time slipping away in what was to have been a
decisive month in Middle East peace negotiations, the Clinton
administration Thursday stepped up its efforts to bring the
Palestinians and Israelis closer to agreement on some of their
thorniest issues, while warning that neither side should expect to
get all that it wants.
</P>
<P>
   The US talks with Palestinian leader Yasser Araft came just days
after the postponement of a third round of separate negotiations
between Israel and Syria that were due to resume Wednesday at
Shepherdstown, W. Va. Arafat's trip was scheduled last month when
those high-level discussions were still ongoing.
</P>
<P>
   Both President Clinton and Secretary of State Madeleine K.
Albright met with the Palestinian leader in an attempt to nudge the
parties along keep alive a Feb. 13 deadline for Israel and the
Palestinians to finish the outline of a final settlement of their
long running dispute over such issues as Palestinian statehood and
the future of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   ``As in any process like this, there must be inevitable and
difficult compromises,'' Clinton said at the top of his meeting
with Arafat, who sat beside him in the Oval Office as he spoke.
``No one can get everything that either side wants. But I am
convinced we can get there, and I am convinced that Chairman Arafat
is proceeding in great good faith.''
</P>
<P>
   In hopes of achieving peace in the Middle East as a key part of
his legacy, the president has invested extraordinary amounts of
personal time in the effort to keep both sets of talks moving.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Arafat said, ``There is no doubt that there will
be difficulties along the way; these are expected difficulties. But
there is also determination.''
</P>
<P>
   After the meeting, National Security Council spokesman Mike
Hammer dampened expectations that the two sides would reach a
preliminary settlement by Feb. 13. They hope to reach a final
settlement in September.
</P>
<P>
   Calling deadlines ``artificial,'' Hammer said, ``If it slips by
a week or two or a month, they are not breaking off. It's an
ongoing process.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright met first with Arafat, hosting him for 40 minutes in
her seventh floor office in front of a roaring fireplace. Then her
motorcade cruised through the snowy streets of Washington to her
home in the Georgetown section, where their talks continued for
another hour over lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the lunch, Arafat said, ``Warm, positive and
beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   Of his later meeting with Clinton, the Palestinian leader said,
``It was a very fruitful and productive and important meeting.''
</P>
<P>
   Arafat's arrival was expected to coincide with the resumption of
direct talks between Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and the head
of the Syrian delegation, Foreign Minister Farouk al-Sharaa. But
those discussions hit a snag over differences concerning proposals
for Israel to return the Golan Heights to Syria. Albright and other
US officials blamed the collapse of those talks on both sides
wanting priority for its key concerns in fashioning an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman James P. Rubin said Syrian officials
would come to Washington next week, to be followed by Israeli
experts, in an effort to work out with some of the outstanding
issues.
</P>
<P>
   Hammer said US officials were determined to nudge the peace
process along on both the Palestinian and Syrian tracks. ``They
will move at different speeds, and that's fine, but in order to
achieve a comprehensive peace, you are going to need success not
only on one track but also on the other,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Said Richard W. Murphy, the director of Middle East Studies at
the Council on Foreign Relations and a former diplomat: ``This is
the decisive hour for determining if the year 2000 is going to see
a major stride toward Israeli-Palestinan agreements.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
