<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON, ARAFAT REMAIN CONFIDENT IN PEACE PROCESS, DESPITE
UNCERTAINTY OF MID-FEBRUARY DEADLINE
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Bill Clinton and Palestinian Authority
President Yasser Arafat agreed Thursday that a comprehensive Middle
East peace accord remains within reach this year, despite the
growing likelihood that a key milestone slated for Feb. 13 would be
missed.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton told Arafat, though, that Palestinians and Israelis
would both have to bend a little in their efforts to negotiate a
land-for-peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``As in any process like this, there must be inevitable and
difficult compromises,'' Clinton told reporters, as Arafat looked
on, at the beginning of an hour-long Oval Office meeting. ``No one
can get everything that either side wants.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton mentioned no issues in particular, but the points of
greatest friction are well known.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians, for instance, want thousands of refugees to have
the right to return to Israel if they choose; Israelis say
Palestinian refugees are an issue for the Arab world to address.
Arafat is also pressing for land to create a Palestinian state _ an
area where Israel has shown some flexibility _ to include a portion
of Jerusalem, a point on which Israel has shown considerable
resistance.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the tough going in the peace process, Clinton said he
remains hopeful that he can help broker an overall peace accord
between Israel and its Arab neighbors before leaving office next
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be disappointed if we don't, because we have the leaders
who can do it,'' Clinton said. ``The issues are clear _ even if
they're difficult, they're clear _ and I certainly think we could
have it and I'm going to do everything I can every day I've got to
try to achieve it.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also said that Syrian-Israeli peace talks remain on
track, despite setbacks in that area as well.
</P>
<P>
   After meetings this month in Shepherdstown, W.Va., and last
month in Washington, Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Syrian
Foreign Minister Farouk al-Sharaa had been scheduled to resume
negotiations near Washington on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The talks were postponed indefinitely, however, because the two
sides were at odds over, among other things, the precise boundaries
of the Golan Heights territory Israel would return to Syrian
control in exchange for peace and normalized relations.
</P>
<P>
   Syrian negotiators are expected to return to Washington as early
as next week, in hopes of rejuvenating the talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't read too much into this,'' Clinton said of the
interruption in the Syrian-Israeli talks. ``Actually, the parties
have a framework for making these decisions that's more clear and
more bridgeable than I would have thought by now.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is scrambling to keep both tracks of peace talks alive,
in hopes of helping to broker an end to half a century of bloodshed
and enmity between Israel and its Arab foes.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat was here to seek Clinton's help in advancing peace talks
between Palestinians and Israelis. Arafat and Barak have pledged to
agree by Feb. 13 to a framework for final peace negotiations, with
an eye toward wrapping up the entire process by September.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli-Palestinian talks have bogged down, however, over
disputes concerning Israeli troop withdrawals from parts of the
occupied West Bank and shortcomings in Palestinian efforts to crack
down on anti-Israeli terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are expected difficulties,'' Arafat told reporters at
the outset of his meeting with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   An hour later, Arafat came out of the White House and told
reporters he remained confident of striking a peace accord before
Clinton leaves office a year from now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure, and we are determined to complete our endeavor of
achieving the goals in a comprehensive peace during the tenure of
President Clinton,'' Arafat said.
</P>
<P>
   It's anything but a certainty.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat met earlier in the day with Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright. The two huddled by a roaring fire in her dark-paneled
office at the State Department in the morning, then repaired to her
elegant Georgetown home for a private lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Following their morning meeting, Albright's spokesman hinted
that the Feb. 13 deadline might be missed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do believe it will be a formidable challenge to meet the
mid-February deadline, or goal, for a framework agreement,'' said
State Department spokesman James Rubin.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Rubin said Albright was prepared to host a summit
between Arafat and Barak, if that would help them meet the Feb. 13
target date.
</P>
<P>
   Albright and Arafat spent much of their time Thursday discussing
``what kind of meetings could take place, what kind of schedule
could be created,'' to try to bring the overall Israeli-Palestinian
negotiations to a conclusion by September, Rubin said, as well as
possible ways for ``bridging the gaps,'' between the two.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said Clinton remains hopeful
that if the Feb. 13 deadline slips it would be by only a few days.
</P>
<P>
   ``If both parties believe that they need extra time, I'm sure
that we will work with them on that,'' Lockhart told reporters at a
White House briefing. ``But we're going to continue working with
them with an eye toward meeting the deadline.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
