<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Friday, Jan. 21. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   TOP
</P>
<P>
   Lead story:
</P>
<P>
   LABOR-CORRUPTION (Undated) _ An internal report lays out a
picture of extensive corruption in a large union. The document
describes how top officials forged checks, made unauthorized
withdrawals from union accounts, siphoned dues into their own
accounts and used union credit cards for personal expenses. By
Steven Greenhouse. Eds.: Details are exclusive. (We plan to move
the story by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Top center story:
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-HELMS (United Nations) _ Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., chairman
of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee and one of the United
Nations' harshest critics, came to the Security Council Thursday
and said that the United States would remain involved with the
United Nations only if, when and how it wished, and pay dues only
when deserved. By Barbara Crossette. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m.
ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   With photos NYT8-10.
</P>
<P>
   Off-lead: 4-column snow photo, NYT7.
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-ADVISERS (Des Moines, Iowa) _ Bill Bradley does not have
advisers in the traditional sense _ and does not need any,
according to a number of those who are acting, as the candidate's
friend Dan Okimoto put it, ``more as a sounding board, raising
doubts here and there.'' But after several perceived missteps in
recent weeks even some supporters are saying the holes in the
campaign are inevitably starting to show. By Melinda Henneberger.
(Scheduled to move by 8 p.m. ET in ``p'' news file.) 1,500 words.
</P>
<P>
   With photos NYT12, 22.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-POLITICS (Hamburg, Germany) _ A leading finance official
of Germany's embattled Christian Democratic party committed suicide
after leaving a note indicating he had become aware of acts of
embezzlement. By Roger Cohen. (The story has moved in ``i'' news
file.) 1,200 words.
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   CENSUS-KICKOFF (Unalakleet, Alaska) _ Stanton Katchatag, an
82-year-old Inuit, answered a knock on his door here today at 10:50
a.m. and found Kenneth Prewitt, the director of the Census Bureau.
Pulling out the census short form he asked Katchatag his age, race
and the correct spelling of his name. This short interview began
the first census of the new century, an effort to count the U.S.
population and find out where every one of the estimated 275
million Americans are living on April 1. By Steven A. Holmes.
(Scheduled to move by 8 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.) 1,800 words.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   ELLIS-ISLAND-RESTORE (Trenton, N.J.) _ New Jersey officials
outline an ambitious, $300 million plan to restore Ellis Island,
most of which has been hidden from the millions who visit every
year, as a setting for world meetings along the lines of Versailles
or Geneva, and with new museums devoted to America's immigrant and
ethnic heritage and to the study of public health. By David M.
Halbfinger. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   With photo NYT13.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE STORIES PROMOTED ON PAGE 1:
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Mozdok, Russia) _ A senior Russian general
became an unfortunate symbol of the difficulties Russian troops
have endured in their campaign to take the Chechen capital, Grozny,
when he was reported missing there. By Michael R. Gordon. (The
story has moved in ``i'' news file.) 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-GREECE (Ankara, Turkey) _ Four years after Greece and
Turkey went to the brink of war over a barren islet in the Aegean
Sea, their foreign ministers meet to sign a series of accords and
pledge themselves to peace. By Stephen Kinzer. (The story has moved
in ``i'' news file.) 700 words.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   TRADE-DEFICIT (Washington) _ The insatiable American appetite
for German cars, French perfume and Japanese televisions has helped
the world's wealthiest countries grow faster than at any time since
the mid-1990s, but the United States is warning that its allies
need to join in the gluttony. The U.S. trade deficit with the rest
of the world set a new all-time high in November. By Joseph Kahn.
(Scheduled to move by 8:15 p.m. ET in ``f'' news file.) 1,000
words.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
