<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1680 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-GROZNY-FIGHTING-BOS &LR;      01-20 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROZNY-FIGHTING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHECHEN REBELS SAY THEY'VE CAPTURED RUSSIAN GENERAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN WHITMORE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Separatist guerrillas claimed Thursday to have captured
a ranking Russian general as fierce fighting continued for control
of Chechnya's capital Grozny, a feat that would strike a dramatic
blow to the Kremlin's military campaign against the separatist
republic.
</P>
<P>
   Major General Mikhail Malofeyev disappeared during fighting on
Monday and Chechen rebels said Thursday that he was taken prisoner.
The Russian Defense Ministry said only that Malofeyev was missing
in action.
</P>
<P>
   The apparent capture of the deputy commander of one of Russia's
three fronts in Grozny, which came as Russian forces seemed to be
regaining the advantage in the battle, was a major setback for the
Kremlin, observers here said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is significant in that it demonstrates the breakdown in
morale and discipline in the Russian army. This is a boost for the
Chechens and means shame for the Russians,'' said Pavel
Felgenhauer, a Moscow-based military analyst.
</P>
<P>
   Television news reports in Moscow gave varying accounts of the
circumstances surrounding Malofeyev's disappearance. Some said he
was shot by snipers while touring Grozny's northern districts,
which Russia claims to control, but others said he vanished during
street fighting in the capital.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Russian troops dodged sniper fire trying to tighten
their noose on the battered Chechen capital as tanks and helicopter
gunships continued to blast the city. Russian army officials said
warplanes and helicopters had flown more than 200 bombing raids and
claimed to be making slow but steady progress toward capturing
Grozny.
</P>
<P>
   Lieutenant General Stanislav Kavun was quoted by news agencies
as saying that Russian troops had control of ``a considerable
part'' of the Chechen capital and that rebels were ``suffering
heavy losses.''
</P>
<P>
   But an unidentified Russian officer in Grozny told NTV
television that the Chechens were putting up a fierce resistance as
they tried to hold their capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are extremely well prepared,'' the officer said of the
rebels. ``In our advance we have already had to cross three lines
of defense. As we get closer to the center the defenses get
stronger and stronger,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   After easily occupying Chechnya's northern region, Russian
troops have been bogged down for weeks trying to capture Grozny.
Chechen rebels still control most of the repubic's mountainous
south.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian military has boasted recently that Grozny would fall
in a matter of days. Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev said Thursday,
however, that the goal was not to meet deadlines, but to minimize
casualties among Russian soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of civilians are believed to be still trapped
in Grozny, unable to escape the fighting. Russia has come under
intense international criticism over the high number of civilian
casualties and for using excessive force in the four-month-old
military campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In a report released Thursday, the New York-based Human Rights
Watch, which has observers in the war-torn region, accused Russian
soldiers of raping Chechen women in the republic's Russian-occupied
areas. Citing eyewitnesses, the report described rapes in Shali, 16
miles southeast of Grozny, and Alkhan-Yurt, just southwest of the
capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rape is a war crime, and these allegations about rape in
Chechnya are very serious,'' the group said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
   The Council of Europe, the continent's highest human rights
body, has sent a delegation to Chechnya on a fact-finding mission.
Lord David Russell-Johnston, president of the council's
parliamentary assembly, visited the war zone this week and asked
Moscow to call a ceasefire and open peace talks with the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin launched its military assault on Chechnya in late
September after a series of apartment bombings that killed hundreds
of people in Moscow and other Russian cities. Russian officials
blamed Chechen rebels for the bombings, although the Chechens have
repeatedly denied any involvement in the blasts.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to preapre this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
