<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1682 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-CENSUS-KICKOFF-2TAKES     01-20 0496
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-KICKOFF-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH AID OF DOGSLED, A CENSUS BEGINS
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Alaska)   (jw) 
 By STEVEN A. HOLMES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNALAKLEET, Alaska _ Stanton Katchatag, an 82-year-old Inuit,
answered a knock on his door here Thursday at 10:50 a.m. and found
himself facing Kenneth Prewitt, the director of the Census Bureau.
Katchatag invited him in and offered a chair.
</P>
<P>
   Prewitt, who arrived on the back of a snowmobile at the end of a
trip that brought him across four time zones, got right down to
business. Pulling out the census short form, he asked Katchatag his
age, race and the spelling of his name.
</P>
<P>
   Describing the scene to reporters afterward, Katchatag said
Prewitt asked for similar information on the only other person
living in the one-story cedar-frame house, Katchatag's wife, Irene.
When the 15-minute interview was over Katchatag, whose ancestors
were among the first people to inhabit the North American
continent, became the first person to be officially counted in the
2000 census.
</P>
<P>
   Displaying plenty of excitement but only a vague grasp of
population figures, Mayor Henry Ivanoff of this tiny fishing
village on the Bearing Sea said, ``That means that over 225 million
people will be standing in line behind him, including the president
of the United States and the vice president, including the
governors and lieutenant governors of all the 50 states, including
Michael Jordan.''
</P>
<P>
   The interview here began the first census of the 2000s, an
effort to count the U.S. population and find out where every one of
the estimated 275 million Americans are living on April 1. The
Constitution calls for a count every 10 years to fix the number of
House seats for each state and states uses the numbers to draw
legislative districts. In addition, billions of dollars in federal
aid will be distributed on the basis of how the population is
counted.
</P>
<P>
   It is the largest peace-time operation undertaken by the federal
government and will take census workers to impoverished areas on
the Texas-Mexico border, to islands off the Maine Coast, and to
shifting groups of shanties erected by homeless people in the
nation's cities.
</P>
<P>
   This critical count is taking place in a country that is more
diverse than ever and that has often been termed less cooperative
than ever. It is also taking place when political power between the
major parties is balanced on a razor's edge.
</P>
<P>
   Forms will be mailed to more than 120 million households and
about a half million census takers will be dispatched to interview
the approximately 40 percent of households that do not return them.
Census statisticians will then tabulate the results for months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Census 2000 is the opportunity to paint a picture of the
country at one of its most dynamic periods in its history,'' said
Prewitt, who began the count going from house to house past
aluminum-frame herring fishing boats set on blocks in the front
yards.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
