<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1683 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-UN-HELMS-BOS &LR;      01-20 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-HELMS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HELMS WARNS UNITED NATIONS ON US SOVERIGNTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE LAURIA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Senator Jesse Helms, confronting an
organization he derides as overreaching and inefficient, bluntly
vowed to the Security Council Thursday that American power in the
world would never be usurped by the United Nation's ``utopian''
vision of a centralized world order.
</P>
<P>
   As chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, Helms has
led the fight aginst US payment of its UN dues and has blocked
several ambassadorial appointments, including that of former
governor William F. Weld.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's clash with the United Nations went beyond the issue
of the UN's budget and efficiency, touching off a philosophical
debate about sovereignty versus collective action.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many Americans sense that the UN has greater ambitions than
simply being an efficient deliverer of humanitarian aid, a more
effective peacekeeper, a better weapons inspector and a more
effective tool of great power diplomacy,'' Helms said. ``They see
the UN aspiring to establish itself as the central authority of a
new international order of global laws and global governance _ an
international order the American people will not countenance.''
</P>
<P>
   Helms, the first member of Congress to address the Security
Council, said the United States is fed up with routinely losing
General Assembly votes, being investigated for human rights abuses,
being called a ``deadbeat,'' being challenged on the ``inherent
legitimacy'' of intervening militarily, and with possibly becoming
a target of UN war crimes tribunals.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the UN seeks to impose its power and authority over
nation-states'' and instead does not remain ``just one part of
America's diplomatic arsenal . . . the American people will cast it
aside,'' he warned.
</P>
<P>
   Helms' at times harsh remarks appeared to shatter the normally
staid atmosphere of the UN chamber. The senator's comments also
drew immediate _ and at times, equally blunt _ responses.
</P>
<P>
   France lectured him on the importance of being tolerant of other
nations, and Namibia blamed Helms' support of the Reagan
administration's constructive engagement of apartheid South Africa
for delaying by several years the former South African colony's
independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The UN is important because it can give people freedom,''
Namibia's ambassador, Martin Andjaba, pointedly told Helms.
</P>
<P>
   Helms said Congress began withholding UN dues in the 1980s to
pressure the UN to reform. In response, the UN has had a
zero-growth budget for the past six years and has reduced staff by
10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Helms and Senator Joseph R. Biden, Democrat of Delaware, put
together a $926 million UN dues package last year signed by
President Clinton that is conditioned on a reduction of the US
contribution from 25 percent to 22 percent in the general UN budget
and from 31 percent to 25 percent in peacekeeping.
</P>
<P>
   Helms warned Thursday that if the UN rejects a reduced US rate
``it would mark the beginning of the end of US support for the
United Nations'' and the remaining $726 million would not be
released.
</P>
<P>
   After the meeting, Helms was asked by reporters whether anything
he heard had changed his perception of the UN. ``Not really,'' he
said. ``I expected the various comments that were made and they are
valid. But we've got to bring this thing to a meeting of minds and
the best way is for everyone to sit down together and talk about
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-00 1953EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000120.0231 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1684 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-CENSUS-KICKOFF-2NDTAK     01-20 1212
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-KICKOFF-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNALAKLEET, Alaska: front yards.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, the Census Bureau began the 1990 census in remote
parts of Alaska in the dead of winter two months before forms were
mailed out to the rest of the country. Bureau officials say it is
more efficient to try to count in person the estimated 50,000
people, mostly Inuits, who are scattered about the 250 million
square miles in the state's remotest areas. In winter, census
takers can travel by snow mobile and dog sled, before people
scatter to even more isolated hunting and fishing areas in the
spring.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the logistical, demographic and political challenges
facing the Census Bureau are as daunting as the trackless
wilderness outside Unalakleet.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   This year's census is by far the most expensive in American
history, even taking inflation into account. So far, the 2000
headcount is scheduled to cost $6.8 billion, a huge increase over
the $2.6 billion spent in 1990. Yet all the expense will not
protect the Census Bureau from challenges in the political arena
and the courts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're living in a period with very balanced political control
between Republicans and Democrats,'' said Margo Anderson, a
professor of history at the University of Wisconsin at Milwaukee
and an expert on the census. ``So both parties see opportunities in
the census, the redistricting process and the presidential election
to resolve the current stalemate to their advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   The bureau is hoping it can slow a decades-old decline in the
proportion of people who take the time to fill out their census
forms and mail them back. In 1990, 65 percent of American
households that received the form completed and returned it, down
from the 78 percent who did so in 1970. This year, the bureau is
planning on a 61 percent return rate.
</P>
<P>
   In Alaska, only 52 percent of the households that received the
forms sent them back in, the lowest mail response rate in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say social trends that have caused mail-back rates to
plummet have strengthened during the last 10 years. There are more
two-earner families with less time to fill out forms. People
receive more junk mail that is thrown out without a glance. The
proportion of the population made up by immigrants, who tend to be
less likely to complete the form, increased to 9.7 percent in 1997,
up from 7.9 percent in 1990. And such signs of civic participation
as voting rates are down.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``We're kind of in our own little worlds,'' said Robert Putnam,
a professor of public policy at Harvard's John F. Kennedy School
and author of ``Bowling Alone: The Collapse and Revival of American
Community,'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster). ``We don't feel an obligation to
our communities and don't connect with our communities.'' He added:
``This is why Ken Prewitt's goal to reverse this decline is such a
big challenge. He's running up a down escalator.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Census Bureau officials are planning a $102.8 million
advertising campaign _ the largest ever for a census _ aimed at
members of minority groups, renters and those living in mobile
homes, who tend not to return their census forms. Executives of
Young &AMP; Rubicam, which is handling the campaign, estimate that many
African-Americans will see the census commercials as many as 120
times and some Hispanics could see them as many 105 times by the
end of April.
</P>
<P>
   The bureau is also working with local governments and community
groups in an effort to persuade people to return the forms.
Starting on March 27, a short time after the forms are first sent
out and running until April 11, the bureau will post on the
Internet the mail-back rate for every city, town and village in the
country, hoping that publicizing the response rates will spur
competitions among municipalities.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Still, not everyone is pleased with the Census Bureau's efforts.
William Spriggs, director of research and public policy at the
National Urban League, said that beyond informing community groups
of the importance of the census, the bureau had come up with few
concrete ideas on how community organizations could help.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many cases, they have not done more than visit our
affiliates and say the census is important,'' Spriggs said. ``We've
known that for five years. So we are left relying on them because
we're not really in the process.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The bureau will also be trying to hire more than 500,000
temporary workers, in an economy with a jobless rate of 4.1 per
cent, the lowest it has been since the 1960s. Because there is such
a high turnover in these jobs, the bureau says it will need an
applicant pool of about 3 million people.
</P>
<P>
   Census officials are also striving to improve on their
performance from 1990 when, according to later studies, more than 8
million people were missed and another 4 million were counted
twice. The undercount was particularly severe among children,
African Americans living in central cities and Hispanics residing
in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that we're worried about is that the causes for the
undercount in 1990 haven't gone away; in some ways they've
increased,'' said Marisa Demeo, regional counsel for the Washington
office of the Mexican American legal Defense and Education Fund.
``So we know there still will be an undercount, even with the
bureau's best efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   To avoid a large undercount, officials plan to conduct a
nationwide survey of a randomly selected sample of 300,000
households. It will use the results to adjust population counts in
geographic areas containing on average 100 people. That statistical
sampling, while scientifically sound, has run afoul of partisan
politics. Because a large percentage of those missed, mainly racial
and ethnic minorities, tend to live in Democratic areas, adjusting
their population totals upward will give Democrats an advantage
when states draw new boundaries for congressional and state
legislative districts for the new decade.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the potential pitfalls, the bureau is ``more ready'' at
this point than in previous count years, said John Thompson,
associate director for the decennial census.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Oblivious to the concerns of the Census Bureau, the residents of
Unalakleet were thrilled to be the first place to be counted.
Scores of school children greeted Prewitt's flight from Anchorage
on Wednesday with hand-made welcome signs. He was given a
traditional parka trimmed in wolverine fur. Changing on the snowy
tarmac out of his black wing tips and into white insulated boots,
the he was whisked into town by dog sled.
</P>
<P>
   Census officials selected Unalakleet to kick off the new count
because of the town's reputation for welcoming outsiders. Indeed,
it is stop every March on the Iditarod dog race, and the
townspeople are used to the presence of news media and celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the old days we used to get folks like Terry Bradshaw and
Lynn Swann,'' said Tim Towarak, the city administrator. ``But this
is much more exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   And, he added, ``This is affecting the whole community.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-00 1953EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000120.0232 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1686 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BRADLEY-ADVISERS-ART-     01-20 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-ADVISERS-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOES BRADLEY'S LACK OF FORMAL ADVISERS MAKE MISSTEPS MORE LIKELY? 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also BRADLEY-CAMPAIGN) 
(ART ADV: Photos NYT12 and 22 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By MELINDA HENNEBERGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ Bill Bradley does not have advisers in the
traditional sense _ and does not need any, according to a number of
those who are acting, as the candidate's friend Dan Okimoto put it,
``more as a sounding board, raising doubts here and there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``His mastery obviates the need for close policy advisers,''
said Okimoto, a college buddy, now a professor of international
relations at Stanford, and someone with whom Bradley discusses a
number of matters, including foreign policy. ``There is no such
structure in place on foreign policy or any other issue. The
candidate is in charge of tone, direction, vision and those around
him provide support. Both in a political sense and on policy, Bill
Bradley is his campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   But after several perceived missteps recently _ a somewhat
confused response during an agriculture debate here, and especially
the decision to spend so much time in Iowa, where his campaign
appears to be lagging, instead of concentrating on New Hampshire,
where he's in a tight race _ even some supporters say the holes in
the campaign are starting to show.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Joe Trippi, an unaligned Democratic consultant who ran Walter
Mondale's Iowa campaign in 1984 and has had generally positive
things to say about Bradley's campaign over the last year, said,
``He really is running his campaign the way he wants to run it, and
I'm not sure he's taking any advice. That's always a bad sign. The
move to Iowa definitely was a risky gambit and I don't think I
would have advised it.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said, it is only after next Monday's caucuses that
``we'll see if Iowa was a big mistake _ or brilliant.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, one of Bradley's sounding boards, his wife, Ernestine
Schlant, a professor of comparative literature, has a theory about
politics that might apply: Any candidate's greatest asset almost
always turns out to be his greatest liability as well, she said in
an interview last summer, citing Bill Clinton and his personal
warmth and empathy as an example.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   While both Bradley's broad knowledge and his determination to
``run a different kind of campaign,'' as he likes to say, have been
keys to his appeal, they have also left him vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, both his Democratic opponent, Vice President Al Gore
and the Republican front-runner, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, have
been criticized for relying too much on consultants of all sorts.
But those in opposing camps _ advisers themselves, of course, with
a clear interest in the perceived importance of their work _ insist
that the lack of a more formal advisory structure in the Bradley
campaign is a problem. And say a truly smart candidate is smart
enough to know he needs help.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really arrogant and characteristically Bradley,'' said a
Bush adviser. ``The truth is that politics is a team sport. The
quarterback gets the credit, but you still need a defensive line,
and I haven't seen that in Bradley's camp, which is a huge
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Critics have called Bradley glacially slow in responding to
attacks, particularly on his health care plan, leaving Gore's
assertion t hat it would end up hurting poor people virtually
unchallenged.
</P>
<P>
   And because he chose to disarm unilaterally, when he finally did
fight back, for example by criticizing Gore's complicated history
with tobacco companies, what may have been perfectly legitimate
questions were seen as out of bounds because he had set himself up
as a candidate who was above that kind of give-and-take.
</P>
<P>
   On those and other campaign decisions, it is not that Bradley
listens to no one, but that , on the contrary, he listens to a
great number of people _ and then makes the important calls
himself. It was Bradley who chose child poverty, health care, race
relations and gun control as the central issues in his campaign.
And who, to a surprising degree, mapped out the plans he wanted to
see put in place.
</P>
<P>
   His staff insists that he does not micromanage, and is happy to
leave mechanical, logistical details like booking planes and
deciding which field directors go where to others. Even in this,
though, ``he does like to be keep informed, and will tell us if
we're going the wrong direction,'' said his campaign chairman,
Douglas Berman.
</P>
<P>
   And the list of ways Bradley is in control of his campaign is
staggering.
</P>
<P>
   Back when nobody but Bradley, Berman and a couple of other
Bradley die-hards thought it was possible to raise even a fraction
of the money the campaign has raised, the senator showed how it
could be done, by pulling in people who had not been politically
active before.
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Aronoff, his point person on policy, said that he had
been refining ideas for a health care plan for years and reached
out to hundreds of people.
</P>
<P>
   '`I don't think you're going to see every decision coming back
through him, but on health care _ the cornerstone _ or child
poverty, he takes an active interest. Or improving race relations.
Or key economic and foreign policy decisions.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   David Cutler, a Harvard economics professor considered one of
the chief architects of his health care plan, said, ``I don't
consider myself to be an incredibly important adviser.'' Told that
nobody else seemed to, either, he said, ``I had a sneaking
suspicion that was true.
</P>
<P>
   He's a very intelligent man, so he didn't need the getting up to
speed that a lot of candidates need.''
</P>
<P>
   The association is so loose, he added, that ``I don't think I've
ever actually met him. And I don't know if he's ever made a formal
decision that, `Oh, now you're x adviser.' I found him very
impressive _ and I don't know him well, so it's kind of the same
way I find the pope impressive _ but he listens to a lot of
voices.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Al Garber, a Stanford professor who was one of those ``putting
the details together'' for the basic plan that Bradley wanted said
the most surprising part of the process was the lack of
``dissension'' among those discussing the options. ``Everyone liked
Bill's idea, and it really is his plan,'' he said. ``He
incorporated diverse views and listened to a lot of people, but
within the campaign there was tremendous consensus, and that
probably reflects Bill.''
</P>
<P>
   On political strategy, too, he is also the final arbiter.
</P>
<P>
   And his staff includes a number of people who have been with him
so long that they often reflect the way he thinks. His campaign
chairman, Berman, who met Bradley when he was an adoring high
school senior, on the morning after the Knicks won an NBA
championship, has been with him since his first Senate campaign in
1977. His finance director, Rick Wright, played basketball with him
at Princeton 35 years ago. Ms. Aronoff was his longtime chief of
staff in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Of these, a friend and former aide to Bradley says, ``It would
only be a slight hyperbole to say Doug is the first person he calls
in the morning and the last one he talks to at night. On political
strategy, it's Doug and Bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Berman describes his job this way: ``If I have a role,'' he
said, ``it's being clear and helping people understand the values
that course through the organization as a reflection of Bill.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the proof that Bradley was not too much of a one-man
show was in the campaign's organizing successes: `We filed in 31 of
31 districts in New York, he was first to file in Oklahoma, we
raised twice as much money as the vice president in the fourth
quarter, and more people in California signed up to be delegates
for Bill Bradley than the vice president.''
</P>
<P>
   And Berman suggested that the campaign had, in fact, taken some
recent hits on purpose. When asked about Bradley's confused
response to a question about whether he had voted against flood
relief while in the Senate _ in fact, he had voted for the bill,
but against an amendment, Berman said, ``We never talk about
specific decisions. But Bradley has said, `I want to run a campaign
as an extension of the way I want to govern, to restore rust and
bring back civility.' And if you say that, you have to operate that
way. It's not that at times there's not the impulse to operate at a
different level. But those who elevate tactics, we disagree with.''
</P>
<P>
   To some degree, of course, the Bradley campaign's position that
it is above all that is itself a tactic. Whatever advice Bradley
does get is purposely underplayed by the campaign, which does not
want to be seen as doing much of anything in the usual way.
``Advisers,'' Berman said, ``are never the story.''
</P>
<P>
   And Richard Ravitch, who has reviewed some ideas about housing
and urban development with members of Bradley's staff, suggested
that the status of some of them was still a bit of a mystery _ even
to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where'd you get my name?'' Ravitch asked. Told he was
considered someone Bradley listens to, he said, ``Glad to hear
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
