r p BC-BUSH-JUSTICES-COX     01-20 0545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-JUSTICES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush says ``Roe v-- . Wade was a reach''
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PELLA, Iowa _ Inching closer to a litmus test that he so far has
refused to adopt, GOP presidential front-runner George W. Bush said
Thursday that he would appoint Supreme Court justices who would not
issue rulings like the one that ended state bans on abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roe v-- . Wade was a reach,'' Bush said. ``It overstepped the
constitutional bounds as far as I'm concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   For months, Bush has avoided taking a vow adopted by some of his
GOP opponents that would exclude the appointment of any justice who
would support abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's comments came while under increased fire from Republican
foes for not being more firm in his stand against abortion rights.
Challenger Steve Forbes, campaigning in Iowa in advance of the
Monday caucuses that kick off the delegate selection season, this
week called Bush a ``pro-life pacifist.''
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference after a speech at Central College here,
Bush renewed his promise to appoint ``strict constructionists'' to
the Supreme Court. He defined that as judges who would ``strictly
interpret the Constitution and not use the bench as a way to
legislate.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, except for the Roe v-- . Wade decision, declined to offer
examples of high court cases that either upheld that doctrine or
ran afoul of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to get into Supreme Court rulings. I'm not a
lawyer,'' said Bush, who long ago was denied admission to the
University of Texas School of Law.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also said that his belief that the Roe v-- . Wade decision
ran afoul of strict constructionism should not ``invite
speculation'' that he would make opposition to abortion rights a
litmus test in picking judges.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to name strict constructionists to the court,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, in response to reporters' questions, defended his
anti-abortion credentials. Unlike other GOP contenders, Bush's
standard stump speech includes no mention of abortion, a major
issue among a large segment of Republican voters here _ a tactic
seen as politically pragmatic but one that also makes Bush
vulnerable to criticism from supporters and opponents of abortion
rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a record. I've promoted adoptions in the state of
Texas. I signed a parental notification law. I worked hard for
abstinence education in the state of Texas. I've got a good strong
record. I've actually done in office. I've performed. You might
have to ask him about that,'' Bush said of Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   Bush believes abortion should be legal only in cases involving
rape, incest or pregnancies that endanger the mother. Despite his
anti-abortion rights stance, Bush has said he does not believe the
nation is ready to approve a constitutional amendment restricting
it.
</P>
<P>
   Asked Thursday what he would recommend for a relative who became
pregnant as a result of rape, Bush said he would ``hope to be able
to ... comfort her.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he would counsel against undergoing an abortion, Bush
said, ``It's up to her.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes, campaigning in Iowa, did not like the answer, saying it
is ``not enough just to say one is pro-life.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
