<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1690 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-ROME-2TAKES-$A     01-20 1109
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-ROME-2TAKES-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROME SHINES FORTH  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 23) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Paul II has summoned tens of millions of Roman Catholic
pilgrims to Rome for the 2,000 Jubilee, a Holy Year that is the
most ambitious ever planned by the Vatican. Taking a cue from the
many Romans who plan to flee, crowd-fearing tourists may decide to
skip the Italian capital altogether this coming year.
</P>
<P>
   The instinct is understandable, but it would be a pity.
</P>
<P>
   Woven into the Vatican's elaborate plans for millennial
religious events is one of the more extensive beautification
projects Rome has seen in a century, a sprawling canvas of restored
or cleaned churches, palaces, museums and piazzas that has brought
long-forgotten light and space to the ancient city.
</P>
<P>
   Rome, unlike other, younger European cities, did not erect any
new, grandiose monuments for the year 2000 such as the Millennium
Dome in London. Instead, it has taken a more humble approach of
sprucing up the oeuvre of preceding generations.
</P>
<P>
   Some Italian critics saw this as cowardice or inertia or both,
but the result is that more than any other city, Rome in the year
2000 will recapture some of the feeling it had in millenniums past.
</P>
<P>
   The most striking feature, and the one that most inspires fear
and anger in the hearts of Romans, is the way the city has used the
Jubilee as an excuse to reclaim streets, squares and public spaces
that for years have served as rush-hour shortcuts and parking lots,
and has turned them into pedestrian areas.
</P>
<P>
   Until last year, walking in the Piazza del Popolo, a large
neo-Classical square that frames twin baroque churches by Carlo
Rainaldi and Bernini, was about as pleasant as crossing an
interstate at rush hour. Cars and motorbikes whizzed around and
around the 1200 B.C. Egyptian obelisk (brought to Rome by Augustus
2,000 years ago).
</P>
<P>
   Now, cars have been rerouted, and the center of the piazza is
reserved for pedestrians and horse-drawn carriages. Walking across
the Piazza del Popolo these days feels a little like it must have
when Giuseppe Valadier designed it in the 19th century.
</P>
<P>
   The same is true of the Campo dei Fiori, where the philosopher
Giordano Bruno was burned at the stake for heresy in 1600 and which
now serves as the city's most colorful outdoor food market. Campo
dei Fiori was closed down for most of 1999 to put in new sewers,
relaid the cobblestones and eliminate the narrow street and
sidewalk around the square.
</P>
<P>
   Cars, which once circled like predatory sharks around the fruit
stands and fishmongers, are banned. Visitors can shop or sit at the
outdoor cafes that line the square without fear of being run over
or mixing exhaust fumes with their espressos.
</P>
<P>
   The city has similarly reclaimed some 100 piazzas, infuriating
residents who now have no place to leave their cars, and who as
recently as the 1970s, could park with impunity even in St. Peter's
Square.
</P>
<P>
   At some places, the absence of cars _ as in a small square in
front of Chiesa Nuova _ is almost imperceptible. At other places,
like Piazza Trilussa, in Trastevere on the west side of the Tiber
facing the newly restored Ponte Sisto, there is a startlingly
agreeable contrast with the recent past.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor of Rome, Francesco Rutelli, risked a public lynching
by decreeing that the reclaimed piazzas will be kept clear of cars
not just for the Jubilee but for the years that follow, though that
remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   In Rome, automobiles are a little like the weeds that grow in
the cracks of the Aurelian walls _ no matter how much you trim them
back, they keep sprouting up anew.
</P>
<P>
   Many visitors may be tempted to steer clear of St. Peter's and
other basilicas where pilgrims will congregate by the tens of
thousands, and that can be done.
</P>
<P>
   The newly opened Domus Aurea, the ruins of Nero's palace across
from the Colosseum, will be almost irresistible. In stark contrast
to the monuments to the power of Renaissance and
Counter-Reformation popes, tourists can relive the wicked ways of
the emperor who slaughtered early Christians.
</P>
<P>
   But it seems almost churlish to completely eschew a
centuries-old pageant that takes place only once every 25 years
(though the more ambitious popes sometimes call extraordinary
jubilees; John Paul II did so in 1983, to commemorate the 1,950th
anniversary of the death of Jesus, and that was seen as a kind of
dress rehearsal for this year.)
</P>
<P>
   Since 1300, the year Pope Boniface VIII first summoned the
faithful to Rome because the crusades had made travel to the Holy
Land too risky, pilgrims have been rewarded with a plenary
indulgence, a remission of punishment for sins. Pope John Paul has
broadened the process for earning an indulgence (a visit to the
Rome airport chapel counts, and so does quitting smoking for a
day), but traditionalists will still visit at least one of Rome's
four main basilicas.
</P>
<P>
   St. Peter's will, of course, be the spiritual epicenter of the
Jubilee, though the Vatican has planned to hold its largest
gatherings, like the Mass concluding the 15th World Youth Day on
Aug. 20, in a field outside the city. The restored 17th-century
facade of St. Peter's, which was unveiled last September after
remaining under scaffolding for almost two years, is less somber,
thanks to restorers' recovery of the original tones, which include
green and reds around the main entrance.
</P>
<P>
   Even nonbelievers may be tempted to brave long lines to cross
through the Holy Door, which the pope opened on Christmas Eve, in a
solemn ritual that dates back to 1450, symbolizing the start of a
Jubilee. The door is bricked over when the Holy Year ends.
</P>
<P>
   But one of the most compelling stops on the pilgrims' route is
St. John Lateran, the first Christian basilica, between the
Colosseum and the Basilica of Santa Croce in Gerusalemme. It was
built by Emperor Constantine in the early fourth century and
renovated in the 17th century by Borromini. It was the church of
the Popes until the 14th century, and served as the model for many
early Christian churches.
</P>
<P>
   A little like Boston or St. Petersburg in the shadow of New York
and Moscow, St. John Lateran has a slightly forlorn, second-place
feel to it that has its own melancholy appeal. (In Henry James'
``Portrait of a Lady,'' Isabel Archer went there to seek
``companionship in endurance'' when her marriage unraveled.)
</P>
<P>
   Even though some of its art treasures and holy relics were moved
to St. Peter's, St. John Lateran remains extraordinarily beautiful,
rich in both medieval mosaics and baroque sculptures.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Jubilee history buffs may want to inspect the small portrait of
Boniface VIII proclaiming the first Holy Year, a fragment of a
fresco believed to have been executed by Giotto, above the
middle-right aisle.
</P>
<P>
   Across from St. John Lateran, is the Scala Santa, a holy
staircase that, according to legend, was taken from the palace of
Pontius Pilate in Jerusalem and was trod upon by Jesus. Pilgrims
ascend the stairs on their knees to the Sancta Sanctorum, an
indulgence-earning rite of humility that also holds a certain
fascination for protestants; some biographers believe that Martin
Luther was in the act of climbing the stairs when he had a sudden
flash of reformist inspiration, and quit midstep.
</P>
<P>
   The steps lead to the pope's private chapel, which is now open
to the public and includes a portrait on wood of Jesus painted by
St. Luke _ and according to legend, completed by an angel.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most alluring feature, however, is a newly
landscaped pedestrian piazza in front of the basilica, which melts
into a large park, a lovely, tree-lined pedestrian path along the
Porta San Giovanni, that leads from St. John Lateran to the
Basilica of Santa Croce in Gerusalemme, another holy shrine revered
for its relics of the true cross.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Maria Maggiore is a fourth-century church and the only one
of the main basilicas that has mostly retained its original form.
Its fifth-century mosaics depicting scenes from the lives of Jesus
and Mary are among the most impressive of the period. There, too,
the outside area has been relandscaped to accommodate visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Basilica-Hopping, however, will be something of a challenge.
Transportation in Rome, reliably unreliable at the best of times,
is not likely to grow efficient in 2000. Even the government agency
in charge of boosting the city's jubilee preparations bluntly warns
visitors on its Web site, www.comune.roma.it, ``It is not easy to
get around Rome.''
</P>
<P>
   The city, which has banned private tour buses from parking near
the Vatican, has laid on 112 blue Jubilee buses to shuttle pilgrims
and tourists from lots outside the city to religious sites around
the center. The Vatican built a six-story underground garage to
accommodate 800 cars and 115 buses.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, perhaps, today's pilgrims will be able to travel
from shrine to shrine by car and bus, while ordinary tourists will
be best off touring the city on foot.
</P>
<P>
   The area around the Piazza del Campidoglio, designed by
Michelangelo in the ancient heart of Rome, has been completely
cleaned. The Capitoline Museums _ repository of sculptures
including the original equestrian statue of Marcus Aurelius, and
the celebrated ``Dying Galatian'' _ and the Capitoline picture
gallery _ with works by Caravaggio, Titian and Rubens _ have been
completely renovated and enlarged.
</P>
<P>
   Not far, even by foot, are the former papal stables at the
Quirinale, an 18th-century building restored last year and opened
for the first time ever to the public in December. Rome is not
known for its modern exhibition spaces, but the stables were
re-designed to allow contemporary-style shows, ranging this year
from an exhibition of French Impressionist paintings from the
Hermitage in St. Petersburg to a Botticelli show, to an exhibition
of photographs by Sebastiao Salgado.
</P>
<P>
   Italian museums, long derided for shoddy lighting, indifferent
guides and baffling hours, have undergone a major overhaul. Hours
have been extended and visitor services, from bookshops to
cafeterias, have been expanded; Rome is one of the main
beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   The Villa Borghese, Rome's most famous public park, has seen
some of the most dramatic improvements. The Borghese Gallery was
reopened three years ago after a 13-year restoration.
</P>
<P>
   Next to it, the secret gardens, so-called because the Borghese
family rather ungenerously kept their private fruit and vegetable
patches walled from view, were reland-scaped and reopened in
December.
</P>
<P>
   The Villa Giulia, the museum of Etruscan Art, has been
completely overhauled, adding new sections that give more
intelligent display to its ancient artifacts, including the
Castellani collection of ceramics, bronzes and gold jewelry, which
has not been seen for more than 10 years. Just down the Viale delle
Belle Arti, the National Gallery of Modern Art is now completely
renovated and open to the public.
</P>
<P>
   New museums are also opening. For 20 years, Palazzo Poli, the
imposing 18th-century palace to which the Trevi fountain is
attached, lay idle. In May, it will become part of the National
Institute for Graphic Arts and hold the world's most important
collection of copper-plate engravings, including all the engravings
of Piranesi, the 18th-century artist famous for his views of Rome.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more unusual museums is just off the Piazza del
Popolo. The Hendrik Christian Anderson Museum, which opened in
December, was once the home of Anderson, an American sculptor and
painter who was born in Norway and lived in Rome from 1896 to his
death in 1940.
</P>
<P>
   It is to be used for short-term exhibits, but also reverently
displays the owner's sculptures, paintings and drawings for his
utopian vision of a ``World City.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Rome's least-loved building, the Victor Emmanuel II
Monument on the Piazza Venezia, an opulent 262-foot-high white
marble confection known to Italians as ``the wedding cake'' and
``the typewriter,'' was included in the restoration effort. The
building, begun in 1885 and completed in 1911, was meant to glorify
Italian unity under the Savoy monarchy, but now mostly symbolizes
fin-de-siecle bad taste.
</P>
<P>
   The cleaning has brought back its original brightness. The
better news is that a vast, high-tech visitors center was
constructed inside, which can help guide visitors to other, newly
appealing parts of the city.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
