<HEADER>
A1692 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u p BC-CAMPAIGN-BUSH-BOS &LR;      01-20 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BUSH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH ATTACKS USE OF ABORTION PILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PELLA, Iowa _ Texas Governor George W. Bush, his conservative
credentials under scrutiny four days before the Iowa caucuses, drew
his firmest line yet on abortion Thursday, saying he would reject
the abortion pill if it were approved by the Federal Drug
Administration and dismissing the Supreme Court decision Roe v.
Wade as ``a reach.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said the 1973 court decision that legalized abortions
``overstepped the constitutional bounds.'' But he refused to say if
he would choose a Supreme Court nominee based on the person's views
on abortion views, instead repeating his vow to nominate judges
only on their strict reading of the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   The comments followed a television advertisement by millionaire
publisher Steve Forbes accusing Bush of being a ``pro-life
pacifist.'' Campaign aides insisted Bush's remarks were nothing
new. But they were in stark contrast to Bush's recent silence on
abortion during speeches, and they fit into a familiar candidate
strategy in the waning hours before the Iowa caucuses: playing to
more conservative voters in the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has hardly raised the topic on the campaign trail in recent
days, hammering voters instead with his other pet themes: tax cuts,
the military, restoring dignity to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   But he frequently responds to abortion questions when asked, and
Thursday the comments came at a news conference after a speech at
Central College here. Seeming reluctant to pursue the issue at
first, Bush eventually reiterated how he would handle selecting
justices for the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would appoint strict constructionists,'' he said. Asked to
clarify that, he said: ``Someone who views the Constitution and
strictly uses the Constitution for what it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the abortion pill called RU-486, Bush also made his stance
clearer. If the FDA were to approve it, he said, ``I would be
inclined not to accept that ruling by the FDA.''
</P>
<P>
   On the first day of his presidential term in 1993, President
Clinton changed a number of abortion-related policies established
by Bush's father when he was president.
</P>
<P>
   Among Clinton's policy changes was his acceptance of the
French-made pharmaceutical that terminates a pregnancy in its
earliest days. Since then, the FDA has determined that RU-486 is
``safe and effective.'' But the agency is waiting to formally
approve the pill until all manufacturing and labeling details have
been determined.
</P>
<P>
   In the previous administration, President Bush had refused to
act on getting approval for RU-486 and had opposed abortion rights.
His wife Barbara, however, has said she does not believe abortion
should be a part of the Republican Party plank. News accounts have
also reported she supports legalized abortion outright.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush would not discuss his mother's position on
abortion Thursday. Nor would he say whether he had discussed the
issue with his 18-year-old twin girls. ``I'm not going to talk
about my daughters' point of view. They're part of my private
life,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He offered only one personal glimpse. Asked how he would advise,
theoretically, a female friend who had been raped and become
pregnant, Bush said he hoped he ``would be able to evoke enough
sympathy'' for her. Asked what he would suggest her to do, Bush
replied: ``It's up to her.''
</P>
<P>
   The abortion remarks briefly overshadowed the chief debate of
the Republican presidential primary thus far: tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Senator John McCain of Arizona have been sparring for
days over each other's tax cut proposals, focusing on a component
of McCain's $237 billion plan that would tax some employer benefits
such as transportation.
</P>
<P>
   Bush had singled out that part of the plan as harmful, saying it
would raise taxes by $40 billion. McCain fiercely objected, saying
the amount would be no more than $3.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   After arguing that particular point for days _ and, in Bush's
case, releasing a campaign ad about it _ Bush Thursday indicated he
might be willing to accept he had been wrong in summarizing the
figures in McCain's tax plan.
</P>
<P>
   Bush defended his criticisms of McCain's overall tax plan,
however, which is nearly half the size of his own. He also pointed
out that his remarks about McCain were based directly on the policy
paper the Arizona senator released.
</P>
<P>
   ``Evidently he changed his plan,'' Bush said. ``I just wanted to
know, John, why? I think the people needed to know exactly what was
in the plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Of Bush's detailed attacks, McCain said: ``My eyes glaze over.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has made taxes the centerpiece of his public appearances in
Iowa and New Hampshire, touting his more than $483 billion tax cut
alongside a mantra of returning money to taxpayers. Thursday, he
announced a new ``tax calculator'' on his Web site, saying it will
allow voters to calculate their savings under his plan.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Yvonne Abraham of the Globe staff contributed to this report from
New York.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
