<SLUG> BC-TEXASDEMS21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gore solidifies spot in Texas
 &HT;    By Scott S. Greenberger
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ As they trudged through Iowa and New Hampshire
this week, Democratic presidential hopefuls Al Gore and Bill
Bradley may have missed an important development in Pasadena,
Texas: Ceole Speight put on a campaign button.
</P>
<P>
   Speight, an AFL-CIO employee, was undecided for months. Last
fall, she was leaning toward Bradley because she was worried about
Gore's electability. But after hearing about Gore at the Texas
AFL-CIO convention in Austin this week, Speight finally picked her
pin: Gore 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Her choice may be emblematic of broader trends in Texas, which
will hold its presidential primary March 14. Several months ago, as
Bradley surged in the polls and the Gore campaign lurched toward a
much-needed overhaul, the Texas race looked like a toss-up. But
Gore has since solidified his position with organized labor,
Hispanics, and other traditionally Democratic constituencies, and
now he looks tough to beat in the Lone Star State.
</P>
<P>
   ``That man is going to be fantastic. He's done an awful lot for
labor,'' Speight said of her newfound champion. ``Anything but
(Republican George W.) Bush _ and I think Gore has the best chance
of beating him.''
</P>
<P>
   A poll released last Friday showed Gore with a comfortable 54
percent to 25 percent lead over Bradley in Texas. The Dallas
Morning News/Houston Chronicle survey, which had a margin of error
of 6 percentage points, also showed Gore running slightly better
than Bradley in a match-up against Bush. And last week the Tejano
Democrats, who only endorse when they can muster a two-thirds
majority, backed Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas State Teachers Association, the Texas Federation of
Teachers and the state AFL-CIO don't endorse national candidates,
but their national affiliates have lined up behind Gore in recent
months.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got teachers, labor, the Tejano Democrats and 400
elected Hispanic officials _ there aren't many places for Bradley
to go,'' said Garry Mauro, the Democrats' 1998 gubernatorial
nominee and a co-chairman of Gore's Texas campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley supporters say it's too early to assess the former New
Jersey senator's chances in Texas. They contend that if Bradley
does well in Iowa on Jan. 24 and in New Hampshire on Feb. 1, he'll
get a boost in New York and California on March 7. And if he does
well in those primaries, he could cruise into Texas with a powerful
tailwind.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the early primary states, where Bradley has already engaged
voters, his popularity has skyrocketed,'' said Harold Cook, the
former head of the Texas Democratic Party and a Bradley adviser.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has raised about $600,000 of his $27 million from Texas
donors, but he hasn't yet opened a campaign office in the state.
The Gore campaign, which couldn't say how much the vice president
has collected in Texas, plans to open offices Tuesday, though they
wouldn't release details. Both campaigns say they have Texas
leaders in place, and will be ready to push hard here once the New
Hampshire primary is over.
</P>
<P>
   Florida, Louisiana, Mississippi, Oklahoma and Tennessee also
will hold primaries on March 14, but Texas and Florida loom largest
because they offer the most delegates. Mauro said Gore may have
clinched the nomination before March 14, but Cook says Bradley's
fund-raising success _ he's collected about as much as Gore
nationally _ means the race will ``go down to the wire.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore had the lion's share of the Democratic insiders
wrapped up long ago. But in the final analysis, the March 14
primary isn't going to be about the Democratic leadership, it's
going to be about primary voters,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cook added that Bradley courted the Tejano Democrats ``out of
respect'' but knew he didn't have a legitimate shot at getting
their endorsement because they are Democratic insiders, too.
</P>
<P>
   But Ed Martin, a former head of the Texas Democratic Party who
hasn't chosen sides in the Gore-Bradley race, said the support of
Democratic leaders is critical because it translates into a
superior campaign organization. Martin said ``the inherent
strengths and advantages that a vice president tends to have'' are
likely to be pivotal in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Those strengths were evident during the competition for the
Tejano Democrats' endorsement. Both candidates have met with the
Tejano Democrats during the campaign, and both sent close family
members _ Gore sent his daughter and Bradley sent his wife _ to the
convention last week. Both mailed campaign literature to members
and had people working the convention floor.
</P>
<P>
   After interviewing Gore and Bradley by phone, the group's
leaders were hard-pressed to distinguish between them on the
issues. But in the end, Bradley failed to sway the one-third of
delegates he needed to block a Gore endorsement. Sen. Gonzalo
Barrientos, who heads the Tejano Democrats, said party loyalty _
and connections _ made the difference. ``One of the things it says
is that Vice President Gore has a little advantage insofar as being
able to work the party machinery,'' said Barrientos, who hasn't
endorsed either candidate.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
