<HEADLINE>
GORE, BRADLEY CONTINUE EXCHANGING BARBS IN IOWA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN AND MICHAEL CROWLEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COUNCIL BLUFF, Iowa _ Winding down the days to the Iowa
caucuses, Al Gore and Bill Bradley traded barbs on who cares more
about the nation's first presidential contest.
</P>
<P>
   It began when Vice President Gore accused the former New Jersey
senator of being disrespectful to Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   ``My opponent ... has spent more money here than any Democratic
candidate in the history of the United States of America,'' Gore
told an enthusiastic crowd in the Iowa Western Community College
gymnasium.
</P>
<P>
   ``But after all of that money ...he has evidently developed a
new vision of the Iowa caucuses. He said `Iowa rewards entrenched
power,''' said Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to say that fighting to reduce the high cost of
pharmaceuticals, fighting to save Medicare...that's not entrenched
power. That is fighting for people!'' Gore declared with a thrust
of his fist, drawing wild applause from the audience of mostly
senior citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was quoting from a news report of Bradley's comments
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley spokesman Eric Hauser said the former senator respects
Iowans and their caucuses. And the Bradley campaign unearthed
quotes they attributed to Gore during his 1988 campaign for
president, in which he called the Iowa caucuses ``madness'' and a
contest that ``distorts the process.''
</P>
<P>
   With several days of campaigning to go before Iowa Democrats
gather Monday in living rooms and community centers to vote for a
presidential nominee, the fight has come down to perception of
victory, instead of absolute victory.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley wants to convince the nation that a loss here does not
mean his challenge to the sitting vice president has failed.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking with reporters after an appearance in eastern Iowa,
Bradley fended off speculation _ encouraged by the Gore campaign _
that his candidacy is stalling here and in New Hampshire. Bradley
trails in most Iowa polls by 20 points or more, and Gore aides say
their internal polling shows Bradley slipping in New Hampshire,
where the two have been in a tight race.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're staying with our basic strategy... I'm upbeat about
this, quite frankly,'' Bradley said. Still, Bradley acknowledged
that Gore's relentless criticisms of his health-care plan may have
taken a toll.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think to a certain extent some voters might have been swayed
by that,'' Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's comments Thursday about Bradley's attitude toward Iowa
represented an expansion of his assaults on health care.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never criticized him personally and I never will,'' Gore
said Thursday. Soon afterward, he reminded the Iowa Democrats that
Bradley has said he admires the governing style of former President
Ronald Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Bradley kicked off a four-day bus tour through
eastern Iowa by making a vigorous pitch for his health-care plan.
He told an audience of senior citizens that his proposal was on par
with the creation of Social Security by Franklin D. Roosevelt and
Medicare by Lyndon B. Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both of those leaders saw something big that needs to be done,
acted on it, and in so doing made all of our lives better,''
Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley was also determined to reassure his audience that
his $650 billion, 10-year plan would not leave Medicare or Social
Security at risk, as Gore has charged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people say you've got to choose _ that you can either
protect Medicare or provide health insurance for all Americans,''
said Bradley in a clear reference to Gore.``I say, `No, you can do
both.'''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley also complained that most voters were unaware of the
``most underreported'' part of his proposal: tax deductions on
health-care costs that Bradley said will amount to a $25 billion
tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   The Bradley campaign announced Thursday it will run two new
advertisements here this weekend, one featuring Nebraska Senator
Robert Kerrey, who announced Thursday that he will not seek
re-election this year, and another with former Boston Celtic star
Bill Russell, a friend from Bradley's pro basketball days. The
campaign also announced the endorsement of Betty Friedan, the
feminist author and co-founder of the National Organization for
Women.
</P>
</TEXT>
