<HEADLINE>
LEADERS MEET OVER SENIOR DRUG BENEFIT PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Pharmaceutical industry leaders met Thursday with
top aides to President Clinton in a further sign that the
government may soon help seniors cover the cost of prescription
drugs through the Medicare program.
</P>
<P>
   The industry and Democratic leaders say they want to offer a
drug benefit, but they are at odds over the details. Drug companies
oppose a plan President Clinton laid out last year. The industry
fears any development that would give the government a hand in
setting prices, and it does not want the government to choose which
drugs would qualify for insurance reimbursement and which would
not.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, industry officials decided to work with Clinton to
devise a benefit plan rather than fight an idea that has become
increasingly popular with voters, who complain of rising drug
prices.
</P>
<P>
   Before visiting the White House Thursday, two industry leaders,
Raymond Gilmartin, chief executive of Merck &AMP; Co. Inc., and Gordon
Binder, chief executive of Amgen Inc., met with Senator Edward M.
Kennedy, who strongly supports a drug benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional and White House aides said that the two sides have
modified several long-held positions to agree on a set of
principles. While falling short of a complete roadmap for
legislation, the principles are a starting point for devising a
drug benefit.
</P>
<P>
   According to aides, the agreement says that all Medicare
beneficiaries should be covered by the new benefit, with extra
assistance for low-income people. Previously, industry officials
had pushed for a smaller benefit targeted at low-income people,
aides said.
</P>
<P>
   In a concession to the industry, the agreement also says that
the benefit would be administered by a new, independent government
agency, rather than by the agency that runs Medicare. This new
agency might survey changes in the cost of prescription drugs each
year and determine the annual premium for the drug benefit, similar
to the way cost-of-living raises are determined for Social Security
recipients.
</P>
<P>
   Coverage would be offered through competing, private plans that
rely on marketplace competition to control costs. But the
government could devise ways to buy drugs in bulk and win volume
discounts, an idea President Clinton included in his proposal last
year.
</P>
<P>
   The benefit would cover all drugs, suggesting that the
government could not favor one type of heart medication, for
example, over another.
</P>
<P>
   Aides also said that the industry is now willing to back the
benefit as a stand-alone piece of legislation. Previously, the
industry wanted the benefit to be included as part of a broad
Medicare reform, which in itself would face long odds of passage in
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Representing Clinton at the White House meeting Thursday were
Chief of Staff John Podesta, Health and Human Services Secretary
Donna Shalala and several other officials.
</P>
<P>
   Representing the industry were Binder, who is also chairman of
the Pharmaceutical Research and Manufacturers of America,
Gilmartin, Alan Holmer, the president of the trade group, and
Robert Wilson of Johnson &AMP; Johnson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
