<SLUG> BC-TRADE-DEFICIT-ART-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ITS TRADE GAP WIDENING, U.S. WANTS OTHER NATIONS TO IMPORT MORE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The insatiable American appetite for German cars,
French perfume and Japanese televisions has helped the world's
wealthiest countries grow faster than at any time since the
mid-1990s, but the United States is warning that its allies need to
join in the gluttony.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. trade deficit with the rest of the world set a new
all-time high in November, statistics released Thursday show. Led
by purchases of autos, electronics, oil and clothing abroad, the
United States posted a monthly trade deficit of $26.5 billion, a
nagging indicator that not everything is perfect in America's
otherwise rosy economic picture.
</P>
<P>
   Based on November's numbers, the U.S. deficit was on course to
reach $267 billion for all of last year, about $100 billion more
than 1998, which was itself a record year. The momentum is also
worrying. Imports grew at double the rate of exports.
</P>
<P>
   Reducing the swelling trade gap is the Clinton administration's
top priority at a gathering of world finance ministers in Tokyo
this weekend. Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers, speaking in
advance of the Group of Seven finance ministers meeting, said that
Europe and Japan need to start thinking big and growing fast, much
like the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``In both Europe and Japan, there's a complacency of low
expectations,'' Summers said. ``The world cannot indefinitely
sustain the present level of imbalances.''
</P>
<P>
   America's stellar growth means that it's consuming more than its
fair share of world output. Europe and Japan have the potential to
grow faster if they loosen up the reins on their economies and
worry less about inflation, Summers said. Ideally, both major
trading partners would then buy more U.S. goods and help even out
global trade.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. trade deficit has been a persistent concern for years,
of course. But U.S. policy-makers are frustrated by its
stubbornness during a period of relative prosperity abroad.
</P>
<P>
   The deficit was supposed to level out, or begin contracting, now
that the rest of the world has started growing again after the
slump that began during the global financial crisis of 1997.
Instead, it continues to set new records, month after month.
</P>
<P>
   Though the deficit is a bigger burden on the economy now than it
was in the 1980s, it has a lower political profile. Few economists
or politicians question the competitiveness of the United States
now as they did then. With inflation staying low and the government
running a budget surplus, the United States is better equipped
today to handle a big deficit than it was 15 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Some even argue that a surge of inexpensive imports has helped
propel the U.S. economy to its current heights. Imports seem to
have helped keep inflation down, allowing the Federal Reserve to
raise interest rates less than it otherwise would. And by buying
manufactured goods abroad for less than they can be made here,
capital has been freed up for investment in the hottest sectors of
U.S. economy, like technology and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the swell in the trade gap poses some dangers. It reveals
a persistent weakness in U.S. manufacturing industries, like
automobiles. Despite the fact that German and Japanese automakers
have invested billions of dollars in the United States to build
cars here _ meaning that the Toyota, Honda and even BMW and
Mercedes-Benz brand names no longer always signal an import _ the
American passion for high-end, foreign-made cars remains one of the
biggest overall contributors to the trade deficit.
</P>
<P>
   A larger concern, at least for economists, is the challenge the
deficit poses to the dollar. Through the record economic expansion
of the 1990s, the U.S. has sought to keep the dollar strong. But
the ever widening trade deficit needs to be paid back, sooner or
later, by a surge in exports or a decline in the value of the
dollar relative to other currencies, or both.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``Every time we have run a big deficit we have ended up with a
big decline in the dollar, and that is bound to happen again,''
said C. Fred Bergsten, who runs the Institute of International
Economics. ``The real question is whether the dollar decline is
hard or soft. The administration is doing what it can to make sure
it's soft.''
</P>
<P>
   The dollar has already lost about a third of its value against
the Japanese yen in recent months. It has remained strong against
the euro, Europe's single currency, but many economists see the
dollar weakening sharply if the trade gap persists.
</P>
<P>
   Predicting the demise of the United States economy has been a
fool's game in recent years. But one possible scenario for the end
of the long expansion begins with a steep fall in the dollar. That
would likely prompt a surge of inflation, causing the Fed to
increase interest rates, choking growth.
</P>
<P>
   If Europe and Japan were to start investing more in their own
economies, and buying more abroad, some pressure on the dollar
would ease, padding the ground for a soft landing, the thinking
goes.
</P>
<P>
   Summers' not-so-subtle plea to allies abroad is raise the speed
limit on economic growth by setting aside, as the United States has
in recent years, the idea that it's better to keep growth well
below its potential than to risk even modest inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Europe and Japan are both growing ``well below their
potential,'' Summers said. ``Having achieved a cyclical expansion
does not constitute the basis for relaxation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Though Japan has made a massive injection of public capital into
its economy and lowered interest rates to near zero, Summers argues
that it must commit to do so going forward. Japan could also do
more to stoke its moribund economy by lowering barriers to
investment, trade and labor mobility.
</P>
<P>
   Europe is a bigger problem for the Clinton administration. Led
by France, many economies there are growing faster now than in
recent years. But central bankers have quickly raised interest
rates to head off potential inflation and keep the newly unified
currency strong, disappointing the United States.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
