<HEADLINE>
HOME HEATING-OIL PRICES HIT HIGHEST LEVEL IN 9 YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A combination of a brutal cold snap and the
determination of OPEC oil ministers has driven Massachusetts
heating oil prices to their highest level in nine years, with no
signs petroleum-producing nations are wavering in their pact to
keep output tight and prices high.
</P>
<P>
   The latest state survey of oil dealers, conducted Monday, found
retail prices have hit $1.17 a gallon for home heating oil, which
in noninflation-adjusted terms is the highest price seen here since
the Gulf War of 1990-91, when prices jumped as high as $1.37.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think on average (wholesale) oil prices have gone up on
average 4 to 5 cents a day for the last seven days,'' said Dick
Horan Sr. of Hughes Oil in West Roxbury, a 47-year veteran of the
heating business whose company was posting a $1.38 a gallon price
Thursday. ``It's just been really, really wild.''
</P>
<P>
   The root cause for the spike appears to be commodity-market
speculation linked to both a sudden spurt in northern US demand for
heating oil after two mild winters, and to new signs that the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries ministers will
probably extend their yearlong production cap when they next meet
in March.
</P>
<P>
   Local specialists disagree over whether the cold weather or OPEC
is more to blame.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't tell me it's the weather, because one week of weather
shouldn't be causing this kind of change,'' said Larry Chretien,
executive director of the Boston Oil Consumers Alliance, a
6,000-member buying cooperative. ``It's not a free market here,
it's a rigged market, and in this country we would call what OPEC
is doing antitrust.''
</P>
<P>
   Chretien's group is backing some Capitol Hill leaders who are
calling on President Clinton to draw down oil from strategic
government reserves to undercut OPEC efforts to drive up prices. He
also said that the recent crude oil price increase to $29 a barrel
is the driving factor behind nascent inflation increases that will
probably make the Federal Reserve raise interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   David O'Connor, state energy resources commissioner, said,
``OPEC has really been sticking to their production quotas, unlike
previous years when they had them but didn't stick to them. Add a
little cold weather, and, bingo, the prices really start escalating
dramatically.''
</P>
<P>
   The current $1.17 average price is, in nominal terms, the
highest price seen since February 1991, when prices hit $1.21 a
gallon during the Gulf War. During the winter of 1996-97, prices
climbed to $1.15, but for most of the last year have been in the
80-cent range.
</P>
<P>
   To some extent the current sticker shock may reflect a long
period of complacency for Massachusetts heating oil users after
back-to-back mild winters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the whole system has sort of relaxed after the last
three mild winters,'' Hughes Oil's Horan said. ``What we have here
is a very short-term spike. The total cure-all is three to four
days of 35 degree weather. The first sign of moderation, the price
will drop like a rock.''
</P>
<P>
   The wholesale New York Harbor price for heating oil hit $1.06
Thursday, a level not seen since market turbulence during the Gulf
War.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are enough stocks. Until last week, the winter had been
been 14 percent warmer than usual. But when the weather gets colder
people get possessive of their barrels and are less willing to
sell,'' said Alan Struth, a petroleum market analyst at Honeywell
HiSpecs Solutions in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a fundamental standpoint there is not much difference
from a week ago. Psychologically, however, there is a lot more
uncertainty and we may see substantially higher prices, but it is
not a shortage problem,'' said Struth.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the market may be overreacting to one week of cold
weather and may soon plunge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this goes well beyond the bounds of what can be
considered normal,'' said Timothy Evans of Thomson Global Markets
on the hikes. ``Once the market cools off, we think the warmer than
normal temperatures due into the Northeast next week and a less
bullish price environment will (put) a pin in this bubble.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bruce Morrell, president of a group representing local
community action programs that distribute federal home-heating aid
to low-income families, said, ``We are very concerned that the fuel
assistance resources we distribute to over 100,000 households will
run out long before the temperatures rise. Our clients are
essentially paying twice as much to heat their houses with oil as
they did last year.''
</P>
<P>
   More evidence of the tight oil market came Wednesday with a
report from the American Petroleum Institute that US oil
inventories dropped nearly 13 percent during 1999, the largest
one-year plunge since at least 1950.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor said New England has inventories of 7.5 million barrels
of oil, down from 13 million a year ago, meaning there is far less
supply available to moderate price jumps when the recent cold
weather triggered increased demand.
</P>
<P>
   Oil prices have been climbing steadily over the last year as
OPEC countries such as Saudi Arabia, Iran and Venezuela have
largely stuck to production limits voted in last March, and some
non-OPEC members such as Mexico and Norway have voluntarily limited
their oil output to help keep prices high.
</P>
<P>
   The International Energy Administration estimated that OPEC
members stayed within about 20 percent of their production limits
in November and December. World oil use is expected to exceed
production by 2 million to 3 million barrels daily during the first
three months of this year, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
