u f BC-CMGI-ACQUISITIONS-BOS     01-20 0420
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CMGI-ACQUISITIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$2.4B DEAL TO SIMPLIFY CMGI'S NET AD STRATEGY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the major companies owned by CMGI Inc. has agreed to pay
about $2.4 billion in stock for two other firms owned by CMGI, in a
deal intended to simplify CMGI's Internet advertising strategy.
</P>
<P>
   CMGI owns 80 percent of publicly traded Engage Technologies Inc.
of Andover, Mass.. The company uses tracking technology to
determine the viewing habits of Internet users, and send them
advertisements targeted to their interests.
</P>
<P>
   CMGI also owns two other Internet advertising businesses,
Adsmart Network of Andover, Mass. and San Francisco-based Flycast
Communications Corp. Adsmart sells advertising space on 385 Web
sites; Flycast represents about 2,000 sites. Engage chief executive
Paul Schaut said that every month, over half of all Internet users
visit sites that use the Adsmart and Flycast services.
</P>
<P>
   Schaut said Engage didn't simply want Adsmart and Flycast to be
sister firms in the CMGI stable. ``You can't always tell your
sister what you want her to do, and sometimes you have conflicting
goals,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So Engage is going to use some of its very valuable stock to
acquire Adsmart and Flycast outright. The company will issue 32
million new shares to CMGI in exchange for ownership of the two
firms. As a result of the deal, CMGI's stake in Engage will
increase to 87 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Financially, the deal is structured just as it would be if CMGI
did not control all of the firms involved. ``The fact that these
two companies are owned by a significant shareholder is
irrelevant,'' said Schaut.
</P>
<P>
   The combined companies will continue to operate as separate
entities for the most part, said Schaut. But they will share a
unified force of 200 ad salespeople.
</P>
<P>
   ``The synergies that come along with the Engage combination make
a lot of sense,'' said marketing analyst Troy Mastin of Raymond
James Financial Inc. in St. Petersburg, Fla. The combination will
make it easier for Adsmart and Flycast clients to gain access to
Engage's system for targeting ads to the most likely customers. In
addition, said Mastin, a unified sales force should enable Emerge
to offer its customers a single point of contact for the services
offered by all three companies.
</P>
<P>
   Engage shares shot up 20 9/16, or 27 percent, to 97 9/16, while
CMGI, based in Andover, slumped 1 13/16 to 120 9/16, both on the
Nasdaq stock exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
