<SLUG> BC-OCEAN-SPRAY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AILING OCEAN SPRAY CHOOSES A NEW CEO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The man credited with turning around the Alpo pet food brand in
the early 1990s, Robert Hawthorne, will head Ocean Spray
Cranberries Inc., the struggling cooperative said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   He will lead a Lakeville, Mass. business that saw net proceeds
(the term Ocean Spray uses for earnings) drop by over 50 percent in
1999.
</P>
<P>
   Hawthorne, 54, formerly an executive at Pillsbury Brands and at
General Mills Canada, was picked to be Ocean Spray's president and
chief executive after a six-month search that considered over 20
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Hawthorne will assume his new duties next week.
</P>
<P>
   In June, Ocean Spray's chief executive, Thomas E. Bullock,
announced plans to retire, once a successor had been found.
</P>
<P>
   Ocean Spray's troubles, which stem from an oversupply of
cranberries and new competition, are reflected in financial results
just released for the fiscal year that ended in August.
</P>
<P>
   In fiscal 1999, revenue fell 8 percent, from $1.48 billion to
$1.36 billion. Net proceeds fell from $280.4 million to $134.9
million, or nearly 52 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Ocean Spray, however, said that a launch of new products and a
new ad campaign have helped it to regain momentum after a two-year
decline.
</P>
<P>
   At one point in 1998, its market share of cranberry drink sales
in grocery stores had dropped below 45 percent. Now, its share is
back up to about 55 percent, Ocean Spray said.
</P>
<P>
   Hawthorne was unavailable to comment Thursday, an Ocean Spray
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   In a prepared statement, Hawthorne said: ``Ocean Spray is a
brand with tremendous power, a company that's respected by
consumers and other companies alike. I look forward to the
opportunity to lead this brand and be a part of Ocean Spray's
future success.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Rob Hawthorne's experience as a brand builder at Pillsbury and
General Mills makes him the right choice to strengthen the Ocean
Spray brand,'' said Donald G. Hatton, chairman of Ocean Spray's
board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   Looking to right itself, Ocean Spray announced plans to begin a
strategic review of its operations when Bullock made public his
decision to retire. The review continues, though Ocean Spray
recently said it had ruled out selling all or part of the
cooperative to a larger company with greater global reach and
marketing power.
</P>
<P>
   Hawthorne will help guide the completion of Ocean Spray's
strategic review, a spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Cranberry and citrus growers are suffering from something that
affects many US agricultural categories: Growers have become so
efficient that they routinely produce crops that far exceed demand.
</P>
<P>
   For many years, Ocean Spray did a good job of keeping supply and
demand in balance, through highly successful marketing campaigns,
with slogans such as ``crave the wave.''
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1990s, however, supply began to exceed demand, and
the price Ocean Spray could pay its growers for a 100-pound barrel
of cranberries fell, from more than $60 to less than $30.
</P>
<P>
   When prices were still high, many Wisconsin growers banded
together to sell to a new publicly traded company, Northland
Cranberries Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Unaccustomed to competition, Ocean Spray has been criticized for
being slow to react to the much smaller Northland.
</P>
<P>
   Ocean Spray hopes that Hawthorne will change that. He spent 14
years at General Mills, leaving in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   During his 10-year stint at Pillsbury, he rose to head six
divisions with annual sales of $3.1 billion. He left in 1996 to run
Select Comfort Corp., a maker of air beds and bedding products.
During his tenure, he led Select Comfort in an initial public
offering of stock.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
