<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKAKEL-PRESS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SKAKEL CASE KEPT ALIVE BY PRESS, OTHERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MACQUARRIE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Michael Skakel, scion of wealth and cousin to the powerful
Kennedy clan, gave himself up on Wednesday to face charges in the
quarter-century-old murder of Martha Moxley, some of the seeds of
his fate lay a continent away.
</P>
<P>
   For there, in Los Angeles, the rage engendered in 1995 by the
O.J. Simpson verdict spurred two men to reexamine the Moxley case
and explore whether money can truly trump justice in this country.
</P>
<P>
   Those men, author Dominick Dunne and former LA police Detective
Mark Fuhrman, rekindled public interest in the 1975 Moxley murder
by writing about the case so compellingly that, in retrospect,
their questions about the justice system seem to have led
inexorably to Skakel's arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Dunne's ``A Season in Purgatory,'' published in 1993 as fiction,
is a thinly veiled account of the teenager's slaying that
excoriates the corrosive influence of wealth and power. While
covering the Simpson trial, Dunne encouraged Fuhrman to investigate
the Moxley case, which Dunne also revisited in a Vanity Fair
article.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dominick told me about the case,'' Fuhrman said. ``I was done
with `Murder in Brentwood,' '' a book he wrote about the Simpson
investigation, ``and I was looking for something to do. He said,
`I've got you something.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Fuhrman, whose inflammatory racial attitudes may have influenced
the Simpson verdict, retired from the LA force in August 1995. By
1998, he had written ``Murder in Greenwich,'' a analysis of the
Moxley case in which he identified Michael Skakel as the likely
killer.
</P>
<P>
   A month after Fuhrman's book was published, a Connecticut grand
jury was convened to reexamine the Moxley case. New evidence had
emerged, including significantly altered alibis from Michael and
Thomas Skakel.
</P>
<P>
   The grand jury, consisting of a single Superior Court judge,
also is believed to have heard testimony that Michael Skakel
allegedly told classmates at a Maine school for troubled boys that
he had committed murder.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Carroll, one of the first Greenwich detectives assigned
to the case, said he believes the initial team of investigators
were dazzled by wealth and power.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think initially we were intimidated by the power and the
wealth that's there,'' Carroll said. ``If they didn't live where
they lived or had the relatives that they did, the investigation
probably would have been much more aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenwich police at first refused to believe that such a
``heinous crime,'' one in which the 15-year-old Moxley was
bludgeoned to death by a golf club, Carroll said.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives at first were given free run of the Skakel home by
the boys' father, Rushton, Carroll said. But because of the
informal approach, and without a search warrant, the evidence
gathering was less scrupulous than it would have been done at the
home of a more ordinary resident, the detective said.
</P>
<P>
   Then, later, when police began to focus on Thomas Skakel as
their primary suspect, the investigation virtually ``shut down,''
Carroll said, when a high-powered attorney hired by the family told
police they would face harassment charges if they continued to
question the youth.
</P>
<P>
   The family, once one of the richest in the country, stopped
cooperating with police completely in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   Timothy Dumas, a former Greenwich reporter who wrote ``A Wealth
of Evil'' about the case, also believes wealth and aura impeded the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The '70s were a lot different from the '90s,'' Dumas said.
``Police were more respectful then of the prominent citizens of the
town, and they poked about much too gingerly, I think, when it came
to the Skakels.''
</P>
<P>
   But the aura of power and celebrity that the Skakels possess
could be double-edged, Dumas said. If convicted, Skakel will now
face a prison sentence that could keep him imprisoned for decades.
If he had been tried as a juvenile, Skakel would have been freed at
age 21.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will work out worse for Michael if he did do this than if
he were a nobody,'' Dumas said.
</P>
<P>
   For if he were a ``nobody,'' Dumas surmised, the wheels of
justice might have turned much quickly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-00 2010EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
