u i BC-YUGO-ARKAN-1STLD-WRIT     01-20 0930
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGO-ARKAN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-330&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOUSANDS MOURN SLAIN SERB WHO WAS ACCUSED OF WAR CRIMES 
</HEADLINE>
  (subs to correct spelling of `Intercontinental' in 4th graf.) 
(bl) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ Several thousand people came Thursday to
bury Zeljko Raznatovic, the indicted war-crimes suspect known as
Arkan, but also to praise him.
</P>
<P>
   After a small funeral service for family and close friends in
the chapel of Belgrade's main cemetery, the thousands of mourners,
some of them weeping, followed Raznatovic's son Mihajlo, who
carried a cross, while uniformed members of Raznatovic's Serbian
Volunteer Guard, known as the Tigers, carried the coffin to the
grave.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing camouflage and red berets, they fired a salute with
their rifles as an old Serbian hymn played. Raznatovic, born in
Slovenia to an army father, was portrayed as a Serbian hero,
fighting to extend and consolidate Serbdom and Serbian land, and he
himself enjoyed wearing a uniform of the First World War.
</P>
<P>
   Raznatovic, 47, was murdered Saturday, along with two other men,
a businessman and a police official, in the Intercontinental Hotel
here. As newspapers competed for unverifiable details about the
assassins and their motives, some officials of the governing party
began to describe Raznatovic as a patriot and a hero, despite his
criminal activities.
</P>
<P>
   As the coffin was lowered into the grave, Borislav Pelevic, a
``general'' in the Guard, said, ``Commander, I hereby submit the
last report: the status of the Serb Volunteer Guard is normal, the
status of the party is regular.'' Raznatovic also led a small
political party, the Party of Serbian Unity.
</P>
<P>
   But there was no mention Thursday of Raznatovic's indictment in
1997 by the international war crimes tribunal in the Hague _ an
indictment announced only last March, during NATO's bombing war
against Yugoslavia over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Raznatovic and his Tigers played an important role on the
Serbian side in the wars in Croatia and Bosnia in 1991 and 1992-95.
He also was a pioneer of ethnic purging, and his indictment _ still
sealed _ is reported to include the murder of 250 Croats taken from
a hospital in 1991.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Goran Hadzic, the leader of the autonomous Serb republic in
Croatia, which was overrun by the Croat army in 1995, praised
Raznatovic on Thursday as a friend, adviser and soldier. ``We were
friends,'' he said. ``But he was a big hero.'' Raznatovic, with
Belgrade's approval, ran guns to the Croatian Serbs before war
broke out there in 1991, and he helped fight in eastern Slavonia,
another region of Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   Ivica Dacic, the spokesman of the Socialist Party of the
Yugoslav president, Slobodan Milosevic, attended Raznatovic's
wedding to the popular folk singer Svetlana, known as Ceca, in
1995, but did not come to the funeral. But in a statement, he said,
``Regardless of his contradictory biography, Arkan was no doubt a
patriot.''
</P>
<P>
   More telling were kind words from the Radical Party leader,
Vojislav Seselj, who had roaring battles with Raznatovic in
television debates. Once, on state television, Seselj said: ``I bet
you've put a black sock on your face more often than on your
foot.''
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday, Seselj said in a statement: ``One thing is for
sure _ Zeljko Raznatovic Arkan was a true Serb patriot and all the
political misunderstandings and conflicts we had should be
forgotten now.''
</P>
<P>
   Opposition politicians, especially from Vuk Draskovic's Serbian
Renewal Movement, have charged that the Milosevic government
probably ordered Raznatovic's death because he was becoming too
powerful and disloyal.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities have asked the police to look into charges that
Studio B, the television station controlled by the Serbian Renewal
Movement in Belgrade, is spreading false information. Draskovic has
already accused the government of trying to kill him in a truck
accident last October, and Studio B's signal is being jammed
regularly in parts of the country, while a major transmitter was
stolen this week, cutting off 2 million viewers in central Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   The newspapers, meanwhile, are reporting that at least two
suspects in the Saturday shooting are in custody while the identity
of a third may be known to the police, who have said little
publicly.
</P>
<P>
   The reports say that a man apparently wounded in the attack,
Dusan Gavric, has regained consciousness in a hospital in Loznica
near the Bosnian border, where he had fled.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper Glas said information provided by Gavric led to
the arrest of a second person as he tried to leave the country for
Hungary, where Serbs do not need visas. In Novi Sad, near the
Hungarian border, a local newspaper, Dnevnik, said a man named
Goran Jevtovic had been arrested in the Arkan slaying.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the official daily Politika, which has been used as
the main instrument of police leaks to show that the investigation
is progressing, said that the police had established the identity
of a third man, described as the ``man suspected of killing
Raznatovic and his two associates.'' But he is apparently still at
large, though inside Serbia, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
   Importantly, the newspaper Blic reported that Gavric, the
wounded man, has attended the police academy in Sremska Mitrovica
and graduated in 1995, though the paper was unable to confirm if
Gavric is still on the force. Glas Javnosti said that Gavric is
still a member of the special police and had taken part in police
operations in Kosovo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-00 2014EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
