u f BC-MIT-PHOTONICS-BOS &LR;      01-20 0514
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIT-PHOTONICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIT GETS $90 MILLION FOR HIGH-SPEED INTERNET RESEARCH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: Fla.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ A Miami-based company pioneering new
photonics technologies that could boost Internet traffic speeds by
hundreds of times is committing $90 million to create a new
research center at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
</P>
<P>
   The move by Nanovation Inc., which includes $10 million to endow
new professorships, is expected to supercharge local efforts in
what is called optical networking, or connecting computers and
telephones to fiber-optic backbone lines through links that can
carry far more traffic than wires or electronics.
</P>
<P>
   Nanovation will sponsor research into what are called
microphotonics and nanophotonic devices and circuits, which can
carry hundreds of times more data at much higher speeds over
connections a hundredth or a thousandth the size of a metal wire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microphotonics is the next revolutionary technology,'' said
MIT professor Lionel C. Kimerling, director of the MIT Materials
Processing Center, who will be director of the new
Nanovation-backed center.
</P>
<P>
   Nanovation president G. Robert Tatum said the company hopes the
center, to be built at an as-yet undertermined location on the MIT
campus, will be ``the finest photonics center in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The stunning initial public offering in October of
Chelmsford-based Sycamore Networks Inc., which now has a stock
market value of $20 billion, has highlighted the emergence in
Greater Boston of what many analysts call the strongest
concentration of optical-networking companies in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Broadly speaking, the quest of optical networking is to upgrade
the bumpy country lanes that connect computers and
telecommunications devices to the fiber-optic Internet superhighway
_ in many places copper and coaxial wires _ with new optical links
that are as fast and have as much bandwidth as the Net fiber
itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fiber optics has sparked impressive growth in the
long-distance carrying capacity of so-called wide area networks,
but local distribution is constrained by electronics and wires,''
Kimerling said. ``The challenge of the next generation is to build
high-capacity tributaries'' to neighborhoods and homes through
photonic technology.
</P>
<P>
   As part of its pact with Nanovation, MIT will have freedom to
publish research results and will share in ownership of patents
developed jointly by Nanovation with MIT researchers and
facilities, which could yield millions of dollars in revenue for
the institute.
</P>
<P>
   MIT launched a microphotonics center two years ago to pool
research efforts by associates of the Materials Processing Center
and other laboratories.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, MIT has pursued several similar joint ventures
worth more than $160 million with corporations such as
biotechnology leaders Amgen and DuPont, pharmaceutical giant Merck,
Ford Motor Co., Merrill Lynch, Microsoft Corp., and Nippon
Telegraph and Telephone Corp.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
