<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bradley forced to defend health care stance
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   OTTUMWA, Iowa _ Democrat Bill Bradley opened a crucial swing
through eastern Iowa on Thursday to sharpen his differences with
rival Al Gore in advance of Monday's Iowa caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   But as often as not, Bradley found himself diverging from his
own message to respond to criticisms Gore has lodged against his
health care proposal and plans for Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   At a morning news conference in Des Moines, Bradley conceded
that Gore's negative attacks, including a television commercial
that raised questions about his health care plan's impact on
Medicaid, were working.
</P>
<P>
   ``To a certain extent, voters might have been swayed by that,''
Bradley said. ``But we are countering that now, and we are making
up our distance very quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   But at a campaign stop here hours later, retired social worker
Don Kirchner expressed concern that Bradley's plan to channel the
uninsured into private plans would amount to a $150 voucher that
wouldn't cover any private plan. In TV ads and during the debates,
Gore has used almost identical language in characterizing Bradley's
health care plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't get hung up on the numbers here,'' Bradley responded,
insisting that the details could be worked out later. ``The idea
here is that this is the direction that I want to take us.''
</P>
<P>
   Kirchner, who is attempting to decide between Gore and Bradley,
said later he was still doubtful. ``Any politician who says to me,
'Don't worry, trust me,' causes me some concern,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Bradley spoke to the Iowa chapter of the
AARP, devoting a portion of his remarks to reassuring the seniors
that he would never jeopardize Medicare or Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has hammered Bradley in recent weeks over his failure to
offer a specific plan to extend the solvency of insurance programs
for the elderly beyond 2015. Gore has also challenged Bradley's
commitment to Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to assure you that Medicare today is rock solid,''
Bradley said. He asserted that the nation's expanding economy would
continue to extend the life of the program without government
intervention now. And he sought to assure the audience that if the
program did require a fix, he had the leadership to accomplish the
task.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
