<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-POLICE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITISH PLAN TO CHANGE ULSTER POLICE DRAWS FIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The British government agreed Wednesday to change the
name of Northern Ireland's police force, cut its size nearly in
half, and speed up the recruitment of Catholics to make it
representative of the population within ten years.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in the House of Commons, Peter Mandelson, Britain's
secretary of state for Northern Ireland, said the government would
implement nearly all 175 recommendations made last September by a
special commission. While a new power-sharing administration in
Northern Ireland has taken over most governmental responsibilities
under the terms of the 1998 Good Friday Agreement, responsibility
for security measures is still in the hands of the British.
</P>
<P>
   The commission, headed by Christopher Patten, Britain's last
governor in Hong Kong, called for a major overhaul of the
13,500-member Royal Ulster Constabulary, or RUC, which is more than
90 percent Protestant. The commission, which included former
Massachusetts Public Safety Secretary Kathleen O'Toole, recommended
changing the name and ethos of the RUC so that more Catholics, who
make up more than 40 percent of the population, would be encouraged
to join. Many Catholics consider the force biased against them.
</P>
<P>
   The plan to change the name to the Police Service of Northern
Ireland, and especially to drop the word ``royal,'' is an emotional
issue for Protestant unionists in Northern Ireland, who consider
themselves British and credit the RUC with holding the line against
the Irish Republican Army.
</P>
<P>
   Ulster Unionist leader David Trimble, who is a member of
Parliament as well as first minister in the new power-sharing
Northern Ireland Assembly, angrily denounced the plan. ``Nothing
that this government says or does can dishonor the RUC and the men
that serve it, but this government can and is dishonoring itself,''
Trimble said.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Tony Blair rose as Trimble sat down, insisting
the reforms did not insult the memory of the 300 police officers
killed and some 9,000 injured since 1969, most of them at the hands
of the IRA.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no dishonor intended to the RUC. Their officers have
given their lives in outstanding bravery over many years,'' said
Blair. ``What we are trying to do is ensure that we have a police
force in Northern Ireland that is capable of attracting support
from all sides of the community so it can police better.''
</P>
<P>
   The government made some minor concessions to unionists, leaving
the job of designing the RUC's new badge to a new civilian
authority. It also rejected a recommendation that local authorities
be allowed to hire private security firms after unionists claimed
it was a scheme aimed at farming out subcontracts to the IRA. But
unionists had been expecting more concessions, and their anger
showed.
</P>
<P>
   The moderate nationalist Social Democratic and Labor Party
welcomed the plan, saying it strengthened the peace process. Sinn
Fein, the political allies of the IRA, which had demanded the RUC
be disbanded, was more cautious. Republicans view many of the
changes as simply cosmetic.
</P>
<P>
   Gerry Kelly, a Sinn Fein assembly member who was once an IRA
bomber, said it was wrong to assume that Irish republicans would
embrace the proposed changes. He said his party would wait to see
the actual legislation before offering a judgment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unionists are upset because the RUC was their police force,''
said Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   The bitter recriminations Wednesday suggested the honeymoon is
over following last month's creation of the first power-sharing
government of unionists and republicans. It also focused attention
anew on a Feb. 12 deadline set by Trimble, who has vowed to resign
and bring down the power-sharing government unless there is
evidence that the IRA is serious about turning in its hidden
arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   Mandelson said the police force would be whittled down to 7,500
within ten years, and that severance pay would be ``generous and
sympathetic.'' He said new officers would be appointed on a 50-50
basis between Catholics and Protestants. In a bid to get more
Catholics to join, the officers' oath will drop a line that swears
allegiance to the Queen. Unionists complained, but no other police
department in the United Kingdom takes an oath to the British
monarch.
</P>
<P>
   Iona Meyers, whose husband was killed by the IRA and who heads
the police widows association, called the government plans ``a sop
to terrorism.'' Sgt. Les Rogers, who heads the police union, called
it ``an act of appeasement of terrorists.''
</P>
<P>
   RUC Chief Constable Ronnie Flanagan said most of his officers
were willing to accept the name change and fundamental reform as
long as paramilitary groups were committed to advancing their
causes through strictly peaceful methods.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
