u s BC-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      01-20 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JORDAN MAKES A RETURN ON HIS OWN TERMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Michael Jordan entered a crowded room Wednesday and
immediately began doing what makes him most comfortable. He changed
the rules.
</P>
<P>
   It was just after 5 p.m. when Jordan approached the dais at the
MCI Center. The first thing you noticed was his left ear, from
which a large diamond-studded ring dangled. Jordan is the only
owner who wears such a ring. But he is more than the league's
best-dressed owner. He also becomes the most handsome owner. The
only owner who can outplay the men who work for him. The only owner
who has his age (36) and skin complexion (sepia-toned). The only
owner who can brag that he has sold ads that represent various
aspects of Americana: basic underwear, gaudy sneakers, greasy hot
dogs and hamburgers, low-cost cologne and high-budget movies.
</P>
<P>
   The Wizards, the second-worst team in the Eastern Conference,
were thinking of those credentials when they excitedly introduced
Jordan as their part-owner and president of basketball operations.
President Clinton attended  &UR; last night &LR; 's game against Dallas and
the mayor of Washington was at Jordan's press conference. I can
understand the enthusiasm for the man Jayson Williams once called
``Jesus in Nikes,'' but I'd like to see Jordan turn water into
wine, a task equivalent to making the awful Wizards winners.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan truly will have to change the rules _ more than he ever
did in his brilliant playing career _ to make this work. He will
have to become St. Michael of the Potomac. You may remember that
Jordan used to call Jerry Krause, the disheveled general manager of
the Chicago Bulls, ``Crumbs.'' Well, I think Jordan will have a lot
more respect for Krause and other GMs after he spends a few months
on the job. It's a gig that looks a lot easier than it is. It is
even more vexing when you don't have a first-round pick (the
Wizards might not) and are locked in a culture of losing (they last
won a playoff series in 1982).
</P>
<P>
   We mentioned changing the rules, right? Well, Jordan will have
to change them to do his job well. A lot of talent evaluators spend
their time on the road, scouting in Sheboygan on a Tuesday night
and in East St. Louis on a Wednesday. Jordan acknowledged that his
celebrity may make this difficult. He may be the first owner who
has to wear an Afroed wig so people won't notice him in public. He
will also be the first operations chief who will not reside in his
team's city; he said he will commute from Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   The sentiment among most Washingtonians Wednesday seemed to be,
``Well, this guy won six championships, so maybe his intensity will
rub off on the team.''
</P>
<P>
   They are right. The intensity will rub off. But intensity
doesn't make salary-cap problems disappear. Bill Russell won as
many MVP awards as Jordan and nearly doubled Jordan's six titles.
Russell tried to revive terrible teams twice, in the 1970s with
Seattle and in the '80s with Sacramento. He had mixed results and
no championships. Jerry West was a great player who is also a great
executive. The man Jordan replaced, Wes Unseld, was a good player
whose only greatness as an executive came from the fact that he was
not fired by the team. What about Jordan?
</P>
<P>
   From what I saw Wednesday, people here need to call this guy,
``Michaelavelli.'' He made it clear that things would be done his
way or jobs would be lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will I practice with the team?'' he said. ``Sure.'' He
explained that the best way to see a man's fear is to look into his
eyes while he's on the court. He also said that Wizards coach
Garfield Heard may not want him practicing but, ``I'm his boss.''
People laughed when Jordan said that, but he was not joking. He was
not joking when he said everyone in the organization would be
evaluated. He was not joking when he said that he now has the
decision-making power over Unseld and that majority owner Abe
Pollin has the final say over both of them.
</P>
<P>
   Unseld gave curt answers Wednesday. He should realize that he no
longer has the protection of Pollin. If Jordan eventually decides
that Unseld has no place in basketball operations, Unseld will have
to go somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   When Jordan practiced with the Bulls, he was known for his
stinging critiques of teammates whom he considered to be slackers.
When he practices with the Wizards, he can trash as many players as
he wants but he'll still have to pay them. He would be wise to
store the cell phone numbers of Kevin McHale and Larry Bird so he
can vent about the priorities of some of today's players. That's
the biggest difference between wearing a uniform and wearing a
suit.
</P>
<P>
   As the man in jersey No. 23, you post a triple-double when you
are angry and want to make a statement. As the man in the
pinstriped suit, you call your peers and beg them to make a deal
with you.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Jordan will have to alter his relationship with
agent David Falk. Other owners could complain that Jordan has a
competitive advantage, due to his close relationship with the
powerful Falk. That's an issue that will have to be handled at
another time. Today's news is more pressing.
</P>
<P>
   On Jordan's first day on the job, the Wizards played the
pathetic Dallas Mavericks. They were blown out, 104-86. He may be
able to do some moderate tinkering with this team. But when things
go bad, all he will be able to do is watch.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Michael Holley is a Boston Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
