<HEADLINE>
LITTLE ELCOM LACKS GLAMOUR, BUT STOCK'S A STAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Down in the gearbox of the new economy, the most mundane
business-to-business software that's run over the Internet is
promising corporate America a new level of organization and
efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take the stock market long to catch on to the
opportunity offered by Internet-based procurement systems, which
can track and execute practically every purchase order a company
issues.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of two high fliers that sell top-of-the-line products,
Ariba Corp. and Commerce One, have climbed more than eightfold
since the companies went public last summer, amassing in a flash a
combined value of nearly $30 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Far less glamorous, little Elcom International Inc., of Norwood,
Mass., is trying to burrow its way into the lower end of the
corporate market for Internet-based procurement software.
</P>
<P>
   It, too, sells systems that allow employees to order supplies
from personal computers, track purchases, bounce e-mails to
supervisors when their approval is needed and, above all, cut
costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can go as low as a business with 100 PCs, and I can save
that company money,'' said Elcom's chief executive, Robert Crowell.
</P>
<P>
   Elcom may not have the bulging, multibillion dollar stock market
value of an Ariba or a Commerce One, but it outran every other
stock in Massachusetts last year, based on percentage gains. It
soared 1,654 percent in 1999, though many bigger local stocks piled
up greater increases in sheer dollar value. At a peak of 34 per
share, Elcom climbed to a $1 billion market value.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stocks in that arena have just gone crazy,'' said Tim Stobaugh
of Stonegate Securities, the only analyst who follows Elcom. He
continues to rate Elcom a ``strong buy'' but has not adjusted his
last published price target for the stock, which was 16 to 20.
</P>
<P>
   Like many other small high-tech stocks, Elcom has taken its
lumps in January. It had sunk like a rock to below 20 by last week
and finished Wednesday at 25. Its total stock value has slipped to
$700 million.
</P>
<P>
   Elcom wants to become the Honda Civic of the procurement
software business, a reasonable choice for people who have a
limited amount of money to spend. Procurement systems from Ariba
and Commerce One can cost millions of dollars. They're better and
more flexible, but much costlier than Elcom's systems, which run
about $150,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ariba has been phenomenally successful, but not everyone is in
a position to pony up the money to buy it,'' said Lisa Williams, an
analyst working on enterpise commerce and applications at Yankee
Group in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a big market out there, and not all that demand is
ever going to be captured by one company,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Elcom's PECOS procurement system has attracted a small but
interesting list of early clients, including CBS Corp., which has
deployed it on a limited basis, and Entergy Nuclear, a subsidiary
of Entergy Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an Ariba or a Commerce One, but it's a pretty quick
and easy solution that provides a lot of the same benefits,''
Stobaugh said.
</P>
<P>
   Crowell has been working on the unglamorous fringes of
technology since he started selling calculators while at the
University of Massachusetts in the early 1970s. Later, he ran the
computer reseller Neeco Inc., of Canton, Mass., but sold the public
company in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Crowell stayed in the computer reseller business when he got
Elcom off the ground, and that's what continues to generate almost
all of its hundreds of millions in annual revenue. But it's the
budding procurement system business that has propelled Elcom shares
and that represents the vast bulk of the company's current stock
value.
</P>
<P>
   The plan: Turn the elcom.com procurement system subsidiary into
a publc company by selling a small chunk of its stock in an initial
offering, then give Elcom shareholders the rest of the new
company's stock in a year when the government will presumably
approve of a tax-free spinoff.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent coversation, Crowell said the elcom.com IPO should
happen in the first quarter of this year. Other company officials
are more cautious, suggesting the offering might take place the
following quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But the goal is clear: Separate Elcom's new opportunity from its
old business.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got too many connotations of being a PC remarketer,''
Crowell said. ``There's not too many businesses that are valued
lower or perceived worse. The margins are in the tank; manufactuers
are all going direct. Their stocks are at their lowest points in
history.''
</P>
<P>
   What happens next depends on the product itself. When companies
like Elcom aim for the low end of a market, they need to attract
lots of customers to make the strategy work. So far, so good. But
there's a long way to go.
</P>
<P>
   And the stock market, enamored of business-to-business software
today, can discover a new pet Internet application in a snap.
</P>
<P>
   ``My ego is well under control,'' Crowell said. ``You really
can't figure out what value the marketplace will put on something
when it's a pure play.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
