<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLASTERER OFFERING GOOD ADVICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. When I pulled off the heavy vinyl paper from the plastered
walls of my living room, some of the paste remained, but some paste
and some of the plaster was pulled off with it. A plasterer said he
would remove the glue, put on a bonding agent, and replaster, for
$700. Is that too much to pay? Could I do that myself?
</P>
<P>
   A.H., Danvers, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. It is not too much to pay, I believe, and the plasterer is
suggesting the right thing, especially using a bonding agent, which
will virtually guarantee that the new plaster coat will stick.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, you can do it yourself. Success depends on your know-how,
time, and energy. To remove the paste, wash with a strong solution
of Spic and Span and water, and let this solution sit on the paste
for a few minutes, to soften it, before scrubbing. If there is a
lot of paste, you might have to scrape it off with a wide putty
knife as you soften it.
</P>
<P>
   If the plaster did not come off in great sections, you can fill
in the voids with joint compound, which has glue in it and should
stick quite well, even without a bonding agent; certainly better
than regular plaster. Let dry and sand smooth. Then paint with a
flat latex wall paint. If you feel the wall is too rough for
painting, apply new Wall-Tex type heavy duty paper with no pattern,
then paint.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My house in Vermont is 200 years old and is so badly located
that the cellar floods in spring and whenever it rains, no matter
what I do. I just installed a new hot air furnace, and would like
to keep it from rusting away in that wet basement. How can I do
that?
</P>
<P>
   JON MILTON, East Barnard, Vt.
</P>
<P>
   A. If you really can't keep the water out by drainage, sump
pumps, and any other means, it means that your house is sitting in
a swamp or wetlands or other area with constant water. If so,
ventilation is your best bet. Make sure the furnace and other
cellar appliances are raised high enough to keep out of flood
waters.
</P>
<P>
   What ventilation does is release water vapor, which otherwise
will rust out the furnace before its time. And if there is water
present, venting will do little good, because there is a constant
source of water vapor.
</P>
<P>
   It's obviously a tough situation, but here's a thought: Make the
basement a crawl space by filling it with earth, and put
polyethylene plastic on top to prevent water vapor from coming up.
Relocate the furnace and water heater to the living part of the
house, or build a little addition to house them. This may not be
prohibitively expensive, and since the cellar is useless and always
will be, why not?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I burned a large pot of rice on the stove weeks ago, and
despite cleaning everything more than once, the kitchen still
stinks. How can I get rid of that odor? Most seems to be coming
from the ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   DAVE KAY, Harvard, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. First, try a deodorant spray. One is Febreze, by Procter &AMP;
Gamble. It is designed for soft materials but could work on the
ceiling. It is sold in supermarkets. Another is Natural Magic Odor
Blaster, sold in various stores. Call 800-376-2442 for locations.
Or, before you do anything, wash the ceiling with white vinegar. It
may smell vinegary for a while, but when that goes away, the odor
might be gone, too. If none of these ideas works, paint the ceiling
with BIN, a pigmented shellac that will seal in the odor. Then
finish with latex ceiling paint.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have a pretty good Stanley miter box, which I loaned to a
friend. He tried to adjust it and now it's all out of whack, and no
amount of adjusting by me seems to help. What can I do?
</P>
<P>
   CHARLES MASON, Lynnfield, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Call the Stanley Works in New Britain, Conn., 800-262-2161,
maker of that miter box. Stanley prides itself on the quality of
its tools and products, so you should get some good advice or even
an adjustment. The handyman worked in New Britain in his salad
days; in fact he could see from his house the Stanley Works, which
is the sole survivor of half a dozen factories in what was callled
the Hardware City. This only means that the handyman has a high
opinion of the Stanley Works. Or, call Sears, which with its new
Brand Central program sells many brands, might be of help, too.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have some window quilts that have been up for many years
and they do work very well in keeping the heat in and the cold out.
But they are quite soiled, and my regular dry cleaner won't touch
them. Who would clean them?
</P>
<P>
   PHYLIS MOWBRAY, Hamilton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Window quilts are simply quiltlike coverings for windows, I
believe, and should clean like a quilt. Try a cleaner who
specializes in cleaning upholstery. Or, try it yourself with a
nonwater cleaner or a rug shampoo. Call Energy Unlimited of
Wayland, Mass., which sells window quilts, 508-358-7358.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
