u l BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      01-20 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SLIPPED DISK AND ITS FLIP SIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I &UR;  &LR; was on ``ER'' last week.
</P>
<P>
   The episode opened with a shot of a station wagon racing through
traffic toward a major metropolitan hospital. As the car pulls to a
stop, two attendants lift me onto a gurney, then zip me through a
maze of corridors.
</P>
<P>
   In the next scene, I'm making my way through the triage
procedure, describing the excruciating pain radiating from my back
down my inner thigh, hoping to inspire at least as much compassion
as the cases of pneumonia, trauma, and heart attacks also vying for
immediate medical attention. A male nurse shows up, smiles, and
performs an act of wizardry worthy of Harry Potter. One moment he
is waving shrink-wrapped Percocet and Valium in front of my face.
Seconds later the magic potions have miraculously vanished _ into
my mouth _ and begin causing indescribable special effects all the
way down to the tips of my toes.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, after a ride on an elevator, several extras,
dressed as nurses, are sliding me into the deep tunnel of an MRI
machine. As the walls enclose me, I struggle to decipher the cries
and phrases with which I realize the machine is desperately trying
to communicate. As the drugs fully kick in, I am overjoyed to
realize that I have at last become privy to the secret of the
universe. As soon as I recall what it is, you can be sure I'll be
the first person to reveal to the uninitiated what magnetic images
truly resonate.
</P>
<P>
   My final scene was the best. Back in the ER, stretched out in a
skimpy johnnie, I open my eyes and behold a vision of salvation in
a senior resident's official white jacket, complete with photo ID.
I find myself looking into deep brown compassionate eyes. I am
reassured by a gentle smile and blessed by the comforting touch of
a guy who can only be described by a woman of my generation as a
gorgeous blond hunk.
</P>
<P>
   This is the moment I know for sure I have died and gone on TV.
</P>
<P>
   After that, reality was a bit of a letdown. I was sent home
(diagnosis: bulging disk) with nothing to do but take large regular
doses of powerful legal drugs and wait for my appointment with an
orthopedist 10 days later. I got to watch lots of videos totally
guilt-free, lie around on various flat surfaces all day, and talk
at length on the phone to fascinating friends I once used to end
conversations with by saying, ``I've got to go now.''
</P>
<P>
   Wow, looking at it that way, it hasn't been that much of a
letdown.
</P>
<P>
   Still, never ending, and out of reach as I lie flat on my back,
e-mail is infiltrating my computer like the swarm of locusts God
sent when Pharaoh dared to dis Moses. I also get business calls.
Some go like this:
</P>
<P>
   ``Hi, Linda. How are you?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really terrible. I've slipped a disk, can barely make it
to the bathroom, and I'm on so much pain medication, I can't think
straight.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, do you think you could put that information for our
April newsletter into the mail first thing in the morning?''
</P>
<P>
   I wonder what would happen if I answered: ``Gee, I'm being
fitted for a coffin at the moment and I'm being buried first thing
tomorrow morning.'' Would my caller ask me to send the information
even sooner?
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, almost a year ago I made a commitment to
address a conference in Boston at the end of January, and I dreaded
telling my contact with less than 10 days' notice that I would be
unable to keep my word.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why, you poor thing,'' she said, her words music to my ears,
``Your only job is to get well and heal as soon as possible. Don't
you worry about a thing. It's my job to find someone to replace
you.'' Believe me, when this woman gets sick and goes on TV, that
blond resident is going to be right there, waiting for her.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, I'm strangely content to let the days pass. No
one has ever accused me of being a Pollyanna (just ask me about the
environmental apocalypse looming in our future), but when it gets
down to the little things, I tend to count my blessings. The pain
in my back is not fatal. It is also tolerable. I have visitors,
helpers, and more indications than anyone deserves that people love
and care about me. With the help of a PowerBook, I'm not in danger
of losing my job. We have excellent health insurance and I trust my
primary physician, a miracle in itself.
</P>
<P>
   I see my orthopod today. Hopefully, he'll get me back on my
feet. As my friend Christina reminds me, I have also been given
time to reflect on why it took a bulging disk to slow me down, and
should be able to figure out a less extreme method of taking care
of myself.
</P>
<P>
   I look like a medical disaster area, but really, what more could
a physical setback do for you?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Linda Weltner's Web site is http://www.shore.net/weltner)
</P>
</TEXT>
