<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1731 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-EPA-ENFORCEMENT-BOS &LR;      01-20 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EPA-ENFORCEMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EPA SAYS '99 WAS A RECORD ENFORCEMENT YEAR IN NEW ENGLAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT BRAILE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Rebutting criticism from inside and outside the agency
for being soft on criminal acts of pollution, the New England
office of the US Environmental Protection Agency announced
Wednesday that it had a record enforcement year in 1999, forcing
violators to spend more than $200 million to comply with
environmental laws.
</P>
<P>
   But criticism persists, even though the agency's record last
year indicates a tougher stand on enforcement over previous years.
Some say the agency still prefers negotiated settlements to
aggressive enforcement, resulting in lower fines and penalties.
</P>
<P>
   The agency said it made 33 judicial referrals and issued 90
administrative penalty actions in 1999, more than in any of the
previous eight years. It also scored a record $7.7 million in
settlements with polluters for ``innovative'' projects, ones that
are not required by law, but supplement what is required. It had
only $2.2 million worth of such projects in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Under former regional administrator John DeVillars, who left the
EPA on Jan. 7 for the private sector, the agency had spent years
trying to develop more imaginative ways of persuading polluters to
comply than simply charging them with violations. The effort won
DeVillars fans and foes alike, the latter criticizing him for
coddling criminals. The regional office's work was the subject of a
Boston Globe Spotlight series last November.
</P>
<P>
   But in forcing polluters to spend $202 million to comply, a 16
percent increase over 1998, and in winning victories over such
corporate giants as Pfizer and Northeast Utilities, the agency said
that while it has a more flexible approach to compliance now, it
has not forgotten the rule of law.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's report ``shows that EPA-New England is not willing
to stand by while irresponsible companies pollute our land, water,
and air,'' said Mindy Lubber, the acting regional administrator.
The findings reflect the agency's overall enforcement strategy, a
mix of strict oversight, compliance assistance, and innovative
technologies, said Lubber, considered the top candidate to be named
as DeVillar's successor.
</P>
<P>
   In a settlement with Pfizer, the Connecticut pharmaceutical
manufacturer, the EPA won a $625,000 penalty for alleged waste and
community right-to-know violations. But it also required the
company to develop better waste management methods with the
University of Rhode Island, and to train Connecticut teachers on
handling school wastes.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA's efforts also resulted in a federal court ruling
against two subsidiaries of Northeast Utilities, the
Connecticut-based power producer, forcing them to pay $10 million
for 25 felony counts at two power plants for violating the federal
Clean Water Act and lying to the Nuclear Regulatory Commission. Of
the $10 million, $3.3 million will be spent on innovative projects,
including $1 million to preserve riverfront land.
</P>
<P>
   The agency struck a pending $45 million agreement with General
Electric and the city of Pittsfield to clean up the Housatonic
River in western Massachusetts and revitalize a polluted 250-acre
site. It took action against seven federal, state and local
agencies. And it launched an enforcement initiative against the
region's 262 colleges and universities.
</P>
<P>
   But some say the agency is just returning to the enforcement
level it had earlier this decade before DeVillars took charge, and
that $202 million in compliance costs amounts to companies
investing in themselves. They also say the agency's predilection to
settle may mean millions of dollars are not being collected for
environmental violations.
</P>
<P>
   ``New England takes enforcement actions only with the consent of
the violator,'' said Jeff Ruch, executive director of Public
Employees for Environmental Responsibility, a watchdog group of
federal employees. ``If they could have gotten $2 billion for the
taxpayers, but only got $202 million, that's nothing to brag
about.''
</P>
<P>
   The agency's criminal enforcement record, which was not detailed
in the report, indicates it has been more or less holding steady
since 1996, said Sam Silverman, who manages the EPA's enforcement
office. Criminal referrals dropped from 24 in 1996 to 17 last year.
But the number of people indicted, charged, convicted, and
sentenced rose or remained constant, depending on the category, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is that we have as aggressive an enforcement
program as we can have every year,'' Silverman said. ``But whether
we get grand juries that indict and juries and judges that convict,
that's beyond our control.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-00 2037EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
