<DOCNO> NYT20000120.0275 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 20:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1733 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-FOREMAN-AD-COLUMN-ART     01-20 1105
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREMAN-AD-COLUMN-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Texas) 
ADVERTISING: A PITCHMAN WITH PUNCH  (Eds: This story is also being
filed in `s' category.) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT15 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In George Foreman's first boxing incarnation, he was a lean,
snarling ogre who mauled Joe Frazier to win the heavyweight
championship 27 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   When he returned in 1987 after a 10-year retirement preaching on
streets and eating his way to 310 pounds, Foreman II became an
image of mirth with punch speed measured by an egg timer.
</P>
<P>
   He did beat Michael Moorer in 1994 to win the title again, but
today, at 51, the closest he gets to boxing is analyzing fights for
HBO Sports. What occupies him now is a second career as a pitchman,
a pitchman with a difference. Instead of endorsing products for
annual fees, as many sports stars do, he has become perhaps the
first to sell his name in perpetuity. Having traded trunks for a
red apron, he now urges television shoppers to buy George Foreman's
Lean Mean Fat-Reducing Grilling Machine.
</P>
<P>
   It's all part of a radical, and lucrative, image make over, from
tough guy to cuddly superstar.
</P>
<P>
   With 10 million nonstick grillers sold since 1995, the
manufacturer, Salton, bought Foreman's name and image last month
for $137.5 million in cash and stock. Foreman will receive $110
million over five years, joining the ranks of the highest-paid
pitchmen. He agreed never to endorse rival cookware, though he is
free to pitch, say, cars or shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Companies like Nike, Coors, McDonald's and now the Internet
dot-coms pay athletes like Michael Jordan, Tiger Woods and Ken
Griffey Jr. handsomely to endorse their products. Foreman had gone
that route, for Meineke and Doritos.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a commercial man,'' he said. ``People would say, `We
want you to sell this,' I'd say, `How much?' and I'd do it.''
</P>
<P>
   But buying a star's name is something else. ``It's unheard of,''
said Bob Williams, president of Burns Sports, a Chicago firm that
matches athletes to advertisers. ``I can't come up with anything
like that.''
</P>
<P>
   And Frank Vuono, president for marketing at the SFX Sports
Group, said, ``Jack Nicklaus built his company around his name, but
I don't know of someone who had his name bought out.''
</P>
<P>
   To revive his dormant career, Foreman packaged himself as a
bald, benevolent, burger-chomping, jelly-bellied boxer determined
to prove that turning 40 (or 50) was not an athletic death
sentence. His loss to Evander Holyfield in April 1991 attracted 1.4
million pay-per-view subscribers, a record that stood for four
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``George created a lot of good will and loyalty by knocking out
Moorer and doing a lot of talk shows,'' said Henry Holmes,
Foreman's lawyer. ``He has an ability to communicate across age,
economic, religious and racial boundaries.'' In 1993, he even
starred in a short-lived sitcom called ``George.'' And a movie on
his life, based on his book, ``By George,'' is being developed by
Ross Greenburg of HBO Sports.
</P>
<P>
   Foreman wants to box again, but his wife, Joan, won't let him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe when you're more afraid of what your wife will do to you
than what fighters will do, you should get out,'' Foreman said last
month in a telephone interview from his home in Kingwood, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   When Salton, a unit of Centre Partners Management, introduced
the Lean Mean Fat-Reducing Grilling Machine _ sans Foreman _ at a
trade show in 1994, nobody paid attention. But then Michael
Srednick, a veteran marketer of products like the legendary
Veg-O-Matic, spotted the griller and gave it to Sam Perlmutter, who
brought it to Foreman, who pined for some link to hamburgers, his
favorite food.
</P>
<P>
   Foreman briefly considered buying it and marketing it himself.
``But I said to George, `You can't do this on your own, you need
marketing and distribution.''' Srednick said. ``So I introduced him
to Salton.''
</P>
<P>
   First, Foreman suggested changes in the grill's size (to expand
its capacity beyond two burgers at a time) and design (it looked
too much like a waffle iron) but said he loved the way the sloped
grill cooked food on both sides, and let the fat drip into
grease-catchers. In 1995, Foreman signed a deal that made him a
partner with Salton, giving him 45 percent of the profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had nothing to lose,'' Leon Dreimann, Salton's chief
executive, said. ``Retailers were not enthusiastic.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``Having George was a wonderful way to reintroduce the
product. It's not that hard to come up with a good product, but it
is hard to separate yourself from the competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Salton's expectations were modest. It knew that Foreman,
remembered by some for waving an American flag after winning the
heavyweight title at the 1968 Summer Olympics, was the most beloved
boxer after Muhammad Ali and that his bouts were among HBO's
highest rated. Most of all, it knew of Foreman's indelible
reputation for wolfing down cheeseburgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got back into boxing, the writers said, `His training
camp is next to Burger King,''' Foreman said. He never tried to
alter the impression.
</P>
<P>
   But he certainly altered Salton's anticipated sales. One day,
Dreimann read that Foreman thought he could make $1 million in
royalties from the griller. Dreimann thought, ``I hope he's not
exaggerating.'' Then, when Foreman predicted in a television
interview that the griller would be a staple in 70 million American
homes, Dreimann remembered ``raising my eyebrows and saying,
`That's a lot.'''
</P>
<P>
   Sales built slowly at first, then exploded, largely because of
Foreman's infomercials and appearances on the QVC home shopping
channel. The company has never marketed its products through
30-second TV spots.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 10 million grills sold, 700,000 have been sold on QVC.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the most successful small appliance in the history of its
category on QVC,'' a QVC spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   Thyra Porter, kitchenware editor for HF Network, a weekly trade
publication, said, ``Salton has done extraordinarily well by
selling the griller with such a charismatic guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Foreman quickly warmed to his calling as an infomercial
superstar like Ron Popeil, the energetic innovator behind the
Pocket Fisherman, and Suzanne Somers, empress of the Buttmaster. He
was becoming as well known for exclaiming about fatty juices
dripping from chicken breasts as for pole-axing opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm learning to accept that the least part of me is about
boxing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But the seminal moment, the moment when Foreman morphed from
part-time boxer to full-time salesman, came in November 1997, when
he stood in a ring in Atlantic City, N.J., and responded to
questions about losing a decision to Shannon Briggs despite
outfighting him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, that's about eight weeks I spent on the George Foreman
Lean Mean Fat-Reducing Grilling Machine,'' he said, hiking his
sweatshirt to reveal a not-so-lean belly. ``I grill right in the
bedroom. Steak and salmon steak. I was able to lose a lot of
weight. That thing really works.''
</P>
<P>
   Wait _ there was more: ``Remember, the George Foreman Lean Mean
Fat-Reducing Grilling Machine. No home should be without this
thing. God bless you. Go get one.'' Had he come to fight or plug?
Hard to say.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Salton approached Foreman with the buyout offer in
June, he had pocketed $50 million to $60 million in royalties. His
grills _ in three sizes, selling for $30 to $100 _ accounted for 38
percent of Salton's 1999 revenues of $506.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was only surprised they came to me so late with this,''
Foreman said. ``I knew sooner or later it would happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The strategy for Salton, which also makes the Juiceman, Breadman
and Toastmaster products, is a financial judgment that the buyout
would be cheaper than royalties well into the future.
</P>
<P>
   Dreimann said the introduction of new Foreman-brand barbecues,
rotisseries and cookware, more competitive products with lower
margins than grillers, meant reduced profits that it preferred to
keep rather than distribute to Foreman.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked at what we'd been paying him on an annual basis, and
what we'd be comfortable paying out over the next five years,''
Dreimann said. ``There's a point in time when you don't know how
much publicity George will be getting. He gets good exposure with
HBO, but the maximum coverage for him may be what the company is
doing for him. When he hits 55 or 60, how much of a pull would he
have without the continuity we would provide?''
</P>
<P>
   Once, Foreman's career was defined by Howard Cosell's call of
his devastating initial knockdown of Frazier:
</P>
<P>
   ``Down goes Frazier! Down goes Frazier! Down goes Frazier!''
</P>
<P>
   Now, his career can be summed up by this exchange from one
infomercial:
</P>
<P>
   ``What have you made for us, George?'' the host asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hot dogs!'' Foreman replied excitedly.
</P>
<P>
   Well, eating lasts longer than a boxing career.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a lifetime commitment for me,'' he said. ``They really
made a good deal with George Foreman. Amen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
