<P>
   BELMONT-DEAD (Los Angeles) -- Los Angeles Unified's two top
leaders recommended Thursday that the district halt construction of
a high school at the environmentallly plagued Belmont Learning
Center site and instead use the property for administrative offices
and warehouse space. The recommendation by Chief Operating Officer
Howard Miller and interim Supt. Ramon C. Cortines precedes
Tuesday's scheduled vote by the school board to determine whether
to continue or abandon the project, which has cost the district
more than $170 million. The district leaders say other district
sites in the area -- including LAUSD headquarters itself -- should
be used as classroom space. By Greg Gittrich (Will move on the
``n'' California and ``a'' national news wires.)
</P>
<P>
   MITNICK-RELEASED (Los Angeles) -- Kevin Mitnick, a San Fernando
Valley man who became legend among underground computer hackers for
his foiling the FBI until his arrest, will be released Friday from
prison, but still contends he is not a criminal. In his first
interview, he told the ``60 Minutes'' news show, he is a ``computer
joyrider'' who broke into business and government networks for fun,
never profit. ``I was an accomplished computer tresspasser. I don't
consider myself a thief,'' Mitnick said. ``I copied without
permission.'' By Phillip W. Browne (Will move on the ``n''
California and ``a'' national news wires.)
</P>
<P>
   SPY-TESTIFIES (Los Angeles) -- A former Russian spy will come
out of the cold Monday at MTA headquarters in Los Angeles to
testify to a congressional panel about ongoing espionage operations
and weapons stockpiles allegedly hidden away in Southern California
and across the nation. The witness, described as a former Soviet
KGB agent and recent defector now in the Federal Witness Protection
Program, will testify -- with his face hidden and voice
electronically altered -- before the House Committee on Government
Reform, which includes Reps. Henry Waxman, D-Los Angeles, and
Stephen Horn, R-Long Beach. By Bill Hillburg (Will move on the
``n'' California and ``a'' national news wires.)
</P>
