<HEADER>
A1736 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u p BC-CAMPAIGN-MCCAIN-BOS &LR;      01-20 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-MCCAIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN LECTURES NEW YORK GOP ABOUT BALLOT ISSUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Sen. John McCain came here Thursday for one purpose _
to stand in the cold snow, lash out at New York's Republican Party
leaders for trying to keep him off the state's primary ballot, and
compare them to the Communist bosses of the old Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   He's uttered that line several times in recent days, only this
time he staged the accusation before a bevy of TV cameras, right
across the street from the Russian consulate.
</P>
<P>
   In the upcoming Russian presidential election, he exclaimed,
``there will be more than one name on the ballot.'' And so, he
said, should it be in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Then he got in his van and was driven away.
</P>
<P>
   McCain made no bones about what he was doing. Asked afterwards
why he chose to make his statement at this Upper East Side location
_ way off the beaten track of any other appointments for the day _
he smiled and said, ``I thought it would make a good photo op.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a desperate tactic, but for McCain, these are desperate
times _ in New York, that is.
</P>
<P>
   The way the state's Republican Party has set up its March 7
primary, McCain could conceivably wind up the favored candidate,
and still not win a single New York delegate to the national
convention.
</P>
<P>
   The party's leaders, who are backing Texas Gov. George W. Bush
in the presidential race, made it this way long ago and for just
this reason: to control the primary outcome.
</P>
<P>
   State law seems, on the face of things, fairly simple: To make
it on the presidential ballot, a candidate needs to collect 5,000
signatures.
</P>
<P>
   However, on the Republican ballot, votes are cast for delegates,
not for candidates directly. And by the party rules, the delegates
must collect signatures from 0.5 percent of registered Republicans
in each of the 31 congressional districts. Furthermore, they must
not include Republicans who have signed another candidate's
petition.
</P>
<P>
   The contest is tilted against McCain in another way. Because the
party leaders have demanded solidarity within the ranks, Bush's
delegates are well-known local politicians. The other candidates'
delegates are, by and large, unknowns. The ballot shows the
delegates' name in big, bold letters _ and the candidates' name in
small, thin ones.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, in the Democratic primary, voters cast ballots for
the candidates. Delegates are chosen later, to reflect the
proportion of votes.
</P>
<P>
   McCain qualified in only 16 of the districts _ and party lawyers
are challenging even some of those petitions.
</P>
<P>
   In turn, McCain has asked the Board of Elections to allow his
name on all the district ballots, and has filed a lawsuit in a
Federal court, which will hear the case next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is, we're a small party,'' said Guy Molinari, the
Staten Island borough president and one of the very few New York
Republicans of any prominence who have endorsed McCain. ``Without
the help of the state organization, it's almost impossible to
qualify in a lot of districts.
</P>
<P>
   ``In lots of districts,'' he went on, ``it's hard to find the
Republicans. I spent a half-day, calling registered Republicans in
a minority neighborhood in Brooklyn. I got one to sign a petition.
Two of my guys spent all day in the Bronx. They got one signature.
It's tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Mercurio, a local Republican consultant, said that, in
over half the districts, ``even the Bush people had trouble
qualifying.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Forbes, the multi-millionaire Republican candidate, made
it on all 31 ballots this time, after going through the same
struggles in 1996 that McCain is going through now. However, Forbes
spent $750,000 merely to organize the necessary petition drive.
</P>
<P>
   It used to be, both parties in New York ran closed primaries.
Until the mid-1970s, all ballots listed only the names of
delegates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The leaders of the Democratic and Republican parties liked to
run uncommitted delegates,'' recalled Martin Connor, an election
lawyer who is the Democratic leader in the New York state senate.
``That way, the bosses could wheel and deal at the national
convention.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1976, candidates' names were added to the ballot, but, to
qualify, their delegates had to collect 1,250 signatures in each
congressional district _ far more demanding than the Republican
rule today.
</P>
<P>
   That year, the state's Democratic bosses threw Jimmy Carter's
delegate-slates off the ballots in every district.
</P>
<P>
   After Carter won the nomination and Eugene McCarthy launched a
campaign as an independent candidate, Connor recalled, ``Carter
said, `Get me the lawyers who threw me off the ballot, and get them
to keep McCarthy off.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers succeeded. McCarthy's name was bumped off the ballot
_ a fact that may have won the state and the presidency for Carter.
</P>
<P>
   In the decades since, the Democratic party here has enacted
reforms in its primaries. The Republican party _ partly because it
is smaller and more cohesive _ has not. ``They've kept pretty much
the same system,'' Connor said. ``They've opted to hang on to
control.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
