<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SNOW-ART-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRIKING ROAD WORKERS GREET REGION'S FIRST SNOW FALL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT7 AND NYT23 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As the season's first real snow blanketed the region
Thursday, Long Island commuters found their way snarled by both the
slick, icy gloss and by politics in faraway Albany, as hundreds of
state workers, unhappy over contract talks, staged a strike rather
than show up to drive snowplows and salt spreaders.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Pataki responded with unusual ferocity, declaring a
state of emergency, putting the National Guard on alert and
obtaining a court order against the workers and their union. He
also ordered an investigation into the walkout, in part to
determine whether the workers could be fired and the union fined.
Labor leaders accused him of overreacting for political effect.
</P>
<P>
   The light layer of snow that fell would rank low on any list of
emergencies, but after three straight mild winters and a balmy
start to this one, New Yorkers could be forgiven for a moment of
panic, not to mention some inept driving, at the first flakes. By
the afternoon rush, about 2 inches had fallen across most of the
metropolitan region, though forecasters predicted that before the
night was through, New York City would get 3 to 5 inches and the
Eastern forks of Long Island would see 4 to 10 inches.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The governor was not alone in mobilizing as if for a military
campaign. Mayor Rudolph Giuliani activated the city's
hurricane-proof, flood-proof, earthquake-proof command center at
the World Trade Center, where he and other officials cited a long
list of impressive statistics to reassure everyone that all was
under control. (Plows at work: 1,272. Spreaders: 353. Tons of salt
spread by afternoon: 5,000.)
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The striking road workers on Long Island are members of the
Civil Service Employees Union, the largest group of state workers,
who have been without a contract since March 31, 1999. The union
has held many demonstrations, increasing in size and intensity, to
protest contract offers from Pataki that the workers consider
inadequate. In April, union members rejected a contract that would
have increased salaries 11.5 percent over four years, and talks
have been stalled since then.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've all been waiting for a pay increase, and everyone is
more or less rebelling,'' said Richard Diffley, an employee at the
state Department of Transportation's depot in Syosset. He said he
reported to work only because his wife was about to have a baby and
he did not want to risk losing any pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``The members are just fed up,'' said William Stodolski,
president of Local 508 of the Civil Service Employees, the local
that included the strikers. ``They don't have a contract, and the
wage offers by the state are unacceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, in anticipation of the storm, the department
ordered 440 workers in Nassau and Suffolk Counties to be at work at
6 a.m. Thursday for snow and ice removal duty on state highways.
``Only 30 of them showed up,'' said Michael Fleischer, a department
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki, in a statement, charged that the strike ``has been
condoned and supported by the state Civil Service Employees
Association.''
</P>
<P>
   But union officials insisted that it was a wildcat strike and
that they had no idea that it was coming. In fact, through the
morning, they gave radio interviews urging workers to report for
duty.
</P>
<P>
   The union contended that by midday, nearly all the workers had
returned, but the administration contended that fewer than half had
done so. Fleischer said that while the department got a slow start
salting the highways, by early afternoon, with help from Nassau and
Suffolk County crews, it had enough plows and spreaders on the
roads to deal with the snowfall.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Thursday afternoon, Pataki declared a state of emergency
on Long Island, mobilized the National Guard and directed the
Department of Transportation to hire private plow operators. The
department contracted for about 15 private plows, which union
officials said were not needed.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The governor directed Roslynn R. Mauskopf, the state's inspector
general, to conduct an investigation into the strike and determine
what punitive action could be taken against the union and the
workers, including, his statement said, ``suspending the workers
without pay, subjecting them to severe penalties and firing them.''
If the administration can establish that the union organized or
condoned the action, it is subject to heavy fines under state law.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   At Pataki's request, the state also got a temporary restraining
order against the union and the employees in state Supreme Court in
Suffolk County, which directed them to end the strike. Justice
Robert A. Lifson, who issued the order, said that if the walkout
continued, he would fine the union $1 million a day if the state
could show that the union had not done everything it could to end
it, and would fine each striking worker $1,000 a day.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki, in an interview on News 12, a Long Island cable
television channel, said: ``This is an illegal act that threatens
the lives of Long Islanders and has resulted in accidents. We're
not going to tolerate it.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   When asked why the National Guard might be needed, Michael
McKeon, the governor's press secretary, said: ``They have resources
they could use. If people were going off the road, they could help.
Mostly, we just wanted them there, just in case.''
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said the action was too well
coordinated and involved too high a proportion of the workers, to
have been carried out without the union's blessing.
</P>
<P>
   Denis M. Hughes, president of the New York state AFL-CIO, called
a reporter to say, ``The governor's response was outrageous, way
out of proportion.''
</P>
<P>
   He also questioned the credibility of the governor's office,
saying that it was telling the union at 1 p.m. that everybody went
back to work, even as administration officials were complaining to
reporters that few of the road workers were on duty. ``The governor
is making this unfortunate situation worse by trying to be a tough
guy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Until the cold spell of the last few days, nature had given the
impression that winter would never come. Thursday's snow _ the
metropolitan area's first of the season, except for a brief dusting
in some spots _ marked the second-latest date for the first
measurable snowfall in New York City's history.
</P>
<P>
   The snowfall covered much of the eastern half of the nation
Thursday, with some cities registering a light dusting while others
saw a thick coating of snow with powerful wind gusts. Roanoke, Va.,
Baltimore and Beech Mountain, N.C., had received 5 inches of snow
by late Thursday, and as much as an inch an hour was falling in
Delaware and southern New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   While the snowfall in the New York area was a bit less dramatic
during the day than had been expected, it was still enough to
tangle roads. The police reported two flipped cars during the
morning rush on Long Island and about an accident per mile on the
Long Island Expressway.
</P>
<P>
   The area's airports saw delays of 30 minutes to two hours, due
mostly to weather problems in connecting cities, and the commuter
trains ran more or less on time.
</P>
<P>
   The greater challenge on the roads may come Friday, when any
slush left on the blacktop will have turned to patchy ice. The
National Weather Service predicted temperatures in the teens, with
high winds and wind-chill readings around zero.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-00 2039EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
