<DOCNO> NYT20000120.0280 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 20:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1738 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-HEALTH-FRAUD-BOS &LR;      01-20 0498
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-FRAUD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LARGEST DIALYSIS FIRM SETTLES FRAUD CASE FOR $486M 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN WILMSEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Concluding a sweeping five-year probe of a massive Medicare
fraud scheme, federal officials have said the world's largest
kidney dialysis company, Fresenius Medical Care North America, has
agreed to pay $486 million to settle criminal and civil charges.
</P>
<P>
   It was by far the largest settlement exacted so far in a federal
campaign to prosecute what were once common forms of corruption in
the lucrative and intensely competitive medical services industry,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message today is unmistakable,'' said Mark Pearlstein,
first assistant US attorney for Massachusetts, flanked by some two
dozen investigators and Washington officials at a press conference
Wednesday. ``The government has the ability to unravel the most
complex and convoluted of schemes, and if you are engaging in these
practices, you will be caught.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the federal charges, three subsidiaries of National
Medical Care _ formerly a Waltham, Mass. company that Fresenius
acquired in 1996 _ routinely filed hundreds of thousands of false
Medicare claims, ordered unnecessary tests, and doled out kickbacks
in an effort to make doctors and health care centers recommend
National Medical Care products.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose of the schemes was simple: to increase revenues,''
Pearlstein said. ``In a very literal sense, these companies adopted
criminal behavior as a corporate strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   National Medical Care was a unit of W.R. Grace &AMP; Co. when the
schemes were carried out, officials said. A federal probe was
already under way when Fresenius acquired National Medical Care in
October 1996, and Fresenius cooperated in the investigation,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of the settlement, Fresenius agreed to pay $101
million to settle criminal charges and $385 million in civil
penalties under the False Claims Act. The company also agreed to an
eight-year government-supervised compliance program to ensure
violations don't continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``These were inherited problems, and the company came into this
with eyes open, knowing there was an investigation going on,'' said
John Markus, a Fresenius senior vice president of corporate
compliance. ``But we're happy to have this behind us.''
</P>
<P>
   Markus said the company has started training programs for
employees and hired outside auditors who will examine the company's
books and practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel very comfortable with how we're working today,''
Markus said. ``We've got people coming around, kicking the tires
and using their instincts to probe for any possible problems. It's
one thing to put a program on paper. The real challenge is to put
it into the culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Fresenius, based in Lexington, Mass., operates more than 800
kidney dialysis centers in the United States and treats some 60,000
patients who have advanced kidney disease.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
