<HEADLINE>
CISCO BUYS BAY STATE, COLORADO FIRMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cisco Systems Inc. expanded its offerings in the burgeoning
virtual private networks market Wednesday, announcing the
acquisitions of Altiga Networks Inc. of Franklin, Mass. for $351.5
million and Compatible Systems of Boulder, Colo., for $214.5
million. Both were stock deals.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition of Altiga will enable Cisco to market products
and services to corporations with employees, such as salespeople on
the road or telecommuters, who need to be linked to their company's
central computers through the Internet. Such virtual private
networks reduce a company's costs by requiring less networking
equipment and trimming overall telephone costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The markets for our kinds of products are moving so quickly
that it's simply phenomenal,'' said Mark Freitas, founder and chief
executive of Altiga. The 76-employee company formed two years ago
to develop virtual private networks and began selling its equipment
in April.
</P>
<P>
   Many companies use toll-free numbers or other dedicated phone
lines for corporate access, a system Cisco officials say is far
more expensive than using the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Virtual private networks is a big opportunity for us, and
Altiga has an experienced management and technical team and a
product that we can get into the market quickly,'' said Ammar
Hanafi, director of business development at San Jose, Calif.-based
Cisco.
</P>
<P>
   Compatible, formed in 1988, also makes equipment for virtual
private networks, and its products will become part of Cisco's line
marketed to Internet service providers.
</P>
<P>
   The Altiga deal represents Cisco's ninth acquisition in New
England in the past five years. Freitas said Altiga, which will
become part of Cisco's enterprise line, will stay in Franklin. It
plans to expand and increase hiring to meet the expected increase
in demand for its products and services, which Cisco will sell to
corporate customers and ISPs.
</P>
<P>
   Freitas said the acquisition offer came after Altiga approached
Cisco and other companies about distributing its virtual private
network equipment, which sells for between $8,000 and $30,000. He
said Cisco was not the only company to make such an offer.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, Cisco will issue 3.13 million shares for
all of Altiga's privately held stock. Based on Cisco's closing
price Wednesday of 112 5/16, that's worth $351.5 million. Cisco
also will issue 1.91 million shares worth $214.5 million for all of
Compatible's stock.
</P>
</TEXT>
