<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reeves says he'll be back next season
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Dan Reeves on Thursday put to rest speculation about
his future with the Falcons. Reeves said he will return to the team
next season for his 20th season as an NFL head coach.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 4, the day after a season-ending 34-29 victory against
the 49ers that left his team 5-11, Reeves, 56, spoke of spending
more quality time with his wife, Pam, ``before we get too old.'' He
said then that his future depended on her opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves, who has two years left on a contract that will pay him
about $2 million per season, discussed it with his wife this week
while vacationing in southwestern Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be coming back,'' said Reeves, whose career record of
167-128-1 ranks eighth in wins. ``She's not ready to have me around
that much more.''
</P>
<P>
   The next step will be determining which assistants will return.
</P>
<P>
   Washington coach Norv Turner called Reeves on Thursday morning,
and was given permission to interview Falcons secondary coach Ron
Meeks, 45, for a similar position with the Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the Falcons put a ``supervisory'' designation on
defensive-line coach Bill Kollar, making it difficult for another
team to hire him away except for a head-coaching job. The Falcons
had to give Kollar, 47, a significant raise last year after the
Titans offered to make him defensive coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation continues that quarterbacks coach Steve DeBerg will
be fired, but Reeves on Thursday denied Internet and radio reports
that he had fired offensive-line coach Art Shell, the former
Raiders head coach. Shell has been on the Falcons staff since
Reeves came to Atlanta in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``That has no merit whatsoever,'' Reeves said.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves denied last week that DeBerg would be fired, but DeBerg
was seen at a California coaching convention two weeks ago looking
for a job. DeBerg, 46, and Shell, 53, have been with the rest of
the Falcons' staff, except Reeves, in Mobile, Ala., this week for
the Senior Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Assistants are supposed to sit down for evaluations with Reeves
between today and Feb. 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may do some things different offensively, but there's no
truth to (the speculation about Shell),'' Reeves said. ``A lot may
depend on what happens when we sit down and talk ... in the next
two weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves spoke a second time with recently fired Cowboys coach
Chan Gailey, a protege since childhood in Americus, who was on
Reeves' staff in Denver, 1985-90.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey is believed to be a candidate for several jobs, including
that of offensive coordinator for the Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if they talked about Gailey joining the Falcons' staff,
Reeves said, ``No. I have talked to Chan, but just about the fact
he's coming in to see his grandmother. We didn't talk about
football.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
