<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1749 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-SKI-CITY-KIDS-ART-BOS     01-20 1212
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKI-CITY-KIDS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036 . )  
 SKI PROGRAM MAKES WINTER BETTER FOR CITY KIDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a child, Richard Williams would grow quiet, wiggling to the
edge of his seat when the newsreel came on at the movie house. Up
there on the screen were people gliding gracefully down snowy
slopes, leaving plumes of powder that glistened in the sun. Where,
he wondered, do you do that?
</P>
<P>
   He was 18 before he got the chance to find out, at Hunter
Mountain in the Catskills. His long coat flapping behind him and a
city hat perched atop his head, Williams spent as much time on his
butt as he did upright, but he knew. He laughed in joy, he reveled
in freedom, and he knew: This was his sport.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the 1950s, and when Williams got back to his New York
City neighborhood eager to share the excitement, his story was met
with derision. Lies, said one neighbor. Black people don't ski.
Poor people don't ski.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said if I could ever take these guys and show them this
experience, I would love to do that,'' said Williams recently. ``I
wanted to take them, and I knew I would never be able to take
them.''
</P>
<P>
   That was not quite true. Since founding Youth Enrichment
Services (YES) in 1968, Williams has helped 125,000 urban
youngsters from disadvantaged backgrounds get onto the slopes,
acquainting the new YES kids with the challenges, responsibilities
and just plain fun of the rural outdoors. Summer programs include
canoeing, hiking, and camping, but skiing remains the
organization's focus.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to introduce kids to things they've never seen
before,'' said Williams in the YES offices in Boston. ``Kids have
to feel they can be part of that kind of America.''
</P>
<P>
   Considering that 41 percent of Alpine skiers in 1998 had
household incomes of at least $75,000 and only 15.2 percent less
than $35,000, according to data provided by SnowSports Industries
America, it's little wonder that YES's target population (described
by Williams as the working poor, a family of four with an income of
$33,000-$35,000 a year) sees skiing as something out of their reach
financially as well as culturally.
</P>
<P>
   But with the help of 200 volunteers and more than a dozen New
England resorts, the privately-funded YES gets yooths skiing or
snowboarding for $17-20 a day, which includes bus transportation,
use of equipment, a lift ticket (usually costing up to $50)
provided by the resort, a mandatory lesson, and even the loan of a
ski cap if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   A big part of the program takes place in the basement ski shop
which, each year, trains about 50 kids to work in the shop, tuning
and sharpening the 1,500 pairs of skis the organization has amassed
through donations, often from resorts that have replaced their own
rental gear; maintaining the 500 pairs of cross-country skis and 55
snowboards; and fitting YES skiers for their weekend outings.
Volunteers must maintain at least a B average in school. Of the 50
positions, only five are paid, at $6 an hour for eight hours a
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big prestige thing to get to the paid positions, but we
have a good farm team,'' said Mary Crowther, YES's vice president
and treasurer who began as a volunteer instructor in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   According to a 1997 study by the Harvard Business School, more
than half of YES's participants continued skiing after they left
the program, and their participation lasted an average of 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have lots of fun, and maybe see a different side of
life,'' said Matt Sawyer, director of marketing at Butternut in
Great Barrington. If the youngsters stick with the sport and become
paying customers as adults, so much the better, but economics are
secondary, according to Sawyer. ``We all want everybody to have an
equal chance,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone has always felt the same way. Back in the late
'50s, when Williams began skiing, there was overt racism. Once, he
and some friends returned to their car to find their tires
flattened. Another time, some whites in the lodge threatened to
stick his face in the toilet bowl. ``They didn't do it, but they
tried,'' said Williams.
</P>
<P>
   As part of Williams's conviction that familiarity would breed
respect (``What we wanted to do was quietly bring these kids
together,'' he said), YES ski trips continued uninterrupted in the
mid-1970s, during Boston's busing crisis. Based in the neutral
South End, YES was perfectly situated to bring youngsters together
for a peaceful activity in a time of turmoil, according to
Williams. Potential troublemakers were warned to leave behind any
belligerent behavior: ``If you can't come here without doing that,
don't come here,'' he told them. The upshot: ``They wanted to
come.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if there were any incidents, Williams could recall only
the bus driver who, upon arriving at a resort in Maine, called the
police to warn them that he had just dropped off a bunch of kids
and there was bound to be a riot. When the police arrived, the city
youths eagerly started following them around to see what was
happening.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted to see the action,'' Williams said, still getting
a good belly laugh.
</P>
<P>
   These days, the reaction tends more toward curiosity than
animosity, and sometimes there is concern that bringing
disadvantaged youth to the slopes does nothing but remind them of
an activity they could not otherwise afford.
</P>
<P>
   Crowther bristles. ``Skiing is affordable,'' she said. ``It's
not the elitist, expensive sport anymore. You have to break down
those stereotypes.'' It's like the difference, she said, between
``a rich person's car or a get-around town car.'' You can stay for
a week at a fancy resort and use all the latest gear, or you can
take day trips and pack a lunch. Either way, you're mastering a
difficult skill that nurtures confidence and pride. ``If I can do
this,'' Williams said the kids begin to feel, ``(they) can do
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Taran Grigsby, a 28-year-old attorney with Goulston and Storrs
in Boston, wholeheartedly agrees. Grigsby hooked up with the
program as a young South End teenager and has been involved ever
since. ``The program was very, very good for me,'' said Grigsby, a
Bowdoin graduate who is now on the YES board of trustees. ``It
helped me decide that I was going to go and do something a little
different: (People assume) black kids don't go to college in Maine.
It's a vehicle to teach people they can succeed in other
environments.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Fitzpatrick agrees, too. As a South Boston teenager with
eight older siblings whose father died when he was just 4 years
old, Fitzgerald would, he said, probably have been down at Fields
Corner on weekends drinking with the neighborhood kids had it not
been for YES.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a program that definitely brought blacks and whites
together, although I don't think I realized it at the time,'' he
said. ``(Williams) gave us responsibilities and trusted us as young
kids. He made a big difference in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(To learn more about YES programs, or to make a donation, visit the
Web site at www.yeskids.org or call 617-267-5877.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
