<SLUG> BC-TRANSMETA-CHIPS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRANSMETA'S `SMART CHIP,' STARRING LINUS TORVALDS, DEBUTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA, Calif. _ The chips are finally down.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the most eagerly anticipated announcements in Silicon
Valley, Transmeta Corp., a secretive, much-watched start-up that
employs Linus Torvalds, creator of the fast-rising Linux operating
system, Wednesday revealed what it had been working on for five
years.
</P>
<P>
   The company took the wraps off a family of ``smart chips,'' or
microprocessors, that Transmeta executives say will transform the
world of mobile computing. ``This thing is ready for prime time,''
said James N. Chapman, Tramsmeta's senior vice president of
marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Called Crusoe, Transmeta's chips are targeted at the
fast-growing market for ultra-light, portable computers and
wireless Web devices. The chips are designed to address one of the
biggest complaints from laptop users _ short battery life. Because
the chips consume less power than conventional microprocessors, a
computer with a Crusoe chip can theoretically run all day on one
battery, according to Transmeta.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to shape the design of microprocessors for years
to come,'' said Linley Gwennap, a microprocessor analyst in
Mountain View. ``This is a breakthrough.''
</P>
<P>
   The chips, which are being manufactured by IBM Corp., are novel
because they incorporate software to handle functions that are
usually done by transistors.
</P>
<P>
   While Transmeta has been around since 1995, secrecy has shrouded
the company's activities. The tinted glass on the company's
headquarters in Santa Clara, contributed to the mystique, as did
the company's decision three years ago to hire Torvalds, something
of a folk hero among software programmers who developed Linux, the
operating system that is starting to challenge Microsoft's dominant
Windows system. Transmeta received backing from Microsoft Corp.
cofounder Paul Allen and financier George Soros, adding further to
its mystique.
</P>
<P>
   In November, Torvalds, who helped develop the software for
Crusoe, dropped a clue about Transmeta's mission. The product was a
``smart chip,'' he told thousands who attended the annual Comdex
computer show in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   What makes the microprocessor smart, Transmeta's founder and
chief executive David Ditzel said Wednesday, is the software that
runs the chip. Called LongRun, the software allows the chips to
constantly adjust their voltage according to the demands of the
applications running on the computer at any given time. As a
result, machines running Crusoe chips burn up far fewer watts than
conventional microprocessors.
</P>
<P>
   The Crusoe software also takes over some of the functions of a
chip, taking a load off the chip itself and allowing it to run much
faster, said Ditzel, a former chip designer for Sun Microsystems
Inc. and AT&AMP;T Bell Laboratories.
</P>
<P>
   While analysts were impressed by the company's technology, they
noted a number of hurdles Transmeta must overcome before it can
begin to whittle away Intel's dominance in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Some question, for example, whether equipment makers will pick
up Crusoe processors for their computers. So far, Transmeta has no
contracts to sell its chips, which are being manufactured in
Burlington, Vt. by IBM and will sell for $65 to $329 apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Ditzel said major computer manufacturers are evaluating the chip
now and are expected to start shipping products containing Crusoe
chips by mid-year. ``We're prepared to take on the industry,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   He did not, however, project how much of the $4 billion to $5
billion mobile personal computer chip market Transmeta is expected
to capture. About 22.2 million mobile computers are expected to be
sold this year, according to Dataquest.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever Transmeta's sales, they are not likely to immediately
affect industry leader Intel Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter how good the product is, it's not something 50
million people will be able to buy next year,'' said Gwennap, the
microprocessor analyst.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, ``Intel should be paying attention,'' Gwennap
said. ``This definitely changes the rules.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
