<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-EDUCATION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH AFRICAN GHETTO FOSTERS A MODEL FOR SCHOOL REFORM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KURT SHILLINGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORANGE FARM, South Africa _ Orange Farm is what South Africans
call an ``informal settlement,'' an unincorporated jumble of
rickety dwellings and metalwork yards spilling outward from a
grassy hill. One of the poorest black ghettos around Johannesburg,
it also has a reputation for being one of the most dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   But as a new school year opens, Orange Farm is becoming known
for something else: a high school of improbably high standards. At
a time when less than 50 percent of final-year students pass the
test required to graduate, the Leshata Secondary School stands as a
model for educators struggling to reform an education system
stumped by acute textbook shortages and gross racial imbalances.
Surrounded by cows and tin shacks, Leshata was one of the only
township schools to have passed every graduating student last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not have long stories to tell you,'' said Moeketsi
Molelekoa, Leshata's principal, explaining the school's success.
``Nothing will ever substitute hard work. Teachers must teach,
learners must learn. That's it.''
</P>
<P>
   Molelekoa's simplicity masks the enormity of the challenge that
he and other educators face. Five years after the demise of
apartheid, South Africa's schools still bear the deep scars of
institutionalized racism. For decades, the former white minority
regimes used a cynical system they described as ``Bantu education''
to train blacks into more efficient servants, but to deprive them
of the intellectual tools needed to thrive in a modern, complex
world. Until 1995, 70 percent of South Africans were denied the
right to basic education.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new constitution, education is now compulsory and
universal, and it claims 22 percent of the national budget. But the
imbalances endure. While most white students have well-equipped
schools and demanding teachers, the majority of students are
fortunate to have pads on which to write. According to the
Department of Education, 60 percent of math and science teachers in
black schools are unqualified.
</P>
<P>
   As schools opened last week, many children faced appalling
conditions. In Soweto, the sprawling township just south of
Johannesburg, some students spent the day cleaning classrooms
rather than receiving instruction.
</P>
<P>
   Around the country, teachers did not show. Principals complained
that new supplies of textbooks promised by the government had not
arrived.
</P>
<P>
   In many rural places, students learn in decrepit buildings
without electricity _ or under trees. Racial tensions persist,
making classrooms and playgrounds violent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Education is where apartheid was victorious,'' Education
Minister Kader Asmal said at a recent breakfast with reporters.
``White schools are one step behind Spain. Black schools are one
step behind the Republic of Congo. We face an extraordinary
imbalance.''
</P>
<P>
   The past is not entirely to blame for the present state of most
South African schools. The national pass rate for the matric, the
exam that students must pass to advance to college, declined
steadily during former President Nelson Mandela's term of office,
the first five years of democracy in South Africa. Last year,
classes were disrupted by a protracted strike as teachers demanded
better pay.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of the new school year, acting on no more than two
day's notice, President Thabo Mbeki rounded up educators last
weekend in the Northern Province, where only 37 percent of students
passed the matric. Mbeki demanded a new level of performance. ``If
you look at Africa, it does not matter what field you look at,
whether in economics or technology, we are the last in the queue.
This must stop. . . . Principals who are found not to be doing
their jobs will be fired,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week Asmal unveiled a five-year national strategy to
improve education standards, including strict policies on HIV/AIDS
in the classroom; the conduct and professionalism of educators;
targets for adult literacy; and improvements for black tertiary
institutions, most of which face extreme shortages of resources and
qualified professors.
</P>
<P>
   In a scene replayed across impoverished townships throughout the
country, Joseph Kobeni stood amid a crowd of desperate parents
outside the yellow-brick walls of Leshata Secondary School who had
been hoping to enroll their children late for classes beginning the
following day. Many fanned away the summer heat with copies of
their child's transcripts.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, Molelekoa sat frustrated in his office. ``We were
supposed to have our first staff meeting today,'' he said. ``These
people should have registered in November, but poor people are
always so disorganized. Apartheid destroyed the mentality of our
people. They don't make the education of their children a priority.
If you are not strong, you will collapse in this job.''
</P>
<P>
   Physically, Leshata is something of a surprise. Built five years
ago by a private trust, 20 classrooms form a smart, sturdy
quadrangle that contrasts sharply with the township's dilapidated
conditions. But that is where the luxuries end. The school has no
library, and laboratory equipment is scarce. Textbooks are
tattered, and are too few for all 900 students. There are no maps
to assist with geography lessons, no computers to keep
administration records. A high fence surrounds the school, but
theft and vandalism are constant problems.
</P>
<P>
   But Molelekoa allows no excuses. The poor matric results
announced last month, marking an all-time low national pass-rate
average of 47 percent, has prompted widespread calls for a
reintroduction of corporal punishment in schools.
</P>
<P>
   Molelekoa has a different sense of discipline. The challenge, he
said, is to inculcate a new ethos within and beyond the school's
walls to replace the apathy ingrained by decades of apartheid.
Teachers are expected to show up early, stay late, and dress like
professionals. Students receive no sympathy for work undone or done
poorly. If parents are called in for conferences and fail to show,
their children will be punished with after-school chores such as
cleaning bathrooms or pulling weeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historically, in black schools, parents did not cooperate.
Schools were very hostile environments under apartheid,'' Molelekoa
said. ``We still have a serious problem with getting parents
involved in the education of their students. I have to force them.
Whether you are rich or poor, you are not excused from your
responsibility to your child.''
</P>
<P>
   A quiet, modest man, Molelekoa, 38, is no stranger to the
disadvantages his students face. During his childhood, his family
was forcibly removed from their home by the apartheid police.
Later, the liberation movement recruited him into protests against
the bantu education system. Yet he still thrived. His illiterate
mother would force him to stay up late doing his homework. From
early adolescence onward, he worked to pay his way through three
college degrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The conditions that my students are in now, I went through
myself,'' he said. ``I was saved by education. Good results are not
manna from heaven. I don't negotiate the rules with my students,
but I stay with them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-00 2048EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
