<DOCNO> NYT20000120.0296 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1760 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-AUTHOR-HIAASEN-ART-BO     01-20 1758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-HIAASEN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036 . )  
 SLIME-RAKER OF SUN COUNTRY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH P. KAHN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Finding raw material for his comic novels ``is like shooting
fish in a barrel down there,'' says Florida native and best-selling
author Carl Hiaasen, lunching at the Charles Hotel while on a
recent publicity swing through the untropical Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cities like Boston have their own colorful histories with
graft. But Miami is different,'' Hiaasen spearing a wad of mashed
potato with a fork.
</P>
<P>
   A muckraking columnist for The Miami Herald by day, Hiaasen
mines familiar territory in his latest novel, ``Sick Puppy''
(Knopf), a multilayered saga of passion and revenge that blends a
powerful anti-South-Florida-development message with scenes of
dognapping, wife stealing, kinky sex, fetishism, torture, murder,
possum eating, and plastic surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and did we mention the hooker who only services Republicans?
</P>
<P>
   ``In Miami, they're just so clumsy and inept about it that it's
fun to write about,'' Hiaasen continues, chewing on _ to continue
the fish motif for a moment _ a piece of broiled scrod.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most politicians who take money realize there's some shame
attached to the moment. In Florida, these guys get caught on FBI
surveillance tape and they're giggling like little children. Money
is flying everywhere down there. (itals)Everywhere.''(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   And then, says Hiaasen, tossing back a shot of iced tea, there's
the case of Elian Gonzalez, the 6-year-old Cuban refugee whose
custodial fate has turned into an agitprop opera bouffe worthy of
Tom Wolfe's ``Bonfire of the Vanities.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I turn on CNN and (anti-Castro) protesters are tying up
rush-hour traffic so people can't get to their doctors or home to
their kids,'' snorts Hiaasen. ``They take this boy to Disney World,
give him Pokemon cards, put him in a parade _ it's disgraceful.
It's child abuse. They don't give a rat's ass about this kid. This
circus has lasted for 40 years and eight presidents, and Fidel is
still there, looking taller in the saddle than ever. He's the
happiest little communist there is right now. The last, and the
happiest.''
</P>
<P>
   Hiaasen waves his fork with a flourish. While he could likely
afford to give up column writing, he confesses, he would miss the
target practice. The real-life shady pols and deal-makers, the scam
artists and theme-park evangelists who practically cruise around
the state wearing bull's-eyes on their backs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The same energy that gets me riled up enough to do a column
about crooked developers goes into the novels,'' Hiaasen opines.
``My outlook is, if you don't stay angry, nothing gets fixed. Not
anger in the sense of venom but in the sense of outrage. You have
to write about these things. Talk about them, put a spotlight on
them. Or they won't get fixed. Even if you don't have all the
answers, you can't turn away.''
</P>
<P>
   Hiaasen smiles and puts down his fork. No longer a cult figure
or boy wonder at age 46, Hiaasen, a third-generation Floridian who
grew up near Fort Lauderdale, still cuts a boyish figure when he
ventures out to meet the book-buying public. Otherwise he holes up
in the Florida Keys _ he rarely sets foot in the newspaper offices
_ in a waterfront home he shares with his second wife, his
8-year-old stepson, and a new baby due any day now.
</P>
<P>
   Critics are left wondering, meanwhile, if Hiaasen the novelist
is a clever genre writer, satiric genius, one-trick pony, or an
unlikely but entertaining combination of John D. MacDonald, Edward
Abbey, and Nathaniel West.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sick Puppy'' has garnered the usual (for Hiaasen) bag of
mixed-to-rave reviews. Writing in The New York Times, Joe Queenan
likened Hiaasen to Donald Westlake and Eugene Ionesco _ an unlikely
combination right there. Queenan also praised Hiaasen for making
``a persuasive case that the most barbarous, ignorant and just
plain awful people living in this country today reside, nay
flourish, in the state of Florida.''
</P>
<P>
   Mystery writer Tony Hillerman once called Hiaasen ``the Mark
Twain of the crime novel.'' Salman Rushdie is said to be a fan.
Others have described Hiaasen as ``Elmore Leonard meets Terry
Southern'' or ``Elmore Leonard after several hits of nitrous
oxide,'' which may amount to the same thing. If one critique dogs
the author, it's that he writes essentially the same book over and
over again, upping the absurdity quotient each time out as he
skewers the Sunshine State and all its grotesqueries.
</P>
<P>
   While his characters remain dependably fresh _ the only
recurrent cast member is a fugitive ex-governor named Clinton
(Skink) Tyree, who returns for a fourth time in ``Sick Puppy'' _
the Hiaasen formula varies little from novel to novel. Each book
typically includes one hideously twisted villain (in ``Sick
Puppy,'' a sadistic hit man who collects 911 tapes for personal
amusement), one resourceful but flawed do-gooder, one or more
corrupt state officials, one sexy ingenue, a murderous animal or
two, a threat to Mother Nature, and a small pile of corpses.
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, at least Hiaasen comes by his formula naturally. The
son and grandson of Fort Lauderdale lawyers, he grew up in a South
Florida relatively unblemished by retirement communities and theme
parks. His love for adventure novels and the outdoors clearly
shaped his thematic concerns. After graduating with a journalism
degree from the University of Florida, he joined the Miami Herald
staff in 1976. As an investigative reporter, Hiaasen went after the
same unscrupulous developers and narco-traders that have become
fodder for his over-the-top fiction. He's got street cred few
novelists can claim.
</P>
<P>
   While in college Hiaasen demonstrated an aptitude for other
kinds of writing as well, collaborating on one book that became the
movie ``Doc Hollywood'' and three more thrillers he wrote with a
Herald colleague. ``Tourist Season,'' Hiaasen's first solo effort,
was published in 1986. In this acclaimed debut, Hiaasen served up a
band of ecoterrorists that feed tourists to the alligators and
kidnap the Orange Bowl Queen. As in subsequent Hiaasen novels, it's
hard to tell the good guys from the bad guys _ and more fun not to
try.
</P>
<P>
   ``I start out with a premise,'' Hiaasen explains. ``Like in
`Lucky You' '' _ his seventh novel _ ``a woman wins the state
lottery. In Florida, if you don't have your ticket, forget it. If
the ticket is stolen, how could you prove it? So I threw a bunch of
characters on stage to see what would happen.''
</P>
<P>
   What happens is a lot of mayhem, gunfire, and satiric commentary
on the white supremacy movement. ``Sick Puppy'' has similar
origins, according to Hiaasen. Years ago, he says, he saw someone
idly tossing trash out of an SUV. Imagining what would happen if
the litterbug were a true sleazebag _ and the eyewitness a
crusading environmentalist _ Hiaasen cooked up his latest plot,
about a slimy lobbyist being stalked by an anger-challenged
eco-warrior. Much merriment ensues, some involving a lecherous
developer with a weird thing for Barbie dolls.
</P>
<P>
   ``All my books are character driven,'' Hiaasen says. ``I'm
always amused to see them described as mysteries, because the only
mystery is how the hell I got from point A to point B.''
</P>
<P>
   While ``disguised as thrillers,'' he continues, ``you pretty
much know who did what. I don't have the attention span to do a
real detective guy. I'm not Bob Parker, although I wish I were. I
wish I could stick with a character like Spenser. But the
characters who fade off into the mangroves at the end of my books,
well, I think they're better left out there.''
</P>
<P>
   If Hiaasen does not seem deeply troubled by his detractors
perhaps it is because, as with James Bond movies, his novels seem
critically bullet-proof. His biggest flop was probably the film
version of ``Strip Tease,'' a 1993 Hiaasen novel about a stripper,
a child custody case, a sex-crazed congressman, and the corrosive
influence of Big Sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Demi Moore and Burt Reynolds shared co-billing in a movie that
posed the question of which was more mind-boggling, Moore
championing motherhood by baring her surgically-enhanced breasts,
or Reynolds wearing a hairpiece that appeared to be on loan from
the Animal Rescue League?
</P>
<P>
   Hiaasen had nothing to do with the movie other than cashing a
few studio checks. His other novels are all under option, but like
Elmore Leonard's books (with the notable exception of ``Get
Shorty'') they seem resistant to sucessful screen adaptation.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that's OK,'' says Hiaasen. ``The whole Hollywood scene is
cool for about five minutes, and only five minutes. You're sitting
in a restaurant and Paul Newman walks in with his agent. After
that, it's boring.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, there are folks in Florida who may be grateful
Hiaasen is not attracting an even wider audience. The Walt Disney
Co. would be one one, about which Hiaasen penned a book-length
essay titled ``Team Rodent.'' If that title doesn't say it all,
Hiaasen's introduction does. ``The absolute worst thing Disney did
is to change how people in Florida thought about money,'' he
writes. ``Merely by showing up, Disney had dignified blind greed in
a state pioneered by undignified greedheads. The gates opened, and
in galloped fresh hordes.''
</P>
<P>
   The Florida Chamber of Commerce would be another. Hiaasen once
appeared live on ABC's ``Good Morning America'' and boasted that
Miami led the nation in corpses found in automobile trunks. Nothing
was wrong with the state, he told host Charles Gibson, that ``a
good force-5 hurricane couldn't fix.''
</P>
<P>
   A third would be Governor Jeb Bush, younger brother of
Republican presidential hopeful George W.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not his favorite writer,'' admits Hiaasen, polishing off a
slice of apple tart. ``He's a smart guy. He's made some good
appointments and some horrendous ones. He understands the
Everglades means votes. But at the very bottom of his soul, he's
still just a real estate developer from Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Hiaasen gets up, preparing to leave for a book signing. One more
thing, he says. He always wanted to write a novel whose hero is a
Labrador retriever. In that regard, ``Sick Puppy'' fulfills a
lifelong dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``Labs wake up and think it's the greatest day of their lives,''
he says with a wink. ``They're my idols. I should know. I've got
visitation rights to two of 'em.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
