<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1762 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-U.N.-HELMS-1STLD-ART-     01-20 0985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.N.-HELMS-1STLD-ART-920(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.C.)  
 HELMS CARRIES MESSAGE OF THE RIGHT TO AN ANGRY U.N. 
</HEADLINE>
 (Subs to add `to' in hed) 
(ART ADV: Photos NYT8, 9 and 10 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036.) 
(jw) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., came to the Security
Council Thursday offering a ``hand of friendship,'' but delivered
the sort of clenched-fist message that has made him the symbol of
right-wing hostility to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Helms, the most powerful conservative voice in foreign policy as
chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, argued that
Congress had the right to dictate conditions for the payment of
American debts to the organization. He warned the United Nations to
keep its ``utopian'' visions away from American sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the United Nations respects the sovereign rights of the
American people, and serves them as an effective tool of diplomacy,
it will earn and deserve their respect and support,'' he said in a
speech to council members. ``But a United Nations that seeks to
impose its presumed authority on the American people without their
consent begs for confrontation and, I want to be candid, eventual
U.S. withdrawal.''
</P>
<P>
   Helms tried to put a positive face on his visit, arranged by a
North Carolina businessman and a friend of the senator who was
appointed an alternate delegate to the General Assembly last fall
and by Richard Holbrooke, the American permanent representative to
the United Nations and this month's Security Council president.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke has spent months trying to build bridges with a
hostile Congress, led by Helms, that has held up payments of U.N.
dues and delayed the confirmation of ambassadors and other foreign
policy officials _ notably including Holbrooke himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is important,'' Helms said, ``that this body have greater
contact with the elected representatives of the American people,
and that we have greater contact with you.'' He invited Security
Council members to visit his committee in Washington. Before the
council meeting, he spoke for about 40 minutes with Secretary
General Kofi Annan and asked him to pose for pictures with the
Helms family.
</P>
<P>
   But in his speech, Helms, asserting that he was speaking for the
American people _ delivered a clear-cut conservative manifesto on
the United Nations, and didn't leave anything open for compromise.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of his address to an extraordinary gathering of
ambassadors, nearly every member of the Security Council challenged
Helms' bleak portrayal of the United Nations, and criticized the
United States for letting the organization down.
</P>
<P>
   Ambassador Alain Dejammet of France, visibly agitated, said to
Helms: ``We hear you, but the idea in this house is that others
must be heard as well.''
</P>
<P>
   And Sir Jeremy Greenstock of Britain added: ``The United Nations
is not a separate organ to which we turn, like a fire service. It
is the member states, and the United States owns 25 percent of the
power and the resources of the United Nations. What it does well,
the U.S. gets credit for. What it does badly, the U.S. must bear
some responsibility for.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to do things here democratically,'' Sir Jeremy said,
``because we all have national sovereignties. We all have national
sovereignties, and in a globalizing world there is such a thing as
the international collective interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Helms told the Security Council that unlike the Europeans, the
American people were moving away from ``supra-national
institutions'' and want no part of ``utopian'' international
arrangements, including the international criminal court created
last year over the objections of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's session, which the council decided only Wednesday to
open to the press and the public, was a gamble for Holbrooke,
diplomats said. But it seems to have paid off both for Helms, who
was welcomed with fanfare and was given an unusual stage to air his
views, and for his adversaries. Diplomats from around the world,
particularly Security Council members who have fumed quietly over
what they see as a deadbeat America bankrupting the organization,
got the chance to tell Helms directly what they thought _ however
diplomatically the comments were couched.
</P>
<P>
   After Helms praised the anti-communist Reagan doctrine for
having brought freedom and democracy to the world without the help
or approval of the United Nations, the Namibian representative,
Martin Andjaba, took impassioned exception.
</P>
<P>
   The Reagan doctrine, he said, denied independence to Namibia and
its Southwest African Peoples Organization, gave support to
apartheid South Africa and empowered the UNITA rebel movement in
Angola, which has prolonged a quarter-century-long civil war.
</P>
<P>
   ``It contributed to a lot of suffering in Africa,'' he said.
``Some of us in SWAPO who were a legitimate and genuine national
liberation movement were called other names: terrorists,'' he said.
``And those that caused death and destruction in Africa were called
liberators _ and they were supported.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That page has passed, but we have it fresh in our memories,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Helms said Thursday that he spoke for the American people, but
in reality he set out a clear-cut manifesto of the conservative
right on international affairs.
</P>
<P>
   In a list of indictments against the organization, he revived
old criticism about votes in the General Assembly that ran against
the United States, he attacked a human rights monitor who reported
on allegations of human rights violations in the United States and
objected to accusations that American debts _ still more than $1
billion despite a recent payment _ were harming the organization.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   He said that the United States had spent $10.1 billion on the
United Nations and its projects in 1999, a figure immediately
disputed by Steven Dimoff, vice president of the U.N. Association
of the United States and the director of its Washington office.
Dimoff said in an interview that the sum ``really does stretch
reality,'' because it included military activities planned and
executed by the United States without any input from the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Dimoff, whose organization supports and studies the United
Nations, said that the spectacle in the Security Council of a
member of Congress and not the president purporting to speak for
the American people on foreign affairs ``demonstrates how the
Clinton administration has ceded all the ground of U.S.
policymaking on the U.N. to Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The appearance Thursday,'' he said, ``is symbolic of the
extent to which Congress is now in charge.''
</P>
<P>
   The representatives of France and Canada also challenged Helms
on his budget assertions and his denials that the burden of
American arrears was falling on poor nations. Helms said that the
American people ``have heard U.N. officials say absurdly that
countries like Fiji and Bangladesh were carrying America's burden
in peacekeeping.''
</P>
<P>
   Canada's representative, Robert Fowler, replied: ``Senator, I
don't know if I am a U.N. official. I don't think I am. But I am
somebody who has spoken recently about Fiji and Bangladesh. I noted
that in 1999 Bangladesh was owed approximately $18 million, or just
under 175 times its regular budget contributions to this
organization, and that Fiji was owed $4 million, or just under 100
times its regular budget assessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``In that 60 percent of all monies owed to the United Nations
are owed by the United States, 60 percent of those numbers are owed
by Americans to Bangladeshis and to Fijians.,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
