<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAUNCH ADVOCATES OF CIVIC MEDIA RESIGN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the surface, they don't seem to have much in common _ two
daily newspaper editors dismissed from their posts half a continent
apart. But the recent departures of Colorado Springs Gazette
(94,000 circulation) editor Steve Smith and Binghamton Press &AMP; Sun
Bulletin (62,000 circulation) executive editor Martha Steffens have
much in common. Certainly, neither of them saw eye to eye with
their new publishers. But more important,both were serious newsroom
innovators, aggressive risk takers, and major proponents of the
civic journalism movement, which unites media outlets and community
members in an effort to identify and attack local problems. And
both will be missed.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parting with (publisher) Scott (Fisher) was very
professional,'' says Smith, who announced his exit this month after
more than four years as editor. ``Scott and I had a different set
of perceptions on content and business strategies.'' Steffens says
her November exit _ after more than two years as executive editor _
was the result of ``deep philosophical differences'' with publisher
William Monopoli.
</P>
<P>
   During her tenure, Steffens liked to make unconventional hires,
using a former assistant district attorney to cover the courts and
bringing a teacher on as a copy editor. She is best known for her
stewardship of Facing Our Future, an ambitious civic journalism
project that brought local residents together to address the
region's economic distress. (Among other things, it helped create a
new interstate highway). A staunch advocate of journalism as a tool
for change, she once traveled to Colombia to talk to editors about
using their papers to combat the drug trade.
</P>
<P>
   In Colorado Springs, Smith held open news meetings in the middle
of the newsroom, published stories that not only included the
reporter's byline, but also the names of the headline writer and
story editor, and told his staff to eschew the traditional
``conflict frame'' of journalism and try producing stories from
different perspectives.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to his exit, Smith completed a major redesign and
restructuring of the paper to re-emphasize fresher news. And daily
circulation this past December was up 3,000 copies over the same
monthin 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to step back and think about things,'' says Smith,
when asked about his plans. ``I'm thinking about academics. But I'm
going to take three months and chill.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have several irons in the fire,'' adds Steffens. ``One
option is teaching . . . Clearly, I felt very strongly about the
role of the community (and) I know from the many calls that I
received that the community very much wants me to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are saddened by the loss of two risk-taking civic
journalists,'' eulogizes Jan Schaffer, executive director of the
Pew Center for Civic Journalism. ``They had both created journalism
. . . that had enormous impact in their communities.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Smith fans will recognize the style _ a gripping tale
of her attempt to cope with her son's imprisonment in the
February/March issue of Ms. magazine. According to editor Marcia
Ann Gillespie, the former Globe columnist _ along with Gloria
Steinem _ will be regular Ms. columnists with broad mandates.
``This is the place to talk about whatever's on your mind,'' says
Gillespie. ``So we just wanted to say `Hit it, girl.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Gillespie says Ms. staffers weighed the merits of hiring Smith _
who resigned from the Globe in 1998 after fabricating characters
and quotes in some of her columns _ and made a decision after being
moved by her piece in the September issue of Essence magazine
reliving that professional nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a country where we pride ourselves on our ability to
move on,'' says Gillespie. ``I read that and wondered, `How many
times does this woman have to say, ``I'm sorry?'' ' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-00 2052EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000120.0300 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1768 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      01-20 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THE MORNING AFTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 THOMAS L. FRIEDMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt _ With the prospects high that Syria will
eventually follow Egypt's lead into a peace treaty with Israel, a
debate has been triggered within Egypt's political elite that could
best be summarized as follows: Is there life for Egypt after peace?
</P>
<P>
   That is to say, once Syria enters the circle of peace with
Israel, likely followed by the Palestinians, Egypt's longstanding
role of first leading the Arab world into war with Israel and then
into peace will be over. So what role does Egypt play next?
</P>
<P>
   ``The question we used to ask ourselves before was: What are we
going to do if the peace process fails?'' said Egypt's foreign
minister, Amr Moussa, in an interview. ``Now we ask, what are we
going to do when the peace process succeeds? Because the situation
is going to change. Peace is going to happen. This is our
conclusion. But the peace has to be fair if it is going to work.''
If it is, though, he asked: ``What's next? All the think tanks here
are working on that question.''
</P>
<P>
   There are many schools of thought. Some, albeit a tiny minority,
argue that Egypt should use the opportunity of peace to redefine
itself out of the Middle East and into Southern Europe, hitching
its wagon to the European Union train.
</P>
<P>
   Others argue that Egypt has been and will forever be tied to the
Arab world by history, language, geography and religion, and its
natural role will be as the chief rival of Israel for regional
influence, once Israel is fully integrated into the Middle East.
The Al-Ahram columnist Salaheddin Hafez predicted last week that
after comprehensive peace, Israel's ``first step will be to
concentrate on diminishing the leadership role of Egypt in its Arab
nationalist environment,'' and Egypt must resist that.
</P>
<P>
   A prominent Egyptian intellectual, Mohammed Sid Ahmed, also sees
a natural rivalry emerging between Egypt and Israel. ``Egypt-Israel
relations have gone through three phases,'' he explained. ``First
was hostility and war. Second was partnership, when Egypt and
Israel worked together to persuade the other Arabs that their
reconciliation was the right way to go. Third, the phase we are now
in, is moving beyond partnership into rivalry over who will set the
guidelines for this region.''
</P>
<P>
   Moussa insists that Israel will not be Egypt's regional rival,
for one simple reason: ``Israel cannot lead the Arab world. If
Turkey can't, how can Israel? The Egyptian leadership role in the
Middle East did not start in 1948. The Egyptian leadership role is
geographical, cultural and geopolitical.''
</P>
<P>
   But the question still lingers: How will Egypt exercise its
leadership post-peace? This region is different today from the days
when the whole Arab world waited to see what the Egyptian press and
movie industry were producing to know what to think. Tiny Qatar,
the smallest Arab state, has its own satellite TV, Al-Jazirah,
which is now the most widely watched TV in the region _ because it
is free, diverse in its views and critical of Arab regimes. Indeed
Al-Jazirah is so influential, Egypt has had to move toward
privatizing some of its own state-owned TV to keep up.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why I believe there is only one role Egypt can play, if
it is to thrive as a country and remain relevant as the Arab
leader, and that is for Egypt to be the model for how the Arab
world adjusts to globalization. Egypt has the people, the market,
the educated middle class and the brains to be the Taiwan of the
Mediterranean. Unfortunately, though, both its leadership and much
of its population remain ambivalent about globalization. They
recognize the necessity of Egypt's getting its industry and
infrastructure up to speed for global competition, and liberalizing
its politics, but they are wary about the transition. In the long
run, though, Egypt's current gradualism will not be sufficient to
retain its relevance.
</P>
<P>
   Egypt will only remain relevant in the Arab world if it can set
the example _ not for how to deliver Israel, but for how to deliver
the goods. To do that will require the current Egyptian leadership
to be as zealous about modernization and political reform as Gamal
Abdel Nasser was about Arab unity and Anwar Sadat was about the
peace process. As one Egyptian businessman put it to me: ``A few
years after the peace between Israel and Syria, Egypt will either
be very important or totally irrelevant.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
