<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1769 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      01-20 1756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WRESTLING WITH THE WWF AND THE SMACKDOWN CULTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA F. MELTZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What is it about WWF that is so compelling for our sons?
</P>
<P>
   For Craig Keville, a fifth-grader, it's entertaining. ``They do
crazy things,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Classmate Tim Beatty can't contain himself: ``Like when they
moon!''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, the ice is broken. The five boys in guidance counselor Corie
Brookshire's office fall over one another laughing as they describe
the moves of World Wrestling Federation superstars Stone Cold
</P>
<P>
   Steve Austin, Mankind, and the Rock. They know WWF is staged,
but there's a heated discussion nonetheless about whether the steel
chairs they break over each other are fake and where the blood
comes from.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not ketchup!'' insists Patrick Carroll. ``The ref cuts
'em with a razor,'' says Lucas Villandry.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas can't imagine life without WWF and takes umbrage when
asked if he and his friends pretend to be wrestlers when they play.
``We don't pretend,'' he says. ``We (itals)are(unitals) the
wrestlers.''
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to find a 9- to 12-year-old boy today who can't
relate. Wrestling is hot. Not only was ``WWF Smackdown'' the second
most-watched programming on network television last year, but WWF
also markets dozens of products to children of all ages, including
action figures for 3- and 4-year-olds even though the show is rated
for 14 and up.
</P>
<P>
   WWF is sports entertainment with a soap-operalike story line
that extends beyond the ring; there are fifth-grade boys who know
more about the feud between Stone Cold and Vince McMahon than about
Revolutionary battles. It also includes language so crude that
Coca-Cola refused to advertise on ``Smackdown.''
</P>
<P>
   Professionals who study the influence of pop culture on children
say boys would be better off if they never saw WWF. Unfortunately
for those of us with preteens, it's too late for that.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Natural inclinations
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Psychologist William Pollack is not surprised that boys are
drawn to WWF. ``They have a natural inclination toward action,
quest, and adventure,'' he says. He runs the Center for Men and
Young Men at McLean Hospital in Belmont, Mass. and is author of
``Real Boys: Rescuing Our Sons From the Myths of Boyhood'' (Holt).
</P>
<P>
   Boys also have an equally strong developmental need to identify
with something powerful, says pediatrician Eli Newberger, who
specializes in male development. (The attraction to something
powerful is also a draw for a smattering of girls, who tend to
follow WWF's female wrestlers.)
</P>
<P>
   ``For boys who are confused about their physical growth and
about where they fit into their social hierarchy, WWF affords
identity with a powerful character,'' he says. He is author of
``The Men They Will Become: The Nature and Nurture of Male
Character'' (Perseus).
</P>
<P>
   By adopting a persona or playing with wrestling action figures,
a boy feels less vulnerable. ``In the play, you are in control.
It's you who is strong and powerful,'' says Kathy Merlock-Jackson,
a professor at Virginia Wesleyan College who specializes in mass
media and children's culture.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Security from ritual
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even the outrageousness meets a need, says Linda K. Fuller, a
professor at Worcester (Mass.) State College who researches sports
and pop culture. ``Ritual provides security for kids because it is
predictable, and WWF is full of ritual,'' she says. Each wrestler
always enters to the same music, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   WWF allows for experimentation with how far rules can be
stretched. ``It's not just wrestlers who are outrageous,'' says
Fuller. ``As spectators, boys can get away with things: screaming
louder than usual, using bad language.''
</P>
<P>
   Individually, each of these is a normal developmental drive. But
the way WWF combines them with violence is unhealthy and troubling,
even though the action is staged and boys know it, says Pollack.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to make a boy who wouldn't hit go out and
hit,'' he says. ``But it does make him less sensitive to real-life
violence: It makes him lose his sense of how much it hurts when he
sees someone else get hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Pollack uses strong words to describe WWF _ he calls it
choreographed sadism _ but it's the wrestlers' emotionlessness that
worries him most. ``They're numb, robotic. They act as if it
doesn't hurt,'' he says. Even though boys know on a cognitive level
that the violence is fake, on an emotional level the lack of
feelings reinforces the still-strong cultural stereotype that to be
a real man is to eschew emotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``That hurts our sons more than anything,'' Pollack says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Impact on boys under 7
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The message is an even bigger issue for boys under 7, says early
childhood educator and author Nancy Carlsson-Paige.
</P>
<P>
   One way young children learn is by observing cause and effect.
When they see wrestlers kick and push and not get hurt, they assume
they won't either. ``That's why a preschooler is genuinely
surprised if he pushes a classmate and she cries,'' says
Carlsson-Paige.
</P>
<P>
   When they see siblings and parents caught up in WWF, the message
is that violence is not only entertaining but also OK: ``Even Mom
and Dad like it!'' In other words, she says, ``they are socialized
to accept violence long before they are able to understand its
meaning.'' A professor at Lesley College, Carlsson-Paige is author
of ``Best Day of the Week,'' a children's book on conflict
resolution, and coauthor of an accompanying teacher's guide,
``Before Push Comes to Shove'' (Redleaf Press).
</P>
<P>
   Without the ability to put the violence in perspective, they
begin to see the world as unsafe. ``They can walk around literally
worried that at any moment someone may break a chair over their
head,'' says Merlock-Jackson. ``In order to feel safe, they become
unduly aggressive _ `I have to hit first so he doesn't hit me' _ or
withdrawn.''
</P>
<P>
   Carlsson-Paige urges keeping children under 7 away from WWF. If
a young child has already been watching, explain that you made a
mistake: ``I didn't know how bad it is for you. Now I do. Let's
find something else you can watch.'' Pollack recommends weaning a
child away from it gradually, watching with him and interpreting.
He also suggests substituting for it with something equally
action-oriented.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WWF and older boys
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With older boys, it gets more complicated. For instance:
</P>
<P>
   --Neither you nor your fifth grader likes WWF but his friends
do. This boy is torn between familial values and a normal need for
peer acceptance, which is too important for us to ignore, says
Carlsson-Paige. While you don't need to endorse WWF, let him know
you understand his conflict: ``I know how important it is to be
included by your friends.'' Be willing to compromise: ``How can we
figure this out so you can watch with your friends and still feel
OK about it?'' If the compromise is for him to watch at a friend's
house, talk about it afterward: ``Tell me about it. Did anything
surprise/worry/upset/please you?''
</P>
<P>
   --WWF is all your son wanted for Christmas, it's all he plays,
it's what he writes about on school essays. This is a red flag,
says Newberger, especially if there also are changes in appetite,
sleep, friendships, or grades, and/or a preoccupation with
violence. He recommends a professional consultation.
</P>
<P>
   --Your son watches regularly but not obsessively. Talk about it
with him: ``Tell me what you like so much about it.'' Be careful
not to be critical, says Pollack; that will shut him down. Reflect
back what he says _ ``So you like the hitting, even though you know
it's not real'' _ and share your concerns: ``It worries me when
people act like it's fun to hurt someone.'' Help him to see how
it's changing his life: ``You used to like to play street hockey,
now you'd rather play a WWF video game.'' Negotiate to reduce
viewing, watch with him, and keep talking.
</P>
<P>
   --Whenever your son and his friends watch, their play afterward
turns violent. Fuller says aggression and bad language typically
increase after viewing. Point this out _ ``Do you notice that. .
.'' _ and help them analyze what's different. They might not like
your doing this (your son is sure to be embarrassed), but Fuller
says, ``It lets them know you care. That matters more than you
think.''
</P>
<P>
   --WWF is a family activity. This may be togetherness, but it's
also a stamp of approval on violence as entertainment, crude
language, and distancing oneself from emotion. ``Tape it and watch
after your kids are asleep,'' says Carlsson-Paige. Fuller says the
only value to watching together is if you analyze along the way _
``If that was real, he'd be paralyzed'' _ but don't get caught up
in it yourself.
</P>
<P>
   Dylan Stockdale, a student at the Hosmer School in Watertown,
Mass., is very aware of the real-life dangers of WWF and can rattle
off a list of wrestlers' injuries. Still, ask him and his four
classmates what they want to be when then grow up and their answer
is unanimous:
</P>
<P>
   Professional wrestlers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TIPS FOR PARENTS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Share your concerns about WWF with your child's teachers. In
some schools, it's such a problem that wrestling play is banned and
there are classroom discussions about its influence.
</P>
<P>
   --It isn't enough for a young child to tell you or for you to
tell him, ``WWF violence isn't real.'' Connect it to his life:
``WWF is like a magic trick, the way they kick and don't get hurt.
What happens if someone pushes you? How do you feel? Remember when
you pushed Cory at the sandbox and he cried?''
</P>
<P>
   --Be careful not to underreact to behavior that shocks you. Boys
always try to push the envelope to bend the rules, so the more
easily you are shocked the less outrageous they have to be to get
the reaction they want.
</P>
<P>
   --Remind them that wrestlers are real people: ``I wonder if he's
married.'' ``I wonder what his mother thinks of his job.''
</P>
<P>
   --Be sure WWF is not your son's only model of manliness and that
he has opportunities for creativity in his life.
</P>
<P>
   --Look for other programming and for books that offer action and
adventure without gratuitious violence. Lobby against violence in
programming.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AFTERTHOUGHT _ A good Web site for parents: An interactive site
designed by mothers, www.playdateconnection.com, offers play-date
connections all over the country. Membership is free.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Barbara F. Meltz welcomes comments and can be reached via e-mail
at meltz(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
