<SLUG> BC-RAYTHEON-MISSILE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSED MISSILE GIVES RAYTHEON ANOTHER BLACK EYE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two heat-seeking devices apparently malfunctioned aboard an
antimissile weapon built by Raytheon Co., which may have caused it
to miss a target in a key test, Pentagon officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The setback, on Tuesday, didn't seem to weaken political support
for the antimissile program, at least immediately. But it's another
black eye for Raytheon, which was looking for a comeback after its
shares fell sharply on Tuesday, when it warned of earnings
disappointments.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking Wednesday on condition of anonymity, a Pentagon
official said ``the preliminary indication is that we had a
malfunction on both'' of the infrared devices aboard the
Raytheon-built ``exoatmospheric kill vehicle.''
</P>
<P>
   The problems prevented it from finding and ramming a mock enemy
warhead in the last six seconds of the test, conducted more than
120 miles above the Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   The official wasn't able to say exactly by how much the device
missed, but said that other navigational instruments, including
optical star-readers, ``got us to the street address'' of the
target missile. ``What we failed to do is ring the doorbell,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The test was seen as a key demonstration of the feasibility of
the antimissile technology, which is being developed by Raytheon
under contract to Boeing Co.
</P>
<P>
   In a more limited test in October, the system found and
destroyed its target, though the Pentagon last week disclosed a
problem with star-scanning devices in that event. A third test is
scheduled for April.
</P>
<P>
   The mock interceptions are being conducted as a prelude to a
decision by the Clinton administration whether to fund the program,
which the Pentagon estimates would cost $10.5 billion by 2005.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, even the program's backers conceded the most recent
failure could tempt the administration to delay things.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, it could more difficult, politically,'' to fund the
program, said Robert Pfaltzgraff, a professor at Tuft University's
Fletcher School of Law &AMP; Diplomancy and one of the system's
advocates. Still, he said, ``setbacks are inevitable, and one miss
isn't enough to scrap the whole program.''
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut Senator Joseph Lieberman reiterated that view,
through spokesman Dan Gerstein.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing in this technological bump in the road'' has dissuaded
Lieberman ``from the view that building a viable, effective defense
should be a clear national priority,'' Gerstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Support from centrist Democrats like Lieberman, a member of the
Armed Services Committee, will be key if the program, known as the
National Missile Defense, is to be funded on the Pentagon's
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   The system _ essentially Star Wars Lite _ envisions a more
limited deployment of concepts first outlined in the 1980s. Then,
the Reagan administration imagined a space-based missile shield
that could defeat a hypothetical, vast first strike by the Soviet
Union.
</P>
<P>
   The current concept is advertised for shooting down a more
limited strike launched by smaller nations, such as North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts aren't worried about any financial impact on Raytheon
stemmed from the failed test, since major appropriations would be
years away. ``It's all still hypothetical,'' said Edward Jones
analyst Bill Fiala. ``I know it will be big; how big is too early
to tell.''
</P>
<P>
   The program has become of symbolic importance to Raytheon,
however, which Tuesday announced an earnings shortfalls that caused
its stock to decline 25 percent. In trading Wednesday, Raytheon's
widely-traded Class B shares rose 11/16 to close at 19-11/16.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, a Raytheon spokesman said the Lexington, Mass.
company was ``disappointed'' by the result but said that it lacked
further data to fully judge the test. ``Until we whave the facts it
would be preamature to say anyhing further right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon said that other components of the system, including
radar and satellite sensors, performed as designed.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to technical challenges, the missile-defense program
faces policy hurdles as well. Many Democrats and arms-control
experts worry it could could destabilize relations with Russia,
with whom the US has agreements not to deploy defense systems that
would undercut the Cold War deterence policies.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials say the missile-defense program
wouldn't change that relationship. But Russian leaders disagree and
last week backed away from assurances they would use its nuclear
arsenal only if the country's existence was threatened.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
