u f BC-LABOR-MEMBERSHIP-BOS &LR;      01-20 0431
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABOR-MEMBERSHIP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERCENT OF AMERICANS IN UNIONS REMAINS FLAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   An ongoing national campaign to increase the ranks of organized
labor added 265,000 new union members last year, yet the percentage
of the US work force that's unionized remained unchanged at about
13.9 percent, the Bureau of Labor Statistics reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In all, about 16.5 million workers belonged to unions in 1999.
That's up from 16.2 million in 1998, but far below the all-time
high of about percent in .
</P>
<P>
   About 112,000 of those who joined unions last year were employed
in the private sector. It was the largest increase in that sector
in 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Labor leaders reported significant growth in union membership
among white-collar professionals and service workers, noting that
45,000 doctors joined or formed AFL-CIO affiliated unions last year
and that 75,000 home health aides formed a union in California.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, a small group of high-tech and communications
workers have begun exploring the possibility of unionization at
Microsoft, Amazon.com, IBM, and AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   Despite such increases, the proportion of union employees in the
labor force remained unchanged last year, even though 2.7 million
new jobs were added to the economy. Labor specialists attributed
that to mergers and consolidations, as well as to factory shutdowns
in the manufacturing sector.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, AFL-CIO president John J. Sweeney said the increase
in membership indicates the labor movement's emphasis on organizing
has had a noticeable impact. The higher numbers should result in
more political clout for the labor movement in the upcoming
presidential election, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to see the largest and most significant activity
that grass-roots workers have ever exercised in any political
election,'' Sweeney said.
</P>
<P>
   Within the public sector, the Service Employees International
Union _ its members include physicians, registered nurses, health
aides, and technicians _ gained 150,000 members.
</P>
<P>
   The SEIU spent $70 million on organizing drives last year,
nearly half of the organization's international budget, a spokesman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the number of public-sector union workers increased by
152,788, the percentage of such workers in unions dropped to 37.3
percent from 37.5, the Bureau of Labor Statistics reported.
</P>
<P>
   Kirk Adams, organizing director for the AFL-CIO, said the labor
movement must add between 500,000 and 1 million new members per
year to grow.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
