<SLUG> BC-CRIMES-TRIBUNAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAR CRIMES PROSECUTOR URGES ACTION AGAINST KRADZIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ International war crimes prosecutor Carla del Ponte
Wednesday implored NATO to do more to arrest former Bosnian Serb
leader Radovan Karadzic, even as her office said it hoped that
others under indictment for war crimes would turn themselves in
following the murder of a Serb paramilitary leader last week.
   Del Ponte met in Brussels with representatives from NATO's 19
member nations on the same day that Zeljko Raznatovic, better known
as Arkan, was being buried in Belgrade. Arkan, who was indicted in
1997 by the International Criminal Tribunal for the former
Yugoslavia but never apprehended, was shot dead Saturday in the
lobby of the Inter-Continental Hotel in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters after she met with NATO leaders, del Ponte
said she singled out Karadzic in her appeal for the military
alliance to do more to arrest suspected war criminals at large in
areas such as Bosnia that NATO forces control.
</P>
<P>
   Karadzic, she said, is ``the most wanted . . . the symbol of
this year, the fugitive who has been longest on the loose.''
Karadzic, former Bosnian Serb president, was indicted on charges
including genocide in connection with an ``ethnic cleansing''
campaign that left 100,00 dead.
</P>
<P>
   Del Ponte acknowledged it would be dangerous and difficult to
arrest Karadzic, who is thought to be in the Serbian area of
eastern Bosnia and surrounded by bodyguards.
</P>
<P>
   Arkan was always flanked by bodyguards, too, but one of them was
killed alongside him when at least two gunmen opened fire on his
entourage.
</P>
<P>
   While insisting that del Ponte prefers that Arkan and others
face justice before the tribunal at The Hague, her spokesman, Paul
Risley, said Arkan's murder may lead Karadzic and other fugitives,
including the Bosnian Serb general, Ratko Mladic, to consider
turning themselves in.
</P>
<P>
   ``The safest and most secure place is the secure detention unit
run by the United Nations here,'' Risley said in a telephone
interview from The Hague.
</P>
<P>
   While many Serbs dismiss the tribunal as being beholden to NATO,
Risley noted that the international court has acquitted some
suspects and given lenient sentences to some who have cooperated
with the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the past five years, the tribunal has proved to be
unpredictable,'' said Risley.
</P>
<P>
   Seventeen of the 33 suspects who have been arraigned at the
court at The Hague were apprehended by NATO, which has 20,000
troops in Bosnia more than four years after the end of the war
there. NATO Secretary General George Robertson said Wednesday that
NATO remains committed to arresting suspected war criminals when it
can, and he shared Risley's hope that Arkan's assassination would
be a catalyst for more surrenders.
</P>
<P>
   Del Ponte said suspects who surrender and cooperate will be
treated more leniently.
</P>
<P>
   Arkan and his paramilitary unit, known as the Tigers, was
accused of slaughtering civilians in Croatia and Bosnia, allegedly
with the approval of Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic, who is
also under indictment for war crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts in Belgrade have speculated that Arkan was killed
by the Milosevic regime to forestall the possibility that he might
surrender and give evidence against Milosevic. The government in
Belgrade, which openly supported Arkan's activities during the wars
in Croatia and Bosnia, has denied it played a role in Arkan's
murder. The assassination of someone seen as close to Milosevic
could lead others ostensibly in the good graces of the Belgrade
regime to seek a safe haven rather than suffer a similar fate.
</P>
<P>
   Arkan was seen to be distancing himself from Milosevic, and had
been in contact with Serbian opposition leader Zoran Djindnic.
</P>
<P>
   Risley said that the chief prosecutor's office had had contact
with ``several individuals'' purporting to represent Arkan over the
last two years, but the discussions never reached the stage of
arranging a surrender.
</P>
<P>
   Risley said the prosecutor's office ``surmises that most of
those attempts were to try to gather information on the nature of
the charges contained in the sealed indictment rather than to
arrange a surrender.''
</P>
<P>
   Risley said it was ``possible that Arkan could have provided
information that would assist'' in the prosecution of Milosevic,
and that the judges who sit on the international court ``take into
consideration any level of cooperation shown by an individual.''
</P>
<P>
   But Risley added that Arkan could not have made his own
indictment disappear, no matter what he offered up on Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   As for others under indictment, and presumably under the
protection of forces loyal to or friendly with Milosevic, Risley
said, ``If I were them, I'd be sweating.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
