<HEADLINE>
INTEL PROGRAM TO BOLSTER EDUCATION AND COMPUTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ore., Texas, Ariz.)  (pr) 
 By EDWARD WYATT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Intel Corp. announced a three-year program Thursday to help
100,000 elementary and secondary school teachers in the United
States integrate computers and the Internet into their classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   In the program, called Teach to the Future, Intel will give
$75,000 cash grants to nonprofit training centers that will offer
teachers a 40-hour instructional program; Intel, Hewlett-Packard
and other companies will donate some computers and offer
reduced-price computers to school districts; Microsoft will donate
software.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, the program intends to train 10,000
teachers this year in four areas: Northern California, Oregon,
Texas and Arizona. Next year, that will expand to 40,000 teachers
in 10 more regions or states, with an additional 50,000 teachers to
be trained across the nation in 2002. The program is also intended
to train 300,000 teachers in 19 foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal is not to produce computer-literate people but to
teach people how to use the computer as a tool to produce
well-educated people,'' said Wendy Hawkins, manager of Intel's
teacher-development programs.
</P>
<P>
   More than half of public school teachers are already comfortable
using computers, according to Intel's research. ``But this program
is designed to take teachers from being users themselves to
incorporating computers into their everyday lesson plans,'' Ms.
Hawkins said.
</P>
<P>
   Intel's program is modeled on a smaller program, Applying
Computers in Education, developed by the Institute of Computer
Technology in Sunnyvale, Calif. The institute is a statewide
agency, founded by the California Legislature, which provides
technology training and planning to schools and corporations.
</P>
<P>
   Intel said it was investing $100 million in cash, equipment,
curriculum development and program management to the program. In
addition, Microsoft is donating software _ primarily its Office
2000 program, which includes word-processing, spreadsheet and
graphics functions, plus its Encarta encyclopedia _ a donation that
the company says is worth $344 million and is its largest ever.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
