<SLUG> BC-SMYERS-CANCER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIATHLETE SMYERS BATTLING THYROID CANCER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ After three years of battling back from numerous
injuries and childbirth, triathlete Karen Smyers is in another
fight: thyroid cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were some scary moments,'' Smyers said Wednesday.
``Probably the scariest is when that c-word was mentioned for the
first time. Now I'm feeling fine. One thing I've learned the last
couple of years is how incredible the human body is in recovering
from things. I feel like everything is under control.''
</P>
<P>
   The 38-year-old Smyers, who in 1995 became the first woman to
win the Hawaii Ironman Triathlon and the triathlon world
championship in the same year, underwent surgery Dec. 18 at
Massachusetts General Hospital to have her cancerous thyroid
removed, but after consultation with several endocrinologists has
decided to delay further treatment until after the Olympic Trials
in May. Triathlon is making its debut as an Olympic sport this
September in Sydney and Smyers is one of the leading contenders to
make the US team. She has resumed training.
</P>
<P>
   The thyroid is a butterfly-shaped gland in the neck, below the
Adam's apple, which makes and stores hormones that regulate heart
rate, blood pressure, body temperature, and the rate at which food
is converted into energy. Thyroid cancer strikes about 16,000
people a year in the United States, accounting for about 1 percent
of all cancers. Most thyroid cancers are highly curable, with a
cure rate that can rise to better than 95 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Common postsurgical treatment consists of the administration of
radioactive iodine. Although the iodine tends to have relatively
few side effects, Smyers would first need to quit the medication
she has been taking since surgery, which replaces the hormones
normally produced by the gland, and the effects of that would
severely inhibit her training for the 0.9-mile swim, 24.8-mile
bike, and 6.2-run that make up the Olympic triathlon.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Smyers's surgeon recommended she undergo the iodine
treatment as soon as her neck healed, within 6-8 weeks of surgery.
Smyers and her husband, Michael King, who live in suburban Lincoln,
were willing to accept that. But in further consultation she was
told of evidence that the treatment might in fact be more effective
if she waited longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was all I needed to hear,'' said Smyers.
</P>
<P>
   Part of her concern stems from the training time she has already
lost to a broken collarbone sustained in a race last November,
putting her in what she called ``pitiful shape. I need every single
week to get in shape for the trials.'' Effects from the iodine
treatment, she has been told, would last at least a month.
</P>
<P>
   Still, with a 1 1/2-year-old daughter to care for, Smyers said
she wouldn't consider putting off treatment if she believed there
was a risk. ``As important as sport is, it's nothing compared to
being around as a mother,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Amazingly, Smyers first learned during a checkup in September
that she might have cancer, but tests were not concluded until
after she finished a strong second in the Hawaii Ironman (2.4-mile
swim, 112-mile bike, 26.2-mile run) in mid-October.
</P>
<P>
   After leading the Ironman during much of the bike and run and
finishing so well, Smyers said, the chances of having cancer seemed
remote. ``I thought, there's got to be a mistake,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   There wasn't, as a biopsy in November confirmed. Still, Smyers
takes heart from the success of Emma Robinson, a 28-year-old
national team rower from Canada who last February was diagnosed
with thyroid cancer and went on to set a world record in the
women's pair in July and win her third consecutive world
championship in August.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's my new poster girl,'' said Smyers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
