<SLUG> BC-SKAKEL-PROFILE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICHAEL C. SKAKEL: A LIFETIME DOGGED BY TURMOIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MACQUARRIE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After living a quarter-century under a murky cloud of suspicion
and innuendo, Michael C. Skakel formally made the transition
Wednesday from whispered suspect to accused defendant in the 1975
bludgeoning death of teenager Martha Moxley.
</P>
<P>
   The long interim has been a rocky one for Skakel, 39, the nephew
of Ethel Kennedy who has been linked his entire adult life to the
sensational Moxley murder committed in exclusive Greenwich, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   From a drunken-driving arrest that preceded his enrollment in a
Maine school for troubled boys, to his testimony in his cousin
Michael Kennedy's alleged relationship with an underage
baby-sitter, Skakel has been dogged by turmoil since Moxley was
discovered brutally slain by a golf club.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Skakel appeared at Greenwich police headquarters with
his lawyer to answer the charges and post $500,000 bond after
journeying north from his home in Hobe Sound, Fla. The charge
followed 18 months of investigation by a single grand juror who is
also a Superior Court judge.
</P>
<P>
   Moxley, 15, was found dead outside her home in the gated Belle
Haven enclave of Greenwich after a pre-Halloween ``mischief night''
of strewing toilet paper and shaving cream aroound the
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   The next-door Skakels initially cooperated with police, but the
willingness of the family, heirs to a Midwestern coal fortune, to
talk with authorities ended abruptly in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   The whispers, however, continued in Greenwich about whether
Michael and Thomas Skakel, ages 15 and 17, had committed the crime.
But police investigators did not develop enough evidence to bring
charges, although through the years three speculation-filled books
kept the sensational crime alive in the public mind for years.
</P>
<P>
   Three years after Moxley's death, Michael Skakel was sent to the
Elan School in Poland Spring, Maine. He twice attempted to flee the
residential drug treatment facility, where classmates were told by
the school's owner that he had been involved in the murder,
according to a former student's testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Skakel left the school in 1980. He once again gained notoriety
when his alleged role in the Michael Kennedy baby-sitter
controversy erupted in 1997. Skakel, who had become a driver in
Sen. Edward M. Kennedy's relection camaign in 1994, became
increasingly close to Michael Kennedy, the senator's nephew and
Skakel's cousin.
</P>
<P>
   In the years after the campaign, according to someone familiar
with the family, Skakel became Michael Kennedy's ``right-hand man''
as his cousin assumed the executive duties at Citizens Energy
Corp., the Boston nonprofit fuel assistance program begun by former
US Representative Joseph Kennedy II.
</P>
<P>
   Skakel lived in Cohasset, Mass. with his wife, who worked as
assistant golf pro at a country club. He also became friendly with
the family of the teenager with whom Michael Kennedy allegedly had
a sexual affair before she was 16, and he is reported to have
intervened on behalf of the family in an effort to persuade Kennedy
to end the relationship.
</P>
<P>
   During this time, Skakel was part of rowdy rafting trips to
Maine, filled with late-night drinking, on which Kennedy and the
teenager had gone.
</P>
<P>
   Skakel alienated the Kennedy family, sources said Wednesday,
when he agreed to answer questions about the relationship from
Norfolk (Mass.) District Attorney Jeffrey A. Locke.
</P>
<P>
   His position at Citizens Energy became increasingly tenuous, and
Skakel is reported to have sought a $250,000 cash settlement to
leave the company.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Kennedy died in a skiing accident in Colorado on New
Year's Eve 1997. Skakel left Massachusetts and moved to Florida to
be near his father, who also lives in Hobe Sound.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-00 2100EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000120.0309 </DOCNO>
