<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERLMAN-CONDUCT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERLMAN TAKES OVER GUEST CONDUCTING JOB IN DETROIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Violinist Itzhak Perlman has been named principal guest
conductor of the Detroit Symphony Orchestra, beginning in 2001-2.
He began conducting about five years ago, and since then has led
many leading American and Canadian orchestras as well as the Israel
Philharmonic and the English Chamber Orchestra. He makes his first
appearance conducting the Boston Symphony at Tanglewood in July.
</P>
<P>
   In a conversation from Detroit Wednesday, Perlman said, ``In my
new job, I'll be making new motions, but it's the old me.''
</P>
<P>
   He explained that he started conducting in the Pearlman Music
Program, an institute on Long Island, founded by his wife to help
train precollege musicians. ``I coached some chamber music and then
began coaching the orchestra, and to coach an orchestra, you have
to conduct it; that experience started me off. Actually, I've
always been lifting the stick in my mind, and I took some classes
in conducting when I was a student at Juilliard. I thought that if
I could accomplish nice results with kids, it might also work with
pros, and one thing has led to another. All of it has made me very
happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Perlman will conduct the Detroit Symphony for three weeks each
season, as well as participate in the orchestra's educational
activities. ``I recently conducted the Detroit Symphony for the
first time and we had such a wonderful rapport; everyone was very
happy. Then they approached me about this position. I thought about
it for about 4 1/2 seconds, and then I said `Yes.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Perlman says he has always kept an attentive eye on conductors
over his long career. ``You watch different conductors do different
things to get different results, and it soaks into you. Three or
four different conductors will give a downbeat and three or four
different kinds of sound will result. That's a fascinating mystery
that I don't want to solve.'' He joked that he has worked with
himself as soloist and found himself a little difficult. ``I refuse
to talk with myself before a rehearsal!''
</P>
<P>
   He admits he is ``excited'' about conducting the Boston Symphony
at Tanglewood. ``Brahms's Fourth Symphony is one of the things I'm
going to do _ I've done it with Chicago and Houston, so I will come
to Tanglewood as a veteran.''
</P>
<P>
   Perlman says his new career will not mean any cutting back on
his violin playing. ``The conducting is something that comes in
addition, another dimension, a way to work on a different repertory
in an active way. I don't think one will replace the other.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the effect on his operatic ambitions _ he once sang
the Jailor in Puccini's ``Tosca'' _ Pearlman said, ``I'm 54 years
old and my career as a singer is almost over _ I made my farewell
debut a long time ago!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-00 2101EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
