<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF: GERMANY, FRANCE, RUSSIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   SETBACK FOR PINOCHET JUDGE
</P>
<P>
   MADRID, Spain _ Spain's government said Thursday it would not
send London a request for an appeal from Judge Baltasar Garzon if
Gen. Augusto Pinochet is freed on medical grounds. It is the first
time since the former Chilean dictator, 84, was arrested 15 months
ago on human rights charges that Spain has refused to transmit the
judge's orders. But a Foreign Ministry spokesman said the case,
once considered strictly judicial, had entered the political realm,
allowing the government to decide not to appeal Gen. Pinochet's
release and his expected return to Chile.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA: MIR REPRIEVE
</P>
<P>
   The space station Mir got a reprieve when the government came up
with more money to keep it in orbit for another seven months.
Private investors, some from the United States, are expected to
provide $28 million for the station. A crew is expected to arrive
in April for a mission of 45 to 72 days, said Yuri Koptev, head of
the space agency. Mir, in its 14th year, has been empty since
August, and was due to crash into the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY: POPE TO SINAI
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican confirmed that John Paul II will visit a monastery
at the foot of the traditional Mt. Sinai on a trip to Egypt lasting
from Feb. 24 to 26, a month before a major pilgrimage to the Holy
Land. The Pope, 79, who plans to visit Israel, Jordan and
Palestinian territories in March, had hoped to begin his tour of
biblical sites at the Iraqi city of Ur, but the Iraqis squashed the
plan.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: PLEA ON NAZI KILLINGS
</P>
<P>
   Germany asked the Greek Supreme Court to dismiss a lower court
ruling that it owes $30 million to survivors of 218 people who were
killed by Nazis in the village of Distomo on June 10, 1944. Germany
says the issue of reparations was closed with a 1960 compensation
treaty with Greece. A ruling is expected in mid-February.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: QUESTIONS ON DEPORTEE
</P>
<P>
   Lord Janner, chairman of the Holocaust Educational Trust,
challenged the government to explain how Alexander Schweidler, 78,
is living freely and drawing a pension in Britain since being
deported by the United States in 1994 after admitting being a Nazi
concentration camp guard. A naturalized Briton of Slovak origin, he
was at the Mauthausen camp in Austria.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY: POLICE SENTENCES UPHELD
</P>
<P>
   A court upheld the seven-and-a-half year jail terms imposed on
five police officers convicted of beating to death Metin Goktepe, a
journalist, in 1996. Human rights advocates say the case is a test
of whether Turkish officers who commit such crimes still enjoy
their traditional immunity from prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: BODY HUNT HALTED
</P>
<P>
   A joint search with American forensic experts for the bodies of
people executed on the orders of drug traffickers has been called
off. The excavations, in Chihuahua state near El Paso, Texas,
unearthed nine bodies. More than 100 have disappeared. A top
prosecutor said Mexico would continue to investigate without
American help.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   SRI LANKA: PEACE PLAN
</P>
<P>
   The main opposition party said it would support a plan by the
government of President Chandrika Kumaratunga to bring peace to the
country by giving greater constitutional autonomy to regions
dominated by the Tamil minority. Earlier, the opposition had
blocked legislative passage of the measure, but now offers its
votes if some of its own reform proposals are included.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ: ANNAN ATTACKED
</P>
<P>
   Stepping up a barrage of verbal attacks on Secretary-General
Kofi Annan for nominating a new arms inspector that President
Saddam Hussein does not like, officials quoted in the controlled
Iraqi press accused Annan of being in league with Washington to
impose a system ``riddled with spies and false experts.'' Annan
named Rolf Ekeus, who dismantled many Iraqi arms from 1991 to 1997,
as the head of a new commission, but he is being blocked by Russia,
France and China.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN: GERMAN FREE TO LEAVE
</P>
<P>
   A German businessman who was sentenced to death in January 1998
for having sex with an Iranian woman has been ruled free to leave
the country. Helmut Hofer, 56, said he would leave Friday. Under
Iranian law, sex outside marriage with non-Muslims is punishable by
death. Germany is a big trading partner of Iran and had warned that
executing Hofer would severely harm relations.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   SUDAN: PIPELINE REPAIRED
</P>
<P>
   Officials have repaired a new 1,000-mile oil pipeline after it
was damaged in a bomb attack. The Beja Congress, representing a
minority ethnic group, claimed responsibility for the attack, the
third since Sudan, locked in a 16-year civil war, began pumping oil
this summer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
