<SLUG> BC-FBN-KING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROOKIE HAS KEYS TO THE KINGDOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA _ The NFL Book says it won't work. You cannot advance in
the NFL playoffs with a rookie quarterback. It's not done.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-two-year-old Shaun King of the Buccaneers is attempting
burn a page out of the Book. King is attemping to go where no
(fresh) man has gone. He is trying to advance to the Super Bowl
despite playing less than half a season of professional football.
</P>
<P>
   Last Saturday at Raymond James Stadium, King led a second-half
comeback, and threw a fourth-quarter touchdown pass that beat the
Washington Redskins, 14-13, propelling the Bucs into Sunday's NFC
Championship Game in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Against the Redskins, King completed only four of his first 16
passes and the Buccaneers compiled only 69 yards of first-half
offense. In the first two quarters, King was 4 for 14 for 45 yards
and the Bucs converted only one of seven third-down situations.
Tampa trailed, 13-0, after King was intercepted early in the third
quarter. Backup quarterback Eric Zeier started warming up in the
bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   But King got it together and directed two touchdown drives to
win the game. Mike Alstott ran the first TD home. Midway throught
he fourth quarter, on third-and-goal from the 1, King tried to run
a bootleg, but found himself in the grizzly grip of Washington
defensive end Ndukwe Kalu. Before going down, the resourceful
rookie shot-putted a TD toss to backup tight end John Davis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't say I played great, but I didn't lose the game,''
said King. ``So I was proud of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Warren Saap, Tampa's All-Pro defensive end, added, ``You all
said our rookie quarterback couldn't get it done. We had all the
confidence in the world this young fellow could get it done. He had
something special and we're glad he's on our side.''
</P>
<P>
   Beating Washington, King became the first rookie quarterback to
win a playoff game since Pat Haden beat the Cowboys for the Los
Angeles Rams Dec. 19. 1976. Dan Marino, Jim Everett, Bernie Kosar,
and Todd Marinovich are the only other NFL rookies ever to start a
playoff game, and they all lost. Before King, the aggregate rookie
QB playoff roll call was 1-5, with four touchdown passes and 13
interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Like Haden, King became a starter due to injury. Tampa
quarterback Trent Dilfer broke his right clavicle Nov. 28 against
Seattle. Zeier was already on the shelf with bruised ribs, putting
King on stage. He finished the season with four wins in five
starts.
</P>
<P>
   King is not your prototype NFL starting quarterback. He's only 6
feet tall, and hardly cat-like at 225 pounds. Five quarterbacks
(Tim Couch, Donovan McNabb, Akili Smith, Cade McNown, and Daunte
Culpepper) were taken ahead of him in last year's draft, and all of
them will be eating cheeseballs and/or hitting 9-irons when King
goes to work against the Rams Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   His is an unlikely story, almost Crapra-esque. He grew up across
the Bay in St. Petersburg, Fla., worshipped the lowly Buccaneers
for all of his young life, and made belivers out of those who
doubted his quarterback skills. Playing for traditionally-weak
Gibbs High in St. Petersburg, he threw for 50 touchdowns and almost
5,000 yards in his final two seasons, but got no attention from the
Sunshine State's NCAA bohemoths, Florida and Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   He went to Tulane and did little in two seasons before Tommy
Bowden was hired as head coach. In King's junior year, the Green
Wave enjoyed its first winning season in 16 years and King broke
most of the school's passing records. The best way to describe
King's senior year is to think of Pedro Martinez with the Red Sox
in 1999. Playing nine of his games with a cast on his broken left
wrist, King threw for 3,332 yards and 36 touchdowns with just six
interceptions. Tulane went undefeated and beat BYU in the Liberty
Bowl. Find a better Division 1 season that that.
</P>
<P>
   No one knew what to expect when the draft came around. King told
hometown folks that if he was not selected, he'd like to work for
the Buccaneers' marketing department (he earned a bachelor's degree
in marketing at Tulane). King's family gathered at his
grandmother's house in Tampa and waited for the phone to ring. The
first call was a prank, Shaun's brother Cedric calling from a
payphone and identifying himself as Tampa head coach Tony Dungy. An
hour later, in the middle of the second round, the real Dungy
called.
</P>
<P>
   King was doing the Scott Zolak/Michael Bishop thing when
Dilfer's clavicle snapped in November. He closed out the victory
over the Seahawks, then threw a pair of touchdowns and beat the
Vikings in his NFL debut on Monday Night Football. Teammates
nicknamed him ``Smoothie.'' He stretched his winning streak as a
starter to 25 games, before a 45-0 loss to Oakland, and completed
61 percent of his passes in the regular season. And now he has a
playoff win on his resume.
</P>
<P>
   The Bucs play conservative, some would say ugly, football under
the direction of coordinator Mike Shula. They are 14-point
underdogs, playing on the road in St. Louis this weekend. And
they're putting a rookie quarterback on the field.
</P>
<P>
   The Book says they can't win.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
