u e BC-BOOK-TASTED-BOS &LR;      01-20 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TASTED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN CULINARY MEMOIR, A HUNGER FOR CONNECTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHERYL JULIAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
THE BEST THING I EVER TASTED 
The Secret of Food 
By Sallie Tisdale 
Riverhead Books, 311 pp., $25.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sallie Tisdale was 9 when she set to work on a daunting project:
Her Northern California grade school class was studying Indians,
and she decided to make acorn meal. She spent hours collecting nuts
on a cold gray day, then crushing and shelling them, boiling them,
roasting (to remove tannins) _ and only then was she ready to grind
meal. Alone, with her father's hammer and her mother's rolling pin,
she made ``a chewy and terrible paste.''
</P>
<P>
   Tisdale reads a lot in this episode. First there is how let down
she was: ``I had a glimpse that day of how much more than a food a
food could be _ and of the disappointment waiting when inchoate
dreams don't come true.'' Acorn gathering must have been a
community effort, she concludes, and she pictures ``the secret
(that) was being kept from me, . . . the secret of men and women
and girls and boys murmuring, singing, laughing together while they
worked.''
</P>
<P>
   This thread of loneliness _ of being an outsider looking in _
runs through ``The Best Thing I Ever Tasted.'' ``I wore myself out,
that fall, grinding acorns in my mother's fluorescent-lit
kitchen,'' she writes, ``longing for a tribe of my own.''
</P>
<P>
   And so Tisdale decides to sort out all manner of
acorn-gathering, food, and tribes. She delves into the medieval
kitchen, the classic French kitchen, Betty Crocker's test kitchens,
her childhood kitchen, her adult kitchen, and the kitchens of
today's harried moms and dieting public.
</P>
<P>
   It's all a little bleak. The ladies at Betty Crocker assure us
of this when they mention that they get calls about whether motor
oil is OK in a cake mix calling for oil. Or if someone should
follow high-altitude instructions if they're on the 10th floor of a
building.
</P>
<P>
   If Americans actually had to cook every night, wonders Tisdale,
would they survive?
</P>
<P>
   She brings extensive research to her study and has an eye for
the good bits (especially the drive-in years of her own childhood
and her flirtation with the counterculture _ ``the air was always
fragrant with virtue''). She's an easy, chatty writer who never
says anything the way you're expecting, which makes reading her a
pleasure. But there are actually two books here: vignettes from a
culinary memoir woven, not always with a tight weft, with a social
history of food. I wanted more Sallie and less history.
</P>
<P>
   Tisdale, author of five books including ``Talk Dirty to Me,'' is
sad about her life. She remembers afternoons with her mother, a
teacher, sinking exhausted into a living room chair, smoking a
cigarette before dinner. Her father, also a teacher, drank too much
and had a temper, which the slightest thing could set off. He was a
volunteer fireman and on the nights he got called away before
dinner, her mother packed the kids into the tan Chevy and set off
for the local A &AMP; W. You can almost hear the kids screaming
``hooray'' in the back seat.
</P>
<P>
   Her mother's been gone for 10 years, and Tisdale still longs for
her Velveeta sandwiches with Miracle Whip on white bread, fried in
margarine. There are so many things she needs to ask her mother,
and of course it's understood that none of them involves recipe
cards. Her father isn't much of a dad, never was, Tisdale says, and
his kitchen is full of prepared, canned foods that he never seems
to touch as they collect dust year after year. ``I have a family,
but I long for a family at times,'' she writes, ``longing for a
dream.''
</P>
<P>
   We jump from a Thanksgiving at the silent father's, which she
and her sister and brother manage to salvage into a raucous good
time, to a discussion of medieval feasts and famine. Once you're
there, however _ aided by historians Massimo Montanari,
Jean-Francois Revel, and Fernand Braudel _ you get Tisdale's
distilled and very interesting version of the events. The rich ate
``high, flying, light food, like birds. The poor ate low, thick,
heavy food, earthy food, like root vegetables and dark grains.''
</P>
<P>
   Tisdale never wags her finger, even at dieters, fickle eaters,
picky eaters, or her own children preferring to graze for dinner as
they stand and eat in the kitchen, or in their rooms, or on their
way out the door, dropping crumbs in their path.
</P>
<P>
   Americans' insatiable appetite for food has little to do with
ingredients, she decides. ``We lost the ability to tell the
difference between excess and sufficiency, between what is enough
and what is more than enough.'' At the Zen Buddhist retreats where
she goes now and eats in silence, dipping thick dark bread and
butter into a steaming bowl of kale soup, she is trying to learn
``what it means to have enough, and not want more.'' I hope she's
looking in the right place.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
