<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-CAMPAIGN-ART-385&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAMPSHIRE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 McCAIN TRIES TO SHOW HE'S NOT PINNING ALL HIS HOPES ON NEW(ART ADV: Photo NYT11 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 (bl)  
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In these late January days when the other presidential hopefuls
are criss-crossing the frozen farm fields of Iowa, one might expect
to find John McCain capitalizing on his decision to play
odd-man-out in Iowa by working single-mindedly to woo the voters of
New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   So it said something he challenges facing his insurgent
campaign that Thursday morning the Arizona senator was fielding
questions from the South Shore Chamber of Commerce, in Randolph,
Mass., rather than sitting in his usual leather chair on the
``Straight Talk Express'' at dawn, wending his way through the
first primary state.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since Tuesday morning, in fact, McCain has been looking
beyond his make-or-break state of New Hampshire toward March 7, the
first multiprimary Tuesday. He has made the obligatory quadrennial
New York pledge to move the U.S. Embassy in Israel to Jerusalem. He
has won enthusiastic standing ovations in Hartford, Conn., and East
Greenwich, R.I.
</P>
<P>
   He has gone to fund-raiser after fund-raiser looking for money
to compete in the expensive media-markets of California, which also
votes March 7. And Thursday he mischievously stood in the snow
outside the Russian consulate to slam the New York Republican Party
for its efforts to remove him from the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that both Russia and New York state will have elections
in March, he said: ``In Russia, there will be more than one name on
the ballot. In New York, unless something happens, there will be
only one name on the ballot. It seems to me that history has been
turned on its head.'' (In fact, not just Gov. George W. Bush of
Texas but Steve Forbes will be on the ballot, too.)
</P>
<P>
   For about a week, the polls have shown McCain with a small lead
over Bush in New Hampshire. One recent poll even had him winning by
double-digits. But the week's schedule may have been less about
confidence than about the McCain campaign's awareness of one of the
senator's vulnerabilities as the last undecided New Hampshire
voters make up their minds.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans dearly want to take back the White House after eight
years of the Clinton presidency. That is why so much of the party
establishment rallied around Bush so early. So McCain has to
convince people who are leaning his way that he can really go the
distance.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   More than once this week voters have asked some version of the
question posed Thursday by Dave Rogers, a 35-year-old lawyer who
asked McCain at the Chamber of Commerce breakfast whether Bush's
money means that in the end he will be ``virtually
insurmountable.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain spoke of his ``secret weapon'': the Internet. It had
helped him raise about $1.5 million, he said. It had drawn
volunteers to carry his petitions in Virginia. And he talked about
the boost that victory could bring.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we get a win in New Hampshire, a win from South Carolina,''
he said, ``if we win both of those we'll have significant momentum.
And by the way we have now enough money that we're up on television
in Michigan. We're going to be up in Virginia. We're going to be up
in the state of Washington. We do have sufficient funding to get us
through March 7.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, for all of the candidate's endless energy and the
optimism on his bus, there are occasional reminders of how daunting
a task it will be for McCain to defeat Bush, who is still far ahead
in national polls.
</P>
<P>
   One sign that McCain might lack name recognition came at the
Marine Air Terminal in New York earlier this week when a police
escort led his campaign bus to a sleek jet with the name TRUMP
emblazoned across it in gold.
</P>
<P>
   As McCain exclaimed, ``Is that the one with the hot tub on it?''
his aides radioed to the police that they had the wrong candidate
and the wrong plane. The motorcade reversed course and headed to a
much smaller aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   The past weeks have also showed the limits of a shoe-string
campaign and brought the first hints that despite McCain's pride in
his ability to ad lib, his habit of holding what amounts to an
18-hour-a-day news conference has its drawbacks.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has relied on his unusual accessibility both to polish
his reputation for candor as well as to bring him free publicity to
combat Bush's daunting campaign war chest.
</P>
<P>
   But his winning personality has not always distracted from his
staff's inability to produce the kind of well-packaged and detailed
policy proposals that the Bush campaign puts forward.
</P>
<P>
   McCain opened himself up to Bush's recent attack on his tax plan
when he did not provide much detail on the $151 billion worth of
proposals to close corporate tax loopholes contained in his plan.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the risks of McCain's own accessibility _ and the
reasons why most other candidates avoid it _ have become clearer as
he moves higher in the polls and more reporters squeeze into the
back of his bus and try to parse his every word at the very time
when he can least afford any gaffe or distraction.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday he talked himself into a tangle when reporters pressed
him about his comment at a recent debate that he had served with
gay soldiers in the military, as he defended the ``don't ask, don't
tell'' policy.
</P>
<P>
   He was asked why he had not reported them for removal from the
military and said he had not been obliged to, because he had not
witnessed a homosexual act. So next he was asked how he knew
someone was homosexual.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, in what was supposed to be a plea for tolerance and
privacy for people, McCain spoke of ``behavior and attitudes'' and
said, ``I think that it's clear to some of us when some people have
that lifestyle.''
</P>
<P>
   That brought protests from homosexual rights groups. Tuesday
morning he had a new answer and said he actually knew because one
of his fellow service members eventually told him he was homosexual
after he left the military.
</P>
<P>
   Even if he wanted to, it would be impossible for McCain to scale
back access now. A little less access would become a very big
story. So his aides have become more vigilant about listening to
what he is saying to reporters and joining the conversation to
steer him from trouble spots.
</P>
<P>
   When Thursday's freeflowing discussion, which went from New York
Republicans to Soviet military tactics in World War II, somehow
meandered its way onto a recent magazine article about a city
favored by homosexuals as a vacation spot, Mike Murphy, McCain's
senior strategist, suddenly piped up with, ``What about the
balanced budget amendment?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
