<SLUG> BC-BIZ-5-QUESTIONS-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GM OFFICIAL GIVES SALES A ONCE-OVER  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 23) 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Questions may be italicized) 
(af) 
 By ROBYN MEREDITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For decades, General Motors' piece of the United States auto pie
has dwindled, to a level that in recent years has raised serious
concerns on Wall Street. Despite increased unit sales and a record
$5.6 billion profit in 1999, GM ended the year with a market share
of 29.45 percent, barely above the 29.40 percent of 1998, when a
two-month strike by the United Automobile Workers shut GM's
factories, and well below GM's 31.29 percent share in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Roy S. Roberts, 60, the GM group vice president for North
American vehicle sales, service and marketing, announced last
Tuesday that he would retire this spring. A week earlier, during
the North American International Auto Show in Detroit, he took time
to explain some of the factors crimping GM sales. Here are excerpts
from the conversation. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. There has been a lot of criticism about any number of
executives _ yourself included _ because GM failed to meet its
market share goal of 30 percent this year. How do you respond?
</P>
<P>
   A. I'm responsible for market share in the short run. Everybody
in this organization is responsible for market share long term.
You've got to have the right products, you've got to have launches
_ you've got to have a number of things right. So I'll take my
responsibility and there are other people that will take theirs
also, I'm convinced of that.
</P>
<P>
   We came out of a strike at the end of the year. Arithmetically,
we couldn't build enough products to keep up with demand. We'd
forecasted the industry to be 15.5 million sales last year. We
couldn't possibly keep up with it, so I don't cry about that. We
did the next best thing _ we got our mix right, we got our costs
right and we made a lot of money. We had the best year we've ever
had in our history in trucks. December was a good month. The
organization is starting to click. Now we've got some inventory we
didn't have. I'm not delusioned about this marketplace, or the fact
that anybody will give up any market share. We're going to earn it
back incrementally.
</P>
<P>
   Q. How do you see the coming year? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I see pricing restraint. I see incentives staying about where
they are. When you start January and you miss your goal, you count
it 12 times. I have no intention of missing more.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Were you able to reach the 30 percent market share last month
only because you put up some pretty stiff incentives or do you see
a more secular turn in the market? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. All of the above. Certainly we wouldn't have put the
incentives in place if we didn't think it would give us a lift. By
the same token, the products are strong. So I'm really optimistic
about our chances. My head is not in the sand about this. The key
to our market share this year: full-sized pickups, full-sized sport
utility vehicles, some vans and medium-sized cars. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Don't dealers say GM has been ruffling their feathers? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes. If you go through this last year, when we've reorganized
the entire company, we've never seen anything like that in the
history of General Motors. We took 1,000 people out of the system.
Thirty-eight percent of the people in the field made a geographic
move. One hundred percent of the people in the field got a new job.
We had six different computer systems for all the different
divisions for order-to-delivery moving to one, and it didn't work
so well.
</P>
<P>
   The order-to-delivery system, VOMS, was an issue because it was
inflexible. We assumed that dealers were much more computer
literate than they were. We assumed that our people were more
computer literate than they were. We thought we had properly
trained everybody, and they were not that well trained. We had to
go back and redo all that, plus change the systems and the
processes with dealer input. And that's going to continue. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Didn't dealers also have trouble getting enough cars and
trucks? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Remember now, we came out of a strike in 1998 and our
inventories were depleted. We started launching our trucks _ three
plants. If you had sat two dealers down in a room and said, now,
you've got a problem with distribution, and let's sort this out _
how many Buicks do you want? No problem. How many Oldsmobiles? No
real problem. They wanted trucks. Hell, we were just building them.
If I've got 10 and you want 100, we've got a problem. So they all
said it is VOMS. It was not VOMS. No distribution system can handle
pent-up demand if you don't have the product. Now we've built back
up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-00 2107EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
