<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-GORE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY MAN GORE HOPES TO DISTANCE CLINTON IMAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WALPOLE, N.H. _ ``Where's Tipper?''
</P>
<P>
   It's a question Al Gore hears often on his presidential campaign
stops, and Wednesday the question came from a a middle-aged man who
managed to squeeze into Burdick's cafe and chocolatier to get a
chance to meet the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's answer _ ``she's campaigning in a different part of New
Hampshire today'' _ is far less significant than the fact that the
voter asked about her whereabouts.
</P>
<P>
   It means Gore is succeeding at conveying an underlying theme of
his campaign, that he is a family man, crazy in love with his wife
of 29 years and devoted to his four children.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Gore is not President Clinton, and voters
needn't worry that a President Gore would drag the nation through a
tawdry, painful ordeal such as the Monica S. Lewinsky episode.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could get strong Gore support, not Clinton support'' in
this picturesque, conservative town in western New Hampshire, said
Snow D. Gray, a 43-year-old farmer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost respect for Clinton a long way back _ the behavior, the
unreliability, the lying,'' Gray said. ``Al Gore restores my
confidence. I see a man who is a true family man. He doesn't fake
it, like Clinton or Reagan.''
</P>
<P>
   As Gore seeks the nomination and the presidency, he is faced
with an uncomfortable quandary: he wants to take credit for the
economic successes of the Clinton administration, while separating
himself from Clinton's personal scandals.
</P>
<P>
   Gore rarely mentions Clinton by name in his speeches, instead
talking about the progress he says has been made ``in the last
seven years.''
</P>
<P>
   The people Gore does mention frequently are his family members.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president frequently mentions his wife in speeches and
makes a point of noting that the couple will celebrate their 30th
anniversary in May.
</P>
<P>
   Kristen Gore, the Gores' 22-year-old daughter, also campaigns
alone or alongside her father. At an event in Indianola earlier
this week, Kristen received a bigger round of applause than the
candidate when the two were introduced to a crowd of college
students and other locals.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president frequently tells stories about his late
father, former Senator Albert Gore Sr. of Tennessee, and how the
elder Gore was an enemy of President Richard Nixon and an early
critic of the Vietnam war.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's mother, Pauline, is also a standard inclusion in Gore's
speeches. She grew up at a time when ``poor girls weren't supposed
to be able to dream,'' was a waitress who eventually attended
Vanderbilt University Law School, he explains.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president's favorite anecdotes are about being a
grandfather, a tact that works well with the middle-aged audiences
he has been wooing in Iowa and New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   His standard joke on his new role _ that he's decided the best
thing to do with a grandchild is to ``give him whatever he wants,
and if it causes any problems, give him right back to his parents''
_ always draws a conspiratorial chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Lehane, Gore's press secretary, said Gore isn't trying to
distance himself from Clinton with his family talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of running for president is introducing yourself to
voters,'' Lehane said. ``They have to understand who you are, what
your background is.'' Gore's unrelenting reference to his family
``is just part of who he is,'' Lehane said.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore is Clinton's vice president and may benefit or be
tainted by that association, some voters say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's any way to separate them,'' said Linda
Spokowski, 47. ``He's been the vice president for two terms.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's still some Clinton baggage'' attached to Gore,
said Jeanne Zimmerman, a 44-year-old editor. ``Some would argue
that he should'' tie himself to Clinton, ``because Clinton had a
pretty good run...but I think Gore is unfortunately saddled with
some baggage,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be quite dificult for him'' to distance himself
from Clinton, said Edwin Sielewicz, 69, after listening to Gore at
the Half Moon Cafe in Claremont, N.H. But the association could
work in Gore's favor, Sielewicz said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton as a president has done a very excellent job,'' said
Sielewicz, a committed Gore voter. ``I can't say I like his social
arrangements.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
