<SLUG> BC-BORDER-ARRESTS-RISE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARRESTS ALONG BORDER UP 24%
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DIANE SMITH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A high number of people illegally crossing into the United
States along the Southwest border with Mexico, coupled with
aggressive patrolling, resulted in more than 88,000 immigration
apprehensions this month _ a 24 percent increase over the same time
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Every year, thousands of undocumented immigrants cross into
Texas, New Mexico, Arizona and California with hopes of finding
work. January, February and March are typically the busiest months
for the U.S. Border Patrol because hundreds of thousands of people
are returning to jobs in the United States after spending the
holidays in Mexico and Central America.
</P>
<P>
   Many undocumented workers are attracted to jobs in construction,
meatpacking and the service industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have individuals who are trying to come back illegally,
and then you have those who are trying to come back for the first
time,'' said Mariela Melero, regional spokeswoman for the U.S.
Immigration and Naturalization Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's uncertain if we have reached our peak,'' Melero said.
</P>
<P>
   Preliminary reports indicate that from Jan. 1 to Jan. 17, a
total of 88,196 undocumented immigrants were apprehended while
crossing the Mexico border into Texas, New Mexico, Arizona and
California, compared with 70,860 during the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
   In the Del Rio sector _ a 205-mile stretch in Texas _ 10,421
undocumented immigrants have been apprehended this month, INS
public affairs officer Carlton Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   The INS estimates that about 5 million undocumented immigrants
live in the United States. Last fiscal year, about 1.5 million
undocumented immigrants were apprehended along the Southwest
border. Between 400,000 and 500,000 were repeat offenders, while
about a million were believed to be new crossers, according to
Border Patrol officials.
</P>
<P>
   Manuel, a native of the Mexican state of Coahuila, returned this
month to his apartment in Irving, Texas, and a butcher's job, even
though he no longer has a permit to be in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone returns to work. To complete the Mexican dream, which
is to try to build your house, to make money _ not be rich but to
not be poor,'' Manuel said.
</P>
<P>
   This year, many undocumented immigrants have been trying to
cross at more more remote areas because the Border Patrol has
stepped up policing in Texas through Operation Rio Grande.
</P>
<P>
   Apprehensions in the McAllen sector, traditionally a popular
illegal crossing area along the Texas border, are down 13 percent
from last year, while apprehensions in El Paso and Del Rio are up
30 percent and 31 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``The routes are changing all the time,'' said Doug Mosier,
public affairs officer for El Paso's Border Patrol sector. ``We are
just staying one step ahead of them by deploying resources to those
areas that are hardest hit.''
</P>
<P>
   El Paso sector agents are focusing on blocking illegal crossings
through the remote New Mexico communities of Demming, Columbus and
Lordsburg.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are little communities,'' Mosier said. ``It's a very
remote, open area. It's inviting for those who are persistent in
finding avenues into the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Maria Dominguez, president of the North Texas Hispanic advocacy
group Familias Unidas (Families United), said she worries that many
immigrants travel in inhumane conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting harder and harder to cross. Each time people
cross, they are risking their lives,'' Dominguez said.
</P>
<P>
   Mosier said this is shown by encounters with large groups being
smuggled into the United States through the sector around El Paso.
Last week, a group of about 100 was found near Columbus, N.M. A
group of 50 was found Wednesday in a cargo van along a highway.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, agents from El Paso sector's Anti-Smuggling Unit found
44 undocumented immigrants from Mexico in a tractor-trailer headed
to Dallas. The rig had no food, water or restroom facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't realize how dangerous this stuff can be,'' Mosier
said.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
