<SLUG> BC-CHINA-BANKING-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA TO REQUIRE REAL NAMES ON BANK ACCOUNTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to update; how the new rule will work, explained in 2nd
sentence of graf 9, has been clarified and is different than
previously thought.)  
(lh) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ The head of China's central bank Thursday described
renewed efforts to turn China's giant state banks and ailing state
enterprises into sound commercial operations, able to withstand the
competitive pressures that are certain to follow China's entry into
the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the People's Bank of China, Dai Xianglong, speaking
at his annual news conference, also pledged a smooth growth in the
money supply and a stable exchange rate.
</P>
<P>
   But what grabbed public attention was something Dai said in
passing, with words that underscored how deeply China's financial
culture has differed from that in the West.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a plan to adopt a real-name system for bank deposits
this year,'' Dai said in answer to a question. This simple step _
requiring people to put their names on their bank accounts _ is
intended to aid tax collection and the fight against corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Now, anyone can open a savings account under any name, no
identification required, with only the passbook needed for deposits
and withdrawals. While most individuals use their real names, the
use of false ones is common enough to have attracted the concern of
top officials.
</P>
<P>
   The practice seems to have roots in the aversion many Chinese
have to revealing their often-sizable nest eggs. People have also
been known to open accounts under aliases to conceal money from
spouses, Beijing residents said, while companies sometimes hide
revenue from tax collectors in phony-name accounts.
</P>
<P>
   But the technique is mainly used by individuals concealing money
gained through bribery, embezzlement or the stripping of the assets
of state corporations, said a corporate lawyer in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer said that officials and state enterprise managers
with questionable income often open several bank accounts under
different names.
</P>
<P>
   ``The adoption of a real-name mechanism is consistent with
inter- national practice,'' Dai said. Un- der the new rule, he
said, money in an account under a false name will have to be
withdrawn and deposited under the depositor's actual name.
</P>
<P>
   Several Beijing residents said Thursday that they welcomed the
plan as a blow against rampant corruption. In private conversations
and on Internet sites, rumors have been traded about what may be
the largest corruption case in decades. It reportedly involves
scores of officials, mainly in the southeastern province of Fujian,
who are accused of smuggling billions of dollars worth of cars,
electronic goods, firearms and oil, avoiding large duties and fees.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation has not been announced here, but in recent
days the Reuters news agency and The Wall Street Journal, citing
anonymous sources, have reported that the wife of a member of the
Communist Party's ruling Politburo has been implicated, making the
case an especially embarrassing one for the authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Under detention, these sources say, is Lin Youfang, head of a
trading company of the Fujian provincial government. She is married
to Jia Qinglin, who is a member of the 22-man Politburo and is also
Beijing's Communist Party secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators are said to have taken over two heavily guarded
hotels in the southern port city of Xiamen, where witnesses and
suspects are being questioned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-00 2113EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000120.0325 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1796 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-ETHANOL-POLITICS-ART-     01-20 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ETHANOL-POLITICS-ART-700(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ETHANOL, FOR ALL ITS CRITICS, PLAYS BIG IN IOWA
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Iowa, Kan.)   (ART ADV: Photo NYT32 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(jw) 
 By NICHOLAS D. KRISTOF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCK RAPIDS, Iowa _ One of the oddest features of the
presidential selection system is the way the candidates troop to
Iowa and rave about corn alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   The brew is not moonshine, but ethanol, a gasoline additive that
here in the heartland is as American as hogs.
</P>
<P>
   Marvin Flier, a hefty and amiable 44-year-old who grows corn and
soybeans on his 650-acre farm near Rock Rapids, in the northwestern
corner of the state, has watched with a bit of satisfaction as the
presidential candidates have come to Iowa, seeking support in
Monday's caucuses, and solemnly declared their support for tax
breaks for ethanol.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I think they just come out and pander to us,'' Flier
reflected as he sat in his kitchen. Then he cocked his head
thoughtfully and added, ``Of course, that may not be the worst
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Ethanol, introduced after the 1973-74 oil crisis, is hailed by
its supporters as a way to avoid dependence on foreign oil and
because it is clean-burning as a solution to air pollution
problems. But many experts have been unimpressed, and a 1997 study
by the General Accounting Office, a research arm of Congress,
concluded that tax breaks for ethanol had cost the Treasury $7.1
billion while having ``little effect'' on the environment or on
American energy independence.
</P>
<P>
   In Iowa, though, ethanol plays a critical role in the
agricultural economy. So perhaps it is not surprising that every
candidate who is campaigning in Iowa supports tax breaks for
ethanol.
</P>
<P>
   Former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey, who is challenging Vice
President Al Gore for the Democratic nomination, has even reversed
his long-standing opposition to ethanol, saying that farmers he has
talked to changed his mind. Only Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., has
denounced tax breaks for ethanol. But McCain is not campaigning in
Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   ``McCain's a good man and has a strong character, but what he
said about ethanol _ that probably cost him my vote,'' Flier said,
shaking his head. ``Now I'm leaning to Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   The ethanol debate underscores the peculiar effects of the
nation's presidential selection system, for Iowa's role as the
first state to vote in the presidential nomination process is
perhaps one reason the ethanol tax break has survived for more than
two decades.
</P>
<P>
   The longtime support of former Sen. Bob Doleof Kansas, a
powerful farm-state politician and three-time Republican
presidential contender, coupled with aggressive lobbying by the
Archer Daniels Midland Co., a major producer of ethanol, also
buttressed the tax break for ethanol.
</P>
<P>
   But ethanol is less a partisan issue than a regional one; it is
supported by Democrats and Republicans alike in major farm states.
And wherever they are from, ambitious politicians who see
themselves as presidential timber may feel inclined to support
ethanol just to preserve the option of campaigning in Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given that the logic of ethanol is more about politics than
environmental protection, the fact that Iowa has an early caucus
looms large,'' said Daniel Esty, director of the Center for
Environmental Law and Policy at Yale.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, ethanol seemed an answer to energy and
environmental problems alike. It is clean-burning and is produced
from home-grown corn, so the federal government instituted a series
of tax breaks to encourage ethanol production. Ethanol-blended
gasoline is taxed 5.4 cents less per gallon than pure gasoline, and
most experts agree that the ethanol industry would disappear
without that advantage.
</P>
<P>
   To critics, ethanol is a prime example of an infant industry
that never grows up to become competitive on its own. In addition,
ethanol evaporates more easily than gasoline, and so in the hot
summer months this can create its own pollution problems of ozone,
or smog.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ethanol helps with some air pollution problems and worsens
others,'' said A. Blakeman Early, an environmental consultant with
the American Lung Association in Washington. ``You begin to wonder
whether it's really worth it to have a subsidy when in some
circumstances it can make air pollution worse.''
</P>
<P>
   While making it clear that he did not condemn ethanol, Early
said that if the goal was to improve air quality, one might
accomplish more by using the money in other ways.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-00 2114EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000120.0326 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1797 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-ETHANOL-POLITICS-ART-     01-20 0539
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ETHANOL-POLITICS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
  
 ROCK RAPIDS, Iowa: other ways. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Critics also often note that it takes a tremendous amount of
energy just to produce ethanol _ plowing the fields, planting the
seeds, harvesting the corn, trucking it _ and some even suggest,
without much evidence, that ethanol may take more energy to produce
than it supplies. Moreover, almost half of the capacity to produce
ethanol is owned by Archer Daniels Midland, the huge agricultural
conglomerate that is a heavy campaign contributor to Republicans
and Democrats alike. Some critics see the ethanol program as
returning a favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a classic case of a corporate welfare-style
giveaway,'' said Scott Harshbarger, president of Common Cause, a
public affairs lobbying organization.
</P>
<P>
   So it might meet seem odd that the presidential candidates would
be rushing around Iowa praising tax breaks for an alcohol fuel that
does not much impress many experts. But that is to miss the point,
because regardless of whether ethanol is a great fuel for cars, it
certainly works wonders in Iowa campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   The one thing that everybody agrees on is that the ethanol tax
break raises corn prices, and in the Midwest, where family farms
are struggling to survive desperately low prices for their
products, that counts for a lot. Farming has been left behind in
the great economic expansion of the Clinton administration; in Iowa
alone, thousands of farmers have been forced out of business.
</P>
<P>
   The toll hangs heavy over entire rural communities as farmers
delay purchases and their families wonder which would be worse: for
the children to pack up and leave the farm or to stay on and risk
impoverishment. By some calculations, without ethanol, corn prices
would be 20 percent lower than they already are.
</P>
<P>
   Flier recalls that when he began farming in 1975, he was getting
$2.40 a bushel for his corn. This year the price was about $1.40.
Yet he said the same tractor that he bought in 1975 for $18,000
would now cost $75,000. And his other costs have also increased
enormously.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we didn't have ethanol, that would take a lot of our
earnings away,'' Flier said. ``Ethanol allows us to maintain our
standard of living.''
</P>
<P>
   Don Breuker, a farm manager here in Rock Rapids, put it more
starkly.
</P>
<P>
   ``You start peeling off another 20 or 30 cents a bushel out of
farm incomes,'' Breuker said, ``and there'd be a whole lot of hurt
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Many farmers, he added, would be driven to bankruptcy, and the
entire agricultural economy would be hurt.
</P>
<P>
   The farmers also dispute many of the points made by ethanol's
critics.
</P>
<P>
   Trevor Guthmiller, executive director of the American Coalition
for Ethanol, says the tax break was deserved because ethanol did
not entail the cleanup costs of gasoline pollution and did not
involve the expense of maintaining the military capacity abroad to
ensure steady supplies of imported petroleum.
</P>
<P>
   Both the farmers and the ethanol industry view the Iowa campaign
period as a rare opportunity to make their case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of our work is educating people,'' Guthmiller said, ``and
we can do that because whether they're Democrats or Republicans,
they need to come through Iowa. And that's our chance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
