<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1798 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-PROFILE-VOLKER-$A     01-20 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-PROFILE-VOLKER-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NERVOUS ABOUT A STOCK BUBBLE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 23) 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Please note subslug for BIZ-PROFILE-SYKES) 
(af) 
 By ALEX BERENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Befuddled by the stock market? Don't understand why shares of
unprofitable Internet companies are soaring ever higher while
shares of old economy titans like General Motors go begging?
</P>
<P>
   You have some good company. The man who managed the United
States economy for most of the 1980s is as nervous about a bubble
as you are.
</P>
<P>
   Paul A. Volcker, the former Federal Reserve chairman,
acknowledged as much earlier this month at his office at
Rockefeller Center. ``My God, everybody in the world owns stock in
the dot-coms except me,'' Volcker said, a wry smile creasing his
face. ``I am just behind the curve.''
</P>
<P>
   For Wall Street, which looks always ahead, never behind,
Volcker, age 72, might seem a part of history. His fourth-floor
corner office, overlooking the Rockefeller Center skating rink and
featuring a museum's worth of knickknacks and testimonials, hardly
dispels that impression.
</P>
<P>
   But during a 90-minute discussion of the economy, the declining
attractiveness of public service, and his recent work heading a
commission on Swiss banks and the Holocaust, it became clear that
for Volcker, retirement does not mean full-time fly-fishing.
</P>
<P>
   Most economists agree that Volcker helped pave the way for the
expansion of the 1980s _ and today _ by breaking the double-digit
inflation that in 1979 and 1980 threatened to stifle the United
States economy. On the day in 1987 that Volcker announced he would
step down as Fed chairman, bonds suffered one of their biggest
losses ever on fears that his successor (none other than Alan
Greenspan) would not fight inflation as well as Volcker had.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Volcker has successfully adopted the attitude that
former Federal Reserve chairmen, like former presidents, should be
seen but not heard, especially on matters of policy. He worked as
chairman of Wolfensohn &AMP; Co., a boutique New York investment bank,
until 1996, when it was acquired by Bankers Trust.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Volcker made news once again, when an international
commission he headed announced the results of its audit of Swiss
banks that accepted deposits from Holocaust victims.
</P>
<P>
   The commission's report found that the banks threw up
unnecessary obstacles to victims and families trying to claim their
assets. But it exonerated the banks of charges that they
systematically destroyed records to keep the victims' assets for
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Volcker agreed to lead the commission only because of an appeal
from an old friend who happened to head the Swiss National Bank.
Crafting the report, which was praised by both the banks and Jewish
organizations that brought the issue to light three years ago, was
often frustrating, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few weeks before the report was due to come out, I thought
we'd never get a consensus, and I was prepared to put it out
whether we had a consensus or not,'' he said. But once the banks
and Jewish groups recognized that he was determined to issue the
report with or without their agreement, they decided to participate
to ensure their views would be heard.
</P>
<P>
   The commission discovered 54,000 accounts of possible Holocaust
victims that could be worth as much as $1.3 billion. His auditors,
Volcker said, ``found as close an approximation to the truth as
it's possible to find after all this time.''
</P>
<P>
   With the report released, Volcker has moved on to smaller
projects, including advising on the bailout of Japan's Long-Term
Credit Bank. He has also departed from his tradition of public
nonpartisanship to support Bill Bradley for president. Volcker
explained that because he had pushed Bradley to run, he felt he
should openly commit to the Bradley campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Volcker, one of a generation of public servants who came
to Washington after World War II and viewed working for the federal
government as the highest calling, admitted that even he has grown
cynical.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so proud of being in government all my life,'' he said.
But now, ``public service at almost all levels has come into
various disrepute. You don't get the people in government that you
should.''
</P>
<P>
   They don't know the rewards of public service that they are
missing, he said. Even successful corporate leaders ``don't have
the same feeling of challenge and satisfaction.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the 6-foot-7 Volcker, who remains a commanding
physical presence with a heavy handshake, is trying _ and failing _
to make sense of the market. ``You obviously have a kind of
speculative fever,'' he said. ``I think it is a kind of casino.
It's all the rage, trading certificates that have no intrinsic
value.''
</P>
<P>
   Does he see a bust on the horizon? ``There's enormous confidence
today, but it can evaporate very quickly for reasons that are not
very clear,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And what about inflation? Volcker remains as hawkish as if he
had never left the Federal Reserve, dismissing suggestions that
inflation is dead: ``I'm never ready to say inflation is not a
problem. If it's not a problem, it's a potential problem.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-00 2115EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
