Jesse Helms, R-N.C., seated second from top, addresses the United
Nations Security Council, Thursday. At top in U.S. Ambassador to
the U.N. Richard Holbrooke. Helms, chairman of the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee, who has made a career of lambasting the U.N.,
kept up the attack as he addressed the council saying Americans
feel ``a lack of gratitude'' from the world organization. (Marilynn
K. Yee/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- Jan. 20, 2000 -- NY-SNOW -- The Brooklyn
Bridge during the metropolitan area's first snow storm, Thursday. A
blanket of soft white cyrstals created havoc for pedestrians and
motorists Thursday as the storm, fed by moist winds blowing in off
the Atlantic, swept up the coastline and covered the tri-state area
with between two and eight inches of snow. (Philip Greenberg/The
New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) UNDATED -- Jan. 20, 2000 -- ANTIQUES-COLUMN -- A
drop-leaf mahogany table, circa 1810, is up for auction at
Christie's. Friday begins Americana week in the city and the Winter
Antiques Show, which runs through Jan. 30 in Manhattan.
(Christie's/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Jan. 20, 2000 -- NEW-MUSIC-SOLOISTS -- The
guitarist Jorge Caballero. Having played two well-received recitals
that combined new works and standard repertory, Caballero is
playing the premieres of three newly commissioned works in Merkin
Concert Hall's Saturday evening ``Zoom: Composers Close Up'' series
on Feb. 26. (Andrea Mohin/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Jan. 20, 2000 -- THEATER-NOTES -- The comic
Eddie Izzard, shown here in ``Dress to Kill,'' will be back. April
4 to 8, Izzard arrives with a new show, ``Circles,'' at Westbeth
Theater Center. The weeklong stint is part of a two-month tour that
will include a trip to Australia, as well as American stops in
Philadelphia, Boston, Los Angeles and a city he called that
``little bit up there,'' known to many as Seattle. (Sara
Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- Jan. 20, 2000 -- THEATRICAL-WRITER-2 --
Claudia Shear as Mae West in ``Dirty Blonde'' - an affectionate
look at the lives of Mae West and two of her most ardent admirers.
Those who were privy to the rehearsal process say the director,
James Lapine, was highly protective of Ms. Shear's writing. (Sara
Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- Jan. 20, 2000 -- THEATRICAL-WRITER-1 -- James
Lapine teamed with Claudia Shear to produce the play ``Dirty
Blonde'' - an affectionate look at the lives of Mae West and two of
her most ardent admirers. The play opened to favorable reviews last
week at the New York Theater Workshop, where it has been extended
until Feb. 13. The producers are mulling a move to a larger
theater. (Sara Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) UNDATED -- Jan. 20, 2000 -- CIR-PEN-SCANNERS -- A new
generation of handheld gadgets offers the option of scanning in
desired text with a wireless pen-size scanner just like using a
highlighting pen. Though they seem simple enought to use, the
scanners are not quite so nimble. But they do show promise for
researchers and mobile professionals. (Tony Cenicola/The New York
Times)
</P>
