satisfaction as the presidential candidates have come to Iowa,
seeking support in the Jan. 24 caucuses, and solemnly declared
their support for tax breaks for ethanol, which is made from corn.
(Nick Kristof/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) HAJVALI, Yugoslavia -- Jan. 20, 2000 --
RUSSIA-KOSOVO-SCANDAL --Beghjet Pacolli at home in the village of
Hajvali, on the outskirts of Pristina. Pacolli, a construction
magnate at the center of a kickback scandal involving former
President Boris N. Yeltsin of Russia and his family, acknowledged
Thursday that he helped supply the family with credit cards.
Pacolli, a Kosovo Albanian, insisted that the scandal was
``nothing.'' (Andrew Testa/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) SOUTH ORANGE, N.J. -- Jan. 20, 2000 -- NJ-SETONHALL-FIRE
-- A man kneels before a makeshift memorial on Thursday near the
dormitory where three students died early Wednesday in a fire.
Seton Hall University administrators defended their fire-safety
procedures on Thursday as investigators continued to search for the
cause of the fire that killed the students and injured dozens of
others. (Angel Franco/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) BIG BEND RANCH STATE PARK, Texas -- Jan. 20, 2000 --
TEXAS-CAMELS-3-HNS -- Doug Baum checks the saddles of a camel
during a desert ride in Big Bend Ranch State Park. The beasts will
eat almost anything that they can reach - even thorny desert brush.
(Tom Reel/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) BIG BEND RANCH STATE PARK, Texas -- Jan. 20, 2000 --
TEXAS-CAMELS-2-HNS -- Dotty Lindquist concentrates on getting into
the stirrup aboard a cranky camel named Irenie (who happens to be
pregnant) as guests saddle up for the second day of camel riding at
Big Bend Ranch State Park. The guests travel into the desert for
several hours, where they eat lunch before returning to the ranch
for supper. (Tom Reel/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) BIG BEND RANCH STATE PARK, Texas -- Jan. 20, 2000 --
TEXAS-CAMELS-1-HNS -- Doug Baum leads a group of camel riders
across a desert basin at Big Bend Ranch State Park in September.
The guests ride into the desert for several hours, where they eat
lunch before returning to the ranch for supper. (Tom Reel/San
Antonio Express-News)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) NEW YORK -- Jan. 20, 2000 -- BLACK-TALK-RADIO -- Civil
rights activist Al Sharpton during a show on WLIB radio in 1998.
Listening to black talk radio makes it easy to understand why it
has long functioned as a roiling, playful and galvanizing lifeline
for blacks in New York City. (Chester Higgins Jr./The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) NEW YORK -- Jan. 20, 2000 -- NY-SNOW-2 -- Christian
Atyde, 8, and his father Ivan Stoinev, enjoy the first snowfall of
the year in Central Park, Thursday. A blanket of soft white
cyrstals created havoc for pedestrians and motorists Thursday as
the storm, fed by moist winds blowing in off the Atlantic, swept up
the coastline and covered the tri-state area with between two and
eight inches of snow. (Librado Romero/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) UNDATED -- Jan. 20, 2000 -- BRADLEY-ADVISERS -- Bill
Bradley's new campaign poster. While both Bradley's broad knowledge
and his determination to ``run a different kind of campaign,'' as
he likes to say, have been keys to his appeal, they have also left
him vulnerable. (Justin Lane/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) SAN FRANCISCO -- Jan. 20, 2000 -- ROSE-PISTOLA-4-LADN --
The chef Reed Hearon of Rose Pistola in San Francisco. Now it's
possible to sample some of Hearon's restaurant fare with a copy of
his recently released ``The Rose Pistola Cookbook,'' co-written
with Peggy Knickerbocker. It's filled with 140 recipes - mostly of
dishes served at the restaurant - that evoke the spirit of North
Beach and its Italian immigrant flavors. (John Lazar/The Los
Angeles Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) SAN FRANCISCO -- Jan. 20, 2000 -- ROSE-PISTOLA-3-LADN --
At Rose Pistola in San Francisco, mussel, broccoli and potato salad
can be served as an antipasto or as a main course. If you've
visited San Francisco's North Beach in the last few years, you may
have run into the Rose Pistola restaurant. Featuring North
Beach-style Italian food, the cooking and menu are influenced by
California and Liguria. (John Lazar/The Los Angeles Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) SAN FRANCISCO -- Jan. 20, 2000 -- ROSE-PISTOLA-2-LADN --
Swordfish brochettes with salsa verde from Rose Pistola in San
Francisco. The restaurant was named after Rose Pistola (who passed
away in 1998 at the age of 90), a colorful and feisty women who
owned a bar and was renowned in North Beach for her Italian
cooking. Her Silician father was a fisherman, and her mother was a
fantastic cook. (John Lazar/The Los Angeles Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) SAN FRANCISCO -- Jan. 20, 2000 -- ROSE-PISTOLA-1-LADN --
Crostini of asparagus, prosciutto and teleme can be assembled in a
jiffy. If you've visited San Francisco's North Beach in the last
few years, you may have run into the Rose Pistola restaurant.
Featuring North Beach-style Italian food, the cooking and menu are
influenced by California and Liguria. (John Lazar/The Los Angeles
Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) UNDATED -- Jan. 20, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JAN. 23 --
ABOUT-CARS-TAURUS-2 -- Aside from body and styling changes, the
2000 Taurus remains, under the skin, basically the same car.
Inside, conservatism rules. The old Taurus' unusual oval control
pod is gone. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) UNDATED -- Jan. 20, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JAN. 23 --
ABOUT-CARS-TAURUS-1 -- After a lukewarm response, the 2000 Taurus
is stepping away from the oval and more into the mainstream of
current design. Since the Taurus was introduced in 1986 as an
all-new, daring design, it has undergone several minor changes and
one large remake, for the 1996 model year. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) UNDATED -- Jan. 20, 2000 -- FOREMAN-ADCOL -- An
infomercial for the Salton product's George Foreman ``Lean Mean Fat
Reducing Grilling Machine'' featured the former heavyweight
champion and Nancy Nelson. With 10 million nonstick grillers sold
since 1995, the manufacturer, Salton, bought Foreman's name and
image last month for $137.5 million in cash and stock. Foreman will
receive $110 million over five years, joining the ranks of the
highest-paid pitchmen. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) COUNCIL BLUFFS, Iowa -- Jan. 20, 2000 -- GORE-CAMPAIGN
-- Vice President Al Gore greets students from the Iowa School for
the Deaf during an appearance at Iowa Western Community College,
Thursday. Many of the students signed ``I love you.'' as Gore
walked past. (Paul Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) ELLIS ISLAND, N.J. -- Jan. 20, 2000 --
ELLIS-ISLAND-RESTORE -- A 1997 file photo of an examining room in a
decaying hospital building on Ellis Island which is closed to the
public. New Jersey officials on Thursday outlined an ambitious $300
million plan to restore Ellis Island, most of which has been hidden
from the millions who visit every year. (Suzanne DeChillo/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) WEST DES MOINES, Iowa -- Jan. 20, 2000 --
BRADLEY-CAMPAIGN -- Bill Bradley, running for the Democratic
nomination for president, talks with senior citizens attending a
gathering organized by the AARP, Thursday. Bradley told senior
citizens Thursday that reform of the nation's health care system is
now inevitable because his campaign took ``the risk of leaderhip''
and put the issue on the political agenda. (Keith Meyers/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- Jan. 20, 2000 -- MCCAIN-CAMPAIGN -- Sen.
John McCain, R-Ariz., running for the Republican presidential
nomination, speaks to reporters outside the Russian Mission to the
U.N., Thursday. Still fuming over a state GOP effort to remove his
name from New York's presidential primary ballots, McCain accused
party leaders Thursday of making New York less democratic than
Russia. (Michelle V. Agins/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) UNITED NATIONS -- Jan. 20, 2000 -- U.N.-HELMS-3 -- Sen.
Jesse Helms, R-N.C., left, during his addresses to the United
Nations Security Council, Thursday. Looking on at right is U.S.
Ambassador to the U.N. Richard Holbrooke. Helms, chairman of the
Senate Foreign Relations Committee, who has made a career of
lambasting the U.N., kept up the attack as he addressed the council
saying Americans feel ``a lack of gratitude'' from the world
organization. (Marilynn K. Yee/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) UNITED NATIONS -- Jan. 20, 2000 -- U.N.-HELMS-2 -- Sen.
Jesse Helms, R-N.C., center, is flanked by U.S. Ambassador to the
U.N. Richard Holbrooke, right, and U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan, left, as they arrive to the floor of the Security Council
Chamber, Thursday. Helms, chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations
Committee, who has made a career of lambasting the U.N., kept up
the attack as he addressed the council saying Americans feel ``a
lack of gratitude'' from the world organization. (Marilynn K.
Yee/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) UNITED NATIONS -- Jan. 20, 2000 -- U.N.-HELMS -- Sen.
Jesse Helms, R-N.C., seated second from top, addresses the United
Nations Security Council, Thursday. At top in U.S. Ambassador to
the U.N. Richard Holbrooke. Helms, chairman of the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee, who has made a career of lambasting the U.N.,
kept up the attack as he addressed the council saying Americans
feel ``a lack of gratitude'' from the world organization. (Marilynn
K. Yee/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- Jan. 20, 2000 -- NY-SNOW -- The Brooklyn
Bridge during the metropolitan area's first snow storm, Thursday. A
blanket of soft white cyrstals created havoc for pedestrians and
motorists Thursday as the storm, fed by moist winds blowing in off
the Atlantic, swept up the coastline and covered the tri-state area
with between two and eight inches of snow. (Philip Greenberg/The
New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) UNDATED -- Jan. 20, 2000 -- ANTIQUES-COLUMN -- A
drop-leaf mahogany table, circa 1810, is up for auction at
Christie's. Friday begins Americana week in the city and the Winter
Antiques Show, which runs through Jan. 30 in Manhattan.
(Christie's/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Jan. 20, 2000 -- NEW-MUSIC-SOLOISTS -- The
guitarist Jorge Caballero. Having played two well-received recitals
that combined new works and standard repertory, Caballero is
playing the premieres of three newly commissioned works in Merkin
Concert Hall's Saturday evening ``Zoom: Composers Close Up'' series
on Feb. 26. (Andrea Mohin/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Jan. 20, 2000 -- THEATER-NOTES -- The comic
Eddie Izzard, shown here in ``Dress to Kill,'' will be back. April
4 to 8, Izzard arrives with a new show, ``Circles,'' at Westbeth
Theater Center. The weeklong stint is part of a two-month tour that
will include a trip to Australia, as well as American stops in
Philadelphia, Boston, Los Angeles and a city he called that
``little bit up there,'' known to many as Seattle. (Sara
Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- Jan. 20, 2000 -- THEATRICAL-WRITER-2 --
Claudia Shear as Mae West in ``Dirty Blonde'' - an affectionate
look at the lives of Mae West and two of her most ardent admirers.
Those who were privy to the rehearsal process say the director,
James Lapine, was highly protective of Ms. Shear's writing. (Sara
Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- Jan. 20, 2000 -- THEATRICAL-WRITER-1 -- James
Lapine teamed with Claudia Shear to produce the play ``Dirty
Blonde'' - an affectionate look at the lives of Mae West and two of
her most ardent admirers. The play opened to favorable reviews last
week at the New York Theater Workshop, where it has been extended
until Feb. 13. The producers are mulling a move to a larger
theater. (Sara Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) UNDATED -- Jan. 20, 2000 -- CIR-PEN-SCANNERS -- A new
generation of handheld gadgets offers the option of scanning in
desired text with a wireless pen-size scanner just like using a
highlighting pen. Though they seem simple enought to use, the
scanners are not quite so nimble. But they do show promise for
researchers and mobile professionals. (Tony Cenicola/The New York
Times)
</P>
