<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Thursday, 01/20/00. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT39) NEW YORK -- Jan. 20, 2000 -- BBA-YANKS-MATTINGLY -- Don
Mattingly, who threw out the first pitch before Game 2 of the 1999
Divisional Series between the Yankees and the Texas Rangers, will
resume his relationship with the Yankees by working as a spring
training instructor next month. Mattingly says the details of his
role have not been completed, but he expects to spend about three
weeks in Tampa, Fla., and then work with minor leaguers during the
season. (Chang W. Lee/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT38) BOSTON -- Jan. 20, 2000 -- YOUTH-VOTE-BOS -- From left:
Adam Sonenshein, Shannon Moran and Chris McNeice of Project Vote
Smart, which surveyed 18- to 25-year-olds. What they found: 70
percent said the Internet is the most useful source for news
information. (Bill Greene/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT37) BOSTON -- Jan. 20, 2000 -- SKI-CITY-KIDS-BOS -- Since
founding Youth Enrichment Services (YES) in 1968, Richard Williams
has helped 125,000 urban youngsters from disadvantaged backgrounds
get onto the slopes. Summer programs include canoeing, hiking, and
camping, but skiing remains the organization's focus. ``We want to
introduce kids to things they've never seen before,'' says
Williams. ``Kids have to feel they can be part of that kind of
America.'' (Frank O'Brien/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT36) BOSTON -- Jan. 20, 2000 -- AUTHOR-HIASSEN-BOS -- Author
Carl Hiaasen at the Charles Hotel in Boston. The title of Hiaasen's
latest satirical crime novel is ``Sick Puppy,'' but the term just
as easily could apply to the Miami Herald columnist. Hiaasen has
populated his plot with some of the most repulsive characters
imaginable. (John Blanding/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT35) LONG BEACH, Calif. -- ADV. FOR SUN., JAN. 23 -- Jan. 20,
2000 --BIZ-CALIF-AEROSPACE -- Dr. Carl Chen in front of a new
Jetcruzer 500. Chen, and a small band of entrepreneurs like him,
believe there remains a bright future here in developing new and
innovative aircraft. ``You have to be sort of childish to think
this, but I think there's still a big opportunity in this
business,'' says Chen, whose company, Advanced Aerodynamics and
Structures, is working on a new line of small turbojets. (Kim
Kulish/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT34) UNDATED -- Jan. 20, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JAN. 23 --
BIZ-5-QUESTIONS -- Roy S. Roberts, 60, the GM group vice president
for North American vehicle sales, service and marketing, announced
Tuesday that he would retire this spring. ``The organization is
starting to click,'' he says. ``Now we've got some inventory we
didn't have. I'm not delusioned about this marketplace, or the fact
that anybody will give up any market share.'' (General Motors/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) UNDATED -- Jan. 20, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JAN. 23 --
BIZ-AIRPORTS-E-COMMERCE -- Developers are building air cargo
centers near the Portland, Ore., airport to lease to e-commerce
retailers to speed product delivery. For many e-commerce retailers,
selling a product online is becoming astonishingly easy; the tricky
part is finding an efficient way to have that product immediately
available, and quickly getting it to the customer. (The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) WASHINGTON -- Jan. 20, 2000 -- CLINTON-EDUC -- On
Thursday, President Clinton proposed a $31 billion package of tax
advantages and financial aid to make college more affordable for
millions of families, including those earning as much as $120,000
annually. With him were Nina McLaughlin, a Trinity College student;
Hillary Rodham Clinton; Education Secretary Richard W. Riley and
Sen. Charles E. Schumer, D-N.Y. (Justin Lane/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) WASHINGTON -- Jan. 20, 2000 -- CLINTON-ARAFAT --
President Clinton meets with Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat in
the Oval Office on Thursday. Clinton urged Israelis and
Palestinians to be flexible as they worked to hammer out a peace
agreement. (Justin Lane/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
