<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1805 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BRADLEY-CAMPAIGN-ART-     01-20 1070
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-CAMPAIGN-ART-750&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIDES FEAR BRADLEY HAS LET IOWA MOMENTUM SLIP AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also BRADLEY-ADVISERS) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT12 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 (bl)  
 By RICHARD L. BERKE with JAMES DAO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ After pouring vast resources into this state,
some of Bill Bradley's top aides question whether their campaign
passed up an important opportunity by not responding more rapidly,
or aggressively, to Vice President Al Gore's attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley was so determined to make an impressive showing in Iowa
that he pumped the maximum $2.2 million into the state, including
more than $1.3 million on television ads, and shuttled more than
400 volunteers here to help get out the vote. In addition, Bradley
stumped in Iowa about 75 days last year, nearly double the number
for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   But confronted by weeks of polls showing that Bradley's early
surge has stalled _ he trails Gore by at least 20 points in most
surveys _ some of the former senator's aides, speaking out for the
first time in interviews, said Gore had waged a more energetic
drive than they had expected.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Lucas, a veteran labor organizer who runs the Bradley
operation in Iowa, acknowledged that when he arrived in the state
last summer, and his candidate was coming on strong, he had higher
expectations for victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``In July, I just didn't know what I know now,'' Lucas said,
explaining how onerous it was to organize in this state,
particularly against a sitting vice president who has the unions on
his side. While he is proud of what his organization has
accomplished against Gore's onslaught, Lucas said he might have
been lulled into a sense of optimism because early on the Gore
campaign did not seem focused on the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought it would be easy,'' Lucas said. ``But I
thought if these guys could stay asleep at the switch, I could
surprise them.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucas said the Bradley campaign suffered last fall when Gore
retooled his campaign, installed Donna Brazile as his national
campaign manager and opened seven weeks of attacks _ which Bradley
shrugged off. ``It was a very rough seven weeks here,'' he said.
``Donna really made a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lucas said he did not know if firing back would have worked
either. ``If we had done that, we would not have attracted all the
people we attracted,'' he said. ``It's a trade-off.''
</P>
<P>
   Several of Bradley's aides said there had been disagreements
among his top staff about whether he should have responded more
fiercely to Gore. Some advisers said that they had pressed Bradley
to be more assertive in debates, but that he resisted because he
felt it would turn off voters, and violate his pledge to run a
positive campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Paul Wellstone, D-Minn., who has campaigned here for
Bradley for months and knows the state well, said he would have
favored a more aggressive strategy. ``Would my approach be
different?'' he asked. ``Yes. When you're five-five and a half, I'm
always looking for the scrappy approach.''
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging that he, too, would counsel to fire back at Gore
sooner, Lucas said: ``I may think some things are not such a good
idea. But this is the way Bill wants to run it. I sure hope Bradley
was right to be positive.''
</P>
<P>
   But Wellstone dismissed those supporters who questioned whether
Bradley should have invested so much into Iowa. ``When you've got a
two-person race, I don't think you can walk away from Iowa. You're
walking away from farms and walking away from the Midwest.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Bradley, opening a four-day bus tour Thursday through
central and eastern Iowa, said Gore's attacks might have hurt him.
``Most voters don't understand, yes, there were two negative ads
run; to a certain extent voters might have been swayed by that,''
he said in Des Moines. ``But we're countering that now. And I think
we're making up our distance very quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley came close to committing a political faux pas _
insulting the Iowa caucus system _ by saying, ``We knew all along
that Iowa is a state that rewards entrenched power.'' He was
referring to how caucuses tend to favor incumbents with potent
organizations, like the one backing Gore. Asked if he meant to
dismiss the system, Bradley said, ``Absolutely not'' adding, ``I
respect the people of Iowa.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats have warned against a repetition of 1988, when
their nominee, Michael Dukakis, failed to respond to George Bush's
assaults, and lost the election.
</P>
<P>
   Marsha Aronoff, a senior Bradley policy adviser, explained the
predicament, saying: ``You're damned if you do and damned if you
don't. If you don't respond, they say you are letting attacks
stand. When you do, they say you are going negative.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Beyond his reluctance to attack, some Democrats have questioned
the effectiveness of Bradley's organization in Iowa. Late this
summer, Rob Tully, the state party chairman, said Bradley could win
the caucuses. Now he said it was highly unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to say this,'' Tully said. ``But I've got to be
truthful. I'm not sure the campaign has caught on. A caucus
organization is a different animal than some people who may have
been brought in understood.'' He added, ``Bradley did everything he
was supposed to do. The campaign just didn't follow through.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of Bradley's advisers also questioned why he has begun
running a commercial that is a tribute from Sen. Daniel Patrick
Moynihan, D-N.Y., when the two other senators who back him here _
Wellstone and Bob Kerrey, D-Neb. _ are far better known in Iowa and
have demeanors that may be more suited to the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not that I have anything against Moynihan,'' said state Sen.
John Kibbie, one of Bradley's most prominent backers in the state,
``but Wellstone or Bob Kerrey would have been more effective in
Iowa.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, some campaign officials insisted Moynihan was revered in
Iowa as an elder statesman, and would also appeal to elderly
voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moynihan is pretty well known and very highly regarded, and
certainly regarded on the issue of trust and character,'' said Eric
Hauser, Bradley's press secretary. ``We didn't go into it
blindly.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, the Bradley campaign also began running a commercial
featuring Kerrey.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
