<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1806 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-FCC-MINORITIES-680&AMP;AD     01-20 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FCC-MINORITIES-680&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FCC REVISES RULES ON HIRING OF WOMEN AND MINORITIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Federal Communications Commission on Thursday
adopted new rules intended to increase job opportunities for
minorities and women in the broadcasting industry, replacing
previous guidelines that a federal appeals court said had
unconstitutionally imposed quotas.
</P>
<P>
   The new rules, adopted by a vote of 4-1, are a carefully
fashioned effort by the commission and especially its chairman,
William Kennard, to retain some kind of pressure on the
broadcasting industry to seek members of minorities and women as
job applicants without violating the court's 1998 ruling.
</P>
<P>
   If the new approach withstands court challenges that it may
produce, it could provide a model for other government agencies and
public institutions to introduce affirmative action programs that
will not run afoul of federal courts, which have been generally
hostile to anything that smacks of forcing employers to hire
minorities and women in specific numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The new rules explicitly state that a company's record in hiring
women and minorities is not to be used as a factor in deciding
whether to renew a broadcaster's license. Under the old rules, if a
broadcaster failed to hire women and minorities at less than half
of their percentage of the local population, it would touch off a
review of their recruitment practices.
</P>
<P>
   Broadcasting executives believed the old rules made a company's
record in hiring minorities and women a factor in getting a license
renewed, although commission officials have disputed that
interpretation.
</P>
<P>
   The new rules roughly fit what has sometimes been called the
original concept of affirmative action: reaching out broadly to
advertise jobs and make them available to minorities and women but
without any requirement that they actually succeed in getting hired
or promoted in any specific numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The rules require broadcasters to disseminate news about job
openings to any group that asks to be notified. They also ask
broadcasters to select from a menu of other methods to publicize
job opportunities, such as by sending representatives to job fairs
or maintaining internship programs for minorities and women.
</P>
<P>
   If a broadcaster ``believes it can accomplish broad outreach
without these recruiting measures,'' the commission said in a
statement, it can work out its own outreach program.
</P>
<P>
   Kennard, who conducted Thursday's commission meeting, said it
was particularly appropriate to adopt the rules on the same week as
Martin Luther King Jr. Day. He said the rules were necessary in a
society that had not yet reached King's dream of a colorblind
society, which he said was evident by the current debate over ``the
virtual absence of minorities in prime time television.''
</P>
<P>
   Henry M. Rivera, a former commission member who is now chairman
of the Minority Media and Telecommunications Council, a lobby
group, said on Thursday that the promulgation of the new rules was
especially laudable since it showed that Kennard did not simply
acquiesce in the face of the court ruling. Instead, Rivera said,
Kennard and the commission have fought back with a new approach to
pressing broadcasters to widen their employment pool.
</P>
<P>
   The National Association of Broadcasters, the powerful trade
association and lobby that represents most of the nation's 12,615
radio broadcasters and 1,616 television broadcasters, has long
chafed at the commission's equal opportunity policies, particularly
the requirement for keeping detailed records of a license holder's
hiring history.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Wharton, a spokesman for the broadcasters association,
said on Thursday that its lawyers would study the new proposal ``in
the hope that this won't increase the already considerable
paperwork burdens on broadcasters.''
</P>
<P>
   The new rules require that license holders continue to file
reports on both their efforts to publicize job openings as well as
how many applicants they get for each position. But the rules say
that the records will be kept by the commission ``only to monitor
industry employment trends and prepare reports to Congress.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The issue in the broadcasting industry began in April 1998, when
a three-judge panel of the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals for the
District of Columbia ruled that the equal employment policies of
the commission, some of which dated to 1969, were unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   The court said the program amounted to a ``soft quota,'' because
hiring records were scrutinized and, if broadcasters had been
hiring minorities or women at a level less than 50 percent of the
local population, they came under special scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   The full appeals court upheld the ruling by a 6-to-4 vote, with
the judges dividing largely along political lines; those who were
appointed by Democratic presidents dissented in a ruling supported
by Republican appointees.
</P>
<P>
   Both the administration and lawyers for civil rights groups then
made a tactical decision not to ask the Supreme Court to consider
the case, fearing that the justices might give the ruling even more
force.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
