<SLUG> BC-BBO-TUCKER-COLUMN21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Baseball's step won't restore balance
 &HT;    By Tim Tucker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ So, can we expect to see the Expos vs. the Brewers in
the National League Championship Series some year soon? Or,
perhaps, the Pirates vs. the Royals in the World Series?
</P>
<P>
   Did Major League Baseball really take the first step toward
parity, toward a level playing field for all teams, with
Wednesday's unanimous resolution in Phoenix requesting that
commissioner Bud Selig ``take such action as he deems appropriate
to ensure ... long-term competitive balance''?
</P>
<P>
   Well.
</P>
<P>
   Let's not get carried away.
</P>
<P>
   Let's say, for the moment, that Selig will find various ways to
benefit the downtrodden, small-market teams. Let's say he gives
them extra amateur draft picks or institutes a preseason waiver
draft in which the weak teams can pluck a player from the strong
teams _ just two ideas kicked around at the Phoenix meetings. Let's
say he eventually gets the Players Association to go along with a
new system of revenue-sharing in which the big-market teams would
get far less of the national-TV money than the small-market teams.
</P>
<P>
   Do such things, and Selig would be making progress. He'd be
helping the Pirates, Expos, Royals, Twins, et al. But, alas, it
would not be enough.
</P>
<P>
   To accomplish the desired end, which is an industry in which
every team has a chance to compete on the field, revenue-sharing
would have to be combined with some sort of salary cap, as in the
NFL and NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Here's why: No matter how Selig might redistribute the sport's
shared revenue _ the national TV money, the Internet money, etc. _
the big-market teams always will have more in their coffers than
the small-market teams. That is because of their superior streams
of locally produced revenue, which would not be subject to sharing.
In other words, the Yankees always will be in position to spend
much more on players than the Royals.
</P>
<P>
   Unless there is a salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   Only a cap, combined with revenue-sharing, can assure that all
teams spend roughly the same amount on players _ that all teams
have a roughly equal chance to compete.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball, of course, is no closer than ever to having a cap.
That can only be achieved in collective bargaining, and the chances
are slim and none. (I'd bet on ``none.'') So this week's move by
the owners is not a panacea. But it is a step in the right
direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want anyone to think we are putting our heads in the
sand,'' Braves president Stan Kasten said from Phoenix on Thursday.
``We don't like the fact that the same six or eight teams make the
postseason every year and the fact that when we leave spring
training 20 teams know they won't be (in the playoffs). It's a
concern to everybody, and I say that as one of those six or eight
teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the eight playoff teams were among the top 10 teams
in payroll size; only once in the past five years has a team with a
bottom-half payroll made the postseason. By this week, the owners
had seen enough of the trend to restore the
``best-interests-of-baseball'' powers taken from the commissioner's
office in January 1994 and to give Selig unprecedented power in
dealing with revenue-sharing. Basically, it'll be his call, subject
to union approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``With these changes, there's no question there is awesome power
there,'' Selig said. ``But these people (the owners) know me. They
know I will use it judiciously.... But they also know I'll proceed
with fierce determination.''
</P>
<P>
   And they know that Selig knows what happens to commissioners who
use their power in ways that those who gave it do not approve. As
Kasten put it: ``Like the CEO of any company, he has to do things
that promote continued confidence in him staying in his job.''
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is that this week's empowerment of Selig is a
strong statement about the seriousness of the competitive-imbalance
problem _ and a desperate plea for someone to do something about
it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
