<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-AFC-FEATURE21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Old guard's taking trip to new turf
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ In 17 years of playing pro football, the
closest Bruce Matthews has come to the Super Bowl was lying on his
couch watching older brother Clay play linebacker for Cleveland in
the 1986 AFC Championship.
</P>
<P>
   The Super Bowl was scheduled for Pasadena, one town over from
where Matthews then lived. He was all set to go.
</P>
<P>
   Along came ``The Drive.'' A year later, it was ``The Fumble.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They got sidetracked a little bit in those two Denver games,''
Matthews said charitably.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's his turn to try. Finally. The player who personifies
the term ``old guard'' for the Titans will experience his first AFC
Championship Game on Sunday against Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   ``For so long having watched other teams play, you kind of
hardened yourself to what it might mean to play in a game like
this,'' said Matthews, 38, who will start at left guard. ``I told
myself, `It's no big deal.' But now that we're in it, it's pretty
cool.''
</P>
<P>
   He grinned. ``And it's a shame I had to wait this long. We
probably shouldn't have messed around 16 prior years.''
</P>
<P>
   Matthews has spent his whole career with the Houston
Oilers/Tennessee Titans franchise and has been around so long that
young teammates are stunned to learn he played college football
with coach Jeff Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've watched the team develop,'' Matthews said. ``We were
horrible back in '94. We were 2-14 and we knew it was going to be a
rebuilding thing. I guess I could have had the opportunity to go
other places, but it was always in my heart to stay here and see it
through.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew that if we ever did make it, it would be that much
sweeter, and it really has been this year. ... But by no means are
we satisfied.''
</P>
<P>
   Until this year, no one paid much attention to Matthews. Of
course, as an offensive lineman, he didn't really have any stats.
</P>
<P>
   But Matthews is the NFL's reigning Iron Man, with 264 games,
more than any active player except kickers Gary Anderson of
Minnesota (278) and Morten Andersen of the Falcons (276). Matthews
has the record for offensive linemen and is No. 7 all-time. He has:
</P>
<P>
   _ Played in 200 consecutive games, starting 197 of them. Both
are NFL records for active players. His streak would be even longer
if not for a contract holdout at the start of the 1987 season.
</P>
<P>
   _ Blocked for 26 different running backs and 15 different
quarterbacks.
</P>
<P>
   _ Played in 38 different stadiums.
</P>
<P>
   _ Made 12 Pro Bowls _ tied with Jerry Rice and one fewer than
Reggie White.
</P>
<P>
   _ Been part of eight 1,000-yard rushing seasons and seven
3,000-yard passing seasons.
</P>
<P>
   And now it all boils down to one game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to get Bruce his ring,'' said running back Eddie
George, who follows the 6-foot-5, 305-pounder.
</P>
<P>
   Matthews got the game ball after the Titans defeated the
Indianapolis Colts 19-16 last Sunday. He was touched by the
gesture.
</P>
<P>
   However, the father of six is uncomfortable talking about
himself. He said he'd rather talk about George, quarterback Steve
McNair, or even a holding penalty or a sack.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like playing offensive line because you get to be part of a
bigger thing,'' Matthews said. ``You can kind of go about your
business. Usually when you go out in a community, the only reason
you stand out is you're a lot bigger than everyone else. I like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   However, when pressed, he'll speculate on why he's been able to
take the abuse heaped on him during 200 consecutive games on the
offensive line.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, he ventured, it's ``my great diet that I'm on with
cheeseburgers and Diet Coke, my great offseason workout plan, and
just God has given me a body that can take this pounding. I'm
humbled that I've been able to play this long.''
</P>
<P>
   After Sunday, Matthews will need 13 games to pass brother Clay,
who played for Cleveland (1978-93) and Atlanta (1994-96). George
Blanda has the all-time record of 340 from 1949-75.
</P>
<P>
   Matthews has two years left on his current contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``My brother's (record is) another season away,'' said Matthews,
whose father, Clay Sr., played linebacker for the 49ers (1950,
1953-55). ``Part of me wants him to have it. Part of me's selfish
and I wouldn't mind having it. ... I'm not looking to retire
anytime soon, but I also realize that it's a lot closer than it
used to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
