<HEADER>
A1811 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BRADLEY-ADVISERS-1STL     01-20 1071
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-ADVISERS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOES BRADLEY'S LACK OF FORMAL ADVISERS MAKE MISSTEPS MORE LIKELY? 
</HEADLINE>
  (Subs to fix spelling of `that' in 10th graf; adds `they' in 8th
graf; corrects to `trust' sted `rust' in 4th graf from end) 
(See also BRADLEY-CAMPAIGN) 
(ART ADV: Photos NYT12 and 22 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By MELINDA HENNEBERGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ Bill Bradley does not have advisers in the
traditional sense _ and does not need any, according to a number of
those who are acting, as the candidate's friend Dan Okimoto put it,
``more as a sounding board, raising doubts here and there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``His mastery obviates the need for close policy advisers,''
said Okimoto, a college buddy, now a professor of international
relations at Stanford, and someone with whom Bradley discusses a
number of matters, including foreign policy. ``There is no such
structure in place on foreign policy or any other issue. The
candidate is in charge of tone, direction, vision and those around
him provide support. Both in a political sense and on policy, Bill
Bradley is his campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   But after several perceived missteps recently _ a somewhat
confused response during an agriculture debate here, and especially
the decision to spend so much time in Iowa, where his campaign
appears to be lagging, instead of concentrating on New Hampshire,
where he's in a tight race _ even some supporters say the holes in
the campaign are starting to show.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Joe Trippi, an unaligned Democratic consultant who ran Walter
Mondale's Iowa campaign in 1984 and has had generally positive
things to say about Bradley's campaign over the last year, said,
``He really is running his campaign the way he wants to run it, and
I'm not sure he's taking any advice. That's always a bad sign. The
move to Iowa definitely was a risky gambit and I don't think I
would have advised it.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said, it is only after next Monday's caucuses that
``we'll see if Iowa was a big mistake _ or brilliant.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, one of Bradley's sounding boards, his wife, Ernestine
Schlant, a professor of comparative literature, has a theory about
politics that might apply: Any candidate's greatest asset almost
always turns out to be his greatest liability as well, she said in
an interview last summer, citing Bill Clinton and his personal
warmth and empathy as an example.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   While both Bradley's broad knowledge and his determination to
``run a different kind of campaign,'' as he likes to say, have been
keys to his appeal, they have also left him vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, both his Democratic opponent, Vice President Al Gore
and the Republican front-runner, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, have
been criticized for relying too much on consultants of all sorts.
But those in opposing camps _ advisers themselves, of course, with
a clear interest in the perceived importance of their work _ insist
that the lack of a more formal advisory structure in the Bradley
campaign is a problem. And they say a truly smart candidate is
smart enough to know he needs help.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really arrogant and characteristically Bradley,'' said a
Bush adviser. ``The truth is that politics is a team sport. The
quarterback gets the credit, but you still need a defensive line,
and I haven't seen that in Bradley's camp, which is a huge
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Critics have called Bradley glacially slow in responding to
attacks, particularly on his health care plan, leaving Gore's
assertion that it would end up hurting poor people virtually
unchallenged.
</P>
<P>
   And because he chose to disarm unilaterally, when he finally did
fight back, for example by criticizing Gore's complicated history
with tobacco companies, what may have been perfectly legitimate
questions were seen as out of bounds because he had set himself up
as a candidate who was above that kind of give-and-take.
</P>
<P>
   On those and other campaign decisions, it is not that Bradley
listens to no one, but that , on the contrary, he listens to a
great number of people _ and then makes the important calls
himself. It was Bradley who chose child poverty, health care, race
relations and gun control as the central issues in his campaign.
And who, to a surprising degree, mapped out the plans he wanted to
see put in place.
</P>
<P>
   His staff insists that he does not micromanage, and is happy to
leave mechanical, logistical details like booking planes and
deciding which field directors go where to others. Even in this,
though, ``he does like to be keep informed, and will tell us if
we're going the wrong direction,'' said his campaign chairman,
Douglas Berman.
</P>
<P>
   And the list of ways Bradley is in control of his campaign is
staggering.
</P>
<P>
   Back when nobody but Bradley, Berman and a couple of other
Bradley die-hards thought it was possible to raise even a fraction
of the money the campaign has raised, the senator showed how it
could be done, by pulling in people who had not been politically
active before.
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Aronoff, his point person on policy, said that he had
been refining ideas for a health care plan for years and reached
out to hundreds of people.
</P>
<P>
   '`I don't think you're going to see every decision coming back
through him, but on health care _ the cornerstone _ or child
poverty, he takes an active interest. Or improving race relations.
Or key economic and foreign policy decisions.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   David Cutler, a Harvard economics professor considered one of
the chief architects of his health care plan, said, ``I don't
consider myself to be an incredibly important adviser.'' Told that
nobody else seemed to, either, he said, ``I had a sneaking
suspicion that was true.
</P>
<P>
   He's a very intelligent man, so he didn't need the getting up to
speed that a lot of candidates need.''
</P>
<P>
   The association is so loose, he added, that ``I don't think I've
ever actually met him. And I don't know if he's ever made a formal
decision that, `Oh, now you're x adviser.' I found him very
impressive _ and I don't know him well, so it's kind of the same
way I find the pope impressive _ but he listens to a lot of
voices.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Al Garber, a Stanford professor who was one of those ``putting
the details together'' for the basic plan that Bradley wanted said
the most surprising part of the process was the lack of
``dissension'' among those discussing the options. ``Everyone liked
Bill's idea, and it really is his plan,'' he said. ``He
incorporated diverse views and listened to a lot of people, but
within the campaign there was tremendous consensus, and that
probably reflects Bill.''
</P>
<P>
   On political strategy, too, he is also the final arbiter.
</P>
<P>
   And his staff includes a number of people who have been with him
so long that they often reflect the way he thinks. His campaign
chairman, Berman, who met Bradley when he was an adoring high
school senior, on the morning after the Knicks won an NBA
championship, has been with him since his first Senate campaign in
1977. His finance director, Rick Wright, played basketball with him
at Princeton 35 years ago. Ms. Aronoff was his longtime chief of
staff in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Of these, a friend and former aide to Bradley says, ``It would
only be a slight hyperbole to say Doug is the first person he calls
in the morning and the last one he talks to at night. On political
strategy, it's Doug and Bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Berman describes his job this way: ``If I have a role,'' he
said, ``it's being clear and helping people understand the values
that course through the organization as a reflection of Bill.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the proof that Bradley was not too much of a one-man
show was in the campaign's organizing successes: `We filed in 31 of
31 districts in New York, he was first to file in Oklahoma, we
raised twice as much money as the vice president in the fourth
quarter, and more people in California signed up to be delegates
for Bill Bradley than the vice president.''
</P>
<P>
   And Berman suggested that the campaign had, in fact, taken some
recent hits on purpose. When asked about Bradley's confused
response to a question about whether he had voted against flood
relief while in the Senate _ in fact, he had voted for the bill,
but against an amendment, Berman said, ``We never talk about
specific decisions. But Bradley has said, `I want to run a campaign
as an extension of the way I want to govern, to restore trust and
bring back civility.' And if you say that, you have to operate that
way. It's not that at times there's not the impulse to operate at a
different level. But those who elevate tactics, we disagree with.''
</P>
<P>
   To some degree, of course, the Bradley campaign's position that
it is above all that is itself a tactic. Whatever advice Bradley
does get is purposely underplayed by the campaign, which does not
want to be seen as doing much of anything in the usual way.
``Advisers,'' Berman said, ``are never the story.''
</P>
<P>
   And Richard Ravitch, who has reviewed some ideas about housing
and urban development with members of Bradley's staff, suggested
that the status of some of them was still a bit of a mystery _ even
to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where'd you get my name?'' Ravitch asked. Told he was
considered someone Bradley listens to, he said, ``Glad to hear
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
