<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFC-FEATURE21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sapp recycles controversy with quotes
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ For four days, the Tampa Bay Buccaneers and the
St. Louis Rams kept the peace. But the teams that meet Sunday for
the NFC title finally got controversial at midweek.
</P>
<P>
   The main dispute stems from Tampa Bay's Warren Sapp calling St.
Louis coach Dick Vermeil a ``recycled coach,'' among other things,
in the December issue of Sport Magazine. Sapp renewed the issue
when he refused to retract the statements on Vermeil during a
Wednesday night interview on ESPN. It drew the ire of a few St.
Louis players.
</P>
<P>
   Sapp added more fuel to the fire at Tampa Bay's practice on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The St. Louis players ``are the same people who called the NFL
Players Association on their coach (last year) and said their coach
was killing them,'' Sapp said. ``I wasn't the only person saying
anything about him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have some friends on the Rams, and I just took what they had
told me and then made a comment. If they don't like it now, so be
it. (Tell them to) line up Sunday and do something about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, numerous St. Louis players complained about Vermeil's
three-hour practices, demanding conditioning program and extra-long
film sessions.
</P>
<P>
   With problems of last season a distant memory for the Rams, the
St. Louis players are planning on using Sapp's statements this week
as extra motivation.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's fine if they want to do that,'' Sapp said. ``But if
that is what they got to use as a rallying point, then they are in
trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   In another brewing war of words, a television station reported
St. Louis quarterback Kurt Warner as saying, ``The only team that
can beat the Rams is the Rams.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that is how most good teams feel _ that if they
execute their game plan the way they should, they are going to be
tough to stop,'' Tampa Bay safety John Lynch said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel the same way about our defense. The only way we are
going to get beat is if we beat ourselves. I don't see (Warner's
quote) as being a negative or overly cocky, it's just the way good
football teams think about themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Tampa Bay players weren't as understanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, if that is the way they feel _ but they don't want to
overlook us,'' defensive back Ronde Barber said. ``We're a good
football team, too. We have the second-best record in the NFC, and
that shows a lot coming from the NFC Central.
</P>
<P>
   ``If (Warner) wants to say that, then the only team that can
beat Tampa Bay is us, too,'' Barber said. ``Whichever team executes
the best and makes the least amount of turnovers and mistakes on
Sunday is going to win. Talk is cheap; we'll see what happens.'' A
few minutes later, Sapp was asked how the defense plans to stop
Warner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to get in his face, and I want to get on top of him as
many times as I can,'' Sapp said. ``That is going to bode well for
me and our ballclub, but it is going to be a task in itself because
their offensive line is playing well.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-00 2138EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
