<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEM ON PERSONAL BUSINESS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 23) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Assessing Your Skills With an Online Survey &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Recent college graduates and executives in midstream may have
more in common than they know. A new Web site,
www.careervectors.com, is promoting career counseling to people who
are entering the work force for the first time or veteran workers
who may be looking for a change.
</P>
<P>
   Job seekers can fill out a self-assessment survey online that
takes about three hours to complete and costs $69.95. The questions
are designed to determine whether the applicant is, for example, a
physical/biological/scientific type or a
creative/self-expressive/intuitive type. Career Vectors says there
are nine categories that applicants fit into.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site also provides Internet links to job banks and other
career-oriented services.
</P>
<P>
   After applicants finish soul-searching, they submit their
answers and within minutes the software program on which Career
Vectors is based delivers an analysis, including such insights as
``I may become bored with repetition and routine,'' or ``I may not
think things through before taking action.'' The report also
suggests jobs ranging from locksmith to physical anthropologist
that match the applicants' profile.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be strong themes that emerge,'' said Gail Magalife,
chief operating officer for human services at Federation Employment
and Guidance Service, the New York-based organization that
developed Career Vectors.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Magalife said Career Vectors was not meant to take the place
of the human touch. ``Ideally,'' she said, Career Vectors ``is for
someone who can meet with a career counselor in addition.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _Lisa Fickenscher
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
