<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FCC Adopts Hiring Rules For Broadcasting Industry
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Communications Commission adopted new rules intended
to increase job opportunities for minorities and women in the
broadcasting industry, replacing previous guidelines that a federal
appeals court said had unconstitutionally imposed quotas. The new
rules, adopted by a vote of 4-1, are a carefully fashioned effort
by the commission and ts chairman, William Kennard, to retain some
kind of pressure on the broadcasting industry to seek members of
minorities and women as job applicants without violating the
court's 1998 ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Profits Up 16 Percent at General Electric
</P>
<P>
   General Electric said its fourth-quarter profit rose 16 percent,
to $3.09 billion, driven by sales of service contracts at
industrial businesses and advertising at its NBC television
network. Revenue rose 15 percent, to $32.9 billion GE's earnings
were a penny better than the 92 cents expected by Wall Street
analysts, but its shares fell $2.78125, to $145.9375.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Chips Fall Again
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq gains Blue-chip stocks fell while signs of growth at
technology companies helped push the Nasdaq composite index to
another record. The Dow Jones industrial average was down 138.06
points, to 11,351.30. The Nasdaq composite index was up 38.22
points, to 4,189.51. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index declined
10.33 points, to 1,445.57.
</P>
<P>
   President Seeking Tax Change
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton moved to change a tax intended to make sure
that wealthy Americans pay some income taxes but that has become a
fast-growing burden on the middle class, particularly families with
children.
</P>
<P>
   World Bank Sells Notes on Internet
</P>
<P>
   The World Bank marked two firsts with its sale of $3 billion in
three-year notes. It sold them directly to retail investors and
offered them over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent's Profit Down as Forecast
</P>
<P>
   Lucent Technologies said it earned $1.25 billion in its most
recent quarter, less than half of its profit a year earlier, as the
company delivered the disappointing results it had forecast two
weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Vodafone Raises Mannesmann Bid
</P>
<P>
   Vodafone AirTouch said it was prepared to offer a modest
sweetener to its all-stock bid for Mannesmann, now valued at $155
billion, but the German company spurned the overture as ``wholly
inadequate.'' Christopher Gent, Vodafone's chief executive, said
his own stockholders would not countenance a bigger increase.
Vodafone's hostile takeover attempt, the largest ever, was begun on
Nov. 19.
</P>
<P>
   SpliChicago Exchange Urged
</P>
<P>
   Responding to the growing threat of competition from electronic
trading systems, the directors of the Chicago Board of Trade voted
overwhelmingly to split the exchange into two for-profit companies.
The plan must still be approved by its members.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola Forms Units in Europe
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola, grappling to restore its image after product
contamination woes last year, formed 2 units to manage its business
in Europe, Central Europe, Russia and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   GM Profit Better Than Expected
</P>
<P>
   General Motors said it earned $1.15 billion in the fourth
quarter, topping Wall Street's expectations, as its sales increased
3.7 percent, to $46 billion.
</P>
<P>
