<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-HEART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY DISCLOSES MORE BOUTS OF AILMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOUNT PLEASANT, Iowa _ Former Sen. Bill Bradley disclosed
Thursday night that he had suffered four bouts of irregular
heartbeat, a chronic condition known as atrial fibrillation, since
Dec. 10, when he first disclosed that he suffered from the aliment.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, who takes daily medication for the condition, said all
four incidents were brief, with his heartbeat returning to normal
without treatment. Several times he campaigned despite his
fluttering heart, his aides said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is just the nature of the particular situation that, time
to time, its spins out,'' Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   Atrial fibrillation occurs when the heart's upper chambers
contract faster than the lower ones.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Bradley said one incident occurred just after Christmas
when Bradley was on vacation. The others were on Jan. 6, 9 and 16.
They said they lasted as long as 12 hours.
</P>
<P>
   The aides said he had been late in taking his medication before
one incident, but not the others.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley disclosed the incidents after his campaign spokesman was
asked about his heart condition by an ABC reporter Thursday. Asked
why he had not been more forthcoming, Bradley said, ``You don't
want me to go around disclosing every time I flip out for an hour
or two.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he would tell reporters if he needed medical treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said the frequency of the incidents, which he
acknowledged were unusual, was not caused by campaign stress. His
aides also said that Bradley's doctors said he did not need to cut
back his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 10, Bradley canceled an afternoon of campaigning and
went to a hospital after a bout of irregular heart beats.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-00 2148EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
