<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1829 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-INVEST-COLUMN-ART-$AD     01-20 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-COLUMN-ART-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PLAN TO OVERCOME INVESTORS' HOME BIAS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 23) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic of a breakdown of world`s total stock market
capitalization is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By MARK HULBERT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you ask investors how the ``stock market'' did last year,
most of them will think of the Dow Jones industrials or the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index. Sure, a few will remember that
the market contains more than the stocks in these indices.
</P>
<P>
   But it is the rare investor who remembers that there are many
more stocks that trade beyond these shores.
</P>
<P>
   Failing to recognize overseas markets is an enormous oversight,
especially in this era of global markets. According to Morgan
Stanley Capital International, the combined market capitalization
of all United States stocks amounts to less than one-half of the
world's total market value. Still, investors in this country
allocate more than 90 percent of their equity investments to the
stocks of American companies.
</P>
<P>
   Consider what this means to an individual who has invested in
the Vanguard Index 500 fund, this country's most popular index
fund, which is dominated by large-cap growth companies. The fund
represents only three-quarters of the United States market, which
in turn accounts for less than half of the total world market. This
individual may think he is investing in ``the market,'' but when
viewed from a global perspective, he is investing in barely more
than a sector fund.
</P>
<P>
   The average foreign investor overweights his own countries'
stocks to the same extent that American investors do theirs.
Investors in Britain, for example, invest nearly 80 percent of
their equity portfolios in British companies. By contrast, American
investors have less than 1 percent of their equity portfolios
invested in British stocks.
</P>
<P>
   This tendency of investors to favor their own country's
securities is so pronounced and so universal that researchers have
given a name to it: home bias.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, when you think about it, home bias should not be so
pronounced. After all, one suspects that the British investor wants
to maximize returns just as much as the American one does. Why
then, should his or her portfolio be so very different?
</P>
<P>
   Hypotheses for why home bias exists to the degree it does have
focused for years on structural factors, such as the fact that
investing outside one's country entails higher currency risk and
transaction costs.
</P>
<P>
   But after examining each of these factors in detail, most
researchers have concluded that these factors can at best explain
only a small portion of investors' home bias. Many now believe that
investor psychology is the major factor.
</P>
<P>
   And this suggests that overcoming home bias will not be easy.
</P>
<P>
   It would be one thing if investors preferred domestic equities
even when they thought that foreign equities would do better: that
would just be a case of rooting for the home team. But it appears
to run deeper than that.
</P>
<P>
   Home bias is so ingrained in investors' psyches that it clouds
their judgments _ causing American investors to be overly
optimistic about United States stocks while leading foreign
investors to be overly optimistic about their countries' markets.
</P>
<P>
   Two British academics _ Norman Strong, a professor of accounting
and finance at the University of Manchester, and Xinzhong Xu, a
senior lecturer in finance at Lancaster University _ recently
completed a survey of fund managers in four parts of the world: the
United States, Britain, Continental Europe and Japan. Specifically,
they tallied the managers' 12-month forecasts for United States
stocks, between October 1995 and June 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The results: There were far more bulls than bears among United
States fund managers over that period. But among fund managers in
the other parts of the world, there were far more bears than bulls.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, when these professors tallied fund managers'
12-month forecasts for stocks in Britain, Continental Europe and
Japan, the opposite trend emerged. In each case, United States fund
managers were far more pessimistic than those regions' domestic
managers.
</P>
<P>
   So, how can an investor hope to combat home bias, if fund
managers cannot? I propose a solution that may appear radical. All
other things being equal, an investor's stock portfolio should be
divided among the world's markets based upon each country's share
of global stock market capitalization.
</P>
<P>
   An investor would then deviate from that allocation only when he
or she had reason to believe that a particular market would do much
better or worse than average, after taking into account currency
risk and the high transaction costs of investing foreign markets.
</P>
<P>
   No, this will not overcome home bias altogether, but it would
focus attention on how bullish an investor ought to be to justify a
major overweighting in domestic stocks. And while my suggestion may
seem like heresy to those financial advisers who routinely advocate
a cap of 10 percent or 15 percent on investors' foreign exposure,
at root it simply suggests using some common sense: An investor
should be able to justify the geographical diversification of his
or her stock portfolio. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mark Hulbert is editor of The Hulbert Financial Digest, a
newsletter based in Annandale, Va. His column on investment
strategies appears every other week. E-mail:
strategy(AT)nytimes.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-00 2149EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
