<HEADER>
A1830 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-LABOR-CORRUPTION-INSU     01-20 0192
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABOR-CORRUPTION-INSURANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW UNIONS INSURE AGAINST THEFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (With LABOR-CORRUPTION)  
(lh) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The losses claimed by the American Federation of State, County
and Municipal Employees are covered by a form of insurance often
referred to as a fidelity bond.
</P>
<P>
   With this kind of coverage, widely bought by corporations and
nonprofit organizations like unions and pension plans, the
organization is reimbursed for theft or embezzlement by officials
and employees.
</P>
<P>
   Premium calculations are based on the type of business _
gambling casinos, for example, are considered riskier and thus more
expensive to insure than consulting firms _ plus the number of
employees and workplaces, said Fred Podolsky, a senior vice
president at Willis Corp., one of the nation's largest insurance
brokers.
</P>
<P>
   To collect from an insurance company, an organization submits
evidence of a loss. The insurance company investigates and, once
the loss is confirmed, pays the loss. Often, determining the exact
amount of the loss is difficult, leading to negotiations with the
insurance company on a settlement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-00 2149EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
