<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BUCS-NOTES21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Leaving comfort of home
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ There is no place like home, but the Tampa Bay
Buccaneers will be forced to leave it today.
</P>
<P>
   The Buccaneers, winners of eight in a row at home, are scheduled
to fly to St. Louis around 3 p.m. today. Rather than the
traditional routine of leaving from the team headquarters directly
to the airport, special events are planned.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay coaches and players will depart on buses from Raymond
James Stadium to the hollering and cheers of the Tampa Bay fans at
2 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Once arriving in St. Louis, the Bucs will have the rest of today
off. Curfew will be at 1 a.m. Coach Tony Dungy said the team will
have meetings and do a normal walk-through of the Trans World Dome
on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   SILENCE OF SAPP
</P>
<P>
   You have a better chance of winning the lottery than catching
Tampa Bay's Warren Sapp at a loss for words. But he turned quiet
when reporters on Thursday brought up the subject of his right
hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   Sapp injured the hamstring during the victory over the Redskins
last Saturday and he left practice early in obvious pain on
Wednesday. He appeared to be back at full strength during
Thursday's drills.
</P>
<P>
   When asked ae specifics of the injury on Thursday, Sapp
quickly replied, ``There is no such thing.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in franchise history, Dungy had more to say
about a topic than Sapp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Warren is going to be fine,'' Dungy said. ``He practiced and
made it through the whole day fine. So we don't anticipate any
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Sapp could be downplaying the injury so his hamstring won't be a
constant target for St. Louis offensive linemen.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive end Brad Culpepper also left practice early this week,
but it was planned. His practice time has been limited since
injuring a foot Jan. 2.
</P>
<P>
   OPERATION HEADSTART
</P>
<P>
   The Bucs and the Rams have not played since the 1994 season,
when the Rams were still located in Los Angeles. The unfamiliarity
between the two teams has resulted in endless hours of studying
film for both both coaching staffs.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay may have a slight advantage in preparation. In last
week's NFC divisionals, the Bucs defeated the Redskins. Mike Martz
was the offensive coordinator for Washington during the 1997-98
season before joining the Rams in a similar capacity this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was big for us to beat Washington last week because there
are a lot of similarities between the offenses of the Redskins and
Rams,'' Tampa Bay safety John Lynch said. ``And from watching film,
you can see there was a lot of carryover from Washington to St.
Louis (by Martz). Now there are a lot of new wrinkles in his
offense at St. Louis, but at least we had a good headstart by
facing Washington last week.''
</P>
<P>
   HANDLING THE HOOPLA
</P>
<P>
   It is not hard to tell that Tampa Bay has not been in the NFC
Championship Game in 20 years. With the exception of Sapp, the
players seem overwhelmed by the media attention. Dungy even had to
stand on a stool at one of his news conferences so he could be seen
by the hordes of video cameras. ``I think our guys know the urgency
and magnitude of the situation,'' Dungy said. ``It's a special time
and, with everything going on media-wise, you know it is a big
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
