<SLUG> BC-FBN-JAGS-NOTES21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Don't key too much on Kearse
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ It might be worth heeding the words of Leon
Searcy, the Jacksonville offensive tackle, who cautions against
getting too freaked out about ``The Freak.''
</P>
<P>
   If you concern your offensive scheme too much with neutralizing
Tennessee defensive end Jevon Kearse, you just might get
blindsided.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been saying all week, you've got to treat `The Freak'
like Michael Jordan,'' Searcy said. ``Everybody used to rally
around stopping Jordan. You'd try to keep Jordan from scoring 50 or
60 points and then the rest of the guys would beat you.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got other guys on that team that make plays, too _
(defensive linemen) Josh Evans, Henry Ford and Kenny Holmes and
(strong safety) Blaine Bishop. The Jordan factor comes into effect
when you're talking about `The Freak.'''
</P>
<P>
   Not to mention the redemption factor. Searcy said the second
loss to Tennessee, 41-14 in Week 15, was a true ``butt-kicking.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Since I've been playing football,'' the former Steeler said,
``I've never been handed to the way we were handed to in Tennessee.
But we've got a chance to redeem ourselves Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   BRUNELL KEEPS IMPROVING
</P>
<P>
   Jaguars quarterback Mark Brunell is, in coach Tom Coughlin's
opinion, ``much better than he was last week'' in moving on his
previously injured left knee. ``I'm not going to say he's 100
percent, but maybe 85. ... This will be his fourth week of
recovery. Most of the time our MCLs (injuries to medial collateral
ligaments) have come back in four weeks.'' ... Jaguars owner Wayne
Weaver said the only two other people besides Coughlin on his final
head coaching interview list five years ago were Tony Dungy, now
the Tampa Bay head coach, then an assistant at Kansas City, and
Mike Shanahan, who was hired by Denver. ... Coughlin has termed
practices ``spirited, with lots of energy.'' He will reduce
repetitions today. ... Coughlin on the rhetoric between team sites:
``The game will be decided on the field, not by verbalization.''
... Speaking about the extra attention from the national media and
its accompanying pressure, ex-Titan Gary Walker said, ``With or
without the media, the game will be played.'' ... Coughlin, on the
extra media attention: ``At this time of the year, we've earned
this right. We're fortunate to be in this position to have the
national media here. I think it's a very positive sign. It's good
for our city. It's good for our team. You learn to deal with it,
like anything else in this game. Hopefully, the experience of
having been there before (in a 20-6 loss to New England in the 1996
AFC title game) will help.''
</P>
<P>
   DOUBLE TROUBLE
</P>
<P>
   Jaguars wide receiver Keenan McCardell is prepared to see a
Titans defense that double-teams both him and Jimmy Smith. For
Smith, it's almost a certainty. ``We're going to have to go out
there and attack,'' McCardell said. ``We're going to have to make
the plays in the double-teams. We're going to have to make plays,
period.'' ... Walker says that with a third game against his former
Titans approaching, it has grown stale to ask about his old
situation. ``That Tennessee stuff is behind me,'' he said. ``Our
goal is to get to the Super Bowl. Regardless of who you have to
play to get there, you have to play.'' ... Lower 50-yard line AFC
Championship seats with a face value of $175 are being scalped in
the Jacksonville area for as much as $750.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
