<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RAMS-NOTES21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wounded Wilkins will kick
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ The one question mark for the Rams this week _ the
kicking game _ has been settled. Sorry, Nick Lowery. Jeff Wilkins
will do the placekicking after all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going,'' said Wilkins, who will kick in Sunday's NFC
Championship Game despite the painful patella tendinitis in his
left knee. Wilkins spoke after kicking in practice Thursday. He
experienced some pain but nothing like earlier in the week, so
Wilkins will play against Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurts and it's going to hurt and I've accepted that,''
Wilkins said.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Vermeil has accepted that Wilkins, who'll need postseason
surgery to clean out the knee and correct the condition that's
bothered him on and off for two years, can kick effectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``His leg bothered him (Thursday) but he kicked well, firmly and
accurately,'' said the head coach. ``As of right now, he'll be our
kicker, and that's a relief. He hit some 50-yarders here, so I
think he'll have the range.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilkins was inconsistent this season, hitting on 20 of 28
attempts. He aggravated the injury on last Sunday's opening kickoff
and later missed a 42-yard field goal attempt against Minnesota.
Vermeil brought in three kickers to work out Tuesday and was
prepared to go with Lowery, 43, who hasn't kicked in a game since
retiring three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   GREEN, NOT WITH ENVY
</P>
<P>
   Trent Green can only wonder, what if? The St. Louis native
signed a four-year, $16 million free-agent contract last February
with his hometown Rams and was still working under Mike Martz, his
quarterback coach in Washington and now the Rams' offensive
coordinator. But after tearing up his knee in the third preseason
game, Green has had to watch Kurt Warner's record-setting success
this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time of the injury, I was playing at the highest level
I've ever played,'' said Green, who was 28-for-32 (87.5 percent)
for 406 yards, two touchdowns and a quarterback rating of 126.6.
``Whether I'd be able to put up the numbers Kurt has, who's to say?
Maybe I put up better, maybe I don't. Those are all
hypotheticals.''
</P>
<P>
   LYLE EAGER TO PLAY
</P>
<P>
   After missing the past eight games with a bruised nerve in his
neck and left shoulder area, free safety Keith Lyle said he is
ready, and eager, to return Sunday. Vermeil isn't so sure. Lyle has
been practicing with the second-team secondary and in nickel
situations, but Vermeil said, ``He has maybe a little better chance
of being able to play this week than last but I don't know how much
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Ex-Falcon Devin Bush has played well in Lyle's absence. But from
the start of the 1995 season through '98, Lyle led the NFL in
interceptions with 23. He's eager to play against the Bucs because
he lives in Tampa in the offseason. And to be just a win away from
the Super Bowl is ``Unbelievable. I've been here six years. Two
cities. Three head coaches. Five defensive coordinators. And I live
in Tampa. So it's exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   ETC.
</P>
<P>
   Vermeil on the Bucs' defensive front: ``To me, they've got four
D'Marco Farr's (the Rams' Pro Bowl defensive tackle). Four
explosively quick defensive linemen. And, of course, they've got
Warren Sapp (the NFL Defensive Player of the Year). They're
extremely quick off the ball, probably the quickest front we've
faced all year.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
