<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Attentive Del Greco on target
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ Kicker Al Del Greco was as valuable for his
eagle eye as his accurate foot last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The AFC Player of the Week after his four field goals against
Indianapolis, he also made an impact on a kick return when he
wasn't on the field. Del Greco saw the Colts' Terrence Wilkins step
out of bounds on a return to the Titans' 4. After an instant replay
review, officials brought it back 60 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just watch,'' said Del Greco, who has kicked around the
league for 16 years, the last nine with the Oilers/Titans. ``I just
happened to be standing right where he stepped out. I always kind
of look at stuff like that just in case. I don't know how the refs
missed it, but they did.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've talked about this team being a team of destiny, with the
Music City Miracle. If that return happens on their sideline, it
never gets reviewed. Things are working in our favor. Hopefully
that'll continue for two more weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Del Greco said teammates are telling him, ``Four more field
goals!''
</P>
<P>
   ``I say, four extra points,'' he said. ``Twenty-eight points
would be a heckuva lot easier to win with than 12.''
</P>
<P>
   PLAYING CATCH-UP
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of the Miracle, Kevin Dyson is best known for scoring
the 75-yard touchdown after Frank Wycheck lateraled the ball to him
on a desperation kickoff return against Buffalo in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   In his first full season as a starting wide receiver, Dyson had
career highs in receptions (54), yards receiving (658) and
touchdowns (4). If you compare his stats with someone like
Minnesota's Randy Moss, who could blame him for wanting to play on
a pass-happy offense?
</P>
<P>
   ``What receiver wouldn't want the ball 12 times a game?'' Dyson
asked. ``But I'm 15-3, I'm in the AFC Championship Game. They're
not in the NFC Championship Game. It doesn't bother me that much.
I'm still playing.''
</P>
<P>
   THE CHARGERS' LOSS ...
</P>
<P>
   Last year he was playing for the University of Georgia. This
year, Titans tight end Larry Brown wasn't sure where he'd be.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't drafted after lackluster workouts, so he signed as a
free agent with San Diego and went to two mini-camps. When he got
to the airport in Atlanta to pick up his ticket to California in
late July, ``They told me the ticket hadn't been paid for,'' Brown
said. ``I thought I'd pay for it, and when I got there they'd
reimburse me.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he found out he'd been cut. Tennessee picked him up,
and he has played in seven games, primarily on special teams.
However, with the injury to Mike Roan, he has moved up to
second-string tight end. FEAR NOT A FACTOR
</P>
<P>
   Wycheck said the Titans, who have won four of the five games
they've played in Jacksonville's Alltel Stadium, really enjoy it by
virtue of ``just the fact that we're not afraid,'' he said. ``You
know, some people go in there intimidated to go against
Jacksonville at their place, but we're not.''
</P>
<P>
   TITAN TOWN
</P>
<P>
   Defensive back Denard Walker said everybody's talking about the
Titans. ``The city has just exploded,'' he said. ``Everywhere you
go, you see the Tennessee Titans logo, the Titans T-shirts, people
wearing the jerseys.''
</P>
<P>
   If the team goes to the Super Bowl, ``I think this will just
blow the city up,'' he said, ``and it would make Nashville the
Mecca of the NFL instead of saying they're just a little town that
just got a team. It'd be a great boost for all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
