<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-BELICHICK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON JETS' FRONT, IT'S STILL TALK, TALK, TALK, AND PLEASE STAY TUNED
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The entwined coaching careers of Bill Parcells and Bill
Belichick will very likely be resolved Friday.
</P>
<P>
   National Football League Commissioner Paul Tagliabue, who was
expected to make a ruling Thursday, is leaving Saturday morning for
the NFC championship game in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Parcells had his third face-to-face meeting over the
last nine days Thursday with the Jets' new owner, Robert Wood
Johnson IV. The meeting was held at an undisclosed location away
from the club headquarters in Hempstead, N.Y., a Jets spokesman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson wants Parcells to return as coach, or at least take a
major role in running the team.
</P>
<P>
   If Johnson persuades him to return as coach, Parcells may not
want the responsibility of running the entire football operation.
The Jets would then be in the market for someone such as the
respected Tom Donahoe, a former director of football operations for
the Steelers.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick quit two weeks ago as the Jets' coach after holding
the post for a day. He said his contract was invalid and that he
wanted to be free to coach elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Many observers believe Tagliabue will reiterate the opinion he
made the day after Belichick quit that he thought the contract was
valid.
</P>
<P>
   At just about the same time that the Jets elevated Belichick to
succeed Parcells, the Patriots, not knowing of the move, had asked
for permission to interview Belichick as their coach and general
manager.
</P>
<P>
   A New England Patriots spokesman, meanwhile, said Thursday that
he was not aware of any contact between the commissioner's office
and Robert K. Kraft, the Patriots' owner. Since then, New England
has interviewed four head-coaching candidates, but none for the
dual roles. Thus, it appears the Patriots' job is waiting for
Belichick when his future is decided.
</P>
<P>
   If Belichick's contract is ruled valid by Tagliabue, then the
Patriots would have to compensate the Jets if the team was willing
to let Belichick go. Tagliabue would not get involved in that
discussion between the teams unless both sides asked him to.
</P>
<P>
   If Parcells is leaning toward a return to the sideline, he has
not let on. Several assistants said this week that they had not
heard from him, but that Parcells had made it clear he was finished
with coaching. Most of the Jets' assistants, who were in Mobile,
Ala., Thursday for Senior Bowl week, headed back to New York. If
allowed to leave, Belichick would likely want some assistants to go
with him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-00 2154EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
