<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERCEDES E430 -- A CAR TO BELIEVE IN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I have just finished driving the Mercedes Benz E430 and I am
looking back more than 25 years to one of the first newspaper
stories I ever wrote, for the National Observer, and I remember it
involved a court ruling on an automobile.
</P>
<P>
   A man had purchased a brand new car with a faulty transmission _
it turned out it had been in a flood _ and despite repeated
attempts by the dealership to fix it, it had never run right. He
asked for a new car. A New Hampshire judge named Charles Douglas
ruled he should have one because, as I recall, Douglas said that a
new car is worth more than the sum of its parts.
</P>
<P>
   When you purchase a new car, he ruled, you are buying more than
just parts in good working order. You are also buying faith in that
automobile, and if you don't have that faith, you've been sold a
lemon. Made sense to me _ especially the ``sum of its parts'' bit.
</P>
<P>
   Don't get me wrong. The E430 is no lemon, and if I owned one,
I'd have complete faith in it.
</P>
<P>
   But back to the sum of its parts: It is solid, comfortable,
fast, safe, quiet on the road, and has the Mercedes record of
remarkable reliability. Problem is, it's no fun to drive. But that
may be no problem for some.
</P>
<P>
   You could hurtle from Caribou, Maine, to Carmel, Calif., in this
rig and never once feel the road. On the other hand, that's the way
some folks like to travel, so if long and effortless trips are your
thing, this is the car for you.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps I got spoiled before I drove the E430. I drove the E55 _
hot-rod version of the same car. Tons of power, great suspension
for corners, meant to help executives who fear kidnappings get away
quickly when they have to.
</P>
<P>
   Not every car has to be the E55, of course. But at nearly
$60,000, I'd like at least some opportunity for adventure. Instead,
I get a cruise _ much like I'd get sitting on my couch watching the
desert wash toward me on a travel show beamed on DVD.
</P>
<P>
   It is a most comfortable car.
</P>
<P>
   Leather seats so wide you wonder where the ottoman is. Firm
leather seats that hold up your thighs, support your back, grip you
on the sides. In the rear, legroom is expansive.
</P>
<P>
   As is typical in a Mercedes, ergonomics are crisp and right at
hand. Dials and buttons may be a bit small, but once you learn
where everything is, it's like typing.
</P>
<P>
   This is a car that approaches two tons in curb weight, yet it
has plenty of power to haul that load. It's got a 275-horsepower V8
with an unusual three-valves-per-cylinder design _ two intake, one
exhaust _ and two sparkplugs per cylinder. It got just over 19
miles per gallon _ pretty respectable for a V8 _ in a week of
driving.
</P>
<P>
   It produces smooth acceleration, even at higher speeds,
accompanied by a throaty rumble.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunatley, the five-speed automatic had a noticeable
shift-up lag when the gas was stomped. The driver-adaptive feature
that supposedly puts you in command didn't add much spark to the
performance.
</P>
<P>
   But if you're running Caribou to Carmel and want only a quiet,
smooth ride without the bother of driving too much, that won't
matter to you. In fact, it may be perfect.
</P>
<P>
   But if you want to make that run and push the car a bit _ get
off the straights and onto some twisting roads _ then it's less
than perfect. And that's surprising, suspension-wise.
</P>
<P>
   It's got upper and lower A-arms up front, complemented by coil
springs, tube shocks, and anti-roll bar. In the rear, you get a
multi-link setup with coil springs, tube shocks, and anti-roll bar.
</P>
<P>
   That's all supported by an automatic slip control system that
senses drive-wheel slip and uses braking or engine power to get
things back under control. That's aided by an electronic stability
program that senses what the driver is trying to do _ it pays
attention to where you are steering and how you are using your
brakes _ and, again, uses engine and brakes to make up for your
mistakes. It's also got a front/rear torque split called 4MATIC
all-wheel drive (this in a rear-wheel-drive car) that incorporates
all of the above when necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Now that is high tech, and that is complicated, and that all
sounds good.
</P>
<P>
   Why then, I ask myself, does this rig feel boaty in the corners?
</P>
<P>
   I don't mean boaty as in you're about to lose control because of
lateral sway and a nose dive to the outside front wheel. Or even
boaty as in riding on dad's lap in the old Buick on a twisty
country road.
</P>
<P>
   I do mean a floating sensation, a lateral, gentle, rock and roll
that feels more lumbering luxury sedan than sport sedan, and since
so many new cars have managed to put sport performance into luxury
sedan, I don't know how Mercedes missed on this one.
</P>
<P>
   Performance-wise, I'd rate the Audi A6 and the Jaguar S-type as
better. I may even put the Lincoln LS _ at almost half the price _
in the same class.
</P>
<P>
   Is this a bad car? Of course not.
</P>
<P>
   For the right person and for the right reasons, this is a
wonderful car.
</P>
<P>
   Caribou-Carmel in total comfort? Go for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh Lawd, wontcha buy me, a MER-CAY-DEEZ-BENZ . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Janis Joplin sang that.
</P>
<P>
   I remember a picture of her behind the wheel _ of a Porsche.
</P>
<P>
   Nice Touches:
</P>
<P>
   --The placement for front-seat adjustments _ bottom, sides,
headrest _ on the door where you can see them, as opposed to down
on the side of the seat, where you end up groping.
</P>
<P>
   Annoyances:
</P>
<P>
   --The small exterior mirrors. If they're not positioned just so,
you get blocked out.
</P>
<P>
   --The clock _ left side of main display panel _ right where only
the driver can see it. What time is it, Dad?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
THE NUMBERS &QL; 
 &QL; 
