<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DETROIT SHOWS OFF ITS CONCEPT VEHICLES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It used to be that concept cars were Jetson-like flights of
fancy: fun to look at but unlikely to ever be produced. That's
changed, as this year's North American International Auto Show
illustrated.
</P>
<P>
   Vehicles that were concepts just a short time ago were unveiled
in Detroit this week as production models. Concepts on display
appeared well-targeted and developed with future production in
mind.
</P>
<P>
   These are boom days in the auto industry, with shared platforms
galore helping to make the types of cars and trucks and SUVs being
built a seemingly endless array.
</P>
<P>
   Companies are getting ever more power out of cleaner, regular
gasoline engines. Companies , notably Ford at this show, are also
looking to appear ``greener'' with a range of environmentally
friendly offerings.
</P>
<P>
   But don't think that powerful cars, trucks, and SUVs are losing
their popularity. For those of you who hate SUVs and trucks, the
news from Detroit is not good: They are flourishing as ever more
manufacturers offer them up.
</P>
<P>
   Some highlights of this year's show:
</P>
<P>
   --Acura rolled out the MD-X, a V6 SUV that clearly has Mercedes
and Lexus SUVs in its sights. Even Porsche has an SUV in the works,
due for the 2002 model year.
</P>
<P>
   --Ford caught attention on the SUV front with two products.
First was the anticipated Escape, a small SUV meant to compete with
Toyota's RAV4 and the Honda CR-V. The company also quietly, with no
formal presentation, dropped a rig called the Equator on the show
floor. Very Hummer-like in its wide stance and rugged, high-box
silhouette.
</P>
<P>
   --Toyota, as had long been expected, showed off its new SUV _
the Sequoia. It's built on the same platform as the critically
acclaimed Tundra pickup truck and will have the same smooth,
powerful V8 engine. With the RAV4 getting a makeover that makes it
a bit bigger, I have to wonder if the 4Runner's days are numbered,
pinched between the Sequoia and the RAV4.
</P>
<P>
   --Hummer _ now being built by GM _ matched Ford with a smaller,
less-military version of the big beast, the H2. Softer corners, not
quite as big, definitely less eclectic than the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   --DaimlerChrysler, saying it was aimed at boulder and boulevard,
offered the Jeep Varsity with a distinct Jeep grille, a wide body,
and a profile that looks like an old Volkswagen Thing on steroids.
</P>
<P>
   News on the pickup-truck front was equally rich as vehicles that
seem part truck/part SUV continue to sprout like weeds.
</P>
<P>
   --Dodge unveiled its MAXXcab, a cab-forward, four-door pickup
with a plush, SUV-like interior and a reasonably good-sized bed at
the back.
</P>
<P>
   --Perhaps the biggest surprise in pickup trucks came from
Volkswagen, which showed its Advanced Activity Concept, an
all-wheel-drive, turbocharged V10 diesel with a short bed.
</P>
<P>
   --Chevrolet added to the ``is-it-a-truck-or-something-else''
movement with two offerings: the Avalanche, an SUV with a bed, and
the SSR, a wild-looking pickup that may also be a sports car.
</P>
<P>
   In the world of minivans it was a relatively quiet show with one
exception:
</P>
<P>
   --Chrysler, still top dog but having lost some market share,
looked to recoup by adding more powerful engines to its lineup and
offering such features as power tailgates, power sliding doors, and
adjustable foot pedals.
</P>
<P>
   And while Chrysler was making this move in the sedate world of
minivans, it also showed a concept car that we can only hope it
will build:
</P>
<P>
   --The Chrysler 300 Hemi, a sleek piece of machinery evocative of
an Aston Martin or a Jaguar. It's a four-seater with about 350
horsepower and 350 lbs.-ft. of torque. Beautiful possibility in a
four-passenger convertible.
</P>
<P>
   And droptops continue to flourish:
</P>
<P>
   --Audi showed its TT roadster; the Honda S2000 and the Toyota
MR2 Spyder continued to draw crowds, even though photographs of
them had long ago made the rounds in all the auto magazines.
</P>
<P>
   --But the two-seater roadster that got the most attention came
from Jaguar, which unveiled an F-Type that is small for a Jag, but
promises plenty of power if they build it: either the AJ-V6 with
240 horsepower from the S-Type, or a 300-horse supercharged version
of that engine.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of unveiling power and size, Ford took a more subtle, if
very broad, approach to its future.
</P>
<P>
   They've hooked up with Yahoo to get Ford owners on the Net. The
Internet, said one official, is the moving assembly line of the
21st century. To get consumers there, Ford offered its Think series
of products: Think City, a small electric car; Think Neighbor, a
jazzed-up golf cart that should sell in retirement communities; and
Think electric bicycles.
</P>
<P>
   --In the race to be green, Ford and GM went head-to-head, with
Ford showing the Prodigy, a Taurus-sized five-passenger sedan that
uses a diesel engine/electric motor hybrid to achieve 80 miles per
gallon. It also showed the Think Focus, based on the
gasoline-powered car of the same name, but this one is a fuel-cell
concept. GM unveiled its Precept, a hydrogen fuel-cell sedan that
could well be part of the long-term solution to ending dependency
on gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   --And finally, in what was certainly the most futuristic
unveiling, Ford displayed three boxy vehicles _ coupe, wagon, small
pickup _ called 24.7, the latter meaning these are vehicles from
which you can be linked to the outside world around the clock. They
offer voice-activated controls, Internet access, even stock
updates. It was truly a case of what's inside being far more
important than the vehicle that enclosed it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Royal Ford's e-mail address is ford(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
