<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-G7-JAPAN-MEET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUP OF 7 GEARS UP FOR AN EXPECTED NONEVENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The meeting here this weekend of the men who chart the
financial and economic policies of the Group of Seven
industrialized nations may turn out to be a nonevent.
</P>
<P>
   At least, that's what their Japanese hosts are hoping.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with the last two years, the global economy is in a
relatively fortunate state. Europe is enjoying a strong recovery,
the Asian economies have rebounded from crisis to post impressively
high growth rates, and the U.S. economy continues to defy the
naysayers.
</P>
<P>
   Even Japan, recently treated as the naughty child of the
international economy, is feeling rather prosperous. The economy
appears to have bottomed out for now, and criticism from the United
States is likely to be subdued, thanks to a hefty package of
pump-priming measures Japan approved last fall and followed up with
a generous budget proposal for the coming fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   ``In general the global economic situation has improved, so we
may not have difficult or _ how shall I say it? _ adversarial
discussions this time,'' said Haruhiko Kuroda, vice minister of
finance for international affairs at the Ministry of Finance.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the Japanese may pay a high price for harmony. The
advance teams that have been working to hammer out language for the
communique that will be issued at the end of the meeting have
failed to reach an agreement on a statement about foreign exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese have been pushing for a reiteration of the
statement issued after the last G-7 meeting in September, when the
yen's rapid appreciation was perceived as a threat to the feeble
economic recovery here. The yen soared to a high of 124.32 against
the dollar last year, and stands now at 105.29 to the dollar. ``We
shared Japan's concern about the potential impact of the yen's
appreciation for the Japanese economy and the world economy,'' that
statement said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the rise of the yen has abated somewhat since then,
Japanese officials are still concerned that a failure to
acknowledge some concern about its level will lead to a renewed
effort by traders and speculators to increase the value of the
currency.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tricky thing,'' said one senior official at the
Ministry of Finance. ``If the market expects there to be some
strong language on exchange rates and that doesn't happen and there
is disappointment, the reaction could be to force an appreciation
of the yen.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Europeans are pushing hard to exclude any mention of
exchange rates in the statement this time, fearing that would turn
attention to what many regard as the weakness of the euro, which
now stands at 1.0166 to the dollar. Some in the U.S. and Japanese
contingents suspect that the Europeans are quietly fostering a
weaker euro to avoid more painful economic changes.
</P>
<P>
   Those who have been trying to work out the language of the final
ministerial statement are still wide apart on the issue, with the
Japanese pushing for strong language on exchange rates or at least
the yen and the Europeans arguing for no mention of exchange rates
at all.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans are in the middle, and may agree to make at least
a nod toward Japan's concerns. In exchange, they would expect yet
another promise from Japan to continue to work hard to encourage
domestic consumption and to stop flirting with the notion of
raising interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. delegation, too, is piqued at Europe's seeming lack of
concern over the value of the euro and may use Japan's concerns as
leverage to gain a compromise.
</P>
<P>
   But many think a statement does not matter one way or the other,
since the Group of Seven is not likely to back its words up with
action. ``There's a lot of talk about whether the G-7 communique
will include any expression of concern over a strong yen, as it did
in September,'' Marshall Gittler, a currency strategist at the Bank
of America, wrote in a report Thursday. ``We expect that it will,
but we don't think it matters because we don't expect the G-7 to
act on those concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   As various Bank of Japan officials have pointed out, the
stronger yen has not wreaked the havoc that many predicted it
would. Japanese companies have managed to post profits despite the
yen's higher value, and corporate sentiment continues to improve.
</P>
<P>
   The ministers will also discuss Russia's economic situation,
although they are not likely to come to any conclusion about
whether the International Monetary Fund should resume its lending.
U.S. concerns about Russia's role in the war in Chechnya and the
interim nature of the current Russian government are hurdles most
consider too high to surmount.
</P>
<P>
   Jockeying to promote various candidates to replace Michel
Camdessus as head of the IMF is likely to generate considerable
interest, although the topic is not part of the agenda. ``Formally,
of course, the subject is not up for discussion,'' Kuroda said.
``Anyway, with so many potential candidates among the participants
in the meeting, how can we discuss it except in the corridors?''
</P>
<P>
   Japan will be pushing its dark-horse candidate, Dr. Eisuke
Sakakibara, the outspoken former occupant of Kuroda's office. He is
considered a long shot, but Japan is still lining up support for
him from its Asian neighbors and others.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Ministry of Finance acknowledge that if the
fund's European shareholders stay united, a European candidate will
be unbeatable since those countries control more than 30 percent of
the voting shares.
</P>
<P>
   But the Japanese have taken heart in the European failure thus
far to coalesce around a candidate, in spite of the stepped-up
lobbying efforts by the Germans to promote Caio Koch-Weser, a
senior bureaucrat in that country's finance ministry.
</P>
<P>
   The post has traditionally gone to a European, but the Japanese
are pushing against convention. ``We have significant support for
Sakakibara, and we will not be embarrassed to offer him as a
candidate,'' one Finance Ministry official said. ``It's very
important to make the point that this is not a decision that is
only to be made by the Europeans.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
