<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE'S LEAD GROWS; FRIEDAN ENDORSES BRADLEY; FORBES ON ATTACK;
STAGING A COMEBACK 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GORE'S LEAD GROWS
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore's lead over former Sen. Bill Bradley in
New Hampshire is growing, though it is still within the margin of
sampling error, the latest American Research Group tracking poll
found. A survey of 600 likely Democratic primary voters from Monday
to Thursday found 46 percent favored Gore and 40 percent favored
Bradley. The margin of error was 4 percentage points. A poll that
had been taken from Sunday to Tuesday had found Gore with 2 percent
less support and Bradley with 2 percent more.
</P>
<P>
   FRIEDAN ENDORSES BRADLEY
</P>
<P>
   Betty Friedan, the feminist author and a founder of the National
Organization for Women, endorsed former Sen. Bill Bradley for
president Thursday. Among women, Bradley is trailing Vice President
Al Gore by a wide margin, polls show.
</P>
<P>
   FORBES ON ATTACK
</P>
<P>
   Steve Forbes said Thursday that his two leading Republican
opponents, Sen. John McCain and Gov. George W. Bush, ``have become
what you might call the timid twins on tax cuts.'' Campaigning in
Iowa, Forbes said he would actively fight against abortion, and in
prepared remarks given to reporters that he did not deliver he
said: ``On the issue of life, Governor Bush and Senator McCain are
pacifists. When it comes to life, we can't afford a pacifist in the
White House.''
</P>
<P>
   STAGING A COMEBACK
</P>
<P>
   Former Rep. Maria Cantwell, a Democrat who became a high-tech
multimillionaire after being voted out of office in the 1994
Republican surge, has announced that she will seek the Democratic
nomination for senator in Washington. She will face the state's
insurance commissioner, Deborah Senn, in the September primary for
the right to take on Sen. Slade Gorton, a Republican.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-00 2202EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000120.0363 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 22:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1842 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-JACKSONVILLE-TAYL     01-20 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JACKSONVILLE-TAYLOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAYLOR IS GRANDMA'S NOT-SO-LITTLE BOY 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ Nearly 11 years ago, when Fred Taylor was
13, his uncle, his grandfather and his grandmother left from his
hometown of Belle Glade, Fla., to drive to nearby West Palm Beach.
Taylor was too young to remember why they left and exactly where
they were going, but he remembers the story and that they left in a
black Beretta. The tragedy and the glory in it remain fresh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they were going to visit my mom,'' said Taylor, the
Jacksonville Jaguars' running back ``They drove down the highway
and ran into a deep canal full of water. My uncle got out and swam
to shore. A truck driver passed by and saw the accident. He jumped
in and saved my grandmother, pulling her to shore, because she
could not swim. My grandfather must have been pinned under the car.
He never made it; he drowned.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor grew up fond of the uncle, Eddie Lusane. His grandfather,
Earthell Allen, was ``a man who could do anything well.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to play together,'' Taylor said. ``He was the
Incredible Hulk, and I was Spiderman. I remember the hot Florida
days growing up with him with air conditioners that didn't always
work so well and on the cool nights using kerosene heaters. It was
rough sometimes. I know that I'm blessed a thousand times over.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially because his grandmother, Rosetta Lusane, was saved on
that night. She raised him. Even today, Taylor calls her mom and
his real mother by her first name, Sharon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything I have and everything I know, I owe all to my
grandmother,'' Taylor said. ``Everything I do, I do for her. I
don't know what would have happened to me if she didn't make it out
of that accident. I probably would have gone down the wrong road.''
</P>
<P>
   And then Taylor sat abruptly upright and added: ``Or maybe I
would have become the man of the house and said, `It's going to be
this way,' and just lead everybody in our family. I'll say this:
I'm just glad it didn't happen that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, every game he plays, every handoff he takes or pass he
catches, Taylor, the elusive and exciting running back, is always
driven by his grandmother. She now lives in a new home in West Palm
Beach that Taylor bought two years ago when he signed a six-year,
$10.7 million rookie contract that included a $5 million signing
bonus. His grandmother has never attended any of his games, and she
will not be in the stands when Jacksonville battles the Tennessee
Titans in the AFC championship game here on Sunday. She cannot
stand seeing him hit.
</P>
<P>
   But she loves to watch him run.
</P>
<P>
   And Taylor has done plenty of that. He owns nearly every
Jacksonville franchise rushing record and last week, in
Jacksonville's 62-7 playoff thrashing of Miami, Taylor ran 90 yards
for a touchdown in the longest run in NFL playoff history.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Taylor keeps running toward greatness even though he has
been slowed in each of his two pro seasons by injuries. In fact,
this season he missed six games with a hamstring injury in his left
leg and played sparingly in two others because of that injury. But
with Taylor in the lineup, the Jaguars are a more formidable threat
to reach Super Bowl XXXIV and to win it.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, 6 feet 1 inch and a deceptive 230 pounds. makes the
Jaguars more gritty.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has speed, quickness, power and makes good decisions with
the ball in his hands,'' said Jaguars defensive end Tony Brackens.
``Fred can make a play that turns a game completely around like
Deion Sanders. The nation does not know just how good he is but if
we get to the Super Bowl, they will find out.''
</P>
<P>
   First, Jacksonville must beat Tennessee. That could happened if
Taylor can outplay Tennessee's star running back, Eddie George.
</P>
<P>
   ``I respect Eddie and I think the difference between us is he's
a little bigger and he has to get going for his speed to be a
factor,'' Taylor said. ``But I'm 230 pounds with 185-pound feet and
speed. Sometimes I think teams watch tape on me and think I'm
smaller, like 210 pounds, because I'm quick. I see linebackers try
to run up on me and think they are going to get the best lick, but
I do. I see defensive backs rush up and try to tackle me high, and
that is a joke.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hurt my hamstring in the second game of the season, and I'm
only 95 percent even right now. I've had to alter my running style
a little bit. Some of the cuts I know I can make I'm not doing now
because I can't plant the same way off my left leg. But it's coming
back. I'll be ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Ready for the Titans' defense and its rookie sensation, end
Jevon Kearse, Taylor's former teammate at the University of
Florida. Taylor said that he and Kearse are planning an off-season
trip together to Costa Rica with other friends. He calls Kearse ``a
monster now.'' But that is how Taylor describes the Jaguars, too.
</P>
<P>
   It is also an apt description of Taylor. He became a high school
star in south Florida, did the same in central Florida in college
and now, in northern Florida, in Jacksonville, is becoming a pro
football staple.
</P>
<P>
   Super Bowl XXXIV, his biggest and brightest stage, is within
reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be crazy here on Sunday,'' Taylor said. ``We've
got to grit our teeth and hit them back. I expect to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say they have destiny on their side, but why can't
destiny be on our side? My life has been full of destiny and hope
and dreams against great odds. My grandmother could tell you
that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-00 2204EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
