u p BC-BUSH-ABORTION-NYT     01-20 0485
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-ABORTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH, PRESSED TO CLARIFY VIEWS, REPEATS OPPOSITION TO ABORTION
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Iowa)   (jw) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PELLA, Iowa _ Gov. George W. Bush said Thursday that the Supreme
Court had interpreted the Constitution too broadly with its 1973
ruling that established the right to abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roe vs. Wade was a reach,'' Bush said crisply and
unequivocally at a news conference here Thursday afternoon. ``It
overstepped the constitutional bounds, as far as I'm concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the governor of Texas, also said that if elected
president, he would probably oppose any approval by the Food and
Drug Administration of RU-486, the pill that essentially causes a
miscarriage in the very earliest stages of pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's abortion,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's aides said that he had stated similar feelings and
positions before, but his comments on abortion Thursday were more
emphatic, if no more conclusive, than usual. Bush was also kept on
the subject of abortion longer than he likes to dwell there, and
grew more and more visibly uneasy as the questions kept coming.
</P>
<P>
   The governor has sent out hazy signals about the degree of
passion he brings to the issue of abortion, simultaneously
conveying a deep personal disapproval of it and a disinclination to
put it anywhere near the top of his political priorities.
</P>
<P>
   He has repeatedly said that he will not use opposition to
abortion as a litmus test for nominees to the Supreme Court, but
that any judge he considers will have to be what he calls a
``strict constructionist.''
</P>
<P>
   When he was asked Thursday what that kind of judge, interpreting
the Constitution in the literal manner that Bush favors, would be
compelled to conclude about the legality of abortion, Bush gave his
response about Roe vs. Wade being a reach.
</P>
<P>
   But he clearly did not want to elaborate, his body tensing and
his voice assuming a slightly perturbed edge as reporters continued
to press him for greater clarity.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is heavily favored to win the Iowa caucuses on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But Republican voters in this state include many Christian
conservatives, and the wealthy publisher Steve Forbes, who places
second to Bush in most polls of Iowa voters, has firmly stated an
opposition to abortion and sought to portray Bush as soft on the
issue.
</P>
<P>
   But throughout his campaign, Bush has said that he will not push
for a constitutional amendment to ban abortions, though he favors
one, because the requisite support for such a measure does not
exist.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how his twin 18-year-old daughters felt about abortion,
Bush testily said that reporters should respect their privacy, and
he did not budge when a reporter pointed out that he had recounted,
in his autobiography ``A Charge to Keep,'' that one of his
daughters argued with him about the death penalty. Bush
emphatically supports it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
