<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 22:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1852 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-LABOR-CORRUPTION-2NDT     01-20 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABOR-CORRUPTION-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: and '80s.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Weinberg said one explanation for the corruption was that the
union is highly decentralized, meaning its locals more financial
autonomy than most other unions. One episode of corruption
described in the report involves Robert Gordon, who was ousted from
his job as treasurer of the Milwaukee local representing 220 sewer
workers after a bookkeeper discovered that some money was missing.
A union audit reported that Gordon had apparently embezzled $96,000
by writing 208 checks to himself that were not approved and were
not used for union purposes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hold ourselves to very high standards, not only in AFSCME,
but in Wisconsin,'' said Richard Abelson, a top official with the
union in Wisconsin. ``Our expectation is things like that don't
happen here.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon's lawyer, Gerald Boyle, said his client was talking to
law-enforcement authorities and was working with union officials.
``We will take care of making sure that whatever needs to be put
back into the union's coffers is put back,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The report said that Steven K. Grubb, the treasurer of a
municipal workers' local in Elkhart, Ind., wrote $13,500 in union
checks for his personal benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Ard, executive director of the council representing all of
the union's 8,000 workers in Indiana, said Grubb had been removed
from office when the local's other officers uncovered the theft.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not anybody's personal money,'' she said. ``This money
belongs to the members of the union.'' She said that Grubb had
admitted to union officials that he siphoned off the money.
</P>
<P>
   Another insurance claim made by the union involved the
controller of a district council in New Jersey, who the union said
stole $42,700 by forging checks and making unauthorized
withdrawals.
</P>
<P>
   Another claim involved the president of a Long Island, N.Y.,
chapter of the union, who the union said stole $14,870 from the
union. The official, Pasquale Ferraro, was removed by a union
judicial panel, although he has repeatedly denied any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Twigg, an agent for the union's insurance company, St.
Paul Cos., said, ``I don't know if they have more claims than other
unions. I don't find them to be extraordinary or unextraordinary.''
</P>
<P>
   Like most other unions, the Federation of State, County and
Municipal Employees has what is known as a fidelity bond insurance
policy that provides for reimbursing the union if an official
commits dishonest acts that cause the union to lose money.
</P>
<P>
   Twigg said his company examines all such claims to make sure
they are valid.
</P>
<P>
   The report did not mention several prominent episodes of
corruption not covered by the claims report. In 1998, for example,
the secretary-treasurer of the union's district council in
Washington pleaded guilty to embezzling $761,000, while the
council's finance director confessed to stealing $73,500.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the claims that St. Paul Cos. processed between last Oct. 1
and Nov. 22, the report said, the company paid off $605,000 of $2.6
million in claims.
</P>
<P>
   The main reason the company paid off less than the claimed
amount was that the union claimed $2.2 million for money it said
was stolen by Charles Hughes, the former president of a local in
District Council 37, representing New York City's school crossing
guards and cafeteria aides. The policy covering Hughes provided a
maximum of $500,000 in reimbursement to the union.
</P>
<P>
   Sarita Kedia, Hughes' lawyer, said Thursday that her client was
innocent of wrongdoing. The report added several new details about
the District Council 37 scandal, asserting, for example, that
several aides to Hughes had improperly written hundreds of
thousands of dollars in checks that ultimately benefited him
personally.
</P>
</TEXT>
