<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNET-CNET_ </SLUG>
 SF CHRON  
 Cnet Expands, Purchases MySimon.com  &HT;     By Kelly Zito 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
San Francisco's Cnet, an Internet hub for tech news and gadgets,
will broaden its offerings by acquiring MySimon.com, an online
comparison shopping service for a wide variety of consumer goods.
<P>
   Cnet said yesterday that it will buy the closely held Santa
Clara company in a stock deal valued at roughly $700 million, based
on yesterday's closing price. The deal should close by the end of
the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The company also will change its name to Cnet Networks to
reflect the growing diversity of sites _ including Builder.com and
Computers.com _ under its banner.
</P>
<P>
   Cnet, whose flagship site of the same name already lets
consumers compare and buy computers, software, printers and other
high-tech paraphernalia, said broader services like MySimon.com are
becoming more valuable as consumers look to navigate the exploding
number of e-tailers.
</P>
<P>
   Cnet compares products from 150 vendors, while MySimon searches
scours 2,500 online merchants for products ranging from cookbooks
to golf clubs to power tools.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we started looking at the comparison shopping space, we saw
it was taking off, and the numbers were off the charts for
MySimon,'' said Halsey Minor, chairman and chief executive of Cnet.
</P>
<P>
   According to Media Metrix, a New York firm that tracks Web
traffic, the number of unique visitors to MySimon.com skyrocketed
from 171,000 in September to 1.9 million in December.
</P>
<P>
   ``This takes Cnet out of just the technology space and puts them
much closer to what the general public is buying online,'' said
Seema Williams, an analyst at Internet consulting firm Forrester
Research.
</P>
<P>
   But some wonder how Cnet will compete with better-known names
like Amazon.com and Yahoo's shopping channel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cnet is definitely a known place for tech, but I don't know if
it's going to be a place where people who want a new frying pan are
going to go for comparison shopping,` said Zona Research chief
analyst Clay Ryder.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, Minor said, MySimon will remain a separate site
with separate offices for its 66 employees. Its management team,
including chief executive Josh Goldman, will also stay at the
company.
</P>
<P>
   Sites like MySimon and Dealtime.com let Web surfers select a
category such as ``home and garden,'' or ``sports and recreation,''
type in a brand name (and sometimes a price range) and let
so-called `shopping bots' _ short for robots _ search the Web for
the specific product.
</P>
<P>
   While sites like these pride themselves on drawing from an array
of e-tailers, few are completely objective in their searches.
Merchants don't pay to be part of MySimon.com searches, but they do
receive top billing in search results for buying ads on the site.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, 650-employee Cnet has promoted an image of
cutting through the clutter.
</P>
<P>
   In opposition to many of the frenetic, quick-cutting television
ads for dot-coms, Cnet recently launched a series of strangely
simple spots. In one, a man wearing a Cnet T-shirt leads a man
wearing a shirt that says ``You'' away from a fellow whose shirt
reads ``The Wrong Digital Camera'' and toward one whose shirt says
``The Right Digital Camera.''
</P>
<P>
   Cnet stock closed down 50 cents yesterday at $62.19.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
