r f BC-SAKS-SAKS_SFCHRON &LR;      01-20 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAKS-SAKS </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Saks to Close Bullock &AMP; Jones  &HT;     By Carol Emert 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Bullock &AMP; Jones, an upscale clothier that has catered to San
Francisco's elite since 1853, will close next month.
<P>
   Saks Inc., which purchased Bullock &AMP; Jones in July 1998, said
the Union Square retailer did not make enough money to justify
keeping it open. After 147 years in business, the store will close
its doors on February 19.
</P>
<P>
   Bullock &AMP; Jones' prime three-story location at 340 Post St. is
now up for grabs. Club Monaco, a casual clothing chain owned by
Polo Ralph Lauren Inc., is close to a deal on the space, which was
custom-built for Bullock &AMP; Jones in 1923, real estate sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Saks will continue to operate the Bullock &AMP; Jones catalog and
will introduce Bullock &AMP; Jones clothing in a limited number of Saks
stores this year, said Carolyn Biggs, executive vice president for
the Birmingham, Ala., department store operator.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Bullock &AMP; Jones store, which sells conservatively
tailored, high-end menswear and a smaller selection of womenswear,
has been an underperformer, said Biggs. Saks ``sets return
expectations on every investment and unfortunately this project
wasn't making it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sidney Goodwill, who sold Bullock &AMP; Jones to Saks a year and a
half ago, said yesterday that he is heartbroken.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sold the business in good faith,'' Goodwill said. ``I
nurtured that business and built it up over 20 years. Then I
reached a point in my life when it was time for me to move on and I
thought they were going to take it to the next level.''
</P>
<P>
   Saks ``may have had good intentions, but I think they weren't
able to execute it,'' said Goodwill, who still owns the Post Street
building, which is worth an estimated $30 million. ``There's a
difference between running a family-run, hand-run business and a
corporate business.''
</P>
<P>
   Saks declined to say whether the store was losing money. Sales
have been static in recent years, even as many other Union Square
retailers have seen dramatic increases, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Bullock &AMP; Jones was founded in the Financial District during the
Gold Rush. Goodwill and his wife, Susan Goodwill, bought the
company in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bullock &AMP; Jones' strength was that they merchandised things
together beautifully and created their own look,'' said one Union
Square retail watcher. Since Saks came in, ``the windows, the whole
store has not been right.''
</P>
<P>
   From Saks' point of view, it probably makes more sense to offer
Bullock &AMP; Jones merchandise in the Saks Men's Store at 220 Post St.
than for Saks to run two upscale men's stores a stone's throw from
each other, this observer said.
</P>
<P>
   Saks also runs a full-line Saks Fifth Avenue department store in
the same block as Bullock &AMP; Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Saks is responsible for finding a sublessee for the Bullock &AMP;
Jones space. With the downtown real estate market so hot, Saks may
be able to rent it out at a profit, sources speculated.
</P>
<P>
   Saks paid $25 million for Bullock &AMP; Jones' inventory and catalog
business in 1998. Annual sales at the Post Street store were
reported at the time as $10 million and catalog sales as $20
million.
</P>
<P>
   Biggs declined to disclose current sales of either division.
Bullock &AMP; Jones' catalog operation, formerly based in South San
Francisco, was moved out of state shortly after Saks took over.
</P>
<P>
   Club Monaco, a Canadian chain that was purchased by New York's
Polo Ralph Lauren last year, is likely to be the next new tenant on
Union Square, sources said. The first Club Monaco store in the Bay
Area is located in the San Francisco Shopping Centre on Market and
Fifth streets.
</P>
<P>
   A telephone call to Polo Ralph Lauren was not returned
yesterday. A Saks spokeswoman declined to comment on lease
discussions.
</P>
<P>
   Club Monaco sells cosmetics and colorful, trendy clothing, with
most items retailing for under $100. It is best known as the source
of the lipstick Monica Lewinsky wore during her interview with
Barbara Walters; a waiting list quickly developed for the lipstick.
</P>
<P>
   Bullock &AMP; Jones' 29 sales associates will receive transfer
opportunities or severance packages, Saks said.
</P>
<P>
   Saks Holdings, owner of the chi-chi Saks Fifth Avenue chain, was
purchased by Proffitt's Inc., a Southern department store holding
company, in 1998. Proffitt's subsequently changed its name to Saks
Inc.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
