<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-WINE </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Wine Study Lauds State's Grapes of Wealth  &HT;     By Peter Sinton 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
The California wine industry uncorked its first comprehensive
economic impact study yesterday. Label the findings impressive.
<P>
   Wine is the leading finished agricultural product from the
nation's leading agricultural state and generates $33 billion in
annual revenues, wages and economic activity, according to a report
commissioned by the Wine Institute and the California Association
of Winegrapecq &LR;  Growers. Nationwide, the California wine industry
has a $48 billion economic impact.
</P>
<P>
   The state's 847 wineries and 4,400 grape growers produce $12.3
billion in California wine sales. The industry creates 145,000 jobs
in the state and $4.3 billion in annual wages. It also attracts
10.7 million visitors, accounts for $1.2 billion in tourism dollars
and pays $3.1 billion in taxes and fees, including $1 billion to
California.
</P>
<P>
   ``This validates the position of the California wine industry as
one of the crown jewels in the state's economy, culture and
world-class image,'' said Wine Institute President John De Luca.
The wine Wine  &LR; industry files plenty of production reports each
year, but until now, it has not developed hard data on its full
economic impact.
</P>
<P>
   Because winemakers wine makers  &LR; and wine sellers are fighting
various distribution, labeling and taxation battles in Washington,
D.C., De Luca acknowledged that the new report ``is a political
document as well as an economic document.''
</P>
<P>
   The industry hopes to use the study to show that it pays its
fair share of taxes and to combat proponents of so-called ``sin
taxes'' against alcohol producers.
</P>
<P>
   The eight-month study conducted by Motto, Kryla &AMP; Fisher LLP in
St. Helena ``shows how important we are not only to the
agricultural community, but to urban communities,'' said De Luca.
``We're not just manufacturers of booze, but vitally involved in
many different sectors of California economic life. We need to be
understood and supported.''
</P>
<P>
   To put the wine industry's $33 billion economic impact on
California in perspective, MKF partner Vic Motto noted, ``total
U.S. online sale of goods over the Internet is projected to be $29
billion in 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the research findings:
</P>
<P>
   _This year, Americans will spend about $20 billion on wine, with
about 72 percent of it coming from California.
</P>
<P>
   _During Over  &LR; the past five years, California's wine sales have
grown at a compound annual rate of 12 percent, about double the
U.S. economy as a whole. The state produces 93 percent of all U.S.
wine, and the only larger producers are France, Italy and Spain.
</P>
<P>
   _Wine grape acreage has increased by nearly a third in
California, to 427,000 from 324,000 acres (equivalent to 55 percent
of the area of Rhode Island) in the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   _Napa and Sonoma counties account for a third of the state's
grape growers, nearly half its wineries and nearly 60 percent of
the $1.2 billion in wine industry tourism revenues. (Twenty-seven
percent of visitors to San Francisco also take in the ``Wine
Country.'')
</P>
<P>
   _The wine industry has a large ripple effect. Besides tourism,
other wine sub-industries include glass (3,000 employees, $1.2
billion annual revenues); cooperage (240 employees and $212 million
revenues); corks and capsules (270 employees and $175 million
annual revenues) and wine labels (1,100 employees, 3 billion labels
and $106 million revenues).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
