<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 22:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1872 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-BARBER-BARBER_SFCHRON     01-20 1482
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARBER-BARBER </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Barber Schools Still Buzzing Around  &HT;     By David Lazarus 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Clebert Triggs settled into a chair at San Francisco Barber College
and said to the student who would be doing his hair, ``You cut
before?''
<P>
   The student, Shan Zhen Yin, stared back. It was her first day at
the school. She spoke no English.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go with the grain,'' Triggs instructed, running a hand over
his hair. ``With the grain?''
</P>
<P>
   Shan said nothing. She gazed at Triggs' hair, and then at the
razor in her hand, and then again at Triggs' hair. Finally, at a
loss for more decisive action, she handed the razor to her
customer.
</P>
<P>
   Triggs, a regular at the barber college, calmly set the razor at
the correct level and handed it back. Shan proceeded to give him a
trim.
</P>
<P>
   Not all haircuts at barber colleges begin on such a dubious
note. But then again, for $5, what do you want?
</P>
<P>
   Some say old-fashioned barber shops are dying out. They rightly
observe that beauty salons and hair stylists are proliferating,
while traditional shave-and-a-haircut providers are no longer to be
found in many neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   But the reality is that there are more job openings for licensed
barbers than there are barbers to fill them. And while the number
of barbers at work today is just a tiny fraction of the number of
cosmetologists _ the industry term for a salon stylist _ barber
colleges continue to turn out new graduates, just as they have for
the past 100 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The barber business went into a slump during the long-hair
era,'' said James Knauss, owner of San Francisco Barber College and
affiliated institutions in Sacramento, Stockton and Fresno, as well
as serving as executive director of the California Barber College
Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``But guys these days are getting tapered cuts again,'' he said.
``And if you want a tapered cut done right, you go to a barber.''
</P>
<P>
   There are 16 barber colleges statewide, and no fewer than three
in San Francisco alone.
</P>
<P>
   However, the total number of licensed barbers statewide has held
steady around 22,000 for the past quarter-century, according to the
California Department of Consumer Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   The number of licensed cosmetologists, meanwhile, has soared to
about 244,000.
</P>
<P>
   These days, San Francisco Barber College, which has been on
Sixth Street near Mission for more than 40 years, caters primarily
to female Asian students _ women who may have been professional
haircutters in their home countries and are now undergoing required
classroom training for a California license.
</P>
<P>
   A few blocks away is Moler Barber College, established in 1910
by barbering legend A.B. Moler, who is credited with opening the
nation's first barber college in Chicago back in 1893.
</P>
<P>
   The current owner is Donald Forfang II _ he doesn't like to be
called ``junior'' _ whose father, Donald Forfang I, purchased the
school in 1954 after about 25 years running his own barbershop. The
younger Forfang took over the college in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have more job opportunities than I have graduates,'' he
said. ``There are more shops open now than there were 10 years ago,
simply because hair is shorter.''
</P>
<P>
   Shorter hairstyles, of course, require more frequent
maintenance, which means more visits to the barber.
</P>
<P>
   African Americans, many of whom favor close-cropped ``fades'' or
intricate designs in their hair, are the most frequent patrons of
Bay Area barbershops. Most of the students at Moler are themselves
African American, and many are now looking to barbering as a way of
turning their lives around.
</P>
<P>
   Willie Scott, 24, will graduate in March after more than a year
at the barber college. He has big plans after pulling earlier
stints as a construction and warehouse worker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be an entrepreneur and open my own business,'' he
said. ``I don't want to work for nobody.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Guardado, 38, used to be a gang member, until a bullet in
his back two years ago convinced him that a lifestyle change was in
order. After four months at the barber college, he already has
plans for his own shop _ ``a real high-class place, sort of Art
Deco.''
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Allen, 55, has been at the college just two months, and
his wife worries that close proximity to his old downtown haunts
will compel him to return to some bad habits.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's not going to happen,'' he said. ``You can't come in
here high. The others wouldn't let me.''
</P>
<P>
   He's probably right. Even a casual visitor can sense the loose
familiarity among students, making the barber college a
surprisingly upbeat place to hang around. Maybe it's not quite as
chummy as Floyd's barbershop on the old ``Andy Griffith Show,'' but
it rises above the generally downtrodden surroundings outside.
</P>
<P>
   It's no coincidence that barber colleges usually are located in
fairly rough-and-tumble neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's to get clientele,'' said Moler's Forfang. ``People are
hesitant enough to go to a barber college. In an upscale area,
people will frequent upscale shops.''
</P>
<P>
   Moler charges $5.25 for a haircut. But, along with San Francisco
Barber College and Bayview Barber College on Third Street, it also
cuts hair for free for low-income people receiving vouchers from
local charities and churches.
</P>
<P>
   At Bayview, owner Dwayne Robinson said demand is strong in his
neighborhood not just for $5 haircuts but also for a new generation
of barbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are only five shops here and about 49,000 African
Americans,'' he said. ``There's no way five shops can handle
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Bayview Barber College was established in 1998 with grant money
from City Hall. Robinson said the school has attracted 33 students
since opening.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't easy, or cheap, to become a licensed barber. To become
qualified to take the state licensing exam, aspiring cutters attend
39-week programs _ or longer if part time _ that cost about $4,000.
</P>
<P>
   Along with on-the-job training, instruction includes classroom
sessions on such topics as shaving, coloring and proper hygiene.
There are also lessons on management of one's own shop and various
barber-related laws.
</P>
<P>
   Among these laws is a state ruling that only establishments with
a licensed barber on the premises can display a striped barber pole
out front.
</P>
<P>
   The state also mandates that the blue liquid in which barbers
soak their combs must be ``an EPA-registered disinfectant with
demonstrated bactericidal, fungicidal and virucidal activity.''
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Whitney, who oversees California's barber industry on
behalf of the Department of Consumer Affairs, said she is unable to
disclose other things that an aspiring barber must know because of
``security considerations'' surrounding the licensing exam.
</P>
<P>
   She did reveal, though, that exam-takers are allowed to use an
interpreter when demonstrating their skills and knowledge, which is
why some students at San Francisco Barber College can go through
the entire program without speaking English.
</P>
<P>
   Willem Kamal, an instructor at the college, said he uses ``body
language'' to communicate with his students, who he said often take
jobs in Chinatown after graduating.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Moler's Forfang believes would-be barbers are best
advised to keep chitchat to a minimum.
</P>
<P>
   ``I teach my students to be cautious about having lots of people
hanging out at barbershops,'' he said. ``Too much hanging out will
discourage business.''
</P>
<P>
   And there are occasions as well when a barber must exercise
self-control.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes people come in here with an attitude,'' said Jimmy
Ford, a Moler student. ``You got to bite your tongue.''
</P>
<P>
   By and large, though, the barbering experience remains largely
unchanged today from decades before. ``Playboy'' still even gives
free subscriptions to barbershops so patrons will have something of
interest to peruse prior to a trim.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of great things about this industry,'' said
Forfang. ``Everyone who comes to see you wants to, and once you get
a license, you can work wherever you like for as long as you
like.''
</P>
<P>
   The average barber, he noted, pulls down as much as $40,000
annually and stays on the job for 25 years. A cosmetologist, by
comparison, typically remains at the same shop no more than five
years.
</P>
<P>
   Those now entering the barbering trade seem mindful of its long
history and say they take pride in what they offer customers.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, barber-college customers appreciate the low-cost
service.
</P>
<P>
   ``A guy can come in here and get himself fixed up,'' said the
Rev. James Boyd, a homeless advocate who was paying a social call
on the patrons of San Francisco Barber College. ``There's no reason
to be looking shaggy.''
</P>
<P>
   He took in his own reflection in one of the mirrors and noted
that he'd have to return soon for a trim.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look good,'' Boyd said, ``you feel good.''
</P>
<P>
