<HEADER>
A1873 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-PACBELL-PACBELL_SFCHR     01-20 0495
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PACBELL-PACBELL </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Pac Bell Plans to Fight Big Fine  &HT;     By Todd Wallack 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   A month after Pacific Bell was ordered to pay $44 million for
sleazy sales practices, the telephone company plans to fight back.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the company will formally ask the California Public
Utilities Commission to throw out the judgment as ``legally
flawed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All of it was wrong,'' said company attorney Colleen O'Grady
Diamond yesterday. Pacific Bell plans to file a 50-page appeal
today.
</P>
<P>
   In December, a PUC administrative law judge fined the company
$20 million and ordered Pacific Bell to spend another $24 million
on a consumer-education campaign after finding the company had
misled customers into buying extra features they didn't want or
need.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Pacific Bell bundled call forwarding, three-way
calling and other extras into a package called the ``basics.'' The
company was also fined $16.5 million for marketing abuses in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   But Pacific Bell says the decision was based on only 15 isolated
complaints collected by consumer groups. Executives said its
customer surveys show most customers are satisfied. ``There was a
dearth of complaints,'' said Pacific Bell President Bill Blase.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Pacific Bell insists it complied with existing
regulations. For instance, commissioners OKd a request to call some
of its calling packages names like the ``basics'' and
``essentials.'' And regulators never specifically ordered the
company to tell customers they could opt to automatically block
their number from showing up on Caller ID; Judge Maribeth Bushey
ruled that Pacific Bell purposely didn't mention the option to help
promote its lucrative Caller ID business.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Bell's Blase said he feels optimistic that either the
judge or commissioners will modify the fine. But a watchdog group
didn't give the appeal much chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the company were smart, they would recognize this as a
wake-up call,'' said Charles Carbone, a consumer advocate with the
Utility Consumers Action Network in San Diego, which filed the
initial complaint that led to the ruling. ``The final opinion went
easy on them,'' he said, pointing out the company took in $391
million last year for custom calling features.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the 15 complaints Pacific Bell cited, Carbone
said customer service representatives testified that they had
misled customers and spotted widespread patterns of complaints that
were never recorded.
</P>
<P>
   Carbone also said the company violated numerous laws and
regulations by misleading customers, even if commissioners didn't
spell out every detail.
</P>
<P>
   He said Pacific Bell is still on the hook for misleading
customers by using terms like ``essentials.'' Although the PUC did
agree to the use of the term, he said the commissioners only
``rubber stamped'' the term in a fast-track process called
tariffing.
</P>
<P>
