<P>
   &UR; BARBER _ &LR;  Clebert Triggs settled into a chair at San Francisco
Barber College and said to the student who would be doing his hair,
``You cut before?'' The student, Shan Zhen Yin, stared back. It was
her first day at the school. She spoke no English. ``Go with the
grain,'' Triggs instructed, running a hand over his hair. ``With
the grain?''
</P>
<P>
   Shan said nothing. She gazed at Triggs' hair, and then at the
razor in her hand, and then again at Triggs' hair. Finally, at a
loss for more decisive action, she handed the razor to her
customer. Triggs, a regular at the barber college, calmly set the
razor at the correct level and handed it back. Shan proceeded to
give him a trim. Not all haircuts at barber colleges begin on such
a dubious note. But then again, for $5, what do you want? By David
Lazarus
</P>
