<HEADER>
A1875 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e BC-TV-UPN-SFCHRON &LR;      01-20 0940
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-UPN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UPN THINKS IT KNOWS WHAT BOYS WANT 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ UPN is testament to the power of the survival
instinct.
</P>
<P>
   Only 18 months ago, its top executives oozed sincerity in
outlining the network's unshakable core belief in general audience
programming.
</P>
<P>
   That strategem led UPN into a near-fatal 1998-99 season, after
which many observers wrote the network off for dead. Without
mourning.
</P>
<P>
   This week in Pasadena, the same UPN execs oozed sincerity in
outlining their unshakable core belief in niche programming.
</P>
<P>
   The difference is that this time, they brought graphs and charts
with them. Do you know what graphs and charts mean? They mean
growth.
</P>
<P>
   Homes, up 35 percent. Adults 18 to 34, up 60 percent. Men 18 to
34, up 90 percent. Male teens, up 158 percent.
</P>
<P>
   It must be noted, before anyone swoons from the majesty of it
all, that it's easier to post spectacular growth percentages if
your base figures are tiny. And UPN started this season with
teensy-tiny numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Teenage guys are the current objects of UPN's core beliefs.
Fortunately, it's easy to figure out what guys like. Guys like
wrestling, explosions, fast cars, fat trucks and big bosoms.
</P>
<P>
   Guys like to have their hormones yanked, and UPN aims to please.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it has high testosterone, we'll air it,'' said Dean
Valentine, the president and CEO of UPN.
</P>
<P>
   ``WWF Smackdown!'' on Thursday nights is charged with enough
testosterone to knock down a rhinoceros, and it single-handedly
accounts for most of UPN's ugly resurgence.
</P>
<P>
   This week, UPN premiered ``I Dare You! The Ultimate Challenge,''
a series in which stunt experts set themselves on fire, blow
themselves up, crash fast-moving vehicles into stationary objects,
and dive from great heights into little pools of water. But hey,
says UPN, it's clean entertainment, just like the circus.
</P>
<P>
   Where to go from there? February is supposed to be when young
men's hearts turn to sweet romance. It's also a big sweeps month,
but there are no valentines in Valentine's vision. No, the UPN
February centerpiece will be a monster truck special that, for the
moment, is called ``Monster Trux 2000: The New Thrillennium.''
</P>
<P>
   Monster trucks are trucks with big wheels. They crush smaller
trucks. These events are as popular as barn dances in some parts of
the country, but UPN is promising a new wrinkle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The monster truck thing is an experiment for us because
frankly, it's been done poorly in the past on cable,'' says UPN
programming chief, or ringmaster, Tom Nunan. ``These things are
just 11-second bursts, so what we're going to try to do is create
characters and story lines not unlike the WWF.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they'll throw trucks against a giant turnbuckle, or smash
windshields with folding chairs.
</P>
<P>
   UPN has some legitimate shows in the works, too, including ``The
Beat,'' a cop show from the ``Homicide'' creative team of Barry
Levinson and Tom Fontana.
</P>
<P>
   But it's more fun to look ahead to more, uh, creative
expressions of boyish fantasy on UPN. You won't believe this, yet
it's true.
</P>
<P>
   To the stunned laughter of critics in Pasadena, Nunan said one
projected series is ``Hip-Hop Bounty Hunters.'' Oh boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the title of that one says it all,'' Nunan said drily.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's a series about undercover female spies, modeled
ever so slightly on the old NBC show ``I Spy.'' This time, the
spies' cover is that they're professional volleyball players.
Presumably, professional volleyball players in small bikinis.
</P>
<P>
   It's called ``I Spike.''
</P>
<P>
   Todd McFarlane of Marvel Comics is working on ``Gorilla World''
for UPN. It's touted as a futuristic look at evolution, though it
might also be a documentary about running UPN.
</P>
<P>
   On the theory that boys' attention spans are nearly as
diminutive as the ``I Spike'' bikinis, UPN is also developing
15-minute comedy shows. Nunan had no details to report.
</P>
<P>
   One critic wondered what all this said about the male half of
America's youth. Another questioned Valentine about UPN's image,
and whether cockfights might find a home on some future UPN
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was growing up, I remember there was a whole thing
about how terrible comic books were,'' Valentine said. ``Somehow in
every generation, whatever young guys seem to like is what's bad
for you.''
</P>
<P>
   I think it's still a ``no'' on the cockfights. Female mud
wrestling probably isn't out of the question, though.
</P>
<P>
   UPN says its idea of giving boys what they want has made the
struggling network viable, and in the nick of time.
</P>
<P>
   The impending merger of CBS and Sumner Redstone's Viacom empire,
which includes Paramount, raises questions last year about the
future of UPN, which is half owned by Paramount. One company can't
own two broadcast networks, at least not yet. So UPN's fate is up
in the air. A waiver might be sought. Or UPN could be sold. The
roster of possibilities, Valentine said, is ``virtually count
less.''
</P>
<P>
   But UPN is all about survival, and its ratings spurt means that
it isn't the white elephant it appeared to be a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that makes me feel best is, when these questions
first started about six months ago, when the merger was first
announced, everybody was sort of worrying _ `I don't want UPN, you
take it,''' Valentine said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're now in a very different position, where we're pleased to
have people fighting over us, as opposed to who has to keep us.''
</P>
<P>
   People fighting over them? Give 'em live ammo and grab a camera.
It could be a UPN series.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
