<DOCNO> NYT20000120.0377 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 22:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1879 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKS-MATTINGLY-A     01-20 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-MATTINGLY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MATTINGLY, REJOINING YANKS AS SPRING INSTRUCTOR, SAYS MANAGING IS
POSSIBLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT39 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 (bl)  
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Four years after Don Mattingly retired from the New York
Yankees, he will resume his relationship with the only baseball
organization he has ever known by working as a spring training
instructor in February. Mattingly said the details of his role had
not been completed, but he expected to spend about three weeks in
Tampa, Fla., and then work with minor leaguers during the season.
</P>
<P>
   Mattingly will join the likes of Goose Gossage, Ron Guidry and
Mickey Rivers as former Yankees whom George Steinbrenner invites to
camp each spring, but Mattingly's return is especially noteworthy
because it apparently signals his intention to eventually re-enter
the major leagues as a coach or manager.
</P>
<P>
   Mattingly admitted Thursday that this was a possible scenario
and said that he wanted to tutor minor leaguers so he would feel a
kinship with the current generation of players when, and if, he
decided to seek a full-time position. While Mattingly stressed that
he was not close to seeking a major league job that would separate
him from his wife, Kim, and three sons for eight months a year, he
conceded that he had envisioned the aspects of a return.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've told everyone that, in my mind, if I really wanted to get
back into baseball, I'd really want to start as a hitting coach and
be able to sit there and watch a great manager work and learn and
learn,'' Mattingly said. ``And then, at one point, be able to
manage. So that would be something I would like to do. If I had to
say right now, `Would you ever want to manage?' I'd say yes. Ten
years from now, I might say no. But I know I don't want to do it
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever so methodically, Mattingly is dipping his toes back into
the baseball pool to gauge the temperature and see if he wants to
dive in. Mattingly has made a few appearances at Yankee Stadium
since ending his glorious 13-year career after the 1995 season, but
he had been reluctant to get too close to the Yankees. Now the
38-year-old Mattingly, who is eligible for the Hall of Fame next
year, said he was eager to be an instructor because it revived the
types of associations he cherished as a player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought it was great that Catfish and Whitey and guys
like that were there with us,'' said Mattingly, referring to the
Hall of Famers Catfish Hunter and Whitey Ford. ``I loved being able
to ask Whitey something for no reason, but just be able to talk
about the past.''
</P>
<P>
   In reviving the past, Mattingly could influence the future and
start the process in which he emerged as an intriguing candidate to
manage the Yankees at some point. Mattingly was a diligent worker
while batting .307 with nine Gold Glove awards, and his class and
his marquee value would appeal to Steinbrenner, who would probably
love to have Mattingly follow manager Joe Torre.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the Yankees barreled to their second straight World
Series title last year, there was speculation that Steinbrenner was
dissatisfied with Chris Chambliss, the batting coach, and that
Mattingly could replace him. Chambliss, who was privately
criticized by some players, was rehired because the Yankees, who
were fourth in the American League in batting average, won it all.
Still, Mattingly's willingness to become more involved and gain
valuable experience looms ominous.
</P>
<P>
   When Torre was appointed in 1996, he told Willie Randolph, the
third-base coach, that he would prepare Randolph to succeed him,
but Torre is entering his fifth year and has two more years on his
contract. The Yankees' new first-base coach, Lee Mazzilli, is
another managerial candidate, but Mattingly might someday prove too
tempting a choice for Steinbrenner to bypass.
</P>
<P>
   Mattingly was asked if he would wear any uniform besides the
Yankees' if he decided he did want to come back to baseball and
manage.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I really made my mind up that's what I wanted to do,
obviously, to me, that would be the best thing, to be in New
York,'' Mattingly said. ``I would like that. But it's one of those
things where you've got to do what you've got to do. If I was dead
serious about it, you can't limit your options. That's a bridge I
don't have to cross right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Mattingly is the proud owner and operator of a horse farm in
Evansville, Ind., and a doting father to his sons, who are 14, 12
and 8. To stay closely involved with what his boys are doing,
Mattingly said he even listened to the music they like. The father
and horse farmer sounded content with his life. But how will
Mattingly react if Steinbrenner ever calls with a persuasive offer?
</P>
<P>
   ``When I decided that was it, one of the reasons was to be
around the kids,'' Mattingly said. ``I don't want to leave them
now. If you decide to do something like coach or manage, it's a
commitment of time and energy because you have to learn so much.
Playing is different than managing or coaching. When I played, I
was worried about first base. I wasn't worried about every guy in
the field. As a manager, you've got to worry about everything.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-00 2230EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
