<DOCNO> NYT20000120.0378 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 22:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1880 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-CUBA-BOY-1STLD-WRITET     01-20 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-BOY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUBAN BOY'S GRANDMOTHERS ARE SET TO FLY TO U.S. 
</HEADLINE>
   (Subs for inserts, rewriting throughout) 
 (sw) 
 By DON VAN NATTA Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration issued visas on Thursday
to the grandmothers of 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez, allowing the two
women to travel to the United States from Cuba and setting up a
showdown on American soil between two sets of the boy's relatives.
</P>
<P>
   The American diplomatic mission in Havana granted the visas as
representatives of the National Council of Churches flew a
chartered plane to Havana to meet the grandmothers. They planned to
take them to New York on Friday, administration officials said on
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's developments in the international custody case
virtually guarantee that a dramatic tug-of-war over the boy will
occur in the United States between Elian's great-uncle in Miami,
who wants permanent custody of the boy, and Elian's grandmothers,
who have said repeatedly that the boy should be reunited with his
father in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Since Elian's rescue from an inner tube off Florida on Nov. 25
after his mother and 10 other people drowned fleeing Cuba, he has
been living with relatives in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   The boy's paternal grandmother, Mariela Quintana, and maternal
grandmother, Raquel Rodriguez, applied for the visas late on
Thursday afternoon, and the visas were granted in a matter of
hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were found to be eligible and the visas were quickly
granted,'' said James P. Rubin, the spokesman for the State
Department. ``We understand they will travel tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Quintana has told the Cuban news agency Prensa Latina that
she wanted to travel to Miami ``for just five minutes'' to pick up
her grandson. Ms. Rodriguez, whose daughter died trying to reach
the United States, has been equally emphatic that the youngster
should return to Cuba to live with his father.
</P>
<P>
   An administration official, who insisted on anonymity, said the
grandmothers had chosen to fly to New York rather than Miami, where
hundreds of anti-Castro Cuban-Americans have demonstrated against
the boy's return to Cuba. The National Council of Churches, whose
leaders have said that the boy should be reunited with his father
on the island, is based in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said on Thursday night that they
welcomed the visit by the grandmothers because they assumed that it
would create sympathy for the Immigration and Naturalization
Service's position.
</P>
<P>
   An aide to Rep. Charles Rangel, D-N.Y., said on Thursday night
that Rangel planned to meet with the two women in New York City on
Friday. Rangel will offer to help the women make their case that
the boy belongs in Cuba, said Emile Milne, a press secretary for
Rangel.
</P>
<P>
   Milne also said it was his understanding that the women intended
to fly to Miami eventually to take Elian back to Cuba. ``They want
to stay away from the hostile environment of Miami,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the boy's great-uncle, Lazaro Gonzalez, filed a
lawsuit in federal court in Miami on Wednesday that challenged the
Immigration and Naturalization Service's ruling on Jan. 4 that the
youngster should be sent back to his father in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department lawyers had considered going to court to ask
a federal judge to enforce the immigration ruling in an effort to
quickly resolve what has evolved into a highly emotional, extremely
difficult political and diplomatic quandary.
</P>
<P>
   An administration official denied that the grandmothers' visit
was intended to circumvent the legal process. ``Presumably,'' the
official said, ``the two grandmothers can speak better for the
father's interests than the boy's great-uncle.''
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said they believed the father did not
come because he did not want to be drawn into the court battle over
his son's custody.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno said on Thursday that Justice
Department officials would move as quickly as possible to resolve
the matter in federal court in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will look at everything that can be done to have the matter
heard appropriately and promptly, with the recognition that it does
the child no good to be in limbo,'' Reno said at her weekly press
conference.
</P>
<P>
   The small corporate jet chartered by the church group arrived at
Havana's international airport at 6 p.m. on Thursday, but returned
to the United States at midevening, with only the flight crew
aboard.
</P>
<P>
   Elian was among 14 people who tried to sail to the Florida coast
from Cuba in a 17-foot aluminum boat, which capsized. The boy's
mother and stepfather and nine others drowned. Elian, and two
others, were rescued after clinging to inner tubes in Florida
waters for two days.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, his fate has become the subject of an intense fight
between his father in Cuba and his relatives in Miami. The boy's
father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, has made it clear that he wants Elian
to return to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   In the suit filed on Wednesday, lawyers for Elian's great-uncle
argued that the Immigration and Naturalization Service had violated
Elian's due-process rights. They asked a federal judge to prevent
the agency from returning the boy before it granted him an asylum
hearing.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for the great-uncle, Spencer Eig, told the Cable News
Network on Thursday night that the grandmothers would be welcome to
visit Elian in Miami, but that they would not be permitted to take
the boy to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Many lawyers whose expertise is family and immigration law
support the position of the Clinton administration, saying the
reunification of a parent and child is a cornerstone of immigration
law and INS practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``The law is rather clear on this,'' said Eliot Lichtman, a
veteran immigration lawyer based here. ``This is a federal issue
for the immigration service. They have interviewed the father and
decided the father has a loving relationship with the son.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-00 2231EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
