<HEADLINE>
GENERAL MOTORS EARNINGS DECLINE BUT STILL BEAT EXPECTATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ROBYN MEREDITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Profits fell as sales rose at General Motors in the
fourth quarter, when the company ran short of high-margin models
and offered discounts to keep sales booming for its less-profitable
cars and trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the results were better than Wall Street analysts
had expected, driving GM's stock price up 75 cents, to $81.25. And
even with a 35 percent drop in fourth-quarter profits, GM finished
the year with record profits of $6 billion, up from $2.96 billion
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   GM set a revenue record of $176.6 billion last year, rebounding
from $155.4 billion in 1998, when a strike depressed sales.
</P>
<P>
   GM earned $1.15 billion in the fourth quarter, or $1.86 a share,
down from the $1.77 billion, or $2.61 a share, in the period a year
earlier. Revenue rose 3.7 percent in the quarter to $46.26 billion.
</P>
<P>
   GM executives said they were happy with the results. ``We did
beat expectations, and it wraps up what I think was a very strong
year for us,'' said J. Michael Losh, the company's chief financial
officer.
</P>
<P>
   The company emphasized that it had prospered in 1999 despite a
market that while growing, allowed little room to raise prices.
``We're pleased that our financial performance remained on track
even as we faced unceasing competitive pressures,'' GM's chairman
and chief executive, John F. Smith Jr, said.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth quarter, GM's net profit margins were 2.5 percent,
just half of the company's 5 percent goal.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the fourth-quarter performance was mediocre. GM
``should be doing a lot better than that,'' said Nicholas
Lobaccaro, an auto analyst at Lehman Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   GM beat analysts' earnings expectations largely because its tax
rate was lower than expected, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good quarter in quantity if not in quality,'' said
John A. Casesa, an auto analyst at Merrill Lynch. ``Very strong
industry volumes are propping up the whole industry's results,
including GM's.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford is expected to report record 1999 earnings Wednesday, and
DaimlerChrysler, which is scheduled to report its earnings Feb. 28,
will turn in the first full-year results since Daimler-Benz bought
Chrysler in November 1998.
</P>
<P>
   GM's profits declined in North America and Europe, while losses
turned to profits in Latin America and losses were trimmed in the
Asia-Pacific region. In the fourth quarter, the North American
market accounted for $1.01 billion of GM's $1.05 billion in profit
from selling cars and trucks.
</P>
<P>
   GM's lending unit, the General Motors Acceptance Corp., brought
in another $367 million, and added a record $1.54 billion in net
income for the year.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes Electronics, a unit GM is considering partly spinning off
to shareholders, lost $61 million in the fourth quarter and $105
million for the year, a reversal from the $119 million in net
income in the fourth quarter of 1998 and the $272 million in net
income in 1998. Nonetheless, its revenue rose 25 percent, to $7.6
billion, because its DirecTV unit added 1.6 million subscribers
last year, GM said.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth quarter, GM was not able to produce as many of its
highly profitable Chevrolet Tahoe and Suburban and GMC Yukon
full-size sport utility vehicles as expected because their
factories geared up slowly after the models were redesigned.
</P>
<P>
   Oil prices are rising, nearing $30 a barrel Wednesday, and
gasoline prices are climbing with them. This has had limited effect
so far on the hot sport utility market. But today's earnings
figures underlined how GM, the world's largest corporation, is
dependent on several models _ all hulking, gas-guzzling trucks _
for a large chunk of its profits.
</P>
<P>
   GM's earnings Thursday included a blizzard of one-time after-tax
gains and losses that largely canceled each other out. The company
reported a $553 million gain as many workers, once thought to have
been permanently laid off, were pressed back into service to keep
factories running in a booming economy.
</P>
<P>
   But GM also took a $408 million charge for higher pension costs
in its new contract with the United Automobile Workers union, a $90
million charge for terminating white-collar workers and a $165
million charge from the Hughes division's wireless business.
</P>
<P>
   Separately Thursday, GM's Saturn unit announced that it had
hired Internet specialists to better link its dealers with its
buyers online.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
