<HEADLINE>
N.Y. TIMES AND ABC IN NEWS DEAL THAT WILL INCLUDE TV AND INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl)  
 By BILL CARTER   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York Times and ABC News said Thursday that
they had agreed to share news coverage in several fields, with the
information to be delivered both on television and over the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The arrangement, announced jointly by Arthur Sulzberger Jr., the
publisher of The Times, and David Westin, the president of ABC
News, will include the creation of a daily 15-minute video report
on politics to be delivered on each organization's World Wide Web
site. The program, entitled ``Political Points,'' will begin Monday
with coverage of the Iowa presidential caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal, The Times is to participate in producing reports
for two programs on the ABC television network _ the ``20/20''
newsmagazine and the morning program ``Good Morning America.''
</P>
<P>
   Initially, The Times will contribute reports in the areas of
technology and health, and executives of the two organizations said
that the topic list could be expanded. One area already discussed
involves specialized Times features like obituaries and the Vows
column, informally known as ``wedding of the week.''
</P>
<P>
   The Times has agreed to supply 4 to 6 reports to ``20/20'' over
the next year and as many as 16 reports on ``Good Morning,
America.'' Some morning segments may involve appearances by Times
reporters or political commentators to discuss articles in the
day's paper.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is essentially limited to this political season. Bill
Keller, managing editor of The Times, said, ``The election gives us
an exit strategy if we're all disappointed.'' But he added, ``We
all hope it works.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The arrangement between The Times and ABC News follows a similar
one announced in November between NBC and the Washington Post Co.
in which reporters from The Post and its cousin Newsweek magazine
will appear on the all-news cable network MSNBC.
</P>
<P>
   The Times/ABC deal is emphasizing the daily political program,
to be posted on each company's Web site at 1:30 p.m. each weekday
starting Monday. It promises to cover developments in the political
campaigns that occur after the morning publication of the paper and
the broadcast of ``Good Morning America'' and before the evening
newscast on ABC, which is owned by Walt Disney Co.
</P>
<P>
   The joint program, based in Washington, will be moderated
jointly by Michael Oreskes, the Washington bureau chief of The
Times, and Mark Halperin, the political director for ABC News.
</P>
<P>
   Like many Times executives, Oreskes called the agreement an
experiment for the newspaper. ``I think the show will be
top-quality political journalism,'' he said, ``but it's going to be
a learning experience. We're not feeling any trepidation. We're
going into a new world, and we need to learn new skills.''
</P>
<P>
   He said each news organization would safeguard any exclusive
report it develops. ``There will still be stories we withhold for
the newspaper,'' Oreskes said. ``But at other times, on a totally
different type of exclusive _ the kind you get in the morning but
you know the world will know by 6 o'clock _ those we'll be putting
on the webcast.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
