<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARBARA-BUSH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPULAR AND FULL OF PRIDE, BARBARA BUSH CAMPAIGNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEBANON, N.H. _ ``I want to thank all of you who are helping
George W. Bush get elected,'' Barbara Bush said Thursday, in the
pleasant but rather flat tone of a practiced campaigner on yet
another stump.
</P>
<P>
   Then Mrs. Bush paused and beamed at the hundred or so people who
had come to see her at the airport here, and in an instant her mien
was that not of a surrogate campaigner, but of a proud mother. ``I
can't tell you how overwhelming that is for a mother to say,'' she
declared. ``This guy,'' she went on, smiling even more broadly,
``is just a great son and father and husband.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Bush, 74, has done several fund-raisers for her son around
the country, but the stop here, the first of a two-day, eight-town
swing across New Hampshire, was her first foray directly into the
primary campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   The popularity of the former first lady can hardly be
overstated. A CBS News poll last year found that 63 percent of
Americans had a favorable view of Mrs. Bush, and only 3 percent had
an unfavorable opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Julia Fifield, a 95-year-old Republican stalwart from Orford,
N.H., called Mrs. Bush ``the most respected woman ever to represent
this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years ago, Mrs. Fifield had one of the first receptions
in New Hampshire for George Bush in his first, unsuccessful race
for president. ``Twenty years later, we're back calling on our
friends again,'' Mrs. Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll keep his promise'' not to run a negative campaign, ``or
his mother will come after him,'' Mrs. Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Bush said that after 1992, when her husband lost a bitter
re-election campaign to Bill Clinton, she had sworn never to
campaign again, and quickly added, ``Maybe I should have said,
`Read my lips.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-00 2239EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
