<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 22:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1888 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-U.N.-HELMS-2NDLD-WRIT     01-20 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.N.-HELMS-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-ART-920(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.C.)  
 HELMS CARRIES MESSAGE OF THE RIGHT TO AN ANGRY U.N. 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Adds ID of N.C. businessman who helped arrange visit. Moves
to 4th graph Helms' claim he is speaking for American people. Other
rearranging.) 
 (ART ADV: Photos NYT8, 9 and 10 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036.) 
(jw) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., came to the Security
Council offering a ``hand of friendship'' Thursday but delivered
the sort of clenched-fist message that has made him the symbol of
right-wing hostility toward the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Helms, the most powerful congressional voice in foreign policy
as chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, contended
that Congress had the right to dictate conditions for the payment
of American debts to the organization. He warned the United Nations
to keep its ``utopian'' visions away from American sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the United Nations respects the sovereign rights of the
American people, and serves them as an effective tool of diplomacy,
it will earn and deserve their respect and support,'' he told
council members. ``But a United Nations that seeks to impose its
presumed authority on the American people, without their consent,
begs for confrontation and _ I want to be candid with you _
eventual U.S. withdrawal.''
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Helms, asserting that he was speaking for the
American people, delivered a clear-cut conservative manifesto on
the United Nations, and did not leave anything open for compromise.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of his address to an extraordinary gathering of
ambassadors, nearly every member of the Security Council challenged
Helms' bleak portrayal of the United Nations and criticized the
United States for letting the organization down.
</P>
<P>
   Ambassador Alain Dejammet of France, visibly agitated, said to
Helms, ``We hear you, but the idea in this house is that others
must be heard as well.''
</P>
<P>
   And Sir Jeremy Greenstock of Britain said: ``The United Nations
is not a separate organ to which we turn, like a fire service. It
is the member states, and the United States owns 25 percent of the
power and the resources of the United Nations. What it does well,
the U.S. gets credit for. What it does badly, the U.S. must bear
some responsibility for.''
</P>
<P>
   Helms had tried to put a positive face on his visit, arranged by
a North Carolina businessman _ Irwin Belk, who is a friend of the
senator and who was appointed an alternate delegate to the General
Assembly last fall _ and by Richard Holbrooke, the American
permanent representative to the United Nations and this month's
Security Council president.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke has spent months trying to build bridges with a
hostile Congress that has held up payments of U.N. dues and delayed
the confirmation of ambassadors and other foreign policy officials
_ including that of Holbrooke himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is important,'' Helms said, ``that this body have greater
contact with the elected representatives of the American people,
and that we have greater contact with you.'' He invited Security
Council members to visit his committee in Washington. Before the
council meeting, he spoke for about 40 minutes with Secretary
General Kofi Annan and asked him to pose for pictures with the
Helms family.
</P>
<P>
   Helms told the Security Council that unlike Europeans, the
American people were moving away from ``supranational
institutions'' and wanted no part of ``utopian'' international
arrangements, including the international criminal court created
last year over the objections of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's session, which the council decided to open to the
press and the public only Wednesday, was a gamble for Holbrooke,
diplomats said. But it seems to have paid off both for Helms, who
was welcomed with fanfare and given an unusual stage to air his
views, and for his adversaries. Diplomats from around the world,
particularly Security Council members who have fumed quietly over
what they see as a deadbeat America bankrupting the organization,
got the chance to tell Helms directly what they thought _ however
diplomatically the comments were couched.
</P>
<P>
   After Helms praised the anti-communist Reagan doctrine for
having brought freedom and democracy to the world without the help
or approval of the United Nations, the Namibian representative,
Martin Andjaba, took impassioned exception.
</P>
<P>
   The Reagan doctrine, he said, denied independence to Namibia and
its Southwest African Peoples Organization, gave support to
apartheid South Africa and empowered the UNITA rebel movement in
Angola, which has prolonged a quarter-century-long civil war.
</P>
<P>
   ``It contributed to a lot of suffering in Africa,'' he said.
``Some of us in SWAPO who were a legitimate and genuine national
liberation movement were called other names: terrorists. And those
that caused death and destruction in Africa were called liberators
_ and they were supported.
</P>
<P>
   ``That page has passed, but we have it fresh in our memories.''
</P>
<P>
   In a list of indictments against the organization, Helms revived
old criticism about votes in the General Assembly that ran against
the United States, he attacked a human rights monitor who reported
on allegations of human rights violations in the United States, and
he objected to accusations that American debts _ still more than $1
billion despite a recent payment _ were hampering the organization.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   He said that the United States had spent $10.2 billion on the
United Nations and its projects in 1999, a figure immediately
disputed by Steven Dimoff, vice president of the U.N. Association
of the United States and the director of its Washington office.
Dimoff said in an interview that the sum ``really does stretch
reality,'' because it included military activities planned and
executed by the United States without any advice or support from
the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Dimoff, whose organization supports and studies the United
Nations, said that the spectacle in the Security Council of a
member of Congress and not the president purporting to speak for
the American people on foreign affairs ``demonstrates how the
Clinton administration has ceded all the ground of U.S.
policymaking on the U.N. to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``The appearance today,'' he said, ``is symbolic of the extent
to which Congress is now ge.''
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of France and Canada also challenged Helms on
his budget assertions and his denials that the burden of American
arrears had fallen on poor nations. Helms had said that the
American people had ``heard U.N. officials declaring, absurdly,
that countries like Fiji and Bangladesh are carrying America's
burden in peacekeeping.''
</P>
<P>
   Canada's representative, Robert Fowler, replied: ``Senator, I
don't know if I am a U.N. official. I don't think I am. But I am
somebody who has spoken recently about Fiji and Bangladesh. I noted
that in 1999 Bangladesh was owed approximately $18 million, or just
under 175 times its regular budget contributions to this
organization, and that Fiji was owed $4 million, or just under 100
times its regular budget assessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``In that 60 percent of all monies owed to the United Nations
are owed by the United States, 60 percent of those numbers are owed
by Americans to Bangladeshis and to Fijians,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Peter van Walsum, the representative of the Netherlands, told
Helms that he had been taught in school that the collapse of the
League of Nations, which the United States had refused to join, had
led to World War II. ``I am mentioning this,'' he said, ``because
you will realize that for not just Dutchmen of my generation but
for all of us, it is a nightmare to envision a United Nations
without the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``We continue to hope that one day the majority of the American
people, including the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, will
appreciate everything this organization has done for the spread of
democratic ideas all over the world,'' he said. ``All the American
and Dutch taxpayers' money spent on this organization has been a
wise investment.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-00 2241EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
