<DOCNO> NYT20000120.0386 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 22:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1890 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CT-GREENWICH-SLAYING-     01-20 1160
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CT-GREENWICH-SLAYING-(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG, SLOW ROAD TO TRIAL IN 25-YEAR-OLD SLAYING CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)  (lh) 
 By PAUL ZIELBAUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ On Wednesday, state prosecutors charged
Michael C. Skakel with killing 15-year-old Martha Moxley in
Greenwich almost 25 years ago, tight-lipped but confident they had
finally solved a baffling case.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the case seemed to be moving right along. A court
date was set for Feb. 8, when Skakel, a nephew of Ethel Kennedy who
has long maintained his innocence, is to appear for a closed
hearing to set a second court date in which he can enter his plea.
</P>
<P>
   But that is where the case will probably begin to bog down
faster than rush-hour traffic on Interstate 95.
</P>
<P>
   Experts on Connecticut's criminal justice system said Thursday
that despite the huge break Skakel's arrest signifies in the case,
his prosecution would most likely encounter years of legal tie-ups,
and Skakel, a Florida resident who was released on $500,000 bond,
is not likely to be acquitted or incarcerated anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   That is largely because of the amount of time that has passed
since Miss Moxley was found face down under a tree in her yard,
bludgeoned and stabbed to death with a golf club the police later
traced to a set owned by Skakel's mother.
</P>
<P>
   Because he was only 15 when Miss Moxley was killed, Skakel was
charged as a minor, said Jonathan Benedict, the state's attorney in
Bridgeport who is expected to lead the prosecution team. So
Skakel's Feb. 8 hearing will be in Stamford Juvenile Court, not
state Superior Court, where adults accused of murder in Connecticut
are prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
   The only way Skakel, 39, will be eligible for any meaningful
punishment, legal scholars said, is if he is convicted in Superior
Court, where he could face a maximum sentence if convicted of life
in prison. But the decision to move the case there will be up to
the Juvenile Court judge, Maureen Dennise. And there is debate
about whether she, viewing Skakel's case through the laws that
existed in 1975, has the authority to make such a move.
</P>
<P>
   If his case remains in Juvenile Court, Skakel could escape
punishment altogether, said David Rosen, a senior research
associate at Yale Law School. That is because the court system that
handled juveniles 25 years ago operated on a philosophy of
rehabilitating youthful offenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``The juvenile justice system in 1975 was not trying to punish
people,'' Rosen said Thursday. ``Its aim was to assist youngsters
that ran afoul of the law, even in heinous ways. It was taking and
making them law-abiding adults.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was accused of committing a crime as a child,'' Rosen went
on, ``and he's now an adult. The juvenile justice system, which is
the system he ran afoul of, simply may not apply.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, if Skakel had been one year older or two years younger
at the time of Miss Moxley's murder, the case against him now would
be entirely different, said Hillary Barger, the prosecutor in
Bridgeport Juvenile Court.
</P>
<P>
   Under Connecticut law, in 1975 as now, anyone older than 16 is
an adult in the eyes of the court system and is eligible to be
tried for murder as an adult, she said. But regardless of the crime
committed, the law prohibits a court from incarcerating children
younger than 14, preferring to rehabilitate them.
</P>
<P>
   When Miss Moxley was killed in 1975, children 14 and 15 years
old were the only minors whose legal status as criminals was left
to a Juvenile Court judge to decide. And because the courts were
guided by the goal of treatment rather than punishment for juvenile
offenders, judges almost never moved cases involving youths accused
of murder to an adult court, said Hugh F. Keefe, a criminal defense
lawyer in New Haven.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Keefe said he could remember that happening only once in
Connecticut. In 1974, a Juvenile Court judge in New Haven allowed
the murder case against 14-year-old Eric Washington, an accused
accomplice in the shooting death of a Yale student, to be
transferred to Superior Court, where a jury convicted him.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, as in Skakel's, Keefe noted, ``There was a
terrific amount of pressure because of the notoriety and nature of
the crime.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But other quirks in Connecticut's changing child welfare laws
are likely to delay any trial in the Skakel case for some time,
legal experts said. And even if the case is transferred, Skakel's
lawyer, Michael Sherman, is expected to do something that, though
not possible today, was common in 1975: appeal. If he does, a state
Appeals Court will then decide whether to overturn any move to
Superior Court, a process that can easily take a year, and often
two years, to complete.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, the state Legislature enacted a statute that made
automatic the transfer to Superior Court of juveniles 14 or older
charged with major felonies, Ms. Barger said. Notably, the statute
also eliminated the ability of the juvenile to appeal the transfer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this had happened under the new statute, this is a
one-minute hearing and the case would proceed in adult court,'' Ms.
Barger said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, as they began planning the best strategy to convict
Skakel, prosecutors in Benedict's office refused to take phone
calls from reporters. But there is no doubt the state's attorney
had Skakel arrested so that he could be tried in Superior Court as
an adult, even if it means enduring years of appeals from Sherman,
who did not return phone calls Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Benedict, the prosecutor, must build his case without the help
of any forensic evidence that could link Skakel to the crime, say
those who have written books about the case. So he must rely on
circumstantial, but powerful, evidence, said Mark Fuhrman, the
former Los Angeles police detective whose 1998 book, ``Murder in
Greenwich: Who killed Martha Moxley?'' named Skakel as the likely
murderer.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to paint a picture of Michael in every way that
they can paint a picture of his emotional state, his relationship
with Martha, his relationship to his brother,'' said Fuhrman,
referring to Thomas Skakel, who at one time was also a suspect in
the killing.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly damning to Michael Skakel, he added, will be sworn
testimony from three people who attended a treatment center in
Maine with him 20 years ago, in which Skakel is recalled admitting
to Miss Moxley's murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strongest evidence is that three independent people are
coming forward and testifying that he admitted that he killed
Martha,'' Fuhrman said. ``It's going to be long, drawn out and
protracted, but I think it's going to be a legal case, not an
emotional case.''
</P>
<P>
   But if the case is kept in Juvenile Court, everything changes.
There will be no jury, no evidence and no trial. A single judge
will decide Skakel's fate in a decision that will be sealed from
public scrutiny.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
