<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 22:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1891 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NJ-SETONHALL-FIRE-ART     01-20 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-SETONHALL-FIRE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUESTIONS AND GRIEF A DAY AFTER DEADLY DORMITORY FIRE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By DAN BARRY and ROBERT HANLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTH ORANGE, N.J. _ Seton Hall University administrators
Thursday defended their fire safety procedures as investigators
continued to search for the cause of the dormitory fire that killed
three freshmen and injured dozens more early Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   On the Roman Catholic university's campus here, questions
swirled with the gently falling snow: How did the fire in Boland
Hall start? Why have false fire alarms plagued the dormitory, for
so many years? Why doesn't the dormitory have a sprinkler system?
Why weren't there fire drills at Boland Hall?
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Grider, a spokeswoman for Seton Hall, acknowledged Thursday
that there had been no fire drills at Boland, at least during this
academic year. But she said the university's lawyer, Katherine
Kiernan, had assured her that the university had been in compliance
with state fire safety laws. In addition, resident assistants are
taught how to evacuate the dormitories, she said.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, investigators continued to examine the third-floor
lounge where the fire began, and interviewed some of the 600 Boland
residents who had awoken to screams and smoke about 4:30 a.m.
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   One person close to the inquiry said investigators also wanted
to identity and talk to three young people who were in the Boland
lounge less than an hour before the fire began. The person said
that a resident assistant in Boland had encountered the three, whom
she did not recognize, and had asked them to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Donald C. Campolo, the Essex County prosecutor, whose office is
leading the investigation, would not comment Thursday on the
resident assistant's account, which was first reported Thursday in
The Star-Ledger, other than to say, ``We are following up every
lead.'' The person close to the inquiry emphasized that the desire
to talk to the three people did not mean that investigators
believed they were responsible for the fire.
</P>
<P>
   Campolo did, however, dispute a Star-Ledger report that
investigators had eliminated careless smoking and faulty electrical
wiring as possible causes. His executive assistant, Charlotte
Smith, later said, ``We are not making any determination as to
whether it's accidental or not.''
</P>
<P>
   The fire scorched the lounge floor, popped ceiling tiles,
consumed two couches and sent clouds of smoke throughout the
freshman dormitory's six floors, disorienting and frightening many
of the 600 residents who rushed from the building.
</P>
<P>
   Three 18-year-old male students were killed. Two were burned to
death in the lounge; the third, found in a room nearby, died of
smoke inhalation. More than 50 students were injured, including 4
who were in critical condition Thursday at St. Barnabas Medical
Center in Livingston.
</P>
<P>
   Twice a semester the resident assistants are required to hold
floor meetings with students under their supervision to discuss
fire safety, evacuation plans and the location of all exits from
the building.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Grider said the university would review its policies and
consider changes to ensure that ``something like this never, ever
happens again.'' When asked if such options included installing
sprinklers in Boland, she answered: ``Absolutely.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the six dormitories on campus, the two oldest _ Boland Hall
and Aquinas Hall _ do not have sprinkler systems. The authorities
said that the buildings were constructed well before the state
required that all large residential buildings be equipped with
sprinklers.
</P>
<P>
   The question of whether to retrofit buildings like dormitories
and high-rise apartments _ even without any legal requirement _ has
long spurred debate among developers and fire safety officials.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth O. Burris Jr., the chief operating officer for the
United States Fire Administration, a branch of the Federal
Emergency Management Agency, said that experts had ``recognized for
quite a number of years that automatic fire suppression systems,''
like sprinklers, ``are the most effective method.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``It is also the most difficult system to have developers and
buildings put in because of the perceived expense involved,''
Burris said.
</P>
<P>
   Claudia Hutton, the spokeswoman for the New York State Dormitory
Authority, the agency that builds dormitories for the State
University of New York system, said that ``whenever we rehab an old
dorm or whenever we build a new dorm, we put sprinklers in.,''
</P>
<P>
   At Felician College in Lodi, N.J., administrators have been
considering installing sprinklers in its Milton Court dormitory,
which houses 50 students. But a college spokeswoman, Nancy Haidock,
said the Seton Hall fire would probably expedite the
decision-making process. Justin Harmon, a spokesman for Princeton
University, said that some of its older dormitories did not have
sprinklers, but added that the university hads a policy of
installing them whenever buildings awere renovated.
</P>
<P>
   At Seton Hall, where classes have been canceled until at least
Monday, several students talked about the lackadaisical culture
regarding fire alarms. False alarms ring so often in Boland Hall,
they said, that students often ignore them or try to hide from
resident assistants sweeping the floors. The culprits are often
pranksters, they said, or pledges seeking membership in a
fraternity.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Grider said that the university had taken several steps over
the years to curtail false alarms. Although she declined to be
specific other than to cite an article in the campus newspaper last
year that implored students to end the practice, the university has
offered rewards, threatened expulsion and posted notices saying
that the pranks are illegal.
</P>
<P>
   As if to underscore the point, a fire alarm rang through another
dormitory, Xavier Hall, Thursday morning, prompting the evacuation
of about 200 students. Officials later said a student had pulled
the alarm after mistakenly thinking she smelled smoke.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody took it seriously,'' said Sam Kissim, 22, a student
from Los Angeles. ``Two months ago, nobody would have gone out.'''
</P>
<P>
   As the university's students mourned the deaths of the three
freshmen _ Frank S. Caltabilota, Aaron C. Karol and John C. Giunta,
all from New Jersey _ stories emerged of quiet heroism and searches
for solance.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Nugent, a sophomore from Northfield, N.J., appeared at a
news conference to tell his story and to ask reporters to allow him
to be ``left alone to deal with the deaths of my friends and
residents.''
</P>
<P>
   Nugent, a resident assistant in Boland, recalled rousting
students from their rooms, and grabbing the arms of one student who
was ``in bad shape'' and escorting her down the stairs. He said he
returned to the smoke-filled third floor to lead more residents
out, this time by crawling, ``as I was taught in training.''
</P>
<P>
   After flames thwarted another effort to return to the third
floor, he said, he and another resident assistant went outside,
grabbed a ladder and helped some students escape through a window.
Nugent said that he and another student then spent time with a
badly injured young man, ``taking a wet towel to cool off his
burns,'' until firefighters arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone in Boland really pulled together,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The recollections of Msgr. Robert Sheeran, the president of
Seton Hall, were more sobering. He said that after the fire had
been extinguished, he and Archbishop Theodore McCarrick, the leader
of the Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Newark, walked through the
dormitory's third floor. Together they knelt before the bodies of
the three young men who had died.
</P>
<P>
   ``We prayed over each of them,'' Sheeran said, ``and we blessed
them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
