<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA'S BALLOT MORE DEMOCRATIC THAN NEW YORK'S, MCCAIN SUGGESTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Sen. John McCain chose the stretch of East 91st
Street that is home to the Russian consulate to offer New Yorkers a
piece of political theater Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   As the snow fell and the white, blue and red Russian flag
whipped back and forth, the Republican presidential aspirant said
citizens of Russia enjoy greater voting rights than their
counterparts in New York, given the Republican Party's tradition of
blocking bids by underdog candidates to get on the presidential
primary ballot.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Russia, there will be more than one name on the ballot'' in
its coming presidential election, McCain said. ``In New York,
unless something happens, there will be only one name on the
ballot. It seems to me that history has been turned on its head.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain and his backers have gone to court to challenge a move by
lawyers for the New York Republican State Committee to knock the
Arizona senator off the March 7 primary ballot in as many as 16 of
New York's 31 congressional districts. The committee has challenged
signatures on McCain's nominating petitions as not belonging to
registered voters or to Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Party leaders declined to comment. But Gov. George W.
Bush of Texas, who is considered the leading contender for the
nomination, suggested that McCain should stick by the established
rules. ``People must get grass-roots support to get on the ballot
in New York,'' Bush said at a news conference in Pella, Iowa.
``It's been this way for every single campaign.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-00 2244EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000120.0390 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 22:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1894 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i BC-MEXICO-UNIVERSITY-HNS     01-20 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-UNIVERSITY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICS BLAMED AS STUDENT STRIKE DRAGS ON IN MEXICO 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DUDLEY ALTHAUS 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Julio Cesar Morales spent much of Thursday morning
searching for a place to vote in favor of ending a student strike
that has closed Mexico's largest university since last spring.
</P>
<P>
   Clutching a copy of the thesis he needs to turn in before he can
graduate from its law school, Morales trekked to the campus of the
National Autonomous University on the south side of the Mexican
capital to vote ``yes'' to a proposal by the school's
administration.
</P>
<P>
   He was turned away at the school's front gate by rough-looking
strikers whose leaders refused to allow any voting to take place on
university grounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of interests involved in continuing this
strike,'' shrugged the nattily dressed Morales, who took time off
from his paralegal job to vote. ``There are manipulations by
political parties on all sides.''
</P>
<P>
   The strike began last April when the university administration
tried to raise tuition from the equivalent of 2 U.S. cents a
semester to around $70 per semester. Although cheap by U.S.
standards, $140-a-year tuition is high for many of the university's
students who come from working-class families.
</P>
<P>
   In the past nine months, through street marches, media campaigns
and occasional brawls, the strikers forced the university's
administration to back down on the tuition increases and other
issues.
</P>
<P>
   But each time the university administration and the Mexican
government ceded to the students' demands, the strikers kept
changing them. The hard-liners who had taken control of the
strikers' committees seem guided by an often-vague leftist creed
that rejects everything from free-market economics to Mexico's
long-ruling political party.
</P>
<P>
   So, the university remains closed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't a student movement. It's political,'' said Pedro
Sanchez, a 30-year-old graduate of the university who works in its
administrative offices. ``If all this were just about student
demands, it would have been finished a long time ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramon de la Fuente, the former health minister who was appointed
university president last November, hopes an overwhelming vote in
favor of returning to classes will give his administration the
moral force needed to bring an end to the strike.
</P>
<P>
   De la Fuente has called for creating a special congress of
students and university employees to determine the future of the
school, for canceling the tuition increase and for granting amnesty
to strike leaders who may have broken the law.
</P>
<P>
   But the strike leaders claim about 600,000 people voted in their
own ``consultation'' held Tuesday and Wednesday. The vote was open
to everyone and so poorly supervised that people could cast as many
ballots as they pleased. Student leaders said 85 percent of the
votes were in favor of maintaining the strike until their demands
were met.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know what the administration wants to do with their vote.
They are going to say a majority wants to return to class,'' said
Victor Garcia, a beefy 25-year-old striker who studied history at
the university until nine months ago. ``But we had our own vote,
and it supported us.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia, one of a dozen strikers manning the barricaded front
gate of the three-square-mile campus Thursday, said, ``This isn't
about a few cents of tuition. It's about keeping the university
free and open to everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   The once-vibrant campus stands silent. Sprinklers pump jets of
water onto empty lawns. Gardeners trim the edges of walkways and
cut the grass. A few office workers take advantage of their lunch
break to exercise on the fields.
</P>
<P>
   Strike slogans have been splashed on every wall. ``All poetry is
revolution. All revolution, poetry,'' theorizes a scrawl on the
philosophy building. ``Mexicans against the system,'' urges
another. And this from Che Guevara, the long-dead Argentine
revolutionary who helped bring Fidel Castro to power in Cuba and
who has become the strikers' icon: ``He who consents to his
exploitation begins to acquire the soul of a slave.''
</P>
<P>
   As much as anything, the strike reflects the profound changes
that have swept Mexican society and politics in the past decade and
a half.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the strike began, the National University had lost
much of its luster. In just 30 years, enrollment exploded from
around 85,000 to today's 270,000 students.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, a degree from the National University was all
but a needed passport for entering the leadership of the ruling
Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI. Now, most children of
Mexico's political and economic elite study at expensive private
universities in Mexico or abroad. With their world-weary slouches,
sparse beards and knee-patched trousers, today's strikers evoke the
image of the leftist revolutionaries who once held this country and
the rest of Latin America in thrall.
</P>
<P>
   A 1968 student strike, which ended in the army's massacre of
hundreds of protestors in downtown Mexico City that October, helped
spur the push for greater democracy in this once-authoritarian
society.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the leaders from the 1968 strikes have become prominent
in national politics, both within the PRI and in the leftist Party
of the Democratic Revolution, which has governed Mexico City for
more than two years.
</P>
<P>
   And many of those former student rebels have publicly called for
an end to the current strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those old leaders are part of the system now,'' said Gomez,
the student striker. ``They use the same tactics against us now
that their oppressors did back then. They have forgotten the
demands they fought for.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-00 2245EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
