<DOCNO> NYT20000120.0391 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 22:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1895 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-LABOR-CLEANUP-NYT &LR;      01-20 0564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABOR-CLEANUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LABORERS UNION CLEANUP PRAISED; U.S. OVERSIGHT IS EASED 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: LABOR-CORRUPTION)  
(lh) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Justice Department agreed Thursday to relax its oversight of
the Laborers union after five years of threatening to take over the
union if the efforts by the Laborers to root out corruption
stumbled.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials said Thursday that they were so pleased with
the union's own cleanup efforts that the government was giving up
its option to run the Laborers.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department officials praised the Laborers' five-year
cleanup effort, which union officials said removed 220 corrupt
officials from union positions, including 127 found to be members
or associates of organized crime.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement announced Thursday by the Justice Department
and Laborers International Union of North America, the union
pledged to continue its self-policing efforts through the year
2006. These efforts have involved an internal union prosecutor,
judge and appellate officer, as well as dozens of investigators,
including numerous former FBI agents.
</P>
<P>
   In the new agreement, the Justice Department reserved the right
to seek an injunction that would order the 750,000-member union to
make good on its cleanup promises.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant Attorney General James Robinson, said, ``We're not
walking away from reform in the union, but substantial progress has
been made.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, the Justice Department threatened to file a civil
racketeering suit that would have accused the union and its
leaders, including its president, Arthur A. Coia, of being
influenced by organized crime.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department decided not to pursue that lawsuit in an
unusual agreement in which the union pledged to set up what was the
largest effort undertaken by a union to clean its own house.
Republican officials attacked that agreement, asserting that the
Clinton administration had decided to go soft on the Laborers
because President Clinton was friendly with Coia.
</P>
<P>
   The two had given each other golf clubs, and Coia had served as
co-chairman for several Democratic Party fund-raisers, while his
union contributed generously to Democratic causes.
</P>
<P>
   But the administration defended the deal, noting that dozens of
union officials were ousted. Indeed, Coia agreed to retire last
month, saying that he had served long enough and was tired of being
hounded by investigators.
</P>
<P>
   The internal investigation cleared Coia of ties to organized
crime, but it found that he had violated some laws in purchasing a
$450,000 Ferrari from a supplier that leased cars to his union.
</P>
<P>
   Several labor experts said the Justice Department would never
have considered relaxing oversight of the Laborers until Coia had
stepped down. But union officials said Coia's retirement had
nothing to do with Thursday's agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Luskin, the Laborers' in-house prosecutor, said, ``In the
five years since these reform programs were first adopted, LIUNA
has made extraordinary strides in eliminating the influence of
organized crime and corruption.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that the government has agreed to ease its oversight of the
Laborers, the International Brotherhood of Teamsters can be
expected to intensify its campaign to get the federal government to
relax its far more intrusive oversight of the teamsters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
