<HEADLINE>
MRS. CLINTON TO MEET WITH ALBANY LEGISLATORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y _ Hillary Rodham Clinton will meet on Monday in the
state Capitol with Democratic legislators, an unusual gathering
that shows how much each camp needs the other in this election
year.
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly speaker, Sheldon Silver, invited Mrs. Clinton, who
is running for the U.S. Senate, to speak to a closed-door
conference of the Assembly Democrats, the first time in three years
that an outside political figure has been asked to such a
gathering. The last person to receive such an invitation was
Charles Schumer, a former Assembly member who was then a
congressman, as he prepared in 1997 for his successful run for the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Silver also invited the Democrats in the state Senate, who are
the minority in their house, to attend.
</P>
<P>
   For Mrs. Clinton, the 124 Democrats in the Legislature represent
a powerful political network, with cadres of supporters in every
corner of the state who can do the legwork needed to run a
statewide campaign and get out the vote. She has worked hard in the
last year courting Silver, who is from Manhattan, and other
important members of the Assembly's Democratic majority.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are absolutely committed to running an on-the-ground,
grass-roots campaign in every part of the state,'' said Howard
Wolfson, a spokesman for Mrs. Clinton's campaign, ``and in order to
do that, we're going to need the help of members of the Assembly
and the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   Although she is expected to fare well in New York City, polls
show Mrs. Clinton lagging in the suburbs and upstate, so she
especially needs the help of people like the Assembly majority
leader, Michael Bragman, one of the most powerful figures in
central New York, and Assemblyman Thomas DiNapoli, the Nassau
County Democratic Party chairman.
</P>
<P>
   For the potential Republican candidate for Senate, Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani, the Republican majority in the state Senate is expected
to play much the same role around the state, and the mayor has
spent a great deal of time building ties to the Senate majority
leader, Joseph Bruno.
</P>
<P>
   Legislators in both parties believe that the stakes are high for
them in the Senate race. All 211 legislative seats are up for
election this year, and the leaders in both houses see having a
strong Senate candidate to draw voters to the polls as their best
bet for holding onto power.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
