<SLUG> BC-TAIWAN-CHINA-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAIWAN CANDIDATE EASES ON CHINA POLICY 
</HEADLINE>
  (SUBS to correct month of election in lede graf.) 
(lh) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan _ In a move that could ease tensions between
Taiwan and China during the campaign here before the presidential
election in March, the candidate of the governing Nationalist Party
declined Thursday to reaffirm the government's policy of dealing
with China ``state to state.''
</P>
<P>
   The candidate, Vice President Lien Chan, said the policy, which
President Lee Teng-hui announced unexpectedly in July, merely
reflected the reality of relations between Taiwan and China.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not reaffirming it, because that has been the constant
position,'' Lien said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Lee's original statement was widely interpreted here
and in Beijing as a crucial step away from the premise that Taiwan
and China are two parts of the same country. The notion of ``one
China'' was the basis of sporadic talks between Taiwan and China.
Beijing angrily broke off contact after Lee's statement, and said
he was setting the stage for Taiwan's independence, something that
China has vowed to prevent, by military force if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Lien said Taiwan wanted ``parity'' in negotiations
with China, ``nothing more, nothing less.'' Political analysts said
with the election less than two months away and with Lien's
trailing in many polls, the vice president was trying to distance
himself from Lee, who has become a lightning rod for Beijing's
impatience toward what it views as a renegade province.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that at this moment we could make ourselves very clear
to them,'' said Lien, 60, a political scientist and protege of
Lee's. ``Taiwan will not go independent. But Taiwan cannot reunite
with the PRC for the foreseeable future, because it is simply
impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   In another gesture, Lien said he would consider relaxing
restrictions on trade with China if relations improved. Under Lee,
Taiwan has maintained strict limits on trade in military and
technology-related products and on investments in Chinese public
works.
</P>
<P>
   Lien's campaign manager, Jason Hu, said the candidate would
offer more details about his China policy in a few days. Political
analysts here expect the vice president to offer a new linguistic
formulation that avoids the inflammatory phrase ``state to state
relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   To a large extent, the debate over Lee's statement is an
exercise in semantics rather than diplomacy. But words matter
greatly in the halting dialogue between Taiwan and China. And
Lien's more circumspect words are quite likely to be welcomed in
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the Chinese government issued yet another warning,
saying that the election, on March 18, ``must not lead to a split
or Taiwan independence.'' A spokesman for the Foreign Ministry, Zhu
Bangzao, said, ``No matter who becomes Taiwan's leader, it should
benefit the development of relations between the two sides and
China's peaceful reunification.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Lien has crept up in popularity polls recently, he
remains in second or third place in most surveys, behind Chen
Shui-bian, a former mayor of Taipei and the leader of the
Democratic Progressive Party, and James Soong, a former Nationalist
Party official who is running as an independent.
</P>
<P>
   As the vote nears, nerves are fraying. In 1996, in the last
presidential campaign, Beijing fired missiles into the ocean near
Taiwan to intimidate voters. Chen's party platform calls for an
independent Taiwan, although Chen has said he would make no
precipitous moves, and Lien is calculating that he can draw votes
away from his rival by promoting himself as the man least likely to
provoke a hostile response from Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   While Lien is reaching out to China, he also appealed to the
United States not to abandon its support of Taiwan. ``After so many
years,'' he said, ``we find that American policy seems to lay more
emphasis on one side, the PRC side, and the Taiwanese side is not
emphasized as much as it needs to be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
