<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1941 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-RAC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     01-20 1320
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAN B FOR ANEES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA _ Alex Hassinger's tuxedo is back on the hanger. The
trainer wore work clothes _ blue jeans and a plaid shirt _ as he
sat behind his desk in The Thoroughbred Corp.'s barn at Santa Anita
Thursday morning and pondered the task ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Hassinger's job is to win the Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Anees, the colt he trained to a 30-1 victory in the Breeders'
Cup Juvenile at Gulfstream Park in November, was named winner of
the Eclipse Award for the outstanding 2-year-old of 1999 at a
black-tie dinner in Beverly Hills on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the evening, Richard Mulhall, racing manager for Saudi
Prince Ahmed Salman's Thoroughbred Corp., said of Anees: ``I think
he'll win the Derby.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to put any pressure on Hassinger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he has a lot of attributes going into his 3-year-old
campaign that anybody would want to have in a horse,'' Hassinger
said Thursday, demonstrating he shares the owners' confidence.
``Physical and mental capacity, pedigree for distance, conformation
for distance _ I think it adds up to a pretty nice horse.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looks like a Michael Jordan now. He's filled out, gotten a
little taller. He's one of those horses who, when they train, make
it look easy.''
</P>
<P>
   It isn't easy, though. Anees might be the winter-book Derby
favorite, but opponents are lining up. One of those opponents is
injury and another is bad luck.
</P>
<P>
   Anees, a son of 1990 Derby winner Unbridled and grandson of 1978
runner-up Alydar, had to miss two weeks of training after bruising
his left hind foot in a December workout at Santa Anita. He
returned to the track to jog on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we lost time, which hurt,'' Hassinger said.
</P>
<P>
   He preaches the importance of following a firm schedule of prep
races _ with carefully chosen alternatives if weather or other
variables interfere _ leading to the May 6 Derby. Plan A, to start
Anees' season with the Jan. 30 Santa Catalina Stakes, had to be
scrapped because of the foot problem.
</P>
<P>
   Now Hassinger is aiming for the 1-mile San Rafael on March 4 or
the 1 1/16-mile San Felipe on March 19 _ or both _ as a prep for
the 1-mile Santa Anita Derby on April 8. Then on to Churchill
Downs, 1 miles from immortality.
</P>
<P>
   Anees will be nominated for all of the nation's major Derby
preps just in case.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever the colt, who won twice in four starts at age 2, does
start the new season, he'll have a new jockey aboard. Gary Stevens
retired suddenly on Dec. 26 because of painful arthritis in his
right knee. Hassinger said there's no hurry to choose a
replacement.
</P>
<P>
   Hassinger, 37, has been a trainer off and on for seven years.
Hired by The Thoroughbred Corp. last spring, he had an immediate
success when Patience Game won the Derby Trial, earning starts in
the Preakness and Belmont Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   But his experience with good young horses goes back to 1991,
when, as assistant to Allen Paulson's private trainer, Dick Lundy,
Hassinger handled Dinard.
</P>
<P>
   Dinard and jockey Chris McCarron overcame a rocky first turn to
win the Santa Anita Derby and would have been favorites in
Louisville. But Dinard was injured in a workout a week before the
race and didn't compete again for months.
</P>
<P>
   The experience taught Hassinger how much can go wrong on the way
to the Derby. He thinks the mistake was running Dinard in a sprint
between two early-season routes. In other words, failing to follow
a firm prep schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Hassinger's planning has been complicated already by Anees' foot
injury.
</P>
<P>
   The colt also must overcome two jinxes _ no Breeders' Cup
Juvenile winner in that event's 16-year history has won the Derby,
and no 2-year-old champion has won it since Spectacular Bid in
1979. But Hassinger doesn't think Anees is one of those horses who
peak at 2 and don't grow up.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looks and acts like a different horse than before the
Breeders' Cup,'' the trainer said.
</P>
<P>
   Anees, who showed the ability to come from behind after a rough
start in the Breeders' Cup, is easy enough to picture in the
Kentucky Derby winner's circle. But it won't be that easy.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend: The Bob Baffert-trained 4-year-old
Hookedonthefeelin, 5 for 6 after beating her age group in the La
Brea, takes on older fillies and mares in the Santa Monica Handicap
Saturday at Santa Anita. The 7-furlong race is the first Grade I
stakes of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Cash Run will have Jerry Bailey in town to ride in Sunday's
Santa Ynez Stakes as she makes her first start since her long-shot
victory in the Breeders' Cup Juvenile Fillies.
</P>
<P>
   There's always a catch: Oaklawn Park in Arkansas is taking bets
on races that have already been run. It's not as easy as it sounds.
</P>
<P>
   Video machines take bets of 25 cents or $1 on 10-horse races
from the past. Fans get skimpy past-performance information and
aren't told where or when each race was held or who ran.
</P>
<P>
   The machines are called ``Thoroughbred Mania.'' We prefer the
sound of the dog-track equivalent, in use elsewhere in Arkansas:
``Thundering Hounds.''
</P>
<P>
   A WEEK AT THE RACES
</P>
<P>
   Santa Anita leaders: Jockeys (going into Thursday's races):
Corey Nakatani, 22 wins; Kent Desormeaux, 16; David Flores and Alex
Solis, 14; Pat Valenzuela, 13. Trainers: Bob Baffert, 10; Bobby
Frankel, 8; Ron McAnally, 7; Ron Ellis, 6; Richard Mandella, 5.
</P>
<P>
   Pincay watch: Laffit Pincay, seventh in the Santa Anita
standings with 11 wins from 76 mounts, has extended his record for
career victories to 8,855. He rode Cee Dreams to a claiming-level
victory in Thursday's fifth race.
</P>
<P>
   On the stakes schedule: At Santa Anita: Saturday, $200,000 Santa
Monica Handicap, fillies and mares aged 4 and up, 7 furlongs, and
$150,000 San Marcos Handicap, 4-year-olds and up, 1 miles on turf;
Sunday, $100,000 Santa Ynez Stakes, 3-year-old fillies, 7 furlongs.
At Gulfstream Park: Saturday, $100,000 Canadian Turf Handicap,
3-year-olds and up, 1 miles on turf.
</P>
<P>
   Mileposts: Del Mar Futurity winner Forest Camp, considered a
Kentucky Derby contender before his poor effort in the Breeders'
Cup Juvenile, is being turned out for two to three months because
of unspecified soreness, said his new trainer Eduardo Inda. Also,
Prime Timber will miss the Feb. 5 Strub with hind-foot problems,
said Inda, who took over Aaron and Marie Jones' horses from Bob
Baffert recently.... Breeders' Cup Juvenile runner-up Chief Seattle
is on his way to the lavish training site in Dubai after being
purchased for undisclosed millions by Godolphin Racing, and could
be Sheikh Mohammed's Derby hope, this year's Worldly Manner....
Menifee, the horse who ran second to Charismatic in the 1999
Kentucky Derby and Preakness, is going to stud after injuring an
ankle in training.... The Hollywood Gold Cup will be held two weeks
later in 2000, on Sunday, July 9, allowing contenders time to run
in the Stephen Foster at Churchill Downs on Saturday, June 17.
Hollywood Park is owned by Churchill Downs, so such cooperation
makes sense. The schedule for the Inglewood track's April 28-July
24 season includes the April 30 California Gold Rush Day, featuring
five existing Cal-bred stakes and one new creation on a $1 million
card.... Bay Meadows, in San Mateo, opened a 49-day season
Thursday, with repairs made to the turf course that was closed
during the fall meet. First post most days is 12:45 p.m., Fridays
7:15. Marquee race: the March 11 El Camino Real Derby.... Santa
Anita's Frank Stronach is adding a sixth U.S. racetrack to his
holdings. It's Great Lake Downs, a western Michigan track that
opened in 1999.... Jockey Pat Valenzuela begins a three-day
suspension Saturday for being disqualified along with Outstanding
Hero in a Jan. 13 race at Santa Anita.... Handicapping feat of the
century: The Daily News' Bob Ike picked seven winners on Sunday's
nine-race card at Santa Anita.
</P>
</TEXT>
