<SLUG> BC-GLF-HOPE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KRAFT, BEEM SHARE HOPE LEAD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY MORGAN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERMUDA DUNES -- Greg Kraft shares the 36-hole lead with Rich
Beem in the $3 million Bob Hope Chrysler Classic, but the
35-year-old has more important things on his mind than winning a
golf tournament.
</P>
<P>
   He's worried about his favorite football team, the Tampa Bay
Buccaneers, who play the St. Louis Rams in Sunday's NFC
Championship. The winner advances to the Super Bowl in Atlanta
later this month.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft said he thinks he knows how the Bucs can win.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way is to get that quarterback and hurt him,'' he
said. ``I like the underdog role, and I just hope the Bucs get in
there early.''
</P>
<P>
   Kraft certainly is the hunt early this week. He has
back-to-backs 65s which leave him tied with Beem, a tour rookie
last season who once quit the game to sell cellular phones and
stereo systems in Seattle, at 14-under-par 130. Another shot behind
is a group that includes Brent Geiberger, who had a 61 at Indian
Wells, first-round leader David Toms (68), Barry Cheesman (62 at
PGA West) and Andrew Magee (65).
</P>
<P>
   Kraft did not have a single bogey in his round, which was played
at Indian Wells, which traditionally gives up the lowest numbers in
this 90-hole marathon. He birdied four consecutive holes in one
stretch of the front nine -- no putt was longer than 15 feet -- and
two of his three birdies on the back side were five-footers.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft said his driving has made the difference so far this week.
He ranked 74th on tour last year in driving accuracy (69.9
percent).
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hitting it well and the swing feels good,'' he said, ``but
I'm having a little trouble with in-between, feel shots. My timing
is a little off with that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to address that the next couple days and try to tune
it up for the weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   Toms, on the other hand, said he has not been driving the ball
well, despite fashioning a two-round total of 13-under 131. His
drive on the par-5, 564-yard 13th hole at Bermuda Dunes, for
example, went out of bounds and he wound up taking a double bogey.
He recovered with two birdies down the stretch, but that earlier
error did not sit well with him when the round was over.
</P>
<P>
   '``One of my amateur partners said, `I wish I could trade my par
for your double,' '' Toms said. ``It wasn't the first time, and it
won't be the last.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just lost my train of thought on it. Those things happen,
especially in a 90-hole tournament. But I hope that's the only time
it does this week.''
</P>
<P>
   Something unusual happened to Magee, who was Indian Wells.
Magee, who finished third in this tournament two years ago behind
Fred Couples (a playoff winer over Bruce Lietzke), hit a marshal
with his first drive of the day and bogeyed the hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hit him in a nice, soft spot,'' Magee said. ``It would have
ended up being a nice shot. I would have had a shot at the green.
He said he wasn't ready for the round to start and I said, `Well,
it started buddy. Let's go.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Lurking ominously behind the leaders are a large number of top
players, including Peter Jacobsen (64-133), last year's runner-up
Steve Pate (69-134) and the man he finished second to, David Duval,
who had a 67 and sits at 135.
</P>
<P>
   Duval, who played at La Quinta Thursday, said he faced only one
troublesome shot when his approach landed in a greenside bunker on
the par-4 14th hole, but he sank it for a birdie.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't look very good, and then it went in,'' he said.
``That sort of turned things around for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval was paired with Rush Lumbaugh and called it an unusual
experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's going to be a lot of peripheral things that aren't
necessarily conducive to good play,'' he said. ``I guess you have
to enjoy it as best you can.''
</P>
<P>
   Tour rookie Casey Martin had an even-par 71 at Bermuda Dunes and
is at 139. Rookie counterpart Gary Nicklaus improved from his
opening-round 74 to a 69 Thursday at Indian Wells and is at 143.
Arnold Palmer also shot lower, but not by much. He followed
Wednesday's 82 at PGA West with a 79 at La Quinta and is last in
the field of 128 players at 17-over 161.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
