<SLUG> BC-CHICAGO-BOARD-SPLIT-510&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHICAGO BOARD OF TRADE RECOMMENDS A SPLIT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mo.)  (rk) 
 By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Responding to the growing threat of competition from
electronic trading systems, the directors of the Chicago Board of
Trade voted overwhelming Thursday to split the exchange into two
for-profit companies.
</P>
<P>
   The directors of the board of trade, a pioneer in the buying and
selling of grain, metals and financial futures for more than 150
years, said they would recommend that the members approve a plan to
demutualize the corporation and divide the exchange into one
company devoted to ``open outcry'' floor trading and another
dedicated to electronic trading.
</P>
<P>
   The board's leadership hopes that the plan, creating two
independent and competitive entities, will help preserve and
enhance the old ways of doing business while developing a system to
capitalize on the growing movement toward low-cost electronic
trading.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a year, members of the board and top executives
have waged a nasty and often public internal battle over how best
to respond to the threat of electronic trading networks and whether
the rise of such trading foretells the demise of floor trading.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after several leading financial exchanges have decided to
move toward for-profit status and after the Chicago Board of Trade
lost its standing as the world's largest futures and options
exchange to Eurex, the Swiss and German electronic derivatives
exchange, the board says it is ready to create two companies that
will be more nimble, more competitive and less bureaucratic.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at the exchange say that the marketplace will be the
final arbiter. ``The CBOT must change if we are going to thrive in
an increasingly competitive environment,'' David P. Brennan,
chairman of the exchange, said in a letter to members Thursday.
``This restructuring plan is the `best of all worlds' because it
will help us to better serve the trading community, while providing
a more stable financial future for our members and customers.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the proposal, which requires approval by a
two-thirds vote of the exchange's 3,600 members, the board of trade
would have a privately held for-profit corporation behind the open
outcry system that has been used since 1848.
</P>
<P>
   The electronic trading operation, which the exchange expects to
spin off in an initial public offering, would compete directly with
the exchange as well as other electronic trading networks. Members
of the exchange, who own seats that allow them to trade on the
floor, will acquire an interest in both companies.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts say the change was inevitable. ``It's clear
electronic trading is the wave of the future, and everyone on the
equity and derivatives side is trying to come to grips with it,''
said S. Craig Pirrong, a professor of finance at Washington
University in St. Louis. ``There have been key tensions that
underlie all the exchanges _ those between the floor community and
the broker community. The brokerage community essentially wants
speed and low execution costs, and the floor community views
electronic trading as a clear threat to their livelihood.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the coming weeks, the board is expected to outline more
details about the restructuring plan, and Thursday several members
said they largely applauded the move, but there are serious
questions about how it would work.
</P>
<P>
   Jacob J. Morowitz, a soybean trader who has been a member of the
exchange for about 30 years, said that he was concerned about the
relationship between the two companies, who will run them and
whether the electronic unit should compete directly with the floor
traders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see the wisdom of this,'' he said. ``As soon as you
set two corporations in competition, you're going to empower one to
eat the other one. I don't know if that's in the best interest of
the customers or the members. If I made you chief executive of the
electronic side, you'd say what can I do to boost volume? Kill open
outcry. You'd want to kill the other guy, create a monopoly and
then raise prices.''
</P>
<P>
   Some traders, however, say that the decision to split into two
companies is the best solution for an exchange where the price of
seats has dropped more than 50 percent from their high last year,
partly over fears of electronic competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality of the world is electronic exchanges are going to
be created,'' said Jay Homan, a grain trader for more than 25
years. ``I will argue the two will coexist. But why would you want
to lose anything to someone else doing electronic trading when you
can do it yourself?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
