<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-BOND-SALES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 FIRST ONLINE OFFERING OF BONDS AT RETAIL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For Joe Moriarty, a computer consultant from
Parsippany, N.J., it was as easy as point and click to buy his
small share of the $3 billion in three-year notes sold by the World
Bank Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The new issue, with lead underwriters from Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co.
and Lehman Brothers, broke more Internet ground by taking a global
bond offering to the retail investor for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the use of the Internet for bond issues, which
is the direction the corporate bond market is moving, is raising a
question about the future role of sales representatives on Wall
Street _ the people who have dealt with customers for years,
providing information and points of view, taking orders and
sometimes just holding customers' hands.
</P>
<P>
   Victor Simone, Goldman's managing director for e-commerce, said:
``We do not envision a world without salespeople. We don't want our
customers to order on the Internet and then not hear from them
again.''
</P>
<P>
   But Tim Bacik, a fixed-income portfolio manager at Alliance
Capital who bought World Bank notes through the Internet on
Thursday, said, ``It appears that the role of the salesperson as it
currently exists will be diminished by the Internet.'' One of the
key roles that would be cut out is the provider of information on a
bond sale, because all of that can now be posted on an Internet Web
site.
</P>
<P>
   In explaining why Alliance used the Internet rather than the
traditional phone dealings with a sales representative, he said,
``We believe that the corporate bond market is moving in this
direction, and we want to keep on top of this development.'' He did
say that because Wall Street was still learning about Internet
sales, his transaction was backed up by a call from a sales
representative.
</P>
<P>
   About one-third of the new World Bank notes were sold over the
Internet, bought by the traditional large institutional investors
that always show up and the middle-level institutional investor,
including insurance companies and banks, and the retail investor,
which the World Bank was making an extra effort to reach in order
to broaden its audience.
</P>
<P>
   The retail sales were done through www.schwabbondsource.com, the
bond Web site for Charles Schwab. A Schwab spokeswoman said that
about 400 customers ordered the notes, with a third of those coming
over the Internet. The total sales were about $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   Moriarty, who said he was buying notes to help rebalance his
equity-heavy portfolio to 50 percent stocks and 50 percent bonds,
said he would not have bought the World Bank issue any other way.
``I don't have a financial relationship with any financial house
dealing in bonds,'' he said. He got his information on the bond
sale, including the expected yield, from the same Web site. But he
was informed of the coming sale, he said, by postcard.
</P>
<P>
   The World Bank notes, which are rated AAA, were priced to yield
7.122 percent, 48.5 basis points, or hundredths of 1 percentage
point, over the comparable Treasury issue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
