<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: TAKING DOWN THE FLAG 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times says in an editorial Friday, Jan. 21: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The entire nation is watching and listening to us,'' said Gov.
Jim Hodges of South Carolina, using his annual State of the State
Message on Wednesday to implore the legislature to remove the
Confederate battle flag that still flies ignominiously over the
Statehouse dome.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to break a longstanding legislative logjam over the
issue, which has led the NAACP to declare an economic boycott
against the state, Hodges called for a compromise. He proposed
moving the flag, a symbol of slavery and segregation to many
citizens, from its inappropriate place of prominence on the dome to
``a place of historical significance'' on the Statehouse grounds.
The legislature ought to take his advice and also heed his call to
end South Carolina's dubious distinction of being the sole state
that does not recognize Dr. Martin Luther King's birthday as a
state holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Hodges' challenge to the legislature makes the cowardly mumbling
on the issue by the leading Republican candidates for president,
Gov. George Bush and Sen. John McCain, look even more disgraceful
than it already seemed. By now the nation should be beyond this
sort of cynical abdication of leadership by serious candidates for
the White House. This is a controversy that reverberates far beyond
South Carolina. As Hodges said, the whole nation is watching.
</P>
</TEXT>
