<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUCENT-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRUE TO ITS WORDS, LUCENT REPORTS A DISMAL QUARTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two weeks after warning that its financial performance for the
latest quarter would fall far short of analysts' expectations,
Lucent Technologies followed through Thursday ith its most
disappointing results since the company split from AT&AMP;T in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent's shares are the most widely held in the nation. As North
America's No. 1 maker of telecommunications equipment, Lucent has
grown quickly as deregulation and the rise of the Internet have
combined to create surging demand for advanced network gear.
</P>
<P>
   But the company's management, led by Richard McGinn, Lucent's
chairman, made its first big mistakes last year, losing touch with
some customers' buying habits and falling behind the company's
archrival, Nortel Networks of Canada, in the fast-growing optical
networking market.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the company posted anemic revenue growth of less
than 1 percent for its fiscal first quarter, to $9.905 billion,
from $9.842 billion during the comparable period of the 1999 fiscal
year. Before Lucent's warning on Jan. 6, many analysts had expected
the company to generate revenue of around $11 billion in the first
quarter, which ended Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Splitting off from AT&AMP;T, the No. 1 phone company, gave a huge
lift to Lucent. But last quarter may have been the first in which
Lucent grew more slowly than did its old parent.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as two weeks ago, analysts had expected Lucent to
earn 54 cents a share during the quarter. But then the company
warned that it would earn no more than 39 cents a share. Thursday,
Lucent announced that it had earned 36 cents a share during the
quarter, or $1.175 billion, excluding one-time charges and gains.
On a per-share basis, that was 25 percent lower than the 48 cents a
share, or $1.523 billion, that the company earned during the period
a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Including one-time charges and profits _ like merger expenses
and gains from sales of investments _ Lucent reported earnings of
$1.25 billion, or 38 cents a share. That was less than half the
$2.544 billion, or 80 cents a share, the company reported,
including one-time events, for the corresponding period of the 1999
fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we've said, we're disappointed with our results for the
quarter,'' McGinn said in a statement. ``However, industry growth
is strong, and we are well positioned to take advantage of that
growth. The fundamental needs of our customers continue to grow,
and we intend to capitalize on this demand as we've done in the
past.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucent has not, however, fully capitalized on the fast-growing
demand for advanced optical communications systems, which transmit
information using pulses of light rather than pulses of
electricity. That has allowed Nortel to stake out a world-leading
position in the optical transmission market.
</P>
<P>
   At least as embarrassing, Lucent said on Jan. 6 that some of its
financial troubles in the quarter were a result of phone companies'
beginning to spread out their purchases of software more evenly
throughout the year, rather than making such purchases mostly at
the end of the calendar year. Shortly after splitting from AT&AMP;T,
Lucent had changed the beginning of its fiscal year to October, in
an attempt to begin each fiscal year with what was thought to be
the most robust quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent also said Thursday that it had agreed to acquire Agere, a
maker of programmable communications chips based in Austin, Texas,
for about $415 million in stock.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
