<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BAD-DRIVERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE EASE CAR SEIZURES IN NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JUAN FORERO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York Police Department disclosed Thursday a
major shift in its policy of seizing the cars of people charged
with drunken driving: Some drivers may be able to get their cars
back after completing an alcohol treatment program and paying
$1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials insist that the policy shift, which was made
public in testimony by Police Commissioner Howard Safir in a City
Council hearing Thursday morning, does not run counter to their
aggressive efforts to crack down on drunken driving.
</P>
<P>
   But it may make the department's policy easier to uphold in a
court of law, said George A. Grasso, deputy commissioner for legal
affairs.
</P>
<P>
   The original policy, which city officials labeled the toughest
in the country, was announced by Mayor Rudolph Giuliani with
fanfare last February. It called for seizing the car of anyone
arrested on drunken driving charges and only allowed for the
possibility of a car's being returned if the driver was acquitted.
</P>
<P>
   As of Dec. 31, the police had seized 1,458 cars; department
officials began forfeiture actions on 827 of those seizures.
</P>
<P>
   The modified policy applies only to drivers who had a blood
alcohol level lower than 0.20 percent when charged, have no
significant prior history of driving while intoxicated or impaired,
and have not been involved in any serious accident, Safir said. The
driver must see a state certified counselor for alcohol treatment
and the $1,000 _ in some cases less _ is charged to cover
administrative and litigation costs, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recognize that in some instances, it might be appropriate
to find a less severe alternative, which allows the defendant to
address what might be an alcohol abuse problem,'' he told the
Council's Public Safety Committee, which called the hearing to
assess the car seizure policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going soft at all,'' Safir told reporters after the
hearing. ``What we're trying to do is, when we have somebody who
hasn't injured anybody, does not have an excessive amount of
alcohol _ it's not an egregious case _ who appears to be interested
in solving their problems, then we would look to give them a chance
to mitigate their violation and return the car.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the policy change was instituted in late November, the
department's legal affairs office has determined that 380 drivers
whose cars were confiscated were eligible to have them returned, as
long as the drivers met the requirements. No one has received a car
back yet, Grasso said, but as of Dec. 31, about 100 letters
offering drivers the opportunity to take advantage of the change
had been mailed out, and 41 responses expressing interest had been
returned to the police.
</P>
<P>
   Grasso told reporters that the policy change also strengthened
the department's legal position, even though the policy on car
seizures has been upheld at the state Supreme Court and Appellate
Division levels. ``We're applying this program that is fair,
equitable and therefore that much more likely to be upheld at every
level of judicial review, up to the New York state Court of Appeals
and the United States Supreme Court, if it goes there,'' Grasso
said.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the city's seizure efforts welcomed the changes in
the program but were annoyed that the Police Department had not
made an announcement earlier. Grasso and other officials said the
policy was not made public because no one had inquired about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never heard of such a program,'' said Norman Siegel,
executive director of the New York Civil Liberties Union and a
critic of the seizure policy. ``Moreover, I think it reinforces the
major points that we've been making all along, that when the city
of New York seizes people's cars without the requisite legal
authority, they make up the rules as they go along.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-00 2327EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000120.0408 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 23:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2067 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-CAGE-NYT     01-20 0409
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-CAGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BETTY CAGE, 82, ADMINISTRATOR WHO HELPED CREATE NEW YORK CITY
BALLET
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Minn.)  (rk) 
 By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Betty Cage, an administrator of the New York City
Ballet who played a quiet but important role in creating the
company, died on Dec. 19 at New York Hospital in Manhattan. She was
82 and lived in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Her title for many years was simply that of general manager, but
Ms. Cage was a linchpin of the City Ballet. She avoided the
limelight and was unknown to the general balletgoing public. A
woman of few words, she presided over generations of dancers,
choreographers and backstage personnel with a wryly detached wit
and a calm, almost uncanny sense of approaching trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Cage was, as Lincoln Kirstein described her role in ``Thirty
Years,'' his history of the City Ballet, ``at once labor
negotiator, certified public accountant, legal expert, mother
superior, confessor, psychiatrist and practicing witch (white
magic).'' She was, Kirstein wrote, ``proficient in the science and
pursuit of the possible and impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in Minneapolis, Ms. Cage grew up in Buffalo before she
moved to New York. She worked in a law office before becoming an
assistant editor at John Bernard Myers' literary journal View and
an assistant to Frances Steloff at the Gotham Book Mart, jobs that
introduced her to the world of poets, artists and intellectuals
involved in dance in the 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   It is likely that Kirstein met Ms. Cage at the Gotham Book Mart,
where he is said to have invited her to work with Ballet Society, a
precursor to City Ballet. Ms. Cage arrived in 1947 and retired
formally in 1985, working first as an assistant to Frances Hawkins,
the business manager at Ballet Society. It was there that Ms. Cage
formed a close professional relationship with Morton Baum, who as
chairman of the City Center's finance committee in 1948 extended a
crucial invitation to the ballet company to become a resident of
the theater. Ms. Cage also helped to engineer the City Ballet's
1964 move to Lincoln Center on terms agreeable to the ballet
company and to City Center. In 1985, she founded the Dancers
Emergency Fund at City Ballet.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Cage was also a practitioner and proponent of tai chi, the
Chinese exercise system. She collaborated with her husband, the
writer Edward Maisel, on ``Tai Chi for Health.''
</P>
<P>
   She is survived by her husband.
</P>
</TEXT>
