<HEADLINE>
RAMS-WARNER TALKS COULD GET INTERESTING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Those who expect that the St. Louis Rams' rags-to-riches,
storybook quarterback, Kurt Warner, will join 17 of his teammates
in the millionaire fraternity in the off-season might be in for a
surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Rams, who are paying Warner a mere $250,000, aren't
obligated to bump his salary beyond $280,000 for the 2000 season,
although it's doubtful they would have him perform at such a
bread-and-water level.
</P>
<P>
   Still, don't look for Georgia Frontiere's notorious financial
hitman, John Shaw, who in an uncharacteristic gesture of
magnanimity recently bestowed a $500,000 bonus on Warner, to lavish
Warner with a multi-year, multi-million dollar contract. For one
thing, Shaw doesn't have to. In his second season with the Rams,
Warner won't be eligible for free agency until 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw also has serious salary cap constraints to consider.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams' payroll this season is $55.7 million under the NFL cap
of $58 million that will increase to $62 million next fall and one
of the team's top defensive players, Pro Bowl cornerback Todd
Lyght, will become a free agent at the season's conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   And four other key performers, receiver Isaac Bruce, defensive
end Kevin Carter and linebackers London Fletcher and Mike Jones,
will become free agents after next season.
</P>
<P>
   Lyght's current income is $3.4 million, and it's known the Ram
coach, Dick Vermeil, is strongly campaigning for the team to retain
his services, meaning Lyght figures to be earning in the $5 million
range if they do re-sign him.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams also have a quarterback on their roster in Trent Green
who hasn't thrown a pass this season and who they gave a $4.5
million signing bonus that was included in his four-year, $18
million contract.
</P>
<P>
   Unless a team drafting early is willing to give the Rams a first
round selection for Green and such a team reportedly might be the
Pittsburgh Steelers Shaw is planning to bring Green to Ram training
camp next summer if for no other reason than to keep Warner in
line.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams' offensive coordinator and future head coach, Mike
Martz, is a passionate advocate of Green and has told intimates
that Green would have done as well as Warner had Green not gone
down with that knee injury during the preseason.
</P>
<P>
   If Shaw does re-sign Lyght and is unable to move Green, then
team sources say Warner won't necessarily be earning the
seven-figure wages next season that would be commensurate with his
remarkable achievements.
</P>
<P>
   ``The agents play hard-ball with Shaw when they have the
leverage, and Shaw has a long history of playing hard-ball with
agents when he has the leverage,'' says one Ram source. ``And right
now, Shaw has the leverage on Warner. Shaw knows Warner is bound to
the Rams for two more years. If Warner decides to hold out, or do
something crazy like that, the Rams could turn to Trent Green. It's
going to be interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if the Rams do trade Green, then John Shaw figures to
give Kurt Warner the lucrative contract he deserves.
</P>
<P>
   But until that happens, Kurt Warner will continue to be the most
underpaid star in the NFL, as was another Ram a long time ago,
fellow by the name of Eric Dickerson. ...
</P>
<P>
   _ Las Vegas gambling figure Jimmy Vaccaro tells me the Rams were
200-1 to win the Super Bowl in Las Vegas in the summer, but that no
serious wagers were made on the St. Louis team to pull off such a
coup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard a few people stepped up pretty good when the Rams won
a few early games and the odds dropped to 60-1,'' reports Vaccaro.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, Vaccaro makes the Rams 5 to 6 point favorites over
Jacksonville if the two teams make it to the Super Bowl. ...
</P>
<P>
   _ Will someone please explain to me why two men who have proven
to be NFL head coaching duds, Bill Belichick and Dave Wannstedt,
suddenly have become such hot commodities? Wannstedt, who will
replace Jimmy Johnson in Miami, was a scandalous bust during his
tenure with the Chicago Bears. And Belichick, who's soon expected
to take over the New England Patriots, fizzled out lamely when he
had his opportunity with the original Cleveland Browns.
</P>
<P>
   It's obvious these guys are far better at promoting themselves
than they are at inspiring their players, so help me Norv Turner.
...
</P>
<P>
   If Don Shula had still been coaching the Miami Dolphins in that
62-7 disaster last Saturday against Jacksonville, the tone of the
post-game analysis by the TV talking heads would have been that the
game had passed Shula by and that he was simply too old.
</P>
<P>
   But since that lovable media darling Jimmy Johnson was the
Dolphins' field commander, I didn't hear a negative word launched
in his direction. The reality with Jimmy Johnson is that he's
always been an overrated coach who benefited in Dallas from the
enormous wealth of talented players that fortuitously fell his way.
I thought he did a lousy job with the Dolphins. ../.
</P>
<P>
   _ The next time Kobe Bryant takes one of his indiscreet shots
which happens about three, four, five, six, seven, eight times a
game Phil Jackson should say this when he bawls him out: ``Stop
trying to be like Michael Jordan. You aren't Michael Jordan and you
never will be!'' Alas, Kobe continues to live with the grand
illusion that he is. ...
</P>
<P>
   _ Felix Trinidad and David Reid were at the Biltmore Hotel
Thursday hyping their March 3 match at Caesars Palace that will be
promoted by Dan Goossen's America Presents by Don King in
association with Caesars.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the fight everyone has been waiting for,'' gasps
publicist Honest John Beyrooty, late of the Press Telegram who on
Saturday will join Mike Tyson's training camp in London where Tyson
has been preparing for his Jan. 29 fight in Manchester against
Julius Francis.
</P>
<P>
   Well, at least one person, David Reid, is excited about this
Showtime pay per view event, since he's set to earn $3 million in
only his 15th professional fight in defending his WBA super
welterweight title against Trinidad.
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad is expected to earn $4 million, slightly less than the
$15 million or so he would have made had negotiations not fallen
apart for a rematch with Oscar De La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Arum has De La Hoya back to fighting a preordained setup, as
he has throughout De La Hoya's career, on Feb. 26 at Madison Square
Garden when he meets Derrell Coley in a match so unappetizing that
I plan to go bowling that evening to spare myself the discomfort of
watching it. ...
</P>
<P>
   _ I'm not sure what's worse, John Rocker's inane musings, or his
ensuing, pitiably contrived displays of public contrition. ...
</P>
<P>
   _ I never would recommend anyone to lay two touchdowns, but I
can't envision Tampa Bay staying within 21 points of the Rams on
Sunday. How are the Buccaneers going to score against the fast,
underrated Ram defense? ...
</P>
<P>
   _ I still don't understand why Michael Jordan retired, since he
obviously savors the limelight so desperately that he would subject
himself to overseeing the sadsack Washington Wizards. Such duty
will pose a terrible hardship on Jordan's golf game. Frankly, I'll
be surprised if Jordan, who's worth an estimated $100 million, is
still at the job a year from now.
</P>
