<HEADLINE>
NYC PRINCIPALS BACK DEAL CALLING FOR LONGER DAYS, MUCH HIGHER PAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ANEMONA HARTOCOLLIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ By a 2-1 margin, New York City's public school
principals and assistant principals Thursday approved a contract
that allows inadequate principals to be removed quickly, requires
all principals to work longer days and summers, and significantly
increases salaries.
</P>
<P>
   The contract, which will increase paychecks by 33 percent for
all supervisors and up to 70 percent for the top 5 percent of
principals based on performance, comes when policy-makers have
complained that low salaries have cut the number of applicants for
principals' jobs while stifling innovation and improvement.
</P>
<P>
   Because of tradeoffs during negotiations, union leaders said,
principals still maintain their right to tenure through a due
process procedure that requires the school system to prove
incompetence or misconduct. Nevertheless, they were concerned that
the concessions would make approval difficult.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, union leaders said, the union's members ratified the
contract because they had been working for four years without a
raise and because they were reassured that remaining job
protections seemed satisfactory.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Harold Levy, the newly selected interim schools chancellor, said
Thursday that he was pleased by the strong show of approval,
because, he said, it indicated that ``principals are willing to
work to the kind of standards that I think are critical for the
system.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who has been feuding with the Board of
Education over its selection of Levy, said the contract was ``an
important step in the effort to bring critical changes and
restructuring to our city's education system.'' He added, ``Only by
creating a system that puts children first, rather than job
protection, can we bring accountability to the New York City school
system.''
</P>
<P>
   Union officials, who had been anxious about the vote until the
final hour, were clearly relieved but a bit wary about how the deal
would work out as it is implemented over the next months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very good for our members,'' said Donald Singer,
president of the Council of Supervisors and Administrators, who
announced this week that he was resigning to take a job with the
union's national counterpart. ``Let's just hope it works. With a
strong chancellor and a strong Board of Education working with one
voice, I think this will be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The contract maintains the pattern of 11 percent raises in base
salary negotiated with other municipal unions. But in addition, it
provides a 19.97 percent salary increase for principals to work a
12-month year, with five weeks of vacation, rather than the current
10 months, and for them to extend their working day by half an
hour, to seven hours. Other union members also got extra raises in
exchange for relatively minor concessions, like cutting 10 minutes
from their lunch periods.
</P>
<P>
   The contract, which extends through March 2001, will give
principals an average salary of $93,200. With incentive pay, the
highest-paid principals, who now earn $83,921, could earn more than
$143,000, an increase of 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
   There were 2,498 votes in favor of the contract to 1,207
against.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest battle, which kept the contract talks from being
resolved for four years, was over tenure. City and school officials
said the new contract provisions, which will be enshrined in state
law, would give superintendents more discretion to remove
principals for unsatisfactory performance and would make the
process much quicker.
</P>
<P>
   The new process calls for principals to be removed for
incompetence only during a 20-day period every year in June, so as
not to disrupt the school year. Superintendents who want to remove
a principal will have to document their reasons with an annual
performance review.
</P>
<P>
   The performance review will be based on criteria negotiated by
the union, the superintendent and the individual principals. The
decision will be reviewed by an arbitrator and may be appealed to
the state education commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   Under law, the process will be limited to 60 days, while the
current appeals process often drags on for years. ``We have the
ability to get rid of turkeys a lot faster,'' said a city official
who was involved in the negotiations. ``That is a wonderful thing.
We obviously will have to make sure we have our ducks in order to
prove our case.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-00 2331EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
