<SLUG> BC-CANADA-U.S.-TERRORISM-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANADA ADDS DETAILS ON ALGERIANS' SUSPECTED BOMB PLOT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash., Vt.) (Eds.: CORRECTS ``charged'' to ``accused'' in 4th graf; CORRECTS
name to Abdel Ghani Meskini in 8th graf; ADDS 2 grafs at end with
more charges being filed in   Seattle) 
 (rk) 
 By CRAIG PYES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ Canadian prosecutors Thursday offered the most
detailed picture to date of a bomb plot they said stretched from
Canada to Brooklyn and involved a number of Algerians, including
one they said was trained at camps in Afghanistan operated by
Islamic militants.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said the plot was coordinated by Mokhtar Haouari, a
31-year-old Algerian who was arrested in Canada last week after a
Manhattan grand jury indicted him on charges of taking part in
plotting an attack. A judge here ordered him held without bail
Thursday after a court hearing.
</P>
<P>
   For three weeks, prosecutors in Seattle, New York, Vermont and
Canada have brought charges against a wide array of Algerians and
their associates. Thursday's hearing, in a Montreal courtroom,
marked the first time in the unfolding case in which anyone has
publicly tried to assemble the pieces of the puzzle.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing raised as many questions as it answered. It remains
unclear whether the Algerians had decided to attack a particular
target in the United States and, if so, where it was. Nor is it
clear whether Haouari was following the lead of some more
internationally known terrorist leader, for instance Osama bin
Laden, the Saudi exile who is accused by the United States of
masterminding the bombings of American Embassies in Africa in 1998
that left more than 200 dead. Intelligence officials say bin Laden
has operated training camps in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation began on Dec. 14, when Customs officials at
Port Angeles, Wash., stopped a man who was trying to drive his car
off the ferry from Vancouver, British Columbia. That man, Ahmed
Ressam, broke into a dead run after a few questions and was
arrested. A search of his car found several jars filled with RDX, a
military explosive, and four Casio watches fashioned as homemade
detonators.
</P>
<P>
   In Thursday's hearing, a Canadian detective, Serge Haineault,
sketched the biographies of three of those accused of taking part
in the plot, saying two of them had known each other as schoolmates
in Algeria. He provided new details about how they allegedly tried
to pull off a bombing, and sought to draw links between them and
radical Islamic movements.
</P>
<P>
   Haineault said Ressam, known by the nom de guerre Abu Reda, had
received military training at camps in Afghanistan and Pakistan run
by militants.
</P>
<P>
   Offering the prosecutors' first detailed account of the
Algerians' frantic efforts to carry out their operation, Haineault
drew a picture of a flawed effort. He said Abdel Ghani Meskini had
been sent by Haouari on Dec. 11 to meet Ressam in Seattle and serve
as his translater and driver as well as provide him with cash drawn
from a stolen bank debit card.
</P>
<P>
   Meskini, by the detective's account, made contact by telephone
with Ressam, who was staying in a hotel in Vancouver, just over the
border from Washington state. On Dec. 14, Ressam told Meskini that
he would be on the noon ferry and that he should ``stay calm.''
</P>
<P>
   But things did not work out as planned, Haineault said. Ressam
was arrested, leaving Meskini wondering what had happened.
According to Hainault, he made a series of phone calls over several
days to Haouari, trying to understand what had gone wrong.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 17, Meskini left Seattle and returned to Brooklyn. He
did not know it, but he was being watched. Federal investigators
had found a piece of paper on Ressam with Meskini's home phone
number, and they began watching his apartment and listening to his
phone calls soon after. According to the Canadian detective,
Haouari instructed Meskini to destroy all records of his trip to
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The precautions were not sufficient. On Dec. 30, a team of
police and federal investigators arrested Meskini and announced
that they had seen him discarding airplane tickets and other
documents.
</P>
<P>
   According to Haineault, Meskini responded to federal agents with
a series of admissions about his travels and dealings with Haouari.
Challenged in court Thursday to support his allegations, Haineault
said that much of his information on the case had come from
statements Meskini made to the FBI after his arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Meskini's lawyer, Roland Thau, said any statement his client
made was ``not a confession of his own involvement in the knowing
transportation or assistance of a bomb carrier.''
</P>
<P>
   Thau said Meskini had not offered to assist American
investigators. The ``statement'' referred to in the Canadian court
proceedings, he said, was not signed. Meskini has pleaded not
guilty, as have all other defendants in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Haineault testified that Haouari had known Meskini since their
school days in Algeria. In fact, he said, Meskini was eager to
become a full-fledged member of the Armed Islamic Group, known as
GIA for its initials in French. The group, which has been involved
in the killing of tens of thousands of Algerians, has not
previously attacked Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Several Clinton administration officials have said the Algerians
involved in the plot are linked to bin Laden.
</P>
<P>
   American officials speculate that bin Laden is linked to the
bomb plot, but have not offered specifics to support their
assertion.
</P>
<P>
   In Seattle later Thursday, prosecutors filed new, more serious
charges against Ressam and another Algerian, Abdel Majid Dahoumane.
The indictment for the first time formally accuses Ressam of
attempting to carry out a terrorist act, and it charges Dahoumane
as an accomplice.
</P>
<P>
   American and Canadian authorities are continuing to search for
Dahoumane, who entered the United States separately from Ressam and
remains a fugitive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-00 2332EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000120.0413 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 23:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2076 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-PHONE-TAKEOVER-NYT     01-20 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHONE-TAKEOVER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANNESMANN REBUFFS VODAFONE'S HINT OF A SWEETENED OFFER
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Vodafone AirTouch said Thursday that it was prepared to
offer a modest sweetener to its all-stock bid for Mannesmann AG,
now valued at $155 billion, but the German company spurned the
overture as ``wholly inadequate.''
</P>
<P>
   The offer, which would increase Mannesmann shareholders' stake
in a combined group to a level somewhat less than 49 percent from
47.2 percent, is conditional on Mannesmann's approving the bid, a
Vodafone statement said.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Gent, Vodafone's chief executive, said his own
stockholders would not countenance a bigger increase. ``They made
it totally clear to me that anything with 49 in it was a bridge too
far,'' he told the Reuters news service Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Vodafone's hostile takeover attempt, the largest ever, was begun
on Nov. 19. At that time, the offer of 53.7 of its shares for each
Mannesmann share valued a deal at $127.7 billion, but that has
increased with Vodafone's share price. At current stock prices,
Vodafone's bid values each Mannesmann share at $305, compared with
$247.20 on Nov. 19.
</P>
<P>
   Klaus Esser, the Mannesmann chief executive, contends that
Mannesmann shares are worth as much as $354 each.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Thursday that Vodafone's newest conditional offer
for Mannesmann might have been intended to tempt the Mannesmann
board into recommending the bid to investors, pre-empting the high
costs associated with hostile bids.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does look as if Chris Gent is holding out an olive branch
to Klaus Esser,'' said Kevin Sheil, telecommunications analyst with
Credit Suisse First Boston. ``If you ended up getting a
recommendation for the offer, you would see cooperation with the
Mannesmann management and Vodafone may look at this as a reasonable
price to pay.''
</P>
<P>
   In its statement Thursday, Vodafone reiterated that its offer
for Mannesmann would close on Feb. 7. But the statement also said:
``Vodafone AirTouch recognizes that a recommendation from
Mannesmann would benefit the shareholders of both companies. There
will be no increase in the exchange ratio of Vodafone AirTouch's
offer in the absence of a recommendation from Mannesmann or a
higher competing offer. Even in the event of a recommendation from
Mannesmann, Vodafone AirTouch would only be prepared to consider a
modest increase in the exchange ratio of offer.''
</P>
<P>
   The statement was made after Gent disclosed his readiness to
increase the offer in interviews with The Financial Times and The
Wall Street Journal.
</P>
<P>
   The Vodafone statement also came as Mannesmann was reported in
talks with the French company Vivendi on a complex form of merger
or other deal that would give it control of Vivendi's Cegetel unit.
Cegetel owns the French mobile phone company SFR.
</P>
<P>
   Presumably seeking to counter such a maneuver, Vodafone
executives said Thursday that their company was also negotiating
with Vivendi, in its case to create European Internet and
interactive pay-television services. Vodafone plans to introduce an
Internet site this summer linked to new-generation mobile phones
and devices like personal organizers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
