<SLUG> BC-GLF-HOPE-CLASSIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KRAFT IS DRIVING HIMSELF INTO SHAPE FOR HIS FIRST TOUR VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERMUDA DUNES, Calif. _ The closer Greg Kraft comes to winning,
the more his motivation increases.
</P>
<P>
   After finishing second in two tournaments last year, and having
his best season on the PGA Tour, Kraft believes he is ready to win.
Perhaps his time will come this weekend at the Bob Hope Chrysler
Classic, a tournament where birdies are always plentiful, and where
Kraft obviously feels comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   Posting his second consecutive 65, Kraft led by one stroke after
Thursday's second round of the 90-hole tournament, as players
continued to post low numbers in near-perfect conditions. Kraft was
at 14-under par (130), a stroke ahead of three players _ Rich Beem,
Brent Geiberger and Andrew Magee.
</P>
<P>
   It was a warm, calm day, and a barrage of birdies occurred at
all four tournament courses. Geiberger's 61 at Indian Wells Country
Club tied the course record set by Bert Yancey in 1974, and equaled
by David Edwards in 1987. This is the same tournament where David
Duval shot a final-round 59 to win last year, and if conditions
remain calm this weekend, more records could be set.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I have to keep making birdies,'' said Kraft, who shot
Thursday's 65 at Indian Wells. ``It's a five-day tournament, and I
know 14-under is not going to win.''
</P>
<P>
   But for Kraft, Thursday's round was further confirmation that at
age 35, he is moving closer to being one of the tour's top players.
He finished with more than $810,000 in earnings last year, 52nd on
the money list, and posted three top-ten finishes, including a
second place at both the Doral-Ryder Open and the Mastercard
Colonial.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the Doral-Ryder finish still haunts Kraft. He reached the
final hole needing a par to force a playoff with Steve Elkington,
the eventual champion, and a birdie on the final hole would have
given Kraft the victory. Instead, Kraft hit a terrible 5-iron
approach shot into the water, leading to a bogey that cost him a
chance for victory.
</P>
<P>
   That memory pushed Kraft during the off-season, as he undertook
a physical fitness program that has left him in the best shape of
his career. If Kraft never wins on tour, lack of effort will not be
the reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't forgotten it, and I don't ever want to forget it,''
said Kraft about last year's Doral-Ryder event. ``That was like a
knockout punch. Am I going to get up, or am I just going to lay
there? It still motivates me.''
</P>
<P>
   During the past three years, Kraft's career has been on the
upswing. He finished 139th on the money list in 1997, 94th in 1998
and 52nd last year. If Kraft continues to improve, he will have a
chance to join some of the tour's elite players, but he is taking
nothing for granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I'm close, but to be one of the guys out here, you
have to win, and you have to be on the leader board a lot,'' said
Kraft, whose strength is his accurate driving. ``I'm not there yet,
but I'm giving myself every opportunity. When I look back, I won't
have any regrets. I'm working as hard as I can.''
</P>
<P>
   While Kraft left the course with the lead, the day was not as
enjoyable for Casey Martin, who shot an even-par 71 at Bermuda
Dunes Country Club, leaving him four under par for the tournament.
One of Martin's amateur partners was Richard Ferris, a PGA Tour
board member, who testified against Martin in the 1998 court case
that resulted in Martin being granted the right to use a golf cart
in competition. Martin suffers from Klippel-Trenauney-Weber
syndrome, a rare circulatory condition that causes severe pain in
his right leg.
</P>
<P>
   Martin said his day with Ferris went smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   ``There could've been tension because of how he testified,''
Martin said. ``But I got to know him, and he's a nice guy. I
enjoyed playing with him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
