<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MISSILES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A SLOWER PATH TO MISSILE DEFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times says in an editorial for Friday, Jan. 21:
</P>
<P>
   The failure of a prototype missile interceptor to hit its target
in a crucial test this week makes it glaringly clear that the
Pentagon has not yet perfected the technology needed for an
effective national missile defense, even one of limited scope.
President Clinton, who has said under political pressure that he
will decide this summer whether to start building such a system,
should defer his decision until a fuller testing record can be
established.
</P>
<P>
   This week's test was the second of a scheduled three. Last fall
an interceptor missile successfully destroyed its target, but
almost by accident. It suffered initial navigational mistakes and
found the target only after luckily homing in on a nearby decoy
balloon. On Tuesday the interceptor completely missed the incoming
missile it was supposed to destroy, apparently because of the
last-minute failure of two heat-sensing devices.
</P>
<P>
   One more test will be held this spring, the last before
Clinton's scheduled decision. Even if it proceeds flawlessly, the
White House will not know for sure whether the system will
consistently work as intended. Missile defenses have to be highly
reliable to be effective.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will need to resist any impulse to approve the missile
system as a political tactic to protect Vice President Al Gore from
charges that the administration has left the country defenseless
against missile attacks from terrorist states. The latest test
failure may help him there by weakening support for immediate
deployment. Although Republican leaders in Congress are still
urging speedy deployment, some Republican senators are now urging
that a decision on the system be deferred.
</P>
<P>
   The defensive system under consideration is not meant to provide
a shield against the substantial missile forces of Russia or even
China, but to shoot down the handful of missiles that unpredictable
countries like North Korea or Iran might soon be able to launch
against the United States. It would still be one of the most
complicated weapons systems ever built. Sophisticated sensors would
have to find incoming missiles during their brief descent through
the atmosphere. Interceptors would then have to shoot these
missiles out of the sky, ignoring possible decoys as the two
rockets closed in on each other atined speed of 15,000 miles
an hour. The technology for doing this has progressed remarkably
far, but not yet far enough.
</P>
<P>
   In deciding whether to go ahead with missile defenses, Clinton
must also weigh the possible effect on arms control treaties.
Russia currently rejects amending the 1972 Antiballistic Missile
Treaty to permit building the system Washington envisions. That may
just be an initial bargaining position that could change as
Russia's acting president, Vladimir Putin, reconsiders policies
inherited from Boris Yeltsin. But there is no harm in giving Putin
more time to change his mind.
</P>
<P>
   Until reliable missile defenses can be mounted without wrecking
arms control, Washington should continue to meet threats from North
Korea and Iran the way it met missile threats from Russia during
the Cold War _ through America's capacity for devastating
retaliation and efforts to restrain the spread of nuclear materials
and missile technology. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-00 2333EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
