<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 23:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2082 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-ABOUT-CARS-TAURUS-ART     01-20 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-CARS-TAURUS-ART-2TAKES-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORD TAURUS: AFTER OVAL ADVENTURES, FORD PLAYS IT SAFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 23)  
 (af)  
 By BOB KNOLL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OLD SAYBROOK, Conn. _ How better to assess the prospects for the
2000 Ford Taurus than to consult the salespeople who have to sell
it? A month or so before the new model reached dealerships, I took
the new Taurus to the local Ford store to gauge reactions.
</P>
<P>
   One might have expected the staff to be unimpressed with the
car's reskinning; after all, car salesmen are not usually described
as car enthusiasts. But I was surprised; they were interested and
impressed.
</P>
<P>
   They enthusiastically noted the new grille, the trunk and the
rear window. They commented on how the highlights of the hood
complimented the edgy new Ford design theme so noticeable on the
Mercury Cougar and Ford Focus. They were especially pleased to note
that the previous Taurus's oval rear window and awkward taillights
were gone. And they did not notice that the doors and windshield
are unchanged, saving a lot on production costs. The designers had
done their job well.
</P>
<P>
   Restyling a successful mainline car is always risky. Since the
Taurus was introduced for 1986 as a daring all-new design, it has
undergone several minor changes and one complete revamping, for
1996. It has been one of the top-selling models in the United
States, even taking the No. 1 spot for several years. Clearly, the
formula worked.
</P>
<P>
   But the '96 redesign was never universally embraced. The car's
styling theme was oval: oval rear window, oval grille opening, oval
central instrument panel incorporating the audio and climate
controls. The Taurus station wagon became especially oval, to the
detriment of practical considerations like access to the rear-seat.
</P>
<P>
   Some thought that the oval was going to be Ford's new look,
spreading to other models. But the public did not warm to that
approach. The 2000 Taurus steps away from the oval toward the
mainstream of current design.
</P>
<P>
   While the Taurus kept the doors and windshield of the previous
model, the rest of the sheet metal has changed. The result is a
much cleaner design incorporating a bit of Ford's new styling theme
of sharp angular lines. Along the way, the Taurus picked up more
room in the rear seat and in the trunk.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from body and styling changes, the Taurus remains, under
the skin, basically the same car. Hundreds of thousands of previous
owners will not be surprised by the way it rides and drives. They
may notice snappier response, especially from the dual-cam Duratec
V6 engine, and they will likely notice more responsive steering
from the new, larger 16-inch tires and wheels.
</P>
<P>
   Steering and handling are now competitive with the best in the
class, foreign or domestic. The feel of the steering is much
improved and there is little body roll on corners. The brakes are
smooth and progressive in normal driving, but I worried a bit about
the small rear drum brakes of the sedan. (The station wagon has
four-wheel disc brakes.) An antilock braking feature is standard on
the SES and SEL models, $600 on the LX and SE.
</P>
<P>
   The ride is softer than in previous Tauruses, and becomes a bit
floaty on certain bumps, but it is still well controlled. The
Duratec V6 in my test car felt powerful and was quiet on the
highway, yet sounded aggressive when the car accelerated
forcefully.
</P>
<P>
   The Duratec, a modern, dual-overhead-cam power plant, is the
engine of choice; the base engine, an old-fashioned pushrod design
called the Vulcan, is the same size but much less powerful and not
much more fuel-efficient. Both V6s meet the low-emission standards
of California and 13 Northeastern states.
</P>
<P>
   But the way the 2000 Taurus looks, rides and drives is not the
main marketing thrust anymore. The emphasis is now on safety. Ford
says the Taurus was ``designed for enhanced performance in crash
tests and real-world accidents.''
</P>
<P>
   To this end, the Taurus (and its fraternal twin, the Mercury
Sable) have what Ford calls ``advanced restraints system safety
technologies.'' The crucial part of this system is a
restraint-control module that takes into account the driver's
seating position, whether the driver and front passenger are
wearing safety belts, and the severity of the crash to determine
the level of air bag protection to deploy _ or whether a bag is
needed at all. The module also knows when to activate the
pretensioners for the front-seat belts.
</P>
<P>
   This is a significant step forward in air-bag crash technology,
in advance of any federal requirements. Several luxury cars have
advanced air bag controls, but none have gone this far. In
real-world crashes, the Taurus will be better able to protect
occupants without the danger of an air bag firing when it is not
needed.
</P>
<P>
   The safety thrust does not end with new technology for front
crashes. Side air bags that help to protect both head and chest,
are a $390 option. The interior is designed with more
energy-absorbing trim; tether anchors are provided in the rear seat
for the new child safety seats that use them; and the trunk now has
an emergency inside release. This simple, T-shaped handle, which
glows in the dark, was added in response to reports of children
dying after they became trapped in car trunks.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
