<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 23:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2084 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-POLS-OFFICE-2TAKE     01-20 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-POLS-OFFICE-2TAKES-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RUN FOR OFFICE MEANS A RUN FOR YOUR MONEY  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 23) 
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attn: Fla., Iowa, Mass., N.C.)   (af)  
 By VIVIAN MARINO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Alberta Hipps, an experienced registered nurse, gave up a secure
career as a hospital staff director several years ago for a
position that pays about half her former salary, has no job
security and requires her to spend several nights a week away from
her family.
</P>
<P>
   Some people might call her foolhardy. Mrs. Hipps, 56, prefers to
think of herself as a servant of the public _ or rather
Jacksonville, Fla., where she has held one of 19 city council seats
since July 1995.
</P>
<P>
   There are many more like Mrs. Hipps _ civic-minded individuals
willing to sideline careers, spend hundreds or thousands of dollars
from their own pockets and countless hours on the road for one of
the estimated 513,200 local, state and federal elected offices. In
any given year, between 100,000 and 150,000 seats are up for grabs.
</P>
<P>
   While the finances of high political office-holders _ like
members of Congress, who earn six-figure incomes and often can
leave for choice jobs with lobbying or law firms _ get the
attention, it is a different story on the local front.
</P>
<P>
   Some successful candidates for lesser posts do move on to
higher-paying offices or parlay their experiences into lucrative
careers in the private sector. But few can expect significant
financial gain.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, some individuals must make serious financial
sacrifices, which could at least temporarily alter their standards
of living. And some in more high-profile offices like leadership
roles in the legislature have to rework their investment portfolios
to avoid conflicts of interest.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Corbett, a former House speaker in the Iowa Legislature,
recalled having to sell shares of a Cedar Rapids, Iowa, start-up
telecommunications company named McLeodUSA Inc. soon after buying
them a few years ago because, as he said, ``There were pieces of
legislation pending that may have had an impact on the company.''
</P>
<P>
   Had he kept the shares, he said, they would have been worth
about $18,000 today, or six times what he paid for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many ancillary effects to consider,'' said Hank
Madden, a financial planner in Jacksonville. As with any business
venture, he said, ``You will need to have a formal financial plan
before you get started. You will have to ask yourself, `what will I
have to give up to do this?'''
</P>
<P>
   He noted that a candidate who left a job or worked part time
while campaigning might lose group discounts for health care and
disability insurance. The candidate may no longer have the
eligibility or the money to participate in an employer-sponsored
retirement plan. Saving for the children's college may be postponed
because money earmarked for them may have to be diverted to the
campaign or living expenses.
</P>
<P>
   And professionals like doctors, lawyers or small-business owners
may be forced to curtail their schedules, and therefore sustain
income losses that could take years to recoup.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to look at how all this will affect your immediate
and long-term plans,'' Madden said.
</P>
<P>
   Financial planners and campaign consultants suggest obtaining as
much money as possible through contributions first, then using
personal savings, before taking out loans or dipping into
retirement or life insurance plans. If borrowing is necessary, a
home-equity line of credit may be best since a portion may be tax
deductible, they say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always say never borrow to buy a depreciating asset, and
let's extend that to running for public office,'' said Jonathan
Pond, a financial planner from Watertown, Mass., and author of
several personal finance books. ``Chances are, even if you're
successful, your income probably is going to suffer,'' Pond said.
``Nobody goes into it for the money.''
</P>
<P>
   Those planning to run for office can expect to spend between
$15,000 and $200,000 to conduct a successful citywide campaign in a
mid- to large-size city, and between $25,000 and $300,000 for a
state legislative office, according to Ron Faucheux, the editor of
Campaigns &AMP; Elections magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional and gubernatorial candidates easily can run up
bills well into six- and seven-figures. ``Campaigns have become
increasingly costly and technologically driven, and candidates have
to prepare for a tough fight,'' Faucheux said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Faucheux (pronounced FOO-show) said it was crucial that all
candidates stick to budgets. He suggested drawing up ``high,''
``medium'' and ``low'' budget plans, or ``ideal'' and ``bare
bones'' plans. These budgets will help dictate how much candidates
need to raise or kick in themselves. ``Candidates have to figure
what the threshold is to be competitive,'' he said. ``It might be
nice to have $200,000, but you may need $150,000 to have a shot.''
</P>
<P>
   The amounts vary greatly by state, said Joel A. Thompson, a
political science professor at Appalachian State University in
Boone, N.C., and co-author of ``Campaign Finance in State
Legislative Elections,'' (Congressional Quarterly, 1998).
</P>
<P>
   Thompson's book, written with Gary F. Moncrief, a political
science professor at Boise State University in Boise, Idaho,
analyzes the cost of winning in 20 competitive state houses of
representatives from 1986 to 1994. ``In some states, the costs are
so high relative to the pay,'' Thompson noted, citing North
Carolina, with costs about twice as high as the base legislative
salary of around $20,000.
</P>
<P>
   In general, the larger the state, the bigger the expense. For
1994, candidates in California spent on average $431,000;
candidates in Illinois averaged $190,000; in Oregon, $78,000; in
Wisconsin and North Carolina, $38,000; in Montana, $6,500, and in
Wyoming, $4,500. New York was not included. Costs are substantially
higher today.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the state, incumbents almost always have an easier
time raising money than their challengers, and usually do not have
to use personal savings, experts agree. But some who had hoped to
continue working at another job find they cannot.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Hipps, a Republican who represents the southwest corner of
Jacksonville, was re-elected to a second four-year term last year.
During her first campaign, she scaled back to part time at St.
Vincent's Medical Center in Jacksonville. For the last two years,
she has worked full time in her council job, which pays $32,000 a
year.
</P>
<P>
   The mother of two grown children, she has had to spend a few
thousand dollars from her own pocket on her two campaigns _ the
bulk of which went for filing fees and, the first time around, a
fund-raising barbecue at her home.
</P>
<P>
   She said she was fortunate, however, to have had strong
financial backing from supporters, thanks to the long hours spent
pounding the pavement, and the health benefits and income of her
husband, Frank, 66, a retired terminal operator for Chevron Oil.
The Hipps also raise cattle on a 17,000-acre family farm in
Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had young children and was at another point of my life I
don't know if I could act on what I wanted to do,'' said Mrs.
Hipps, whose foray into politics stemmed from her displeasure with
the city's plans to build a prison on a closed Naval air station,
near her home. ``I really do enjoy what I do a lot,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   For some public officials, though, the sacrifices are too great.
Corbett, 39, of Cedar Rapids, Iowa, resigned last year after 13
years in the legislature, the last five as House speaker. He said
he tired of having to solicit contributions for re-election every
two years, and wanted to earn more.
</P>
<P>
   He now heads the Cedar Rapids Chamber of Commerce and earns more
than double the $31,000 base salary and an $86-a-day stipend during
sessions, he was paid as speaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to start thinking about things like college and my
children and a bigger house,'' said Corbett, the father of five
children, aged four months to 8. ``We didn't miss any meals, though
my wife was driving around in an '84 Ford van with 109,000 miles on
it. I drove a newer car _ an '87 Cavalier with 180,000 miles on
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-00 2335EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000120.0419 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 23:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2086 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-RAMS-VERMEIL-NYT &LR;      01-20 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RAMS-VERMEIL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON PRO FOOTBALL: EVEN IN TRIUMPH, VERMEIL'S HIRING IS A SORE POINT
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Last summer, Warren Sapp, the Tampa Bay defensive
end who never met a microphone he didn't like, was asked about St.
Louis coach Dick Vermeil. Sapp didn't mince words, claiming Vermeil
was a ``washed up'' coach who got his job only as a result of the
old-boy network.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Sapp was asked whether he wanted to, well, rethink
his inflammatory comments, especially considering that Vermeil was
named coach of the year after his Rams went 13-3 in the regular
season. Sapp didn't back down, saying his feelings had not changed.
</P>
<P>
   As harsh as Sapp's words about Vermeil may have been, they were
not necessarily untrue. When Vermeil was put in charge of the Rams
in 1997, he was 60 years old and had not coached a game since 1982,
when he was the coach of the Philadelphia Eagles. Vermeil had spent
the time in between as a television analyst for college football
games.
</P>
<P>
   So Vermeil was a retread. Many in the news media blasted the
hiring at the time as yet another indication that a white coach,
even one out of the profession for 15 years, always had an edge
over a black coach because of race. At the time, black assistants
privately asked what was so special about Vermeil.
</P>
<P>
   Vermeil's hiring, in some ways, is still a sore point with many
black assistants. While coaches like Vermeil get a second chance,
they say, most black coaches do not. Ray Rhodes, formerly of the
Philadelphia Eagles and recently let go as the head coach in Green
Bay after an 8-8 season, is the only black head coach to get a
second job after being fired. The Atlanta Falcons offensive line
coach Art Shell coached the Oakland Raiders and was 54-38. He is
considered one of the smarter coaches in the game. Still, his phone
has not been ringing with offers. He has not received the second
chance that white coaches do.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams and the Buccaneers meet in the NFC championship game on
Sunday, and it must be said that Vermeil, despite the opposition by
so many to his hiring three years ago, has proven Sapp, and many
others, wrong. Vermeil did something that other older coaches would
not, the most notable being Mike Ditka, who was stuck in the 1980s
and was as old school as an eight-track tape.
</P>
<P>
   Vermeil adapted.
</P>
<P>
   Vermeil changed.
</P>
<P>
   Vermeil refused to go the way of the dinosaurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a 180-degree turn between last year and this year,''
Rams linebacker London Fletcher said of Vermeil.
</P>
<P>
   His change in personality is something that Vermeil will not
address fully, mainly because that is the way of NFL coaches. They
do not readily admit that they may have made a mistake. Football is
too macho for that.
</P>
<P>
   But the evidence is clear. When Vermeil went to St. Louis, he
made several crucial errors. He drafted the troubled running back
Lawrence Phillips in the first round, something that proved to be a
disaster after he got into a number of off-field difficulties. The
Rams eventually cut Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   Vermeil also alienated players with brutal practice sessions. In
training camp, he held three-hour, hard-hitting sessions twice a
day. Once the regular season began, Vermeil held practice once a
day, but it was still harsh, and the players became so irate that
there was almost a mutiny; especially irritated were the older
players, who would be worn down by the end of the season. Players,
as well as high-ranking officials throughout the organization,
spoke to Vermeil about easing up, and he did.
</P>
<P>
   That was the beginning of Vermeil's change. ``I think what he
did was that he kept an open mind about things,'' St. Louis
defensive back Todd Lyght said.
</P>
<P>
   Vermeil also began making smart draft and personnel moves, such
as trading for running back Marshall Faulk, who this year had an
NFL-record 2,429 all-purpose yards. ``We wanted guys who could
move,'' Vermeil said. ``As you can see, we don't have any fat guys
who can't run.''
</P>
<P>
   Vermeil also delegated much of his authority to his offensive
coaches and allowed them to open things up, despite his strong
affinity for the more conservative ground game.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a happy Vermeil as well as happy players, some of
whom are winning for the first time in their careers. ``Not only
would we lose games due to the fact that our personnel didn't match
up,'' Lyght said, ``we would be outcoached. And that hasn't been
the case this year.''
</P>
<P>
   The contrast between Vermeil and Ditka is startling. Ditka, the
longtime Chicago Bears coach, never adapted after returning to the
New Orleans Saints. He made questionable personnel decisions, such
as trading the rest of his entire draft for running back Ricky
Williams last April. One Saints player said privately last month
that the team saw Ditka more as a caricature than a respected
coach. The owner, Tom Benson, recently fired Ditka after going
15-33 during his three-year stint in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   Why Vermeil was able to make the transition and Ditka was not is
one of those interesting mysteries. All Vermeil cares about now is
that he is a heartbeat away from taking the Rams to the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   And his team just might run over Sapp on the way there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
