<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 23:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2088 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-AIRPORTS-E-COMMER     01-20 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-AIRPORTS-E-COMMERCE-2TAKES-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAREHOUSE PROJECTS SPROUT IN DIGITAL AGE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 23) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ore., Texas, Calif. Va., Conn.)   (af)  
 By TODD MURPHY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The two buildings will spread themselves over some 160,000
square feet _ more than three football fields _ on the south side
of the airport in Portland, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   But when their construction is complete at the end of this year,
don't call them warehouses. Call them ``pass-through facilities.''
</P>
<P>
   And call them one developer's answer to a vexing issue in
electronic commerce these days _ actually delivering the goods
ordered through point-and-click shopping.
</P>
<P>
   The Trammell Crow Co., one of the country's largest commercial
real estate businesses, is helping to develop the Portland project,
with the hopes of leasing space to e-retailers and to the companies
that provide warehousing and delivery for them.
</P>
<P>
   For many e-commerce retailers, selling a product online is
becoming astonishingly easy; the tricky part is finding an
efficient way to have that product immediately available, and
quickly getting it to the customer.
</P>
<P>
   The issue has brought digital-age e-commerce companies back to
industrial-age concerns _ to roads, trucks, warehouses and airports
_ and to a search for ways to speed up the whole system.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way that e-commerce is going to effectively compete
with local retailers is if a customer logs on and orders something,
and they can get it within a day,'' said Steven Bradford, a vice
president with Trammell Crow. ``If I have to wait for three or four
days, I'm going to just go out and buy the thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Such concerns have led e-commerce companies, and the companies
who want their delivery business, to a range of options.
</P>
<P>
   The $16 million Portland project represents one of them. The
Dallas-based Trammell Crow and its partner, the AMB Property Corp.,
a San Francisco real estate investment trust, are building the
Portland locations not so much to store goods as to whisk them on a
whirring conveyer belt from Internet order to the customer's door.
</P>
<P>
   When finished _ completion is expected at the end of this year _
the buildings will be configured to make it easier for loading
equipment to maneuver. The buildings are being constructed at
Portland International Airport and will have direct access to its
taxiways. Four 747s and 68 large trucks will be able to load and
off-load goods at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Bradford said the developers were working to attract air cargo
companies, freight integrators and e-commerce concerns. ``We feel
like it's the next generation _ it's the logical extension of
e-commerce,'' Bradford said of the Portland project. ``The closer
you can get your product to the air cargo center, the quicker your
delivery time.''
</P>
<P>
   The partnership will pay $523,000 a year to lease the property.
Trammell Crow would not discuss specific rental rates for its
sites, but airport authorities in Portland said on-airport rentals
went for a premium _ perhaps double the commercial rate for the
area. Analysts say the project developers should have little
trouble renting the space in Portland, either to e-retailers
themselves or the companies that provide shipping services for
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody's going to gobble up that space, no doubt,'' Stacie
McCullough, a senior analyst with Forrester Research, said of the
Portland project.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Trammell Crow and AMB completed a similar development
at the Dallas-Fort Worth Airport. Tenants there include a priority
mail operation of the Postal Service, the air cargo division of
Lufthansa and a fresh-flower e-commerce company. And Bradford said
the partnership was looking to develop other such locations.
</P>
<P>
   But projects like these _ located right on airport property _
represent only a fragment of the delivery systems being built for
or used by e-commerce companies nationwide. Because on-airport land
is limited, most new warehouse developments are built near large or
geographically important airports _ especially airports that serve
as a hub for package delivery companies.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard's e-commerce subsidiary, hpshopping.com, for
example, has its warehouse near Memphis, the largest air cargo hub
for Federal Express, hpshopping.com's primary delivery service. By
locating the warehouse there, the unit extends how late a customer
can order a product online and still get it the next day.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly if you're going to be playing in this next day or
two-day kind of space, you're got to be near a hub, near an
airport,'' said James Morales, the logistics manager of
hpshopping.com.
</P>
<P>
   For other e-businesses, proximity to large airports seems
relatively unimportant. Amazon.com, for example, added about 2.7
million square feet of distribution center space across the country
from December 1998 to last November, in places like Fernley, Nev.,
Coffeyville, Kan., and McDonough, Ga. _ paying more attention to
their proximity to potential customers, said Bill Curry, a company
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon delivers more than 60 percent of its products through the
Postal Service, he added, noting that, in general, they are not the
kind of products customers expect the next day.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're selling books and hammers and TVs and Walkmans and
stuff like that, you can get a book or a Walkman to a customer
faster and less expensively with a set of regional facilities,''
Curry said.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon has invested $300 million on its entire warehousing and
delivery system. But the vast majority of e-commerce retailers,
said Elissa Myers, president of the Electronic Retailing
Association in Arlington, Va., are outsourcing the delivery of
their products to catalog companies and other businesses with
existing warehouse and delivery systems.
</P>
<P>
   For 50 years, the Minneapolis-based Fingerhut Companies has been
shipping home furnishings, knickknacks and clothing sold through
its catalog. Now, the company _ purchased last year by Federated
Department Stores for $1.5 billion and an e-retailer itself _ does
much more: it uses its warehouses and distribution system to
provide ``order fulfillment'' for a number of online retailers,
including eToys and the online operations of Pier 1 and Wal-Mart
Stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've reinvented themselves, basically,'' Irving Chernofsky,
research director for the consulting firm Gartner Group in
Stamford, Conn., said of Fingerhut and a few other formerly
catalog-only companies. ``They're now e-commerce fulfillment
houses.''
</P>
<P>
   For many e-retailers, paying _ usually by volume _ to use such
an established system and for the expertise to make it work makes
much more sense than paying the huge cost of building a system
themselves, Ms. Myers said. That is especially true, she added, for
online sales that are seasonal. ``You may need 100 people packing
packages for two weeks, and one person for the next two months,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   What e-commerce companies need most, of course, are happy
customers. And many in the industry believe that having happy
customers has almost nothing to do with fancy Web sites and
everything to do with getting the goods to the customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sooner you get the customer something,'' said Morales of
hpshopping.com, ``the more likely they are to be happy with the
whole product and purchase, and with you.''
</P>
<P>
   That, some say, will only become more true. ``The next level of
competition is going to be time shopping: who can get it to me
quickest?'' Chernofsky said.
</P>
<P>
   And the companies that fail that test won't last long.
</P>
<P>
   ``These Web sites have nothing if they don't have brand
loyalty,'' Chernofsky said. ``Bad word of mouth spreads very
rapidly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
