<HEADLINE>
CLOSS A NO-SHOW AT PRACTICE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The phenomenon known as Keith Closs-trophobia _ &UR;  &LR; an apparent
fear of closing in on NBA success _ has filled this week's quota
for bad Clipper karma.
</P>
<P>
   Well, that six-game losing streak is no slouch.
</P>
<P>
   Closs was a no-show at Thursday's practice, one day after
skipping out early on his weight-lifting assignment, a maneuver
Coach Chris Ford responded to by saying the 7-foot-3 backup center
would not suit up for tonight's game with Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not here,'' Ford said. ``Elgin (Vice president of
basketball operations Baylor) will deal with it. We put in our
calls like we do for people who don't show up. We haven't heard
from him. It's a shame.''
</P>
<P>
   According to team sources, the birth of Closs' first child is
due, which might explain why the third-year Clipper would miss
Thursday's workout.
</P>
<P>
   But it doesn't figure to excuse Wednesday's incident or get him
off the hook for not phoning it in Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Late Thursday, the Clippers said Closs still had not been
reached. An official decision on his status for tonight's game will
be made today.
</P>
<P>
   T'wolves at the door
</P>
<P>
   The Timberwolves, who are a toasty 7-3 in their last 10 games,
scored a 91-88 victory over the Utah Jazz on Wednesday at the
inhospitable Delta Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been playing extremely well,'' Ford said. ``They're on
a nice roll. They're finding ways to win. ''
</P>
<P>
   The best way seems to include frequent passes to budding
superstar forward Kevin Garnett. Garnett put up 31 points against
Karl Malone and the Jazz, and another 37 in Monday's victory over
the Indiana Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   But Ford may be even more impressed with Garnett's defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played defense on Karl (Malone) as well as I've seen anyone
play defense on Karl,'' said Ford, a dedicated follower of the NBA
on DirecTV.
</P>
<P>
   Fast breaks
</P>
<P>
   One visitor to Thursday's practice at Veterans SportsComplex in
Carson was Lamar Odom's agent, Jeff Schwartz. Schwartz, who lists
Odom as his only NBA client, did have an extended chat with
shooting guard Derek Anderson. Anderson is believed to be
considering a change in agents, joining the growing ranks of NBA
players set to abandon the representation of rap star Percy
``Master P'' Miller's No Limit Sports. ``DA'' continues to pass on
the opportunity to testify about his agent situation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
