<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 23:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2091 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-BLACK-TALK-RADIO-ART-     01-20 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACK-TALK-RADIO-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALKING BLACK, TALKING BACK: RADIO CHAT CAN AMUSE OR EMBOLDEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT24 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 (bl)  
 By MONTE WILLIAMS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It is midafternoon, two days before Y2K, and Sarah
from Brooklyn is calling WLIB, the city's premier black talk radio
station. She is dismayed about Rudy Crew's exit as the schools
chancellor, and she has her own take on the reason for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I strongly believe this, and I told this to a number of
educators the day after the Board of Education raised Crew's salary
to over $200,000,'' Sarah said, just getting started on her, um,
unique theory.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was more money than the president of the United States of
America makes. Did one African-American really think that that
amount of a raise was really for a black man in office? That amount
of money was raised because the mayor knew Rudy Crew's time was
short, and that raise was secured for the next Caucasian female,
who is an educator and who I happen to know and I happen to believe
will be the next chancellor.''
</P>
<P>
   Minutes before, Puffy Combs was the subject on WLIB, and the
phones were ringing as if the station were conducting a cash
giveaway. Several callers were supportive of Combs, the rap star
and promoter who was arrested late last month on a gun charge. But
one listener was riled at the self-described ``ghetto fabulous''
impresario.
</P>
<P>
   ``A man of Puffy's caliber, his status, which they allege that
he has millions of dollars, shouldn't he get security and not these
nitwit brains he has securing him?'' the caller sniffed. ``A gun in
the car. I mean this is really ridiculous, and you see it over and
over again with these so-called millionaire rappers.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Riley, the host of ``Politics Live'' on WLIB-AM (1190),
agreed. ``If you're going to have somebody who's going to be armed,
have somebody who's licensed, a professional,'' he said. ``What
happens is these guys pick the biggest cat they used to run with.''
</P>
<P>
   And so it goes, day after day on WLIB and a handful of other
stations that broadcast talk shows geared to the full range of the
city's black listeners. On some shows, the talk can be angry and
conflicted, with hosts and callers tackling everything from trouble
hailing cabs to Amadou Diallo to the use of the word ``niggaz'' on
a popular DMX record.
</P>
<P>
   Other conversations can be more mainstream, where, for instance,
one might hear sad, knowing talk about the people from Princeville,
N.C., the nation's first black-governed town, which was ravaged by
rains last fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Black talk radio is the drum of the community,'' said Imhotep
Gary Byrd, a popular former host at WLIB.
</P>
<P>
   But if much of the city, black or white, is aware of black talk
radio's existence, its various conversations _ irreverent,
emotional, academic and, yes, sometimes conspiratorial _ are not
regularly heard by the city's mainstream. Several weeks of
sustained listening, then, revealed a rich and varied dialogue, one
that made it easy to understand why black talk radio has long
functioned as a roiling, playful and galvanizing lifeline for
blacks in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   State Assemblyman Roger Green of Brooklyn was recently a guest
on ``The Open Line,'' a Sunday morning talk show on WRKS-FM (98.7),
better known as KISS-FM. Green compared the current foster care
system to chattel slavery.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have mothers who are coming into my office on a weekly
basis who have literally had their babies in some cases torn from
their breasts,'' he said. He also called ``the prison-industrial
complex'' a menace to black children, ``who are being picked like
cotton and being shipped upstate.''
</P>
<P>
   In New York state last year the only growth in the governor's
budget was in prisons, he said. ``There's no question that people
come to Albany to lobby to create prisons,'' he said. ``It's become
a perverse economic stimulus package for poor whites in rural white
areas.'' In reality, the governor did propose modest spending
increases in other areas.
</P>
<P>
   Such conversations have been going on a long time. Black talk
radio had its genesis in Chicago in 1948 on WSBC, where Jack I.
Cooper was the host, said Bob Law, a veteran of both talk and
rhythm and blues radio. Law, now on WWRL-AM (1600), a
black-owned-and-operated station in Woodside, Queens, recently
wrote a book about black radio, ``Voices for the Future,''
published by African-American Images.
</P>
<P>
   ``Black talk was the only outlet for the frustration and the
attainment of information,'' Law said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without black talk,'' he added, ``the community becomes
voiceless. White talk is not neutral or impartial. It's
Eurocentric. White talk raises no critical questions. Right now,
Clinton has encouraged European countries not to buy bananas from
Caribbean farmers. He wants them to buy only from Chiquita or Dole.
The bananas they were selling to European countries were just
enough to sustain them. This issue is never examined on white
talk.''
</P>
<P>
   In the early days at WLIB, talk radio was an outgrowth of public
affairs requirements imposed by the Federal Communications
Commission. ``There was no real energy in it,'' Law said. ``It was
not a priority. Some of the disc jockeys had to come back and do
these public affairs shows about health, housing and education.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, four New York City stations have black talk shows. Judy
Ellis, general manager at KISS-FM, said ``The Open Line'' had
139,200 listeners, while the station's Sunday night show, ``The
Week in Review,'' had 36,300 listeners. (KISS's overall
listenership for people 12 and older is 1,288,500, which puts it in
the top 10 in the New York market.)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   WLIB management said it did not have figures for individual
shows, but the mostly talk radio station has a listenership of
280,300 for people 12 and older. WBAI-FM (99.5), which has five
black hosts, including Elombe Brath, the activist and artist, has
about 200,000 listeners, according to management. And WWRL, which
has a show by Tony Brown, a well-known broadcaster, has 250,000
listeners.
</P>
<P>
   James Mtume, a member of KISS-FM's talk team, said there was
tremendous growth potential in black talk radio. ``Given the
landscape, I think black talk radio is a sleeping giant ready to
blow up,'' he said. ``People would love something else other than
the next love songs. Blacks are starved for information.''
</P>
<P>
   Black talk radio has not been without controversy over some of
its content. In the early 1990s, for example, the Jewish Action
Alliance held protests over comments made during the Crown Heights
riots. ``On WLIB and WWRL there was an unbelievable amount of
anti-Semitism,'' said Beth Gilinsky, president of the group. ``We
held demonstrations. It was 1991, during the year of the Crown
Heights riots. We located their sponsors and they started pulling
ads.''
</P>
<P>
   But employees of black-owned and black-programmed stations say
their shows are held to a different standard than the white
mainstream. Steve Rendall, a senior analyst at Fairness and
Accuracy in Reporting, a national media watch group, echoed the
sentiment. ``We've noted and quoted the occasional black talk radio
host,'' said Rendall. ``But in New York City, the irresponsible
comments from black radio hosts are nothing compared to the torrent
of bigoted talk that comes from white hosts on big mainstream radio
stations.''
</P>
<P>
   Undeniably, black talk radio is chiefly driven by the city's
great engine of emotional discourse: race. And virtually every week
brings a new framing question.
</P>
<P>
   After the actor Danny Glover's problem getting a cab in New York
in the fall, the mayor's offensive on cab drivers who bypass blacks
dominated the shows. At KISS-FM, a panel of pundits discussed the
improvements they had already witnessed since the mayor announced
that he would revoke the hack licenses and impound the taxis of
drivers who whiz by blacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Friday was one of the days that a brother could get out there
and put his arm out and a cab would stop,'' said Bob Slade, a talk
radio veteran and the moderator of the Sunday night show, ``The
Week in Review.'' ``You could be talking, making an expression and
the arm would accidentally go up and the cab would stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile on WLIB, Riley, the host of ``Politics Live,''
discussed Dr. Lenora Fulani, a black radical former presidential
candidate who has endorsed Patrick Buchanan, the Reform Party
candidate, for president. ``What some people thought was the
strangest match in this century or in any other century, for that
matter,'' Riley began, ``was Pat Buchanan and Dr. Lenora Fulani,
late of the New Alliance Party, but obviously functioning now
within the Reform Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, she is Buchanan's most prominent black backer. She
has promised to take him to Sylvia's and some other places. Somehow
Pat Buchanan and soul food don't work well with me. But I have an
open mind. Hey, Dr. Fulani could have him rioting before this is
all over.''
</P>
<P>
   But if there was something loopily hilarious about Pat Buchanan
eating at Sylvia's in Harlem, things got heated when Minister
Conrad Muhammad took over the mike at WLIB last week during his
show, ``One on One.'' Muhammad, the minister of Mosque No. 7 in
Harlem, invited Karl Evanzz to discuss his book, ``The Messenger:
The Rise and Fall of Elijah Muhammad.'' The author made a case for
the Nation of Islam leader's resilience in the face of years of
monitoring by the FBI. But then, Evanzz, as others have, accused
Elijah Muhammad of being the father of several illegitimate
children.
</P>
<P>
   A livid caller lashed out at Evanzz, an online editor at The
Washington Post. ``The Messenger was 100 percent true to what he
taught until his departure in 1974,'' the caller said. ``This FBI
business about producing children at Temple 2, a temple which is
full of hypocrites since the 1930s, making children by sisters and
charging the messenger with this evil. So this person writing this
book does not have his facts. Stop slandering the Honorable Elijah
Muhammad.''
</P>
<P>
   Callers on black talk radio stations, not unlike on other radio
stations, can be unpredictable. Several months after the fact, Mark
from Brooklyn wanted to talk about the Klan's anemic march in
downtown Manhattan, although Utrice Leid, the host of Talk Back, a
call-in show on WBAI, was discussing Hillary Rodham Clinton's run
for the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the Klan was marching I didn't see no responsible black
leadership speaking against the Klan,'' Mark said. ``Did you notice
anybody?
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, maybe it's just me. Those same voices that said, `Oh,
no, Khallid this, Sharpton that, and Farrakhan, the other one' and
always the ones denouncing. I ain't seen those same voices saying
no they shouldn't march. It's just one of those things that make
you say hmmmm.''
</P>
<P>
   Laughing, Ms. Leid said: ``Did you say hmmmm?
</P>
<P>
   ``I said hmmmm,'' Mark said.
</P>
<P>
   And on to the next caller.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
