<SLUG> BC-LOSANGELES-SCHOOLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DROP SCHOOL PROJECT, LOS ANGELES IS URGED BY NEW SUPERINTENDENT
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In his first major decision, the acting
superintendent of the Los Angeles school system has recommended
that officials abandon a $170 million investment in an urban school
construction project that has been troubled by environmental
hazards.
</P>
<P>
   In a report made public Thursday, Ramon Cortines, who assumed
control over the Los Angeles district on Sunday, and Howard Miller,
the chief operating officer, said open-ended cleanup costs and an
additional $55 million needed to finish construction made the
project, the Belmont Learning Complex, unfeasible, especially when
the money would have to come from funds needed for books and
teacher salaries.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the report said that the site should be used as a new
headquarters for the city's school administration and that quickly
finding space for students in the crowded area should become a
priority. Board members are scheduled to consider the
recommendation on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is important to realize that this is not a question of
mathematics, but of judgment,'' the report said. State energy
officials had warned of the site, a former oil field, and it has
been found to have dangerous concentrations of methane and hydrogen
sulfide.
</P>
<P>
   The recommendation raises the stakes in one of the most
politically sensitive issues in Los Angeles in recent years. If
board members were to reject it, it would put them in the position
of spurning the advice of an official they avidly courted last
fall.
</P>
<P>
   Political fallout from the project was a significant factor in
the departure of the previous superintendent, Ruben Zacarias.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
