<HEADLINE>
FAA EASES RULES ON BOEING 777 LONG-HAUL ROUTES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Federal Aviation Administration has decided to
ease restrictions on how far Boeing's 777 can fly from emergency
landing sites on long-haul routes across the North Pacific, the
Post-Intelligencer has learned.
</P>
<P>
   The rule change will become final in 60 days, and will provide a
marketing boost to current models of the 777, as well as the even
longer-range 777X that is expected to be launched soon.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA's policy statement regarding the change will go into the
Federal Register on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Post-Intelligencer obtained a copy of the 30-page statement.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA said safety will not be compromised as a result of the
change. It said the 777 has proved itself to be extremely reliable.
</P>
<P>
   A number of airlines, including Continental, United, Delta and
American, have pushed hard for the FAA rule change because it means
they can fly their 777s on shorter, more fuel-efficient routes with
fewer schedule changes that inconvenience air travelers.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus has mounted an intense campaign against the change in
so-called ETOPS regulations. ETOPS stands for extended range
twin-engine operations.
</P>
<P>
   The European airplane maker's long-haul, A340 widebody jet,
which competes with the 777, has four engines and is not subject to
the same restrictions as the twin-engine 777. Industry analysts say
this has given Airbus an important advantage in sales competitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This certainly eliminates a potential disadvantage to our
airplane,'' Chet Ekstrand, Boeing's vice president responsible for
ETOPS, said Thursday in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``It (the FAA decission) provides an advantage to the 777 which
is consistent with its remarkable design and capabilities. ... This
action by the FAA recognizes that capability and eliminates a
disadvantage that is wholly inappropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   The FAA decision will become final 60 days after it is entered
into the Federal Register, though the agency will allow an
additional 45 days for public comment.
</P>
<P>
   It already has taken hundreds of pages of public comment since
last April.
</P>
<P>
   The change was sought by the Air Transport Association, which
represents more than two dozen U.S. and international airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Although some smaller pilot unions and groups have opposed
easing the current restrictions on how far the 777 can fly from
emergency landing strips, the transport association's request for
the change has the backing of the Airline Pilots Association, which
represents more than 55,000 airlines pilots with 51 airlines in the
U.S. and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Under current ETOPS regulations, the 777 flight must be within
180 minutes (three hours) at all times from an emergency landing
site on northern Pacific routes, such as from Tokyo to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The change approved by the FAA will allow a 15 percent extension
to 207 minutes (three hours and 27 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   The most optimal way for airlines to fly across the North
Pacific takes the plane on a Great Circle route for which the
half-dozen emergency airports are in Alaska, the Aleutian Islands
and the Russian Far East.
</P>
<P>
   If these alternate landing sites should be closed because of
weather, there is a 5- to 13-minute gap that exists where the plane
would be beyond the current 180-minute restriction. In that case,
twin-engine planes must fly a more southernly route, which can add
as much as 45 minutes or more to a flight from Los Angeles to
Tokyo, for example.
</P>
<P>
   The new extension to 207 minutes will close that gap. It applies
only to the 777.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA, in its statement that will go into the Federal
Register, said a study by United Airlines found that 10 percent of
its flights would benefit from the extension to 207 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   In opposing the extension to 207 minutes, Airbus has said it
would further erode safety in the event of an in-flight emergency
such as an engine failure.
</P>
<P>
   But the FAA said adding the 27 minutes actually will improve
safety, since it will bring planes closer to more enroute alternate
airports.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus last year caused something of an industry uproar with an
ad campaign that suggested its four-engine planes were safer than
two-engine planes.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing's Ekstrand said studies do not support the Airbus
position.
</P>
<P>
   He said twin-engine planes actually have a lower rate of
engine-related accidents than four-engine planes.
</P>
<P>
   And the 777, he added, has the highest flight completion rate of
any widebody passenger jet.
</P>
<P>
   Since the 777 entered service, he said, it has only been
diverted one time to an alternate airport because of an
engine-related problem.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to safey issues, the Allied Pilots Association,
which represents mostly American Airlines pilots, submitted
comments to the FAA that Boeing wanted to ease the current ETOPS
rules for marketing reasons.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA, in its statement, did not agree, saying:
</P>
<P>
   ``... The FAA rejects the notion that the safety decision to be
made for 207-minute ETOPS operations are related to the marketing
of airplanes.''
</P>
<P>
   The FAA said it will closely monitor the applications by
airlines for the 207-minute extension. Only airlines that currently
have approval for 180-minute ETOPS operations can apply for the
extension, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
   The agency also said it will ask its aviation rulemaking
advisory committee to recommend safety standards and procedures for
extended range operation of aircraft regardless of the number of
engines.
</P>
<P>
   That could mean the Airbus planes that compete with the 777
might have to have additional equipment or requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing's four-engine 747 would be included in such a review.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-20-00 2341EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000120.0429 </DOCNO>
