r s BC-GEN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LB     01-20 1234
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENBERG GETS HIS WISH AT CBS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dick Enberg has always been one of the more sincere, upbeat men
in a field, sportscasting, that breeds insecurity. Regardless of
how tilted things may be, Enberg usually finds some redeeming
quality.
</P>
<P>
   But for several months late in 1999, the former voice of the
Rams, Angels and UCLA basketball admittedly was in a funk. A second
NFL season was passing him by, he had a contract offer in hand to
return to NFL-less NBC, and he wasn't sure if any other network
wanted him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't realize how much I'd miss the NFL,'' said Enberg ``I
had done NFL games for 32 consecutive years, starting with the 1966
Rams, and I never wanted to accept the possibility that I might
never work a NFL game again.
</P>
<P>
   ``When NBC lost the NFL, I sent a passionate letter to (NBC
Sports President) Dick Ebersol asking if he would consider allowing
me to move on. But with two years left on my deal, the network was
unwilling.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last six months, from May on, were pretty down emotionally
for me. I couldn't say yes to NBC's offer. Dick went the extra mile
by contacting CBS and Fox and asking if they were open to me doing
NFL games for them on loan, but they understandably didn't want
that kind of arrangement.''
</P>
<P>
   What it did was open CBS' eyes to hiring Enberg full-time for a
variety of events, which they officially did on Wednesday. Enberg
will become the network's No. 2 NFL play-by-play man, do regular
season and tournament college basketball games, serve as a
commentator on golf tournaments like the Masters, and host CBS'
U.S. Open tennis coverage.
</P>
<P>
   The deal worked well for Enberg financially, and he's excited
about his work schedule. He may not fill any particular No. 1 chair
at CBS, those being filled by Greg Gumbel and Jim Nantz, but he's
unconcerned about it and excited by the new events and new (and
some old) people he'll be involved with.
</P>
<P>
   On NFL games, he'll be paired with former ABC Monday Night voice
Dan Dierdorf, who restored his reputation with a strong 1999. On
college basketball, he'll be reunited with Al Maguire, the former
Marquette coach who was a partner when NBC had the NCAA package.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd pay to work with Al,'' Enberg said. ``He taught me more
about life than anyone outside of my own father.'' Enberg and
Maguire will work Saturday's Ohio State-St. John's game, and before
the regular season ends, the two will be joined by Billy Packer for
a reunion telecast.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a lot like going through a divorce,'' said Enberg.
``When you've been with someone for 25 years, you can take each
other for granted. I'm starting a new relationship that has all of
the unknowns, challenges and excitement that I haven't experienced
for awhile.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to miss a lot of events and people I love, like
Wimbledon. But you can't hold on to old girlfriends. I can't have
it all. I feel a real nice glow now from being wanted (by CBS).''
</P>
<P>
   The other perk is more free time than he usually had at NBC. He
has three kids moving through their high school years, and he wants
to be available to see their games and school events.
</P>
<P>
   It will also add events to his resume. By the time Enberg
decides to stop talking for a living, he'll have touched virtually
every base in the business.
</P>
<P>
   He has 32 years with the NFL, starting with the Rams and
including eight Super Bowls. He was the voice of the Angels on KTLA
and KMPC for many years before being hired by NBC, and worked one
World Series and several other big games during his time there. He
did UCLA basketball games for KTLA during John Wooden's magnificent
run, and seven years of Final Fours at NBC.
</P>
<P>
   He did eight Rose Bowls with ex-Ram partner Merlin Olsen as well
as three Olympics, world championships in track, figure skating and
gymnastics, and horse racing's Breeders Cup and Arlington Million.
He now will add tennis' U.S. Open to his Wimbledon and French Open
coverage, and the Masters to a shot sheet that already has the U.S.
Open and Ryder Cup.
</P>
<P>
   And for those who have forgotten, Enberg was the blow-by-blow
announcer on boxing at the Olympic Auditorium for three years
(1966-68) at KTLA; covered one of Muhammad Ali's fights in Munich,
with Candace Bergen as an analyst; and cut his teeth as a
play-by-play man by doing L.A. Blades hockey in their last year
here before the NHL expanded and the Kings were born.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's funny about that is that Rams' owner Dan Reeves thought
he was going to get the L.A. NHL franchise, and I probably would
have had the chance to be the Kings voice,'' Enberg said. ``And
then Jack Kent Cooke swooped out of Toronto without warning and got
the franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``All things considered, I've been blessed and privileged.
Someone has been looking over me since that first audition at KTLA,
and now I have a new opportunity that has me excited.''
</P>
<P>
   THEY GOT GAMES: The NFL's version of the Final Four is set for
Sunday, and the voices are gargled and ready. Fox's Pat Summerall
and John Madden will do the Rams-Bucs game and CBS' Greg Gumbel and
Phil Simms the Jags-Titans.
</P>
<P>
   Madden respects Tampa Bay's defense and expects it to play well,
but says the team will have to do other things well if it wants to
be in the game in the fourth quarter. ``Tampa needs to intercept a
ball and run it in, or block a punt, or return a kickoff,'' he
said. ``They can't win just by playing good defense. At some time,
Tony Dungy is going to need some points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't remember an offense exploding like the Rams have all
season. It's comparable to the 49ers when they had Joe Montana,
Roger Craig, Jerry Rice and John Taylor. They're built to play on
that domed carpet, and they always look like they're going 100
miles an hour.''
</P>
<P>
   Simms says the most relevant aspect of Jacksonville and
Tennessee meeting for a third time is the lack of any surprise
factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The emotions are never the same in a game and there are always
different angles,'' he said. ``Both teams are emotionally high and
generally healthy, so the only advantage is Jacksonville being at
home. I would be shocked if either team does something that catches
the other by surprise. They know each other too well. It should be
a close, hard-hitting game.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And now the news
</P>
<P>
   NBC and Turner Sports signed three-year deals to air Wimbledon
coverage, with Turner taking the cable package once held by HBO.
TNT will air 61 hours of coverage and CNN/SI 28 hours, which is a
25 percent bump over the 57 hours HBO aired last year. NBC's usual
schedule of coverage over three weekends and a late night wrapup
show stays the same. ... HBO's Real Sports on Tuesday (10 p.m.)
updates the story of now ex-homeless former NFL quarterback Joe
Gilliam, and examines why so many former Super Bowl players have
had to hock their rings. ... ESPN and ESPN2 will provide coverage
of the Australian Open through the finals next weekend, including
airings at 9:30 p.m. this Saturday and Sunday. ... And this just
in: A new syndicated TV show that is being pedaled to the networks,
The Consultants, features a former basketball player named Dennis
Rodman in the role of a whacky fellow who blames his behavior on
the bullet lodged in his brain. Man, these shows are getting more
realistic all the time. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
