</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-PISTONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARBURY AND FEICK HELP NETS WIN NAIL-BITER OVER PISTONS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ For nearly three quarters of play of a
New Jersey Nets 122-120 victory over the Detroit Pistons, the story
at Continental Arena Thursday night revolved around Jamie Feick.
After being all but benched in the Nets' loss to the New York
Knicks on Wednesday, Feick, the league's fifth-leading rebounder,
returned with a vengeance, grabbing 19 rebounds against the Detroit
Pistons in the first half alone.
</P>
<P>
   The backboard brilliance of Feick, who started the game after
playing just 8 minutes against the Knicks, had helped the Nets
build a 14-point halftime lead that increased to 17 late in the
third quarter. But the Pistons interrupted the Nets' cruise to
victory with a 17-4 run over the final three minutes of the
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   After a seesaw fourth period, the story was no longer Feick but,
for the fourth straight game, the Nets' late-game execution. With
10.2 seconds left, they led 121-120 thantephon Marbury's
outstanding 12-point fourth period, and were inbounding the ball at
midcourt. Twice, the Nets were forced to call timeouts because they
could not inbound the ball, but finally they got it to Johnny
Newman, who was fouled immediately by Michael Curry.
</P>
<P>
   Newman, an 81.8 percent foul shooter, made 1 of 2 free throws
with 9.4 seconds left. Thus, the tables were turned, and Detroit
diagrammed a final play in the huddle. The Pistons got the ball to
Jerry Stackhouse, who scored 14 of his 28 points in the fourth
quarter, and he passed to Lindsey Hunter. Guarded tightly by
Marbury, Hunter put up a contested 15 footer with 3 seconds left,
and a wild scramble for the rebound ensued.
</P>
<P>
   Fittingly, the ball ended up in Feick's hands with 0.2 seconds
left with the Nets leading, 122-120. It was his career-high 25th
rebound of the game, one fewer than the Nets' franchise record for
a regulation game, and two fewer than Buck Williams' 27 rebounds in
a four-overtime game on Feb. 1, 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Marbury, who all but single-handedly kept the Nets in it in the
fourth, led everyone with 34 points and a season-high 15 assists.
Christian Laettner matched Stackhouse with 28 points for the
Pistons, and Grant Hill added 23 points.
</P>
<P>
   The victory broke the Nets' three-game losing streak and
improved their record to 16-23 heading into Saturday's home game
against Dallas. Detroit, which had won nine of its last 11 games,
dropped to 21-17.
</P>
<P>
   Down 93-89 entering the final period, Detroit took its first
lead since the middle of the first quarter when Laettner scored to
make it 103-102 with 6 minutes 21 seconds remaining. The clubs
exchanged one-point leads several times after that, but the Nets
were forced to battle without two starters, Keith Van Horn and
Kendall Gill, at game's end. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Van Horn fouled out with 2:44 left after scoring 28 points, and
Gill fouled out 59 seconds later with 12 points. Scott Burrell put
the Nets ahead 119-118 with a scintillating layup with 48 seconds
to play, and then Marbury made a runner off the glass to push the
lead to three points with 19.6 seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets did little wrong in building a 66-52 halftime lead, and
Feick was their catalyst. He outrebounded the entire Pistons team
by himself, grabbing 19 first-half rebounds to Detroit's 16.
Feick's dominance gave the Nets a 28-16 advantage on the glass and
helped them pull away despite shooting only slightly better than
the Pistons.
</P>
<P>
   With Feick pulling down 13 rebounds, including five on the
offensive end, in the first quarter, the Nets outscored the Pistons
12-0 in second-chance points and took a 35-26 lead into the second.
By the half, Feick had grabbed seven offensive rebounds and nearly
every carom of a missed Pistons shot _ Detroit had only one
offensive rebound. Feick's 13 rebounds were the most in one quarter
by any player in the league this season.
</P>
<P>
   Marbury's scoring was slow in developing, but he threw numerous
crowd-delighting passes from all sorts of angles. While not all of
them resulted in baskets, he recorded seven assists in the first
quarter and nine by the half. When his shooting touch kicked in,
there was no stopping him. Marbury made three of his last four
shots of the half, including a 37-footer at the buzzer, and his
first five attempts of the third quarter to help the Nets push the
lead to 17 points. His final two baskets in the string were
3-pointers
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
